<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-NYT &LR;      07-29 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE SOX CRUSH YANKEES, 11-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ There was one out in the fourth inning on Wednesday
night when Joe Torre stepped out of the New York Yankee dugout to
relieve Andy Pettitte, who waited on the mound, sweat dripping over
his eyes and down his cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez, the first baseman, jogged to the mound and tapped
the left-hander on the side. Pettitte held out the ball for Torre
and as the manager accepted it, Torre patted Pettitte on the back.
The pitcher trudged off the field, sunk onto the bench and stared
ahead, his future uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts from teams considering a trade for Pettitte watched it
all here in Comiskey Park. They saw how he labored badly, how he
threw 90 pitches to get just 10 outs in what turned into an 11-2
loss to the Chicago White Sox that ended the Yankees' seven-game
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   The scouts saw Pettitte pitch so tentatively that he could have
been mistaken for a rookie in his first outing; Pettitte allowed
eight hits, two walks and three runs in three and a third innings.
</P>
<P>
   The man who has ultimate authority in the Yankees' organization
and must approve any trade _ George Steinbrenner _ presumably
watched on television. With a midnight trading deadline on
Saturday, the Yankees have offers for Pettitte in hand, deals they
can make right now. In the next three days, Steinbrenner will
either agree to trade Pettitte, or hang onto him, in the hope the
left-hander can recapture the undaunting presence he had in his
first few years.
</P>
<P>
   Just 27, Pettitte is 75-43 in this, his fifth season with the
Yankees. ``Andy Pettitte has been a part of this club since I've
been here, and we've won two World Series in three years,'' Torre
said before the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte is a mystery to the Yankees, an expensive puzzle
who is destined to become more costly next year. He is 7-8 with a
5.65 earned run average and is earning $5.95 million this year, and
because he is eligible for arbitration this winter, he will make
perhaps $7 million or more next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are sure he is healthy, that his back and elbow are
sound; rival scouts who have seen him recently concur. The Yankees
believe his stuff is good, that he is throwing his fastball about
the same as he always has, and his pitches have movement; scouts
who have seen him concur.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte is finding ways to lose now, with a strangely
passive approach to pitching, and the Yankees have no idea why.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte loves pitching for the Yankees and has known for weeks
that they have talked about trading him, with Seattle (for Jeff
Fassero), Houston, Philadelphia, Cincinnati, Detroit and others. He
knew, as he took the mound on Wednesday night, that this would be
his last chance before the nonwaiver trade deadline to re-establish
himself, to show his old form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it's on his mind,'' said Torre. ``There's no
guarantee everybody's going to be here'' after the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than demonstrate his former aggressiveness, however,
Pettitte only confirmed the mysteriousness of his ways this season.
He retired Chicago in order in the first inning, throwing 15
pitches, including an unusually large portion of changeups.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte allowed a broken bat single one out into the second
inning, and with a count of 1 ball and 2 strikes, Paul Konerko
reached out and lined a ball into the right-field corner, the
runner scoring and Konerko ending up with a triple.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte reacted like a youngster touching a hot pot: He was
suddenly tentative, as if afraid to throw the ball over the plate.
Brook Fordyce, the next batter and the No. 7 batter in the Chicago
lineup, walked on four pitches, prompting the pitching coach Mel
Stottlemyre to visit the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte nodded and spoke reassuringly to Stottlemyre, but when
he tried to jam Craig Wilson with a fastball, Wilson blooped a
single to right, Konerko scoring. Pettitte gestured to the catcher
Joe Girardi: what luck.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago scored two runs in the inning, but more telling was the
fact that Pettitte threw 37 pitches to get the three outs; he had
thrown 52 pitches in two innings. He threw no fewer than three
pitches to any batter in the first two innings, and averaged more
than five a batter. He was in deep, deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox loaded the bases in the third, including a one-out
walk drawn by Magglio Ordonez, before Fordyce grounded out to end
the rally. But Pettitte threw 20 more pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson singled to start the fourth and after going ahead in the
count no balls and two strikes to Mike Caruso, Pettitte threw an
inside fastball and Caruso whacked it over the head of the right
fielder Paul O'Neill. It was Caruso's 12th extra-base hit in 339
at-bats this season.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson stopped at third. Dan Naulty began to warm up in the
Yankees' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte struck out Ray Durham with a cut fastball. Throwing two
great breaking balls or cutters _ there was that good stuff again _
Pettitte jumped ahead in the count by no balls and two strikeq
against the left-handed hitting Chris Singleton. All he needed was
another strike, and there would be two out and Pettitte would still
be in the game and have a chance for his eighth victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was at this juncture that Pettitte seemingly invented a way
to lose. He could have thrown another of his hard-breaking pitches
that had Singleton befuddled.
</P>
<P>
   He could have wasted a fastball inside. He could have thrown a
breaking ball in the dirt. Instead, Pettitte dropped his arm angle
and threw sidearm, like Orlando Hernandez or David Cone, a pitch he
very rarely throws.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, with the score tied, a benign breaking ball _
Pettitte's 90th pitch _ hung over the plate, Singleton smacked it
into right field, giving the White Sox a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   A moment later Torre was at the mound and Pettitte was headed
for the dugout, and perhaps Seattle or Houston or Philadelphia or
some other place where Pettitte doesn't want to be.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox battered the relievers who followed and went on to
accumulate 19 hits.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
