<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8079 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-TOMJANOVICH-HNS &LR;      07-29 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TOMJANOVICH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SALT LAKE CITY _ For most NBA head coaches, a summer league like
the Rocky Mountain Revue is supposed to be a break, a chance to set
up some tee times, sit and gossip, and maybe watch some basketball.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is somewhat ironic, then, that Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
chose this venue for his return to work after a hiatus that lasted
almost a month.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich, who for medical reasons was forced to step down as
coach of the Dream Team that competed in the Olympic qualifying
tournament in Puerto Rico earlier this month, was in the stands
Wednesday to watch the Rockets' Rocky Mountain Revue entry beat
Sacramento 90-73.
</P>
<P>
   It was less than a month ago that Tomjanovich, complaining of
dizziness and weakness, was checked into Memorial Hospital by Dr.
Jim Muntz. Tomjanovich was found to be suffering from ``extreme
physical exhaustion'' and spent the next three days in bed.
Tomjanovich left the hospital July 4, and Wednesday marked his
first full day back on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great,'' Tomjanovich said of being back. ``I went to
practice this morning, and just grabbing a basketball I pulled the
team together and grabbed a ball it felt good to be back. We have a
bunch of good guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to see our veterans, Michael (Dickerson), Cuttino
(Mobley) and Bryce (Drew), but then we have a lot of nice young
players who are trying to make our team. So it was really nice to
get back into the basketball environment.''
</P>
<P>
   And, true to his nature, Tomjanovich dived right in. Instead of
kicking back and gabbing with colleagues, Tomjanovich busied
himself by scribbling plays on scrap paper.
</P>
<P>
   But Tomjanovich swears he has learned his lesson. No more
marathon work sessions. No more studying videotape until he keels
over from lack of sleep. No more pushing himself beyond the limits
of his endurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have priorities, and I got to where there were no
limits,'' Tomjanovich said of his work habits. ``I like to work at
night, away from people, and it got out of hand. I learned a little
bit about those things. When I was a younger guy, I could go two or
three days without sleeping, and it got to where I got worn out.
And if you don't get your sleep, physically and mentally things
just don't work right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really sort of a helpless feeling that I didn't want to
be in, and that was frustrating because I really wanted to do the
USA (basketball) deal. But there was no way I could have given them
my best effort. And even after I slept a couple of days, my body
was so worn down. And finally, it took awhile to sink in. I figured
that after a day's rest I'd be ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to take some of the medications and all that
stuff. I just wanted to get back out and do it (his job). But
finally it was drummed into my head _ `You're really down and you
have to take this time off.' It finally got through my hard head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken three to four weeks off, getting away from
basketball,'' Tomjanovich added. ``I went up north to Michigan and
then spent a couple of days in Wyoming. I got some fresh air and
some exercise, and I'm really excited to get back with the team.''
</P>
<P>
   But what still bothers Tomjanovich was having to step down as
head coach of USA Basketball's 1999 Men's Senior National Team,
which went on to win the gold medal at the Tournament of the
Americas Olympic qualifier in San Juan.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich had been named Dream Team coach after leading the
NBA lockout-weakened United States team to a surprise bronze-medal
finish in the 1998 World Championships of Basketball in Athens,
Greece.
</P>
<P>
   But when his physical exhaustion set in, doctors advised
Tomjanovich to skip the Olympic qualifying tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I have a hard
time even now when I think about it. I enjoyed so much being
affiliated with those people (USA Basketball) the year before (at
the World Championships).''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was troubled by the decision to step down as coach
but grew to understand that fretting over it only exacerbated his
condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listened to some people about understanding that sometimes
this happens, and you have to take care of yourself,'' he said. ``I
had no doubts at all that things were going to go well with Larry
Brown, Tubby (Smith) and Gene Keady (doing the coaching). There
were no doubts in my mind at all. There are times when you just
have to understand that you have to take care of yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The odd part, Tomjanovich said, was that he could feel the
exhaustion coming on. But because of the the playoffs, the NBA
draft and then the Rockets' trade discussions with Toronto
concerning Hakeem Olajuwon, there wasn't enough time to step away
from the job and take a proper vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say this: It was a tough two to three weeks,''
Tomjanovich said. ``I had been struggling two to three weeks with a
lot of the work overload and a lot of the things that we had to
look at. There was a big workload there, and a couple of weeks or
10 days before that, I took a break. I sort of had to get away
because I felt it coming on. But when the draft came up, there was
no way I could (stay away). I had felt it coming on earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the exhaustion hit, Tomjanovich was almost floored by
the effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's about balance,'' Tomjanovich said. ``When you
don't keep your balance, things can happen. I really learned a
lesson. I'm not the young guy I used to be, where I'd lock myself
up for three days, grab a whole bunch of tapes and nonstop go over
them until I crashed. I learned a lesson. I got to where I was
staying up real late doing work, and I've always done that, ever
since I was an assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is that I feel I have to do a little better job of
managing those things. There were never limits _ time limits or
times of the day or night _ when I did things. And those things can
knock you out of whack. I just have to understand that I have to
become more disciplined _ there's only so much you can do, and you
have to do it at a certain time.''
</P>
<P>
   That revelation comes at an odd time, considering that Sunday
will mark the start of NBA mayhem _ the first day teams can sign
free agents and make trades. Tomjanovich and his staff will be hard
at work, no doubt putting in long hours as the Rockets try to plug
the leaks from last season's first-round playoff loss to the Los
Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley is a free agent, as is Sam Mack. And there have
been constant rumors swirling around Scottie Pippen's status, even
though Pippen swears he wants to remain a Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the confusion, Tomjanovich has made his return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we have different people who do different things, and I
have my role in it,'' he said. ``Yeah, I'm going to try and do the
best that I can and take something from the lessons that I've
learned. And I'm sure things will come up later in my career that
I'll have to learn from, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was something that I didn't think would happen, but it
did. It was very frustrating, and I learned that sometimes you have
to put yourself as a priority and take care of yourself, or none of
those real good things are going to happen because you're just
going to wear your butt out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
