<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8095 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURDER-SUIT-SPI &LR;      07-29 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDER-SUIT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTY, STATE PAY SETTLEMENT IN WOMAN'S DEATH BY EX-BOYFRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REBEKAH DENN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michelle Smith's ex-boyfriend was sentenced to life in prison
for her 1995 murder. Now others whose errors led to Smith's death
are paying as well.
</P>
<P>
   Whatcom County and Washington state have agreed to a $1.5
million settlement in a lawsuit brought by the Bellingham woman's
family that charged negligence in the county's oversight of the
ex-boyfriend, Lloyd Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe, who had been in jail in 1995 for assaulting Smith,
killed her after he was mistakenly released.
</P>
<P>
   The financial settlement will provide lifetime support for
Smith's daughter, which is all the money the family had wanted,
said family attorney Mark Leemon. And the ``stone-age'' procedures
that allowed Monroe to be released from jail also have been changed
as a result of Smith's death, Leemon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Smith's parents) had two goals. ... One was to make sure
their granddaughter was taken care of, and the other was to make
sure this didn't happen to other families,'' he said. ``From the
beginning, that's what was important to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The $1.5 million settlement includes an annuity for Smith's
daughter, which is expected to provide $10 million for the girl
over her lifetime, according to settlement papers.
</P>
<P>
   The family also sought and received one other form of
compensation: a letter of apology from the county for releasing
Monroe from jail on Feb. 22, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe had repeatedly violated no-contact orders obtained by
Smith and was being held in jail that day for allegedly beating and
raping her.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe had told Smith he would kill her if she reported him to
police again, but she did nonetheless and cooperated with
prosecutors who then filed a felony charge against Monroe, Leemon
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They finally had enough of a hold on him that Michelle could
feel safe ... '' he said. ``She did everything right. She did
everything she could to save her own life.''
</P>
<P>
   But Monroe was mistakenly released after a court appearance that
settled a different charge dating back to an earlier violation of
the no-contact order, Leemon said. Whatcom County Jail did not
require a written court order to release a prisoner at that time,
Leemon said. Instead, it relied on reports from jail transport
officers who accompanied the prisoners to court.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe was sentenced to five days in jail on the earlier
misdemeanor charge and was released because he had already been in
jail more than five days. The jail officer asked a prosecutor if
Monroe could be released, and the prosecutor _ who dealt with
misdemeanors rather than felonies _ answered that the hearing took
care of all the charges he knew about, according to Leemon and
court papers.
</P>
<P>
   The jail's own records clearly showed Monroe shouldn't have been
released, and ``it was clear they could have found out six ways to
Sunday that this guy had a felony that hadn't been disposed of,''
Leemon said.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on jail officers for the court record was an unusual
practice and one that both the jail's chief of corrections at the
time and the county undersheriff at the time said in writing was a
bad practice that should be changed, Leemon said in a mediation
letter. The jail now requires written authorization for releasing
prisoners, which must be checked by both a corrections officer and
supervisor, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was terrified when she learned Monroe had been released,
calling police and telling a supervisor she had called the
prosecutor's office as well, the mediation letter said. She was
last seen two days after his release; her body was found the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   Smith died a horrible death, Leemon said _ beaten, raped, then
strangled.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe is serving life in prison without possibility of release
for Smith's murder.
</P>
<P>
   Whatcom County officials refused all comment on the case
Wednesday, but the county acknowledged in court papers that its
employees knew Monroe posed a danger to Smith and should have known
that he was being held on a felony charge and hadn't posted bail.
</P>
<P>
   The county has sued the state in the case, arguing that the
prosecutor who spoke to the jail officer was acting as an agent of
the state, Leemon said. The percentage of the settlement each
agency pays could change after that lawsuit is settled, but
initially the county will put up $775,000, and the state will put
up $750,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 32, worked at Value Village in Bellingham, and
``according to everyone, her daughter was her life,'' Leemon said.
The child, now 12, lives with her father.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
