<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA PLAYERS PLEAD NO   CONTEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUGLAS HABERMAN AND ROBERT MONROE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
LOS ANGELES _ Nine UCLA football players pleaded no contest
Wednesday to illegal possession of handicapped parking placards, a
misdemeanor, and were sentenced to 200 hours of community service
and $1,485 apiece in fines and fees.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seven of the players _ and two others who postponed their court
hearings _ will be benched for the first two games of the season,
said UCLA Chancellor Albert Carnesale.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence imposed by Los Angeles Municipal Court Judge Sam
Ohta requires the players to perform half of the community service
with the Special Olympics, which holds athletic events for the
disabled, and half with other organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The players apologized, but more than a dozen people in
wheelchairs jeered the plea bargain and sentences outside the
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a slap on the wrist,'' said Lillibeth Navarro of the
California Foundation of Independent Living Centers. ``They're
punished by going to a party _ the Special Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA outside linebacker Ali Abdul Azziz said he and his
teammates regret their actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to apologize to the disabled community,'' he
said in a statement after the sentencing. ``We did not realize the
seriousness of our actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Azziz said they never parked in handicapped spaces with the
illegally obtained placards but used them to park free.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had realized then how offensive our actions were to the
disabled community and to others, we would never have committed
these acts,'' he said. ``We know we have embarrassed our school,
our families and ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafer Johnson, 1960 Olympics decathlon champion and board
chairman of Southern California Special Olympics, called the
sentence appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``These athletes made a mistake, and every one of them have told
me that, and have said that to everyone within hearing distance of
them,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Harland Braun, who represented six of the nine
players entering pleas Wednesday, and Deputy City Attorney Brian
Williams said the sentences were fair and appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Braun said average people pleading to the same charges would
have been sentenced to pay $1,300 in fines and fees, with no
community service.
</P>
<P>
   The misdemeanor charges carry a maximum sentence of 6 months in
jail and a $1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   In return for the pleas, the City Attorney's Office dismissed
one misdemeanor charge against each of the nine for filing false
documents with the state Department of Motor Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The use of the parking passes by current and former players came
to light after a campus patrolman spotted a car with an improperly
placed placard Jan. 16 and questioned the driver.
</P>
<P>
   Nine Bruins will miss the first two games of the season against
Boise State and Ohio State universities, Carnesale said, and all 14
players charged face additional punishments as students, ranging
from probation to suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has just had their wrist slapped,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carnesale said federal and state laws will prevent him from
revealing which students received which punishment. He added that
the university will require them to participate in meetings with
disabled students and awareness-raising efforts ``in a meaningful
and extensive way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruin head coach Bob Toledo said he was very disappointed by the
players' actions but lauded Carnesale's decision and agreed to the
two-game suspension before Wednesday's court action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a surrogate father. I'm going to love 'em. I'm going to
scold 'em. But I'm not going to throw them out,'' Toledo told
reporters at a press conference on the UCLA campus.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the charged individuals either have graduated or are no
longer on the team.
</P>
<P>
   The nine players sentenced Wednesday were: Azziz, 22, of Sherman
Oaks; Damian Allen, 21, of Van Nuys; Marques Anderson, 20, of Long
Beach; Oscar Cabrera, 21, of Highland Park; Deatra Clinton, 21, of
West Covina; Ryan Nece, 20, of Palms; Ryan Roques, 21, of Mar
Vista; Robert Thomas, 18, of Imperial; and Anthony White, 20, of
Sherman Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Five other UCLA football players charged in the case will be in
court Aug. 25. Four asked for more time to consider the City
Attorney's plea bargain offer _ Duval Hicks, 23, of Sherman Oaks;
Craig Walendy, 21, of Westlake Village; Durell Price, 21, of
Newhall; and James Ghezzi, 22, of Mar Vista. Mark Reynosa, 20, of
Sylmar, asked the judge for more time to hire an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks and Walendy are at NFL training camps and were not in
court. They and Reynosa were seniors last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
