<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8102 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     07-29 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MICHAEL Jordan and Wayne Gretzky quit because there was nothing
left for them to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Sanders quit _ if indeed he has _ because he will never
accomplish what he hasn't already.
</P>
<P>
   As an individual performer, Sanders deserves same-sentence
mention with both Air and The Great One. Although he may not have
reinvented the fine art of carting a football over, through and
around people, he certainly refined it. For now, or at least until
Terrell Davis puts a wrap on his Bronco-busting career, it can be
safely said that Barry buries them all.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody else has gone 10-for-10 in the NFL, as in 10 consecutive
1,000-yard seasons. Sanders leaves on top, the very top, as the
best back of them all, certainly when you factor in a three-year
college career that saw him set 13 NCAA records and claim the
Heisman Trophy for a so-so Oklahoma State program.
</P>
<P>
   You don't believe Barry is No. 1? It's only because he hasn't
won anything. Which is also why he's going. His paycheck makes him
almost untradable in the hard salary-cap era, and the Lions'
entrenched mediocrity, some four decades in the honing, ensures
there will be no championships in his future.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, only New Orleans has been a more inept franchise than
Detroit in the post-merger era of the NFL. Walter Payton hung
around Chicago long enough to finally earn a Super Bowl ring while
raising the NFL's career rushing record to lofty new heights. But
Sanders, 31, might not live long enough to see the Lions go the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   And Barry has nothing to prove as far as Payton's numbers are
concerned. He trails Sweetness by less than 1,500 yards, yet he has
run for more than 3,500 over the last two seasons. Barring a
catastrophic injury, which was unlikely considering his established
durability, Sanders figured to leave Payton's prodigious total of
16,726 lost in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? The Lion King might have had it in him to push the
20,000-yard barrier.
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason for him to retire? Payton is suffering from
a congenital liver disease and desperately needs a transplant. Did
Sanders, certain to be a first-ballot Hall of Famer, feel any great
need to erase a beloved hero's name from the history books while he
battles for his life?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's giving Sanders too much credit, and perhaps his
objectives are as greedy and self-serving as the skeptics are
suggesting they are. This could be just another poorly disguised
contract ploy, or a hardball play to force a trade to a contender,
the cap be hanged. Barry does, after all, have a rich history of
such behavior.
</P>
<P>
   He has held out on three occasions during his gold-dusted
career, and he has renegotiated so many times no one seems to be
exactly sure how much he would have made on the deal he's presumed
to be walking away from.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a definite majesty in bowing out at the apex of
one's skills, before the ravages of the aging process take their
humbling toll. Jim Brown did it, slipping away after just nine NFL
seasons to pursue an acting career _ and, in those days, a fatter
income. In baseball, Sandy Koufax begged off after winning 27 games
at age 30, before his fabled left arm fell off.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan? He clearly departed on his own terms, with lots of gas
still in the tank. His decision had to have some impact on Sanders,
who was no doubt already toying with the idea himself after another
season in which he had run to lots of daylight while the Lions
wandered lost in their usual fog.
</P>
<P>
   In Barry's third season _ 1991 _ Detroit reached the NFC
Championship Game. The Lions haven't sniffed at the Super Bowl
since, and there's no reason to believe Bobby Ross' current lugs
have anything more than a .500 season in them, with or without
Barry.
</P>
<P>
   No one can be completely sure, though, what he is thinking, or
when the idea that culminated in Wednesday's farewell statement
germinated. Sanders has traveled to London, where his anonymity
figures to be secure. The Brits wouldn't recognize Barry, who
stands only 5-8 in loafers, if he wore his Lions helmet down Oxford
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, they didn't have a clue who Julius Erving was.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, Sanders' physique holds the key to what he's really up
to. Jordan's retirement surprised no one because he hadn't been
working out, and the good life was beginning to show on his person,
which turned up regularly on glitzy golf courses and at Las Vegas
gaming tables.
</P>
<P>
   Should Barry still be at his fighting weight _ 200 pounds,
roughly _ he's probably not done with the NFL just yet. But to find
that out, we have to get a good look at him first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
