<SLUG> BC-SAFECO-FOOD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JANITORS HELPED WITH FOOD SERVICE ON SAFECO'S OPENING NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON AND SARAH SKIDMORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Temporary janitors were shifted to food service duty
during Safeco Field's opening night, public health officials
confirmed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials admit they don't know exactly what took place,
or how many workers were involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they'd been taking out the garbage, we would expect that
they would at least have to have changed their clothes and washed
their hands,'' said Steve Curry, senior food safety inspector for
Public Health _ Seattle &AMP; King County.
</P>
<P>
   Volume Services America Inc., the food vendor at Safeco Field,
has received numerous citations for food safety violations since
the stadium's opening July 15. The company has said concessionaires
at the Seattle Mariners' new ballpark were under extraordinary
pressure on opening night as frustrated patrons waited in long
lines for food.
</P>
<P>
   Curry said Alton Hutcheson, general manager for Volume Services
at Safeco Field, acknowledged that workers hired to do clean-up
around the food stands were transferred ``on the spur of the
moment'' to help with food services. The exact number could not be
determined Wednesday, although a food service worker, who asked
that his name not be used, told the Seattle Post-Intelligencer it
involved about 20 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Hutcheson) said they were all put into the condiment
areas,'' Curry said. This would still require health department
certification, he said, but can by law be done within two weeks of
starting any food service work.
</P>
<P>
   Curry said he told Hutcheson that all of these clean-up workers
transferred to food service should have been given immediate
training in basic hygiene, such as proper hand-washing and using
bleach-water mixtures to clean-up spills. Hutcheson did not say if
the workers had received the training. But because he was assured
that the job shift only involved condiments, Curry said he wasn't
too concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking his word on that,'' Curry said. He said this
potential infraction was not as high a priority as the 50 other
``red critical'' violations at Safeco Field that had posed an
immediate threat of spreading foodborne illness.
</P>
<P>
   Hutcheson did not return telephone calls late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``(It's) something we'll look into,'' said Elaine Richner,
spokeswoman for Volume Services at company headquarters in
Spartanburg, S.C. She said Hutcheson had made himself available
earlier for questions from the media and was too busy to answer
further questions Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Volume Services held a news conference Wednesday along with a
food safety training session for Safeco Field concessions
supervisors. Aiming to avoid a costly ``third strike'' on public
health violations, the company is requiring more extensive food
safety training for its work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The training further emphasizes that these things need to be
taken seriously,'' Hutcheson said at the morning news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Concession stands and kiosks operated by Volume Services at
Safeco Field received 24 ``red critical'' food safety violations on
the first visit by public health inspectors and 26 ``red critical''
violations on the second visit. Seven of the second set of
citations were repeat offenses. These violations require action to
prevent the spread of foodborne illness. If the stands and kiosks
already cited twice earn a third violation within a year, public
health officials say they will be temporarily shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisors and managers have already been through a similar
company training program. Wednesday's ServSafe training was taught
by SYSCO Corporation and was created by the Educational Foundation
of the National Restaurant Association. The class learned about
safe food handling, storing and preparation of foods, temperature
danger zones and potential biological, chemical and physical
hazards of food.
</P>
<P>
   Stand and kiosk workers will go through a condensed version of
the training before the next home game Friday. Some workers have
gone through the company training and all have earned the
certification required by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a fan comes out here Friday or was out here last Thursday
and had food from Food Services, they should be assured it is as
safe as you can go,'' Hutcheson said.
</P>
<P>
   Hutcheson said one of the primary contributing factors leading
to the violations was the short window of time in which the vendors
had to set up the stands and kiosks. Some of the violations, which
included a lack of paper towels and soap at the washing stations,
were the result of equipment problems. The holders for these items
have been replaced by larger ones so the materials will not run out
during games. However, for the storage and temperature violations,
Hutcheson said, ``there is no excuse for that, but it has been
corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutcheson said Volume Services was originally going to be
allowed access to the stands in April and the date then gradually
slid forward until July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole thing has been blown out of proportion
because the stands were given to us only three days before,''
Hutcheson said. ``Any new facility is like this.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged he would keep some of the stands closed if he
had to do it over again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
