r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SEATS-KAN &LR;      07-29 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SEATS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES ARE EXPECTED TO MAKE CHILD CAR SEATS MORE STABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The biggest changes in children's car seats
in at least two decades are beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Safety seats made after Sept. 1 must come equipped with tether
straps that will attach to an anchor, which usually will be on the
back shelf under the rear window of the car. Most model year 2000
cars and light trucks will come equipped to handle the tethers.
Retrofit kits also are available for many older models.
</P>
<P>
   And that is just the beginning. A new way to secure the base of
the car seat will start showing up next year. The new method will
dispense with using the vehicle's seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   The result will be a somewhat more expensive car seat, but one
that should be safer and easier to use. The addition of the tether
strap by itself is expected to make the car seat far more stable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times are changing and this is good,'' said Ronda Barrett, a
child-development coordinator at the University of Kansas Medical
Center in Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   The changes come after years of complaints that car seats are
too difficult to use and consequently don't do their job.
</P>
<P>
   Most children ages 6 or under who are killed in traffic
accidents aren't in car seats. But each year about 230 children in
that age group are killed and 66,000 are injured in traffic
accidents even though they're in safety seats. Some of those
fatalities and injuries are due to incorrectly installed seats,
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Safety Traffic Administration, the federal
agency pushing the seat redesign, points to a study in four states,
including Missouri, showing that 80 percent of car seats are
misused or installed incorrectly.
</P>
<P>
   Instructions for installing the seats can be difficult to
follow. Aggravating the situation are features in cars and light
trucks. Seat cushions, for example, often aren't level and make a
child's car seat unstable.
</P>
<P>
   The car seat redesign is expected to go a ``long way to address
these issues,'' said David Campbell, vice president of research and
development for Century Products, a car seat manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Sept. 1, child car seats must be made with tether
straps. The strap will add about $10 to the cost of the seat. The
nylon strap goes from the top back of the seat to an anchor at the
rear of the car. Children will still have a harness to hold them
into the seat.
</P>
<P>
   The tether will hook into an anchor installed on the vehicle. In
a car, the anchor will usually be on the shelf under the rear
window. In a minivan, the tether will probably be draped over the
back of the seat and hooked into an anchor on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   At least 80 percent of the year 2000 models will come with at
least two tether anchors installed as factory equipment. Some of
the 2000 models _ the Ford Windstar and Chevrolet Impala, for
instance _ have already arrived in dealers' showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support it (the tether) wholeheartedly,'' said Artie
Martin, a safety engineer for General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Some details are still being worked out for the remainder of the
car seat redesign. But starting in the fall of 2000 and over the
following three years, a bar will be installed in new vehicles
where the top and bottom seat cushions meet. Instead of using the
vehicle's seat belts, the car seat will clip on the bar. The tether
will continue to be used at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago the tether was dropped as a mandatory feature
of child car seats because it wasn't used. And the car seat as then
designed required the strap to keep it from tipping too far forward
in a crash.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 20 years, most car seats relied on the vehicle's
seat belts to keep them from tipping too far forward _ no more than
32 inches, according to federal regulations. But that required the
seat belts to tightly fit through the car seat, which is often a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new design, a tethered car seat can tilt forward no
more than 28 inches in crash tests.
</P>
<P>
   That's a substantial improvement, said Stephanie Tombrello,
director of SafetyBeltSafe, a national group promoting the use of
child safety seats.
</P>
<P>
   But there are concerns. One of the biggest is what to do about
people who have older seats and cars without the tether anchors.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the redesigned car seats will continue to
work without the tether. You'll be no worse off, although you won't
get the improved performance.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers, however, are coming out with retrofit kits to put
the tether anchors in older models. General Motors, for example,
has them for most vehicles back to the 1989 models. It will also
install one anchor free per customer.
</P>
<P>
   A new car seat with the tether can already be purchased. And
some of the car seats already sold came with a hole where a tether
can be attached. The tethers can be purchased at stores that sell
the car seats.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McGinley, general manager of the Superior Chevrolet
dealership in Merriam, Kan., said his dealership had stocked
retrofit kits to install the anchors on older models.
</P>
<P>
   But news about the changes is just beginning to reach many other
dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Looper of Kearney, Mo., can testify to that. The volunteer
firefighter has seen what a car accident can do to a child. She
takes all the precautions she can for her two children. When it
came to a recent purchase of a new car, she wanted one with tether
anchors. But the car salespeople she spoke to weren't aware of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had no idea what we were talking about,'' she said. She
finally purchased a Ford Windstar that comes with the tether
anchors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
