u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELFARE-REFORM-SPI &LR;      07-29 1589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-REFORM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESSES - AND FAILURES - IN STATE'S WELFARE REFORM OF TWO YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT GAVIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLYMPIA, Wash. _ The welfare reform experiment was failing for
DeAnn Prentice, a 36-year-old single mother. She had found and lost
two jobs, and on a day about a year ago, things took what seemed
another turn for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to apply for a job at a Yakima hotel, she got lost
and ended up at another hotel. Two months out of work and fearing
she would lose benefits under Washington state's welfare reform
law, she filled out an application, anyway, and went home, feeling
desperate and defeated.
</P>
<P>
   But just 90 minutes later, the hotel called her in for an
interview. Today, Prentice is completing her first year as a night
auditor at the Doubletree Hotel, a job that pays $7.25 an hour,
with health insurance. More important, it offers a career.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice says she is one of the lucky ones, not only for this
fortunate turn, but also because she had the education _ nearly two
years of college _ that made her attractive to employers. Many of
her neighbors in Yakima's 801 Central Street housing project,
Prentice said, lack the skills, education and experience that
helped her make the transition to work after 11 years of welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice and her neighbors represent both the success and
challenges that face Washington after two years of welfare reform.
When Gov. Gary Locke marks the anniversary of WorkFirst in a visit
to a Seattle training program on Thursday, he will tout a record
that includes a 30 percent reduction in caseloads; budget savings
of more than $100 million a year; and a cultural change in the
welfare system that now values work, first.
</P>
<P>
   But even with this long list of accomplishments, lawmakers,
administrators and advocates for the poor say the hard work is just
beginning. Left on the rolls are the most difficult cases _ drug
and alcohol abusers, victims of domestic violence, people without
education or skills, and immigrants who don't speak English _ while
many who have found jobs still live in the margins.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking the cycle of poverty will mean more investments in
education, training, child care, health care and transportation,
many policy-makers and advocates agree. The question facing the
state in this time of prosperity is how many of those investments
will be made, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time when we have resources to deal with these
issues,'' said Rep. Kip Tokuda, the Democratic co-chairman of the
House Children's and Family Services Committee. ``It's not just
putting them in dead-end jobs in a very good economy. If it is,
then we're basically privately supporting them in poverty, instead
of publicly supporting them in poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington's WorkFirst program, passed by a
Republican-controlled Legislature, went into effect Aug. 1, 1997,
about a year after the Republican-controlled Congress approved the
national welfare reform law.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's program takes a carrot-and-stick approach. It
provides transitional income assistance, health insurance and child
care benefits while also offering job training, placement and
education opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   It also reduces benefits by up to 40 percent for those who fail
to seek or take steps to find work, and sets a five-year limit for
staying on public assistance. About 3,000 recipients are sanctioned
each month, according to the state Department of Health and Social
Services. Critics say it relies too much on the stick, and fails to
allow the flexibility needed to help people succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Dent, a Seattle mother of four, recently completed a
clerical training program and will leave the welfare rolls next
week, even though she has yet to find a job.
</P>
<P>
   Dent, whose days begin at 6 a.m. getting her children off to
school before attending a training program she will soon complete,
said state caseworkers had no understanding of the demands she
faced trying to care for her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They browbeat you,'' she said. ``They have these classes for,
you know _ life skills, and if you miss an hour, you have to start
over again. You may go for two or three days, and if you have a
sick child, and miss an hour, you start all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   By other measures, however, the program appears a success.
Helped by the booming economy, welfare caseload reductions have far
exceeded original projections.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the number of welfare cases fell to 59,712 _ 30 percent
below the target of about 85,000 set by the Legislature. The figure
also represents the lowest rate of public assistance in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   When WorkFirst began, the state had nearly 100,000 cases, with
each case typically representing a family. Ken Miller, Locke's
welfare policy adviser, points to other indications the program is
working: the average wage paid to former welfare recipients _ more
than $8 an hour _ is among the highest in the nation, and many earn
more money six months after beginning work, according to a
Department of Social and Health Services survey.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of people returning to welfare within a year has also
declined, from about 20 percent to 15 percent, according to recent
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kind of factors are real encouraging,'' Miller said.
``Fewer people are coming back to welfare. We have a vision to make
it a lasting change, to stay with people and give them a good
chance to move ahead and make a good life for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Prentice, the mother of two, now believes she has a chance for a
good life. She's had her job for about a year, and soon expects
another raise. Her immediate goal is to get off the overnight shift
and work days, and one day move into management.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice admits the welfare reform law pushed her to get back in
the work force. She also said that without pressure to find a job,
she probably would not have accepted the bookkeeping job _ a job
for which she had no prior training.
</P>
<P>
   ``It forced me to take a chance,'' she said. ``I like the fact
that I'm able to maintain my household without any help from
welfare. I want to stay with the corporation, move out of here and
transfer to a bigger hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   There are any number of success stories like Prentice, but
advocates for the poor say they are only part of the picture. What
remains unknown is where most former welfare recipients end up, and
whether they have merely joined the ranks of the working poor.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Donlea, executive director of Washington Works, a job
training program, said his agency is seeing clients who lack the
most basic skills, such as understanding the need to show up for
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Dannhardt, executive director of Triumph Treatment Services
in Yakima, said her clients face additional barriers as they try to
break free of welfare: drug and alcohol addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to be on welfare,'' she said. ``But we're
talking about women who can academically perform at the third- and
fourth-grade level.''
</P>
<P>
   Little is known about those who leave welfare and where they end
up. Some point to the effect on private charities as an indicator
that not all are escaping poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Food banks across the state say they've seen little change in
demand despite the booming economy. Northwest Harvest said visits
to 270 food banks and meals programs it supplies have increased
slightly over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   In some counties, however, visits have increased 50 percent and
more. In Mason county the number of people going to food banks has
doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Boutwell, who runs the Hood Canal Food Bank in Hoodsport,
said demand is up 35 percent over the past year. He blames it on a
poor economy that has too many people working in low-wage jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The so-called welfare reform has been more successful where
there are a lot of jobs, not so here,'' Boutwell said. ``It has
worked against us. It just seems there is a larger and larger gulf
developing between the `haves' and the `have nots.'''
</P>
<P>
   Al Poole, director of Operational Emergency Center in South
Seattle, said he has seen the impact of welfare reform in the
number of families coming on `baby day', when center distributes
diapers, formula and other infant care products. The numbers have
jumped from an average of 200 to more than 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in Seattle since 1968, and I've never seen times
better,'' Poole said. ``I'm wondering what will really happen if we
have a downturn.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the governor's welfare adviser, said the Locke
administration is committed to making welfare reform a way to
improving lives, not just maintaining them in poverty. The state
will spend about $700 million helping welfare recipients over the
next year, reinvesting about half the money saved from reduced
caseloads and expanding programs to help develop skills needed to
succeed in the job market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tough row to hoe,'' he said. ``We have only taken
steps to making permanent changes in the welfare system. We have
not yet demonstrated this can be a lasting change.''
</P>
<P>
   Prentice said she hopes she's made a lasting change. But she
also knows how difficult those changes can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're scared to death,'' she said. ``You're looking for a
job. If you don't have education, you don't have transportation,
and they're taking what you do have (in benefits) away from you,
it's really scary. It puts you in a really desperate situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer reporter Judd Slivka contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
