<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOVE-AD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN'S LOVE SPURS MONUMENT IN NEWSPRINT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Dennis McCarthy is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily
News.) 
By DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``I was married 55 years to one woman. I loved
her. What else can I tell you?'' _ Max Odrezin.
</P>
<P>
   Not much, Max. That about says it all. A lot of people search
their whole lives and never find what you and Rhoda had.
</P>
<P>
   You know you were a lucky guy, which explains the picture in the
paper the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Explains why a guy walks into a newspaper office on the second
anniversary of his wife's death, just like he did on the first, and
buys a big spot on the obit page to show the world how beautiful
she was and how much he still misses her.
</P>
<P>
   Class act, Max. There isn't a woman alive who wouldn't want the
same treatment after she's gone.
</P>
<P>
   She was quite a looker, Max, that wife of yours. A real siren.
That picture of her sitting on top of a suitcase _ dressed to the
nines and flashing a smile that could kill _ is a knockout.
</P>
<P>
   She always played the dumb blonde in movies, you told me
Wednesday. Whether it was the role of one of the dancers in
``Around the World in 80 Days,'' or the cashier who fired Doris Day
in ``Love Me or Leave Me'' with James Cagney.
</P>
<P>
   Helene Drake was her stage name. The dumb blonde.
</P>
<P>
   Only she wasn't dumb, was she, Max? No, she was as smart as a
whip, and could see through all the phoniness of Hollywood, and all
the casting couch directors who promised to make her a star.
</P>
<P>
   You two used to laugh about it, didn't you? Come home at the end
of the day and trade war stories.
</P>
<P>
   You'd tell her about how some panhandler got another free meal
out of you over at your Van Nuys restaurant, where the word was out
that you were a soft touch for a hard luck story.
</P>
<P>
   She'd tell you about her day, how some producer wanted her to
fly up to his cabin in the Sierras over the weekend to screen test
for a role. Yeah, right, buddy. Fat chance.
</P>
<P>
   They never could see past the blond hair, could they, Max?
Couldn't see the Rhoda Tomack you fell in love with back in
Brooklyn, not the Helene Drake screen testing in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The New York doll working as a dancer at the World's Fair when
she walked into the Brooklyn stationery store you managed back in
1941, and headed for the candy counter to buy a Mr. Goodbar, her
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   She slid the nickel across the counter at you, and what'd you
do, Max? You slid it back. On the house, you said.
</P>
<P>
   Got to her heart through her sweet tooth, didn't you, Max? It
worked beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, you guys were spending more time at Ebbets Field
watching the Bums play baseball than you did at work.
</P>
<P>
   But then the war touched your lives and you two had a big
decision to make in a hurry. You asked, and Rhoda said yes.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months later, your young wife was kissing you
goodbye, like a lot of young wives.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years later, you were in Europe getting shot up
pretty bad. Bad enough that when you came home in '45, the doctors
told you having your own children was out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   Rhoda welcomed you home, and told you exactly what you wanted to
hear. It was OK. We'll adopt, she said.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what you guys did later, moving to California in 1946
after coming home from the war and finding that your old job at the
stationery store had been given to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   But it all turned out for the best, didn't it, Max? After a
couple of years driving a delivery truck for the old Owl Drugstore
chain out here, you had saved up enough to open your own
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   First it was Drakes on Wilshire Boulevard for about 10 years
until the landlord doubled the rent on you, then the Patio in Van
Nuys for an additional 30, where you got that rep as having a soft
heart for a hard luck story.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rhoda's modeling was leading to her first movie job
as one of those bathing beauties behind Esther Williams. Rhoda
didn't swim too well, you said, but she had no problem filling out
a bathing suit.
</P>
<P>
   But those movie days ended when the '50s did. It was finally
time to adopt those kids you'd talked about, and start a family.
</P>
<P>
   Helene Drake, dumb blonde, retired.
</P>
<P>
   Rhoda Odrezin, mother, took over.
</P>
<P>
   And now she's gone, and you're still hurting.
</P>
<P>
   Walking into a newspaper office on the second anniversary of her
death to buy space on the obit page to show the world how beautiful
she was, and how much you still miss her.
</P>
<P>
   Class act, Max.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
