<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT-FARMS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHERING HEAT, LACK OF RAIN ARE MORE THAN INCONVENIENCE FOR
FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA and JERRY BERRIOS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ You don't have to tell Max Hockemeier about
the fickle nature of, well, nature.
</P>
<P>
   Hockemeier's farm had too much rain this spring, when showers
flooded his Ray County fields and forced him to replant his crops.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when those plants could sorely use the rain, there's barely
a hint of it in sight. Even worse, the heavy spring rains weakened
his replanted crop, which hasn't developed roots deep enough to
find adequate moisture.
</P>
<P>
   While others lament the 100-degree heat, farmers like Hockemeier
fret about the lack of precipitation. Kansas City has received 0.39
inches this month, about one-tenth the normal total.
</P>
<P>
   Nurseries, nature centers, golf courses and lawns _ any places
where green slowly is turning to brown _ feel the stress, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Hockemeier has felt Mother Nature's whims as much as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   He heard forecasts for rain on Wednesday. Although other areas
received a shower, he saw only a tenth of an inch. That evaporated
before lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you farm, you know the one thing you can't control is the
weather. So when the clouds come up and you get that ray of hope
and it just passes you by...'' said Hockemeier, who farms south of
Richmond, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say you ever get used to the disappointment,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But farmers aren't suffering alone, and the oppressive heat wave
is exacting more than an economic toll: It has claimed 49 lives
across the country, 18 in Missouri. St. Louis confirmed five more
deaths on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals in the Kansas City area reported no deaths or serious
heat-related injuries on Wednesday; two deaths have been reported
in the area since the latest heat outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures in Kansas City reached 101 degrees downtown on
Wednesday with a heat index of 114 degrees; Wednesday's high at
Kansas City International Airport was 98.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters expect dryness to continue through the weekend. They
note a chance of rain on Saturday but say not to count on it.
</P>
<P>
   In the country, miles away from smog, high-rises and concrete,
living things of other types are feeling the strain, too.
</P>
<P>
   Leaves are wilting, turning brown and falling off. Animals have
to travel farther to find water because their usual watering holes
are probably dried up, biologists say.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Reed, director of the Parkville Nature Sanctuary, said the
ground is cracked and the bugs, mosquitoes and ticks are out. But
the deer, raccoons, turtles, possums and foxes haven't been seen
lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are just resting,'' Reed said. ``It's just so
hot.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly ideal for humans, either.
</P>
<P>
   Because the center has no air-conditioned building, officials
have put July programs, such as hikes, on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Nature sanctuaries and centers are nursing stressed trees,
plants, flowers and grass. Some are watering, others are letting
nature decide.
</P>
<P>
   Even with no relief in sight, all the centers think their plants
will bounce back after some steady rain or cloudy days.
</P>
<P>
   Helene Miller, an urban forester for the Missouri Department of
Conservation's Kansas City office, said trees planted in the past
three years need special attention.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said a tree ideally should receive an inch of rain per
week during its growing season, from April to October. It's best to
soak the tree once or twice a week, she said, instead of watering
it a little every day.
</P>
<P>
   She added that it's a typical summer for this area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have definitely seen worse than this,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the flora at the Martha Lafite Thompson Nature Sanctuary
in Liberty, Mo., isn't exactly embracing the dryness.
</P>
<P>
   A hawthorn tree is so confused that it's producing red berries
that normally don't appear until fall. Visitors can see right
through the usually lush redbud tree, whose green leaves have faded
to orange and brown, now dotting the ground.
</P>
<P>
   But all is not lost.
</P>
<P>
   The turnout at the Excelsior Springs (Mo.) Golf Course is about
a third as high as normal. Those who play find brown grass draping
bone-dry dirt.
</P>
<P>
   But the dry course means drives will bounce on the dry fairways,
carrying them an extra 50 to 100 yards. That could turn Joe Duffer
into Tiger Woods for a day.
</P>
<P>
   At Powell Gardens, between Lee's Summit and Warrensburg, Mo.,
the staff is watering every day. The greenery still looks green.
</P>
<P>
   But another week or two of this heat and ``we might not look as
beautiful as we usually do in the summer,'' said Eric Tschanz,
executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers need relief in a hurry, too.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide in Missouri, 20 percent of the corn crop is reported
in poor or very poor condition, twice as high as last week.
Soybeans are suffering at the same rate.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Townsend already is sure his yield will be down.
</P>
<P>
   As the dryness continues, Townsend said his corn and soybeans
were shutting down. They stop producing seeds in a desperate
attempt to stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they're fighting for moisture, they'll stop making ears
(of corn) or growing soybeans. Unfortunately, those are the two
things I need,'' said Townsend, who farms about 2,000 acres near
Orrick, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Although recent sprinkles have added to the miserable humidity,
Townsend said they help plants, which absorb moisture from the air.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't enough for other farmers. Several said they need
steady rain in the next week to avoid large, irreversible losses.
</P>
<P>
   Again, blame it on the rain.
</P>
<P>
   The above-normal rainfall of May and June pampered the crops,
said Dwight Gigstad of the Farmers Cooperative Association in
Edgerton, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Because crops received so much rain, they didn't develop the
roots they use to search out water below the soil, Gigstad said.
Now, in the ``critical stage,'' is when the plants could use those
roots, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Townsend is holding out hope.
</P>
<P>
   One good rain and he'd be happy. He'd forget about Mother
Nature's weeks of neglect. He'd overlook the flooding caused by
earlier downpours.
</P>
<P>
   But, after 20 years on the farm, he knows enough that the relief
would last only until the next crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad part of it is it's totally out of your control,'' he
said. ``This farming thing, we're an unhappy bunch. It's either too
wet or too dry. Very seldom do you find us where everything is just
right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
