<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8126 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYCLIST-CANCER-KAN &LR;      07-29 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYCLIST-CANCER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG'S CYCLING TRIUMPH INSPIRES, AMAZES OTHERS WITH CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD RICHMAN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Throughout the 20 stages of the 1999 Tour de
France, over rocky terrain in the Pyrenees and across the rugged
Alps, American cyclist Lance Armstrong rode as if he had something
to prove.
</P>
<P>
   It was simply this: There's always hope in the fight against
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, 27, won the Tour on Sunday. Cancer survivors
worldwide will sing his praises for years.
</P>
<P>
   Many watched the nearly monthlong race in awe as Armstrong
pedaled 2,292 miles while showing none of the effects of the
testicular cancer that spread to his brain and lungs and threatened
his life three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get back to the point where he is now is truly amazing,''
said Norm Stewart, a cancer survivor and the former men's
basketball coach at the University of Missouri-Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer survivors stick together like family. They're bound by
struggles _ the vomiting, weight reduction and hair loss. Stewart
doesn't know Armstrong, but he has kept an eye on the cyclist the
same way he used to track the Kansas Jayhawks' progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's remarkable how he overcame the physical part of it,''
Stewart said. ``I've been through the chemo. It zaps you. It takes
you down. But he made it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dying occurs to you when you have cancer. I tried to think
about living. You have to be mentally strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of cancer victims in sports is long. Dan Quisenberry,
Jim Valvano and Dick Howser succumbed to it. Arnold Palmer and Jim
Colbert are beating it.
</P>
<P>
   Golfer Paul Azinger, who posted his best season in 1993 when he
finished No. 2 on the money list, hasn't been the same since he was
diagnosed with lymphoma later that year. His best finish on the
money list since then was 50th in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Golfer Trevor Dodds, a member of the PGA Tour, returned from
testicular cancer and won a tournament. Kansas City Chiefs Hall of
Fame quarterback Len Dawson is whipping prostate cancer. Yet the
thought of it resurfacing haunts him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going on seven years since surgery, and I'm OK,'' Dawson
said Wednesday. ``I'm assuming it isn't (going to return), but it's
still in the back of my head that what if some of it did get into
my lymph nodes?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Armstrong was diagnosed with cancer. Some of the tumors
in his abdomen were as big as golf balls. His right testicle was
removed, as were two brain lesions.
</P>
<P>
   The prognosis for Armstrong was 50-50 _ that he'd survive.
Still, he'd bike 30 to 50 miles daily after a weeklong session of
chemotherapy treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong lost 12 pounds, and his hair fell out. It got so bad
that Armstrong was quoted as saying he was ``on his death bed.''
Yet he persevered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance isn't a miracle. He just reaffirmed there's life after
cancer,'' said Chris Brewer, also a victim of testicular cancer and
now the caretaker of Armstrong's Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Dodds, who plays in the first round of the Canon Greater
Hartford Open, said: ``He (Armstrong) had a worse case than I did.
It just goes to show you people who have gone through hardship can
come back better than they were before.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Geier, a Kansas City, Mo., oncologist, was amazed by
Armstrong's resilience. Geier said a typical testicular cancer
victim wouldn't be himself for at least six months to a year after
the chemotherapy. To then fight back and tackle such a grueling
test as the Tour de France is a testimonial to how far oncology has
come in battling testicular cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Geier said a combination of medicine and Armstrong's fortitude
was the remedy. There's a 2 percent chance Armstrong's cancer will
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed a level of determination I couldn't relate to.
Determination and guts,'' Geier said.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson, who won a Super Bowl, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Off the top of my head, I can't think of anything (that
compares to Armstrong's comeback),'' Dawson said. ``How many days
is that race? That would be grueling enough if you didn't have any
problems. He just showed what one is capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Geier said Armstrong overcame a cancer that carries one of the
most intense types of chemotherapy treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Treatments are relentless,'' Geier said.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, diagnosed with cancer six days after Armstrong, knows
the suffering. The veins in his arms became a pincushion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's shocking when the nurse comes in wearing these heavy
latex gloves and says if she spills the medicine, they'd have to
call in the HazMat (hazardous materials) team to clean it up,''
Brewer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had mood swings, lost my hair. It did increase my sense of
smell. I took every dry-scented flower and threw them in the closet
and said, `If you open it up, I'll kill you.' And fresh-baked
bread...it made me want to puke.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer and Armstrong linked forces through e-mail during and
after their chemotherapy. Brewer knows how Armstrong was able to
recover and compete at the highest level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though he appeared very ill, people said you could still
see the fire in his eyes,'' Brewer said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City businessman Paul Hunt is a former high school
football star and a sprinter on the track and field team at the
University of Kansas. He never cared about cycling until he learned
that he and Armstrong had a link. Hunt was diagnosed eight years
ago with chronic lymphocytic leukemia. Hunt suddenly was starved to
read all about Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought of myself when I read about him,'' Hunt said. ``And
I have to say, it's one of the greatest athletic feats ever in
terms of the odds. He should be dead or easily could have been. I'd
love to ask him questions about what he went through. Or at least
I'd like to tell him how much I admire him.''
</P>
<P>
   As he finished his cycling victory, Armstrong mouthed a few
words into the camera as he pedaled toward the Champs Elysees in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   He was sending a hello to Kelly Davidson, a cancer patient who
helped raise $17,000 for the Lance Armstrong Foundation, a
nonprofit organization that promotes cancer research. The
telephones have been busy at the foundation in Armstrong's home of
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Haussmann, the foundation's executive director, said one of
the calls this week was a $25,000 donation from Nike. The
foundation netted $400,000 last year and gave $300,000 of it to
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Including Nike, we've received about $50,000 in the last two
days,'' Haussmann said. ``If I had to get inside his mind, I'd say
Lance sees what he did as a victory for the cancer community. Lance
is committed to this. He just puts his head down, drives forward
and doesn't listen to the naysayers.''
</P>
<P>
   To reach Armstrong's Web site, go to www.laf.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
