r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SPELLMAN-     07-29 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SPELLMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS MIGHT SIGN ALONZO SPELLMAN TODAY, SOURCE SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys are discussing the
possibility of signing former Bears defensive end Alonzo Spellman
and an announcement could be made as soon as today, a source said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, who said this week that the team
would be pursuing a veteran to bolster their depleted defensive
line corps, declined to comment about Spellman.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Cowboys are always looking to improve their roster,
but he said there was nothing going on right now.
</P>
<P>
   Spellman's agent, Leigh Steinberg, was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   A source said the Cowboys have actually been looking at Spellman
since he was cut by the Bears last year, but have been treading
carefully because of his past problems.
</P>
<P>
   Spellman, the Bears' No. 1 draft choice in 1992, recorded 24
sacks in six years. But he did not play at all in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   His departure from the Bears before last season came after
several bizarre off-the-field issues that resulted in Spellman
seeking psychiatric help.
</P>
<P>
   Most prominent was a May 9, 1998, incident when he barricaded
himself in the home of his publicist for several hours before being
subdued.
</P>
<P>
   If Spellman has overcome his past issues, his addition would be
an immediate upgrade for the Cowboys' suspect pass rush and give
the team more options in their attempts to make up for the loss of
suspended defensive tackle Leon Lett. PAGE READY TO GO
</P>
<P>
   Despite missing the first day of training because of contract
negotiations, second-round pick Solomon Page said he was able to
catch up pretty quickly when he joined his teammates for workouts
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Page, who will vie for backup time on the offensive line at
guard and tackle, credits quick progress on his presence at the
team's two minicamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not far behind,'' Page said. ``I learned a lot in the
minicamps, so I was ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said the rookie was ``a little rusty''
Wednesday but agreed that the presence of the rookies at minicamps
offset any negatives of missing a day or two of training camp.
McKNIGHT EAGER TO LEARN
</P>
<P>
   Veteran receivers Michael Irvin, Raghib Ismail and Ernie Mills
practice for an hour each day catching passes from quarterback Troy
Aikman. They won't start full-fledged camp work until tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, James McKnight, who has spent the past five years in
Seattle, finds himself as the old man among boys.
</P>
<P>
   His training camp began Monday along with other young receivers,
mainly because he wasn't acquired by the Cowboys until June. That
meant he missed both the team's minicamps and the voluntary
coaching sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish the trade would have happened earlier,'' the 6-foot-1,
198-pound McKnight said. ``I went to four minicamps up there. I
would have liked to get one camp in Dallas under my belt. So, I'm
here just looking to get things done in training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   McKnight did get the aid of quarterbacks coach Buddy Geis, who
gave up a couple of weeks of his vacation to tutor the former
Liberty University star in the nuances of the Cowboys' intricate
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Once he gets the offense down, McKnight will take his place
alongside the big three.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought me in here to help build a good receiver corps,''
McKnight said. ``Along with Michael, Rocket and Ernie, I hope to
get in there and work this thing out.'' EKUBAN, ZELLNER IMPRESS
</P>
<P>
   What was impressive about rookie defensive end Ebenezer Ekuban
(first round) and Peppi Zellner (fourth round) in college has been
in evidence in camp.
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban, a former North Carolina star, was the fastest defensive
lineman at the NFL combine, running the 40-yard dash in 4.7
seconds. Zellner, out of tiny Fort Valley State, was No. 2,
clocking 4.72 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their quickness has showed up,'' Gailey said. ``A lot of
times, it's not obvious on the practice field. But you can see it
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban is expected to contribute immediately as a third-down
pass rusher. Zellner, who has played a little more than a year of
football since leaving junior college in 1995, is considered a
project. He played only three games in 1996 at Fort Valley, traded
in his football uniform for a basketball jersey in 1997 before
finishing his senior season in football in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   However, his speed could land him on the field earlier than
expected. PRACTICE CHANGE
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have changed the time and location of Saturday
night's practice. Instead of 8-10 p.m. at Memorial Stadium in
Wichita Falls, the team will practice from 6-8 p.m. at Midwestern
State. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
