<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8130 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEMICAL-CONTAMINATIO     07-29 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEMICAL-CONTAMINATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERBICIDE POSES RISK TO INFANTS, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR and RUTH IGOE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A common weed killer used on 70 million acres
of corn each year poses a serious health risk to bottle-fed
infants, according to a report released Wednesday by a national
environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This product is a serious threat to infants' health,'' said
Jane Houlihan, an author of the report ``Into the Mouths of
Babes.'' ``The government should be taking decisive action on
it....''
</P>
<P>
   The report was issued by the Environmental Working Group, which
has campaigned for years for a national ban of atrazine, a
suspected carcinogen now under review by the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The maker of atrazine on Wednesday called the report a bogus
attempt to discredit a safe and reliable herbicide.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Into the Mouths of Babes' might better be titled `Out of the
Mouths of Alarmists,' '' said Dave Whitacre, senior vice president
for Novartis Crop Protection Inc., the largest manufacturer of
atrazine.
</P>
<P>
   Whitacre also criticized the Environmental Working Group for
failing to have its report scientifically peer-reviewed, which
would evaluate whether the group's methodology was sound.
</P>
<P>
   Whitacre said current federal safety standards are so strict
that his company thinks a 22-pound toddler could drink 3,000
gallons of water a day for a lifetime without any health risks from
the herbicide.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based Environmental Working Group focused on
seven Corn Belt states, including Kansas and Missouri, where each
spring farmers apply atrazine to fields. The chemical shows up in
the drinking water of farm communities or large cities downstream.
Usually, it's found at levels below federal limits.
</P>
<P>
   But even such low levels pose serious health risks for infants _
especially if they're being fed formula made with tap water, the
Environmental Working Group said.
</P>
<P>
   The group based its calculations on EPA and state data on
atrazine levels in public drinking supplies and EPA data on how
much water infants ingest.
</P>
<P>
   The group estimated that in as many as 40 cities across the
Midwest, infants can exceed their legally allowable lifetime cancer
risk from atrazine by their first birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Larger water utilities, such as Kansas City and Johnson County
water departments, spend millions of dollars to remove the chemical
from drinking water. Both systems comply with federal limits.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA released a brief statement on Wednesday, addressing
atrazine but not the new report.
</P>
<P>
   ``EPA, recognizing that there may be special concerns for
children's exposure to atrazine, has been conducting a careful
scientific review in our pesticide protection program. The review
will be completed by next summer,'' according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
   An EPA official said Wednesday that the agency had not reviewed
the Environmental Working Group's scientific method in producing
its estimates for infant exposures to atrazine. It also had yet to
complete its own scientific analysis for infants, the EPA official
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a few days, the EPA is scheduled to meet a new deadline to
consider tightening the limits on a number of pesticides in food
and water, taking into account how infants ingest large quantities
of certain foods and liquids.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said Wednesday that, until the EPA completes its
special review of atrazine, which could result in tighter limits or
even a ban, they can do little but ensure that communities meet
current federal limits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, for example, 10 Missouri communities failed to meet the
limit of 3 ]parts per billion, which is based on a annual average
of four samples. Each of the last two years, though, only one
community in Missouri has averaged more than the federal limit. In
Kansas, usually one or two communities fail to meet that limit.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Working Group's president, Ken Cook, questioned
Wednesday whether it's fair for water utilities to have to pay for
chemical-removal costs and pass that cost on to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atrazine should be banned,'' Cook said. ``It shouldn't even be
in the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowering the federal limit, Cook's group added, would only make
it more difficult for smaller utilities to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Even in communities that do comply, the environmental group
found in its report, infants are exposed to too much atrazine. When
the government set its current limit, the report found it
underestimated by as much as 15 times a bottle-fed infant's
exposure to atrazine.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the report estimated that a bottle-fed infant in
Kansas City, Kan., can get a lifetime dose of atrazine in about
nine months. And that calculation is based on just 1.3 parts per
billion of atrazine _ not even half the legal limit _ in the water,
the group's Houlihan said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, Kan., water department officials add powdered
activated carbon to the water during treatment, as needed, to keep
atrazine levels low, said Don Gray, the city's assistant manager
for water operations.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, the Board of Public Utilities will open a new $56.5
million treatment plant that will filter out more atrazine than the
old plant, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to comply with federal regulations, but until there is
more substantial scientific data to substantiate what they claim
(about the dangers low atrazine levels), I don't know,'' Gray said.
``It's a heck of a debate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
