<SLUG> BC-SIGNATURE-GROUP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECT MARKETING FIRM CLOSES THREE OFFICES IN KANSAS CITY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Signature Group, a direct marketing
company, has closed its three area service centers and laid off
about 470 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The employees, who were let go last week, will receive two
months' pay, said Fanette Singer, a spokeswoman for the Signature
Group in Schaumburg, Ill. The company, however, is not providing
outplacement services for the workers.
</P>
<P>
   The company's three area offices were in Independence and
Grandview in Missouri, and in Kansas City, Kan. The Kansas City,
Kan., office was the biggest local office, with 250 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Signature Group is a subsidiary of Montgomery Ward &AMP; Co.,
which is emerging from bankruptcy reorganization. GE Capital Inc.
is in the process of acquiring all of Ward's operations.
</P>
<P>
   Singer said the Signature Group was not closing the offices
because of changes being undertaken by GE Capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to do with technological efficiencies we're gaining,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also closed two call centers in Florida last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Signature Group has about $650 million in annual revenue,
with about half its telemarketing and customer-service business
coming from Ward. The company also handles credit card inquiries
for oil companies and banks. General Electric Co. also is an
important client. Orders by mail also are handled by the Signature
Group.
</P>
<P>
   The company has 25 call centers around the country, Singer said.
</P>
<P>
   Call centers have been a growing industry in the Kansas City
area, employing more than 40,000 people. The demand for
customer-service and telemarketing representatives has been high.
That was one reason America West Airlines recently pulled out of
the market _ it was having trouble attracting and keeping workers
at competitive wages.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, GE Capital Retailer Financial Services cut more than
200 customer-service jobs at its call center in Merriam, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   But along with cutbacks, other companies have been building call
centers in the area. For example, H&AMP;R Block Inc. is building a call
center in Kansas City, Mo., that will employ more than 700 people
during peak seasonal periods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 0127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
