A8132 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-INCENTIVES-KAN &LR;      07-29 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-INCENTIVES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY OFFICIALS DELAY ACTION ON TAX BREAKS FOR FARMLAND,
AMERITRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK P. COUCH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Kansas City Council's Finance and Audit
Committee on Wednesday delayed action on tax-incentive plans for
Farmland Industries Inc. and Ameritrade Holding Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are asking the city for exemptions on property
taxes and sales taxes to help finance office buildings in the
Northland.
</P>
<P>
   Farmland is seeking tax breaks worth at least $10 million to
help construct the first building on a headquarters campus near
Kansas City International Airport and to finance road improvements
in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Ameritrade, an online discount brokerage based in Omaha, Neb.,
has requested a tax break valued at about $1 million to help buy a
vacant office building. Ameritrade hopes to convert the building
into a data center employing 23 persons.
</P>
<P>
   Both plans seek to use a rarely used tax-incentive tool that is
becoming more popular with city economic-development leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are asking the city to issue bonds and use the
proceeds to buy land and equipment for the companies. The city
would own the land, buildings and equipment and would lease it back
to the companies. The lease payments would retire the bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Because the city would own the land, buildings and equipment,
they would be exempt from sales and property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Platte County Presiding Commissioner Betty Knight asked city
leaders to develop a policy that would boost the role of county,
school and other elected officials in the process of granting such
tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The bond plans ``use county taxes at the discretion of the
city,'' Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can take taxes meant for schools, developmentally
disabled, mentally ill, libraries and seniors and use them to
attract business for up to 10 to 20 years, and we have no input,''
Knight said. ``That isn't the way we have worked before.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight said that she thought Farmland was an asset for Kansas
City but that she was concerned about a plan that could become a
model for future incentive packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a commissioner, I am always careful in making decisions
that I know will have to be made again and again and again,''
Knight said. ``In these development decisions, precedents are
always set and at times come back to haunt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmland is asking the city to issue $40 million in bonds to
assist in the farmer-owned cooperative's relocation to land near
the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Farmland is proposing to construct a six-story building that
would house 925 workers.
</P>
<P>
   The building, scheduled to open in February 2001, would include
a cafeteria, credit union branch office, a product test kitchen and
an employee fitness center.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Miller, a lawyer for Farmland, said it was possible, but
unlikely, that the city would become the owner of kitchen forks or
weight-room equipment in the new Farmland building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bond proceeds are not being used for everything and not
for anything that's getting moved over,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said most of the proceeds from the bonds would be used to
pay for land and the building.
</P>
<P>
   Miller also explained that the city would not face financial
risk because an independent lender would buy the bonds. Farmland
has already found a buyer for the bonds if they are approved by the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary benefit is the tax exemption,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   The value of the property and sales tax breaks would be $5.03
million, according to the City Planning and Development Department.
</P>
<P>
   Under the incentive package offered by the city, Farmland's new
development would also qualify for a rebate of up to half the
earnings and utilities taxes paid to the city for 20 years. The
value of that benefit, which would be used for road improvements,
would be as much as $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   A second office building is planned for the year 2005. It would
qualify for a similar earnings and utilities tax rebate from the
city if the project is started by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Ameritrade is asking the city to issue up to $44 million in
bonds to buy and equip a vacant office building. The purchase price
is $8.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   David Fenley, a lawyer for Ameritrade, said the value of the
incentive package was $1 million. Ameritrade would qualify for
property- and sales-tax breaks when the city uses the proceeds to
buy the land and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Fenley said the company preferred the Kansas City site but was
considering leasing an office in an unspecified city on the East
Coast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
