<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILINGUAL-PARROT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARROT'S SQUAWKS IN RUSSIAN, ENGLISH SEAL A HAPPY REUNION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nearly two dozen people, some from the far reaches
of the county, came to the West Valley animal shelter to claim an
exotic African gray parrot that flew its coop in Porter Ranch last
week.
</P>
<P>
   As proof of ownership, they brought receipts, pictures,
veterinary records, theft reports and sad stories.
</P>
<P>
   But only one person could make the parrot talk _ in English and
Russian _ so Wednesday she got to take her Oscar home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you understand?'' the bird squawked in Russian to Irina
Simmons, 33, as she was reunited with her bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very happy,'' Simmons said. ``I was pleased to see how
well he was taken care of here. He was totally content. He didn't
seem to miss anything at home where he lives in a wrought-iron cage
with a tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons lost the 5-year-old parrot July 21 when she was talking
with an animal handler about transporting Oscar and her dog to
Texas where she and her husband are moving.
</P>
<P>
   While she and the animal handler were talking, Oscar pushed open
the door to his bird cage and flew away. She searched for him and
put fliers up in her neighborhood, but had no luck.
</P>
<P>
   After a story about the parrot in the Daily News, a parade of
would-be owners came through the West Valley Animal Care and
Control Center in suburban Chatsworth, said Lt. Richard Felosky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Valley _ with more than 1 million residents, and half of
them wanted the bird. They wore me out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One person from Pomona, more than 30 miles east of downtown, and
a group of five from Malibu were easy to rule out, he said. Felosky
said he wanted to give Oscar to a 90-year-old woman whose gray
parrot was stolen, but then she took one look at Oscar and decided
it wasn't her bird.
</P>
<P>
   When Simmons heard that an African gray parrot was at the
shelter, she showed up to take home her bird. But once there, Oscar
only whistled and wouldn't talk _ not enough to prove ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hysterical,'' she said. ``I called my husband in Texas.
I called the Better Business Bureau. I felt helpless. I found him,
but I couldn't get him. But I was persistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons returned with pictures of Oscar sitting next to her dog
in the dog's water bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``He let me handle him,'' she said. ``He saw it was probably my
bird because Oscar was real cuddly.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Felosky said he needed more proof. He needed Oscar to
speak. And then, as Simmons was leaving, Oscar said, ``Hi, What's
up?'' in English and ``Do you understand?'' in Russian, she said.
</P>
<P>
   That cinched it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long, drawn-out process, but it was worth it,''
Felosky said. ``The owner is ecstatic. She thinks the sun rises and
sets on us because who would have thought anybody cared about her
parrot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
