<SLUG> BC-BLAIR-WITCH-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$35,000 `BLAIR WITCH' COULD WORK BIG BOX OFFICE MAGIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``The Blair Witch Project'' will be put to the
test this weekend as the ultra-low-budget horror film moves from
art houses to the nation's multiplexes.
</P>
<P>
   The results could be spectacular for the Santa Monica-based
company that is distributing the movie. ``Blair Witch'' has enough
potential as a mainstream hit that a $100 million domestic gross is
not out of the question, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heat on `Blair Witch' just keeps building,'' said Steven
Rothenberg, executive vice president for domestic distribution of
Artisan Entertainment. ``Our phones have been ringing off the hook
from distributors wanting to book it. Every year, there's one film
like this that comes completely out of the blue.''
</P>
<P>
   The behind-the-scenes story of ``Blair Witch'' is almost as
compelling as the on-screen action. The movie is a mock documentary
that follows three young filmmakers into the wilderness near
Burkittsville, Md., in search of a 200-year-old witch. It was made
in eight days for a grand total of $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   Artisan paid $1 million for the film when it received favorable
buzz at the Sundance Film Festival. That small investment paid off
when ``Blair Witch'' grossed an astounding $5 million in 10 days at
just 31 theaters across the country. The per-theater average last
weekend was a breathtaking $63,812, or five times the average for
box office leader ``The Haunting.''
</P>
<P>
   What that meant was that at the Nuart in West Los Angeles and
the Laemmle Playhouse 7 in Pasadena, many moviegoers were either
turned away or waited for hours to get into packed ``Blair Witch''
screenings. ``It was our plan to make this a hard ticket early
on,'' said Amir Malin, Artisan's president.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's on to 1,100 theaters this weekend, where it'll face two
major openings _ Samuel L. Jackson shark thriller ``Deep Blue
Sea,'' and the Julia Roberts-Richard Gere romantic comedy ``Runaway
Bride'' _ plus another horror film, ``The Haunting,'' which led
last weekend's box office with $33 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our polling shows that 80 percent of moviegoers want to see
this film and we've never ever seen numbers that high before,''
said Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source forecasting
service. By comparison, ``Runaway Bride'' has a 56 percent
want-to-see rating while ``Deep Blue Sea'' is at 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Malin has said ``Blair Witch'' could take in $75
million by the end of its run; Bucksbaum believes that number could
hit $85 million.
</P>
<P>
   Those forecasts carry credibility because of Artisan's decision
two weeks ago to book the film into a pair of megaplexes _ the AMC
Block 30 in Orange and the Mills 24 in Phoenix _ along with 25
art-house theaters. The AMC generated the top three-day gross in
the country at $164,354.
</P>
<P>
   ``By opening in two big commercial megaplexes, we proved to
exhibitors and other distributors that `Blair Witch' had great
commercial viability,'' Rothenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   And other studios flinched at that point, with Warner Bros.
moving the release date of ``Deep Blue Sea'' forward two days _ it
opened Wednesday at 2,854 theaters _ and Universal delaying
``Mystery Men'' for a week until Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost unheard of for studios to shift dates that close
to an opening,'' Bucksbaum noted. ``It was done to appease theater
owners because they want `Blair Witch.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Blair Witch'' will clearly be a serious force this weekend
amid what continues to be a sizzling summer. Bucksbaum predicts
``Runaway Bride,'' which Paramount is opening at more than 3,000
theaters, will lead with $20 million while ``Blair Witch'' could
take in $16 million to $18 million and battle for second with
``Deep Blue Sea'' and DreamWorks' second weekend of ``The
Haunting.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry trackers have been impressed by Artisan's bold
promotional campaign, which simply highlights the film's basic
premise _ that the footage was recovered a year after the
filmmakers disappeared. The Web site, blairwitch.com, never admits
the story is fiction and includes a timeline from the witch's
origin to the search for the missing film crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marketing on this film has been just tremendous,'' said
Paul Dergarabedian, president of Exhibitor Relations Co. ``There
are no big stars so they've managed to make the hook _ which is
`Did this really happen?' _ work very well for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that the films contains no special effects and
intentionally grainy, herky-jerky footage, audiences find ``Blair
Witch'' to be emotionally satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to believe it's true and it's such a unique idea
that it really doesn't matter whether it is,'' Bucksbaum said. ``If
you didn't know it was a hoax, you'd think it was real. And when
people watch it, people are riveted _ more so than they were for
`Independence Day' or `Jurassic Park.'''
</P>
<P>
   Artisan's original plan was to go to about 300 theaters this
weekend but as the buzz over ``Blair Witch'' built, that figure was
revised upward first to 700, then 900 and now 1,100. By next
weekend, Artisan plans to add 500 or 1,000 more theaters.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have `Blair Witch' in every theater of
importance,'' said Chandler Wood, head film buyer for the Los
Angeles-based Pacific Theatres chain. ``When a movie is this hot,
you find ways to get it into theaters. I don't know how it's going
to do in Middle America, but I think it will do quite well in our
theaters in California.''
</P>
<P>
   For theater owners, that means either reducing the number of
screens for current releases or saying farewell to holdover films
earlier than expected. That's a tricky line to walk for exhibitors
since they need to maintain good relations with the major studios
that supply most of their films.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the business of getting the money while you can, so
the best thing to do with `Blair Witch' is to get it on as many
screens as you can,'' said Richard Fay, president of AMC Films.
``We're scrambling as we speak to get more screens. Artisan has
created a tremendous want-to-see buzz for this movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Fay noted AMC's pioneering strategy of building megaplexes, with
as many as 30 theaters under one roof, pays off smartly when a film
like ``Blair Witch'' breaks out unexpectedly. ``We're blessed with
a greater number of screens and seats, so it's not really any
difficulty,'' he said. ``We have a lot of flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Can ``Blair Witch'' keep up its seemingly unstoppable momentum
once the first wave of screenings are over? ``I think it's on a
roll now,'' Fay said. ``It's beginning to step out beyond
adolescents and young adults. It's a real pleasant surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Blair Witch'' has already surpassed the performance of other
films made for next-to-nothing, such as 1994's ``Clerks'' and last
year's ``Pi,'' and is now poised to join other bargain-basement
blockbusters, such as ``Scream'' (which cost $14 million), ``Pulp
Fiction'' ($8 million) and ``The Full Monty'' ($3 million).
</P>
<P>
   ``Blair Witch'' has also already transformed Artisan into a
serious player following recent releases such as ``Wishmaster'' and
``Black Mask'' that have had only moderate success.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly based in Van Nuys and knowqh &QR; dY9tain[Y7t, !]4a c+W,e
</P>
</TEXT>
