<HEADLINE>
IHOP PROFITS SWEET AS SYRUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. _ Restaurant operator IHOP Corp.'s second
quarter per-share earnings are expected to rise nearly 16 percent
compared with the like year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts surveyed by First Call estimate that the Glendale-based
company _ the owner and franchiser of the International House of
Pancakes chain _ will earn 37 cents per share. The company is
expected to release its statement for the three-month period
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The company earned 32 cents per share in the comparable
three-month period last year.
</P>
<P>
   IHOP has exceeded analysts' expectations the past few quarters
and seems to be on track for continued earnings growth, said Brandy
Shin, a junior analyst with Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. in New York City,
which projected 37 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they continue to show good growth,'' Shin said.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate is based in part on the company's monthly
same-store sales _ that is, sales at outlets open at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while same-store sales were down 0.9 percent in
April, they rose 2.3 percent and 2.4 percent in May and June,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, in the first quarter ended March 31, net income
rose about 40 percent to $6.6 million from the prior year's $4.7
million. On a diluted per share basis, the company earned 65 cents,
up about 38 percent from 47 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
