<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECO IMPRESSIVE FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ OK, maybe there is hope for the season, or for
next season, or for mankind.
</P>
<P>
   If Robinson Checo, who was hit around worse than a
batting-practice pitcher in his previous stint with the Dodgers,
can turn around his game to the point he did Wednesday against
Cincinnati, anything and everything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the more improbable events of the season, Checo was
sensational while giving up one run in five innings as the Dodgers
beat the Reds 9-1 at Dodger Stadium for their second win in nine
games. Checo left the game with a tweaked groin muscle, but it
wasn't initially considered serious.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Arnold, who has a five-game suspension in the appeal
process, pitched the last four innings for his first major-league
save.
</P>
<P>
   Before Checo (1-0) was promoted from Triple-A Albuquerque to
make his first Dodgers start, manager Davey Johnson joked about
whether his name was Checo Robinson or Robinson Checo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't around long enough for me to find out,'' Johnson
said jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, well, now Mr. Checo will do just fine. This game was so
out of the norm, the Dodgers' Raul Mondesi walked a career-high
three times.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan was to pitch Checo against the Reds, skip him
in the rotation next time around and then make a determination of
what to do the next time a fifth starter was needed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Checo, who replaced lefty Carlos Perez, all but insured
another start with the Dodgers. And not only did he pitch
splendidly, he also had his first major-league hit. It scored two
in the Dodgers' four-run third as they built a 6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Former Dodgers lefty Dennys Reyes, making his first start of the
season after making 41 appearances in relief, lasted but 22/3
innings. Reyes (2-2), involved in the Jeff Shaw-Paul Konerko trade,
gave up six runs on five hits and walked five.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the numbers some thought Checo would have, given the
way his other Dodger Stadium appearances went.
</P>
<P>
   After being one of three minor-leaguers acquired in the
salary-dumping Dave Mlicki trade with Detroit, Checo was hit hard
in two outings. He allowed five runs on eight hits in 31/3 relief
innings in his Dodgers debut and then allowed two runs in one-third
of an inning.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Johnson said Checo's fastball wasn't as lively as the
reports he had heard. The 26-year-old right-hander from the
Dominican Republic, once a coveted pitching prospect in Japan, was
sent to Albuquerque with a 17.18 ERA and was supposed to never be
heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had the same initial reaction I did when he went down,''
Johnson said. ``They worked with him and he's been pitching
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, funny thing. Checo was placed in Albuquerque's starting
rotation, his mechanics were ironed out and his velocity increased
to the mid-90 mph range.
</P>
<P>
   He was still erratic, but that changed lately. In his last two
starts, Checo went 2-0 with a 2.84 ERA and earned the nod to take
Perez's spot. It was Checo's third major-league start and eighth
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Checo, whose only other major-league win came in 1997 when
pitching with the Boston Red Sox, allowed three hits, walked four
and struck out four while lowering his ERA to 8.31. He was also
helped by an early lead as the Dodgers scored on Gary Sheffield's
ground ball out in the first and Angel Pena's sacrifice fly in the
second.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds made it 2-1 in the third when Dmitri Young doubled to
score Mike Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheffield homered to start the four-run rally in the third.
It was his 18th homer. Eric Karros then doubled, Devon White had an
RBI single and three batters later, Checo stroked his first career
hit to score two runs and give the Dodgers a 6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Grudzielanek added a fifth-inning two-run homer to make it
8-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
