<SLUG> BC-BBA-SEGUI-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS TRADE SEGUI TO TORONTO FOR BULLPEN HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There was a time when the Mariners added
veterans at the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, we've been the team going out and seeking players,
and now we're the team that people are seeking to help them out,''
right fielder Jay Buhner said Wednesday after first baseman David
Segui was traded to the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good situation to be in. We did it to ourselves. As
a team, you control your own destiny, and this year we're
struggling as a team. It's certainly not over yet ... but we've got
a hell of a challenge ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days after trading outfielder Butch Huskey to the Boston Red
Sox for one minor league pitcher, the Mariners sent Segui to
Toronto for two. Right-hander Tom Davey and left-hander Steve
Sinclair, who both had been pitching for Class AAA Syracuse, will
join the Mariners bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Woodward said more moves may be coming before Saturday's
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward, M's vice president of baseball operations, said
Wednesday's deal accomplished his goal of getting players who can
help both now and in the future. He is hoping Davey and Sinclair
can match the success of Freddy Garcia and John Halama, the
pitchers acquired from the Houston Astros last July when ace Randy
Johnson was dealt.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward said he had no concerns about making two trades this
week with the teams leading the wild-card race, Boston and Toronto.
He said there was ``limited interest'' in Segui, and Toronto made
the best proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't pitchers in A-ball, they are pitchers in triple-A
and they've both had a little taste of the big leagues,'' Woodward
said. ``They can come in and help us win. If we have success with
these kids as we did with Garcia and Halama, then they can help us
immediately and certainly for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And plus, we were not going to be able to sign Segui. We made
an offer to him at the beginning of the season that was a very good
offer, and that wasn't going to work out. Instead of just losing
David Segui, we were able to get some pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui is in the final year of a two-year, $4.75 million
contract. He hired a new agent, Scott Boras, over the winter, and
the Mariners offered an extension for three years and close to $18
million during spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Based on deals for other first basemen, such as Kevin Young of
the Pittsburgh Pirates, who is on a four-year, $24 million
contract, Boras and Segui were seeking a four-year commitment.
Boras said he called Woodward a few weeks ago, thinking Segui's
success this season might have shown the M's he would be a wise
investment for a fourth year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said we were interested in moving this thing along,'' Boras
said. ``The difference was really just the term of years. We were
not eons apart on the dollar issue. Frankly we were within the
ballpark of one another. The issue was really a three-year or a
four-year deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui, who packed quickly, said goodbye to teammates and
declined to speak to reporters, was batting .293 with nine homers,
39 runs batted in and just three errors this season. Blue Jays
manager Jim Fregosi said he planned to use Segui at first base,
left field and designated hitter. But if Segui ends up solely at
first base, as expected, Carlos Delgado will become the team's
full-time DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to have a chance to play for a team who perhaps can
compete in the World Series this year, and that's what I told
him,'' said Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez, a close friend of
Segui's. ``He's going to be a great asset for that team and
solidify their infield immensely.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was asked if the trade signified anything about how
Mariners management views the direction of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty self-explanatory,'' Rodriguez said. ``All I have
to do is go out and do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Was it unexpected?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything is unexpected around here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Can this team get back in the division or wild-card race?
</P>
<P>
   ``Time will tell,'' Rodriguez said. ``We're responsible for our
own play. Time is of the essence, and we're running out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Rodriguez, center fielder Ken Griffey Jr. has long stressed
the importance of this season, which now could be slipping away.
Griffey mocked the Segui trade after first hearing of it, and later
spent at least a half-hour in private conversation with manager Lou
Piniella. The topic of that conversation was not known, but when
asked his opinion of the trade, Griffey refused comment.
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Edgar Martinez said he was sorry to see Segui
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good time of the year, especially when some teams
are looking for players to improve their teams,'' Martinez said.
``It's sad to see Segui go after we know what he brings to the
team. He's a great defensive player and good hitter, and it's sad
to see him go.''
</P>
<P>
   After his own meeting with Piniella, Buhner said he understood
the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things are going, I don't want to be singling out and
pointing fingers at the bullpen, because we're a team and we win
and lose as a team,'' he said. ``But at the same time, too, I think
everybody understands that our bullpen has been a little erratic. I
mean, we've got a (6.54) ERA in our bullpen. So I think it can
certainly help us, no doubt about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing Butch and David is tough to replace, no doubt. They
both did an awesome job for us. But we got some help that we
desperately needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will use Raul Ibanez and Buhner at first base, with
John Mabry another option. On days when Buhner plays first and the
M's face a left-hander, Piniella said, Ozzie Timmons can play right
field. Shane Monahan will be promoted from Class AAA Tacoma
Thursday to take Segui's roster spot, and more moves will be made
if Sinclair arrives Thursday, as expected, and when Davey joins the
team in Seattle Friday.
</P>
<P>
   One American League scout described the 25-year-old Davey as an
above-average prospect with a ``plus fastball'' in the 94-96 mph
range. Sinclair, the scout said, is a ``fringe prospect'' but has a
chance to be successful if he locates his 88-89 mph fastball
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-7 Davey was 1-1 with a 4.70 ERA in 29 games for the
Blue Jays this year. He had been considered a potential closer, but
the emergence of Billy Koch in that role and Toronto's abundance of
right-handed set-up men made Davey expendable. He faced the
Mariners twice in May, earning a save by throwing 31/3 scoreless
innings on May 1 but getting hit hard two days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws the crap out of the ball,'' Buhner said. ``He's a
big, huge kid, throws a super sinker and throws the ball real
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair, who turns 28 next week and is a native of Victoria,
B.C., pitched in 24 games for Toronto last year, going 0-2 with a
3.60 ERA. He pitched in three games for Toronto this year but
otherwise has been the closer at Syracuse, where he had a 2-2
record, a 2.06 ERA and 18 saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few days we've gotten three good, young arms,''
Piniella said. ``We're starting to stockpile some arms. I don't
know if we're done or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward said he is talking with two or three clubs, and still
believes there is a ``50/50'' chance of making another move. The
Mariners had a scout watching Andy Pettitte of the New York Yankees
in Chicago last night, and free agent-to-be Jeff Fassero still
could interest New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners did clear about $1.3 million off their payroll by
trading Huskey and Segui, which would make it easier to acquire a
veteran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
