<HEADLINE>
YOUNG IS SAFE ON DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dodgers second baseman Eric Young won't be traded
before Saturday's non-waiver trading deadline. By baseball rules he
can't be, because he was put on the 15-day disabled list before
Wednesday's game against Cincinnati after an MRI showed
inflammation in his left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   However, it doesn't rule out the possibility that the
32-year-old second baseman will be traded later. Young could clear
waivers and be traded before the season ends, and with $9 million
and two years remaining on his contract, that shouldn't be a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was traded here Aug. 18,'' Young said. ``Anything can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The future will take care of itself. The past week, though,
revealed an ugly situation. Young wanted to go on the disabled
list, but Dodgers management didn't want to place him there because
it would rule out an early trade.
</P>
<P>
   It's the outcome Young wanted, but the means at which it arrived
obviously hurt Young.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was further aggravated when Young lost his
starting spot at second base on Friday. Young said he's been
playing hurt and was bothered by a sore hamstring, calf and ankle
at various points of the season. He said it's a reason his average
is .263 and he has stolen just 16 bases in the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   There were also clubhouse rumblings that management lost faith
in Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lesson to be learned from this,'' Young said.
``Look at it and respond positive about it. . . . I'm human. I know
I give it my all every time I step on the field. You can't ever
question whether I'm going to go out and give 100 percent. I take a
lot of pride in my work.''
</P>
<P>
   Lefty reliever Jeff Kubenka was recalled from Triple-A
Albuquerque to fill Young's spot. Kubenka is 0-1 this season with
the Dodgers. He was 4-4 with seven saves and a 2.91 ERA at Triple-A
Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Perez promises return: Demoted $15.5 million pitcher Carlos
Perez worked out Wednesday afternoon before packing his bags and
heading to Albuquerque, where he'll start Tuesday. He also vowed to
return after a few weeks and live up to his end of the exorbitant
three-year deal he signed during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get my stuff back and get back into the starting
rotation,'' said Perez, who was optioned to the minors after
Tuesday's game. ``I'm not going to go home and put my head down. I
look around and see a lot of good pitchers struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez is 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA. He hasn't pitched in the minor
leagues since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I could do the job in the bullpen, but it's the
decision of the manager and general manager,'' Perez said. ``I know
for sure I'm going to be (back) here soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Cromer returns home: Dodgers utility infielder Tripp Cromer, who
was on a rehab assignment with Albuquerque, returned to Los Angeles
on Tuesday to undergo more tests on his heart. Cromer is being
examined by Dodgers team physician Dr. Michael Mellman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just having some more tests done,'' Cromer said. ``I'll be
back playing soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Cromer left the Dodgers on July 6 with an irregular heartbeat.
He was cleared to play July 19 and began a rehab stint with
Albuquerque, where he batted .267 in four games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
