<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUALIFIER SEKULOV SHOWS QUALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ James Sekulov thought he needed a brief vacation,
a week away from tennis to keep his confidence from diminishing
even further.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't been playing well in the past couple weeks, so I was
just going to spend the week in Montreal and visit with some
friends before the next tournament,'' said Sekulov, who had lost
his last three matches. ``But my roommate said that I should come
to L.A. because it is a fun place to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Sekulov went beyond merely having fun on Wednesday, when he won
the biggest match of his five-year professional career. Sekulov, an
Australian who is ranked 236th, upset fifth-seeded Thomas Enqvist,
6-7 (1-7), 6-4, 6-3, in the second round of the Mercedes-Benz Cup
at UCLA's Los Angeles Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   After winning two matches in three days over the weekend to
enter the main draw as a qualifier, Sekulov beat Martin Damm in the
first round and took advantage of the inconsistent baseline play of
Enqvist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just getting through qualifying gave me a big confidence
boost,'' Sekulov said. ``Obviously, Enqvist wasn't playing as well
as he could. He was spraying a few forehands around, but with the
way I had been playing, I'm very happy to be where I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercedes-Benz Cup is the first ATP Tour event this year for
Sekulov, 22, a regular on the Challenger series. He qualified for
last year's U.S. Open but lost to 50th-ranked Davide Sanguinetti in
the first round, and his previous biggest tournament victory came
against 149th-ranked Luis Herrera in a Challenger event in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sekulov plays in the shadow of some of his more successful
countrymen, including top-ranked Patrick Rafter, 18-year-old rising
star Lleyton Hewitt and doubles star Mark Woodforde. He is winless
in six career ATP tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can get frustrating, especially when I'm so far away from
home,'' Sekulov said. ``Not many guys can do what (Hewitt) is
doing. A lot of Australians mature later, like Wayne Arthurs, who
didn't start playing well until he reached his late 20s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep playing as long as it's still fun for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Who's the winner? After their second-round match, eighth-seeded
Wayne Ferreira and Justin Gimelstob seemed to stage another
contest, to see who could sound more downtrodden in postmatch
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost feel guilty about winning,'' Ferreira said. ``I was
hitting the ball OK and hitting some winners, but I just don't have
any motivation out there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who makes the last shot deserves to win. He gets to
play another match, I don't,'' Gimelstob said.
</P>
<P>
   Gimelstob's frustration is easier to understand. The former UCLA
star won the first set and had match point at 5-4 in the second,
but Ferreira rallied to win nine of the last 11 sets and the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty obvious that I played some terrible shots out
there,'' Gimelstob said. ``He's a great athlete and you can't do
that against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira doesn't hold himself in such high regard these days.
Ranked 38th in the world, the 27-year-old South African has failed
to advance to the quarterfinals of a tournament since April and was
a first-round loser at Wimbledon last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a pretty ordinary time on the court for the past
three years or so, because of injuries and such,'' Ferreira said.
``I tried to play through some things when I maybe just should have
stopped playing, and now I find it difficult to get up for every
single match.''
</P>
</TEXT>
