<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINER FRUSTRATIONS MOUNT AGAINST ROYALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ He has been the Mariners' survivor, lasting
through spring training and through the trades of Matt Mieske,
Butch Huskey and now David Segui _ all of whom played one of this
survivor's positions with the M's and now play them for contenders.
</P>
<P>
   When Segui was dealt to the Toronto Blue Jays for two minor
league relievers Wednesday, Raul Ibanez got his first start of the
year at first base in the Mariners' game against the Kansas City
Royals. He responded with a two-run homer in his first at-bat, a
Segui-like scoop of a throw in the second inning and a Segui-like
bat-slam after a pop out in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Mariners, the last action was the most
telling.
</P>
<P>
   It was another frustrating night for the M's, who fell to the
Royals, 5-3, before 17,476 at Kauffman Stadium. The loss was the
Mariners' fourth in five games on this road trip, and their 13th in
18 games since July 6.
</P>
<P>
   They failed to gain ground on the Texas Rangers, who lost to
snap a nine-game winning streak and remain 12 games ahead of
Seattle in the American League West. The M's now trail the
Huskey-led Boston Red Sox in the wild card race by 7{ games.
</P>
<P>
   Ibanez's second-inning home run gave the Mariners a 2-0 lead,
and a solo homer by Jay Buhner the next inning increased Seattle's
lead to 3-0. But while the Mariners failed to convert with men in
scoring position the rest of the way, the Royals scraped together
five runs off Freddy Garcia to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't hit with men on base in a long time,'' said
Mariners manager Lou Piniella, whose team stranded 12 runners in
Tuesday's loss and eight Wednesday night. ``We need to get that
component working. ... You get runners on, you've got to get them
in.''
</P>
<P>
   The M's had the bases loaded with one out in the first, but a
strikeout by Buhner and groundout by Russ Davis ended that threat.
A popout by Brian Hunter with a runner on second ended the fourth.
Ibanez's popout and a fielder's choice grounder by Dan Wilson ended
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner and Davis singled with one out, and David Bell rifled a
liner to right field. But Jermaine Dye made a rolling catch and
threw to second to double off Buhner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a nice play,'' Piniella said. ``(But) we've made two
baserunning mistakes in the last couple of days late in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia (10-6) held the Royals scoreless through three innings
but surrendered a pair of two-out runs in the fourth and then
surrendered the lead in the fifth when Chad Kreuter led off with a
homer and Carlos Beltran hit a two-run shot with two outs.
Beltran's homer came after a walk to Carlos Febles.
</P>
<P>
   ``(On) 3-2 to Febles, I thought it was a strike, but they didn't
give it to me,'' said Garcia. ``The 1-1 to Beltran was a changeup
up (in the strike zone). I was supposed to throw it away and down,
but when you throw it in the middle, they kill it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Ibanez, he went hitless after the homer. But his average
stands at .300, and Piniella expects to use him more at first base
with Segui gone. The 27-year-old is in his eighth season in the
Mariners organization, and there should be plenty more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always encouraging when you feel like you're wanted
somewhere,'' Ibanez said. ``I grew up with this organization, and I
like it here. But I'll feel happy at the end of the year if we win
a lot of ballgames and I can contribute. That'll make me happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
