<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANG DUSTING HIMSELF OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Michael Chang, close to being the subject in the
dreaded ``Whatever happened to...'' question, is trying to
recapture the spark that once made him one of the world's top
tennis players.
</P>
<P>
   At 27, Chang is searching for something positive to build upon
after injuries forced him to miss last month's grasscourt season
and dropped him to No.70 in the world, and he might have found it
in this week's Mercedes-Benz Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a while since I've been past the second round of a
tournament, so this feels pretty good,'' Chang said after a 6-4,
6-2 victory over Guillaume Raoux on Wednesday at the Los Angeles
Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   One more victory would put Chang, the 1996 champion, in the
semifinals of an ATP tournament for the first time this year.
Waiting for him there would likely be Pete Sampras, who earned a
7-6 (7-5), 6-3 second-round victory over Sebastien Lareau, but
Chang is content to take baby steps right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like this is a good start,'' said Chang, who won the
1989 French Open at age 17. ``It's going to take a while to get my
confidence back. One of the biggest things is just believing in
what I can do out there, and feeling that I am capable of hitting
any shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang, hampered throughout 1998 by knee and wrist injuries,
finished the year ranked No.29. He reached the round of 16 at the
Australian Open in January, but back spasms forced him to miss the
past two months.
</P>
<P>
   Playing his first ATP tournament since May, Chang lost only four
games in a first-round victory over Wayne Black on Tuesday, and
showed good mobility against Raoux, a Mercedes semifinalist for the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Chang broke serve in the first game and held for a 6-4 first-set
victory. Raoux held four game points in the 10th game, but killed
each chance by leaving lob attempts in the net.
</P>
<P>
   In the quarterfinals, Chang will face Australian qualifier James
Sekulov, who provided the biggest upset of the day by beating
fifth-seeded Thomas Enqvist of Sweden, 6-7 (1-7), 6-4, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when I lost the first set, I thought there was still a
chance,'' Sekulov said. ``If he would have won 6-1 or something, I
probably wouldn't have had as much hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Sampras on Wednesday night, Sebastien Lareau had a great
deal of hope in the first set. Lareau handled Sampras' big serve
well and had a chance to serve for the set at 6-5, but Sampras
broke back and eventually won in the tiebreaker. ``Coming back in
that first set was big for me, because I was already thinking about
having to regroup for the second set,'' Sampras said. Lareau broke
Sampras twice in the first set, but Sampras held his first two
serves in the second set and broke to go up 3-2. The players would
hold serve until Sampras broke Lareau to win the match with a
cross-court forehand volley that Lareau could not reach. ``He
really made me work out there,'' Sampras said. ``I've played him
three times now, and I think each time he gets a better look at my
serve. At times he was picking it up pretty easy. The players most
recently met at Wimbledon, where Sampras beat Lareau in the second
round. Sampras will take on eighth-seeded Wayne Ferreira of South
Africa, who beat Justin Gimelstob, 5-7, 7-5, 6-2. Ferreira has
beaten Sampras in their last four meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Gimelstob, a former UCLA star who reached the Mercedes
semifinals last year, had Ferreira at match point in the second
set, but was broken and never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was pretty obvious that the momentum switched right
there,'' Gimelstob said. ``It hurts more because I wanted a chance
to do well here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
