<HEADER>
A8176 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-ROCKIES-HN     07-29 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ROCKIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DENVER _ The Astros continued their climb up the mountain Wednesday
night. Meanwhile, somewhere beneath the avalanche lie the Colorado
Rockies.
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the third straight game, Colorado pitching caved in as the
Astros took turns hitting everything in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell hit his second career grand slam and the Astros
produced their highest hit total in 23 years in a 16-8 rout at
Coors Field. With their sixth straight victory, the Astros moved 22
games above .500 (62-40) for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   And with Cincinnati's 9-1 loss to Los Angeles, the Astros' lead
in the National League Central grew to 3{ games.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros will seek to complete a rare four-game sweep at Coors
Field this afternoon. Before this week, the Astros were 6-23
all-time in Denver. Meanwhile, the Rockies continued to nose-dive,
losing their sixth straight to fall a season-worst 13 games below
.500.
</P>
<P>
   The 21 hits by the Astros were their most since they got 22
against Montreal on July 18, 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, you start to feel for the other team,'' manager
Larry Dierker said. ``I've never seen both teams score in five
consecutive innings. You almost feel like you don't have enough
runs, but at the same time you feel like, `Don't rub it in.'''
</P>
<P>
   The two teams combined for 18 runs and 30 hits _ from the fourth
inning on.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton earned his 14th victory, tying St. Louis' Kent
Bottenfield, Philadelphia's Curt Schilling and Astros teammate Jose
Lima for the NL lead. Hampton also had a career-high three hits,
including a club-record-tying third triple of the season.
</P>
<P>
   After being held scoreless for three innings, the Astros erupted
for five runs in the fourth, two in the fifth, two in the sixth,
four in the seventh, two in the eighth and one in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell went 4-for-6 with two RBIs. Tony Eusebio had three
hits. Glen Barker, Craig Biggio and Bagwell each had two hits. In
three games against the Rockies, the Astros have pounded out 30
runs and 50 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offense is starting to come around, and everybody is
starting to feel comfortable at the plate,'' Bell said. ``It's
scary. It's fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton (14-3) won his fifth straight decision, allowing five
runs and 13 hits over seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those nights when we needed some offense and we
got it,'' said Hampton, whose .824 winning percentage is second in
the majors behind Boston's Pedro Martinez (15-3, .833). ``We're
playing well, and everything is working.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, Colorado held a 1-0 lead in the third inning.
It lasted about 10 minutes until the Astros broke through in the
fourth with five runs _ all coming with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hidalgo drew a walk, and the Astros followed with five
straight hits off Rockies starter Roberto Ramirez (1-3).
</P>
<P>
   After a single to right by Matt Mieske, Bell followed with his
first of four singles to tie the game 1-1. Eusebio followed with a
broken-bat RBI single to center, Tim Bogar hit a shot past third
baseman Vinny Castilla, and Hampton added a two-run triple for a
5-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton became the first pitcher to collect three triples in a
season since Bob Forsch of St. Louis did it in 1975. The three
triples tied a club record set by Dave Roberts in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it in the right spot,'' Hampton said. ``One good thing
is I have pretty good speed, so I'm going to go for more triples
than a lot of pitchers would.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Ramirez could retire the side in the fourth, Rockies
manager Jim Leyland had seen enough. Ramirez was gone, but the
relievers who followed allowed 11 additional runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros got two in the fifth on Barker's RBI double and a
sacrifice fly by Bogar. In the sixth, the Astros sent eight batters
to the plate, tacking on a pair on RBI singles by Barker and Bell
to increase the lead to 9-2.
</P>
<P>
   Barker has three RBIs in his career _ all in the last two days.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado pulled within 9-4 in the sixth on RBI singles by Jeff
Barry and Terry Shumpert, but the Astros loaded the bases off
reliever Mike Porzio in the seventh and Bagwell cleared them with
his second career grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   It was his 33rd homer, and the Astros' fourth slam of the season
and second in six days.
</P>
<P>
   Daryle Ward hit his first major-league home run, a solo shot in
the eighth, and Russ Johnson followed with one of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen of Colorado's 18 hits were singles, two shy of the club
record. The Rockies scored seven runs off Hampton and two relievers
in the final five innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
