<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKEY GIVES RED SOX A BOOST 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BLUE JAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Pat Rapp, the Red Sox starter of last resort, and
Butch Huskey, an added starter only two nights ago, made for the
unlikely combination that propelled the Red Sox ahead of the
Toronto Blue Jays again in the wild-card competition with a
stunning 8-0 shutout Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, completing a two-game sweep
of their Canadian cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Rapp, who has watched while the Red Sox auditioned such untested
rookies as Jin Ho Cho and Tomokazu Ohka ahead of him in the
rotation, allowed just two singles in eight innings and retired the
last 17 batters he faced as the Red Sox won for the eighth time in
nine meetings against Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just stayed ready for every hitter every time,'' Rapp said.
``I didn't even have to turn around to see who it was. I could tell
by the music they were playing who was at bat. Some of it was even
pretty good. The music they play for Jose Cruz, that's what they
play for those wrestlers (New Age Outlaws). And the `woo-hoo,' that
was Shawn Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they were going back to the dugout left and right, and the
ballpark played big tonight. The flyballs they hit stayed here.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could not be said for the long flies hit by Huskey.
Serving as DH in a role that would have been filled by Mike Stanley
before his arrival, Huskey borrowed a bat from catcher Jason
Varitek to hit a grand slam off Blue Jays starter Joey Hamilton
that broke a scoreless tie in the sixth inning. He then hit another
home run, his 17th, off John Frascatore leading off the ninth, when
the Sox scored four more runs.
</P>
<P>
   How much help can the Red Sox expect from Huskey, who had three
hits in his Sox debut in Tuesday night's 11-9 win over the Jays?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll put it to you this way, he's helped us so far,'' said
John Valentin, who added a two-run home run in the ninth after
rookie Donnie Sadler, the new starting second baseman, singled and
scored from first on Trot Nixon's double.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, whenever you get a new acquisition,'' Valentin
said, ``he's definitely going to come over and try to do what he
can to help the team. He's a big guy, so whenever he hits the ball,
it's going to go somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much is he going to help us? It's just wait and see. He's
hit the ball well in these two games, but we've got a long two
months ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rapp walked just one batter and allowed only one Blue Jay base
runner to advance as far as second base. That was in the third
inning, the only inning in which Toronto had as many as two
runners.
</P>
<P>
   Rapp had made 10 relief appearances since his last start, June
22 in Baltimore, in which he came away with a no-decision in a 5-3
loss to the Orioles. A winner of just two games all season before
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, Rapp was resigned to remaining in the bullpen
until Ohka and Cho both flamed out in their auditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty much,'' he said. ``Watching guy after guy after guy
come in and get a start, and I'd been a starter all my career, I
just decided, `Do your job, do your job in the bullpen, and help
this team win any way you can.' But it's been hard, because I
haven't been in too many games that we've won.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays had come into this series winners of nine of their
previous 10 games and with a 1 1/2-game advantage over the Sox, who
hadn't won consecutive games since July 4-5 but have now won the
first two games in which Huskey has put on a Red Sox uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays blew a 7-3 lead in the series opener, won by the
Sox, 11-9, then came away unimpressed by Rapp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't put guys down,'' said Toronto cleanup man Carlos
Delgado, who was 0 for 7 in the series and had his best chance for
a hit taken away by a terrific diving catch by Sadler in the
seventh inning Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, ``but (Rapp) had a career night.
He's an average pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give him credit for tonight, but he's no Cy Young.''
</P>
<P>
   Rapp gave up a two-out infield hit in the first to Shawn Green,
who tied a club record by extending his hitting streak to 26 games,
and a single to Homer Bush with one out in the third. He walked the
next batter, Shannon Stewart, but retired Willie Greene on a fly
ball and Green on a foul pop to Varitek to end the inning, and did
not allow another baserunner thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   If it were up to Rapp, Green's hitting streak should have ended
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night. Garciaparra gloved the ball in the hole, but his
throw arrived on one hop to first baseman Brian Daubach, who
couldn't handle the bounce.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, they only had one hit today,'' Rapp said. ``The
hometown scoreboard gave them the other. If the throw is in the
air, he's out. But it bounced, the play looked close on the replay,
so they gave him a base hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they looked to me to throw him the ball, I felt like
throwing it 10 rows into the upper deck. But it's his town.''
</P>
<P>
   The game, however, belonged to Rapp. Asked if he expected to
draw another start Monday against the Indians, he shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``I plan on starting Monday, but
you'd better ask somebody else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
