<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX LOSES GORDON FOR YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-GORDON-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Red Sox reclaimed their hold on a wild-card spot
from the Toronto Blue Jays Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, but that became
secondary to three major developments, all of which figure to have
a major impact on whether the Sox will be returning to the playoffs
in October.
</P>
<P>
   --Closer Tom Gordon said he was told by orthopedist James
Andrews that he probably will require season-ending surgery to
repair a torn ulnar collateral ligament in his right elbow. That
news, which came after Andrews reviewed films of Gordon's last
magnetic resonance imaging, taken two weeks ago, erased the faint
hopes that the pitcher would return for the stretch drive this
season while raising fears he may not be back for a full year if he
undergoes Tommy John tendon transfer surgery, as expected. It also
provoked clubhouse grumbling about the quality of team medical
care, with Nomar Garciaparra the most vocal critic.
</P>
<P>
   --Staff ace Pedro Martinez, who has missed two starts,
pronounced himself ready to return to the starting rotation as soon
as next Tuesday, the first day he is eligible to come off the
15-day disabled list. Martinez is scheduled to see Dr. Arthur
Pappas Friday in Boston before getting the green light to face the
Cleveland Indians in Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if I see him or not, I'm pitching Tuesday,''
said Martinez, who had made 172 consecutive starts until he
strained the muscles in the back of the rotator cuff in his right
shoulder. ``That's how good I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   --All-Star second baseman Jose Offerman, who already had been
kept out of the team's previous two games, said he was told
Wednesday by manager Jimy Williams that he is being benched
indefinitely because of his defense, with rookie Donnie Sadler
becoming the second baseman until further notice. Offerman, signed
to a four-year, $26 million contract last December, was shocked by
the decision, as was his closest friend on the team, Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pay me too much money to be on the bench,'' Offerman
said. ``I don't want to be in this situation, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who said he was called by the Alabama-based Andrews
Wednesday afternoon, informed Williams he was flying back to Boston
ahead of the team Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night and hoped to see Andrews
Thursday. The possibility remained, he said, that because Andrews
was leaving Friday on vacation, he would have to wait until next
week to see him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way Dr. Andrews talked to me today, there's a pretty good
chance I will have surgery,'' said Gordon, still miffed that the
doctor he'd consulted for a second opinion had to wait so long for
the results of his tests. ``I wish I had known this a couple of
weeks ago. I wish this had been taken more seriously, and didn't
take so long to get out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He read (the MRI) today and said he didn't like what he saw. I
told him that Dr. Pappas said he saw scar tissue. He said, `From
what I saw, the tear is still there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said Andrews, who performed Tommy John tendon transfer
surgery on Red Sox reliever Rheal Cormier two years ago, said the
Sox reliever was displaying similar symptoms. Cormier underwent the
tendon transfer surgery on May 21, 1997, and did not return to the
big leagues until this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Dr. Andrews) said that after five or six weeks (of rest and
anti-inflammatory medication) I should feel better,'' Gordon said.
``I do feel better, but there's still the ache and discomfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's elbow problems first surfaced in spring training in
February, though pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said Wednesday Gordon
told him Tuesday night he may have first hurt the elbow last
November while pitching for a team of major-league stars in an
exhibition series in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he felt juiced up in the first two games of the
Japan series and by his own admission probably overthrew,''
Kerrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   On April 18, he went on the disabled list for the first time
with what was described as a strained elbow flexor, returned May
10, then made 13 appearances before being placed on the DL a second
time June 11, this time for what was described as an inflammation
of the ulnar nerve and a slight tear of the ligament.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon had a second MRI July 15 and resumed a throwing program,
but reported continued discomfort even as Pappas told him it
appeared, from the buildup of scar tissue, that the ligament was
healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had taken care of this in spring training, where would I
be?'' said Gordon, who was still throwing as recently as last
Sunday. ``He (Andrews) told me that I was taking a risk of totally
blowing it (if he continued to throw).''
</P>
<P>
   In Tommy John tendon transfer surgery, named after the former
big-league pitcher who underwent the procedure pioneered by Dr.
Frank Jobe, a tendon is taken from the opposite wrist and attached
to the torn ligament. It usually takes a player at least a full
year before he returns.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas has said that if Gordon needed surgery, it would be the
Tommy John procedure. Gordon said he wouldn't know for sure until
he saw Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   As Gordon circulated through the Sox clubhouse, informing
teammates of his situation, Garciaparra, sitting in front of his
locker, loudly belittled the time it took to determine that Gordon
probably needed surgery. ``Our doctors are killing us,''
Garciaparra said to teammates. ``This is just like the bone
bruise.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to the original diagnosis made last year of
Lou Merloni's leg injury, which later was found to be a stress
fracture.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were within earshot in the clubhouse while Garciaparra
made his comments. They were following manager Williams out onto
the field in the middle of the clubhouse when Garciaparra, noticing
that Williams was limping slightly, said: ``What did you hurt,
Jimy? I'll tell you who not to go and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was asked afterward how upset he was. ``I really
have nothing to say about the whole situation,'' he said. ``I'm not
going to say anything. It ain't worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, meanwhile, was in considerably better spirits after
testing his shoulder playing long toss. ``I'm very happy,'' he
said, giving a thumbs-up sign. ``It's excellent. I'm going to throw
on the side, and on Tuesday I'll be on the mound to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez hasn't pitched since July 18, when he gave up nine runs
(seven earned) in just 3 2/3 innings against the Florida Marlins,
the worst outing of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan said Martinez long-tossed from 250 feet for about eight
minutes, then pitched for three minutes from a flat surface. ``He
showed a real healthy arm today,'' Kerrigan said. ``His ball was
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll see the doctor on Friday, and if all goes according to
what the doctor tells us to do, he'll probably pitch on Tuesday. It
all depends on what the doctor says Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said the doctor can't tell him anything he doesn't
already know. ``I know my body really well,'' Martinez said, ``and
I'm telling you right now, I'm ready to pitch. I'll give you my
paycheck back, give me my outing.''
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite side of the clubhouse from where Martinez sat,
Offerman told reporters of his pregame meeting with Williams, one
in which he came away convinced that he was out of the lineup
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a move he decided to do,'' Offerman said. ``He
said my defense has to improve a little bit. I thought I was
playing good defense. I thought my problem was hitting. But I guess
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I can do is (be patient),'' he said. ``I can't
make any trouble. I have to take it as a professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman's average, which was .346 on May 19, has dropped 74
percentage points since then, to .272. In July, he's batting a
team-low .167, and had just one hit in eight at-bats in the first
two games of this trip before being kept out of the lineup the last
three games.
</P>
<P>
   He said Williams told him that he was planning to play Sadler,
recalled Tuesday, ``for awhile. I'll be like everybody else. I'll
be like everybody else, come in here every day and expect to be in
the lineup someday.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman, who displaced Jeff Frye as the starting second baseman
April 21 in Detroit, ranks next to last in fielding percentage
among American League second baseman, with a .970 mark. The
Yankees' Chuck Knoblauch, who has made 18 errors while trying to
overcome a mysterious throwing problem, is last at .959.
</P>
<P>
   Williams would not say how long he plans to keep Offerman out of
the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed whether the move might be as permanent as Frye's
removal, Williams said: ``No, not necessarily. I'm not going to say
one way or the other, but probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought Offerman was out of position at second base,
Williams said: ``This kid has good hands out there. No, he's a good
fielder.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he couldn't understand the decision to bench
Offerman. ``Why do you sit a guy like that making all that money?''
Martinez said. ``You got to play him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever (Williams) and (general manager Dan) Duquette are
doing they need to do, but I know he's getting paid a lot of money
to sit on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he didn't think Offerman's defense was a problem.
``I don't think so,'' he said. ``I thought he was playing steady.
He made a couple of great plays. He bobbled a couple, like
everybody does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy better be right about the things he's saying, right about
what he says about his defense. The reason we're not winning is
we're not healthy. And we haven't been playing well. But it's not
one person. The team overall is at fault. Our fault. The whole
team's fault.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
