<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-BRAZIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US CAN'T COPE WITH BRAZILIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUADALAJARA, Mexico _ There was no miracle this time. Kasey
Keller couldn't do a thing after Ronaldinho's header caromed off
the post in the 13th minute. And once Joe-Max Moore's penalty kick
in the 73d was blocked Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, the US men's soccer team
ended up where it usually does when it plays Brazil _ on the wrong
end of a 1-0 score before 54,000 inside Jalisco Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deserved at least a draw,'' said Keller, whose mates can
still advance to the semifinals by drawing Friday night with the
Germans, who walked past New Zealand, 2-0, here Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night.
``It's a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, this was the most moral of the collection of 1-0
defeats (five in seven matches since 1992) that the US has suffered
at the feet of the Samba Kings. This time, the Yanks attacked with
confidence and verve. This time, they held the Brazilians to a
handful of chances. This time, they left the field disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three points was our ultimate goal tonight,'' said Moore, who
came in for limping Revolution teammate John Harkes in the 58th
minute. ``I think we actually played better than we did against
them last year. But we lost the game. That's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they defeated Brazil, 1-0, at last year's CONCACAF Gold
Cup in Los Angeles, the Americans prevailed only because Keller
played the match of his life (and the best of any keeper in US
history), thwarting top star Romario five times. ``If Brazil gets
that many chances again, we'll lose by four goals,'' predicted US
coach Bruce Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians, fresh off retaining the Copa America (the South
American championship) two weekends ago, had hammered Germany, 4-0,
in the tournament opener, scoring all of their goals in the final
28 minutes. ``Were we surprised?'' mused US striker Brian McBride.
``With Brazil, you can never be surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet while the Brazilians had beaten the US seven of eight times,
they had never done it by four goals. ``We don't have fear of the
Brazilians,'' Arena said. ``We have great respect.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Arena made some changes in a lineup that had
managed only a 2-1 victory over New Zealand Saturday, putting
defender Gregg Berhalter on his four-man back line, along with
fleet Frankie Hejduk on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   But even Hejduk couldn't match the Brazilians' raw speed. Barely
a dozen minutes in, striker Christian dashed past him down the
flank and cracked a soaring cross to Ronaldinho, the gangly
19-year-old artiste with the maloccluded grin who's being touted as
the next Ronaldo. Ronaldinho smartly headed the ball off the right
post and past Keller, and the Samba Kings were on the board.
</P>
<P>
   That spelled trouble for the Americans, who had scored only one
goal on their rivals _ Preki Radosavljevic's 1998 winner _ since
1930. The Yanks had never managed to mount much of an attack on
Brazil; they didn't even attempt a shot in their 1994 World Cup
meeting. And their only two good chances in Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's
first half came to nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Cobi Jones, alone in the area with nobody between him and keeper
Dida in the 31st minute, inexplicably passed back to McBride at the
top of the box. Then, a minute later, Ernie Stewart popped one over
the crossbar from 8 yards out.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the US was down by only 1-0 at the half. ``We told them,
just stay in the game,'' said Arena. ``We felt if we could get a
push in the last 20 or 25 minutes, we might get the equalizer.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Yanks came out on the run, pushing upfield, getting
numbers into the box. And when Odvan foolishly chopped down Jones
from behind and Swedish referee Anders Frisk whistled for a
penalty, the US had its chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking to put it in the corner, but I didn't get enough
of it, to be honest,'' said Moore. Dida, the keeper, got an early
jump on the ball, dove right and knocked it askew.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Yanks tied the score, they might well have gone on to
win. There were other chances _ a deflected header by Jones that
Dida saved and a shot by Moore that was cleared away. But when the
whistle blew, it was history as usual. A moral loss is still a
loss. ``It's the score that matters,'' said defender Jeff Agoos.
``That's what goes down in the record books.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
