r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     07-29 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECO IMPRESSIVE FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ OK, maybe there is hope for the season, or for
next season, or for mankind.
</P>
<P>
   If Robinson Checo, hit around worse than a batting practice
pitcher last time he was here, can turn it around like this,
anything and everything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the more improbable moments of the season, Checo was
sensational Wednesday night at Dodger Stadium while giving up one
run in five innings as the Dodgers beat Cincinnati 9-1 for their
second win in nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Arnold pitched the last four innings for his first
major-league save.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what would be a Dodgers game without, at the least, a
minor crisis. That occurred when Checo left the game with a tweaked
groin muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Checo (1-0) said he'd be fine in two or three days. The Dodgers
are also helped by Monday's off day, which means they won't need a
fifth starter again until Aug. 7, which should give him time to
heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really feeling it, deep in his groin,'' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said. ``But I thought he threw the ball great. By and
large, he still threw some high fastballs. The breaking ball was
sharper, everything was more crisp.''
</P>
<P>
   It was exactly what most people weren't expecting. Before Checo
was promoted from Triple-A Albuquerque, Johnson joked about whether
his name was Checo Robinson or Robinson Checo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't around long enough for me to find out,'' Johnson
said jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, well, now Mr. Checo will do just fine.
</P>
<P>
   When he was demoted in April, Dodgers pitching coach Claude
Osteen was Albuquerque's pitching coach. His memory of Checo isn't
flattering.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a body out of control,'' Osteen said. ``There were
legs, elbows, his head; movement in every different direction.
Somebody like that, who has quality stuff, you have to be careful
you don't mess up his nuances. But you have to get some of it under
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Checo, who replaced lefty Carlos Perez, all but insured another
start with the Dodgers when his groin heals.
</P>
<P>
   And not only did he pitch splendidly, he also had his first
major-league hit. It scored two in the Dodgers' four-run third as
they built a 6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Former Dodgers lefty Dennys Reyes, making his first start,
lasted 22/3 innings. Reyes (2-2), involved in the Jeff Shaw-Paul
Konerko trade, gave up six runs on five hits and walked five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming into the situation like this, we needed (Checo) to
pitch well and give the bullpen a rest,'' said Dodgers left fielder
Gary Sheffield, who extended his hitting streak to nine with a
third-inning homer. ``We needed that, a good pitching performance.
We scored some runs for him and that was great.''
</P>
<P>
   After being one of three minor-leaguers acquired in the
salary-dumping Dave Mlicki trade with Detroit, Checo was hit hard
in two outings. The 26-year-old right-hander from the Dominican
Republic, once a coveted pitching prospect in Japan, was sent to
Albuquerque with a 17.18 ERA and was supposed to never be heard
from again.
</P>
<P>
   But Checo was placed in Albuquerque's starting rotation, his
mechanics were ironed out and his velocity increased to the mid-90
mph range. He was still erratic, but that changed lately. In his
last two starts, Checo went 2-0 with a 2.84 ERA and earned the nod
to take Perez's spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first inning I was a little nervous, but after that I
settled down,'' said Checo, whose only other major-league win came
in 1997 with Boston. ``I have new mechanics, new height (on a leg
kick). Anytime you throw (your body) open, you throw too many high
balls. Two of the (Reds') hits were on high balls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
