<HEADER>
A8209 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     07-29 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPARTURE IS TYPICAL OF SANDERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The most compelling reason for bringing football
back to L.A. wasn't forwarded by Bill Chadwick Tuesday in his
presentation to the NFL owners in Chicago. Rather, it came a day
later from Detroit in the form of a simple statement announcing
that Lions running back Barry Sanders had decided, on the eve of
his 11th NFL season, to retire.
</P>
<P>
   No way should the entertainment capital of the world have missed
being mesmerized by arguably the greatest running back of all
time.It's a crying shame only 43,850 Los Angeles area football fans
can say they saw Sanders play in their backyard.
</P>
<P>
   That was the paid attendance at Anaheim Stadium when Sanders ran
for 91 yards on 26 carries in a Detroit victory over the Rams on
Oct. 24, 1993. It was his only Southern California appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who surpassed the magical 2,000-yard mark in 1997,
didn't get to play in the Coliseum before Al Davis sent his Raiders
packing. Now it looks as though he never will, regardless of how
favorably the league's owners smile upon the Coliseum deal.
</P>
<P>
   Now the running back is gone and the NFL is poorer for it, no
matter how many hundreds of millions of dollars it commands in
expansion fees from L.A. or Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders was a worthy successor to Gale Sayers and Jim Brown,
O.J. Simpson and Walter Payton. Considered by some to be too small
and too slow to succeed in the NFL, Sanders led linebackers to lie.
</P>
<P>
   He once busted the Carolina Panthers' Lamar Lathon with a move
that left Lathon looking so silly, the linebacker invented a
hamstring injury to explain away the missed tackle.
</P>
<P>
   It reportedly will cost Sanders millions of dollars to break
loose from the Lions, who have him contractually in their clutches
through 2002. However high the sum, the bonus money Sanders will
have to pay back probably won't equal all the endorsement gold he
has left on the table over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' monk-like repudiation of the material trappings of
success calls to mind another marvelous athlete who retired in his
prime, Sandy Koufax.
</P>
<P>
   Our culture has grown more celebrity-crazed since Koufax's
retreat in the 1960s. And yet Sanders stands as proof that it
remains possible for an extraordinary athlete to lead an ordinary
life. The key, of course, is not going out of your way to draw
attention to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders can lose himself in a public that is otherwise quick to
put perennial Pro Bowlers on pedestals. He eschews the flamboyant
clothes, flashy cars, extravagant homes, swanky friends and
commercial ventures that would give off the impression he's
something special.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that even after years of being in fame's grip, he
is impossible to pin down.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't dissuade people from trying. Plenty of pundits took
it upon themselves Wednesday to flesh out Sanders' bare-bones
statement by suggesting Sanders doesn't really want out of
football, he just wants out of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is so soft-spoken, maybe people just didn't hear him
when he said in early 1996 that he would consider retiring after
the 1998 season because, ``I always felt when I was younger that 10
was a nice number.''
</P>
<P>
   People surprised by the abruptness of Sanders' announcement must
not have caught the playful warning he issued in June of 1997.
``When I quit,'' he said, ``it'll be `See you guys later. Had
enough.'''
</P>
<P>
   That Sanders retires needing only 1,458 yards to supplant Payton
as the NFL's all time leading rusher was shocking only to those
deaf to the beat to which Sanders marches.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his decision was in harmony with his past. As a high
school senior, Sanders needed 33 yards to overtake a league rival
who had set a season rushing record. One or two more carries and
the record assuredly would have been Sanders' to savor.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he sat out the final few minutes of the regular-season
finale, explaining later that he didn't want to risk injury with
the playoffs looming.
</P>
<P>
   He showed the same shocking disregard for ego gratification in
1989, his first season after getting drafted No.3 overall by
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Needing just 10 yards to wrest the rookie rushing title from
Kansas City's Christian Okoye, Sanders abstained from re-entering a
game against Atlanta in the fourth quarter because he didn't want
to deny his backup Tony Paige precious playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Other history, not Sanders' own, indicates this is yet another
one of his inspired breaks for daylight. Simpson and Eric Dickerson
were 31, the same age Sanders is now, when their numbers started to
sag. Tony Dorsett was two years older when age (and linebackers)
started to catch up to him.
</P>
<P>
   So Sanders didn't pass Payton and he tripped up on every run to
the Super Bowl. He would appear to have peace of mind and, really,
isn't that what all of us are chasing? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
