<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 03:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8215 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCAIN-LIBERALISM-SFC     07-29 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-LIBERALISM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN ADDS A DASH OF LIBERALISM TO CONSERVATIVE GOP STEW
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For a moment, Republican presidential hopeful John
McCain almost sounded like a San Francisco liberal.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator said Wednesday that gays and lesbians would
be welcome to serve in his administration. He decried the influence
of money in politics. He endorsed a moratorium on offshore oil
drilling. And he touted legislation to end sugar subsidies _ a
cause championed by Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., and Rep.
George Miller, D-Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   No one familiar with McCain's 17-year record in Washington could
mistake him for Willie Brown's ideological soul mate, however. The
62-year-old lawmaker is an avid supporter of the military who
pledges to uphold the legacy of Ronald Reagan and consistently
receives near-perfect scores from conservative groups.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's comments during a lunch with California reporters
across the street from the Capitol reveal an independent streak
that he hopes can carry him to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fastest growing registration of voters in California is
independents,'' McCain said. ``I believe I can appeal with my
message to independent-minded Republicans in California.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's refusal to toe the party line, most notably on campaign
finance reform and tobacco legislation, has earned him both respect
and scorn. His strategists believe that it accounts for his
emergence as a leading alternative to Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
who remains the overwhelming leader in fund-raising and public
opinion polls. He added to his maverick credentials Wednesday by
outlining a plan to provide school vouchers for disadvantaged
children at the expense of government subsidies for ethanol, sugar,
oil and gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   McCain proposed that $5.4 billion be spent over the next three
years to provide $2,000 education grants for poor children that
could be used at either public or private schools. He would pay for
the vouchers by abolishing the subsidies that benefit corn
producers and sugar farmers, a stance that many believe is
political suicide in Iowa _ site of the nation's first presidential
caucus in February.
</P>
<P>
   The ethanol subsidy, which costs taxpayers hundreds of millions
of dollars each year, has strong bipartisan support. McCain said
that his attempt to pit ``corporate welfare'' against children's
education is unlikely to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has about the same opportunity as I do of being on the next
launch into outer space,'' McCain said. ``We need to have people on
the record.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the reaction of Republican leaders: ``They are overjoyed
as usual,'' McCain said sarcastically. ``They voted me again, Mr.
Congeniality.'' The sugar subsidy helps domestic sugar growers,
most of whom are in Florida and Louisiana. The subsidy makes it
difficult for refineries _ like the C&AMP;H sugar refinery in Crockett
- that rely on foreign sugar to remain competitive. Opponents also
contend that it raises the cost of sugar for all consumers.
</P>
<P>
   McCain solidified his renegade reputation when he sponsored,
along with Senator Russell Feingold, D-Wis., a campaign finance
bill that would ban the unlimited donations to political parties
known as soft money.
</P>
<P>
   He said that it is opposition from fellow Republicans that is
preventing the measure from becoming law, but said he has no
intention of leaving the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the party has been in the past the party of
reform and can be in the future,'' McCain said. ``I believe in the
principles of the Republican Party as articulated by Abraham
Lincoln, Theodore Roosevelt, Ronald Reagan and others. ... I
believe that my most effective course of action ... is to improve
(the party) rather than to leave it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he disagrees with Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott's opposition to President Clinton's nomination of Richard
Holbrooke as U.N. ambassador, just as he disagrees with Lott's
opposition to San Francisco philanthropist James Hormel as
ambassador to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elections have consequences,'' McCain said, acknowledging
Clinton's right to make such appointments.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has been hailed by many in Silicon Valley for his
promotion of legislation that will shield the high-tech industry
from litigation arising from possible Y2K computer bugs.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain made clear Wednesday that he would not pander to the
industry, which is playing an increasingly prominent role in the
2000 campaign. ``We can't have our entire legislative agenda driven
by them,'' said McCain, who is ignoring the pleas of high-tech
leaders who want to make it easier to export encryption technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, look, you can't override the director of the FBI, the
head the CIA, the national security adviser and the secretary of
defense of the United States and expect me to go back to Arizona
and say, `My dear friends, for the sake of encryption, I overrule
the the strong views of those who are entrusted with our national
security.' It's just foolishness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain understands that he is far behind Texas Governor George
W. Bush both in money and the polls. His staff boasts about his
standing as the second most popular, one referring to him as the
leading the ``non-Bush caucus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good man, and a good friend in mine,'' McCain said
Wednesday. ``I don't know gov. Bush's positions on a lot of issues.
I know we disagree on ethanol subsidies, probably disagree on
campaign finance reform. It's hard to compare myself to him. That
opportunity will clearly be there.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain plans to spend about 10 days in California next month,
and boasted that he is already quite familiar with the state --
just like thousands of Arizonans who flee the summer heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the months of July and August I am required to got to San
Diego to visit my constituents,'' McCain said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
