<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8327 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-PRODI-BOS &LR;      07-29 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-PRODI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EU CHIEF TACKLES BREAD-AND-BUTTER ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ In the two months he has been president of the
European Commission, Romano Prodi has yet to be on time for an
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   When he was the prime minister of Italy, Prodi was always
punctual. But as he criss-crossed Europe, getting a feel for his
new job, Prodi came to experience firsthand one of the biggest
headaches on the continent: air traffic delays.
</P>
<P>
   The experience was an epiphany for Prodi. He has seized on it as
a problem that affects all Europeans, and one which he is
determined to tackle during his five-year term as the head of the
organization that is trying to turn the dream of a united Europe
into a reality. It is part of Prodi's ambitious plan to make the
European Union, more relevant to the 349 million mostly indifferent
people who live in the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when Prodi introduced his new 19-member European
Commission to oversee the administration of the European Union, he
sought to distance his team from its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the European Commission resigned en masse after
several commissioners were implicated in the biggest scandal in the
EU's 42-year existence. Jacques Santer, Prodi's predecessor, and
several of his commissioners were accused of mismanagement,
awarding sweetheart contracts to cronies, and abusing expense
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Prodi was brought in by the leaders of the 15 nations to restore
the EU's integrity. But Prodi, who has four holdovers from the
Santer regime on the commission, has more in mind than improving
the EU's image. He wants to chip away at the apathy evidenced last
month when less than half of eligible voters turned out for the
European Parliament elections. His plan is to focus on issues that
affect the everyday lives of Europeans, from getting the planes to
run on time to improving consumer confidence in food.
</P>
<P>
   Prodi's populist streak is a break from his predecessors, who
saw themselves primarily as international statesmen. While the EU's
leaders have spoken in grandiose terms about European integration
having made war in Europe impossible, Prodi says he is more
concerned about how an increasingly federal Europe can improve the
quality of life for Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Prodi has an international outlook. He sees things in a
global way. But he combines that with a Tip O'Neill view that all
politics is local,'' David O'Sullivan, Prodi's top aide, said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   While European leaders were congratulating each other for
presiding over the greatest example of reconciliation in the 20th
century, many Europeans were complaining about nightmarish airport
delays, contaminated food, and the seemingly endless scandals that
taint sports from soccer to cycling.
</P>
<P>
   Prodi contends that while the European Union has been successful
at addressing the big things, small things have been overlooked.
Europeans have created a single market and a single currency. They
are trying to create a single defense and foreign policy, which
would be even more impressive examples of putting aside national
interests for regional ones.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the air traffic control systems across Europe remain a
confusing patchwork that vary from country to country, inhibiting
the coordination needed to handle the increase in air travel. While
Europe is a single market, it has no single agency overseeing food
quality or testing, and contamination scares like the one last
month that led to pulling Coca-Cola from store shelves in four
European countries are common. The bodies that oversee sports,
meanwhile, are competing fiefdoms whose financial interests often
cloud attempts to police athletes.
</P>
<P>
   In his first speech to the new parliament Wednesday, Prodi
singled out airport delays, consumer fears about food, and the use
of performance-enhancing drugs by athletes as issues he wants to
address. They are hot-button topics across Europe, discussed with
equal fervor in London pubs, Parisian cafes, and Munich beer halls.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people are crying out for is a clear answer to the
problems that matter in their daily lives,'' said Prodi. ``At the
end of the day, what interests them is not who solves these
problems, but the fact that they are being tackled _ that consumers
have confidence in the food they buy, that the public can take to
the skies with confidence, that sport is clean.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to wanting European bodies that can coordinate air
traffic and monitor sports, Prodi proposed an independent body
modeled on the US Food and Drug Administration. His proposal was
made the same week that the United States imposed tariffs on EU
goods because the EU refuses to allow the import of hormone-treated
beef from the United States. Europeans remain bitterly divided over
the wisdom of allowing cheaper, genetically modified foods from the
United States into their market.
</P>
<P>
   While Prodi hopes to fashion a new European Union that better
reflects the ordinary concerns of Europeans, he must first confront
the public cynicism and political factionalism that has hampered
the development of a united Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Hans-Gert Poettering, the German who leads the center-right
European People's Party, the largest group in the European
Parliament, denounced Prodi's 19-member team as being overloaded
with leftists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe that this commission is politically
balanced,'' said Poettering, who threatened to block the
appointments at confirmation hearings in September.
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan, meanwhile, personifies one of Prodi's tactics for
addressing factionalism. Most everyone expected Prodi to choose a
fellow Italian as his right-hand man. Not only did Prodi choose
O'Sullivan, an Irishman, but he directed his 19 commissioners to
hire aides who are not from their own country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about being truly European, and it's also about avoiding
the appearance of a conflict of interest,'' said O'Sullivan. ``If
you have three Italians or three Germans in one room deciding on an
issue, they may take a decision for the best of Europe, but there
will be a suspicion. We have to confront that.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk is revolutionary for an institution that critics say
is the epitome of unaccountability. While the 626-member parliament
is elected, most power rests with the commission president and the
19 commissioners, who are appointed by the member nations.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with powers created in the wake of the mismanagement
scandal, Prodi will have a tighter rein on his commissioners. He
secured a promise that they would resign if their integrity comes
under serious question.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Prodi's task of breaking down cynicism was not made any
easier by the unveiling this week of the parliament's opulent new
$500 million home in Strasbourg, 270 miles from the EU's
headquarters here. The parliament already has a bigger, more
expensive building in Brussels that opened two years ago. But in
1992 the French government secured an agreement that mandates the
parliament meet also in Strasbourg.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-story circular building in Strasbourg, where parliament
will sit for about 60 days a year, opened with elevators, air
conditioning, and telephones malfunctioning.
</P>
<P>
   Saying they could not find their way out of the building, some
parliamentarians immediately dubbed their new part-time home
Alcatraz. And many Europeans see it as a temple to the kind of
wasteful spending they associate with the EU.
</P>
<P>
   For Prodi, it is a visceral reminder of the task at hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 0950EDT &QL; 
