u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMIGRANT-SCAM-BOS &LR;      07-29 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANT-SCAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLISH TREATY MAY AID SUSPECTED SWINDLER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Janina Demma worked hard, saved religiously, and built her nest
egg for a big investment in her native Poland. She thought the
dividends would build her own dream house back home.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, authorities said, the money helped build the Krakow
business of the man who allegedly swiped her life's savings.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe that Marian F. Golemo, who allegedly
swindled Demma and other Worcester (Mass.) County victims out of
$300,000, is using the money to sell cars in Poland, operating a
Peugeot dealership there that may be beyond the reach of US
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just sick over this,'' Demma, 51, said Wednesday. ``I'm
never going to be the same. What he's done is very, very painful.
They should bring him back. I pray to God they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Worcester District Attorney John J. Conte said his investigators
have traced Golemo, who fled across the Atlantic after he was
charged with bilking Polish immigrants in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But efforts to return him to face those charges may be thwarted
by a 1927 treaty barring extradition of criminal suspects from
Poland to the United States. Also, Polish law could shield Golemo,
a Polish citizen, from prosecution there for violating US laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't allow their nationals to be extradited,'' a
spokesman for the US Department of Justice said.
</P>
<P>
   That is distressing news for Golemo's alleged victims such as
Demma, who charges that she entrusted $52,000 to him, money she
earned during nine-hour shifts at a pharmaceutical factory.
</P>
<P>
   She said Golemo promised her the funds would be shipped to her
relatives in Poland and placed in a bank account as part of the
services he offered at his Worcester travel agency.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, authorities charge that Golemo, wanted on warrants
charging him with larceny and fraudulent securities sales, pocketed
the money and took off. Authorities have said they believe that
Golemo may have swindled more than 50 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made my family suffer very, very much,'' Demma said. She
said three nephews, her sister, and her brother, who also allegedly
lost his life's savings, fell prey to Golemo.
</P>
<P>
   Before he eluded authorities, Golemo was a prominent figure in
the Polish immigrant community in Massachusetts' second largest
city.
</P>
<P>
   He ran a television repair shop, a video store, a food company,
and a local market that he called home to the best kielbasa ``this
side of Krakow.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Potash, an attorney representing Demma and some of
Golemo's other alleged victims, said Golemo ran a money transfer
business out of his travel agency. He collected a fee to ship the
funds through the National Bank of Poland to his customers'
relatives back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He also claimed to some of them that he would invest their
money and get them high rates of interest,'' Potash said. ``The
money was never invested.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are basically people who are essentially blue-collar
workers, who worked hard to earn their money and these are their
life savings,'' Potash said. ``And they may never recover their
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Demma said she trusted Golemo because earlier transfers for
smaller amounts made it back to Poland just as he had promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was going to send the money like he did before,''
Demma said. ``I signed the check and he cashed it. I wanted to
settle down and life comfortably, not day by day like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Conte's office has said it is seeking the help of the Justice
Department to determine how and whether there is a way to prosecute
Golemo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's long gone and we just have a very sad situation,'' said
John W. Spillane, the attorney who represented Golemo's wife,
Danuta E. Golemo, when she was acquitted in a related larceny case
in 1977.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 0951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
