</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8335 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-GILLEY-BOS &LR;      07-29 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GILLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLEY RELEASES HONKY-TONK'S BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Say the word ``Gilley's'' and it still summons memories of
the ``Urban Cowboy'' film shot there in 1980, back when John
Travolta followed up his blockbuster role in ``Saturday Night
Fever'' by donning a cowboy hat and taking a ride on the mechanical
bull that made Gilley's such a tourist attraction in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Gilley's was dubbed the ``world's largest honky-tonk'' and was
registered that way in the Guinness Book of Records. It was a
6,000-capacity, 48,000-square-foot club in suburban Houston _ and a
``must'' stop for country performers from Faron Young and Ernest
Tubb, to Loretta Lynn, Emmylou Harris, and Rosanne Cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it was or wasn't the largest honky-tonk didn't
matter,'' co-owner Mickey Gilley says with a laugh. ``I submitted
the listing and I got it.'' He concedes that Billy Bob's in Fort
Worth ``could have been bigger,'' but it's an academic argument
because Gilley's burned down 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But not before Gilley, a nationally known entertainer and a
cousin of Jerry Lee Lewis, saved 1,000 rolls of 24-track tape
filled with performances that had aired on the ``Live at Gilley's''
radio show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took them home and stored them in my garage, where I kept my
buses,'' says Gilley, who is hoping to open a new Gilley's in
Dallas someday.
</P>
<P>
   After years of tracking down licensing approval from the artists
and finding the right record label fit, he has managed to transform
his tapes into a one-of-a-kind boxed set, ``Live at Gilley's,'' on
Q Records (distributed by Atlantic). It's a four-volume set
lovingly compiled by producers Alan Rubens and Clark Enslin, who
rightly call it the largest collection of previously unreleased
country music in the world _ and all of it done on the same
recording console at Gilley's.
</P>
<P>
   The new box has everything from Willie Nelson's classic ballad
``Crazy'' and Jerry Lee Lewis's ``Whole Lotta Shakin' Goin' On,''
to Ed Bruce's ``Mamas Don't Let Your Babies Grow Up to Be Cowboys''
and Loretta Lynn's ``Out of My Head and Back in My Bed.''
Lesser-known artists Razzy Bailey, Moe Bandy, and Dave and Sugar
are represented, as are legends like Carl Perkins and Fats Domino.
And, of course, honky-tonkers such as Johnny (``Take This Job and
Shove It'') Paycheck and Gilley himself (with ``Roomful of Roses'')
are in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the boxed set the last word on Gilley's. Individual live
albums from Paycheck, Domino, Perkins, and the Bellamy Brothers
have also been released. And two more live albums by Lewis and
Bobby Bare come out Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   All of this from a club that has been gone for a decade _ much
to the regret of Gilley, whose days there ended in a feud with a
partner whom he couldn't persuade to spend more money on
maintaining the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that Gilley's would have ever run its course, if
more money had been invested,'' he says. ``The parking lot had
holes in it and the building had deteriorated. And the lighting and
sound systems were outdated.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in its glory days, Gilley's was the place to go in Texas;
witness the sign on the door that read: ``Through these doors pass
the greatest entertainers and customers in the world.'' Gilley
often played there and his band featured former Boston guitarist
Rocky Stone, a onetime mainstay with Boston's Chuck McDermott and
Wheatstraw. (Stone, who originally came from Rhode Island, was
immortalized in ``Urban Cowboy'' when Gilley said ``Take it away,
Rocky Stone'' during a solo. Stone died of a stroke last year.)
</P>
<P>
   The peak for Gilley's came with ``Urban Cowboy,'' the 1980 film
whose story was developed from an Aaron Latham piece in Esquire
magazine. Gilley was skeptical that a film would ever come of it,
but ``I became a believer when I saw those trucks roll in from
Paramount.''
</P>
<P>
   While some observers later felt that ``Urban Cowboy'' had a
mixed impact on country music (attracting trendies who didn't stick
around), Gilley still waxes ecstatic when he talks about the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought a lot of people into country music that would never
have heard it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As for the historical impact of Gilley's, the club is often
viewed as the transition point where the more traditional country
music gave way to the crossover country-rock that is popular in the
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Gilley, who just turned 63, rarely tours because he
owns his own theater in Branson, Mo., where he prefers to perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pulling in 800-1,000 people a day,'' he says. ``There's
no point for me to go out on the road. This way, I don't have to
pay an agency and I don't have to worry about buses breaking down.
I'm very happy with the way things are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
