 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2561 -- July 29, 1999  NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2561 -- July 29, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. FOR THE DISABLED, SPECIAL DOGS ASSUME SPECIAL DUTIES For
almost 70 years, blind people have been assisted by guide dogs.
Now, an increasing number of people with physical disabilities are
getting the same kind of help from ``service dogs,'' specially
trained to make up for limitations in mobility, coordination or
strength. By John O'Neil. New York Times Science Times. 950 words +
photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
WHEN THE BRAIN'S MAILBOX IS FULL Memory lapses or ``senior
moments'' in older people may signal that a mailbox of memory is
full rather than that the brain fails to process information,
suggests a new study on memory. As we get older, we run out of
places to store new information. We have a limited amount of space
in our memory system. By Nancy Beth Jackson. New York Times Science
Times. 675 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
ONE DAY SOON WE HOPE ALL CANCER PATIENTS CAN BE CURED Jerome
Groopman, a professor of medicine at Harvard, who is the author of
``The Measure of Our Days,'' writes of his elation when Lance
Armstrong, a cancer survivor, won the Tour de France, and also of
his regret that progress in cancer therapy and finding an overall
cure is painfully slow. By Jerome Groopman. New York Times Op-Ed.
800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
THERE IS A NEW, HOPEFUL CLIMATE IN THE MIDEAST A new era is
announcing itself in the Middle East. It may be that the yearning
to get on with the effort for peace and development has inflated
hopes. But the belief that there really is a new chance is itself
an important part of the climate change. The focus is on Israel's
new Prime Minister, Ehud Barak. By Flora Lewis. 800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 5.
BELLYDANCING FEVER SPREADS AT GYMS Belly dancing usually has its
place in dimly lit clubs, thick with incense and the beat of drums.
It is believed to have originated in what is now northern India and
spread throughout eastern Europe and into northern Africa 700 years
ago, mixing with indigenous dance forms. Now urban gyms have
tailored the dance into a legitimate workout, good for
coordination, endurance, balance and toning. By Amanda Hesser. New
York Times Science Times. 1,200 words + graphic.
_____________________________________________________________
</P>
