<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There are few better ways to make a living
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ There are four professions whose
practitioners generally take pride in what they do, though the rest
of humanity views them in a somewhat lesser light.
</P>
<P>
   _ Politicians.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cops.
</P>
<P>
   _ Journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians are considered to be at the bottom of the heap among
these four professions. The word itself, ``politician,'' is used as
an insult, second only to calling someone a liberal. The worst
insult these days is ``liberal politician.'' Candidates try to win
election by avowing that ``I'm not a politician,'' a contradiction
in terms since the very act of seeking elective office defines one
as a politician. Perversely, I admire people who view politics as a
noble calling, even when I don't agree with them. If devoting one's
life to playing some small part in running the greatest country on
earth isn't a noble calling, then what is?
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean there aren't scalawags in politics, probably
too many. But I'm not sure there are any more scumbags in politics
than in plumbing, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers. Bless their hearts. Search the Internet sometime for
lawyer jokes. Even Aggies don't have as many jokes told about them.
Most are pretty darned funny, too.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my best friends are lawyers. They work hard arguing
cases, protecting clients' interests, recovering damages when
warranted, and prosecuting or defending those who have been accused
of committing crimes. I know many fine people who are lawyers, and
I have known a few lawyers I wouldn't spit on if they were on fire.
Again, it's not much different than the plumbing profession,
percentagewise, in my view.
</P>
<P>
   Cops. Cops and journalists are often at loggerheads. We have
different agendas. Their job is to enforce the law, put the bad
eggs in jail and keep the peace. Our job is to report what
happened. Sometimes that conflicts with what a police officer is
doing. The cop thinks the case might be a bit stronger if we don't
write a story until the officer is ready for a story to be written.
My standard answer is, ``If you won't try to run the newspaper, I
won't try to be a police officer.'' A newspaper is not an agency of
law enforcement, any more than it's an agency of the city
commission, the school board or the football team. We're not the
booster club; we're journalists.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, I have an abiding admiration for police officers.
Like most journalists, they work long hours for mediocre pay _
nights, weekends and holidays. People are always yelling at them.
Their spouses wonder why they don't find a less stressful line of
work.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that we journalists rarely put our lives at
risk. Most days, we don't worry about getting shot or assaulted.
Cops face that risk every day, and that's why I hold them in high
esteem even when they're mad at me for putting something in the
newspaper they wish had been kept out. Or even when they're jerks.
Refer to the plumbing analogy, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to journalists. I'm proud of having been in this
line of work more or less steadily since I was 13, more than three
decades. Luckily, there aren't many journalist jokes. But maybe
even more than politicians, cops and lawyers, we're fair game
because, at least in the print media, what we write is there
forever for everyone to see. And sometimes we write really dumb
things, or we spell names wrong, get facts wrong, or make
grammatical or spelling errors. As a beleaguered editor for this
newspaper put it about 90 years ago, ``An editor is a man who is
liable to grammatical blunders, toothache, typographical errors and
lapses of memory, and usually he has half a million people watching
to catch him tripping. And yet the world is full of people who want
to be editors.''
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, I have seen more than my share of folks who had no
business working for a newspaper. They couldn't get basic facts
right, or they were lousy writers, or they simply lacked integrity
and fairness. The percentage is not much different from plumbing, I
figure.
</P>
<P>
   Watching a newspaper created from scratch each day, to steal a
phrase from politics, is like watching sausage being made. It's
fast, sometimes ugly, a bit frenetic and too often some adulterated
content slips into the product. Luckily, we get to start anew the
next morning. All we can do is try to do a little better the next
day, aware we'll never be perfect, but that we must be fair and
honest and acknowledge our mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   I can't think of a better way to make a living.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
