<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Seedlings of peace growing again under Barak
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to forecast Middle East politics would unnerve even the
most brazen soothsayer, but for what they are worth, the early
portents from the change in Israeli governments are promising.
</P>
<P>
   A caution, however: Even if the good intentions that seem to be
breaking out all around are genuine, don't expect peace on a
platter next week. The issues are real and difficult and won't be
resolved by even a thick salve of warm feelings.
</P>
<P>
   A rapprochement in the region has been elusive for more reasons
than the perversity of the parties titularly involved in the hunt
for it.
</P>
<P>
   That said, some of the players usually busily engaged in making
the difficult impossible are currently on their good behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian hard case Hafez Assad has moved from unapproachable to
hard-to-get, sensing a deal with Israel might finally bring a
return of the Golan Heights. (And by loosening international
sanctions, help an economy that Assad's policies have trashed.)
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah militants at the Lebanon border have stopped harrying
Israeli troops. Lebanon is run second-hand from Syria, and Assad
turns Hezbollah on and off like a water tap. Jordan's new king,
Abdullah, is playing honest broker between Jerusalem and Damascus,
apparently with Israel's encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian President
Yasser Arafat have met three times and if not yet productively _
they don't see eye-to-eye so far even on the threshold issue of
when to implement the Wye River accords _ they are talking free of
the gut dislike that marked sessions between Arafat and the
previous prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   As the Netanyahu government said Arafat could if he would _ and
to that government's credit insisted that he do _ the Palestinian
has kept the yearning terrorists in his population on ice. (Though
some of the worst are scimitar-rattling again.)
</P>
<P>
   Israel, tendering goodwill gestures, has canceled threats to
close Orient House, with its Palestinian offices, in East Jerusalem
and has freed up East Jerusalem residency permits for some
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The Barak government has cut subsidies to ideologically
motivated Jewish settlements in the West Bank and recently acted
forcefully to remove extremist settlers who tried to create an ad
hoc encampment, strong warning to a movement that, under Netanyahu,
was allowed to create ``new facts on the ground'' _ each of which
complicated, as all were meant to, any effort to create a coherent
Palestinian homeland.
</P>
<P>
   In that, crucially, Barak is making it clear that Israeli policy
is firmly in hand and will not continue to be the patsy of
pre-emptive Israeli rejectionists. Netanyahu seemed helpless
against his own disparate and unstable coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has asked Washington to back off the role of peace
provocateur that it felt it had to play during Netanyahu's balky
tenure, in favor of letting the region's contenders thrash matters
out themselves. At the moment, there are signs they just might be
able to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
