</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BLACK30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cornwell's character gets close, personal
 &HT;    By Meggen Lindsay
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ While Patricia Cornwell packs ``Black Notice''
with her standard intensity and gore, both are subdued by Virginia
chief medical examiner Kay Scarpetta's lingering grief. It is
Christmas in Virginia, but the spirit is lacking as Scarpetta still
mourns the death of her FBI lover, Benton Wesley (``Point of
Origin,'' 1998).
</P>
<P>
   With her cherished niece Lucy out to prove something in a
perilous undercover police investigation and a power-hungry new
deputy chief trying to take control while bumping her longtime cop
buddy Capt. Pete Marino from his position, Scarpetta hopes things
can't get much worse.
</P>
<P>
   They do.
</P>
<P>
   When she can't identify the cause of death of a body found in a
locked and sealed container aboard a ship, it doesn't strike alarm
_ until the same kind of fine, animal-like hairs that were on the
corpse on the ship turn up on the body of a brutally murdered store
clerk. The killings extend to Europe, and Scarpetta and sidekick
Marino are summoned to Interpol's headquarters in France, where
they receive secret orders and information that could endanger
their careers, not to mention their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Scarpetta's home front turns tumultuous as well, as she
discovers that someone has been sending slanderous e-mails online,
using her name. As office sabotage progresses and the plots mingle,
Scarpetta is at her most vulnerable, yet she holds her head high
and plows through the danger.
</P>
<P>
   This story lets the reader into the more personal side of
Scarpetta and the supporting characters. Love may return for her as
the beginning of a new interest sparks _ business meets pleasure
(sort of) in France. Emotions run even higher as she and Lucy
quarrel and the concerned aunt fears for Lucy's mind-set _ she is
not handling her grief over Benton's death in a ``healthy'' way.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the plot is unbelievable, it's captivating enough
to make the reader suspend disbelief until the book is closed for
the final time. It's as deliciously creepy as Cornwell usually is,
but a lot is going on here apart from the mystery. It's not the
best book in the series, but it's definitely high on the list, and
well worth the read this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Meggen Lindsay writes for the Dayton Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
