A8354 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-MALICE30-COX     07-29 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MALICE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Female lead takes the case in `Malice'
 &HT;    By Laura Dempsey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It's sometimes tough to wade into a series
midstream, several books after the recurring characters and base
settings have been well established. It can be tough, but it can be
invigorating when the series in question seems worthwhile. That's
the case with ``Acts of Malice,'' the fifth in a series of legal
whodunits written by a pair of sisters _ Pamela and Mary
O'Shaughnessy _ under the pen name Perri O'Shaughnessy.
</P>
<P>
   The focus is Nina Reilly, a workaday lawyer in Lake Tahoe who's
forged a good reputation in her slightly renegade solo practice. A
cynical and stoic secretary keeps things running as Reilly shuttles
from tough case to single motherhood and back again, raising a
teen-age son and a dog the best she can while handling tricky
defenses and mundane paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Acts of Malice,'' Reilly is hired to defend Jim Strong,
whose younger brother Alex died in what was originally ruled a
skiing accident before the rickety old coroner found evidence of
some lethal chest stomping. The case against Jim is shaky _ the
very idea that a man would stomp his brother to death is hard to
stomach _ but his family's refusal to rally around and his wife's
outright accusation make it less clear-cut for Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   But even a morally ambiguous client would be too simple for this
book: Reilly falls in love with the prosecuting attorney, a man who
left town under the cloud of some type of nervous breakdown,
slightly breaking her heart. The defense attorney and the
prosecutor are sleeping together; the defendant is either a
psychopath or the victim of some cruel conspiracy; the secretary is
acting really weird; and the son wants to go to Germany to visit
his dad _ such a bunch of loose ends to tie, but the O'Shaughnessy
sisters manage quite well. They even throw in a sub-subplot
involving an insurance settlement and a woman with a gambling
problem, but that's just to show Reilly's soft professional side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acts of Malice'' is a good story, well told. It's a fine
summer read with a strong female lead _ that and a glass of
lemonade will get you through a summer weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Dempsey writes for the Dayton Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
