</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Remember when skates had keys?
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Remember when life seemed to be simpler? Before
faxes and e-mail and CDs and VCRs, we traveled at a slower pace.
Here's some readers' recollections of the way we were ...
</P>
<P>
   Gene Currier of Tuscaloosa, Ala., who writes he was ``raised
up'' in San Francisco, Los Angeles and Seattle, proves some things
were universal. He remembers:
</P>
<P>
   _ When we all stood in the schoolyard and recited the Pledge of
Allegiance as our flag was raised each morning.
</P>
<P>
   _ When Burma Shave signs adorned every highway.
</P>
<P>
   _ When a long distance phone call was something special.
</P>
<P>
   _ When roller skates had four wheels, clamped onto regular shoes
and were tightened with a skate key.
</P>
<P>
   _ When neighborhood grocery stores took your order by phone and
delivered it to your kitchen door the same day.
</P>
<P>
   _ When school didn't start until after Labor Day and basketball
season ended in February.
</P>
<P>
   _ When banks closed at 3 p.m. Monday through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Woods, of Modesto, Calif., remembers:
</P>
<P>
   _ When white sugar was caramelized in an iron skillet to make
``brown sugar.''
</P>
<P>
   _ When the children took turns bathing in the wash tub and used
the same water.
</P>
<P>
   _ When mustard plaster was used for a chest cold and bread
dipped in milk was applied to an infected area.
</P>
<P>
   R. Norrod, of Lufkin, Texas, remembers:
</P>
<P>
   _ When you had to slice your own bread.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you had to color your own margarine.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you might see a Packard, Studebaker, Nash, DeSoto,
Hornet, Edsel, Essex or Model-T driving down the street and no one
thought anything of it.
</P>
<P>
   _ When a web site was where a spider might build her trap.
</P>
<P>
   _ When windshield wipers worked on vacuum and slowed down when
you went up a hill.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you had to wind a watch.
</P>
<P>
   Jynger Garcia, of Riverbank, Calif., will be attending her 40th
high school class reunion in Long Beach, Calif., this October and
remembers:
</P>
<P>
   _ When all drug stores had a soda fountain and chocolate Cokes
were a treat.
</P>
<P>
   _ When girls cold not wear pants to school.
</P>
<P>
   _ When all houses had clothes lines in the back yard and clothes
had to be ironed.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you dialed a phone _ not pushed buttons _ and you knew a
human would answer.
</P>
<P>
   Faye Brown, of Moundville, Ala., remembers:
</P>
<P>
   _ When kids were embarrassed to take a sausage and biscuit
wrapped in a page from the Sears and Roebuck catalog to school for
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you got your Christmas tree from the pasture instead of a
parking lot or grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   _ When no one ever bought new clothes for wearing for ``play.''
Play clothes started out as church clothes which became school
clothes, which became ``knock-about'' and then did they finally
become play clothes.
</P>
<P>
   _ When there was no pre-sweetened cereal. In fact the cereal of
choice was corn bread crumbled in a glass of milk.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you played baseball among the bitterweeds and cow piles,
and without a uniform.
</P>
<P>
   _ When if you were lucky enough to have a phone, you shared it
with several families and your ring was ``two shorts and a long.''
</P>
<P>
   What do you recall about the ``good old days''? Send your
remembrances to Ernest Murray, managing editor of The Lufkin Daily
News. E-mail: emurray(at)coxnews.com. Mailing address: P.O. Box
1089, Lufkin, Texas 75902.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
