<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's his job, and he's sticking to it
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Alex Gonzalez was in a world of pain when he
penned a letter announcing his intent to retire. The West Texan
underwent two surgeries this year to relieve extensive nerve damage
and thought he just wouldn't be able to continue working.
</P>
<P>
   As he recuperated, however, he began feeling better and changed
his mind about retiring. He tried to take the letter back only to
be told he couldn't. Gonzalez vows to go to court to keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   This is one employment dispute with a very long reach. You see,
Gonzalez is no ordinary employee.
</P>
<P>
   He's a state district judge with time left on his term. And the
letter went to Gov. George W. Bush. The governor's staff takes the
position that Gonzalez resigned and his resignation was accepted
and are proceeding with the search for a successor.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez says that once a successor is found, the governor is
going to have to take legal action to remove him, because he's not
leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to withdraw my retirement and called the governor's
office to let them know. They didn't like it,'' Gonzalez said.
``It's a matter of principle. I'm an elected official and I want to
serve out my term. The governor can't dictate when my term ends.''
</P>
<P>
   The area of Texas over which Gonzalez presides is closest to the
Hollywood image of the state _ lots of mesas, cactus and attitude.
People out there don't take kindly to being pushed around and
jealously guard their right to be left alone.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for the governor, Linda Edwards replied that the staff
takes the position that Gonzalez's letter was a resignation and
treated as such. He can't take it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our belief is that a retirement is tantamount to
resignation,'' Edwards said, adding that allowing Gonzalez to
rescind his resignation would set a bad precedent.
</P>
<P>
   What if he doesn't leave once an appointee is selected?
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Gonzalez) chooses not to vacate, the governor or the
attorney general could take legal action.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a situation that has a lot of ramifications beyond the
legal ones. It puts the governor in the position of attempting to
shoo out an elected judge. Bush has been steadfast in his support
of electing judges.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the flavor of this little saga of power, principle and
politics are the facts that Gonzalez is both Hispanic and
Republican. Appointed to the bench by Gov. Mark White in 1984,
Gonzalez switched parties ``about five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor has gotten a lot of mileage out of the Texas and
national press with his outreach to Latinos. Gonzalez was the first
Hispanic to assume the bench in that part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's vow not to go quietly could have a political reach
far beyond the Trans-Pecos country where the 84th State District
court is located.
</P>
<P>
   C/CNN, the Compadre/Comadre News Network that links the Latino
communities around the state will trump whatever spin the
governor's campaign puts on it.
</P>
<P>
   And no doubt, the state's judiciary will be watching closely
events as they unfold. The state's judges have a stake in this as
well.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you look west, you'll see a storm brewing.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
