<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Seniors need an Rx for prescription drug costs
 &HT;    For release Aug. 1, 1999.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Inasmuch as the company I have worked for has blessed me with an
outstanding medical plan that includes a significant reimbursement
on prescription drugs, I have been somewhat indifferent to the
plight of senior citizens and poor people.
</P>
<P>
   In the last years of their lives, my parents _ who had no
prescription drug coverage; neither Medicare nor their secondary
insurance provided any _ would cheat on their drugs, as do so many
other senior citizens. If the prescription called for a daily dose,
they cut the pill in half to save money.
</P>
<P>
   As the cost of prescription drugs became prohibitive to them,
and I discovered they were cutting their pills in half, I began
paying for my parents' prescriptions rather than they cheat
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   I never had to cheat myself, and often a doctor would defend his
writing of costly prescriptions by reminding me that I was insured
for them.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, however, I decided to take note of my
prescriptions and evaluate how much a day I would be paying had I
not had insurance.
</P>
<P>
   It was stunning. I wonder how anybody on Social Security, with
no prescription insurance, can make it.
</P>
<P>
   My health is middling for a guy my age. I'm in my second year of
Medicare backed by my company policy. I'm taking medication for
Type 2 diabetes, a cholesterol problem and a digestion situation.
At this age level, these problems are not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom-line cost of my prescriptions comes to $15.76 a day.
That's $472.80 a month, $5,752.40 a year! With so many living on a
Social Security payment that provides in the vicinity of $14,500 a
year, there's little left for the rent, food, transportation and
backup medical insurance.
</P>
<P>
   One drug I take, for Type 2 diabetes, is retailing at $4.74 a
pill. Another, for cholesterol, is $3.19 daily, while a stomach
pill is costing $3.98 a day. Throw a few others in for allergy and
such, and the adding machine stops at $15.76 a day.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has been a major advocate of prescription drug
funding for Medicare beneficiaries. In a speech in July in
Michigan, Clinton said that 75 percent of elderly Americans
``either have no drug coverage at all, or coverage that is
unstable, unaffordable and rapidly disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican tax-cut bill offers a bone to prescription drugs
for Medicare beneficiaries _ a small tax writeoff.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies, meanwhile, are fighting the president's
position. Knowing full well that Medicare will not pay the
outrageous prices being charged for medication, they argue that any
dimunition of drug profits will arrest their abilities for
research.
</P>
<P>
   I would agree that such might be the case. I wonder, however,
how much money could be diverted from ballyhoo to research. For
more than a couple of years, a particular antihistamine has been
advertised heavily in national publications, including offering a
$5 discount for getting your doctor to prescribe it for you.
Likewise, a capsule to keep your stomach calm.
</P>
<P>
   Those who take the drugs say it works wonders for them; I take
the one for the stomach and can attest to its potency. But what I
would challenge is how much the pharmaceutical companies spend on
advertising and promotion for some of their drugs (and how many
rewards they give doctors for prescribing them), as opposed to how
much they might lose if Medicare payments _ i.e., if rational
prices were applied to prescription drugs _ became a significant
factor in the income.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting some of that heavy advertising over to research might
be a consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America
recently noted that America's aging population _ growing rapidly _
is the target for almost 600 new drugs reaching the market.
</P>
<P>
   If drug manufacturers need to spend money on research,
development and promotion, they simply include it in the cost of
the drug. But the patient has nowhere to turn. And, as the patient
ages, his or her income begins to decline in most cases. Soaring
drug costs against diminishing income is not a formula for what are
supposed to be the Golden Years.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us fortunate to have reimbursement for our drugs,
the Golden Years are a lot more palatable than for those who don't;
those who cut their pills in half, take them maybe once every three
days, or can't afford them at all.
</P>
<P>
   Heed the president on this one.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
