<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What does John Cornyn's future hold?
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If you went to Central Casting for someone tos
up in 2002, and while he certainly hasn't said he's quitting, it
would not be completely surprising if, after 18 years, he decided
to do something else.
</P>
<P>
   As for governor, if current Gov. George W. Bush wins the
presidency, Lt. Gov. Rick Perry would become governor and,
presumably, seek re-election in 2002. Cornyn probably wouldn't look
at a race for lieutenant governor as a step up, but running for
governor or senator in 2006 would by no means be out of the
question.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, as do most good incumbents barely sworn in, says he
loves his job. So that means the only race he'd consider would be
for re-election?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Cornyn said, slowly smiling, ``never say never.''
</P>
<P>
   McNeely writes about politics for the American-Statesman. You
may contact him at dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
