<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FUTURE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What's ahead for travel? Let's trek into the future
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the last century, travelers explored
the world by boat and horse, often at great risk.
</P>
<P>
   Huge ocean liners appeared in the early part of this century _
the Queen Elizabeth, the Queen Mary, the S.S. France _ and those
with money and wanderlust traveled in style.
</P>
<P>
   Air travel came in the 1940s, and only one grand liner, the
Queen Elizabeth 2, was left to travel between continents.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the super mega-liners are back, although most don't roam
the globe. Travelers are getting adventurous. They're scaling rock
cliffs, kayaking and hiking in far-flung places.
</P>
<P>
   What possibly could be next in the 21st century? Here's a peek
at the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   OUT OF THIS WORLD: You've gone white-water rafting down the
Zambezi, and you've scaled mountains in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   What's left to explore in the new millennium?
</P>
<P>
   The next step is space.
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh. NASA is serious about space tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the market demand is there. A lot of people would
like to go to space,'' says John Mankins, manager of NASA Advance
Concepts Studies.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has conducted studies to see how much people are willing to
spend to be space travelers. They found that a lot of people would
pay $1 million, but if the price went down to $100,000 or less,
there would be ``tens of thousands'' of people who would take that
giant leap for touristkind.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, NASA is trying to figure out how to bring the
costs down.
</P>
<P>
   NASA would like nothing better than to be host to a lot of
paying customers.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial development of space travel would help pay the bills,
Mankins says.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly when will the first tourists be free of gravity?
</P>
<P>
   ``If money were no object,'' says Mankins, ``it could be done in
a few years, but if they really wanted to make it a lot cheaper,
it's probably going to be at least 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   E-HOTELS: The two main amenities of hotels in the past have been
a nice firm bed and a window with a view.
</P>
<P>
   Guests at hotels in the next century may be able to choose their
view with computer-generated scenery. Want to see a beautiful
beach? Press a button.
</P>
<P>
   And the firmness of the bed will be adjusted electronically.
</P>
<P>
   Bedside ``butlers'' will allow guests to adjust window curtains,
room temperature, TV, and even the bathtub water.
</P>
<P>
   Faculty members at the Conrad N. Hilton College of Hotel and
Restaurant Management at the University of Houston are testing ways
to pamper the stressed-out travelers of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Ideas include mattresses that are electronically controlled for
firmness and support, white noise, soundproof rooms, virtual
reality entertainment centers, and alarm clocks that will wake
guests up with light.
</P>
<P>
   Special lighting will help long-distance travelers adjust to new
time zones.
</P>
<P>
   FEEL (at) HOME: Other trends sure to be strong in the next
century include a focus on the business traveler and families.
</P>
<P>
   Business suites will feature ``work zones'' that have high
intensity lighting, easily accessible data ports and electric
outlets, high-speed Internet access, free local calls and
long-distance access.
</P>
<P>
   Families often were ignored in the past. Now they're sought out.
Travelodge's Bear's Den rooms, a concept introduced in 10 cities,
offers kid-friendly amenities such as a child's chair, Sleepy Bear
bedspread, VCR, and a Sleepy Bear toy to take home.
</P>
<P>
   Women also are another largely untapped market. The Arizona
Biltmore in Phoenix started a Ladies Choice package when research
showed women like to have a timeout from jobs, husbands and
children. The package includes spa services, cooking classes, golf
clinics and more. Other hotels are sure to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
