<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bright flash of Columbia helps carve away much darker image
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I've told the story many times to impress children
about how quickly information moves. With each passing year they're
less impressed.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of Jan. 28, 1986, I was in the newsroom when a
pressman brought the unbelievable: ``The space shuttle blew up.''
</P>
<P>
   At the nearest terminal I pulled up The Associated Press. There
was the first bulletin. We hustled to the newsroom TV. There on CNN
was a patch of ocean and shards of white splashing into it.
</P>
<P>
   Challenger _ or its pieces _ wasn't out of the sky yet and news
of its demise had sped around the world. That's how fast
information travels, kids.
</P>
<P>
   For all these years the fatal plume of that obliterated ship has
been bookmarked in our minds. Now I have another image that won't
be dislodged.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night just past 10, gawking Central Texans got a most
spectacular scene _ shuttle Columbia speeding through Earth's
atmosphere on its way to a Cape Canaveral landing.
</P>
<P>
   A full moon still awaiting mankind's return helped light the
way.
</P>
<P>
   Over Central Texas, Columbia came from the west, shedding heat
and light like a giant pop-bottle rocket. Only this rocket didn't
pop, didn't stop at its apex. It made a giant croquet wicket above
us, a jet-trail-like path. Horizon to horizon, it took 30 seconds,
or less.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later it had touched down. I didn't have to rush
downtown to the newsroom for the latest. I pulled up the news on
the home computer. No wonder speedy-information tales don't hold a
young audience anymore. But scenes like these in the sky do. My
youngest son was talking about it far into the night.
</P>
<P>
   People fortunate enough to see Columbia streak across the sky
were experiencing something tribal and primal. You could almost see
chariot wheels and winged steeds pulling the traveler.
</P>
<P>
   One was reminded of other moments when human endeavors in space
made us tingle: The night 30 summers ago when we trained binoculars
and junior telescopes on a moon with fresh human footprints. Twelve
summers earlier we'd tracked ominous Sputnik across our skies.
</P>
<P>
   No, we haven't been back to the moon since 1972. But space
travel is becoming something routine, akin to the wire-service
transmissions that don't impress so many. The mission of Columbia
was aimed at placing an X-ray telescope into orbit. Future shuttles
will deliver parts of the International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as romantic, but any 1980s notion that the space
program has run aground are long debunked.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there will be budget skirmishes. And there should be.
Republican budget writers in the House voted to allocate NASA 10
percent less next year. President Clinton's proposal is essentially
a freeze.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has to accept limits, just as do other federal functions.
Space efforts are becoming international and collaborative, not us
vs. anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Columbia crew have two women, including the
first female commander, Eileen Collins, it also had a French
mission specialist.
</P>
<P>
   The space program may be costly, may dabble on the fringes of
what we need to know to survive. But it's something we do because
we can't help it. It's who we are, what we do. We explore.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is editorial page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
