   COXNET BOOKS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Books page for the current week. This
layout will be available Friday before 1 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0731 MIGRANT WORKER _ Elva Trevino Hart was working
for IBM, making six figures and driving a Mercedes, when she
decided to take a writing course at a YWCA. She felt a need to
write about her migrant worker childhood. The result is a touching
memoir of a fascinating life. (Morris, Austin American-Statesman)
Art includes 3-column color photo of author and her sister and a
6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SMUTTY NOVEL _ For those of you not keeping up with the
difficult task of pairing off in your 20s, it's become an entire
publishing subgenre of late. It's brought us some good reads
(notably, Melissa Bank's ``Girls' Guide to Hunting and Fishing'').
Now it's brought us a royally bad one _ Amy Sohn's ``Run Catch
Kiss,'' a collection of fleshed-out Penthouse letters masquerading
as modern literature. (Wizda, Austin American-Statesman) Art
includes 1-column color photo of author and a 6-pica color photo of
book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   GATES PLOT -- Author Gary Rivlin has written an intimate history
of the do-or-die competition that reigns in the lucrative,
high-stakes world of computer technology, a history that centers on
the amazing success of Bill Gates and Microsoft. (Bernstein, N.Y.
Times News Service) Art includes 1-column photo of Bill Gates and a
6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER READING -- Short takes on latest mystery releases of
note. (Warmbold, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes three
6-pica color photos of book jackets.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK NEWS -- As the publishing world discovered when Princess
Diana was killed, nothing sells books like the tragic death of a
much-loved celebrity. Expect the same with John F. Kennedy Jr.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-FOR-KIDS _ Roundup of new books for kids. (Bookman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MALICE _ It's sometimes tough to wade into a series
midstream, several books after the recurring characters and base
settings have been well established. It can be tough, but it can be
invigorating when the series in question seems worthwhile. That's
the case with Acts of Malice, the fifth in a series of legal
whodunits written by a pair of sisters _ Pamela and Mary
O'Shaughnessy _ under the pen name Perri O'Shaughnessy. (Dempsey,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-BLACK _ While Patricia Cornwell packs ``Black Notice'' with
her standard intensity and gore, both are subdued by Virginia chief
medical examiner Kay Scarpetta's lingering grief. It is Christmas
in Virginia, but the spirit is lacking as Scarpetta still mourns
the death of her FBI lover, Benton Wesley (Point of Origin, 1998).
(Lindsay, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Having learned their lesson from the Princess Diana
tragedy, publishers are hastily re-issuing and updating books on
JFK Jr. and planning to publish new ones. Also, expect a flurry of
books about Hillary and Bill in the next year. Gail Sheehy's book
on the First Lady is out this fall and Peggy Noonan, the former
Reagan speechwriter, is penning ``The Case Against Hillary'' for
next spring. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
EDT.
</P>
