<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, July 29, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Mark Helm at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-KILLINGS- (Yosemite National Park, Calif.) _ After
receiving a flood of queries about unsolved killings from
California law enforcement agencies, the FBI has agreed to help
local cops determine if Cary Stayner is responsible for any other
unsolved homicides. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-SUSPECT (Yosemite National Park, Calif.) _ Somewhere in
the drama-infused life of Cary Stayner, seeds of serial murder were
planted. But while research into the minds of multiple murderers
has identified common causes, the template doesn't fit neatly over
Stayner's story. Stayner, 37, has confessed to the killings of
three tourists he held captive in Yosemite National Park and a
naturalist who worked there. By MICHAEL DOUGAN and ELIZABETH
FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   PACIFICA-RADIO (Berkeley, Calif.) _ In what appeared to be an
abrupt turnaround, the Pacifica Foundation announced it would
reopen KPFA and remove itself from management of the beleaguered
Berkeley radio station for six to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AGILENT-NAME (San Francisco) _ ``Air Sick Bag Inc.'' Much to the
surprise of Palo Alto-based Hewlett-Packard Co. executives, that
was one foreign translation of a proposed name for the company's
new spin-off corporation. Hewlett-Packard avoided that gaffe by
naming the spin-off Agilent Technologies. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-SARATOGA (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ The 131st opening of
Saratoga Race Course drew a dapper, chapeau-wearing crowd of 26,720
Wednesday, a record for a July start and 1,150 more people than
last year. Horseplayers packed the grounds and grandstand, full of
expectations and carrying fat wallets. A July opening day record of
$3,193,902 was wagered at the track, $95,700 more than 1998's
kickoff. By LINDA TRISCHITTA.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RAIDERS-KICKER (Napa, Calif.) _ It isn't easy for any player
who joins a new team. If he's lucky, there'll be a few guys he's
played with before. Still, he's an outsider trying to fit in as
quickly as possible. It's an even tougher adjustment for a kicker.
Michael Husted, the Raiders' new field-goal kicker, understands
there is a natural prejudice against the men who do his job. By
FRAN BLACKMAN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK-BLAME (Albany, N.Y.) _ As cleanup continues on the
decimated property that was once Woodstock '99, a national expert
in rock concert crowd safety said organizers are to blame for
creating an environment that was ripe for Sunday's riot. By ALAN
WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK-HAVENS (Oakland, Calif.) _ Talking to a crowd at a
bookstore, Richie Havens was asked why he thought people rioted at
the latest Woodstock nostalgia concert. Havens, whose act opened
the original Woodstock in 1969, shook his head. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CAST CHANGES (Pasadena, Calif.) _ You need a program to track
the cast changes for the fall. But we know this much: Heather
Locklear is going to become a cast member on ``Spin City.'' That
probably won't help in toning down all the relentless sex jokes of
this once-stellar show. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLD-SOUP (Undated) _ About the last thing anyone wants to do on
an 80-degree day is simmer a pot on the stove for several hours.
But not all soups need to be simmered and served hot. The harvest
of summer produce brings with it the ability to make cold,
refreshing dishes that just happen to be liquid and served in a
bowl: soup. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ It looks like another cold,
dreary summer day in San Francisco. Just as I mumble, ``Bummer,'' I
remember recent conversations with family and friends back East who
say the heat wave is hell. I must live in paradise. By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
