<HEADER>
A8436 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-MAYOR-$ADV01-     07-29 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MAYOR-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LORD MAYOR OF LONDON TO VISIT SOUTHEASTERN U.S. FINANCIAL
CENTERS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 1 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Seeking better ties between the British capital's
financial community and the booming American Southeast, the lord
mayor of London will travel to Atlanta this week(8/5-6) to meet
with business and political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Levene, also the lord of Portsoken, said last week(CQ)
that it is essential for London to reach out beyond the familiar
turf of New York City if it is to retain its position as one of the
world's foremost international financial center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe the United States begins and ends in
Manhattan,'' said Levene during an interview at the official
mayoral residence, Mansion House. ``We regard the (U.S.) Southeast
with Atlanta at the center of it as being enormously powerful and
very important. If you took the Southeast of the United States and
just ring fenced it, that in itself would probably be one of the
largest most important countries in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Levene intends to stop in Charlotte, N.C., to meet with
NationsBank Chairman Hugh McColl before arriving in Atlanta, where
he will meet with Gov. Roy Barnes. He also will meet with
executives from Wachovia and SunTrust banking companies, Insurance
Commissioner John Oxendine and representatives of the regional
transportation authority.
</P>
<P>
   The lord mayor said his message is simple: ``We want to persuade
banks, companies, financiers -- anyone who's interested in
international trade -- that they should look at London as the first
stop in the international financial world.''
</P>
<P>
   Also chairman of European investment for Deutsche Bank, Levene
is one of the most experienced business and political leaders to
serve in the largely ceremonial post of lord mayor. He was former
British Prime Minister John Major's adviser on efficiency and
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   He is using his high profile to reassure the business world that
London has lost none of its luster even though Britain is the most
conspicuous European player to reject joining the unified currency.
The euro was initiated for banking and other electronic
transactions last January.
</P>
<P>
   Levene said the city's financial center has been affected little
by the Euro. ``The reason is that London is by far the most
important financial center in Europe, and we trade here whatever
financial instrument is trading, be it euros or dollars or yen or
anything else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling with the lord mayor will be Max Taylor, the chairman
of Lloyd's of London; and Tim Carroll, the chairman of the
International Underwriters Association of London.
</P>
<P>
   After his business trip, which also includes stops in Miami and
San Francisco, Levene said he will vacation at his home on Sea
Island, where he has been a part-time resident for 14 years. ``I
have quite strong ties with Georgia because we also have a home
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Levene is the last of his ancient line of lord mayors to hold
the post without the presence of an elected mayor, who will preside
over the city of 7.2 million beginning next year. London has never
before had a directly elected mayor or the level of autonomy
contemplated in its proposed new government.
</P>
<P>
   The election, a source of considerable political friction here,
will be held next May. Among the candidates is Jeffrey Archer, the
blockbuster novelist and member of the House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
