<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8438 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIRGIN-TRASH-$ADV01-C     07-29 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRGIN-TRASH-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CASH-STRAPPED VIRGIN ISLANDS HIDING DIRTY LITTLE SECRET -
GARBAGE
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 1 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands _ These islands, bathed in
the warm tropical waters of the Atlantic and the Caribbean, are one
of the world's most popular tourist destinations. They boast
undulating verdant slopes, a host of duty-free shops and old
Danish-style buildings lining picturesque waterfronts.
</P>
<P>
   But there are sites locals are well aware of that -- hopefully
-- no tourist will ever see: the Bovoni and Anguilla landfills.
</P>
<P>
   The Bovoni Landfill, on the south side of St. Thomas island, is
an unsightly spectacle of junked cars, discarded appliances and
other garbage. Methane gases smolder underground, so much so that
pockets have exploded, spitting fireballs 30 feet into the air.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Anguilla Landfill on St. Croix towers 70 feet
high and is less than a half-mile from the Henry E. Rohlsen
International Airport. Aviation officials say birds attracted by
the garbage are endangering airplanes during take-offs and
landings.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the landfills pose a risk to air travelers,
according to environmentalists, they also threaten local residents
who for years have complained of coughs, nausea, and stinging eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone here agrees on the need for new landfills.
That's not the problem. The problem is money. This U.S. territory
is broke.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to mismanagement, hurricane damage and falling tourism
revenues, the Virgin Islands government is burdened with at least
$1 billion in debt, an extraordinary sum for a population of
110,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This government has been a notoriously big spender and, at the
same time, a poor planner,'' said Adlah Donastorg, chairman of the
territorial Senate Committee on Planning and Environmental
Protection and a critic of the lack of progress in addressing the
waste problem.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Gov. Charles Turnbull, who inherited a budget
deficit of more than $100 million, as well as a long-term debt of
$1 billion, when he took office last January, said the government
is searching for alternate sites to build landfills but that, so
far, no sites have been located.
</P>
<P>
   He said Turnbull has vowed to chip away at the debt with a
five-year ``austerity plan'' to be unveiled by September.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the three-island chain are saddled with an
extraordinary amount of trash.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, the
Virgin Islands generate 9.2 pounds of garbage per person per day,
more than double the U.S. mainland average of 4.4 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Excessive trash is partly the result of day-trippers who visit
the islands via cruise ship, as well as all the imported products
packaged in boxes and crates that must be disposed of.
</P>
<P>
   But the government has never implemented a recycling program,
nor has it charged dumping fees at the landfills that might have
incited residents to monitor the garbage generated.
</P>
<P>
   All this has left the landfills overwhelmed with garbage, so
much so that they attract birds that can smash airplane windscreens
and dent propellers.
</P>
<P>
   The landfill in St. Croix violates Federal Aviation
Administration rules that state any site attracting wildlife should
be kept five miles from any airport.
</P>
<P>
   To build a new landfill could cost as much as $70 million,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Not a small sum when the Virgin Islands government is struggling
to pay its utility bills. The debt-ridden U.S. territory owes $16
million for electricity and $17 million for water, according to the
Virgin Islands Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   The government can't even afford to maintain its fleet of public
buses, forcing locals to take the nicer, but more expensive tourist
buses.
</P>
<P>
   Irate at this, some critics blame the government _ which has a
budget of about $466 million _ for mismanaging its money.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Donastorg said the islands are represented by 15
senators, an unnecessarily high number. He said millions of dollars
could be saved by cutting the number to nine.
</P>
<P>
   Other observers say a bigger culprit to blame for the islands'
financial fix -- at least partly -- is a decline in the number of
overnight visitors, and the money they spend.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1994, before Hurricane Marilyn hit, visitors
spent $919 million. In 1996, after the hurricane, they spent only
$781 million.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the number of overnight visitors to the U.S.
territory fell from 555,000 in 1988 to 410,000 last year, a decline
of 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time the government is being robbed of essential
tourist dollars, it has spent some $250 million to rebuild on
hotels and other tourist facilities alone over the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Hurricane Marilyn, which damaged 80 percent of the
islands, we lost quite a lot of business, and it is taking time to
build that business back up again,'' said Beverly Nicholson,
executive director of the St. Thomas/St. John Hotel Association.
</P>
<P>
   Still, money or no money, Jim Casey, EPA's coordinator for the
Virgin Islands, insisted that some government action must be taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``The landfills don't comply with EPA rules,'' he said. ``These
are really dumps, and not landfills.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the government monitors what comes in to the landfills,
but that the waste is not screened. He said trash is not separated,
nor is it adequately covered.
</P>
<P>
   Casey said that, under an agreement with the FAA, the Anguilla
Landfill must be closed by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Bovoni Landfill will reach capacity within the
next five years. The EPA ordered the government in June to clean up
the site, which is in violation of the Clean Water Act because of
its damage to sensitive tidal salt flats and nearby mangrove
wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``These landfills really should have been closed in 1996, but
the money just hasn't been there to find an alternative,'' Casey
said. ``And it's also not easy to find alternative sites on such
tiny islands, so I'm not sure what the government is going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
