<HEADER>
A8467 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-HOLLYWOOD-REMAKE     07-29 1374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-HOLLYWOOD-REMAKES-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWICE-TOLD TALES: HOLLYWOOD'S ONGOING ROMANCE WITH REMAKES 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Pierce Brosnan
and Rene Russo in ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' and Vince Vaughn in
``Psycho.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The technical term is deja vu.
 &HT;    If you were around in l968, you may remember ``The Thomas Crown
Affair,'' a highly watchable romantic thriller starring Steve
McQueen as a bored tycoon who steals Old Masters for kicks and Faye
Dunaway as the single-minded insurance investigator who melts in
his arms. From the wardrobe to the dizzying, constantly moving
camera, it was one of the most stylish movies of the decade.
 &HT;    On Aug. 6, ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' will reopen _ but this
time with Pierce Brosnan, best known these days as Agent 007, in
the McQueen role. Rene Russo, like Dunaway an ex-model, plays his
pursuer.
 &HT;    Which begs the question: Why bother with a remake when the
original was so good?
 &HT;    It's a question that should be posed more often. Hollywood's
track record with recycling is shaky, to say the least. There was
``Sabrina'' _ the l952 version with Audrey Hepburn, Humphrey Bogart
and William Holden, revamped disappointingly with Julia Ormond,
Harrison Ford and Greg Kinnear in l995. ``Lolita'' _ filmed in l961
by the late Stanley Kubrick and redone in l997 by Adrian Lyne with
limited success. ``Meet Joe Black'' _ a l997 remake of ``Death
Takes a Holiday'' (l934) which managed to be a miserable failure
even with Brad Pitt and Anthony Hopkins.
 &HT;    All of which attests to the fact that a remade classic does not
a hit guarantee. In fact, the video shelves are crowded with these
vain efforts to reinvent the movie wheel.
 &HT;    In a category of its own is one of last year's most ... well,
unusual films. Everyone remembers Hitchcock's masterpiece
``Psycho'' (1960). But, even five years from now, who will recall
the mundane l998 shot-for-shot remake by Gus Van Sant?
 &HT;    It helps if there's a reason for doing a remake. Mike Nichols
thought the 1978 French farce ``La Cage Aux Folles'' deserved wider
exposure in America, for example, so he faithfully translated it
into ``The Birdcage'' (l996), with Robin Williams and Nathan Lane,
and scored a hit.
 &HT;    But for every ``Birdcage'' there are a dozen updates and remakes
that could well have gone unmade, some of them with major names
attached. Certified celluloid genius Martin Scorsese had only
limited success with ``Cape Fear'' (1991), even with Robert De Niro
as the vicious rapist played by Robert Mitchum in the l961 version.
Steven Spielberg struck out with ``Always'' (l989), based on ``A
Guy Named Joe'' (l943), which starred Spencer Tracy.
 &HT;    Of course, some argue that a remake is justified to make an
older film accessible to contemporary audiences. That's the line
taken by Leslie Dixon, screenwriter for the new ``Thomas Crown
Affair.''
 &HT;    ``At first I thought, `Oh, this is going to be easy to adapt to
'90s sensibilities _ I can keep most of it in,''' Dixon says. ``But
what I found was that, while for l968 it was an excellent film and
I admired the screenplay, I only ended up keeping four lines of
dialogue and the idea behind three scenes.''
 &HT;    The primary issue was pacing, he says.
 &HT;    ``The audience's attention span in l968 was so lengthy compared
to that of l999 moviegoers,'' the writer explains. ``At that time
you could begin a movie with a 40-minute heist in which the girl
plays no active part. And then there are cuts back to Steve
McQueen, with him thinking, `I bet they're breaking into the bank
right now _ but I'm here in my office doing nothing.'
 &HT;    ``You can't do that anymore. From that point on, things start to
unravel.''
 &HT;    The new version, accordingly, has Brosnan as a more active
thief, if not quite on the level of Tom Cruise in ``Mission
Impossible'' (l997).
 &HT;    Again, the original ``Thomas Crown'' depicted a seductive chess
game between Dunaway and McQueen, leading to their first sexual
encounter.
 &HT;    ``If you did it the same way,'' Dixon says, ``it would be
considered a ripoff. So you have to come up with something else.
The way it was done in the film was too arch _ her fiddling with
her bra strap works great when you look at it through a l968
telescope. Do it in l999, and you are going to look like a bit of
an idiot.''
 &HT;    Charles Shyer, who directed the 1991 remake of ``Father of the
Bride'' (1950), with Steve Martin stepping in for Spencer Tracy,
says that it's actually a good idea not to pay too much attention
to the original.
 &HT;    ``With `Father of the Bride,''' he recalls, ``we tried to put
Spencer Tracy, Vincente Minnelli's film and Elizabeth Taylor out of
our minds a little bit, because you can get paralyzed thinking
about the original movie.
 &HT;    ``In our movie Steve brought his brand of humor, unique and
brilliant, and he's so different from Spencer,'' he adds. ``If they
had asked us to do it with another actor, I don't think we would
have. Because you say, `Oh, nobody can be Tracy.'''
 &HT;    Hollywood executives say that part of the appeal of remaking the
films of the past lies in the idea _ far from proven, of course _
that it provides some insurance against a flop.
 &HT;    ``Making movies gets costlier every day,'' says one independent
producer who requested anonymity, ``and executives worried about
runaway budgets will do anything to play it safe and avoid
megabudget films.
 &HT;    ``Taking a familiar old film is one way to reduce the odds,'' he
adds. ``If you are redoing a well-known title, it can cut the risk
factor by maybe one-third in what is an annual Hollywood
crapshoot.''
 &HT;    Of course, it comes with risks of its own. As dicey as Van
Sant's ``Psycho'' remake may have been, arguably Turner
Broadcasting is about to take an even greater gamble, remaking an
even more beloved film: Fred Zinnemann's ``High Noon'' (1952), the
seminal Western that starred Gary Cooper and Grace Kelly.
 &HT;    Even some of Turner's own employees have broken ranks on this
remake, set to air in 2000. Longtime Hollywood reporter Robert
Osborne, who also hosts ``Turner Classic Movies'' on TBS, pulls no
punches in denouncing the project.
 &HT;    ``They should leave the classics alone,'' Osborne says. ``I'm
sorry they did `Psycho.' I spent two terrible hours watching it.
They should redo those awful movies based on great books. There's
no point in remaking the classics _ they're just cashing in on the
titles.
 &HT;    ``Who can compete with Gary Cooper? Who can compete with Anthony
Perkins in `Psycho?'''
 &HT;    Turner isn't even the first studio to have the idea. Four years
ago, according to Arnold Kopelson _ who later produced ``The
Fugitive'' (1996) _ he was seriously thinking of redoing ``High
Noon.'' He changed his mind.
 &HT;    ``The consensus was that this is one you don't tamper with,'' he
says. ``It's a classic, and it's there for history.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Thomas Crown Affair,''
consult the film's official Website at
www.mgm.com/thethomascrownaffair. And don't forget to visit The New
York Times Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate
for information on Hollywood Stars and other features. &QL; 
