<SLUG> BC-FILM-BLAIRWITCH-TEX </SLUG>
 
`BLAIR WiTCH' OPENS WIDELY ACROSS NATION 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After playing in only 27 theaters nationwide, ``The Blair Witch
Project'' is finally opening widely on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After creating a buzz at the Sundance Film Festival, this
$20,000 indie about three documentary filmmakers who disappear in
the Maryland woods while researching a local legend has succeeded
well beyond anyone's dreams. Unprecedented crowds have descended
upon Dallas' Inwood Theatre, for example, breaking every record the
theater had set.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought in a crowd that we're not used to having,'' says
Inwood manager Tearlach Hutcheson. ``It's the multiplex crowd.
We're used to the more academically inclined people who would watch
a foreign-language film.''
</P>
<P>
   But although they expected crowds, Hutcheson says, they didn't
expect the kind of mania they've faced the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we had an exclusive, and there has been such a hype
that you've got to see it, ... we've had a lot of angry people,''
he says. ``Especially when you've got a weekend that's over a
hundred degrees and people are standing outside trying to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael H. Price, director of Sundance Square's Gourmet Cinema
program at the AMC Sundance 11 in Fort Worth, doesn't seemed too
concerned. When ``The Blair Witch Project'' opens in downtown Fort
Worth on Friday, Price says he's ready for the inevitable mob.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had outrageous crowds before this summer, so it's just
business as usual as far I'm concerned,'' he says. ``We need one
indie like this a year to bolster the ones that maybe have an
audience of about 500. I'm looking forward to fighting for a seat
in my own auditorium.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutcheson is looking forward to a chance to catch up on
neglected paperwork, but he admits that all the buildup is
warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I watched it,'' he says, ``I think it was the
only time in my life I've actually been chilled to the bone.''
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
