<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING STOCK IN OURSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're thinking about going public.
</P>
<P>
   We haven't made a final decision yet, but we are exploring the
idea of making our column, Boston Capital, a public company. We've
been huddling with our investment bankers, mulling the pros and
cons of doing a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Why do we want to go public, you might ask? We can think of at
least four reasons.
</P>
<P>
   1) Like the New York Stock Exchange, we are responding to a
changing competitive landscape. After more than 200 years as a
private organization, the stock exchange recently announced plans
for an initial public offering. ``I don't think there has ever been
a period like this in the history of world capital markets,''
chairman Richard Grasso said by way of explanation for his move.
``Everyone is in everyone else's business today. Whether you sell
stock or sell suits, the Internet has changed the world.''
</P>
<P>
   We couldn't agree more. Exactly how the stock exchange and
Boston Capital will be more competitive as public companies isn't
completely clear, but now isn't the time to niggle over details.
</P>
<P>
   2) Like United Parcel Service, we need a currency to make
acquisitions. UPS, too, recently said it would go public, despite a
long and profitable history as a private business. Company chairman
James Kelly conceded his firm has plenty of money. But he added,
``We need the extra financial flexibility for acquisitions,
including e-commerce opportunities.'' Us too. With our inflated
stock price, we will pay inflated prices for other companies, just
like everyone else. What will we buy? Don't worry. We'll think of
something.
</P>
<P>
   3) Like other entrepreneurs, we want to take advantage of
current market conditions. In case you haven't noticed, this is a
great time to go public. This summer an average of 13 companies a
week have done IPOs, an impressive pace. The current boom has been
likened to the Oklahoma Land Rush. If that's true, we want our 40
acres and a mule before they stop handing them out. Later this
year, markets could be less receptive to new companies as investors
get nervous about Y2K problems. You'll be happy to know Boston
Capital is already Y2K ready.
</P>
<P>
   4) Like the rest of the have-nots, we're jealous. In the spirit
of full disclosure required by the Securities &AMP; Exchange
Commission, we have to be honest here. It's tough to write a market
column, reporting day after day about 20- and 30-year-olds becoming
millionaires overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week there was Chemdex. Two years ago the firm was
just an idea in the head of David Perry, a Harvard Business School
student. Perry drew up plans for the company and entered them in a
school competition. He didn't win. Tuesday Chemdex hit the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   The business _ which sells something over the Internet, who
cares what? _ had sales of $165,000 last year. The sub shop on your
block probably had bigger revenues. But by the end of Tuesday
Chemdex had a market value of $800 million and 31-year-old David
Perry was worth about $40 million. When is it our turn?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly we have a lot of work to do. We are going to have to
spend heavily to promote our brand name: billboards, radio,
television, maybe even an ad during the Super Bowl. We'll spend
whatever it takes. By the time we're through you'll be seeing the
Boston Capital name in your dreams.
</P>
<P>
   We're going to need a multichannel strategy. Right now we're
available in the newspaper and on the Globe's Web site. In our new
incarnation we'll have our own spot on the Web. Look for the words
``dotcom'' to show up in our name.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that at the moment we don't have any revenue. We don't
see that as a problem. But we don't have any losses either. That
could create a credibility issue on Wall Street. Rest assured we'll
spend enough on marketing to guarantee the kind of robust
seven-figure losses that analysts like to see in an emerging
company.
</P>
<P>
   Chemdex lost $6.8 million last year. That's an ambitious target,
but we're confident we can reach it.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes time to write up the prospectus, we'll have to
inform would-be investors about all the risks this new venture
entails. The biggest one is obvious: One day soon, everyone will
wake up and realize we are in the midst of an incredible
speculative bubble. They'll figure out that even though the
Internet is profoundly remaking the business world that doesn't
mean every Tom, Dick, and Boston Capital is worth all the money
that is being thrown at it.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully that won't happen until the week after we go public.
Happy investing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The Domini Social Equity fund, one of best known socially
responsible mutual funds, this week passed $1 billion in assets.
The fund has grown rapidly in the past few years, driven both by
good performance and by new inflows of money, especially from
retirement plans. The fund is an index fund which includes many of
the big companies that make up the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index.
Companies are excluded from the fund if they invest too much money
in defense activities or if they have poor records in environmental
affairs or in their treatment of employees. In 1999 the fund has
slightly underperformed the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   --Network Plus Corp. of Quincy, Mass. is expected to announce a
deal with At Home Corp.'s At Work subsidairy to expand high-speed
Internet access for commercial customers of Network Plus
nationwide. Network Plus will use At Work's nationwide broadband
backbone to provide Digital Subscriber Line service to customers,
supplementing its own broadband network.
</P>
<P>
   --Yahoo Inc. said it will invest $1.5 million in Webhire Inc.
and use the Lexington, Mass. company's resume service. The stock
market didn't seem to know how to react. The news sent Webhire
shares soaring at first, from 14 1/8 to 17 5/8, but they finished
the day down 1 5/8 to 12 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
