<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8498 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COLLINS-     07-29 1572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS VERSED IN THE TRICKS OF THE TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAYNHAM, Mass. _ The figure fills the door frame. Silouetted by
sunlight, the weight and bearing of an offensive lineman are clear.
The 291 pounds packed loosely onto the 6-foot-5-inch frame create
an optical illusion, making the player seem shorter and thicker
than his listed measurements. With the exception of muscular
forearms, his strength is disguised as he stands still. When he
walks, the gait is slow and laid-back. The size of his body suits
him.
</P>
<P>
   From all observable indications, Dan Collins has the physical
qualities to play professional football. He also possesses the
pedigree, frequently mentioning his uncle and former NFL
quarterback Matt Cavanaugh in conversation. A copy of the Sports
Illustrated cover that captured his uncle celebrating a national
championship at Pittsburgh hangs above his bed. As part of the
storied tradition of offensive linemen educated at Boston College
and as a student of the current Green Bay offensive coordinator,
Collins developed under the tutelage of men who knew the talent
needed to play professionally.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins has taken an unlikely and unexpected route to
Patriots training camp, which begins Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Burdened with unfulfilled potential, he came close to quitting
his college football team the spring before he earned a starting
position. Converted from defense to offense before his junior year,
his talent and technique need refining. Undrafted, but signed as a
free agent, he enters camp with lots to prove and lots to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to be drafted, but I told myself to expect
the worse,'' said Collins. ``I just wanted to get into camp. I
didn't care how I got in, as long as I had a shot. Draft day was
just long. It felt like it was three days. I was sitting around and
the rounds just kept going and going. It would have been nice (to
be drafted).
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to hear your name, but then it doesn't happen. It was
in some ways dissappointing, but at the same time just the thrill
of a lifetime . . . (Not being drafted) doesn't nag at me at all.
It gives you a little extra drive, I think. You're fighting against
guys who are drafted.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins knows more than most would-be rookies about the NFL. He
spent his childhood following the exploits of his uncle. The free
agent visited Foxboro Stadium after the draft and recognized the
weight room and locker room from a childhood visit. His uncle, who
began his 14-year NFL career with the Patriots in 1978, once gave
Collins and his sister a tour of the team's facilities. The stadium
sits just 15 minutes from the Collins family home in Raynham, where
Dan shares a bedroom with his brother Ken.
</P>
<P>
   The Collins family also visited Cavanaugh at training camp,
creating a lasting memory for Dan. Standing in the middle of the
cafeteria with an ice cream cone, a young Collins watched Pete
Brock approach. The center stole the cone from Collins and ate it.
The 23-year-old guard still shakes his head at the recollection. At
the time, the world of pro football players was super-sized and
awe-inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   Collins followed his uncle's stops in San Francisco, where he
backed up Joe Montana, then to Philadelphia and New York. During
his NFL tour, Cavanaugh was a member of two Super Bowl champions
(1984 with the 49ers and 1990 with the Giants) and fostered his
nephew's love of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids look up to all these different players that they
really don't even know,'' said Collins. ``I was fortunate enough to
have my uncle who was an actual player. When I was growing up, I
always thought that was cool. I wanted to be like him some day. I
wanted to be the next one in the family to have a chance to play in
the NFL. I never in a million years thought I would follow my
uncle. I always wanted to, but your chances are just so limited.''
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Collins, it sounds as if every milestone in his
career was met with disbelief. When BC coach Tom Coughlin offered
him a scholarship before his senior season at Bridgewater-Raynham
High, Collins thought it was a joke.
</P>
<P>
   When he was told pro scouts had inquired about him at the start
of last season, he asked his position coach, ``Are you kidding?''
After all, who could see potential in a player yet to start his
first college game? When he signed as a free agent with the
Patriots, Collins could hardly fathom the course his career had
taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while I was thinking about it quite a bit,'' he said of
his rise from one-year starter to pro prospect. ``I just had to
smack myself. I didn't know what was going on. It all happened so
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to his junior year of college, Collins had received a
scholarship from Coughlin, spent three unproductive years under
coach Dan Henning and his staff and thought seriously about
quitting a year after Tom O'Brien took over. Former defensive
coordinator Phil Elmassian hurt Collins with comments that he was
unfit to play Division 3 football, never mind Division 1. In 1996,
when most of his playing time came on special teams, Collins
received a three-game suspension after it was learned he bet on two
games.
</P>
<P>
   Collins initially hoped to see time his sophomore season and
contribute his final two years. Instead, he barely played his first
two years, did not travel with the team early in his college
career, and thought more about graduation and going home than any
post-collegiate football opportunities. The spring preceding his
fifth year at the Heights, Collins faced a tough decision and had
all but made up his mind before he called his uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Collins told Cavanaugh he was considering not returning to BC;
Cavanaugh hung up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that really wasn't what he wanted to do,'' said
Cavanaugh, who now works as the Baltimore Ravens offensive
coordinator. ``Like a lot of guys in college, he had certain
expectations. I knew he really loved the game. I knew he wanted to
prove to himself that he could play in college.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins needed only one season to demonstrate his talent on the
offensive line and convince NFL teams he possessed untapped
potential. After four years of waiting, the former defensive
lineman started the first time for the Eagles at right guard
against Georgia Tech. His nervousness before the season opener was
increased when his prediction that Mike Cloud would run for 200
yards were publicized and posted in the opposing team's locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   But with the help of Damien Woody and former offensive
coordinator Jeff Jagodzinski, Collins survived the opener and
started all 11 games for the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   When members of the O'Brien coaching staff arrived, they
announced that several defensive linemen would try to play on the
offensive line. That spring, Collins divided his time equally
between defense and offense. The coaches evaluated his play and
decided Collins would be better suited on offense. The player felt
more comfortable protecting the quarterback and opening holes for
the running back and agreed to the switch. In retrospect, he wishes
the conversion from defense to offense had happened before his
junior season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Collins got the chance to be part of a record-setting
offensive unit last fall. He helped the Eagles post 4,527 yards in
total offense, with Cloud running for 1,726 and setting the
school's all-time rushing record. The right guard also took pride
in the fact that BC allowed the fewest sacks in the Big East (13).
</P>
<P>
   ``When the changes started, he was shuffled around from place to
place and had a lot of opportunities to say, `Forget it.' I don't
think he had a chance to flourish because he was always bounced
around,'' said Jagodzinski, now the Packers' offensive coordinator.
``If I had been able to work with him for three to four years, he
would have been a drafted player. He never really settled into his
position until his senior year. He did a great job for us. I
thought he had real good feet. He was quick. He played next to
(Patriots first pick) Damien Woody, and I think that really helped
him. I don't think there's a better place in the country to play
offensive line than BC.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Jagodzinski and Cavanaugh have given their protege the same
advice. They emphasize that Collins has a rare opportunity to play
professionally and must make the most of it. His uncle has told
him, ``All you can do is your best and make their decision
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Dave Uyrus, the Patriots' director of team
scouting, the team was attracted to Collins because of his size,
solid work ethic, and close ties to the area that allowed the local
team to become more familiar with the player.
</P>
<P>
   The scouting director recognizes that Collins must work on his
technique and may, like most offensive linemen, need two to three
years to develop. Although he would not predict Collins's chances
of making the team, Uyrus noted that players in Collins's position
generally make the practice squad and then spend time in Europe
acquiring game experience. Cavanaugh believes Collins's ``knack for
surviving'' will help him through training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to something serious like this whole football
thing, I look at it as my only opportunity,'' said Collins. ``I'm
going to do everything I can now to make it happen or it's never
going to happen again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
