<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS SCANDAL RAISES OLD ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the Public Broadcasting Service, it was a nasty case of deja
vu. Stunning revelations that public stations _ beginning with
Boston's WGBH-TV _ swapped donor lists with the Democrats not only
triggered Congressional hearings and endangered future funding, it
brought a divisive political issue out of mothballs.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, taxpayer-funded television stands accused of cozying
up to the left.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1992, that issue was so hot that the Republican Party
platform officially deplored ``the blatant political bias of the
government-sponsored radio and television networks.'' A few years
later, House Speaker Newt Gingrich threatened to ``zero out''
funding for public TV. But as the Republican Revolution waned and
PBS programming seemed more palatable to conservatives, the cries
of liberal bias receded into a bare whisper. Now, even as evidence
of list trading with Republicans surfaces, it's public TV's ties to
the Democrats that have reopened an old ideological wound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in recent years, CPB (the Corporation for Public
Broadcasting) has been aware'' of the bias charge ``and tried to
balance its programs,'' adds Ken Johnson, spokesman for
Representative W.J. ``Billy'' Tauzin, Republican from Louisiana,
who chairs the House subcommittee overseeing public broadcasting.
But this ``blossoming scandal . . . reinforces the old stereotype''
and ``sets the stage once again for a knockdown drag out fight over
funding . . . Santa Claus has fled the building.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This raises the old bugaboo that they tried to put behind
them,'' echoes Robert Lichter, president of the Center for Media
and Public Affairs. ``The irony is that this matter is coming up
just at the moment the issue was fading away.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, Lichter was a major combatant in the bias
battle when the center released a 160-page study analyzing 225 PBS
documentary programs that aired from April 1987 to March 1988. The
report concluded that ``on the social and political controversies
addressed by PBS documentaries . . . the balance of opinion tilted
consistently in a liberal direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Lichter in the early '90s chorus of critics was Laurence
Jarvik, then an analyst with the Heritage Foundation, who argued
for the privatization of PBS, which he accused of operating ``like
a government bureacracy.'' A battalion of conservative media
critics _ the Committee on Media Integrity, Accuracy in Media, and
the Media Research Center _ intensified the assault on PBS,
complaining of programming that was too pro-tree hugger and too
anti-military.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I understand, some people objected to specific
programs,'' says PBS vice president of communications Tom Epstein.
But ``there was never a wide-ranging indictment of the schedule as
a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   That might represent a rose-colored assessment of the critics'
views. But in the past several years, their complaints abated. For
one thing, the Center for Media and Public Affairs' studies of PBS
``NewsHour'' coverage of the 1992 and 1996 presidential campaigns
found that in 1992, the ``NewsHour'' gave George Bush a fairer
shake than ABC, NBC, CBS, and CNN. And in 1996, only CBS was kinder
to the GOP nominee _ Bob Dole _ than PBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is that PBS saw (the bias charge) as a problem
and moved to correct this,'' says Lichter.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the left-wing media watchdog Fairness &AMP; Accuracy in
Reporting released its survey of PBS public affairs programming
ranging from ``Charlie Rose'' to the ``McLaughlin Group.'' It did
not exactly conclude that the network was too conservative, but it
did allege that the mix of PBS voices and sources was skewed toward
the institutional elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past six or seven years, the corporate voice on PBS
has gotten much louder,'' says William Hoynes, the Vassar College
professor who conducted the survey. ``The term I use in the study
is public broadcasting has `insider orientation' (that) doesn't
open up the boundaries of public discourse.''
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, when Fairness &AMP; Accuracy in Reporting released a
survey with similar findings, it was a lone voice in the wilderness
countering the cries of liberal bias. But times had changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was not this loud challenge from the right like there
was from 1992 to 1995. That had been quiet lately,'' Hoynes says.
PBS thought it had finally won the bias war, ``and I think they
probably had. And now it's back.''
</P>
<P>
   So all bets are off as Congress currently awaits a report on the
extent of the fund-raising scandal before convening another public
hearing and tackling the politically recharged funding issue. ``We
will not move the CPB authorization forward until we hear a full
accounting of this unsavory practice,'' says Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the scandal has expanded to involve both the
Democratic and Republic parties, Epstein asserts that ``the direct
mail fund-raising had no political motivation whatsoever. It was
strictly to raise money.'' And the Fairness &AMP; Accuracy in Reporting
program director Janine Jackson says ``it would be regrettable if
we sink back to the left-right debate.''
</P>
<P>
   But other PBS funding foes eagerly await that opportunity. Media
Research Center staffer Tim Graham _ who testified at last week's
Congressional hearings that PBS's ``left-leaning image'' was ``well
earned'' _ says that when critics of public funding focused on
programming, they were accused of bashing some of TV's most revered
icons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice thing about this set of revelations is that it
changes the subject,'' he says. ``It isn't the `fry Big Bird'
issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
