<SLUG> BC-MA-TOCCO2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHER-ED CHIEF'S BULLDOG STYLE DRAWS BITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- There are six names on Steve Tocco's list of people
who will say nice things about him. The trouble is, five of the six
are also on the list that other people give as Steve Tocco's
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   And his critics don't come from the expected quarters _ unions
he battled as head of the state's port authority, Democrats _ but
from people who served alongside him in the Republican
administration, who in the weeks before Gov. Paul Cellucci named
him as the new chief of the state's higher education system, were
privately lobbying the governor to choose someone else.
</P>
<P>
   The public complaints about Tocco's appointment have focused on
his lack of education experience. Trained as a pharmacist, Tocco's
work within government and now as a lobbyist has mostly involved
transportation and construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the scenes, it's not Tocco's lack of relevant
experience that's the problem, former colleagues say. It's his ego
and unpredictability _ so notorious that former Gov. William F.
Weld used to warn Tocco in senior staff meetings not to do anything
he hadn't been explicitly authorized to do.
</P>
<P>
   Like his predecessor, James F. Carlin, Tocco is known for
butting heads and infuriating his enemies. But while he may
generate the same headlines that Carlin did, critics say he won't
generate the same results.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's every bit the lightning rod, but not as effective,'' said
one person who served in the administration with Tocco. ``If you
look at Steve's record, he's created an enormous amount of noise,
but no product. A lot of other people ended up cleaning up a lot of
things that weren't that hard to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, though, said he chose Tocco for his aggressive
leadership and ability to push an agenda. And Tocco himself insists
that if he alienated anyone, it was only because he takes on tough
projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always put in positions that were difficult,'' he says
in an interview at his office at the law firm Mintz Levin Cohn
Ferris Glovsky &AMP; Popeo, where he heads a lobbying, public
relations, and consulting unit. ``Could I have had a softer side to
that? Absolutely. If I'm driven by anything, it's trying to
accomplish it. But nothing I did was ever without the mandate of my
boss, either Governor Weld or Governor Cellucci.'' He shrugs.
``It's a style.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Buckingham, who worked with Tocco in several positions
in the Weld administration, acknowledges Tocco ``leaves noses out
of joint.'' But, she says, it is only because he is so focused on
getting the job done. ``I see him in the Carlin mode,'' she said.
``He has a clear vision, he's very articulate, he's able to inspire
people with his vision. He's very clear-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   Even his critics agree that Tocco is his own best salesman.
Stocky and feisty, he is upbeat about his qualifications for the
job, proud of his past experience.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lee King, Weld's chief policy advisor, acknowledges Tocco
can be intimidating. But she admires his forcefulness, saying it
will help him confront aggressive education advocates as he
oversees 29 campuses of the University of Massachusetts and state
and community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a good manager because he is tough. I Knew his
management style would be what the governor was looking for. I'm
not sure you need to be an education specialist to manage.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci brought Tocco into the 1990 Weld campaign, and he
served as a senior aide in the early years of the new
administration, and later as Weld's secretary of economic affairs.
He was handed several significant projects, including an emergency
plan to shrink state bureaucracy during the budget crisis of the
early 90s, an economic development blueprint, and a proposal to
build a new stadium and convention center. But while he gets credit
for taking on the tough jobs, the animosity he generated often
threatened to get in the administration's way.
</P>
<P>
   When Weld put Tocco in charge of Massport in 1993, he also
handed him responsibility for selling the idea for a new sports and
convention center complex that was to be called the Megaplex. But
the deal was dead almost as soon as it was unveiled, largely,
critics said, because Tocco crossed swords with then-Senate
President William M. Bulger over how the deal would be paid for and
designed. Leaders in South Boston accused Tocco of unveiling plans
for the stadium without any consideration for what the community
might want, and suspected him of trying to strong-arm the
commmunity into building a new football stadium on Massport land.
</P>
<P>
   Even some critics of the original plan now say that Tocco was
only acting on Weld's direction, and may have taken more blame than
he deserved when the plan fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Tocco also failed to secure trust within the Weld
administration, and had to be brought into line, sources said,
after the governor discovered that Tocco had been quietly lobbying
to build the stadium in South Boston, even as Weld _ still his boss
_ was arguing to locate it on a competing site in Roxbury.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Tocco clashed with Weld again, when he tried to
seize control of the Third Harbor Tunnel. He filed an amendment
during a late night Senate debate to put the tunnel under
Massport's direction, acting against the advice of even aides at
Massport, and in direct opposition to a Weld bill that would have
the tunnel controlled by the state Turnpike Authority. The governor
was reportedly so stunned at the sheer chutzpah of the move that he
put his head on the table and laughed in disbelief. Other aides
said they had to call Cellucci late at night and get him to tell
Tocco to stop the power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve was always acting like he was the governor, going out
and cutting deals in the governor's name, even if he didn't always
have the authority to do them,'' says one former top aide. ``Weld
was always sort of having to sit on him.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Massport filed a $387 million bond
prospectus that was to pay part of the agency's share of the
Central Artery project. The prospectus said that Massport would
raise tolls on the Tobin Bridge, even though the Legislature had
never authorized such a hike. When Senate President Thomas M.
Birmingham discovered this, he passed a budget rider declaring that
tolls could not be used to pay for Massport projects. The bond
prospectus had to be pulled from the market, costing Massport $16
million, and Wall Street agencies put Massport's bond rating under
review, jeopardizing its ability to borrow money to pay for any
construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not phobic about tolls,'' Birmingham says now. ``But he
was completely contemptuous of the Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Tocco, again, seemed surprised at the furor he had set off:
while aides tried to reassure Birmingham and Wall Street, he was in
Las Vegas playing golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't spend a lot of time considering how his actions
might be affecting people,'' Buckingham says. ``He's focused on his
goals and he's very good at achieving them, but he's not a pat on
the back kind of person. I don't think that's a bad thing when
you're trying to get stuff done. He can get people to a consensus,
but if he can't, he's not afraid to drive the agenda in the
direction he thinks it should go.''
</P>
<P>
   Tocco says it's too early to say where he will put his energies,
but he is eager to begin. Already, he has expressed concerns that
measures to raise standards at the University of Massachusetts may
end up cutting off access to some students. For those students, he
says it's important the state colleges and community colleges offer
valuable degrees.
</P>
<P>
   As secretary of economic affairs, he saw firsthand the
importance of having a well-trained work force. And that, he said,
is what education is really about, and why he is fit for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can make an argument that it makes sense. I think
you have to think about it to have it make sense, but it does make
sense.``
</P>
<P>
   As for critics, Tocco appears undaunted.
</P>
<P>
   ``My persistence is a pretty powerful thing,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
