<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-KILLINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI SEEKS LINKS IN UNSOLVED KILLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. _ After receiving a flood of
queries about unsolved killings from California law enforcement
agencies, the FBI has agreed to help local cops determine whether
Cary Stayner might be responsible for any other unsolved homicides.
</P>
<P>
   Since news broke that Stayner reportedly confessed to killing
four women in or near Yosemite National Park, the bureau has been
receiving requests from other agencies eager to find out whether
Stayner killed anyone else, especially women whose throats were
slashed or who were beheaded.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents would not say Wednesday which unsolved deaths were
under investigation. But local investigators have asked the FBI to
look at several cases with similarities to the Yosemite slayings,
including one woman whose burned, mutilated body was discovered at
Don Pedro Reservoir, very near where Stayner has said he killed and
dumped 15-year-old Juli Sund in February.
</P>
<P>
   Among the deaths the FBI will review are a prostitute whose
decapitated body was found in Calaveras County; a headless,
handless woman found near a river in Sutter County; and a
19-year-old decapitated waitress found near Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokesman Nick Rossi said part of the effort would be to
document Stayner's life and travels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to follow up on all logical investigative leads,
which includes developing information about his history,'' Rossi
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going back to establish a time line to determine where
he was at certain periods of time to see if, in fact, there are any
unsolved homicides that can be linked to him,'' said Tuolumne
County Sheriff Dick Rogers, whose agency has been part of the FBI
task force since the bodies of Carole Sund, her daughter, Juli, and
family friend Silvina Pelosso were found in two sites within his
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Stayner has been charged only in last week's killing of
Joie Armstrong, a Yosemite naturalist. Stayner's next court
appearance is scheduled for Aug. 6 in federal court in Fresno,
where he is expected to enter a plea. The FBI said it was building
its case against him in the Sund-Pelosso killings.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers is also looking at Stayner in one cold case of his own.
In December 1994, the charred body of Denese Smith was found
stuffed in a barrel at Don Pedro Reservoir in Tuolumne County.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was stabbed many times before her body was burned and
dumped, investigators said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not too far _ only about 2 miles _ from where Juli
(Sund) was found,'' said Tuolumne County sheriff's Lt. John Steely.
``Her body had been burned and had been stuffed in a 50-gallon drum
burn barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   Next door in Calaveras County, sheriff's Detective Robert
Mortimer said FBI agents had indicated they would question Stayner
about the 1994 death of a 23-year-old prostitute, Sharalyn Mavonne
Murphy, whose severed hands were found near New Melones Reservoir
in October 1994. Her headless torso was found off a mountain road
in Calaveras County two months later. Neither the head nor her
killer has ever been found.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI will also serve as a central repository of new
information and tips in these cases, which could help local
investigators even if it turns out that Stayner has no connection
to their unsolved crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real good thing for us,'' said Detective Sgt. Hal Lamb
of the El Dorado County Sheriff's Department. ``They are giving us
a central place for all of this information.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb is asking the FBI to look into the 1992 decapitation of 19-
year-old Veronica Martinez, a Sacramento waitress whose body was
found dumped in a steep ravine between Auburn and Placerville.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was reported missing Jan. 27, 1992. But her body was
not discovered until March, when a person looking for bottles saw
her body near Highway 49.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was tossed off the side of the road,'' Lamb said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators had a suspect: a man in Martinez' life. But they
were never able to link him to the crime. ``We're happy to take a
fresh look at this case in light of the new information,'' Lamb
said.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner reportedly confessed to all four Yosemite area murders
during interviews with the FBI and a TV reporter. In the unrecorded
interview with the reporter, Stayner said he hadn't killed anyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators suspect that he may be lying, something experts
and other veteran homicide investigators agree is a tendency of
killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've interviewed numerous killers, and they always lie,'' said
Eric Hickey, a professor of criminology at Fresno State University
and the author of the 1997 book ``Serial Murderers and Their
Victims.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's about the facts, but always about their
motives,'' Hickey said. ``They always lie about the real issues.
... They like to play games with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts and investigators interviewed for this story said they
suspect Stayner did not start killing with the Sund-Pelosso trio.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they look into his past, I bet they will find others,''
Hickey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
