<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8514 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERNS-RETURN-ART-BOS &LR;      07-29 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERNS-RETURN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOREBIRD MAKES A COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEAVEY ISLAND, N.H. _ The first time he ventured among the
nesting terns, Drew Trested looked like a victim from Alfred
Hitchcock's classic horror movie ``The Birds.''
</P>
<P>
   The second that the young biologist stepped into the grass where
the birds were tending their young, the terns took to the air,
screeching and pinwheeling around him in a blur of white feathers
and sharp orange beaks. When he knelt to put metal identification
bands on the fluffy little chicks, terns pecked him on the head so
much that his hair was matted with blood.
</P>
<P>
   Adding insult to injury, they bombed him with hot white
droppings, too.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Trested, though sore, was happy. The terns, driven by gulls
and human development from their home on the New Hampshire coast
for 50 years, were back with a vengeance, defending their turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get agitated quickly, which is a good thing. It keeps
them defensive,'' said the Audubon Society of New Hampshire
biologist, who learned to stuff a sock in his hat and wear a
raincoat for protection against the hostile birds. ``The ones that
are not aggressive do not do well at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The return of the terns to Seavey Island is part of a broader
recovery of the sleek, fork-tailed birds, whose arrival has long
been one of coastal New England's sure signs of summer. Thanks
largely to intensive human efforts to save them, common tern
populations from Maine to New York have nearly tripled since 1977,
reversing decades of losing ground to gulls, rats, and other
refuse-eating animals.
</P>
<P>
   Today, biologists refer to New York and Massachusetts as ``tern
factories'' because of enormous colonies that are home to thousands
of birds, while Maine has almost as many terns as it did in the
1930s. One species of tern, the roseate tern, is federally
endangered, but even its numbers have increased by 50 percent in
the Northeast since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   On Seavey Island, a beautiful yet stark slab of granite among
the Isles of Shoals, the birds returned almost immediately after
the Audubon Society drove off the gulls that had taken over, then
put out tern decoys and played tern calls to make the atmosphere
more homey. So far, 139 common tern pairs nest on the four-acre
island, compared to none in 1996, giving New Hampshire its first
significant tern colony since the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Head biologist Diane De Luca ``is doing great things up there,''
said Steve Kress, the National Audubon Society visionary who
pioneered the use of decoys and bird sounds to restore seabird
colonies in Maine. ``I think she got bitten by the `T-bird bug,' ''
a term for the powerful affection some have for terns despite the
head pecks and the droppings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the birds' progress, however, biologists say the terns'
migratory lifestyle is too harsh and the threat from predators too
real to declare victory. This year, for example, foxes routed
thousands of pairs of terns from their nests on Massachusetts'
Plymouth Beach, leaving the colony practically deserted.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, almost all the big colonies are protected by watchdogs
such as the New Hampshire Audubon Society, which stations two
biologists in an old lighthouse complex adjacent to Seavey Island.
Untended tern colonies tend to get overrun by gulls before the
terns arrive in the spring from their winter homes in Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is too unstable still to be called a success,''
said Brad Blodget, Massachusetts state ornithologist and director
of regional recovery efforts for the roseate tern. ``Not only do''
terns ``live in a very unstable environment, but they are subject
to storms and predation and they move frequently, so there is no
assurance year to year.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, terns are among the leading victims of people's
love of the coast. Growing coastal populations in the 1930s brought
more landfills, more fishing boats, and other food sources for
opportunistic animals such as gulls, skunks, rats, foxes and other
species that prey on tern young and eggs. Coupled with increasing
human use of tern nesting grounds, the birds went into a
precipitous decline.
</P>
<P>
   In the Isles of Shoals off the New Hampshire coast, up to 2,000
pairs of common terns once lived on Lunging Island, but, by 1950,
gulls had chased the terns away. Meanwhile, a manned Coast Guard
lighthouse on an island connected at low tide to Seavey prevented
significant tern nesting there.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the 1960s, conservationists tried to right the
ecological balance between terns and gulls, poisoning gulls to
clear space for the terns to return. But it was not until the early
1980s when Kress began restoring puffins and other seabirds on
Maine's Eastern Egg Rock that conservationists found both the
techniques and the institutional support to recreate more than a
dozen lost tern colonies.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, regulators clamped down on open dumps in the
region, depriving gulls of a favorite food source and checking
their extraordinary population growth. ``We're definitely in a
period of gull decline and that has probably been to our
advantage,'' said De Luca of New Hampshire Audubon.
</P>
<P>
   De Luca, who worked with Kress for nine years, finally turned
conservationists' attention to the New Hampshire coast in the early
1990s when the Coast Guard automated its lighthouse near Seavey
Island and prepared to deed Seavey over to the state. Though terns
had never nested in large numbers on Seavey, its windswept rocks
and grass were perfect for the birds.
</P>
<P>
   De Luca followed the decoy-and-bird-sounds formula set down by
Kress, with the exception that late 1990s political reality made it
impossible to kill gulls. Instead, they harassed the animals,
putting bricks in their nests, setting off fireworks and constantly
patrolling the island. Within weeks of the gull harassment in 1997,
the first six pairs of terns returned.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Seavey Island has the hallmarks of a fast-growing new
community as terns from up and down the coast flock there _ and
find it to their liking. In many colonies, the youngest chicks die
for lack of food, but not on Seavey where the hake and other small
fish are so abundant. And, even though gulls continue to hang
around the edges of the colony, Trested and fellow biologist Dan
Hayward continually shoo them away.
</P>
<P>
   By some measures, the recovery at Seavey Island is cheap. At a
cost of about $40,000 a year in public and private funds, the
Audubon Society established the only major tern colony for 110
miles, completing a chain of bird refuges from Maine to New York.
``This is probably one of the last historical sites to get
restoration with the exception of Canada,'' said De Luca.
</P>
<P>
   But biologists warn that, while the amounts of money on any
individual site may be small, money will largely determine whether
the birds continue their recovery or not, because the terns will
always need people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, terns are now a ward of the state,'' said Tom
French, director of Massachusetts' Endangered Species and Natural
Heritage Program. ``Terns will not make it on their own. Terns'
success is directly related to the level of human efforts to
protect them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
