<HEADLINE>
FOR TOO MANY SITES, BEING FIRST IS FOREMOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There it was in print: a picture of three fetuses in amniotic
fluid, blissfully unaware of their imminent change in scenery. And
there was the invitation: ``For the first time ever, you can view
the birth of triplets LIVE over the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Here we go again, another dubious Internet ``first'' brought to
you by the same folks who staged the ``first live birth'' online
last year. The photo was featured in a half-page advertisement that
ran Monday in national newspapers including the Globe (which
charges $20,364.75 for a half page). ``Point. Click,'' the ad read.
``It's a girl, a girl, and a boy.''
</P>
<P>
   The triplets, Deanna, Desiree, and Christopher Diaz, made their
grand entrance on TheHealthNetwork.com, a new entity formed when
Fox Network combined its own Fit TV with ahn.com and America's
Health Network. The folks at ahn.com made headlines last year when
they broadcast the arrival of Baby Sean; days later, Sean's mom was
was arrested on check fraud charges after authorities spotted her
online. Bad news for Mom, great publicity for the network.
</P>
<P>
   This time out, the network was touting its new incarnation in
the Fox family. The archived tape of the Diaz Cesarean section
plays like a slick, soft news magazine, with scripted commentary
and commercial interruptions. See the babies cry. Wait for their
post-natal scores. Watch sneak previews of upcoming shows.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, some medical student may be able to pick up a few
pointers from the surgery, but does the world really need another
Internet ``first''? Funny, the stunt was aired the day before the
30th anniversary of the Apollo 11 moon landing, a bona fide first.
If Neil Armstrong took his small step today, it would only be a
matter of time before Web broadcasters were hawking the first lunar
pas de deux or the first outerspace hop, skip, and a jump. (On the
day of the anniversary, a site called space.com was launched,
billing itself as ``the first mover on the Web'' in the aerospace
category.)
</P>
<P>
   Everyone is one-upping each other online; everybody's stretching
to come up with the first, the only, the ultimate. We've lost all
perspective of what's significant and what's hype. That's not to
say there haven't been genuine online innovations. The first time
an engineer named Ray Tomlinson typed the (at) sign in an e-mail,
he created a global icon. The first time librarian Jean Armour
Polly wrote the words ``surfing the Net,'' she coined a universal
catchphrase.
</P>
<P>
   But really, this is getting out of hand. You've heard about
first editions, the First Amendment, first aid. But the first
virtual bowling game? The first Japanese pizza page? You can find
both of those online. The page featuring squid ink pizza
(www.oakland.edu/mdchachi/jpizza.html) even won an award from
``Sick Site of the Day;'' and it has already spawned copycats, such
as Utah's first Internet pizza camera page, which may or may not
serve a useful purpose at the 2002 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the innovations are created by regular Joes yearning to
stand out, desperate for distinction. But is there really any great
claim to fame for the first Internet cafe in Latvia or Bucharest?
Does anyone really care about the first home page targeted at beer
collectors in Bucharest? Is there a prize for the first redneck on
the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   I'm not making any of this up; all these pages exist. Ye of
little faith, visit the self-described redneck at www.cledus.com.
Or browse at the first Internet tie store (www.wildties.com), which
features such neckwear categories as oinks, Beatles, and Cirque de
Soleil.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, after all, is the great equalizer: Now unknowns
are entitled to promote their own fabulousness, just like the admen
on Madison Ave. This sort of self-promotion is essentially
harmless, but what's it all about? Are we all so programmed by the
slick techniques of advertising that we all want to wear some
hyperbolic label? We didn't win the spelling bee or First Prize at
the science fair, so does that mean we have to make up for it by
creating the first Liz Phair fan site?
</P>
<P>
   The individuals staging these firsts are one thing, but the
corporate publicity stunts are another thing entirely. Last year,
the live birth garnered international attention, with 1.4 million
viewers boosting the launch of the commercial health network.
Mission accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   But why did so many people watch? Nobody wants to miss their
chance to be a first-class voyeur. Last year, folks went nutty when
two alleged teenagers promised to become the first lovers to lose
their virginity online, broadcasting their romance on a site called
``Our First Time.'' The whole thing turned out to be a theatrical
hoax orchestrated by two aspiring actors, a filmmaker, and an
online sex shop. Reporters who were perfectly happy to cover this
history-making event went ballistic when they found out that the
venture into virgin territory was actually a scam.
</P>
<P>
   But the race to be first continues. What's next? The Elite
modeling agency just introduced the first virtual model, a lovely
lady known as Webbie Tookay. Maybe she'll marry Buzz Lightyear from
``Toy Story,'' and we'll be treated to the first online birth of
the first virtual baby.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe everyone will stop all this nonsense, and folks will be
happy with second or third or just Honorable Mention. Folks will
stop claiming they're breaking new ground with the most far-fetched
innovation. Now that would be a true Internet first, and you'll
read about it here firs. . . Oh, never mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
