u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      07-29 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS SHINGLES ARE STREAKED AND SPOTTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Three years ago, I put up new red cedar shingles on my
70-year-old, three-story house. A local painter applied an oil
primer, then a brown stain of some kind. There are a lot of streaks
and spots, and the house looks awful, although only a quarter of it
looks that bad. A contractor suggested putting up new shingles.
What can I do about it?
</P>
<P>
   DAVID MILLARD, Needham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Replace three-year-old shingles? That is the ultimate in
folly. It is not the shingles that are acting up, but the stain. I
just wonder if the painter applied a semitransparent stain over the
primer, but that would look horrible from the start, because a
semitransparent stain cannot be put over a primer or old paint. So,
if it is not a semitransparent, it must be a solid stain, latex or
oil. If so, and only one coat was applied, then it is the fault of
the solid stain, which sometimes does get streaked and spotty over
time.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest this solution: If the stain is peeling or flaking,
scrape and sand. If it is not peeling, sand as necessary. Then
apply two thin coats of a solid-color latex stain. Thin coats are
important; I would also change the brand, too, but try not to
change the color too much. Stains usually last about five years
before wearing away or fading; in your case, three years before
trouble is not long enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are the pros and cons of asbestos-cement siding? I am
thinking of buying a house with asbestos siding. It is in an ideal
location, and I like the house.
</P>
<P>
   CONCERNED OVER SIDING
</P>
<P>
   A. There are no pros on asbestos-cement siding. Well, one
semi-pro is that on the house, it is safe, as long as it is not
drilled, sanded, abraded, broken, or abused in any way; such action
will release asbestos fibers into the air. The cons are numerous:
You cannot power wash, sand, scrape, or anything, but you can use
bleach and water or detergent and water to clean it. If any paint
is peeling, it cannot be removed by any friction method.
</P>
<P>
   Removing the siding is expensive. One choice is to strike a
bargain with the seller, knocking off some of the price to pay for
removal, or having him remove it before the sale.
</P>
<P>
   With all these things in mind, the better part of valor might be
to look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am thinking of building a 12- by 12-foot tool house in my
yard. What is best for footings?
</P>
<P>
   DAN ANTHONY, Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Before you do anything, I suggest making the house 12 by 16
feet instead of 12 by 12. For footings, you can put concrete piers
3 feet into the ground, creating a foundation that will not heave
in winter. Or, set the house on 4 x 4 or 4 x 6 pressure-treated
posts sunk 3 feet into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Or, set concrete blocks on the ground, or a few inches into the
ground, and take your chances that the house will not heave and go
out of level. It may stay stable for some years, but if it does go
out of skew, the size and the weight of the house is going to make
releveling it difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons I suggest making the house bigger: 1. People who
plan such things usually overestimate a tool house's storage
capacity. 2. It's easier to build big now than to add on later. 3.
And in your case, the rectangular shape is more practical than a
square one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The new central air-conditioning system in my
1,200-square-foot addition on the second floor will not cool to 70
degrees; it seems to stop at 74 degrees. The installer said the
system is slightly oversize, and there is nothing wrong. I had the
thermostat replaced without success. How can I get it to cool?
</P>
<P>
   KATHY WILLIS, Plaistow, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. Relatively speaking, 74 degrees is not really that warm. I
don't know the answer, for sure, but here is one question for you:
Are there air returns in the rooms of the addition, to bring air
back to the unit? If there are none, they should be installed,
because without air returns the a/c is pumping air into a dead-end
area, and less air can be pumped in a situation like that.
Sometimes, keeping doors closed will help, sometimes keeping them
open will help.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, make sure the addition is separate from the rest
of the house, so the unit does not try to cool the whole house.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
