<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU CAN REVERSE A DOOR, YOU CAN DO ANYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was this handyman, you know, who had his screened porch
closed in.
</P>
<P>
   It worked well, except the entry was awkward, so the handyman's
wife, whose idea the enlcosure was in the first place, suggested,
``Why don't we call back the contractor to relocate the entry to
make it less awkward and allow access to two rooms at once?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A great idea, dear,'' said the handyman, who was so excited
and pleased by this project that he offered to pay for everything _
well, nearly everything.
</P>
<P>
   The deed was done, for a fee, and the handyman and his wife were
delighted. The only problem, said the contractor, is that the back
door now opens the wrong way, blocking entry to the newly enclosed
porch.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, said the handyman, ``I'll just reverse the door.''
</P>
<P>
   The contractor looked a little startled but recovered enough to
reply, ``You do know about renovation, don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   Thereby hangs this tale: how to reverse a door, using hand
tools. The handyman knows he can do it, particularly because he has
done it before, or at least hung new doors. Ergo, anyone can do it.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not reversing the door, rather it is relocating the
hinges on the opposite jamb, and relocating the lock and latch to
their opposite jamb, so the door will open to the left, not to the
right.
</P>
<P>
   You can't turn the door around; that would make the outside face
in, and the hinges would be mislocated, making the door open
outward. Turning it end-to-end obviously will not work, either.
</P>
<P>
   So, the hinges both on the jamb and the door edge must be moved.
And all of this is done with hand tools; there is no router
available to cut the mortises (the openings in which the hinge
leaves fit).
</P>
<P>
   To start, transfer the position of the hinges on the opposite
jamb and the door edge. This is best done with the door closed. Set
a level on the top edge of the hinge, and draw a level line on the
opposite side of the door and the jamb. This new line should be
exactly level with the top of the hinge. Do this to all hinges.
</P>
<P>
   Once the new location of each hinge is marked, undo the hinges,
and take down the door. Position one leaf of a hinge (a leaf is
half a hinge) on a new location, and drive all screws in place.
</P>
<P>
   Now, cut around the hinge leaf with a utility knife; this will
provide the exact mortise to set the hinge leaf flush with the door
edge. The leaf will fit snugly once the mortise is cut. Tracing the
hinge leaf with a pencil, then cutting, will not be as accurate,
resulting in a loose fit.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the hinge leaf, and cut the opening as deeply as the leaf
is thick. Make several parallel cuts in the mortise so that you can
chisel out the wood accurately. Use a good, sharp chisel, and chip
away, being careful not to gouge too deeply.
</P>
<P>
   Do this with all the hinges. On an exterior door there are
usually three hinges, making the project a little longer. Once all
mortises are cut, set in the hinge leafs, screw them home, and set
the door on the hinges, fit in the hinge pins and see if it works.
If it does, it means you lined up all the hinge leaves properly. If
it doesn't, then it's back to the drawing board to figure out what
went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   A bad fit may mean that the hinges are too deep or shallow in
their mortises, or they are misaligned. Hope that the hinge leaves
are not misaligned. It is really tough to try to relocate the
hinges; it means you may have to make the mortise higher or lower
to make it meet with its partner on the jamb.
</P>
<P>
   Making the mortise larger will reduce the holding power of the
hinge. A snug mortise fit is important because the edge of the leaf
sits on the bottom of the mortise, which is sort of a shelf. With
this support, there's less tension on the screws.
</P>
<P>
   Once the door works, you can fill in the old, empty mortises
with a thin piece of wood. Glue it in, sand smooth and restain or
repaint.
</P>
<P>
   How about the latch and lock? Most locks are reversible, so it
is simply a matter of removing the lock and striker (the latch
opening on the jamb), drilling the proper holes on the opposite
edge of the door, relocating the striker, and seeing how things
work.
</P>
<P>
   You can fill the holes left by the lock's removal with large
dowels or a disk of wood as thick as the door. Glue them in, sand
smooth, and restain or repaint. The plug will show, but not much.
The strength of the door will not be affected; it will be as strong
as it was originally.
</P>
<P>
   And you will have your reversed door, opening the right way,
ready for everyone to ooh and ah over your brilliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
