<HEADER>
A8533 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS &LR;      07-29 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
--TYING GENETIC CHANGE TO GROWTH OF CANCERS  
 --TESTING NEWBORNS' URINE FOR CEREBRAL PALSY RISK  
 --MGH RESEARCHERS BACK REGULAR MAMMOGRAMS  
 --AQUARIUMS FOUND TO AID APPETITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Tying genetic change to growth of cancers
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years, scientists have known that mistakes, or mutations, in
certain key genes can trigger cancer. But they haven't known
whether these initial genetic changes continue to play a role over
time in helping tumor cells thrive. Now, they do.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the current Nature, Dana-Farber Cancer Institute
researchers have shown that a mutated form of the ras gene not only
triggers melanoma, a potentially fatal form of skin cancer, but
keeps melanoma cells growing. It does this in part by stimulating
vascular endothelial growth factors that cause blood vessels to
grow near tumors to supply them with nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Working with mice, molecular biologists Lynda Chin and Ronald
DePinho found a way to turn ras on and off by altering the animals'
drinking water. When they turned it on (by adding a compound to the
water), the animals developed melanomas in two or three months.
When the compound was withdrawn (in essence, when the genetic
``switch'' was turned off), the tumors shrank.
</P>
<P>
   That suggests that ras continues to pump out signals that keep
cancer growing _ and that anti-ras drugs now under development
might be able to stop cancer growth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Testing newborns' urine for cerebral palsy risk
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taiwanese researchers writing in the current New England Journal
of Medicine report that a urine test can help identify newborns at
risk for oxygen deprivation in the brain that can lead to cerebral
palsy. CP is a relatively rare, but devastating neurological
disease that affects 3 of every 1,000 babies and can be triggered
by oxygen deprivation during delivery.
</P>
<P>
   For 130 years, doctors have tried to find better ways to spot
the newborns at highest risk, says Dr. Jeffrey M. Perlman , a
pediatrician at the University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center
in Dallas, who wrote an editorial accompanying the report. Babies
whose blood is acidic, who have sluggish heart rates and
respiration, or who need resuscitation seem to be at highest risk.
</P>
<P>
   Testing the urine within six hours of birth for the ratio of two
metabolic products, lactate and creatinine, can help spot babies at
highest risk, the study indicates. Research is under way to see
whether moderately cooling high-risk babies to 94 degrees
Fahrenheit can minimize brain damage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MGH researchers back regular mammograms
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Using a computer model based on tumor growth and spread,
Massachusetts General Hospital researchers confirm what 20 years'
worth of clinical trials show _ mammograms every one to three years
reduce the risk of dying from breast cancer by 30 percent. It also
shows the importance of regular mammograms.
</P>
<P>
   But the model goes further: It suggests that if women had
mammograms every six months, they could reduce their risk of death
from breast cancer by 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The MGH team, writing in the August issue of Radiology, stops
short of recommending mammograms that often, but says this should
be tested. Currently, the American Medical Association, the
American Cancer Society, and others recommend annual mammograms for
women 40 and over. The National Cancer Institute recommends them
every one to two years for women 40 and over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Aquariums found to aid appetites
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other medical news . . .
</P>
<P>
   --A Purdue University nursing professor has found that putting
aquariums in nursing homes helps Alzheimer's disease patients calm
down and eat better. Compared to patients who looked at a picture
of a seascape, those who were riveted by colored fish swimming in a
special, tip-proof tank exhibited fewer disruptive behaviors and
ate on average 17 percent more food, the professor reported at a
recent conference in London.
</P>
<P>
   --People with implanted defibrillators can safely walk through
electronic antitheft systems _ if they get through in less than 15
seconds, Indiana University researchers report in the current
Circulation. The antitheft machines use a beam to detect security
tags; defibrillators can interpret this as a rapid heartbeat _ and
try to shock the heart into normal rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   --In a letter to the New England Journal of Medicine, German
doctors told of a 10-year old boy who arrived at the hospital with
stomach pains after eating. After doctors retrieved a toy
flashlight from his innards, the boy was fine.
</P>
<P>
   So was the flashlight, which still worked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
