<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN01-COX     07-29 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blouse-shedding sweeping America
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ After a tension-packed race that went down to the
wire, New York's next U.S. senator, Hillary Rodham Clinton,
celebrated her victory by ripping off her blouse, falling to her
knees and screaming for joy.
</P>
<P>
   Showing her support to her supporters, Clinton clinched her
fists and waved her blouse over her head at the news that her
opponent, New York Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, had conceded defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was wearing a shimmering silver full-coverage, racerback
bra out of Victoria's Secret Second Skin Satin collection that can
be purchased for only $28 at any Victoria's Secret store or over
the Internet at www.VictoriasSecret.com.
</P>
<P>
   By pulling off her top in a sign of triumph, New York's next
senator was following the recent example of Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright, who pulled off her blouse after the
televised signing of a new Mideast peace accord between Palestinian
and Israeli leaders in the White House Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Albright was wearing a white seamless All the Time
by Maidenform underwire bra enhanced with stretch satin and Lycra
spandex to give a superb fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always dreamed of signing a major peace accord in my
Maidenform bra,'' said the jubilant Albright, who couldn't stop
waving her blouse in front of the startled Middle East leaders who
evidently had not picked up on the craze that swept the United
States after Brandi Chastain pulled off her shirt when her kick
clinched the women's world soccer title over China.
</P>
<P>
   Because men soccer players often pull off their shirts in
triumph after a winning move, Chastain's shirt-removal was seen as
an act that demanded equality with men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any man who would complain that women can't pull off their
shirts the same as men do all the time is a sexist pig,''
challenged the editor of Bras for the Millennium, a new magazine
rumored to be funded by an international consortium of brassiere
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   That warning apparently hit home because very few men have
complained about the fad that is showing up in college classrooms,
in business offices, at board meetings and in the nation's bingo
parlors, as well as during sporting matches.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation has never been confirmed that this latest craze was
the result of a successful marketing ploy by the big bra makers as
a way to get back at the drunken Madison, Wis., fraternity boys who
dreamed up bra-burning as a form of feminist expression.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Nike's stock skyrocketed after investors around
the world put all their holdings into brassieres after Chastain
tore off her shirt before a worldwide television audience and
showed the planet that champions wear Nike's new high-end Inner
Active Sports bra that will sell for $40 in stores near you soon.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain served on an advisory committee of athletes who helped
Nike with advice about the bra during its development.
</P>
<P>
   Nike has personal contracts with Chastain and five other members
of the U.S. women's soccer team. The company supplied the team
members with its new sports bra.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen if professional wrestler Dennis Rodman,
who was famous for pulling off his jersey when he played
basketball, now will pull off his top after he flattens an opponent
with his purse and shows the fans his sponsor's newest sports bra.
</P>
<P>
   If Supreme Court Justices Sandra Day O'Connor and Ruth Bader
Ginsburg rip off their robes and peel off their blouses after a
narrow victory on the court, most experts believe the trend begun
by soccer player Chastain will become part of the culture that
makes America such a great and perplexing country.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the end is not in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: rnethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
