<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO READ TO LITTLE ONES _ AND WHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At lunch one day with a group of Harvard undergraduates,
researcher and author Ellen Handler Spitz happened to ask if any of
them had brought a favorite childhood book to college. To her
amazement, all six had, from ``Where the Wild Things Are'' by
Maurice Sendak to ``Love You Forever'' by Robert Munsch.
</P>
<P>
   That a childhood book could serve as a security blanket for an
18-year-old may surprise some parents, but for Spitz it highlights
a long-held belief that books have far more than educational
importance to young children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the book itself that counts,'' she says. ``It's
the experience that goes with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's the sound of Mama's voice, the cozy feeling that
comes with sitting on her lap, or the way a story can tap into a
child's fantasy life, first books carry a big wallop. Even a
6-month-old can have a favorite book, one whose words have the
power to soothe and calm just because they are familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Reading specialists have long recognized that there are many
advantages for children when we start to read to them from birth.
At the very least, snuggling together creates a cozy, pleasurable
sensation that predisposes a child to want more. But in addition,
even if we don't realize it, we're beginning to communicate
book-handling skills, says researcher Barbara Alexander Pan of
Harvard University Graduate School of Education. Watch a 9- to
12-month-old play with a board book, and you'll see him turn the
pages. The sounds he's making are an attempt to imitate your voice
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   With young babies, the best books are simple ones, with one or
two pictures and words per page. ``At this age, the key is to match
your mood to hers,'' Pan says. By 12 months, he's noticing babies
and animals, so Pan suggests books about both, as well as tactile
books like ``Pat the Bunny'' by Dorothy Kunhardt and board books
that can be safely mouthed.
</P>
<P>
   By 15 months or so, some babies are so active they don't sit
still for a book. That doesn't mean we should stop reading, just
that we need to be spontaneous _ reading while he's in the high
chair _ and flexibile. ``Don't make it a struggle: `Reading is good
for you; we started to read this book and we're going to read it!'
'' says Pan.
</P>
<P>
   At about 18 months, reading starts to get more exciting, as a
child's cognitive abilities change. Now a book functions on more
than one level, which is why a toddler or preschooler wants the
same book over and over again, says Beverly Goldfield, an early
language researcher at Rhode Island College.
</P>
<P>
   Because a young child can only focus on one or two things at a
time, she takes in something new at each reading. ``Repetition may
bore us, but it invigorates a toddler,'' Goldfield says. ``When a
child is bored with a book, you'll know. Until then, as long as she
wants it, a book is serving a purpose for her.''
</P>
<P>
   In one study, Goldfield watched a mother and 2-year-old read the
same book over and over for about a year. When they began, the
mother was pointing to pictures and labeling words. A few months
later, they talked about what the characters were doing and, by the
end of the year, about why they were doing what they were doing.
Often, they stayed on the same page. ``Neither mother nor child
ever seemed bored,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Parents facilitate language development when we connect an
illustration, a written word, or both to an actual object by
pointing it out, literally and figuratively: ``We have a red ball,
too, just like the one in the book. Look!'' ``The gate in this
picture is just like the gate at Grandma's house!''
</P>
<P>
   One day, he'll make a similar connection: ``Daddy car!'' This is
a big deal. ``It means a child has made the leap to understanding
that books are representational,'' says Pan. When we validate the
connection _ ``Yes, that car is blue, just like Daddy's car!'' _
he'll be emboldened to make more.
</P>
<P>
   There may also be a psychological component to wanting the same
book over and over. ``Little kids live in a world where they don't
know what will happen next,'' says Spitz. ``When they master a
book, they know what comes next. That gives them predictability
which equals control and security.'' She lectures at Stanford
University and is the author of ``Inside Pictures Books'' (Yale,
1999).
</P>
<P>
   Maria Tatar, a professor at Harvard who teaches children's
folklore and literature, says it was no surprise to her when her
son used a familiar and beloved book to make his transition from
home to day care. ``Every day, as soon as we got there, he would go
to the same book, and we would read it together several times
before I left. It created a comfort level for him,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, there's a reason why a child is attracted to a
particular book or a specific page. It may be something as simple
as a fascination with the colors or with a tiny detail in an
illustration, or because he likes the sound of the words. ``The
more we pay attention, the better window we have into what's going
on in her mind,'' says Tatar.
</P>
<P>
   Spitz tells of a 3-year-old who loved ``The Very Hungry
Caterpillar'' by Eric Carle. One day when they got to the page
where the caterpillar gets a stomachache, the preschooler
announced, ``He's sick because he misses his mommy.'' Her diagnosis
had nothing to do with the story line _ the caterpillar was sick
because he ate too much _ but, says Spitz, it had everything to do
with developmental issues of separation that typical 3-year-olds
are working on. (Just because you get information like this doesn't
necessarily mean you need to deal with it. ``Just tuck it away and
consider yourself enriched,'' says Spitz.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, early reading has direct benefits to language
development. Pan says some of the classics in childhood literature
provide the best reading for children not just because they strike
universal themes but also because the language works so well and is
so meaningful. ``The repetition, rhyming, and rhythm grabs their
attention and facilitates learning,'' says Lauren Adams, senior
editor of the Horn Book Magazine, a review journal of children's
literature. Her 13-month-old daughter's favorite book is ``My First
Mother Goose'' by Peter and Iona Opie, which is full of rhymes that
have tickled generations of young children. Repetitive sentence
patterns in a book like ``Goodnight Moon'' help a child learn
syntax.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, ``Goodnight Moon'' by Margaret Wise Brown is the one
book professionals point to over and over as a must for every
baby's bookshelf. Here are some other recommendations. Who knows?
One of them could end up at Harvard with your child:
</P>
<P>
   --For babies from birth to 4 months: ``A Child's First Picture
Book'' by Edward Steichen; any of Helen Oxenbury's baby books,
especially ``Tickle, Tickle''; wordless picture books; poetry.
</P>
<P>
   --6 to 12 months: ``Chicka Chicka Boom Boom'' (original edition,
not the board book) by John Archambault and Bill Martin Jr.; ``If
the Moon Could Talk'' by Kate Banks; ``Where's Spot?'' by Eric
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   --12 to 24 months: ``Hi'' by Ann Scott; ``My Five Senses'' and
``Whose Hat?'' by Margaret Miller; and ``The Snowy Day'' by Ezra
Jack Keats; ``Are You My Mother?'' by P. D. Eastman.
</P>
<P>
   --2- to 3-year-olds: ``A Hat for Minerva Louise'' by Janet
Stoeke; ``Trucks, Trucks, Trucks'' by Peter Sis; ``Make Way for
Ducklings'' by Robert McCloskey; ``One Fish, Two Fish'' and other
Dr. Seuss titles; ``Moonlight'' by Jan Ormerodd.
</P>
<P>
   --3- to 4-year-olds: ``Red-Eyed Tree Frog'' by Joy Cowley;
``Where the Wild Things Are'' by Maurice Sendak; ``Corduroy'' by
Don Freeman; ``The Story About Ping'' by Marjorie Flack and Kurt
Wiese; ``The Wall'' by Eve Bunting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --When you're reading, take your cues from your child on whether
to stop and talk about the book. Some kids hate an interruption;
others will ask questions as you go along.
</P>
<P>
   --By 12 months, leave books scattered around the house, even in
his crib, so he'll encounter them as he moves about. The books
should be varied, so some have a more challenging story line or
more complicated illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   --If a child doesn't like a book that you love, respect his
wishes and try it again in a few weeks or months.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't insist that every page be read in its entirety.
</P>
<P>
   --Have a reading routine like bedtime, but also read at least
one other time spontaneously during the day.
</P>
<P>
   --To read wordless stories, take turns: ``I'll tell this page
and you tell the next one.'' The idea is to stimulate her
imagination; anything she comes up with is OK.
</P>
<P>
   --When a child tells you, ``You're reading it wrong!'' your
expression may be different than she's used to. Don't get
defensive. Ask her, ``What's the right way? You teach me.''
</P>
<P>
   --We serve as role models: Does your child see you reading?
</P>
<P>
   --Introduce a new book by leaving it on the floor among the toys
for a few days before actually reading it.
</P>
<P>
   --Encourage an older sibling to read to a younger one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz is author of ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell). Meltz
welcomes letters and comments and can be reached via e-mail at
meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
