<HEADLINE>
HOLD THE TUNA, PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are pregnant, or even thinking of becoming pregnant, stay
away from tuna. And, if you know someone who's pregnant, tell her
the Food and Drug Administration recommends not eating more than
one 8-ounce portion of shark or swordfish a month. According to a
recent advisory from the state Department of Public Health,
pregnant women should also avoid eating fish caught in our state's
rivers, lakes, or streams.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? These fish contain elevated levels of mercury, a
poison that attacks the central nervous system. How potent is it?
Well, a drop of mercury the size of an M&AMP;M is enough to contaminate
the entire Quabbin Reservoir or 5 million gallons of Boston Harbor.
While we've been blissfully unaware, mercury, in mounting
concentrations, has been accumulating in the bodies of many of our
commonly eaten fish.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, you won't drop dead 10 minutes after you eat a tuna
sandwich, but according to a recent study by Health Care Without
Harm and the Environmental Working Group, a 140-pound pregnant
woman risks subtle but permanent brain damage to her fetus by
eating half of a 6-ounce can of tuna per day, and the average
4-year old exceeds the EPA's ``safe'' dose if he or she eats one
small can of tuna per week.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA insists that tuna, shark, and swordfish are safe for the
average human being _ think 155-pound male _ ``provided they are
eaten infrequently (no more than once a week) as part of a balanced
diet,'' but the child in utero faces a special threat. The
developing nervous system is highly susceptible to the toxic
effects of methyl mercury, which, once it enters the mother's body,
easily crosses the placenta, ending up 30 percent higher in fetal
blood cells than in the mother's bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   Shouldn't this be huge news? If items in our food supply are no
longer totally safe for children and pregnant women, shouldn't it
be cause for immediate action by regulatory agencies?
Unfortunately, not when cause and effect cannot be proven beyond a
shadow of a doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what we know about mercury's effects comes from
overdoses in places like Iran, where a mercury-based fungicide in
bread killed hundreds and damaged the health of thousands. Less is
known about the impact of low-level exposure, although a long-term
study of 7-year-olds in the Faeroe Islands recently found that
children with prenatal exposure to one-third of what are now
considered ``acceptable'' levels of methyl mercury later suffered
from impaired attention, language, and memory, as well as higher
blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are sparse, and very much in dispute. FDA
toxicologist Mike Bolger says such fears are exaggerated, and that
the findings in the Faeroe Islands are complicated by other
factors, like PCBs and dioxin. Tuna is safe, he insists, since it
falls below the FDA's current limit of mercury of one part per
million, although you can't help but wonder how US scientists can
be so positive when Canadian scientists have set their standard for
mercury in fish at half our concentration.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know what to do when the experts disagree and both
sides are making the strongest case possible. I side with the
conservatives. Having lived this long, I've seen the awareness of a
hazard slowly make its way into popular consciousness before. The
early safety estimates are usually far too optimistic, and by the
time standards are revised downward, a great many people have
suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Remember lead? Asbestos? How about radioactivity?
</P>
<P>
   The danger is clear enough that Governor Cellucci, the other New
England governors and the premiers from eastern Canada have signed
an agreement to curtail by half how much more mercury is released
into the environment by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Until there's less mercury in the environment, however, there
are things you can do to protect yourself and your family. Since
seafood is so good for your health, it's sad that limiting and
varying your consumption of fish is one of them. In addition,
never, never discard a mercury thermometer into the trash. Wait for
a hazardous waste collection day at your local dump to dispose of
it, and when you buy a new one, make it digital.
</P>
<P>
   It may turn out that mercury in fish has nothing to do with what
has been described as an epidemic of attention deficits and
learning disabilities in young children today.
</P>
<P>
   My advice? Avoid it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
