<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COPTIC30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coptic faithful to celebrate church patriarch in Ohio
 &HT;    (For use Saturday, July 31 and thereafter.)
 &HT;    By Meggen Lindsay
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ For many Egyptian immigrants in the Miami Valley,
this is the most important summer of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Pope Shenouda III, the patriarch of the Coptic religion, is
visiting St. Mina &AMP; St. Abunoub Coptic Orthodox Church in
Centerville Aug. 20. It is the first time the patriarch has come to
southwestern Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really a big event for us,'' said Father John Ragheb,
41. ``We are really excited _ for some it will be their first time
to meet him, and they will be very honored.''
</P>
<P>
   Shenouda III, who was consecrated as pope of Alexandria and
patriarch of the See of St. Mark in 1971, is the spiritual leader
of more than 25 million Coptic Orthodox Christians worldwide,
including 500,000 in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The Coptic church was established in 40 A.D. by St. Mark the
Apostle in Egypt and split from the Orthodox church in the fifth
century. The Coptic church is one of the founders of the World
Council of Churches and is a member of the African Council Churches
and the Middle East Council of Churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``When His Holiness became pope in 1971, there were only four
churches in North America. Today there are over 80 churches and one
monostary,'' said Ragheb.
</P>
<P>
   Shenouda III is coming to consecrate a new icon, which was drawn
in Egypt and recently delivered to the church. He may lead a Mass
with his accompanying bishops, but plans are not yet final.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first time many of the local congregation
members will see the leader of their faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people (in the church) are born here, not in Egypt, and
some married into the church, so they have never seen him,'' said
Ragheb. ``They are excited to get his blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ragheb is also excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ordained me in 1995 in Egypt,'' he said. ``We haved
traveled all over to spend time with him and listen to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he was a Coptic priest, Ragheb was a civil engineer in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I received a call from God to do this,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   While a Coptic church has been established in the Miami Valley
for 25 years, an official church was not dedicated until 1991.
Previously, priests came form different cities to conduct Mass, and
the congregation rented buildings.
</P>
<P>
   St. Mina &AMP; St. Abunoub Coptic Orthodox Church, which serves
Dayton, Cincinnati, and Kentucky, has about 60 families in its
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our members are Egyptian, but we also have American
and Ethiopian families who come,'' said Naeim Tadross, 61, a member
of the board of deacons and the church's treasurer. ``Some people
who are from the Middle East attend as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The church will hold its annual bazaar Saturday and Sunday with
Egyptian food and desserts, crafts and literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is for everybody to come,'' said Tadross.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the bazaar or the church, call (937)
866-0622.
</P>
<P>
   Meggen Lindsay writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: meggenlindsay(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
