<HEADER>
A8539 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-29 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE HIGH BROW AND MONTY HALL MEET AND DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like so much PBS programming, ``Antiques Roadshow'' is trash
without guilt. It's the ``Masterpiece Theater'' version of ``Let's
Make a Deal.'' I'm addicted.
</P>
<P>
   I sit there and watch it and tell myself, hey, this is highly
educational, I'm learning about antiques, when all I'm really doing
is getting vicarious thrills and a dose of savage amusement.
</P>
<P>
   The show taps the mother lode of human eccentricity. Some of the
contestants _ excuse me, guests? hopefuls? petitioners? what do we
call them? _ even look as though they could be trying to get on
``Let's Make a Deal.'' Remember how people used to dress up like
chickens and clowns trying to catch Monty Hall's attention? And
what's with all those people toting bundles of stuff and milling
about in the background looking dazed and aimless, like they're in
a George Romero movie, ``Yard Sale of the Living Dead''?
</P>
<P>
   The last thing I want to do here is get serious, but PBS has
tapped into something elemental in the human psyche with ``Antiques
Roadshow.'' No wonder it can be found on one or another of our
local public television outlets six nights a week. It appeals to
the gambler in all of us, the magical dream that someday we're
going to find a piece of junk that turns out to be worth a fortune.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the lure of schadenfreude, the pleasure we take
from someone else's misfortune. Sure, it's nice when a sweet old
lady discovers she has a treasure, but it's much more satisfying
when somebody clearly thinks she has a treasure and it turns out to
be trash. I don't think we get to see enough of those moments on
the show.
</P>
<P>
   I like it when the expert says, ``Well, we have some good news
and some bad news.'' Because the bad news is almost always a
corker.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent show a woman brought in an Arts and Crafts lamp she
said she'd found stuffed in a box in a corner of her attic. First
the good news, the expert said. It would probably fetch $15,000 to
$20,000 at auction. Then the bad news. If she hadn't cleaned and
polished it, it would bring $85,000 to $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   This little segment was great theater. Watching it, I was swept
by a series of conflicting reactions and emotions, as follows:
</P>
<P>
   --Oh, the poor thing.
</P>
<P>
   --Twenty thousand bucks? For something that looks like her kid
made it at summer camp?
</P>
<P>
   --Ha, that's what she get for being a compulsive cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that could have improved the little drama would
have been if the woman had wept and cursed and howled on hearing
the bad news. And if she'd been dressed like a chicken, so much the
better. But she sat there composed, betraying only the slightest
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the supplicants _ is that the word? _ are so subdued you
might think they'd been tranquilized. Perhaps they're just
exhausted, reduced to a zombie-like state by the ordeal of lugging
their possessions to the show and waiting in line for an appraisal.
Or maybe the show's producers tell them how to behave on camera:
look happy but not too happy, disappointed but not suicidal.
Personally, I wish they'd take a hint from ``Let's Make a Deal''
and encourage people to scream and cry and jump up and down and hug
the guest experts.
</P>
<P>
   But it is PBS, after all, which is why, the next time some
hideous knick-knack turns out to be worth a small fortune, it's
owner will say, almost inevitably, ``Oh really? But I'd never think
of selling it. It has great sentimental value.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't believe it for a second.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
