A8549 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDNEY-PROMISE-BOS &LR;      07-29 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDNEY-PROMISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOW TO DONATE KIDNEY BROKEN, RETIREE IS OUT $2,500 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EGREMONT, Mass. _ Dr. Anthony Robbins, a retired neurologist and
chairman of the town's Board of Health, propped himself up in his
king-size bed Wednesday and told of a broken promise that nearly
cost him his life.
</P>
<P>
   It began two years ago when Robbins's friend, Police Chief
Michael Balcom, made a life-saving offer: he would donate his own
kidney for Robbins's desperately needed transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship, though, seemed mutally beneficial. The
chief, who had fallen on hard financial times, got $2,500 from
Robbins, no strings attached.
</P>
<P>
   But Balcom apparently changed his mind about the transplant and
vanished _ after he got the loan. Robbins, who passed up the chance
for an earlier transplant in Utah, then sued to get the money back.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit became an ugly legal battle that has set the usually
sedate town in the southern Berkshires abuzz. Three weeks ago,
Balcom was due in court after a judge ordered him to repay the
money, but he did not show up.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Balcom has filed for bankruptcy, according to court
documents. The move further delayed the case, which Robbins and his
wife, Ellen, desperately want to end.
</P>
<P>
   While Robbins insists he never gave Balcom the money in exchange
for his kidney, as local newspapers have widely reported, Robbins
said he was so angry when his friend reneged that he filed the
lawsuit to get the money back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never asked anything of anybody. He brought up the
subject,'' said Robbins, who recently had his left leg amputated
due to complications from diabetes. Balcom ``made a promise he
could not keep,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Balcom, who abruptly quit his job in 1997, has an unlisted
telephone number and has not talked to reporters. Though he is
believed to live near town, he has apparently not been seen since
he quit.
</P>
<P>
   Balcom reportedly left because he faced gambling debts, but town
officials also wanted him out. According to his severance
arrangement, town officials are barred from discussing his
resignation, according to Mary Brazie, the Selectmen's
administrator.
</P>
<P>
   But one official said that Balcom ``needs to get the hell out of
town, since everybody knows what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he came to the Berkshires, Robbins had a medical career
that spanned two decades, mostly in his native New York City. But
in the mid 1970s, he was diagnosed with diabetes and forced to slow
his pace.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins moved to the quiet and solace of Egremont, but still
commuted to New York each day. Finally, Robbins retired in the
mid-1980s and left New York for good.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins and his wife flourished in Egremont, a town of 1,000
whose population doubles during the summer. He gained respect as
the Board of Health chairman and in 1995 met Balcom, the town's
police chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We became friends. We had a camaraderie,'' Robbins said.
</P>
<P>
   During one conversation, Robbins discovered that he had known
Balcom's mother, a nurse in a New York hospital. The little boy
that Robbins often saw tagging along with her was Balcom, now in
his 40s.
</P>
<P>
   The men had been friends for two years when one day in 1997,
Robbins recalled, the police chief noticed that Robbins looked ill.
The doctor had recently suffered two heart attacks, and his kidneys
were barely functioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I need a kidney,' and he said, `I will give you one.'
'' Robbins said. To that point, ``I never asked anyone for (a
kidney) but my children'' and none of them were appropriate donors.
But Balcom was a near perfect match.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Balcom was having financial problems and eventually
asked his friend for help. Robbins gave him $2,500, but wasn't
worried about getting it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never expected a payment. I didn't pursue it because it was
a friend,'' said Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Robbins had been in touch with a Utah hospital which
had found a possible match for him. He didn't pursue it, though,
because he believed his friend's word was gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was my friend,'' Robbins said. But as days and
months passed, ``he was nowhere to be found. I got angry as a
hornet'' and decided to sue.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins called the Utah hospital to see if he could still get a
transplant, but doctors there said he had become too sick to risk
the operation. Fortunately, a local hospital was willing to perform
the transplant this spring after a donor kidney was found.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the acrimony and the lawsuit, Robbins insists he holds
no grudge against Balcom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really not a bad guy,'' he said. ``I just didn't think
near the end of my life I would have to deal with terrible things
like this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
