<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8554 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-29 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANK YOU FOR READING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I started writing columns for The Boston Globe in the summer of
1993. Back then, they were published every other Saturday. I always
imagined that at some point the Globe would reclaim the space and
send me on my way. But they never did, and in the summer of 1995
editorial page editor David Greenway asked me to increase my output
to once a week.
</P>
<P>
   By the fall of 1996, I was actually writing two columns a week,
one for foxnews.com on media and technology and the other for the
Saturday Globe. In June 1997, Greenway asked me to come on
full-time as a staff columnist, and I happily accepted his offer. I
now happily resign.
</P>
<P>
   I say ``happily'' because the Globe has been, as the ``Saturday
Night Live'' baseball player used to say, ``very, very good to
me.'' Greenway and op-ed page editor Marjorie Pritchard never never
changed the substance of my copy, and never told me I couldn't
write about certain subjects. Once, they even let me criticize The
New York Times, which at the time had just purchased The Boston
Globe. Throughout my time writing for the paper, they gave me the
closest thing I've ever known to complete editorial freedom.
</P>
<P>
   That freedom enabled me to write about a range of subjects that
I might not have written about otherwise. And that, in turn, led to
a series of job offers which were simply too good to pass up. In
September, I will begin anew as an Internet consultant (or
principal, depending on the outcome of negotiations), as a
columnist for Fast Company magazine and (for a week) as the Ryder
Cup columnist for Thestreet.com. Greenway has also asked me to
continue to contribute to the Globe's op-ed page, which I intend to
do as often as time allows.
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons I am leaving the Globe, of course. First
among these is that my standing as a political columnist has been
undercut by the fact of George W. Bush's presidential candidacy.
Bush is my first cousin and a friend. Writing columns about his
candidacy was, for me, like playing three-dimensional chess. I
finally gave up trying, and in so doing, realized that a political
columnist who didn't write about politics should probably, as they
say, get a life.
</P>
<P>
   Our life has changed as well. When I started writing for the
Globe, I lived in the Boston area. Because of my wife's work, we
moved to New York late last year and have now bought a home in
Westchester County near the Hudson River. Part of being a good
columnist is being part of the community the paper serves. We have
no intention of moving back to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   And there comes a time in life when you want to know if you're
right. I have a lot of ideas about the impact of Internet
technologies on commerce, some of which I have written about in
these pages. I'd really like to know if these ideas work; if they
are as applicable in the real world as I think they might be.
There's only one way to find that out. You just have to go do it.
</P>
<P>
   Writing a twice-weekly column for a major metropolitan newspaper
is a great privilege and a lot of fun. It gives you access to
people who would be otherwise hard to reach. But there's a
trade-off, which is that it doesn't pay particularly well,
particularly by New York standards. Money matters when there are
children to be educated and retirement on the horizon. I've got two
children and am older than I think I am. Denying these realities is
no longer an option.
</P>
<P>
   There are many people to thank for making possible my time at
the Globe and I will thank most of them privately. But there are
two I would like to thank publicly. First, I am especially grateful
to Ben Taylor, who published my work even though I suspect that he
probably disagreed with much of it. Had the roles been reversed, I
can't imagine I'd ever have been as tolerant or as supportive.
</P>
<P>
   And I am also especially grateful to you, the reader of this
space. The only demographic that matters in modern life is the fact
that no one has any time. There are always a hundred other things
to do. The fact that you read this column and in some cases took
the time to write or e-mail me was, for me, the highest compliment.
</P>
<P>
   The great satisfaction of writing comes from connecting with
your reader, if only for a while. The connection now breaks, but my
gratitude remains. I thank you for your time and attention.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
