<HEADER>
A8555 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-SUMMER-BOS &LR;      07-29 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-SUMMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMERTIME AND THE GARDENING IS . . . FUNNY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The other seasons are busy, serious, but summer _ especially
high summer _ is a time to lie back. It is light comedy, it is
mysteries, it is a special entity with its own sounds, sights, and
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's time for some plant division, says I.
</P>
<P>
   Long or short division, says she. Ba-da-bing.
</P>
<P>
   In a small gravelly bed, Oriental lilies and lavender thrive,
appreciating the good drainage and enduring the somewhat hellish
conditions. Something is needed to skirt the lilies (red `Star
Gazer' and white `Casa Blanca'), though, for the picture is barren.
Small, yellow day lilies are just the thing, with cascading,
grasslike foliage, and I already have mature clumps out front.
Despite the heat, I will divide them. First, I dig the holes where
the divisions will go, for I don't want the roots to dry out
waiting while I dig. I lever the clumps up and out, slice them into
sections with leaf fans and roots, and plant them. Then I water
like crazy.
</P>
<P>
   This is such a success that I move on to a line of heuchera
`Raspberry Red.' There's a gap, and I take the farthest one back
and whack it in twain to provide a replacement. This works
reasonably well. The new heuchera seems to respond to the watering,
but the remainder of the original is flagging, its leaves browning;
mulch may help.
</P>
<P>
   The sunflowers come next. They need thinning, and rather than
waste the thinnings, I pop them out using a thin trowel and replant
them. I water mightily, but within 30 minutes they have wilted.
Some plants resent being transplanted, and sunflowers are among
them. Frequent watering helps, though, and I think they may
recover. I've had mixed success in similar moves of cosmos
seedlings. They just collapse in pathetic, wilted heaps. Some
recover and grow, some don't.
</P>
<P>
   Dividing and planting in high summer is not recommended, and for
good reasons. The recommendation can be ignored, but not the
reasons: Plants transpire in heat, the moisture comes from the
roots, and those roots are decimated when moved. So, frequent
watering is needed, and it can help to prune some of the plant tops
to reduce the amount of moisture lost through the leaves. Plants
also are stressed because they are faced with having to generate
new roots at a time when they otherwise have shut down. Day lilies
and heucheras are tough guys, though.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And that brings us to mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   What is eating my roses? Oh, the usual suspects are present,
Japanese beetles and earwigs, but there's another, a tan and
mottled gray beast about the size of a Japanese beetle, though much
easier to hand-squoosh. I've noticed them before, but never in such
numbers as this summer.
</P>
<P>
   I do research on the Web (some good sites are
plants.okstate.edu/plantdoctor and
http://everest.ento.vt.edu/Facilities/OnCampus/IDInfo.html) and
think it might be the Asiatic garden beetle. I call the master
gardeners at the Massachusetts Horticultural Society (781-235-2116,
10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays). The nice woman
who answers isn't sure what my beastie is but thinks I might have
an infestation of thrips, too, based on many rose flower buds
failing to open. Great.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I sleuth it out. I call Deborah Swanson at the Plymouth
County Extension. It isn't the Asiatic garden beetle, it's the
Oriental beetle, she says, which often associates with Japanese
beetles. She advises hand-picking, which is what she does, though
``I live with a lot of damage.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to inadvertently kill snakes, toads and birds with
pesticides, either, so I will continue squooshing. And I'll take a
new look at earwigs. Swanson suspects they do a lot more damage
than is generally supposed.
</P>
<P>
   Further research reveals that the Oriental beetle is closely
related to the Japanese beetle and the Asiatic garden beetle, and
they have similar life cycles, with their grubs being particularly
destructive to lawns. The beetles emerge from the soil in July and
August. Endemic in the Northeast, they are thought to have arrived
from Japan in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   High summer is a semimystical time, when heat saps the body,
leaving the mind to wander, memories tapped by sweat and dust and
idle musings on cloud formations. The drones of the cicadas are
exactly as they were last summer, and the summer before, and the
summer of 1955 in a berry patch outside Halifax, Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   The gardener is reduced to early morning chores, before the sun
presses flat the will to work. We notice yews that need pruning,
diseased branches in a cherry that should come out, weeds. We
notice a big hairy grin among the cannas _ Lucy the Newfoundland
dog is lazing in the garden! Out, out! She rises and ambles off,
her eyes sparkling with mischief (perhaps we anthropomorphize), and
we see that she somehow managed to lie among the plants without
damaging a single one. Ba-da-bing.
</P>
<P>
   These are the dog days, and it's a laugh a minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
