<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8563 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOSEMITE-SUSPECT-HNS &LR;      07-29 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-SUSPECT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAYNER STATEMENT CALLED DUBIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN and ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. _ Somewhere in the drama-infused
life of Cary Stayner, seeds of violence were planted. But while
research into the minds of multiple murderers has identified common
causes, the template doesn't fit neatly over Stayner's story.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner, 37, has reportedly confessed to the killings of three
tourists he held captive in Yosemite National Park and a naturalist
who worked there.
</P>
<P>
   In an off-camera interview with a TV reporter, Stayner said he
had been entertaining visions of slaying women for three decades _
meaning, if true, that his frightening fantasies began when he was
7.
</P>
<P>
   What may have been the defining event in Stayner's life _ the
1972 kidnapping of his younger brother, Steven, by a pedophile and
Steven's surprise return to the family fold seven years later _
came too late to explain his deadly deeds, the reporter said
Stayner told him. Three years before the kidnapping, by his own
time line, images of mayhem began to flicker on his mental screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not typical (in serial killers), and I'm not sure I
believe it, either,'' said P. Terry Macdonald, a San Jose State
sociologist who studies the minds of multiple murderers. ``It's
very rare for a 7- year-old kid to fantasize about killing women.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases serial killers begin their criminal careers
following the failure of a key relationship, Macdonald said. ``I
suspect he has had some failed relationships that turned out pretty
bad, and I doubt if he started having them at 7,'' Macdonald said.
</P>
<P>
   Macdonald said the infamous Ted Bundy had started his killing
spree in response to a girlfriend's rejection. Most of his victims
resembled that woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would go back and look at (Stayner's) ex-girlfriends
immediately, if he had any ex-girlfriends,'' Macdonald said.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner had no recent romantic entanglements, according to his
neighbors in El Portal, just outside Yosemite. Stayner lived and
sometimes worked at the Cedar Lodge, where three of his alleged
victims were staying when they were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Ludwig, 16, said Stayner had described a ``dry spell'' in
the dating department. ``He hadn't had sex in about six months,''
said Ludwig, who works in the town's only gas station.
</P>
<P>
   Stayner reportedly also enjoyed talking to teenage girls in the
community.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his alleged victims were adolescents: Juli Sund, 15, and
Silvina Pelosso, 16. Stayner has reportedly admitted murdering
both, as well as Juli's mother, Carole Sund, in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   His last alleged victim _ park naturalist Joie Ruth Armstrong,
who was found dead on July 22 _ was 26.
</P>
<P>
   While some serial killers report abusive childhoods, other
deficits in their home environment can lead to violence later in
life, according to several experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes what you find instead is abandonment,'' said Mike
Rustigan, an San Francisco State University criminologist.
``Sometimes you find a lack of any bonding between child and
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Stayner's parents _ Delbert and Kay Stayner, who live near
Merced about 50 miles west of the Yosemite National Park _ are
thought to have been attentive and devoted to their children. But
Kay Stayner has been described as aloof.
</P>
<P>
   ``Del was much more emotionally and affectionately involved with
the kids than Kay was,'' said Mike Echols, who wrote a book about
the Steven Stayner kidnapping case called ``I Know My Name Is
Steven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kay, in a perfunctory sense, was very concerned about their
being fed and clothed, but she was not touchy-feely. She was not
physically affectionate,'' Echols said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cary and Steven Stayner were not physically abused by
their parents, Echols said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kay pushed Del into physically punishing the kids, but that
was relatively rare, and Del did everything he could to avoid it,''
Echols said. ``He just absolutely hated that.''
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Miller, who wrote the screenplay for a TV miniseries based
on Echols' book, told Hollywood columnist Army Archerd that after
spending ``quite a bit of time with the whole Stayner family,'' he
``found no affection between the parents and children.''
</P>
<P>
   The known central trauma in Cary Stayner's life was the
abduction and return of his younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Stayner escaped from his captor, Kenneth Parnell, in
1980. His return home was marked by much media hoopla, and Cary
Stayner was pushed into the background as his parents attempted to
reassimilate his younger brother into the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steven got all the attention,'' said Anna Jones, Delbert
Stayner's sister, in an interview with the Sacramento Bee.
``Whatever Steven wanted, Steven got.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the TV reporter who interviewed Cary Stayner in
jail Monday, Stayner said his first homicides came in February of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   That Stayner may have begun committing murder at mid-life fits
the pattern of other serial killers, Macdonald said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average age is 35,'' Macdonald said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Almost all serial murderers have low-paying jobs
that don't seem to be going anywhere. Thirty-five seems to be about
the age that they crack and can't handle the strain of knowing what
their lives are going to be like. Plus, they're afraid that maybe
they're losing their sexual attractiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Rustigan said the organized manner in which Stayner allegedly
pulled off the Sund-Pelosso murders indicates he might have killed
before. ``There could be more victims,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Stayner has denied in news accounts that he sexually
molested his victims, Dr. Reid Meloy, a San Diego forensic
psychologist and author of ``The Psychopathic Mind,'' said the
ferociously violent murders fit the rare homicidal category known
as serial sexual killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hunch is there's a high probability these were sexual
homicides: Women were targeted who were unknown to the
perpetrator,'' Meloy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
