<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTOONS-BOWL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTOONS ARE WHAT'S UP AT THE BOWL, DOC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NANCY HEWITT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ George Daugherty is not ashamed to admit he still
enjoys watching cartoons. But better still, he enjoys the
soundtracks so much that he created a musical program that combines
the best of both worlds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bugs Bunny on Broadway IV'' comes to the Hollywood Bowl at
7:30 p.m. Aug. 8. For a few hours, the audience will enjoy a
collection of cartoons featuring that wascaly wabbit and his pals
cavorting on a huge screen and accompanied by the Hollywood Bowl
Orchestra conducted by Daugherty. ``The audience sees a 50-foot
screen hanging over the orchestra,'' Daugherty says. ``And the
orchestra plays the music live, completely synchronized with the
cartoons.''
</P>
<P>
   The program is so popular that many audience members are repeat
customers. ``People wear rabbit ears and carrot corsages and shout
out dialogue along with the characters because they've seen them so
many times,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, approximately 150 fans bought a box at the Bowl
and came dressed in hats similar to what Bugs Bunny wears in the
cartoon ``What's Opera, Doc?'' ``It was still light,'' Daugherty
recalls, ``and I looked into the audience and saw 150 gold helmets
with horns. For the rest of the night they got everyone doing the
wave.''
</P>
<P>
   Daugherty is a classically trained pianist who also has dabbled
in producing, directing and writing, as well as conducting American
and international symphonies.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up with a fondness for the cartoons created by Chuck
Jones and Friz Freleng not only because they entertained him but
because of the snippets of classical music that he heard with them.
``We've all grown up with these wonderful cartoons. I was drawn to
these cartoons through the music when I was a kid,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Daugherty believes he has found the best possible union for
introducing kids _ and even their parents _ to classical music. He
says his goal has always been ``to bring children, families and
adults in to experience classical music.''
</P>
<P>
   However, what he feels is most important is introducing
classical music in small doses. ``Thirty-six hours of Wagner is
condensed to seven minutes, which is about what most people can
tolerate of Wagner,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Simple takes on popular operas _ such as the ``Rabbit of
Seville'' based on the Barber of Seville _ delight audiences
without overwhelming them.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices range from $3 to $75, half price for children
under 12. To purchase tickets, call Ticketmaster at (213) 480-3232
or visit the Hollywood Bowl box office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
