<SLUG> BC-PACIFICA-RADIO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERKELEY OWNER OFFERS TO REOPEN RADIO STATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ In what appeared to be an abrupt turnaround,
the Pacifica Foundation announced it would reopen KPFA and remove
itself from management of the beleaguered Berkeley radio station
for six to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   The statement came as the crisis at KPFA seemed to be deepening
_ mediation appeared on the verge of collapse, bigger protests were
planned and board members substantiated rumors that Pacifica was
discussing selling off the left-leaning station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reopening the station is a goodwill gesture on the part of
Pacifica toward resolving the conflict and moving toward
diversification on local terms,'' Pacifica chairwoman Mary Frances
Berry said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-year-old listener-sponsored station has been at the
center of a bitter struggle over the direction and control of its
future.
</P>
<P>
   Pacifica closed the station two weeks ago and began airing tapes
of old programs after a reporter was heard on the air arguing with
armed security guards under orders from management to remove him
from the station for reporting about the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   KPFA union representative William Harvey, said Berry called him
Wednesday afternoon to lay out the offer. She said a written
proposal would be presented Thursday morning through federal
mediators, who have been involved with negotiations between staff
and management since last week.
</P>
<P>
   Aileen Alfandary, co-news director, was elated yet hesitant
about the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is an amazing turnaround,'' she said. ``However,
I would caution, I am still extremely skeptical. Pacifica has not
negotiated in good faith from day one of this crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Harvey, Berry offered to reopen the station Friday
at 9 a.m., remove all security guards and welcome back all staff
except Nicole Sawaya, the well-liked station manager let go on
March 31, and Larry Bensky, the veteran broadcaster fired a few
weeks later for criticizing on the air Pacifica's refusal to renew
Sawaya's contract.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bensky and Sawaya are involved in legal discussions with
Pacifica regarding their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Pacifica said Bensky violated a long-standing policy forbidding
on- air discussion of internal personnel matters. KPFA supporters
called it a ``gag rule.'' Harvey said Berry's proposal included
suspending the gag rule.
</P>
<P>
   Berry's statement also said the Pacifica national offices, now
located in Berkeley next to the KPFA station, would move to
Washington, D.C., where Berry, chairman of the U.S. Civil Rights
Commission and a law professor at the University of Pennsylvania,
is based.
</P>
<P>
   While Pacifica, which also oversees stations in Los Angeles,
Houston, New York and Washington, is removed from management of
KPFA for the proposed six to 12 months, it will monitor KPFA's
audience ratings and diversity of its programs and listeners, two
areas which Berry has said she wanted to see improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Mediation through the Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service
will continue, Berry's statement said, ``until a more permanent
resolution is met.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Imani, who is a member of the KPFA steering committee
involved in the mediation, said that he was hesitant to continue
negotiating with Pacifica because it had not shown good faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to mediate with somebody who has no
integrity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey said he was satisfied with Berry's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we have some skepticism borne of the difficulty that's
happened throughout this whole thing, it meets most of the items on
the union short-list,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
