</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Labor costs surged in the first quarter
at their fastest clip in eight years, a Labor Department report
showed, stirring fears among investors that inflationary pressures
will force the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates. Stock and
bond prices fell sharply following the report. The rise in labor
costs came at a time when the economy slowed abruptly as consumers
curtailed their spending. Gross domestic product rose a comfortable
2.3 percent in the second quarter, slower than the first quarter's
4.3 percent annual pace and much slower than what economists had
expected. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-DAEWOO (Seoul) _ No one can quite divine the meaning of
the government's decision to step in with more than $8 billion to
prevent Daewoo from defaulting. In bringing to an end the series of
debt rollovers that has kept Daewoo going for the last several
years, has the government indicated a renewed commitment to reform?
Or was the intervention reminiscent of the past, when
government-directed lending and political considerations, rather
than market forces, determined the winners and losers in South
Korea's economy? By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
