<SLUG> BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
  
 ART ADV.: Photos with TERNS-RETURN and AUTOS-REVIEW are being
transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-PRODI (Brussels) _ Romani Prodi wants to restore the
relevance and the integrity of the 15-nation European Union after
scandal forced out his predecessor. By Kevin Cullen. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TERNS-RETURN (Seavey Island, N.H.) _ Terns, symbols of New
England summer that had been driven from their island home for
almost 50 years, are back. By Scott Allen. 1295 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   KIDNEY-PROMISE (Egremont, Mass.) _ Anthony Robbins has felt the
sting of misplaced trust as a person he considered a friend
promised him a life-giving kidney and then reneged. The former
friend is a foemr police chief. By Tasha Robertson. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-WEBSITE (Undated) _ Ling Chai helped lead the student
protest at Tiananmen Square. She was nominated twice for the Nobel
Peace Prize. Now she's feuding with Harvard over a website. By
James Bandler. 1090 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-TOCCO (Boston) _ Ever since Gov. Paul Cellucci named Steve
Tocco higher education chairman, criticism has focused on the
appointee's lack of education experience. But officials say the
real problems are Tocco's unpredictability and enormous ego. By
Kate Zernike. 1470 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JACOBY-COLUMN (Undated) _ The demagogues against tax cuts are
poisoning the debate. By Jeff Jacoby.
</P>
<P>
   ELLIS-COLUMN (Undated) -- The great satisfaction of writing
comes from connecting with your reader, if only for a while. By
John Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE &LR;   &UR; (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-SUMMER (Undated) -- High summer is a semimystical time,
leaving the mind to wander, memories tapped by sweat and dust and
idle musings on cloud formations. By Steve Hatch.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDCARE-COLUMN (Undated) _ That a childhood book could serve
as a security blanket for an 18-year-old may surprise some parents,
but books often have far more than educational importance to young
children. By Barbara Meltz. 1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Hold the tuna, please. By Linda
Weltner.
</P>
