<SLUG> BC-CRACK-BABY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME `CRACK BABIES' FARE BETTER THAN PREDICTED 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (Repeating for all needing)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- With ambulance sirens wailing, Maleeka arrived at
Children's Hospital, a newborn so tiny doctors could hold her
squirmy, 3-pound body cupped in one hand.
</P>
<P>
   The cocaine that had swirled in her bloodstream caused sections
of her intestine to shrivel. At 2 months old, surgeons
reconstructed it, but feared she would die.
</P>
<P>
   She survived, a miracle girl with a label on her head: ``crack
baby.'' It was 1989 when that phrase sent shudders throughout
Boston and the nation. Doctors cringed at the thought of Maleeka's
miserable fate.
</P>
<P>
   Now 9, Maleeka is an outgoing, talkative girl who thrives on
attention, and writes and reads at grade level. A row of A's marks
her report card, except in math, which is a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can be anything she wants in the world,'' said her
adoptive mother, Barbara Webb of Harwich.
</P>
<P>
   More than 12 years since the birth of the first generation of
crack babies, researchers have reached an unexpected and hopeful
conclusion: Crack-exposed babies did not grow up to become the
irreparably damaged children that everyone once feared. While most
of them need some help, you cannot, just by looking at them, tell
them apart from other children.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said these babies were damaged. That they would be
retarded and become wards of society,'' said Barry Lester, a
leading researcher on cocaine-exposed children, based in
Providence. ``Now we know that they do show differences, but the
differences are subtle and can be corrected with treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say they believe the brains of some of these
children are smaller and less developed, with neurological glitches
that cause misfires in processing information. Most of the children
struggle to stay focused, take longer to understand complex
thoughts and solve math problems, and tend to get excited easily.
The average crack-exposed child has an IQ about 3 points lower than
the average child, studies show. But with special education
programs, researchers say these children can perform as well as
other children.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than a decade ago when TV news began flashing
pictures of scrawny babies with glassy eyes who shook
uncontrollably and did not like being held. Pediatricians, nurses,
and social workers blamed the horrors on a new drug called crack _
a potent, highly addictive form of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, doctors realized they overlooked another possible
culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are classic symptoms of heroin withdrawal,'' said
Lester. ``At the time, people would find out the mother was using
cocaine, and they didn't look for signs of other drugs. They
thought cocaine was doing all the dirty work.''
</P>
<P>
   Most pregnant mothers who smoke crack also smoke cigarettes,
drink alcohol, and often do other drugs. In Maleeka's case, her
mother was so strung out on drugs, she told doctors she did not
know she was pregnant. She gave birth to Maleeka in her Dorchester
apartment, then dialed 911.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem for many of the children: poverty,
malnutrition, lack of mental stimulation, neglect, and growing up
in dysfunctional homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's remarkable that these kids do as well as they do
considering all they are facing,'' Lester said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maleeka is tall for her age, a bright-eyed girl with tremendous
energy, who admits, ``I love to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day, she ran around her home, talking to her Furby
doll. Then she walked in front of a visitor, tapped a pair of chop
sticks on the table, and announced, ``Ladies and gentlemen,'' while
raising the sticks in front of an imaginary choir. As she waved the
sticks, her voice boomed: ``La. Lee. La. La.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, with a giggle, Maleeka revealed the scars hidden under her
T-shirt. ``Here are my railroad tracks,'' she exclaimed, pointing
to the incision and staple marks stretching across her abdomen. It
is a reminder of the surgery she had at 2 months old. Another scar
marks her gallbladder removal. Along her lower spine, a fleshy
mound reminds her of the recent removal of a cyst in between her
vertebrae.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors don't know what caused it,'' said Webb, 42. ``I
find it hard to believe it's not connected to the cocaine.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite physical ailments and minor learning disabilities,
children like Maleeka do so well most people would never suspect
their mothers smoked crack.
</P>
<P>
   Like Fred, 5, who has a sly grin, is outgoing and friendly, but
easily distracted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you try to get him to play with blocks or do a puzzle, he
doesn't stay engaged. You have to work hard with him,'' Lester
said.
</P>
<P>
   He has trouble controlling his excitement, and gets emotional
easily. But his IQ on various tests is 98, two points shy of
average. And he speaks and understands concepts as well as his
peers.
</P>
<P>
   Fred's mother smoked crack cocaine about four times a week in
the first trimester, but says she stopped because she worried that
continued use would cause harm. If anything, drug and alcohol use
causes the most damage in the first trimester, doctors say, when
the baby's central nervous system and major organs are forming.
</P>
<P>
   But, Lester said, Fred's mother continued to drink and smoke
cigarettes throughout her pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Lester has known Fred since birth and thinks he will do fine
despite his minor handicaps. Fred's mother has done an about-face
and now reads with him, plays with him, and gives him the kind of
nurturing and stimulation he needs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the good news, the effort continues to fully understand
cocaine's effects on the brain. Researchers theorize that the
brains of crack-exposed children are smaller based on studies that
show the diameter of their heads is about a centimeter smaller at
birth than those of children not exposed to crack. But no one has
published a study showing such children's brains are actually
smaller. Also, it is difficult for researchers to prove that crack
limits children's brain functions, basing the belief on the poorer
performance of crack babies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
