<HEADLINE>
IN MORE WAYS THAN ONE, IT'S A VERY COOL CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The shadowy gray light through my bedroom window
tells me before I am fully awake that it will be another cold,
dreary summer day in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Just as I mumble, ``Bummer,'' I remember recent conversations
with family and friends back East. Their words drift through my
brain like the soft, cool breezes they all believe have deserted
them forever.
</P>
<P>
   Miserable.
</P>
<P>
   Stinking.
</P>
<P>
   Debilitating.
</P>
<P>
   Disgusting.
</P>
<P>
   Hell.
</P>
<P>
   I turn on National Public Radio and hear that the latest heat
wave torturing the East and Midwest has killed 49 people.
</P>
<P>
   Crops are withering in fields. Pennsylania has an official
drought emergency. Relief workers in Iowa are passing out electric
fans and opening air-conditioned shelters.
</P>
<P>
   In Cincinnati, it has been above 90 degrees for more than a
week. Four people in St. Louis died in one day when the temperature
peaked at 102. Everywhere the demand for power is off the charts.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, the branches of my neighbors' trees whip in
the wind. The sky above them is the color of wallpaper paste.
</P>
<P>
   Near my deck, a jasmine vine _ recently transplanted from a
warm, sunny clime _ looks as if it's passed through some Star Trek
wormhole and ended up in an alien galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   I pull on jeans, a turtleneck, thick cotton socks, hiking boots
and a heavy cardigan sweater. Because I'll be on public transit all
day, including late afternoon when the Pacific fog shoves its way
into town, I grab a big scarf.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1975, shortly before I moved to California, I was living
in New York City. I'd grown up in Indiana and once spent what a
boyfriend labeled an ``oppressive'' summer in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   All I knew about June, July and August were heat and humidity.
</P>
<P>
   But that final East Coast summer was a lulu and moved me to
write in my journal: ``God. Merciful rainstorm. I can't remember
when I've been so conscious of the heat, day in and day out. I
dread it at night, hours before I go to bed, anticipating the soggy
sheets and dozens of awakenings. When I finally admit defeat in the
morning and get out of bed, I mentally sort through my closet and
try to find the coolest thing to hang on my back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life here at the equator. Fitzgerald's reference to a time so
hot one didn't care `whose flushed lips he kissed, whose head made
damp the pajama pocket over his heart.' Maybe it's quite the right
time to be moving to seasonless San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, I remember it well: Pantyhose that felt as if they were
literally growing into my legs, like some moist synthetic skin
graft. Rivulets of sweat trickling down my sternum, forking left
and right under each breast, then running headlong into the
rivulets coming down from under my arms.
</P>
<P>
   Hair, always damp and stringy and in my face. Hands sticky,
nails gritty. Fingers and ankles swollen. Every crease, from the
top of my ears to between my toes, a mini-salt water marsh.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the stench from the subway and streets. Any
garbage more than two hours old had the olfactory force of a
decomposing corpse. Dog doo was so potent it was like smelling in
Day-Glo. The anti-perspirants of stockbrokers and even fashion
models were useless; no old lady's talcum powder had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Shirt lacquered to my back, I'd walk into my Midtown office, a
bank or a bar, and swoon in relief at the meat-locker climate.
</P>
<P>
   Then (especially if it was a bar), I'd forget about the real
world until I walked out and felt as if I were standing under the
afterburners of a Titan rocket.
</P>
<P>
   And it lasted, day after day, for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, strolling toward the 24th Street BART station,
I can't help but notice all the fleece zip-ups, sweatshirts,
leather jackets and tweed sportcoats. Descending the station steps,
I watch three maintenance workers repairing a broken escalator.
They wear windbreakers.
</P>
<P>
   A street musician, dressed in a dark leather jacket, felt hat
and pants, stands outside the BART turnstiles, singing ``(Sittin'
On) the Dock of the Bay.'' A chill wind creeps through my sweater
and blows my hair into my mouth.
</P>
<P>
   I smile.
</P>
<P>
   Another lousy summer day in paradise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
