<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-RICHARDS _ Former Gov. Ann Richards, the first Democrat to
lose to him, says the best way to go after George W. Bush is not
to. ``I wouldn't pay any attention to the opponent,'' Richards said
when he asked for her advice on how to run against Bush. As Bush
looks more and more like the inevitable GOP nominee, the Democrats
are scrambling for the most effective way of running against him.
So far, the Gore camp has adopted a relatively low-key, subtle
approach. But the Democratic National Committee, ignoring Richards
advice and perhaps foreshadowing what's to come, is mounting a
full-frontal assault. A look at the Democratic strategy for beating
Bush, an early front-runner in this earliest of election campaigns.
(Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   GARYBAUER-BUSH _ The former editorial page editor of the
Manchester (N.H.) Union Leader, which regularly wrote scathing
editorials about George W. Bush, is now heading up Bush rival Gary
Bauer's campaign in New Hampshire. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BALKANS _ SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzogovina _ President
Clinton arrives Friday in the capital that introduced most of the
world to Balkan bloodshed. The mission this time is peace, as
Clinton and his counterparts from more than three dozen countries
gather to map out a blueprint for knitting the region back into the
fabric of south-central Europe. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: This story was budgeted for Thursday papers but is still
good for use on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-DEATHPENALTY _ JERUSALEM _ After two cases in which
fathers killed their children, a few shocked Israelis made a call
for the country to start using the death penalty against murderers.
But, the suggestion was rejected with barely a debate as Israel,
despite a history of terrorist attacks and a rising crime rate,
seems decisively against the form of punishment that is so
prevalent in the United States. Israel has only used the death
penalty once in its 51-year-history. That was to execute senior
Nazi SS leader Adolf Eichmann under a law concerning crimes against
humanity. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-SPENDING _ WASHINGTON _ A massive influx of funds to
expand and renovate the nation's airports is flying a holding
pattern in Congress. Some budget-minded senators are objecting to
the $57 billion House-passed measure that exempts airport
improvements from spending caps. Action is required by August 6,
when some provisions of the current airport law expire. (Malone,
Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
