<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8629 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-BANKS     07-29 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-BANKS-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON'S SENATE BID MAY HELP WALL STREET BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 1.)  EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee says
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's bid for a U.S. Senate seat may
boost prospects for enactment of legislation allowing banks,
securities and insurance firms to merge.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: Wall Street is drooling for the bill. And the New
York financial community is an important constituency that cannot
be ignored by New York politicians. Mrs. Clinton is revved up to
run for the U.S. Senate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is pretty obvious: If you are running in New York
it's hard to be against this bill,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas,
chairman of the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm recently told a group of industry lobbyists that Mrs.
Clinton's candidacy ``would make it difficult'' for President
Clinton to veto the legislation, as he has threatened to do to the
Senate version of the bill. The White House has signaled approval
of the House version.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said while ``there are still some tough issues'' to work
through, he believes lawmakers will successfully reconcile the
differences between the two bills _ a process that is expected to
begin this week.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would end Depression-era laws that have barred
banks from selling insurance and have limited their ability to sell
stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The main difference between the two bills is that the Senate
version would require banks to set up a separate holding company to
conduct insurance and securities businesses while the House bill
would let banks sell insurance and securities through a bank
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   The difference may seen insignificant, but under the Senate bill
it would mean that the Federal Reserve would become the nation's
main financial services regulator because it oversees bank holding
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House bill, the Treasury Department would maintain its
current role as the supervisor of bank subsidiaries. In fact, banks
could choose whether they want to set up a subsidiary or a separate
holding company, so both the Federal Reserve and the Treasury
Department would continue to have a hand in bank regulation,
depending on how banks decide to organize.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill also would weaken the Community Reinvestment Act
that requires banks to document loans they make in neighborhoods
with large numbers of minorities and low income people _ groups
that have previously been denied access to credit.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, who said he would like to do away with the Community
Reinvestment Act entirely, included a provision in the Senate bill
that would exempt about 4,000 banks with less than $100 million in
assets from CRA rules. Gramm argues that the CRA paperwork burden
is too tough on smaller banks.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, including Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., are strong
supporters of the CRA and believe it has contributed to a rise in
home ownership rates among minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very much want a bill,'' Schumer said. ``But I think you can
have one without'' changing the CRA.
</P>
<P>
   If the proposed CRA changes are left out of the final bill, some
lawmakers and lobbyists believe the White House may cave in on
provisions that favor the Federal Reserve over the Treasury
Department as the main regulator of the new financial services
conglomerates that would be created as a result of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department is part of the executive branch while
the Federal Reserve is independent of the White House and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats support President Clinton's position that would
maintain Treasury's financial services regulatory role along with
that of the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said he would back the bill regardless of which federal
regulator is chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York wants this bill,'' Schumer said. He said he has not
spoken with Mrs. Clinton about the bank bill.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Guenther, the top lobbyist for the Independent Bankers
Association of America, said Mrs. Clinton's candidacy ``could make
a difference'' in getting the White House to abandon its quest to
protect the Treasury Department's role as a financial services
regulator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street wants this bill in the worst way,'' Guenther said,
noting that the financial services industry in New York would
provide campaign contributions to Mrs. Clinton and anyone else
running for the seat being vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
D-N.Y., regardless of party.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Mrs. Clinton's campaign, the prospects for
enactment of the financial services legislation are better than
they have been in the past 20 years. This year's House and Senate
votes mark the first time that both chambers have approved the
measures in the first session of Congress. This will give lawmakers
up to a year and a half to work out the differences between the
bills and get it signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the House approved the bill in May while the Senate
never took it up. Even if it had, lawmakers and lobbyists say there
wasn't enough time to work out the differences between the bills
before Congress ended its two-year session. Once a session ends all
uncompleted legislation dies and the process of enacting it must
start over in a new session of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1437EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8631 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-BANKS     07-29 0918
