<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGILENT-NAME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY SEARCHES THE GLOBE FOR RIGHT NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Air Sick Bag Inc.''
</P>
<P>
   Much to the surprise of Palo Alto-based Hewlett-Packard Co.
executives, that was one foreign translation of a proposed name for
the company's new spin-off corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard avoided that gaffe by hiring San Francisco-based
Landor Associates, the nation's largest branding consultants, to
help name its new company, which carried the working name
``NewCo.''
</P>
<P>
   The result of the $1 million effort led by Landor was that H-P
has announced that it was naming its $8 billion measurements and
medical technology spin-off Agilent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Landor, which has been helping companies pick names for the last
60 years, is responsible for such corporate titles as FedEx, the
overnight shippers, and Lucent, the technology research company
formerly known as Bell Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   According to Agilent Vice President Bill Hahn, the quest to find
a name for the new company began shortly after H-P's March 2
announcement that it was splitting itself in two.
</P>
<P>
   One company, which manufactures computer hardware and software,
would retain the Hewlett-Packard name. The other company, which
would focus on Hewlett- Packard's less-consumer oriented electronic
measuring and medical equipment, needed a new name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to start off fresh,'' said Hahn, a former H-P
controller. ``So picking the right name was crucial for us.''
</P>
<P>
   An internal Hewlett-Packard contest, along with input from
Landor, generated a list of 2,000 candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Then the list was put through a complex winnowing process.
</P>
<P>
   Names that incorporated the the Hewlett-Packard brand were
eliminated. Next, many candidates were dropped because they could
be found in the dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really isn't any regular word out there that doesn't
have a claim on it already,'' said Peter Harleman, a vice chairman
with Landor. ``The English language is pretty much impossible to
use now.''
</P>
<P>
   The 200 or so candidates that were deemed suitable were then
checked to see if they could legally be used. According to
Harleman, H-P had to clear the names through the legal systems of
the 100 countries where the new company would be conducting
business. The survivors of that process were then put through what
Harleman called the cultural screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brand names can have some interesting and very unintended
meanings overseas,'' said Harleman. ``You definitely don't want to
have a Nova situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Nova situation'' is legendary among brand consultants.
When General Motors debuted its Chevrolet Nova in South America, it
failed to notice that nova means ``It doesn't go'' in Spanish. (Not
to be outdone, Ford Motor Co. didn't check the name of its Fiera
sports car in Latin America, where the name translated into ``ugly
old woman.'')
</P>
<P>
   Proposed names that passed these tests were then put before an
eight-member panel of H-P employees and executives.
</P>
<P>
   Agilent was finally chosen because ``agile'' best reflected the
mandate of the new company, Hahn said. The NT ending, Hahn said,
was added to give the word ``strength and forward motion.'' It also
avoided the quandary of the name's being interpreted as feminine or
masculine overseas by adding an ``e'' or ``a'' ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agilent is now like an adverb,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The final name ``was exactly what we want people to think about.
It didn't oversell the company, and it spoke to our mission,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It also didn't translate into anything like ``air sick bag.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that we know of,'' Hahn said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Agilent Technologies will become a separate company Nov. 1 with
Edward W. ``Ned'' Barnholt as chief executive officer. It will be
headquartered on the Palo Alto site where H-P was founded 52 years
ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
