<HEADER>
A8646 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODSTOCK-HAVENS-HNS &LR;      07-29 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK-HAVENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SAFE HAVEN FOR WOODSTOCK SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Talking to a standing-room-only crowd at the
Barnes &AMP; Noble, Richie Havens was asked why he thought people
rioted at the latest Woodstock nostalgia concert. Havens, whose act
opened the original Woodstock in 1969, shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason is, it wasn't Woodstock,'' said Havens, who was in
Oakland to introduce his new book, ``they can't hide us anymore,''
written with Steve Davidowitz (Avon Books).
</P>
<P>
   To his mind, said Havens, the real Woodstock will be held in
mid- August on the original site _ Max Yasgur's 600-acre farm _
with the original artists on hand, including Arlo Guthrie, Melanie,
Country Joe MacDonald, John Sebastian and Havens himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was tragic. It didn't have to be that way,'' Havens
said of last weekend's riots, which ended a three-day festival at a
former air base outside Rome, N.Y. He said co-organizer Michael
Lang, one of the original Woodstock organizers, made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the mistake of thinking he put on the first one. The
people put it on,'' said Havens. ``The last two (Woodstock) shows
have been failures because they disrespected that.''
</P>
<P>
   Havens didn't come down hard on youngsters at the concert, in
the wake of a riot that targeted ATM machines and left vendors'
booths and trailers burning. ``They are actually freer than we
are,'' he said. ``They need more space. They need more respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Havens called his autobiography, 25 years in the making, ``they
can't hide us anymore'' because that's the thought that occurred to
him at the first Woodstock, held on Yasgur's farm outside Bethel,
N.Y., as Havens was being flown in a bubble-front helicopter over
hundreds of thousands of people to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking below my feet at all those people and I thought,
`They can't hide us anymore,''' he said. ``And you know, they still
can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Havens was supposed to be the fifth act of the concert. But the
refusal of others to go first, and the inability to get It's a
Beautiful Day out to the stage in time, sent Havens out after a
delay of almost four hours. He started a set that was supposed to
go 20 minutes with ``Minstrel from Gault'' and kept singing as the
set grew to 40 minutes and more.
</P>
<P>
   Havens left the stage half a dozen times, only to be pressed
back to fill the gaps in music. By the seventh time, Havens ran out
of songs and improvised ``Freedom'' to a driving backbeat. It set a
tone for Woodstock and left Havens feeling that ``Bethel was such a
special place, a moment when we all felt we were at the exact
center of true freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Blackfoot Native American father and mother from
Barbados, Havens grew up in Brooklyn during the 1940s and '50s,
``doing doo-wop on the street corner with my buddies, getting water
thrown on us, all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Havens moved on to the Greenwich Village music scene, meeting
later-to-be-famous names, from Bob Dylan to James Baldwin, as the
'50s wound down. He still makes his home in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Havens opened his presentation at Barnes &AMP; Noble by playing
``All Along the Watchtower'' on a guitar he brought with him, his
foot thrumming time on the floor. The audience, 100-plus stuffed
into a corner of the store, fell silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to sing this six times a day back in the Village, seven
days a week, seven years in a row,'' he said. Then Dylan got the
words of the song from Havens, and ``I stopped singing it because
my friend recorded the definitive version.''
</P>
<P>
   But lately youngsters are asking him to do the song, said
Havens. Holding an arm out waist-high, he said, ``They're this big,
and I ask them where they heard this song and they say, `Oh, I've
got my grandma's records.' `Grandma?' Couldn't they at least say
`Mom's records?'''
</P>
<P>
   Havens delighted a mixed crowd of gray-hairs, longhairs and no-
hairs with three songs and a walk down memory lane. Looking much
the same as he did in the days of his 1968 album ``Something Else
Again'' _ rings on every finger, hair in a ponytail, shy smile on
his face _ Havens said, ``Some people called me a folk singer ... a
folk- rock singer, a folk-jazz singer, a folk-blues singer. I just
call myself a song singer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on tour since December of '67,'' said Havens. ``I
say it as a joke, but it's true. I did get to see the changes
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Havens built his autobiography up and tore it down over the past
quarter of a century, settling on a weekly tape session with writer
Davidowitz to get it finished. ``He came over every Tuesday, wound
up with 100 hours of tapes,'' said Havens.
</P>
<P>
   He tells his story, as might be expected, with great sweeps of
emotion and constant kindnesses to the people around him.
</P>
<P>
   Insights into the top music figures of the time are there, from
Elvis to Janis Joplin to Jimi Hendrix, and Havens writes a lament
for both the mistakes of drug use and the mistakes of the
government's war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   There are times when ``they can't hide us anymore'' gets too
airy for its own good, as when Havens waxes poetic about the
Natural Guard, a group of youngsters heading to Washington to teach
politicians the true way, and when he argues for a fleet of baby
seals to be taught how to release the safety belts of passengers
trapped inside airplanes downed in rivers and seas.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, Havens stays surprisingly down to
Earth, as he did Tuesday night at Barnes &AMP; Noble. There will never
be a bigger champion of the Woodstock ethic than Havens, who told
the bookstore crowd the first concert ``was the biggest
non-negative get-together we have seen, to this day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
