<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLD-SOUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLD SOUP ON A HOT DAY IS VERY COOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   About the last thing anyone wants to do on an 80-degree day is
simmer a pot on the stove for several hours. But not all soups need
to be simmered and served hot.
</P>
<P>
   The harvest of summer produce brings with it the ability to make
cold, refreshing dishes that just happen to be liquid and served in
a bowl: soup.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike winter soups and stews, summer versions aren't cooked for
long, or even at all. While that means the kitchen _ and the cook _
stay cool, there's no processing to bring out the ingredients'
flavors. This means the soup is only going to taste as good as the
ingredients you use. Therefore, buy the ripest, most flavorful
ingredients you can find.
</P>
<P>
   If the soup is served with chunks of vegetables, cut the
ingredients by hand, writes James Peterson in his book ``Soups.''
Food processors and blenders tend to over-process ingredients,
creating a mushy texture instead of a chunky one with the contrasts
of the vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   To make Peterson's gazpacho, a flavorful soup based on fresh
tomatoes, use the following method:
</P>
<P>
   Peel, seed and chop 8 large, ripe tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Place in a large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Peel 3 cloves garlic, mince and then mash them with salt until
paste-like.
</P>
<P>
   Add to tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Chop 2 large sweet onions, 2 cucumbers, 2 yellow bell peppers
and 2 jalapeno peppers (optional).
</P>
<P>
   Add chopped ingredients to tomatoes as you go.
</P>
<P>
   Add in the juice of 3 limes, a pinch of cayenne pepper, salt and
pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Serve drizzled with olive oil and topped with croutons.
</P>
<P>
   Pass hot pepper sauce and extra chopped vegetables if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Summer fruits are also excellent for making soups such as in
this recipe for Santa Fe Chilled Nectarine Soup from the California
Tree Fruit Agreement (a promotional group for that state's peach,
nectarine and plum producers):
</P>
<P>
   Combine 1 pound cut up nectarines, 1/2 cup apple juice, 1/2 cup
cranberry-raspberry juice, 1/4 teaspoon salt, 1/4 teaspoon red
pepper flakes and 1 1/2 teaspoons balsamic vinegar in a blender.
</P>
<P>
   Process until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Add 2 tablespoons fresh cilantro leaves and process to chop.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate until serving.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish with lime slices.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 (1-cup) servings.
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't have some of the ingredients on hand, don't
sweat. You can always substitute peaches for nectarines, green
peppers for yellow peppers and wine vinegar for balsamic. After
all, taking it easy is the way you should make cold soup in the
first place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1541EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8692 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRIDE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     07-29 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RUNAWAY BRIDE': PRETTY WOMAN IS BACK, BUT NOW SHE'S CAUTIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nine years after sparkling her way through ``Pretty Woman,''
Julia Roberts has come a long way from that streetwalker's role.
She's come so far in ``Runaway Bride'' that she plays a woman who
runs a hardware store and looks perpetually ready to fix a sink.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the kind of folksy Maryland town that has quaint
hand-painted signs and not a single chain store, this new
collaboration between the stars and director of ``Pretty Woman''
takes pains, geographically and otherwise, to get as far away from
Rodeo Drive as it can. The small town's streets are even roamed by
a barbershop quartet.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ``Pretty Woman'' bloom is definitely off the rose as
Ms. Roberts plays a pale, stern woman with an incongruously
screwball-type problem. It seems that her character, Maggie
Carpenter, is altar-phobic. She avoids her own weddings in a way
that makes for nifty one-liners (``May the groom's heart be full of
hope and the bride's feet be full of lead!'') and even newspaper
headlines (``Hardware Honey Goes Nuts and Bolts'').
</P>
<P>
   This is an even worse problem than the one with which Ms.
Roberts grappled in ``Notting Hill'' (being famous). And maybe it's
not as funny as it's supposed to look.
</P>
<P>
   But Garry Marshall smoothly turns Maggie's little kink into
big-screen sitcom fodder, just as he managed to put a nice spin on
the idea of a rich, powerful Pygmalion buying a Hollywood Boulevard
hooker to redo. Richard Gere returns, this time in the smiling nice
guy's role, to rekindle some of the earlier film's warm glow.
</P>
<P>
   His and Marshall's reunion with Ms. Roberts guarantees a comedy
that's easy on the eyes and dependable in the laugh department. But
``Runaway Bride'' also, like Maggie, shows signs of strain.
Chemistry-wise, it can't bode well for a romantic comedy to feature
two stars who apparently posed for the poster art on separate days.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the film there's a glimpse of Gere and Ms. Roberts
having a great time playing cards together. But it flashes by
quickly as part of a standard feel-good montage, and it leaps out
as the rare spontaneous moment in a largely mechanical romp.
</P>
<P>
   More often, the film is like a ride through a car wash: forward
motion, familiar phases in the same old order and a sense of being
carried along steadily on a well-used track. It works without
exactly showing signs of life.
</P>
<P>
   Gere plays a veteran newspaper columnist. We know he's an old
pro because a) he's named Ike, b) he's chummy with workmen in the
street and c) he's right at home at the local bar. If an audience
buys that, is it a big leap to the idea that Ike's entire
professional future hangs on his investigation of Maggie's habit of
jilting her fiances?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes. But the movie packs Ike off to Hale, Md., anyway so
he can follow Maggie around in a state of Act I animosity. Only the
barbershop quartet's harmonies are as sure as the promise that by
Act II or III the ice will melt.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Ms. Roberts does let her hair down and start turning
the world on with her smile. But it takes a while for that to
happen. Much of the film's first hour is devoted to Ike's Cheshire
Cat-like ability to turn up grinning anywhere in Hale, and Maggie's
annoyance over his presence.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay by Josann McGibbon and Sara Parriott is much
better on delivering zingers and developing minor characters than
it is on plotting. It also locks no-nonsense Maggie and misogynist
Ike into a stale battle of the sexes that isn't much fun.
</P>
<P>
   But Marshall does know when to let the stars turn on their high
beams and keep the film's secondary characters amusing and bright.
These include Paul Dooley as Maggie's father, who dryly says things
like: ``Wedding cake freezes. This we know.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Meloni has some funny moments as the latest
unfortunate fiance, the jock who plans to coach Maggie through a
wedding ceremony as if it were a sporting event. Joan Cusack makes
a dependably tart best friend for Maggie, Laurie Metcalf runs the
local bakery and Jean Schertler plays Maggie's grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Aficionados of mainstream nuptial comedy will not be surprised
to hear Grandma ogling young men and saying funny, raunchy things
about the wedding night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Runaway Bride'' does a smooth job of working Ike into this
down-home crowd. So it isn't long before the nicely ubiquitous Gere
is jamming on the guitar with Hale's mayor and sheriff, wearing a
Hale football jacket, etc. Maggie resents this; then the story
gives her and Ike nighttime car trouble on a deserted country road
by moonlight and of course things start to change.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, they have one of those arguments in which each
character sums up the other in a tidy nutshell. (Maggie to Ike:
``All you do is tear others down and laugh at them and criticize
what they do because you're too afraid to do anything yourself!'')
And at last Ms. Roberts pulls out all the stops, ready to dazzle
Ike and the viewer as if a peacock were fanning out its feathers on
cue.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's better moments are the ones that escape this
pattern, like a glimpse of Maggie's first near-wedding, the one
with a Grateful Dead motif. (Ms. Cusack is seen with a tambourine.)
There's also a Federal Express joke so good that it constitutes a
best case scenario for product plugs, in a line delivered by Hector
Elizondo, another ``Pretty Woman'' veteran.
</P>
<P>
   He plays the man who replaced Ike in the affections of Ike's
ex-wife, played bluntly by Rita Wilson. Honk if you guess that the
ex-wife happens to be Ike's newspaper editor too.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `RUNAWAY BRIDE' is rated PG (Parents strongly cautioned). It
includes mild profanity and nothing terribly unsuitable for
children.
</P>
<P>
   `RUNAWAY BRIDE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Garry Marshall; written by Josann McGibbon and Sara
Parriott; director of photography, Stuart Dryburgh; edited by Bruce
Green; music by James Newton Howard; production designer, Mark
Friedberg; produced by Ted Field, Tom Rosenberg, Scott Kroopf and
Robert Cort; released by Touchstone Pictures and Paramount
Pictures. Running time: 110 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Julia Roberts (Maggie Carpenter), Richard Gere (Ike
Graham), Joan Cusack (Peggy), Hector Elizondo (Fisher), Rita Wilson
(Ellie), Paul Dooley (Walter), Christopher Meloni (Coach Bob),
Laurie Metcalf (Mrs. Trout) and Jean Schertler (Grandma Julia).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
