u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-DEATHPENALTY-0     07-29 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-DEATHPENALTY-0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EVEN AFTER BRUTAL MURDERS, ISRAELIS NOT FAVORING DEATH PENALTY
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A crime shocked Israel this week as it would any
other country: A father stabbed and strangled to death his wife and
two toddlers.
</P>
<P>
   But, the minority calls for the death penalty were quickly
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the terrorism of the past or horrible domestic crimes of
the present, Israel chooses to do without the capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, only one man has been executed in the 51-year history
of the state. In 1962, Nazi SS officer Adolf Eichmann, who had been
captured in hiding by Israeli agents, was hanged for organizing the
deportation of hundreds of thousands of European Jews to death
camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``They felt the enormity of the offenses was so great that a
sort of cosmic justice required his execution,'' explained Ruth
Gavison, law professor at Jerusalem's Hebrew University and a civil
rights activist.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Israel's view of capital punishment was apparent in
this week's reaction to the case of Amnon Cohen, accused of killing
his wife and children.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Leeron, director of the government's Authority on the
Status of Women, created a stir by saying on Israeli radio that the
case required the death penalty. It would show, she said, that the
government is serious about domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have another solution,'' Leeron later told the Cox
News Service. She said domestic violence is increasing, and that
men who murder their wives act in a ``calculated'' manner. ``They
are not violent at work. They are only violent with their wives,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But, her radio comments brought quick rebuttals from Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak, Justice Minister Yossi Beilin and State
Prosecutor Edna Arbel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those proposing to impose the death penalty on killers of
wives and children are making populist statements that don't bring
a real solution to the problem,'' Beilin was reported as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Another case Thursday seemed to reiterate the country's
sentiment. A military court sentenced a Palestinian terrorist to
three life sentences and 15 years for the murder of a settler rabbi
and a series of other attacks. Some settlers and the victim's
family wanted a death sentence, though not even the prosecutor had
requested it.
</P>
<P>
   Military law allows the death penalty of terrorists and in
several cases military judges have ordered executions. However,
each time, the sentences were either overturned by appeals courts
or military commanders simply refused to carry them out.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli military leaders see the death penalty as problematic.
Executions, they maintain, create martyrs and could provoke revenge
attacks that would endanger Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Though many Israelis support a limited death penalty, they are
much cooler to the idea than Americans. Polls often show 70 percent
of Americans favoring the death penalty and more than 350
executions have been carried out since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, where crime is less frequent, the death penalty has
less support, though polls were not available.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a cultured nation. We don't need this,'' said Israeli
Ruth Sheinfeld, a 79-year-old retired agricultural worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a religious person and I believe it is God who decides
the fate of people,'' said Yair Sinai, a 29-year-old teacher and
Orthodox Jew. ``We don't talk about this much. We talk all the time
about security and peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli view could be seen as somewhat contradictory. The
death penalty is eschewed, but the government has resorted to
commando assassinations of terrorists, seen as a way to protect
Israelis from their schemes.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israeli experts point out that their country is in line
with growing numbers of countries that are abolishing the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is way out in left field,'' said Leon Sheleff, a
sociology professor at Tel Aviv University and a death penalty
opponent. ``There's almost no chance of it being changed here.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
