<SLUG> BC-FALLS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TWIN FALLS IDAHO': TALE OF A MENAGE A TROIS, WITH THE EMPHASIS ON
DEUX 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)``Twin Falls Idaho'' was shown as part of this year's
New Directors/New Films series in New York. Following are excerpts
from Janet Maslin's review, which appeared in The New York Times on
April 9. The film opens Friday in Manhattan.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   An eerily effective film, ``Twin Falls Idaho'' takes the
real-life closeness of the identical twins Michael and Mark Polish
into the realm of haunting fantasy. These arrestingly gaunt,
watchful-looking brothers star in the film as conjoined twins,
Blake (Mark) and Francis (Michael) Falls, whose delicately balanced
interdependence provides a rare brand of tension.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which the Polish brothers wrote and Michael directed,
begins as the twins encounter a wild, gorgeous young woman named
Penny (Michele Hicks, a former model) in an interestingly desolate
hotel. It's a setting that the cinematographer, M. David Mullen,
photographs with bleak and painterly precision.
</P>
<P>
   And it is here that the brothers' differences begin to emerge,
with Blake as the stronger figure and the one most powerfully drawn
to Penny. Imagine how a Siamese twin might conduct a courtship, and
imagine this rendered with intense acuity and no gimmicks.
</P>
<P>
   Because Francis is the weaker and more dependent of the two, and
because the situation's menage a trois possibilities are
unavoidable, the film explores aspects of symbiotic relationships
that nonconjoined viewers will easily understand.
</P>
<P>
   It also has strong, offbeat atmosphere and a richly perverse
sense of mischief where the twins are concerned. A pivotal part of
the film unfolds on Halloween, when the Falls boys impress
strangers with their marvelous costume (a two-armed, three-legged
suit) and attend a party where they seem like the most normal
people in the room. Though the twins have done time as a circus
attraction, the film itself never treats them like freaks.
</P>
<P>
   With an especially affecting performance by Mark Polish as the
story's dominant figure, and with Ms. Hicks a striking kohl-eyed
presence even when she struggles with the story's more demanding
scenes, ``Twin Falls Idaho'' has style, gravity and originality to
spare.
</P>
<P>
   It's a film that dwells as hauntingly on loneliness as it does
on never actually being able to be alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1601EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      07-29 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INTIMATE UNIVERSE: THE HUMAN BODY': COMPELLING BUT OCCASIONALLY
DEPRESSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   So much for the spiritual significance of those near-death
experiences. The tunnel and the light that people talk about seeing
has something to do with vision-control neurons firing at random.
And the sense of euphoria and inner peace just comes from various
brain chemicals at work. The same thing happens to test pilots
undergoing ``gravity-induced loss of consciousness'' in the
centrifuge.
</P>
<P>
   As for the dream of middle age _ turning back the clock by
shaping up now with the right diet and exercise _ forget it. The
body is just a big photocopying machine (making new cells that are
supposed to be duplicates of the existing cells), and it tends to
make inferior copies. Taking better care of the machine now might
help slow down the deterioration of future copies, but it couldn't
turn the process back to copying from the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intimate Universe: The Human Body'' isn't just award-winning
television; it's depressing. At least the last few episodes, which
are being shown on the Learning Channel on Sunday and Monday
nights, are.
</P>
<P>
   In the first, ``The Brain,'' the series' host, Dr. Robert
Winston, even drinks a lot of wine to establish once and for all
that alcoholic beverages don't make people more charming and
amusing than before. After a bottle or so, in fact, Winston can't
remember his lines and can't quite pronounce the word
``belligerent.''
</P>
<P>
   The photocopier analogy comes from ``As Time Goes By,'' the
episode about aging. Bud and Viola, a farm couple who met almost 50
years ago, are the living examples of the effects of aging, which
is described as ``one of the greatest paradoxes of human biology''
and ``probably a genetic accident.'' When the couple pay their
first visit to New York and seem a little rattled while trying to
navigate its busy streets, a voice-over explains that the brain, as
it gets older, ``has to work harder to make sense of the limited
information it's getting from the outside world'' and ``this means
fewer brain cells for memory and decision-making and might account
for the confusion, especially in strange and noisy places.''
</P>
<P>
   And the scientific explanations of the frequently reported
near-death phenomena come from the penultimate episode, ``Life's
Last Chapter,'' in which Herbie, a charming German man living in
Ireland, invites cameras in to watch as he slowly dies from
inoperable stomach cancer. Although basic medical information is
imparted (``Hearing is the last thing to go''), the fascination _
and the real learning _ is in observing Herbie's psychological
preparations for death.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in ``The Making of `Intimate Universe: The Human
Body,'' the filmmakers take viewers behind the scenes for a look at
the show's use of scanning electron miscroscopes, motion-control
cameras, thermal imaging, endoscopy and other technology. The
series began earlier this year with four other episodes _ on
pregnancy, babies, teen-agers and the average human lifetime _
which will be shown again Saturday night at 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intimate Universe'' has flaws. At times, the use of people
like Bud and Viola to illustrate universal truths seems
self-consciously folksy and predictable. And there are only so many
ways you can make an explanation of the development of the
opposable thumb interesting. But just as often, the series does
something brilliant, like showing microscopic hair cells in the ear
actually dancing to ``Rock Around the Clock'' (then how is it
possible that we don't all have rhythm?) or showing several views
of Monet's famous bridge at Giverny that teach as much about
Impressionism as about eye disease. If everybody had had science
classes this compelling, we'd probably have cured cancer by now.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `INTIMATE UNIVERSE: The Human Body'
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Channel, Sunday and Monday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   Last four episodes of an eight-part series co-produced by TLC
and the BBC: Andrew Thompson, producer and director for ``Brain
Power'' ; John Groom, producer of ``As Time Goes By''; Christopher
Spencer, producer and director for ``Life's Last Chapter,'' and
Liesel Evans, producer of ``The Making of `Intimate Universe''';
first four episodes: Richard Dale, producer and director for ``Life
Story''; Emma De'Ath and Liesel Evans, producer and director for
``Building a Baby.''; Thompson, producer and director for ``First
Steps''; Peter Georgi, producer and director for ``Raging Teens'';
Sandra Gregory and Susan Winslow, executive producers for TLC;
Dale, series producer for the BBC; Alan Bookbinder and Lorraine
Heggessey, executive producers for the BBC. Dr. Robert Winston,
series host  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
