<HEADER>
A8748 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1S     07-29 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Thursday, July 29, 1999     
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following for
Friday and Sunday.. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Mark Helm at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: TEACHING-DOCTORS; BUSH-CONFIDENCE; BALKAN-SUMMIT;
MATCHMAKER-ROOMMATES; BROWN-UNITY and FOOD-LAWSUIT)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BALKAN-SUMMIT (Sarajevo, Bosnia) _ President Clinton and
European leaders gather in Sarajevo to confer on economic aid for
the Balkans and to structure a plan to help stabilize the
war-wracked region. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CONFIDENCE (Houston) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, with $37
million in the bank and a commanding lead in the polls, is
campaigning like the primaries are already over, despite his claims
that he ``takes nothing for granted.'' By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE-SECT (Washington) _ Li Hongzhi, the U.S.-based founder
of an outlawed sect in China, will not be extradited because
Washington and Beijing don't have a reciprocal extradition treaty.
China has banned the group and on Thursday ordered Li's arrest. By
ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   HURD-NOMINATION (Washington) _ David Hurd is likely to be
confirmed as a U.S. District Court judge for the northern district
of New York. Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., predicts ``clear
sailing'' for his confirmation vote in the Senate Judiciary
Committee, which could come today. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHING-DOCTORS (Washington) _ When aspiring doctors do their
residency at Beth Israel Medical Hospital in New York City, the
institution receives more than $57,000 annually for each resident
from Medicare to defray the cost of training. But if the same
residents were to train at Houston's Memorial Hermann Hospital, the
Medicare program would pay the Texas hospital $6,924 for each
doctor. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MATCHMAKER-ROOMMATES (Austin, Texas) _ University of Texas
students living on campus may soon be able to steer clear of
roommates from hell by applying a new solution to an age-old
problem. Student leaders and campus housing officials are
developing an on-line matchmaking service that's set to debut in
December. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES
</P>
<P>
   BROWN-UNITY (Houston) _ Houston Mayor Lee Brown, the nation's
former drug czar, is calling black and Hispanic elected officials
together this weekend for a ``unity breakfast'' in an effort to
shut down a growing rift between the two groups. By JULIE MASON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-LAWSUIT (Houston) _ Gene Chung's Asian food company, which
has been recognized as one of Houston's best start-ups, nearly went
bankrupt when a competitor stole its biggest client. Now the
founder of Chung's Gourmet Foods has won a $14.5 million judgment
against Minh Food Co., one of the nation's largest egg roll makers.
By SHANNON BUGGS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton's uniform has
become the natty, tailored pants suit, reflecting not only a daring
sartorial change for a first lady but the national trend toward
casual dressing. Her predecessors were never seen in anything but
skirts, but she is being cheered rather than criticized. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON-BANKS (Washington) _ already filed _ Senate
Banking Committee Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas, says First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton's bid for a U.S. Senate seat may boost
prospects for enactment of legislation that would allow banks,
securities and insurance firms to merge. By JENNIFER CORBETT
DOOREN. Story was also be filed in the FINANCIAL-BUSINESS NEWS
(``f'') category.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-WINE (Washington) _ The wine industry is fighting
legislation aimed at stopping teen-agers from ordering its products
over the Internet, contending it will hurt small vintners trying to
make sales on the World Wide Web and through mail-order catalogues
to adults. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. Story will also be filed in
the FINANCIAL-BUSINESS NEWS (``f'') category.
</P>
<P>
   RIVLIN-FED (Washington) _ Alice Rivlin, once told by Harvard's
public service school that women need not apply, has had
high-profile government jobs that many Harvard grads can only dream
of holding. Rivlin, who just stepped down as vice chairman of the
Federal Reserve, looks back on three decades of public service. By
JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
