A8751 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CASTCHANGES-HNS &LR;      07-29 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CASTCHANGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCORECARD MIGHT COME IN HANDY FOR FALL TV CAST CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Everything we know we learned from the TV
critics press tour: You need a program to track the cast changes
for the fall. But we know this much: Heather Locklear is going to
become a cast member on ``Spin City.''
</P>
<P>
   That probably won't help in toning down all the relentless sex
jokes of this once-stellar show.
</P>
<P>
   Nikki Cox, former star of ``Unhappily Ever After'' on The WB _
the only show known better for its Internet sites devoted to Cox's
body than actual episodes _ will join the cast of ABC's ``Norm''
show.
</P>
<P>
   Probably no sex jokes there, either.
</P>
<P>
   So much for Ellen DeGeneres' retirement from Hollywood. She's
developing a pilot for CBS. She better finish it in a hurry _ that
network's fall programming looks painfully bad.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca DeMornay may be joining the cast of ``ER,'' mostly
because the hospital hit needs some life. Already, Maura Tierney
(``NewsRadio'') has joined the cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``NYPD Blue'' executive producer Paris Barclay joked that the
networks are suddenly so desperate to cover for their fall
whitewash that they'll be having open auditions in Compton.
</P>
<P>
   He made those comments Wednesday on ``Good Morning America,''
shot live here at the hotel _ which made for a 4 a.m. appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ABC flew the cast out and worked endlessly to turn part of the
hotel into a studio. But when the critics got a chance to talk to
Diane Sawyer and Charlie Gibson on Tuesday, they virtually had
nothing to say.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer didn't answer questions as to why she took two personal
days off as the JFK Jr. story broke. This only fueled charges that
high-profile, highly paid national news anchors have become
celebrities themselves and are too chummy with the people they
cover.
</P>
<P>
   The ``GMA'' producers didn't talk about a new set being built in
Times Square (see, you've got to have big windows if you're a
morning show in New York) or what it would look like. And everyone
was too afraid to say whether CBS's ``Early Show'' with Bryant
Gumbel was causing lost sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Which prompted the question: Why the hell are you here wasting
our time?
</P>
<P>
   TCI is changing its name to AT&AMP;T Cable. So when we complain
about not getting The Cartoon Network or The Food Network or ESPN2,
can we also complain about our long-distance bills?
</P>
<P>
   Why it took Latinos this long to get organized and complain
about a lack of roles in Hollywood is confusing. Don't they know
that the TV industry is reflexive, and that all those new roles are
going to African Americans first, because executives down here
don't ``get'' the problem?
</P>
<P>
   Sample question from next year: ``We see you've added a lot of
black actors. What are you going to do about the Latino audience?''
</P>
<P>
   Sample network answer: ``Isn't Cheech Marin on `Nash Bridges'?''
</P>
<P>
   If only that were a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Asians also need to step to the plate. God love Sammo Hung, but
do you really want Middle America to think that's who you are?
</P>
<P>
   Looks like the honeymoon could be over for David Kelley, the
golden boy producer who gave us ``Ally McBeal'' and ``The
Practice.'' His half-hour version of ``Ally'' looks to be nothing
more than a money grab, because he acknowledged that half-hour
shows make more money in syndication (and the ``new'' episodes will
be repackaged starting from the very first show, then run
chronologically).
</P>
<P>
   Plus he got a lot of ``Chicago Hope'' cast members mad by
writing them out of the show on last year's finale. And now he has
developed ``Snoops'' for ABC, which has met with massive critical
disinterest down here.
</P>
<P>
   At least Michelle Pfeiffer still loves him.
</P>
<P>
   If you're wondering which network will be the first to crumble,
consider this: Chris-Craft, a TV station group that owns half of
UPN, had its second-quarter earnings drop nearly 50 percent, and
the blame went straight to UPN. Better hope the network's wrestling
idea pays off _ and quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Bring me the head of ``Shasta McNasty.''
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, sad news: ``Two Guys, A Girl and a Pizza Place'' is
losing the pizza place. Yes, the kids have grown up and won't be
baking pies anymore, so it's just going to be called ``Two Guys and
a Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   We suggested ``Why Is This Show Still On?'' but it was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The High Fives:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``The Sopranos'' getting all those Emmy nominations. (And
yes, the show will repeat all the original episodes before the next
season, which starts in January).
</P>
<P>
   2. Farrah Fawcett was down here, and she wasn't spacey, like her
infamous Letterman appearance.
</P>
<P>
   3. The same could not be said for ``Ally McBeal'' star Lisa
Nicole Carson, who was lucky she had a limo driver.
</P>
<P>
   4. Quick synopsis of the fall: Too many teens, too many dramas,
but overall not bad.
</P>
<P>
   5. The death march with cocktails is winding down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1629EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
