<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8760 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONDUCT-BOOK-REVIEW-N     07-29 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONDUCT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CONDUCT UNBECOMING A WOMAN': MALPRACTICE OR MISOGYNY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1889, a well-known gynecological surgeon named Mary Dixon
Jones was tried for manslaughter resulting from what prosecutors
said were botched and unnecessary operations. The charges, which
led to a sensational trial, were prompted by a series of newspaper
articles in The Brooklyn Daily Eagle accusing the doctor of gross
malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   After the trial, in which she was acquitted, Dixon Jones sued
the newspaper for libel, prompting an even more spectacular trial
in 1892. By centering on the reputation and methods of one of the
few female surgeons in the United States, the trials opened a
window on the conflicts in values and the deep sexual anxieties
prevalent in the country at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conduct Unbecoming a Woman'' by Regina Morantz-Sanchez, a
historian at the University of Michigan, is a close and probing
examination of these nearly forgotten events. It is a study not
just of the drama of the trials or the struggle of Dixon Jones to
succeed as a surgical innovator in the male world of American
medicine. Ms. Morantz-Sanchez's main purpose is to forge a social
history of late-19th-century medicine. She develops several themes:
the role of newspapers in creating social consciousness; the
conservative ethos that prevailed in Brooklyn in the 1870s and
1880s; the rapid development of gynecology as a speciality, and the
use of radical surgery. But the main idea is this: that the
journalistic and legal assault on Dixon Jones represented
punishment aimed at a woman whose chief offense was to step beyond
the accepted bounds of feminine behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dixon Jones,'' Ms. Morantz-Sanchez writes, ``attained a
professional status unique to her sex at the time, but one that was
bound to be challenged, particularly in a conservative city like
Brooklyn, struggling not only with complex social changes but also
with the various challenges to the medical status quo raised by her
chosen specialty.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morantz-Sanchez is more interested in the scholarly value of
her story than in its inherent drama, and that will make the book
tough going for some readers. Ms. Morantz-Sanchez's writing is not
obscure _ certainly not compared with much of the writing that
appears in academic books these days. But she does lay a level of
theory rather heavily over her narrative, which is bespeckled with
a trendy, abstract, ritualistic boilerplate that will seem strange
to the uninitiated. Phrases like ``mediated symbolic forms,''
``multiple meanings,'' ``medical construction of the female body,''
and the monotonous overuse of words like ``strategies'' and
``negotiate'' are the standard, unoriginal and imprecise components
of academic writing. ``In the next chapter we will see how her
finely tuned antennae helped her negotiate the uncertain waters of
a new speciality in the making,'' Ms. Morantz-Sanchez writes at one
point. Here we have the dubious spectacle of antennae helping to
negotiate waters. There are many such pretentiously clunky
passages.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the story is fascinating, and the analyses thoughtful and
provocative. Ms. Morantz-Sanchez also scrupulously provides all the
relevant, sometimes self-contradictory information, and she invites
the reader to draw different conclusions than her own. The story
begins with a journalistic battle waged over the actions of Dixon
Jones. Even as The Eagle's expose provided lurid details of her
mistreatment of patients, another newspaper, The Citizen, came to
her defense. Ms. Morantz-Sanchez also tells all that is known about
the specific medical complaints against Dixon Jones before
embarking on historical interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   This leads her to a thorough examination of the social and
medical context in which Dixon Jones lived, both as a hard-driving
and ambitious doctor and as a woman. Ms. Morantz-Sanchez describes
Brooklyn in the last third of the 19th century as an especially
conservative society that consciously saw itself as a family- and
church-oriented alternative to sinful and dissolute Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   She then devotes several chapters to medical history, especially
the emergence of surgical gynecology as a specialty. She makes a
persuasive case that surgery was viewed through other prisms than
the purely scientific. Specifically, the use of radical surgery
seemed in those early days not to cure women but to destroy their
ability to bear children, which was seen as a sacred role. ``Cries
of women being `spayed, unsexed, mutilated' were common, and many
conservative practitioners, some of them female, drew parallels
between gynecological surgery and vivisection,'' Ms.
Morantz-Sanchez writes.
</P>
<P>
   And later: ``If the female body stood in for the city in the
minds of Dixon Jones' enemies, then her alleged violation of
patients' bodies represented an even more egregious attack on the
social body _ indeed, on motherhood itself _ and spoke pointedly to
the true nature of her shameful breach of Brooklyn's trust.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as Ms. Morantz-Sanchez makes clear, matters were not so
simple. Questions remain, including: was Dixon Jones persecuted and
prosecuted because of these underlying cultural anxieties or was
she a bad doctor who botched operations? As always, we will find
all the information on this significant question in ``Conduct
Unbecoming a Woman.'' When Ms. Morantz-Sanchez recounts details of
the libel suit, she acknowledges that the evidence presented by the
newspaper was ``overwhelmingly convincing'' and that it was drawn
from ``a staggering number of dissatisfied patients.'' Indeed,
Dixon Jones lost her libel suit.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, in other words, that Dixon Jones committed
malpractice rather than that she was persecuted as a woman
challenging a male preserve. And yet this reader, at least, tends
to side with Ms. Morantz-Sanchez. It seems reasonable that if Dixon
Jones had been a man she would not have been the subject of The
Eagle's expose, and that if surgery had not been so new and
frightening, there would have been no trial. Whatever the case, and
despite the awkwardness of this book's execution, we owe it to Ms.
Morantz-Sanchez for having laid out this rich and absorbing case
for our own deliberation.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CONDUCT UNBECOMING A WOMAN'
</P>
<P>
   Medicine on Trial in Turn-of-the-Century Brooklyn
</P>
<P>
   By Regina Morantz-Sanchez
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 292 pages. Oxford University Press. $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
