<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8781 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS-COUPLES-TEX     07-29 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS-COUPLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SPARKS FLY BETWEEN FILM COUPLES, YOU DON'T NEED AN A+ SCRIPT
FOR SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by COUPLES-LIST) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This weekend, Paramount Pictures is taking a gamble that will
probably pay off. The studio is betting that even though it's been
nearly 10 years since ``Pretty Woman,'' audiences will remember how
fondly they responded to the teaming of Julia Roberts and Richard
Gere, and watch the duo's reunion in ``Runaway Bride.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Roberts and Gere have starred in only one
picture together. ``Bride,'' which opens Friday, is likely to
steamroller that fact and any other obstacle in its way. It'll plow
through Gere's spotty track record in '90s movies, and it'll run
over the way Roberts' offscreen life has been more interesting than
many of her films.
</P>
<P>
   It won't matter that ``Bride'' is, to be kind, haphazardly
written _ from its unrealistic portrayal of Gere's USA Today
columnist to its use of eggs as personality-defining objects _ or
that ``Woman'' director Garry Marshall films ``Bride'' in a style
that's as obsessed with cuteness as a rack of Hallmark cards.
</P>
<P>
   Quality's not the point here; chemistry is. And Gere and Roberts
generated enough chemistry in ``Pretty Woman'' that their teaming
is being touted as the reunion of one of the screen's favorite
romantic couples, putting them in a league with William Powell and
Myrna Loy, Rock Hudson and Doris Day, and Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan.
For fans of ``Woman,'' the reunion of Gere and Roberts will
generate a lot of good will, and that tends to makes audiences
forgive _ or not even notice _ many of a film's flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Romantic teams in movies and TV aren't always saddled with
faulty material, of course; Spencer Tracy and Katharine Hepburn's
movies were of consistently high quality, and Michael Douglas and
Kathleen Turner were served well in the three '80s movies they made
together. But when a script is mediocre, star chemistry can save
it.
</P>
<P>
   It worked for Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan in two movies, the
underwritten ``Sleepless in Seattle'' and the overwritten ``You've
Got Mail''; Hanks' all-American boy and Ryan's perky girl next door
go so well together, it's easy to ignore the morose qualities of
``Sleepless'' and the forced cleverness of ``Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   But there wasn't much Hanks or Ryan could do for the dreary
``Joe vs. the Volcano,'' despite Ryan giving one of her most
interesting performances in a triple role.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their flaws, ``Sleepless'' and ``Mail'' were better
movies than ``Runaway Bride,'' but they still relied more on charm
than depth, and hung their hopes on their star pairing. It was a
wise move, as both were hits and had enough resonance that Hanks
and Ryan are serious contenders for big-screen couple of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   That title could have gone to David Duchovny and Gillian
Anderson, if only they had made more movies. As the stars of ``The
X-Files,'' the duo has been blessed with a wealth of well-written
material. And when ``Files''' writing sags, the combination of
Duchovny's laconic deadpan and Anderson's steel-eyed earnestness
carries the show.
</P>
<P>
   Chemistry like theirs is important in the world of TV, where
even quality shows suffer from the occasional clunky script simply
because of the volume of material being churned out. When you
invite couples into your living room every week, it helps to like
them, and TV has an advantage over movies in that series have more
time to fix their problems and watch their characters grow.
</P>
<P>
   A good example is ``Friends,'' a 5-year-old sitcom that found
new life this past season by pairing Courteney Cox's Monica and
Matthew Perry's Chandler, who actually seemed to be enjoying their
onscreen romance. It was a switch from the mopey bickering that
marked the romance of Ross (David Schwimmer) and Rachel (Jennifer
Aniston). After a promising start, their relationship bogged down
the show, largely because his whininess didn't play well off of her
flaky energy. But the pairing of the relatively grounded Monica
with the wisecracking but insecure Chandler helped the show's
writers bring its scripts to new levels.
</P>
<P>
   TV has all but taken over the idea of serial romantic teams,
from Lucy and Desi in the '50s to ``NYPD Blue's'' Bobby and Diane
in the '90s, and perhaps it's because of TV's ability to spend time
developing its characters. Screen teams, once a staple of the
movies in the days of Bogart &AMP; Bacall and Astaire &AMP; Rogers, have
become increasingly rare. More often than not these days, the
screen teams are male-male couples such as Danny Glover and Mel
Gibson or the eternal Jack Lemmon and Walter Matthau. Pairings like
Gere and Roberts or Hanks and Ryan fill a void, which is why
audiences will ignore anything critics have to say about ``Bride''
and turn it into a huge hit.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1644EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLES-PITTSBURGH-3RD     07-29 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-PITTSBURGH-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PITTSBURGH: the structure.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Richardson whets your appetite for more, walk down Grant
Street. On the way you will see Frick's Union Trust Building
(1915), with a breathtaking stack of nine balconies, crowned by a
round stained-glass skylight, and a froth of terra-cotta turrets,
balustrades, pinnacles and balustrades on the roof; the Koppers
Building (1929), in an urbane Art Deco style, and the USX Building
(1970), a bold tower in Cor-Ten steel, which oxidizes to a deep
red-brown, protecting against deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   The USX Building, by Harrison &AMP; Abramovitz, looks much less
dated than the slightly earlier buildings from the same hands, New
York's Metropolitan Opera House and Avery Fisher Hall at Lincoln
Center. Its exoskeleton of vertical beams is filled with water and
antifreeze as a fire retardant.
</P>
<P>
   In a real sense the USX Building is a continuing advertisement
for the company that built it, once named U.S. Steel. So is the
former Alcoa Building (1953), nearby on Sixth Avenue, whose skin is
formed of preformed aluminum panels, and the glass-faced PPG Place
(1984), on Third Avenue, which was built by a company formerly
called Pittsburgh Plate Glass.
</P>
<P>
   A Cultural Catalyst
</P>
<P>
   No family has done more for Pittsburgh, especially for the arts
in Pittsburgh, than the Heinzes, purveyors to the world of 57
Varieties _ actually, today, more like 5,700. It was H.J. Heinz II,
known as Jack, who had the idea that cultural resources could aid
in jump-starting an economic revival here. He bought four abandoned
movie theaters dowltown and helped turn them into the Cultural
District, anchored by Heinz Hall, home to the Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz Reiner, William Steinberg, Andre Previn and Lorin Maazel
all helped to mold the orchestra's global reputation, but Heinz
dollars balanced the organization's budget. Without them, as Gideon
Toeplitz, the managing director, said several years ago, Pittsburgh
would have ``a small regional orchestra rather like the Wheeling
Symphony just down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, the new home of the Pittsburgh Public Theater will
open across the street from Heinz Hall with a world premiere of a
play by August Wilson, a Pittsburgh native. Designed by Michael
Graves, with a great copper cowl giving its facade a distinctive
appearance, it has a Heinz connection, too. It was partly financed
by the friends of, and named for, Anthony J.F. O'Reilly, H.J. Heinz
Co.'s 's Irish-born chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Next door will stand a fountain designed by Louise Bourgeois.
</P>
<P>
   Drama is a many-layered thing in Pittsburgh. Apart from the
Public Theater and the musicals that also play in the Cultural
District, there are the venturesome City Theater on the South Side
and Karla Boos' lively Quantum Theater, which performs in spaces
either discovered or improvised.
</P>
<P>
   Neither opera nor dance is big-league yet, but the city has an
amazing number of dance organizations, large and small. The most
prominent is the Pittsburgh Ballet Theater, whose artistic
director, Terrence Orr, has steered it away from the Balanchine
tradition toward that of his alma mater, American Ballet Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The Phipps Botanical Gardens, an 1893 gift from Henry Phipps,
one of Carnegie's sidekicks, has a 13-room Victorian conservatory,
one of the finest in the country. And the Frick Art Museum, a
country cousin of the New York showplace, exhibits the collection
of Henry Clay Frick's daughter, Helen; its highlights are a
magisterial Rubens portrait and works by the Sienese masters Duccio
and Sassetta.
</P>
<P>
   Bones and Art
</P>
<P>
   But the heaviest hitters here, in addition to the Symphony, are
the Carnegie and Warhol museums.
</P>
<P>
   The Carnegie complex, in Oakland, east of downtown, includes a
museum of natural history, renowned for its dinosaur collection, as
well as the art museum, headquarters for the International, whose
curator this year is Madeleine Grynsztejn. Since its beginning, the
art museum has concentrated on the art of the 19th and 20th
centuries _ ``the Old Masters of tomorrow,'' as Carnegie himself
put it.
</P>
<P>
   Paintings, sculpture and the decorative arts are intermingled to
good effect in galleries occupied by the permanent collection.
Take, for instance, the room devoted to the Arts and Crafts
Movement; there, furniture by C.F.A. Voysey and Harvey Ellis and
copperware by W.A.S. Benson keep company with two huge, newly
acquired Pre-Raphaelite canvases by Burne-Jones.
</P>
<P>
   First-rate pictures by the likes of Cezanne, Kirchner and Degas
(a smashing portrait of the engineer Henri Rouart) lie ahead. But
most intriguing to me was a selection of pioneer American
abstractionists like Burgoyne Diller, George L.K. Morris and
Stanton Macdonald-Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Over at the Warhol, installed in an old seven-story building
renovated by the New York architect Richard Gluckman, you are
greeted by a big cobalt-blue self-portrait of the artist,
wide-eyed, spiky-haired. The building is filled with Warhol's
collections (milk glass, shoes famous people); Warhol's wallpaper
(I liked the pink-and-yellow cow pattern); Warhol's films; Warhol's
portraits of Mao, Liz and Mick; Warhol's books and Warhol's
archives _ 605 identical boxes filled with everything from the
master pack rat's mail to the original images on which he based his
famous silk screens.
</P>
<P>
   A Pittsburgh native whose parents came from the Carpathian
Mountains in central Europe, Warhol once wrote: ``You live in your
dream America that you've custom-made from art and schmaltz and
emotions just as much as you live in your real one.'' The museum is
Andy's world, custom-recreated.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh has taken to it slowly; Thomas Sokolowski, the
director, says, ``It's a sober city, very Presbyterian.'' Of the
65,000 visitors to the museum last year, half came from out of
state, many from Japan and Germany. But Sokolowski keeps plugging.
He has started a Friday happy hour and has big plans for musical
events, including a staging of the Satie-Poulenc-Ravel triple bill
``Parade,'' as big a scandal in its day as Warhol in his.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS IN 4TH TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
