<HEADER>
A8783 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUPLES-LIST-TEX     07-29 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUPLES-LIST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE COULDN'T TAKE OUR EYES OFF THEM
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies FILMS-COUPLES) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a short list of popular romantic couples through the
decades, and what made them work:
</P>
<P>
   1930s: William Powell and Myrna Loy. Usually, on-screen
chemistry is a matter of clashing styles, but not in the case of
Powell and Loy, who matched each other in sophistication and
repartee in the Thin Man series. Essential movie: ``The Thin Man.''
</P>
<P>
   1940s: Humphrey Bogart and Lauren Bacall. It shouldn't have
worked; Bogart was short and ugly, Bacall sounded like a man, and
their age difference was more than 20 years. But it did, because
Bacall never seemed threatened by Bogart's tough-guy cynicism.
Essential movie: ``To Have and Have Not.''
</P>
<P>
   1950s: Katharine Hepburn and Spencer Tracy. Although they
started in the '40s and worked together in the '60s, Hepburn and
Tracy did the bulk of their best work together in this decade, when
her feisty crackle taught his befuddled curmudgeon a thing or two
about male-female relationships. Essential movie: ``Adam's Rib.''
</P>
<P>
   1960s: Rock Hudson and Doris Day. They really didn't make that
many films together, but the combination of his sensitive hunkiness
and her freckle-faced wholesomeness created a spark that made them
minor romantic-comedy icons. Essential movie: ``Pillow Talk.''
</P>
<P>
   1970s: Woody Allen and Diane Keaton. Until he hooked up with
Soon-Yi Previn, Allen had a way of casting his off-screen loves in
his movies. Keaton was the only one who could hold her own with
him. Her beguiling kookiness was the perfect foil for his uptight
neuroses. Essential movie: ``Annie Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   1980s: Michael Douglas and Kathleen Turner. They only made three
movies together, pairing his long-suffering alpha male with her
strong-willed adventurer. Their strongest work, however, came in
``The War of the Roses,'' which detailed the disintegration of a
marriage in one of the screen's darkest comedies, all the more dark
because they seemed made for each other. Essential film: ``War of
the Roses'' (duh).
</P>
<P>
   1990s: Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan. They've also made three movies
together, and one _ ``Joe vs. the Volcano'' _ was barely watchable.
But although they've done their most interesting work apart,
something special happens when his boy-next-door earnestness gets
together with her girl-next-door perkiness. Essential film:
``Sleepless in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Philpot
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
