<HEADER>
A8788 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      07-29 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERHAPS NOT THE BEST PLACE TO SPEND A COUPLE OF NIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAUNTING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Liam Neeson, Lili Taylor, Catherine Zeta-Jones, Owen Wilson,
Bruce Dern, Marian Seldes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jan De Bont &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 117 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The ad in the paper calls for insomniacs to participate in a
study of sleep disorders, but as the project director, Dr. David
Marrow (Neeson), puts it, what he's really after are several
narcissistic types with low self-esteem to be guinea pigs in his
research on fear and hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   Three applicants are selected and told to report to Hill House,
a menacingly convoluted old pile in the Berkshires. The most
flamboyant of the trio, Theo (Ms. Zeta-Jones), is a woman of many
affairs (bisexual) and a natural foil for the noble Nell (Ms.
Taylor), who makes a career of getting kicked around by abusive
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The third specimen, Luke ( Wilson), is a young man of no
apparent distinction other than his quickness with a quip.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the house. Old man Crain, a textile baron, started
construction 130 years ago and now glowers down from a huge,
unflattering portrait dominating the cavernous central hall. When
life didn't pan out as he envisioned, Crain became a recluse, madly
adding rooms and, it is learned later, doing twisted things to
children who slaved in his factories and were brought to the house
for a ghastly end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get a real strong sleep high from this place,'' Luke
observes early on. That's because a large and virulent
netherworldly presence rumbles and snuffles about, battering doors,
dislodging beams, cracking plaster and waking the dead, who emerge
from cherubic carvings to waft about in the form of Crain's young
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Within a night or so, Marrow, who picked the house for these
very properties, realizes that he has a little more than he can
handle in the fear and hysteria department. Only Nell, who connects
with the spirits, can save them now.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE The worst behavior is exhibited by the house itself,
which sprouts spectral faces and fists from walls and ceilings and
creaks and rocks about like a ship at sea. As for bodily violence,
one head is lost and a small amount of blood spilled in a film that
is filled with latent violence throughout. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Theo sashays and flirts a bit with Nell, but there's nothing
too sexy about the Hill House situation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Some but not much. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-8 Way too frightening for many young children (though
some would be highly entertained). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 9-11 Parents know their children, but by now many can
handle the scary stuff and they'll find the movie spooky and fun. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP They should be fine. But by now viewers might
sense an unintended comedic flavor to some of the goings-on, which
could make the film seem a trifle foolish, especially to older
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   DROP DEAD GORGEOUS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten Dunst, Kirstie Alley, Denise Richards, Allison Janney,
Ellen Barkin &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michael Patrick Jann &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 97 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In a very tired scenario, Jann's film sends a documentary crew
to Mount Rose, Minn., to record a teen-age beauty pageant. The
odds-on favorite is Becky Leeman (Ms. Richards), daughter of the
local furniture merchant, a contestant brimming with patriotism,
religious fervor and phony self-effacement. Besides, as someone
points out, she's the richest girl in a small town.
</P>
<P>
   Becky's major competition is Amber Atkins (Ms. Dunst), who lives
in a trailer and practices tap dancing while working at the funeral
parlor. Other than the local nymphomaniac, the rest of the field
seems virtually retarded. One of the judges actually is retarded,
with the others ranging from dim to perverted.
</P>
<P>
   Becky can't abide the thought of losing, nor can her mother,
Gladys (Ms. Alley), a strident former pageant winner and chairwoman
of the event. To say that either of them would kill for the crown
is no exaggeration. Various mishaps befall Amber and those
associated with her, including a football player who is shot dead
by a sniper (not to point fingers, but Becky is president of the
Lutheran Sisterhood Gun Club).
</P>
<P>
   With her candidacy consistently sabotaged, Amber taps on, even
after the trailer burns down and the costume for her routine is
ruled obscene. The pageant proceeds, with all the girls preening
and strutting and doing plenty of vomiting (a Hollywood obsession
and a must in a movie of this ilk) after partaking of tainted
seafood. Is winning merely everything, or is it the only thing?
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE This is a spoof and clearly so, but arson and murder
are arson and murder.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX One contestant is continually making out with her boyfriend
and Gladys casts a longing eye at a hunky schoolboy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY No torrent of profanity, just a stream. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-9 In no way should this be construed as a movie suitable
for small children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-13 Parents could well veto the film on grounds of taste,
but children will press to attend.
</P>
<P>
   INSPECTOR GADGET &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Broderick, Rupert Everett, Joely Fisher, Michelle
Trachtenberg &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by David Kellogg &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG 85 minutes
</P>
<P>
   When John Brown (Broderick), a nice security guard, gets more or
less killed in an altercation with a smirking son of Satan named
Sanford Scolex (Everett), what's left of him is outfitted with
implements one would come across at Home Depot. Utter the correct
verbal command and the new Brown, rechristened Inspector Gadget,
can turn himself into a power drill perhaps, or a walking
stepladder.
</P>
<P>
   Such a contraption is naturally of value to local law officials,
though the police chief (Dabney Coleman) resists robotization on
his force. Put together by Dr. Brenda Bradford (Ms. Fisher), with
whom Brown-Gadget remains smitten throughout his makeover, the
inspector becomes a one-man hardware store in the struggle against
Scolex, who has stolen a mechanized foot and plans world
domination.
</P>
<P>
   On it goes. Gadget is provided with a supercar powered by a
talking computer with attitude (the voice of D.L. Hughley) and
loaded with popular food and drink. Faster than a speeding product
endorsement, Scolex manufactures a replica of Gadget, called
Robogadget (also Broderick), a pyromaniac who walks the streets
like Godzilla and has clacking teeth. Fortunately, Gadget squirts
toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Solid mayhem but strictly silly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Some glancing references, but mild. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-6 This may not be ideal fare for the littlest ones, but
Broderick has gentle, winning ways and the villainy isn't too
scary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 7-10 Just right. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP Starting to attend movies with friends, many
pre-teen-agers bid farewell to PG movies. Gadget will still appeal
to some, but turn off others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
