<HEADER>
A8797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     07-29 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT ON A NEW ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANN POWERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEN: ``You Can't Stop the Bum Rush'' (The Work Group). Rock is
bouncing back from the doldrums, with artists like Limp Bizkit and
Kid Rock scoring mass adulation. But those bad boys are giving a
nasty reputation to the blend of hip-hop and punk galvanizing the
renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock's fires illuminate only one aspect of this important
juncture. Others are more promising than menacing.
</P>
<P>
   Len, whose frisky song ``Steal My Sunshine'' is this summer's
emblematic hit, advocates looting _ but this Toronto-based bunch
prefers the friendly, cultural kind. Len is eclectic to a fault,
blending rap with all kinds of pop and rock. A lightsome touch
saves the band from getting buried in its own musical diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the siblings Marc and Sharon Costanzo, Len began in 1990
as a pop-punk band. Traces of that past remain on ``You Can't Stop
the Bum Rush.'' The band's probable next single, ``Feelin'
Alright,'' boasts a crunchy riff by the hair-metal guitar god C.C.
DeVille and a cathartic lyric reminiscent of the Offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Hyperactive emotions are only one ingredient in an album that
surveys trends from old-school rap revivalism to German techno
tributes, turntable artistry, 1960s candy pop, and even a
gospel-inspired blockbuster ballad.
</P>
<P>
   Len merrily acknowledges its kleptomania by sharing the
spotlight with its heroes Kurtis Blow and Biz Markie, whose human
beatbox propels ``Man of the Year.''
</P>
<P>
   And by turning out charming spirit-lifters like ``Steal My
Sunshine,'' Len shows that musical thieves can work like Robin
Hood, stealing from music's history to enrich the here and now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1650EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
