</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVLIN-FED-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALICE RIVLIN REFLECTS ON FED, OTHER GOVERNMENT POSTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 1.)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In 1953 Harvard University's public affairs school
told Alice Rivlin that women need not apply.
</P>
<P>
   Today Rivlin laughs as she recalls the incident _ perhaps
because in the decades since then she has held high-profile
government posts that most Harvard graduates can only dream of
having.
</P>
<P>
   She has been:
</P>
<P>
   _Vice chairman of the Federal Reserve from 1996 until last
month.
</P>
<P>
   _Deputy director and then director of the White House's Office
of Management and Budget (OMB) from 1993 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   _Head of the Congressional Budget Office (CBO), which she
created, from 1975 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   _Assistant secretary for planning and evaluation at the then
Department of Health, Education and Welfare in 1968 and 1969.
</P>
<P>
   _Chairman of the Washington, D.C., Financial Control Board since
last September.
</P>
<P>
   Rivlin, reflecting on her years of public service, said in an
interview last week that her favorite job was running the CBO,
which determines how much all those bills that lawmakers propose
will actually cost. ``We got to design a new government agency,''
she said. ``It was very, very challenging and difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Her next-favorite post was at the Fed's Board of Governors,
which she described as a calm oasis compared with the White House's
OMB. That, she said, is the ``crossroads of government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is probably the most pressuring job in government,'' she
added. ``Just about everything in the government goes through
OMB.'' Not only does the agency put together the president's annual
federal budget, but it also handles regulatory changes proposed by
government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of job that no human being can ever feel that he
or she is doing well,'' Rivlin said. ``You are always trying to
catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   A big part of the OMB job is negotiating with Congress on behalf
of the White House. Rivlin held the post during the height of
budget battles between President Clinton and the
Republican-controlled Congress when parts of the federal government
shut down in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   When she moved to the No. 2 spot at the Fed, Rivlin recalled,
she was surprised at ``how civilized it was after the chaos of the
White House. Decision-making was quite deliberate, meetings started
on time and people were called on in turn.''
</P>
<P>
   As Fed vice chairman, she, Chairman Alan Greenspan and the rest
of the seven-member board _ along with the 12 presidents of the
Fed's regional banks _ periodically considered raising or lowering
interest rates in order to keep the U.S. economy stable. That
19-member group, called the Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC),
meets eight times a year. Last year it cut rates three times.
</P>
<P>
   But monetary policy, which gets the most publicity, takes up
only a quarter of the Fed's time, she said. Mostly, the job
involves setting U.S. bank regulations and attending academic and
banking conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the publicity that Greenspan gets, Rivlin insisted
that economic decisions are made by the entire FOMC and not solely
the chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a go-around-the-table in which everybody says what
they think is happening out there,'' Rivlin said. ``Greenspan is
the last to speak. He listens to all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivlin said the 12 regional Fed presidents are key to the Fed's
decision-making, especially in deciding whether to raise, lower or
leave interest rates steady. ``They interact with the business,
banking, agriculture communities where they are from,'' she
explained.
</P>
<P>
   While Rivlin was at the Fed, she picked up another demanding job
as chairman of Washington, D.C.'s control board.
</P>
<P>
   It had been created by Congress in 1995 to run the city's
finances, schools and other government functions during the reign
of then Mayor Marion Barry, who presided over a near financial
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Under Rivlin's chairmanship, however, the control board returned
most of the day-to-day activities to the new mayor, Anthony
Williams, and city council. The board still oversees the city's
budget.
</P>
<P>
   After almost a year of two jobs, Rivlin wanted to spend more
time with her husband, Sidney G. Winter, who teaches part of each
week in Philadelphia at the Wharton School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   So she is now settling in at the Brookings Institution, a
Washington-based think-tank where she will study and write about
urban policy and economics. One study will cover why U.S.
businesses have become more productive.
</P>
<P>
   Rivlin calls Brookings her ``home room'' because she has
returned to the research organization between government
assignments. In fact, she started her career there in 1957 while
she was finishing her doctorate at Radcliffe College, which was
then Harvard's school for women.
</P>
<P>
   Now she thinks she will stay at Brookings for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 68,'' Rivlin said. ``I'm not looking for any more big
positions.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PICKETT-EARLY-MUSIC-A     07-29 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PICKETT-EARLY-MUSIC-ART-720(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIP PICKETT: UNLEASHING EARLY MUSIC'S DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One might have thought that all the European period
instrument ensembles that have become stars on recordings over the
last couple of decades had already visited New York, where
appetites for early-music recordings are healthy, and indigenous
competition, while formidable, is not overabundant.
</P>
<P>
   But there are pleasures still to be sampled. Philip Pickett, a
recorder player and one of the most imaginative early-music
directors working in Britain, is just now getting around to
performing in New York with the New London Consort, the ensemble he
founded in 1976. The group is to make its U.S. debut in a Mostly
Mozart concert Sunday afternoon at Alice Tully Hall.
</P>
<P>
   What took so long?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to answer that,'' Pickett said. ``We didn't have a
U.S. agent, and when one got interested, we were offered a terrible
deal. We could come the first time for nothing and spend a few
weeks on buses and planes going nowhere in particular. And we had
so much work to do in Europe and other parts of the world that it
just didn't seem worth behaving like students again.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most ensembles of its kind, the New London Consort is a
flexible group with a roster that expands and contracts as the
musical needs demand, and those needs vary widely. The group's
repertory begins with 12th-century works for small ensembles and
runs through the chamber orchestra repertory of the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   For about half of BBC television's Shakespeare productions since
the 1980s, Pickett and company have provided the music, sometimes
on camera. They also have performed on a few film soundtracks,
including ``Robin Hood: Prince of Thieves.'' Over the last decade,
Pickett has led his ensemble in a growing collection of superb
recordings for Decca and its early-music imprint, L'Oiseau-Lyre,
and for the independent Linn label.
</P>
<P>
   For the consort's Mostly Mozart appearance, Pickett has put
together a program devoted mostly to 17th- and 18th-century English
theater music. The works of lesser-known composers like Matthew
Locke, Giovanni Battista Draghi and John Blow will be heard beside
those of their more famous contemporaries, Purcell and Handel, with
a paean to Shakespeare, composed in 1776 by Thomas Linley Jr., as
the finale.
</P>
<P>
   Pickett has always been one for making provocative assertions,
and this constellation of composers will allow him to test one of
them. In Pickett's view, the 20th-century notion that Purcell was
the greatest 17th-century English composer _ ``modern Purcell
worship,'' as he puts it _ is all wrong, and prevents us from
understanding the era and the way its composers worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think in terms of individual achievement is misleading,''
he writes in his program notes. ``A corporate style with individual
mannerisms would be nearer the mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaborating on this theme in a telephone interview from his home
in London, Pickett speculated on why Purcell has become a symbol of
the era while composers like Blow, wh was Purcell's teacher, are
known mainly to specialists and collectors of early-music
recordings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think mainly it's because we never get to hear performances
of the other chaps. Or if we do, they're always low-budget
productions. The real money gets spent on Purcell, and that's
important. If some music college presents a work by Matthew Locke,
because it's more interesting for the students _ there's more for
them to do _ nobody takes any interest at all. So I'm definitely up
for championing some of these other guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, I think Purcell is quite straightforward. We have a
tradition of performing Purcell, so people tend to understand
what's going on. But music by people like Draghi, Locke and even
John Blow can be very tough. A performer has to be aware of
symbolism, characterization and allegory, and then be able to
project those things. When they do get those things right, and put
them forward in a performance, I think John Blow's music can be as
moving, touching and convincing as any piece of Purcell's.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why in some ways I prefer Blow's `Venus and Adonis' to
Purcell's `Dido.' I feel it's a much more personal, heartfelt
statement. `Dido' is great art. But when you understand the Blow,
it hits you in the chest in a way that `Dido' never has.''
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts from both works are included on the consort's program.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Pickett added that modern audiences have never heard ``Dido
and Aeneas'' the way Purcell meant it to sound, despite a
burgeoning catalog of period-instrument recordings of the work. In
particular, he said, few performers have devoted much study to
Purcell's time signatures _ the numerical indications of how many
beats are in a bar of music, and which kind of note is used as the
basis for counting those beats _ which he considers crucial to the
work's dramatic and emotional structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't use the same kind of time signatures that we do,''
he said of Purcell and his contemporaries, explaining that they
were more precise about relationships between tempos than today's
musicians. ``I have performed `Dido' with very careful attention to
these details, and the performance sounded rather unusual because
all the tempi were completely different to everybody else's. But I
felt it had much more impact dramatically and was much more
sensible. Implied or projected states of emotion were suddenly very
different when played at different tempi. These composers knew what
they were doing. It's just that we are so far from them that we've
lost a lot of the plot.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickett said he had no immediate plans to record his
reconsideration of ``Dido and Aeneas.'' At Mostly Mozart, he is
offering Dido's famous Lament. Because only a single selection will
be performed, listeners won't be able to hear how Pickett's tempos
work. But the performance will differ from most period-instrument
readings in that it will be accompanied by strings only, without
the harpsichord or lute continuo that has become standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of a long tradition of laments, which goes right
back into the Renaissance,'' he said. ``They were always
accompanied by violas da gamba, with very low string parts to imply
the depression of the soul. So you shouldn't have harpsichords or
lutes clattering around.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is more Purcell on the program _ selections from ``The
Indian Queen'' and ``Timon of Athens'' _ as well as music from a
17th-century production of ``The Tempest'' that was long attributed
to Purcell, but is now believed to be by an unknown contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   Locke, who Pickett believes was a strong influence on Purcell,
and Draghi, Locke's sometime collaborator, are to be represented by
selections from ``Psyche,'' a work that Pickett describes as ``the
beginning of the English musical theater.'' And there is a scene
from Blow's ``Venus and Adonis.''
</P>
<P>
   The program also includes selections from two nontheatrical
works, Handel's ``Acis and Galatea'' and Linley's ``Ode on the
Spirits of Shakespeare.'' Pickett included them, he said, for their
quasi-theatrical associations. The Handel, after all, tells its
story in a theatrical way, and the Linley, more a cantata than a
theater piece, was once performed in a theater that was owned by
the composer's father. Including it was also a way to call
attention to Linley, an English contemporary of Mozart who was
considered promising and forward-looking at the time of his death
in a boating accident in 1778, when he was 22.
</P>
<P>
   Pickett regards this sampler of British music as a look at the
origin of a quasi-operatic theater style that can be traced through
Gilbert and Sullivan to the modern English and American musical
theater. Does he, one wondered, really see a link between Purcell
and Andrew Lloyd Webber?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Pickett said with a mischievous laugh, ``we do seem to
have a very strong tradition here in England of not writing opera.
And in effect, with a couple of exceptions the piece we are going
to perform could be regarded as the Lloyd Webber shows of their
day. They were extremely popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that people in England have always liked to go to a
play with a lot of music, with colorful costumes and as many sets
as possible _ a spectacle, a multimedia entertainment. But we never
seemed to have much sympathy for pieces which were all sung. And
that possibly stems from the time when Italian opera was popular
here. Those early experiments by people like Handel didn't really
work. Or they worked in terms of the wonderful arias that were
written for the great singing stars to show off. But all those
endless, boring recitatives that nobody could understand drove
people away in the end.'' Pickett, 48, became interested in early
music in the mid-1960s, when he was a trumpet student at the
Guildhall School of Music and Drama in London, and had been
captivated by performances of Renaissance and medieval music that
were proliferating in England under the direction of David Munrow
and other young musicians. He received encouragement from Anthony
Baines, a musicologist best known for his histories of instruments,
who persuaded Pickett to take up the valveless Baroque trumpet.
Around the same time, ickett became fascinated with recorders and
other early wind instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blew all my grant money, which was meant to pay for my
education, on some nice recorders and nice krummhorns,'' he said.
He began attending Munrow's classes at the Royal Academy of Music,
even though he wasn't enrolled there, and eventually persuaded
Munrow to give him a few recorder lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took weeks to get him to hear me play,'' Pickett said,
``but in the end he did, and I got a job straight away. Having been
a trumpet player, I played the recorder without vibrato. All the
other recorder players in England warbled like mad.''
</P>
<P>
   After his first year at the Guildhall School, Pickett gave up
the trumpet and devoted himself entirely to wind instruments. He
also became interested in musicology and sat in, again
unofficially, on classes given by Ian Bent, who was then at the
University of London's King's College. He quickly realized that
instead of looking for repertory in published anthologies, as most
other London medieval and Renaissance ensembles were doing, he
could make a stronger mark by searching libraries for unpublished
gems. With the fledgling New London Consort, he gave the first
performances in England of works by Hildegarde of Bingen and Peter
Abelard, and of manuscript collections like the ``Carmina Burana''
and the ``Cantigas de Santa Maria.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickett's musicological explorations have also led him to
idiosyncratic interpretations of familiar works. In his liner notes
for the New London Consort's 1994 recording of Bach's
``Brandenburg'' Concertos, for example, he proposed that the set of
works, compiled for the Margrave of Brandenburg, were meant as a
procession of mythical scenes, figures and virtues.
</P>
<P>
   He presents a compelling argument that the First Concerto was
meant to evoke a Roman triumph, or military procession; that the
prominent trumpet of the Second Concerto portrays Fame, and that
the Third Concerto, with its symmetrical string writing, depicts
the harmony of the Spheres. The Fourth, in Pickett's reading,
describes a contest between Apollo and the satyr Marsyas; the
Fifth, with its combination of French and Italian styles and its
extended harpsichord cadenza, is a musical version of Hercules'
choice between Virtue and Vice, and the low-lying string writing in
the Sixth is a reminder of death and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no concrete evidence at all,'' Pickett said when asked
for the basis of this reading, ``but there is a mountain of
circumstantial evidence. And I'm more convinced than I was then
that you can find a locus topicus _ or, you can try and imagine
one, because you'll never really find it _ for almost any piece of
Baroque music. I have yet to come across a piece which was not
obviously based on something allegorical, symbolic or emotional. I
promise you, it's not pie in the sky. This is how these composers
worked, and I believe that these are the things that were in Bach's
mind when he wrote those pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   For their first dozen years, Pickett and his group pursued their
repertory adventures in the concert hall, on European tours, in
radio concerts for the BBC and in recordings for small British
labels. Not until 1989 did the band make its major label recording
debut, a collection of dances from Praetorius' ``Terpsichore,'' for
L'Oiseau-Lyre. As it turned out, the long wait for a label deal
proved beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we played so many concerts,'' Pickett said, ``all of
our early recordings we made after a great deal of experience with
the music. We were able to go into the studio and make the
recordings without having to use session time to rehearse. And the
company loved that, because in a lot of cases they would commission
an ensemble to record repertory that they had not performed, and
the players would turn up, rehearse and record, and make the record
by cutting together eight bars at a time. We were a breath of fresh
air because we'd come in and perform 15 minutes of medieval music
without rehearsing and without stopping. Those early recordings
have hardly any editing.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, as the group's repertory expanded toward Baroque and
Classical works, and as the label began requesting works that were
not in the repertory, the consort began making recordings that were
exclusively studio productions. Even so, the performances on those
disks _ the group's fine accounts of Monteverdi's Vespers and
``Orfeo'' are examples _ have the same lively edge that have
characterized the ensemble's work from the start.
</P>
<P>
   When Pickett isn't conducting or playing recorder with the New
London Consort, he is working with his other band, the Musicians of
the Globe. Formed in 1995, this ensemble of mostly younger players
is resident at the reconstructed Globe Theater in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, they wanted the New London Consort,'' Pickett
said, ``but the old-guard players are too established in their own
right, and they don't want to sit in a theater three to five nights
a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was very eager to do it, because I did a lot of theater
work in my younger years, and when I watched the Globe going up I
was thinking, `Wow, if only it were me.' So we hit upon a plan
where I would use a lot of younger players, but also make sure that
the group had a life of its own outside the theater. And that has
worked out, because the Musicians of the Globe now play concerts,
make broadcasts and recordings, and go on tour. But because they
are part of this group, they can be strong-armed into the theater _
you know, `If you want to be part of this, you have to suffer!'''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Pickett and the New London Consort will make their
American debut on Sunday at the Mostly Mozart Festival with
``Orpheus in Albion: Great Moments in the English Musical Theater,
1670 to 1770,'' a program of works by Locke, Draghi, Purcell,
Handel and Blow. The concert begins at 3 p.m., with a preconcert
lecture at 2 p.m., at Alice Tully Hall, 1941 Broadway, at 65th
Street, at Lincoln Center. Information: (212) 721-6500. Tickets:
$35.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
