<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON TOBACCO AND `60 MINUTES'; `EYES' MYSTERY; GETTING OLDER?
GREAT! 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Michael Mann, director of ``Last of the Mohicans''
and ``Heat,'' is nervous. So is Joe Roth, chairman of Walt Disney
studios. And who can blame them?
</P>
<P>
   The two men are awaiting reaction to Mann's newest and most
anticipated film, ``The Insider,'' which deals with, among other
issues, the decision by CBS News in 1995 not to broadcast an
interview on ``60 Minutes'' with a tobacco company whistleblower.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volume has been turned up in the media,'' said Mann, who
created the television series ``Miami Vice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not so much concerned about CBS or Mike Wallace or Don
Hewitt or those folks,'' Mann said of the ``60 Minutes'' reporter
and the executive producer, who are portrayed in the movie in a
less-than-flattering way. ``The big concern was _ and is _ tobacco.
They're highly litigious. They compelled CBS, a paragon of
journalistic integrity, to yank a show.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-and-a-half-hour film, to be released by Disney on Nov.
9, stars Al Pacino as Lowell Bergman, a former ``60 Minutes''
producer, and Russell Crowe (``L.A. Confidential'') as Jeffrey
Wigand, a scientist who decided to reveal information that his
former employer, the Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., had lied to
Congress about tobacco's addictive effects. The film deals with the
complex and volatile relationship between Wigand, a complicated,
almost withdrawn figure, and the aggressive television producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're totally different,'' Mann said. ``In a social context,
they wouldn't be attracted to one another as friends or even get
along. And Jeffrey Wigand is not `Mr. Deeds Goes to Washington.'
He's precisely as imperfect as all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS initially decided against broadcasting its interview with
Wigand with the acquiescence of Hewitt and Wallace. Bergman, who
was Wallace's longtime producer, strenuously argued with his
bosses. CBS later broadcast the interview. But Bergman quit.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman now teaches at the University of California at Berkeley
and does free-lance reporting, including some assignments on
contract with The New York Times. Wigand lives in Charleston, S.C.,
and runs a project intended to keep youngsters from smoking
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Mann said he had known Bergman for years and had considered
making a film based on another ``60 Minutes'' episode produced by
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every week or so I'd get a call from him,'' Mann said. ``I was
inside those events when CBS closed down the story and Wigand was
under intense personal pressure. At one point I said, `What you're
living through, that's a drama.'''
</P>
<P>
   An article about Wigand in Vanity Fair, by Marie Brenner, which
was the basis for the movie, accelerated the project.
</P>
<P>
   Roth, Disney's chairman, said the script by Eric Roth, who won
an Academy Award for his screenplay, ``Forrest Gump,'' immediately
sold him on the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good drama, a good thriller, a good story of how
corporations face responsibilities or not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roth added that he was convinced that the various portrayals of
real people in the film were accurate and that the drama was not
merely a criticism of the CBS journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned that the people at `60 Minutes' would see the
movie as something other than what it intends to be, a drama told
on different levels in which they went along with corporate
decisions that they probably regret in retrospect, and Mike Wallace
has gone on record as saying that,'' Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   Roth said he was a bit reluctant to talk about Brown &AMP;
Williamson's response to Disney's decision to make the film.
``We've certainly heard from them along the way,'' he said. ``Our
lawyers have been in this the whole time. I have a great deal of
confidence in Michael Mann's meticulous research.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Mann, who is credited as a co-screenwriter on the film, and
Roth made clear that they hoped any potential uproar about the way
CBS News or Brown &AMP; Williamson is presented in the movie would not
overshadow the movie itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sell the controversy or the potential problems
with `60 Minutes' or Brown &AMP; Williamson,'' Roth said. ``It's a
great American story about how difficult it is, even if you're
right, to go against hugely rich and powerful companies in
communications and manufacturing. And the irony is not lost on me
that I work for one of those, too.''
</P>
<P>
   `Eyes' Mystery
</P>
<P>
   Though executives at Warner Brothers, as well as those at rival
studios, say they expect Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut'' to
emerge as a big success overseas, its box office in the United
States dropped 54 percent in its second weekend, raising the
question of why a sexual drama with Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman
has fallen so sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Reviews for the film were wildly mixed, and several rival
marketing and distribution executives said that audiences who saw
the movie in its first days were disappointed and conveyed their
views to friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a drop like this, it's because it doesn't
deliver in a way that people anticipated,'' one distribution
executive said. ``The early publicity was very strong. People
anticipated a masterpiece. They were disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Another distribution executive said that two groups of
moviegoers _ fans of Kubrick, Cruise and Ms. Kidman _ showed up the
first week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kubrick fans were probably more pleased than the Cruise
fans,'' the executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Older? Great!
</P>
<P>
   By the time actors turn 50, their careers often take a downhill
slide. Not 59-year-old James Cromwell.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of struggle and a period in the 1970s when he
almost dropped out of acting, Cromwell has turned into perhaps the
busiest film actor in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm actually getting scripts now, offers,'' said Cromwell,
sounding a bit incredulous at his sudden good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   The austere-looking, 6-foot-6 character actor _ who often plays
Army generals, government officials and police officers _ has made
about 30 films in recent years. And they keep rolling out.
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent film, ``The General's Daughter,'' a drama
about a daughter who is murdered, Cromwell plays the general, who
has some deep secrets. Next Cromwell will play a prison warden
(``The Green Mile''), a priest (``The Bachelor'') and William
Randolph Hearst in ``RKO 281,'' an HBO drama about the making of
``Citizen Kane.''
</P>
<P>
   After working mostly on television and in the New York theater,
Cromwell's film career took off in the mid-1990s. His earlier
experience in the movie business in the 1960s and '70s had been
dismal, partly because he was so tall that casting directors
avoided him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My agent sent me a script and said it was about a pig,''
Cromwell said. ``I leafed through it. I had about 12 lines. I
thought it was this Disney thing. So I thought I'd go for the
audition. It's not as if I had a lot of offers.''
</P>
<P>
   Five months later he got word to fly to Australia to make this
movie, ``Babe,'' which became one of the biggest hits of 1995.
Cromwell received an Academy Award nomination, and has not stopped
working since.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cromwell often plays villains now _ ``Maybe it's my
height,'' he said _ the actor's personal life is unusually
altruistic. In the 1960s and '70s, he worked in the civil rights
movement in the rural South, touring with the Free Southern Theater
and directing and starring in ``Waiting for Godot'' for black
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most rewarding experience I ever had in the theater,''
said Cromwell, who is married to Julie Cobb, the daughter of the
actor Lee J. Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Cromwell has immersed himself in the plight of
the Lakota tribe in South Dakota, and has founded a project with
the help of wealthy Hollywood figures like Norman Lear to build a
fine arts college at the Pine Ridge Reservation there. ``I've
always had a political bent,'' Cromwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The actor grew up in Hollywood. His father was John Cromwell,
the actor and director who was blacklisted in 1954, and moved to
the East Coast after that. His mother, Kay Johnson, was a stage and
film actress, and so was his stepmother, Ruth Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Cromwell, who studied acting and directing at Carnegie Mellon,
spent years in Los Angeles struggling to earn a living as an actor.
His low point, he said, came in the 1970s, when he grew despondent
about his acting career. He sailed around the world for 18 months,
and returned to Los Angeles intending to work as a probation
officer.
</P>
<P>
   But a friend, Gordon Davidson, artistic director of the Mark
Taper Forum, asked him to appear in ``Hamlet,'' which starred Stacy
Keach. Shortly afterward, Lear offered him the role of Stretch
Cunningham in ``All in the Family.'' Cromwell has since worked
regularly _ if not full time _ on television and in the New York
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Cromwell said he could hardly believe his recent good fortune.
Finally. ``It's the luck of the Irish,'' he said. ``Better late
than never.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
