<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Mini-Trove Of Velazquez? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Frick Collection hopes to unite six portraits by Velazquez
(1599-1660) that have never hung together before. If all goes as
planned, this small, highly focused exhibition, organized to mark
the Spanish master's 400th birthday, will bring together works from
the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Hispanic Society and the Frick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed appropriate to have some kind of celebration,'' said
Samuel Sachs II, the Frick's director. ``These six works will cover
the artist's entire career.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic Society is lending three paintings: ``Gaspar de
Guzman, Count-Duke of Olivares,'' ``Camillo Astalli, known as
Cardinal Pamfili'' and ``Portrait of a Little Girl.'' It is the
first time in 90 years the society has allowed any of its
collection of Old Master paintings to leave the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Pending approval from the Metropolitan's board, those works will
be joined by ``Juan de Pareja'' and the ``Infanta Maria Teresa of
Spain,'' neither of which has left the Metropolitan since they
visited the Prado in Madrid nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth work in the show, a portrait of King Philip IV of
Spain, is from the Frick's collection. It was acquired by Henry
Clay Frick, and therefore cannot travel. (Under Frick's will, the
art he acquired _ about two-thirds of the collection _ is not
allowed to be lent.)
</P>
<P>
   Sachs said the show, which runs from Nov. 16 through Jan. 16,
was the brainchild of Jonathan Brown, a Velazquez scholar who is on
the Frick Art Reference Library Council Association. It will be
installed in the oval gallery, which is where the Frick's Velazquez
originally hung when the house-museum opened in 1935. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smithsonian Tours &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It seems to be something of a trend for museums to send their
collections on tour to other institutions when they close for
renovation. The Barnes Foundation in Merion, Pa., and the Van Gogh
Museum in Amsterdam, for example, have organized highly popular
traveling exhibitions of their prized paintings.
</P>
<P>
   So it comes as no surprise that while the Smithsonian Museum of
American Art and its Renwick Gallery are shut for a three-year
renovation beginning in 2000, ``Treasures to Go,'' eight thematic
exhibitions of paintings and sculptures organized by the museum,
will travel to museums across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have a lot more people understand how important
American art is and to learn more about us,'' said Elizabeth Broun,
director of the Museum of American Art.
</P>
<P>
   The shows are: ``Young America,'' tracing the transformation of
the colonies, with portraits by John Singleton Copley, Charles
Willson Peale and Gilbert Stuart, as well as landscapes scenes of
early America; ``Lure of the West,'' which includes portraits by
George Catlin, Western subjects by Frederic Remington and Albert
Bierstadt and works from the Taos school; ``American
Impressionism,'' concentrating on 19th-century artists from the
late 1880s like Childe Hassam, James McNeil Whistler, Mary Cassatt,
John Twachtman and William Merritt Chase; ``The Gilded Age,'' which
highlights artists after the Civil War and through the mid-1920s,
including John Singer Sargent and Abbott Thayer; ``Scenes of
American Life,'' exploring the century from 1909 to 1980 through
works by Edward Hopper, Jacob Lawrence and Paul Cadmus; ``Modernism
and Abstraction,'' surveying the 20th century from emerging
technological innovations to new political theories, from Jo%ph
Stella and Georgia O'Keeffe to Marsden Hartley and Arthur Dove;
``Contemporary Folk Art,'' showcasing self-taught artists from the
last 40 years, and ``Arte Latino,'' about Latino art traditions and
innovations.
</P>
<P>
   These shows will go to a varied group of about 70 museums, from
Portland, Ore., to Portland, Maine., and to urban sites like Miami,
Dallas and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Fees for the exhibitions range from $30,000 to $40,000, Ms.
Broun said. As a government institution, the Smithsonian does not
try to make a profit but is concerned with covering its costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Principal Financial Group, a Des Moines-based insurance and
financial services company, is providing funds for various
initiatives connected with the shows. It will help pay for
advertising and publications as well as produce several national
cable television specials and a syndicated program for network
affiliates in each city on the tour. It will also help pay for a
new section of the museum's Web site about the exhibitions, which
can be reached at www.nmaa.si.edu. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Sculpture Park &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Following in the footsteps of cities like Washington and Dallas,
Seattle is about to have its own museum-affiliated sculpture
garden.
</P>
<P>
   This week the Seattle Art Museum and the Trust for Public Land,
a nonprofit organization that works with public authorities to
preserve open spaces, received a $4 million gift from the Allen
Foundation for the Arts, a Seattle-based organization.
</P>
<P>
   The gift will go 4oward the purchase of a $17 million, six-acre
site adjoining Myrtle Edwards Park, downtown Seattle's last
remaining parcel of undeveloped land. The site, which is currently
owned by the Unocal oil company, will be developed into a
waterfront sculpture park.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has also received a $4 million pledge from the Bill
and Melinda Gates Foundation and a $5 million endowment pledged by
Jon and Mary Shirley, Seattle collectors, to insure the park's
long-term operation and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   So far, $24 million has been raised toward what is estimated to
be a $37 million project. The Seattle City Council has also passed
a resolution to help finance the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sculpture has become a vital collecting field in Seattle,''
said Mimi Gardner Gates, director of the Seattle Art Museum, who
added that the project is expected to take about three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``First we wanted to insure that we had the land because there
were many developers right behind us,'' she said. ``The artistic
program, along with the design of the park, has still to be
developed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
