<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV05-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKSLIDING INTO THE POLITICALLY INCORRECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, Aug. 5)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The story goes something like this. Two women were out on the
soccer field when the new coach, a man, walked by and one woman
player turned to another woman player and said ``cute butt,'' not
realizing at the time that the amused woman to whom she'd tossed
the remark was the coach's mother.
</P>
<P>
   The anecdote with ``cute butt'' ended up in a newspaper story
about more women playing soccer, along with a happy-ending part
that the admiring player and the coach fell in love, got married
and her teammate became her mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   The ``cute butt'' comment probably gave many women a knowing
chuckle for this is something that women are known to say about
men. The male posterior is often a focus of admiration and
attention, particularly in sport settings.
</P>
<P>
   Men pay attention to this aspect of the female body too. But men
have been sensitized against making public comments which can get
them into trouble. Say something like that about a female soccer
player and the person sitting next to you might fire back, ``Is
that all you ever notice?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in this particular case the comment didn't get anyone
in trouble but became part of family lore.
</P>
<P>
   But some who read ``cute butt'' did not see it in its ironic
context. Some cried foul, asking how come a woman can say this
about a man but not vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit that my first reaction was not as a member of
the politically correct squad but as a person who sometimes finds
delight both in large social gaffes and the occasional football
huddle.
</P>
<P>
   What's the harm in ``cute butt''? I asked. Is there a man alive
who would protest the compliment? If a man's mother doesn't mind,
why should anyone else?
</P>
<P>
   But the arguments were there, waiting offshore like some giant
wave getting ready to come in and knock me to my senses.
</P>
<P>
   If a man made the same comment about a young woman to her father
would it be as funny? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   And, considering the scrutiny we now give to coaches, what if a
male coach said that about a female player?
</P>
<P>
   Given the wide range of anatomical commentary used on the female
body, ``cute butt'' isn't much to fret, but if a coach said it he'd
likely lose his job.
</P>
<P>
   The day after ``cute butt'' ran in our newspaper, another
newspaper quoted a joke about men by musician Chrissie Hynde which
made ``cute butt'' sound as harmless as ``nice shoes.'' But I know
... I know, that doesn't make it OK.
</P>
<P>
   It would be so easy to take a break from PC and to say ``Oh for
heaven's sake. We're just kidding.'' Or to allow for certain
exemptions. But that's assuming that everybody doesn't need any
more awareness.
</P>
<P>
   The PC concept was once considered an essential learning tool,
but now the practice is resented by enough people that ridiculing
PC speech is its own kind of humor. But look who's making the
jokes? Aren't they mostly white males?
</P>
<P>
   Look how many laughs Jack Nicholson's piggish character got for
insulting ethnic minorities in ``As Good as It Gets.''
</P>
<P>
   This fall there's a trend in gross-out humor coming on TV that
will get yuks on everything offensive from nose picking to jokes
about big breasts (they will not be called breasts). These shows
are supposed to appeal to young males who are tired of being
sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   My daughter isn't a boy-talk fan but she does like the rude
``South Park'' series. She said, ``It's funny because it's so
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But does everybody get that it's wrong?
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad that people are bored with good taste and fair
play, but it seems that somebody's got to keep paying attention,
because, take it from me, people lapse.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon one person's CB becomes another's T and A and then
we're back to slurs about pink people and we'll have to sign up for
PC training all over again.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
