<HEADER>
A8820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUMMER-DANCE-880(3     07-29 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUMMER-DANCE-880(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE MOVES BACK TO NATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dance heads for the parks, plazas and streets of the
city and beyond each summer. In a working vacation of sorts,
dancers have a chance to perform for larger, newer audiences, often
on shared programs with artists in other fields. For audiences,
summer festivals can be full of distractions not found in a formal
theater setting. Still, the experience is also serendipitous and
the price is right most of the time, with admission often free or
by small suggested donation.
</P>
<P>
   What makes a festival work? Money, of course, and rainless days
and nights. Even more, the success of the longest-running New York
festivals is attributable to directors who are knowledgeable,
imaginative and tireless.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard de Paur, the first director of the Lincoln Center Out of
Doors festival, retired in 1988 and died last year. But the memory
of his sonorous voice, which lent extra importance and a touch of
humor to even the most mundane festival announcements, is likely to
linger long, as is the memory of de Paur making the rounds of his
festival day after day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spent hours on that plaza,'' Norma de Paur recalled of her
husband, who is being honored by the festival this year. ``He loved
it. He'd walk and walk and walk. You never knew where he would
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Center Out of Doors, led today by Jenneth Webster, is
one of the four largest summer performing arts festivals in and
around New York. Each has its own personality. Celebrate Brooklyn,
now in its 21st year, combines funk and gleaming grandeur with
surprising ease in the performers it offers, the 7,200 people it
can accommodate on seats and across the lawn, and a $3.4 million
upgrading of the audience and backstage areas at the Prospect Park
Band Shell.
</P>
<P>
   The august Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival in the Berkshire hills
and meadows of Becket, Mass., offers the unusually contemplative
dance equivalent of green thoughts in a green land, to paraphrase
Marvell. Performances, talks, exhibitions, open classes and films
and videos seem to sprout up everywhere as one walks across lawns,
past gardens and into the rustic theaters, studios and exhibition
centers.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Center Out of Doors, founded in 1971, sprawls across the
plaza, spilling over into the Damrosch Park Bandshell, in a vivid,
festive mix of professional and community dance and music groups.
And the cutting edge and funky hip reign at Central Park
Summerstage, which celebrates its 14th anniversary this year.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more going on. Spot an awning or banks of sound
equipment and there is likely a smaller neighborhood performing
arts festival in full swing. One popular site this year has been
Battery Park, where the Downtown Dance Festival will offer a
glimpse /f mostly unfamiliar dance from other countries on the lawn
at the close of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the fare at New York City performing arts festivals
tends to be more diverse than it was at the city's earlier
festivals, at the vast Lewiqohn Stadium in Harlem from the late
1920s through the '60s, and at the popular Delacorte Dance Festival
in Central Park from the early 1960s into the '70s. Both audiences
and performers are conscientiously nurtured more, too, with
improvements in seating and stages and slowly increasing pay for
dancers. Festivals are also commissioning work and offering
residencies that include precious free rehearsal time.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrate Brooklyn! will present the Goldhuber &AMP; Latsky duo and
Maia Claire Garrison and her troupe M'zawa Danz, both festival
dance residents this year, in a shared program on Aug. 7 preceded
by an open rehearsal and workshop on Aug. 4. New pieces are being
developed in a monthlong rehearsal period that includes three weeks
at the Picnic House in Prospect Park and a final week of stage
rehearsal in the band shell with full crew and production elements.
</P>
<P>
   The program will combine relatively laid-back downtown
experimentalist dance with dance that passionately addresses social
issues. Lawrence Goldhuber and Heidi Latsky, choreographers and
performers who are probably best known for the way they juxtapose
their large and small bodies, will present a new piece in a suite
called ``I Hate Modern Dance,'' featuring puppets and social
dancing. Ms. Garrison's new work will be the first segment of a
suite called ``The Panther Peace,'' which honors the Black Panthers
and was inspired in part by Paul Taylor's allusion to the Ku Klux
Klan in his recent ``Oh, You Kid!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally we look for two very different choreographers to
share an evening,'' Jack Walsh, co-producer of the festival with
Rachel Chanoff, said of the residency programs. ``This is a large
venue and we must develop wider audiences. We've found that when we
produce like-minded artists it is not so exciting and risky.''
</P>
<P>
   Other festival dance attractions include Momix, an offshoot of
Pilobolus, on Aug. 13, and the younger Stephen Petronio Company on
Aug. 20. The festival also presents music of all kinds, including
jazz by David Gonzalez and the D.D. Jackson Trio on Friday night
and a shared program Saturday of bluegrass music by Orrin Star and
the Sultans of String and Irish traditional music by Solas. Feature
and short films are also shown on the festival's 50-foot screen on
Thursday nights in the Sundance Channel Film Series.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It would probably have been inconceivable in 1970, when Lincoln
Center Out of Doors began as a relatively small festival that
relied on community performing groups, that an all-male ballet
company would one day be performing a work by Merce Cunningham at
the Damrosch Park Bandshell. But this year the irrepressible lads
of Les Ballets Trockadero de Monte Carlo will be dancing
Cunningham's 1964 ``Cross Currents'' on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   It would probably have been equally hard to imagine the festival
having money to commission works from well-known modern dance
choreographers like Molissa Fenley and Ronald K. Brown. Ms. Fenley
will collaborate with the New York City Ballet principal Peter Boal
on a new piece, set to music by Joan Jeanrenaud, that will be
performed Aug. 12 as part of Ms. Fenley's ``Expanding Universe''
program. Brown's new ``Ode to Ellington'' will be performed Aug. 19
and 20 by the exuberant Philadanco troupe from Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other commissioning grants have also gone to dance.
The festival has provided the choreographer Risa Jaroslow with 11
wading pools for her ``Pool Party Paradise II'' on Aug. 24. In a
dizzying change of pace, Lincoln Center Out of Doors will also
present the New York Baroque Dance Company in ``Vivaldi
Carnivale,'' to be performed among the leafy trees of the South
Plaza on Aug. 25 and 26.
</P>
<P>
   The range of remaining dance is wide, from Trisha Brown's
charmingly breezy new ``Five Part Weather Invention,'' set to music
by Dave Douglas and his Charms of the Night Sky ensemble, to
traditional folk dance from Peru, Haiti and Taiwan and some nutty
prop-dance choreography from Rhode Island's Everett Dance Theater.
The festival also inclu$es many music programs and events like
``Homemade Instrument Day'' on Aug. 14 that are designed for
children's participation.
</P>
<P>
   Central Park Summerstage has laid down a carpet of green plastic
turf _ by now as reassuringly bedraggled as city grass _ that has
reduced the dust in the air. But the festival remains a potent
slice of New York adventurousness, with music and dance events that
bring disparate audiences together and even have them dancing in
the aisles and chatting. That atmosphere is not accidental. ``Part
of the fun of it is that we can be both artistically adventurous
and populist at the same time,'' Bill Bragin, director of the
festival, said. ``We have the benefit of free admission and a great
location. People from different backgrounds feel welcome in the
park. Particularly for dance, people sometimes feel intimidated by
the venues. Summerstage allows people to take a chance and see
sophisticated work but also drink a beer and eat a burger. People
end up engaging with the art and with other audiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Still to go on the festival dance roster are the avant-gardists
Muna Tseng and Ping Chong, who perform Aug. 17 in a program shared
with the poet Cornelius Eady and the jazz composer Diedre Murray.
The next night is devoted to dance, opening with Rennie Harris
Puremovement, which builds on street and club dance forms, and
including a commissioned work by Leon Parker, whom festival
officials describe as a ``scientific hambone artist.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most complete summer dance experiences is to be had
at the Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival, founded in 1941 at the
bucolic home that the modern-dance pioneer Ted Shawn created for
his Men Dancers company a decade earlier. This weekend, Michael
Moschen will juggle fire, hoops and crystal balls at the Ted Shawn
Theater in the meditative blending of motion and light that have
made him a popular and iconic performance artist.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hill in the less formal Doris Duke Studio Theater, Jane
Comfort will present her Bessie Award-winning ``Underground
River,'' which features puppets by Basil Twist and an a cappella
score composed by Toshi Reagon. The score for Ms. Comfort's prickly
``Three Bagatelles for the Righteous'' includes music for tabla
drums, balafon and gamelan instruments as well as sound bites from
speeches by President Clinton, Pat Robertson, and other political
and religious figures.
</P>
<P>
   The Pillow, together with the just-ended American Dance Festival
in Durham, N.C., is one of the most active commissioners of new
work. Under the direction of Ella Baff, the Berkshires festival is
also focusing on dance with live musical accompaniment for a little
mini-Tanglewood flavor. Live music will be a feature of a program
by Los Munequitos de Matanzas, a three-generation family rumba
troupe from Cuba that performs Aug. 11 to 15.
</P>
<P>
   During the week of Aug. 18 to 22, music will be performed on
African traditional instruments by the Harlem-based Batoto Yetu
children's dance troupe founded by Julio Leitao of Angola, at the
Shawn, and gamelan music performed by the New Jakarta Ensemble will
accompany Yin Mei's ``Empty Tradition/City of Peonies'' at the
Duke. And in the festival closing week, there will be live music
for the dancers of the Bolshoi Ballet appearing at the Shawn in
American premieres by Aleksei Ratmansky, with Seamus Egan and his
Solas group providing the accompaniment for Sean Curran at the
Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing Honeymoon,'' to be performed on the Mark Morris Dance
Group program next week at the Shawn, is set to taped songs by
George and Ira Gershwin, Jerome Kern and Cole Porter. But as George
Gershwin put it, who cares? The Pillow roster will be completed by
the Teatro Hugo and Ines, puppeteers who perform at the Duke
starting Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the greatest pleasures of the Pillow experience is
simply to wander. Down a steep incline lies the Simon Performance
Space, a simple wooden platform that seems to float over the wooded
hills beyond. A free hourlong program of choreography by dancers _
Abby Yager and Ming-Lung Yang of the Trisha Brown troupe and Fritha
Pengelly of the Doug Elkins Dance Company _ is on tap Friday night,
followed Saturday by young performers in Chet Walker's Jazz on
Broadway Workshop at the Pillow school. Other free outdoor
activities include the Wednesday afternoon talks on the Great Lawn
by members of companies appearing this season at the festival.
</P>
<P>
   Back up the hill is Blake's Barn, a rough-hewn, airy hub of
activity. Marge Champion, the film dancer, actor and choreographer
and a presiding spirit at the Pillow, will talk there Saturday
about the glory days of the Hollywood musical and her own career,
illustrating the latter with film clips. Other Saturday afternoon
talks feature members of companies performing at the festival.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The doors are always open, too, for the leisurely viewing of
exhibitions of dance photographs by Lois Greenfield and artifacts
from the Pillow archives as well as two continuously running
videos. One is a documentary by Nuria Olive-Belles on the making of
Joanna Haigood's 1998 ``Invisible Wings,'' a site-specific outdoor
piece about the Underground Railroad station that was once on
Pillow grounds. The other video demonstrates the ``motion capture''
computer technique of Paul Kaiser and Shelley Eshkar that has been
used by Merce Cunningham for his recent ``Biped'' and for work by
the Estate Project for Artists with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   There is food here for the mind as well as the eyes and ears.
And for the body, there are the picnics that are another
distinguishing feature of summer festival dancegoing in and beyond
the city. As for the performers?
</P>
<P>
   ``A gig is a gig,'' Goldhuber, the Celebrate Brooklyn! dance
resident, said teasingly. ``But keep it light, I'd say, and pray
for cool weather.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
