<SLUG> BC-SC-LOVE-STORY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL BRINGS FLURRY OF YELLOW RIBBONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSE FRANCO   
 The (Spartanburg, S.C.) Herald-Journal  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAYO, S.C. _ Donna Blake saw the sign, and she knew there was
only one Choice.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, retired truck driver Choice McKinney proposed to his
girlfriend of two months by writing it on a huge aluminum sign off
Highway 221.
</P>
<P>
   And this upstate South Carolina town hasn't been the same since.
</P>
<P>
   It's what people talk about at the local diner, the Mayo
Drive-In and at the Fast Fare convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the biggest prankster in South Carolina,'' McKinney, 64,
said. ``I did it for a joke, and to show her how much I loved her
and to get people to talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers passing by honk their horns in approval or slow down to
get a closer look at the note that reads: ``Donna, I love you! Will
you marry me? If yes, put a yellow ribbon on the fence. Choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, 131 yellow ribbons popped up along the barbed wire
fence.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney had proposed two weeks earlier, but Blake couldn't give
him an answer at the time.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney said he decided to ask for a yellow ribbon because the
song ``Tie A Yellow Ribbon Round the Old Oak Tree'' kept running
through his mind.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney, who spent 42 years on the road and has been a widower
since 1989, said he's had a crush on Blake for three years but
didn't have the nerve to ask her out until two months ago. Their
first date was over coffee at the Waffle House.
</P>
<P>
   Both Blake, who is 58 and has been a widow since 1973, and
McKinney said their former spouses would approve. ``I think both of
them would want us to be happy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Blake was embarrassed by all the attention but wanted to match
McKinney's proposal. So, she gathered all the yellow ribbon she
could find and tore up a yellow bed sheet to make the 131 ribbons.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney drove by that afternoon in his pickup and saw the sign
and said, ``Holy smoke!''
</P>
<P>
   He picked her up, and while driving out to look at the sign he
proposed once again, this time placing a ring on her finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just what I have been waiting for. I know what's ahead. A
life of love,'' she smiled, squeezing his hand.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal has certainly sparked talk around town.
</P>
<P>
   The wedding is set for Aug. 24 _ Blake's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Friends have suggested they get married where McKinney professed
his love. The couple is considering that idea, but haven't decided.
McKinney is trying to figure out something to top his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Journal in Spartanburg, S.C., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
