<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPIRITS-REVIEW-NYT     07-29 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPIRITS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RESTLESS SPIRITS': SOMETHING FOR EVERYONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time and station are
for New York area; see local listings.) 
(mk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The time is 1927, two weeks before Charles Lindbergh's historic
nonstop New York to Paris flight. The pilot of the downed plane is
the French World War I ace Lt. Charles Nungesser; the other victim
of his crash is his navigator, Francois Coli, their lives lost en
route from Paris to New York in quest of the $25,000 prize won by
Lindbergh.
</P>
<P>
   On this footnote to aviation history pivots the action of
``Restless Spirits,'' the television movie to be seen Sunday at 8
p.m. ET on Showtime. Part ghost story, part girl's adventure, part
history lesson, part tale of generational conflict, part portrait
of psychological trauma, part message movie as it heads for its
lump-in-the-throat finale, this something-for-everyone story is
rightly presented as one of the cable channel's ``Original Pictures
for All Ages.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the imperfect but engaging and
well-intentioned ``Restless Spirits'' focuses on a bright but
difficult 12-year-old, Katie Penhallow (Juliana Wimbles), who is
dropped off with her all-but-mute kid brother, Simon (Nickolas
Swan), to summer in Newfoundland with their paternal grandmother,
Lydia (Marsha Mason).
</P>
<P>
   Their mother (Leslie Hope), the widow of Lydia's son, a test
pilot killed in a crash four years earlier, is about to fly to
Paris for a rendezvous with her boyfriend, a decision that only
deepens Katie's persistent anger.
</P>
<P>
   But when Katie sneaks out one night to meet some of the local
children at Porter's Pond, she encounters the ghosts of Nungesser
and Coli, fresh from their crash 70 years earlier. Because Porter's
Pond has always been a source of local ghost stories, no one
believes her.
</P>
<P>
   But her dreams and those of little Simon, who begins wearing a
black eye patch like Coli, are filled with images of the two
aviators' jubilant takeoff from Paris in their little biplane,
called L'Oiseau Blanc (the White Bird), and of their descent
through the trees into the pond.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, with the submerged plane, which exists in the past
and the present, as a physical connection between flesh and
phantom, Katie is helping the vainglorious Nungesser (Lothaire
Bluteau) and the kindly family man Coli (Michel Monty) to retrieve
and repair their aircraft so they can complete their flight and
rest their souls.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, as she races against time to thwart two aviation
archeologists determined to retrieve the wreckage for their own
purposes, Katie learns to come to terms with the past and move on
to the future.
</P>
<P>
   As her grandmother tells her: ``Loss is a part of life. Get used
to it. Hold on to the memory. Put it in your heart, where nobody
can take it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of David Wellington, working from a script
by Semi Chellas, Ms. Wimbles gives an appealing performance as
Katie, who begins as a brat and finishes as a young woman of
courage. Monty transmits the warmth and decency of Coli, and Ms.
Mason is fine as an understanding no-nonsense grandmother. But
Bluteau, whose credits include Denis Arcand's ``Jesus of
Montreal,'' is saddled with a poorly drawn role that requires him
to flaunt his medals and exhibit unbelievable hauteur and ill
temper before he is allowed to act like a human being.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the mumbo-jumbo of the impact of fog on transactions
between ghosts and children, ``Restless Spirit'' packs a reasonable
amount of everyday entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `RESTLESS SPIRITS'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Sunday on Showtime
</P>
<P>
   Written by Semi Chellas and based on a story by Gail Collins and
Ms. Chellas. Directed by David Wellington; Susan Cavan and Patrick
Whitley, producers; Sheila Hockin, co-producer; Andre Pienaar,
director of photography; music by Ron Sures.
</P>
<P>
   With: Marsha Mason (Lydia), Lothaire Bluteau (Charles
Nungesser), Michel Monty (Francois Coli), Juliana Wimbles (Katie),
Leslie Hope (Mom), Nickolas Swan (Simon) and Ben Cook (Andy).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
