<HEADER>
A8860 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASCAR-PONTIAC-NYTR &LR;      07-29 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-PONTIAC-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PONTIAC GAINING MOMENTUM IN AUTO RACING WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Lakeland, (Fla.) Ledger  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time Pontiac had a dominant car on the track in Winston
Cup racing was 1993, when Rusty Wallace won 10 races and Pontiac
11.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, believing that General Motors was primarily
focused on Chevrolet, Wallace left Pontiac and went over to Ford.
Pontiac had pretty much been in the tank since then _ until this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Joe Gibbs' two-car team featuring Pocono winner Bobby
Labonte and rookie sensation Tony Stewart, Pontiac is staging a
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   With Labonte's three wins and another by John Andretti, Pontiac
has already scored more victories in 1999 than any year since 1993.
It's not impossible that, excluding 1993, the car could win more
races this season than in any year since it returned to the sport
in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   There are three primary reasons for this:
</P>
<P>
   _ First was Gibbs' decision to switch from Chevy to Pontiac
prior to the 1997 season. Gibbs felt Chevy's major effort was
concentrated on two teams, Rick Hendrick and Richard Childress, and
Pontiac, which had dropped off dramatically with the loss of
Wallace, knew it needed to develop another lead team.
</P>
<P>
   _ The improvement in other teams such as those owned by Richard
Petty and Bill Davis. Andretti has a win in Petty's car and Ward
Burton has been in position to win with Davis.
</P>
<P>
   _ The chance to work with a car that is now becoming more of a
known quantity. As Kyle Petty explained, Pontiacs ended the 1997
season strong, but the picture changed in 1998. ``They took more
spoiler and more front air dam away from us than the other makes,''
he said. ``Now they've brought the Pontiacs back. We're basically
back to the rules we ended the 1997 season with.''
</P>
<P>
   With almost a brand new team, Petty hasn't shown the improvement
of some of the others. But Labonte says you can't blame losing on
the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people can argue we don't win races because
we're running a Pontiac,'' Labonte said. ``I think this team has a
shot to win almost every track we go to.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the race tracks where we don't have a shot are not because
it's the car's fault,'' Labonte said. ``It's my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton said the addition of crew chief Tommy Baldwin late last
year has increased his team's capability of winning on a consistent
basis.
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac teams have a new level of confidence in 1999, and it's
showing in their performance on the track.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
