<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ROUSH-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUSH TEAM LOOKING FOR ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is about 100 miles from Liberty, N.C., where Johnny Benson
and Kevin Lepage have their race shop, to the garage of Mark Martin
and Jeff Burton, which is in Mooresville, N.C. But when it comes to
racing, the distance between them is much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Benson, Lepage, Martin and Burton, along with Chad Little, also
housed in Mooresville, are all part of Roush Racing.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that they all race under the same name is about all
they have in common.
</P>
<P>
   In 19 races so far, Martin and Burton have combined to win five,
finish in the top five 23 times and in the top 10, 28 times.
</P>
<P>
   The other three cars have not won a race between them nor have
they finished in the top five. Together, they have just three top
10s, two by Little and one by Benson.
</P>
<P>
   From a practical standpoint, what has developed are three
separate teams, Martin and Burton, Benson and Lepage and Little.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after winning at Charlotte, N.C., Burton remarked that
the way he and Martin help each other ``is an example of how a
two-car team should work together.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, though, what works for Martin and Burton is not working
for the rest of Roush Racing.
</P>
<P>
   And it is having an impact.
</P>
<P>
   Lepage's primary sponsor was purchased by a competitor earlier
this year and pulled out. Roush got TV Guide as a replacement, but
now it looks as if TV Guide will leave at the end of the year, and
there is the possibility Lepage's team may fold, leaving him
looking for a ride.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Lepage's crew chief, James Ince, was let go and
blamed for Lepage's poor performance. Ince, who is now crew chief
for Rich Bickle, said he was the scapegoat for a team that had
major problems.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to centralize his operation, Roush is building new
facilities in Concord, N.C., which is near Mooresville just north
of Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Little and current Busch Series points leader Matt Kenseth, who
will join Roush in 2000 in a car partially owned by Martin, will
move in first, with Benson and Lepage following, if Lepage has a
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   With Benson, Little and Lepage all having worse years than they
did in 1998, Roush hopes moving them closer to stock car racing's
center will help pick them up.
</P>
<P>
   Benson thinks it might. He said the Liberty shop has done well
but it is difficult to get enough good people to work on the cars
in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will make a huge difference,'' Benson said. He said
many of the people who have been working in Liberty commute about 1
1/2 hours each way from the Concord and Charlotte area.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot to ask of somebody that's working the hours they
work _ to work seven days a week and then ask them to drive 21
hours a week back and forth to work,'' Benson remarked.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Kenseth could work for the others, because
Kenseth is considered by some to be the best driver in the Busch
ranks, Dale Earnhardt Jr. notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth is not likely to tolerate second-class status among the
Roush teams, and with Martin involved, has a direct connection to
Roush.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever happens, it can't be any worse for Benson, Lepage
and Little, who are scraping bottom now.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
