<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-KICKER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIDER TRADITION LURED FORMER BUC KICKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANK BLACKMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPA, Calif. _ It isn't easy for any player who joins a new
team. If he's lucky, there'll be a few guys he's played with
before. Still, he's an outsider trying to fit in as quickly as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   It's an even tougher adjustment for a kicker.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Husted, the Raiders' new field-goal kicker, understands
there is a natural prejudice against the men who do his job. Most
of the time in training camp, they're trying to stay out of the way
while the rest of the team is hard at work preparing for the
season. And, anyway, everyone knows kickers are different _ you
know, a little weird.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I make my kicks they talk to me,'' Husted joked. ``Yeah,
I've always tried to break that stereotype of kickers being the
weird guys, the kooky guys, whatever you want to call us. I have a
lot of people in Tampa Bay say, `Wow, you're the most normal kicker
I've ever come across.'''
</P>
<P>
   Husted was with the Bucs last year, where he made 21 of 28
field- goal attempts, including a long of 52 yards. But that still
wasn't good enough to guarantee him a job for 1999. He got caught
in a salary cap squeeze and was told by management there was a good
chance he wouldn't be back.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than hanging around to find out for sure, Husted
instructed his agent to call the Raiders to see if they were
interested in him. He definitely was interested in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a Raiders fan,'' he said. ``I think they have
a great tradition. Mr. Davis (owner Al Davis) wants to win. He
gives every player an opportunity to come out here and win a game.
Like I said, the Raider tradition speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Players have been saying that for decades now. The problem is
that the Raiders' commitment to excellence hasn't resulted in a
Super Bowl victory since 1983. So how could that once-glorious
tradition affect a player like Husted? He was 13 years old the last
time the Raiders played in the sport's biggest game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes a tradition,'' he said. ``There's just that
thing about the Raiders that you always hear growing up. A lot of
things when you grow up were very impressionable on you and they
stick with you. That's the way it was with me.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough that Husted wanted to play for the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   His dream team had to want him, too. It did.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Davis was the field-goal kicker last year and finished the
season with the lowest (63) percentage in the NFL. See ya, Greg.
When Husted's agent called, coach Jon Gruden grabbed the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Husted because a couple of years ago he led the NFC in
touchbacks'' the coach explained. ``I think he's going to be a real
good kicker, and a real asset to our special teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders like Husted so much, they haven't even brought in
another kicker to compete with him in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're only allowed to bring so many guys to camp nowadays,''
Gruden explained. ``When you have three or four kickers, you have
one less lineman or one less defensive back. You have to take that
into consideration. Ideally, you'd like to have competition
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Husted has looked around and noticed that there aren't any other
guys lining up to practice field goals, too. But, he insists, that
doesn't make a bit of difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, I always compete with myself,'' he said.
``I've always had the approach that they can bring in one guy, they
can bring in 10 guys, I've still got to make my kicks. It's between
me and those uprights. If I don't make my kicks, it doesn't matter
what the other guys do. And if I make my kicks, it still doesn't
matter what the other guys do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
