<HEADLINE>
THE 72 FACES OF KAREN BLACK  
 NEW RELEASES OF VIDEO CASSETTES: REVIEWS BY NEW YORK TIMES
CRITICS  
 PAST RELEASES: LITTLE FILMS THAT ROAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE 72 FACES OF KAREN BLACK: Look up Karen Black's videography,
and the list of credits, while falling well short of, say, John
Wayne's, stretches about as long as any actor's. From 1960 and
``The Prime Time'' (a satire about a day of American television
without the censors) to 1997 and ``Cries of Silence'' (about a
traumatized girl found in the aftermath of Hurricane Camille), the
Black entries in ``Videohound's Golden Movie Retriever'' number 72.
(Wayne stands at 140.)
</P>
<P>
   Among these films are ``Easy Rider'' (1969), with Ms. Black
playing a prostitute, and Bob Rafelson's ``Five Easy Pieces''
(1970), in which she portrayed a waitress and received an Oscar
nomination and Golden Globe Award as best supporting actress. There
is also her acclaimed performance in ``Nashville,'' Robert Altman's
1975 classic, for which she also wrote two songs.
</P>
<P>
   Of all this work, what do many people remember most? ``Almost
everyone who comes up to me says `Trilogy of Terror,''' Ms. Black
said the other day. That would be Dan Curtis' three-part horror
film, made for television in 1975 and released on videocassette
last week by Anchor Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Black stars in all three episodes. In the first she is a
teacher toying with a student who makes the mistake of trying to
seduce her; in the second she is a woman with a monumental
split-personality disorder. In the third segment she is Amelia, the
victim of a foot-high jagged-toothed Zuni hunting doll she has
bought for her boyfriend. The doll's name is He Who Kills, and the
little man isn't kidding as he chases the frantic Amelia around her
apartment biting her on the ankles and elsewhere, cutting his way
out of suitcases, breaking through barricaded doors and finally
escaping cremation in a hot oven.
</P>
<P>
   People remember. ``I wish they said `that wonderful movie you
did for Robert Altman,' but they don't,'' Ms. Black said. ``They
say, `that little doll.'''
</P>
<P>
   For her, ``Easy Rider'' represents a turning point in films. In
the 1970s, she said, the studios realized that audiences wanted
reality. ``They wanted to see people throwing up, smoking grass,''
she said. For ``Nashville'' Altman used two cameras and did not
stage scenes. ``He would let you do what you did,'' she said. ``He
would find you there. The camera probed into the room and found the
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Even current action films, she added, have more interesting
material within. ``Inside the framework of that adolescent plot
line, you still have people with idiosyncrasies, real problems,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   These days she concentrates on writing films as well as acting.
Now and then she advises young filmmakers who seek her opinion. One
of her own projects, she said, was developed at the screenwriter's
lab at the Sundance Film Festival. As an actor, she prefers art
films that play the festival circuit, though she says that their
directors, concerned primarily with character, should pay more
attention to story. ``They aren't disciplined enough,'' she said.
``They might have to admit they don't know everything.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES OF VIDEO CASSETTES: REVIEWS BY NEW YORK TIMES
CRITICS
</P>
<P>
   MESSAGE IN A BOTTLE
</P>
<P>
   1999. Warner. $107.37. 132 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Release date: Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Out there in the romantic suds are the high-powered Chicago
newspaperwoman Theresa Osborne (Robin Wright Penn) and the laconic
sailboat builder Garret Blake (Kevin Costner). Taken with a longing
note from a man to a woman that she has found corked in a bottle,
Theresa analyzes the cork, plots ocean currents and tracks down
Garret, the note's author, an aw-shucks kind of guy who lives on
the Outer Banks of North Carolina. Cozy snuggling ensues on beach
and boat, followed by Garret's winningly awkward trek to Chicago.
Nevertheless, Costner, who should stay out of overalls and goggles,
seems stodgy in, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, a
``prettily torpid film with the warm glow of a hazelnut coffee
commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   CRUEL INTENTIONS
</P>
<P>
   1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $107.37. 95 minutes. Closed captioned.
R.
</P>
<P>
   Release date: Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   In a radical overhaul of Choderlos de Laclos' 18th-century novel
``Les Liaisons Dangereuses,'' the sexual predators are turned into
very late '90s teen-agers and placed in Manhattan. A nasty pair of
brats, Sebastian Valmont (Ryan Phillippe) and Kathryn Merteuil
(Sarah Michelle Gellar) plot the ruin of young friends and make a
bet. Either Valmont beds the very virtuous Annette (Reese
Witherspoon) or Kathryn gets his prized 1956 Jaguar. Half-baked
subplots involving bisexuality and interracial sex only further
undo a movie whose tone ``veers uncertainly between comedy and soap
opera'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   TANGO
</P>
<P>
   1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36. 100 minutes. Spanish with
English subtitles. PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Release date: Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Not much plot is required in Carlos Saura's thrilling film,
which wafts dreamily through countless forms of tango music. At the
center is Mario (Miguel Angel Sola), properly brooding and
smoldering, a director who, having been abandoned (cruelly) by his
wife, turns his attentions to a sylph (Mia Maestro) and gangster's
girlfriend. Heat to a boil in performances that alternately move
from decorous to furiously angry in a film that ``finds artful ways
to turn each tango encounter into something new'' (Janet Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   20 DATES
</P>
<P>
   1999. Fox. $100.98. 92 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Release date: Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about Myles Berkowitz, but he did come up with
a salable gimmick for a documentary. Date 20 different women in Los
Angeles and fall in love with one of them, all on camera. Berkowitz
doesn't mind embarrassing people, but he's often as dismissive of
himself as he is of others. That can be amusing, as are gambits
like not having enough money or getting kicked out of Spago for
bringing a camera crew. ``But whenever `20 Dates' begins to
establish a playful mood, it's liable to do something to make you
squirm'' (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   PAST RELEASES: LITTLE FILMS THAT ROAR
</P>
<P>
   Buried by any week's biggest renters (``A Civil Action,''
``She's All That'' and ``Saving Private Ryan'' are at the top of
the list this week) are a dozen or so fine smaller films that are
virtually made for catching up with on video. Here are some
examples from Video Business Magazine's list of best renters that
had limited theater release, playing on 475 screens or fewer:
</P>
<P>
   AFFLICTION. A small-town policeman (Nick Nolte) struggles to
control himself after a life of anguish under the thumb of a
drunken savage of a father (James Coburn). 1998. Universal. $99.36.
114 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   THE HI-LO COUNTRY. In a film by the British director Stephen
Frears, two young cowboys (Billy Crudup and Woody Harrelson) go
into the cattle business and fall for the same married woman
(Patricia Arquette). 1998. Polygram. $108.81. 114 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   HURLYBURLY. Adapted from David Rabe's play, Anthony Drazen's
film stars Sean Penn, Robin Wright Penn, Kevin Spacey and Chazz
Palminteri in a 1980s Hollywood war between men and women that
chooses macho camaraderie, sexual exploitation and drug abuse as
its weapons. 1998. New Line. $105.77. 122 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   GODS AND MONSTERS. Ian McKellen is the director James Whale,
whose thoughts of the past leave him vulnerable to an obsession
with his young gardener (Brendan Fraser). 1998. Universal. $99.91.
105 minutes. Closed captioned R.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER DAY IN PARADISE. In Larry Clark's colorful film, two
druggy older would-be Bonnie and Clydes (James Woods and Melanie
Griffith) take two younger ones (Vincent Kartheiser and Natasha
Gregson Wagner) on a slide to nowhere. 1998. Trimark. $99.99. 101
minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
</TEXT>
