<SLUG> BC-FOOD-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUESTION OF HONOR: TEXAS COMPANY WINS $14.5 MILLION IN FOOD
FIGHT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Okla.) 
 
By SHANNON BUGGS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Gene Chung has experienced every high and low a
small-business owner can have.
</P>
<P>
   His Chung's Gourmet Foods, which makes egg rolls and frozen
Oriental meals, has been recognized as one of the city's best
start-ups but has been on the verge of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   This week, however, a state district court jury in Houston
awarded his company $14.5 million in damages in a civil lawsuit
Chung brought against a competitor he says stole his biggest
client.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first experience with the judicial system,'' Chung
said. ``I am, of course, very pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Chung started his company in 1986 in a 3,000-square-foot plant
in the suburbs. In about three years, his factory was producing
80,000 egg rolls each day and his workers were stepping all over
each other to make them.
</P>
<P>
   He got a low-interest loan from a city-run economic development
program and in 1990 opened a plant closer to downtown. That
expansion allowed Chung's Gourmet Foods to compete with Minh Foods
Co. of nearby Pasadena, the nation's No. 1 egg roll producer in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, Chung had added frozen specialties, such as moo goo gai
pan, to its product line, employed 300 people and developed
vacuum-packed cartons shaped like traditional takeout containers.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the first setback occurred. In 1994, Chung's biggest
customer, Pace, a food wholesaler operating mainly in the
Northeast, closed its doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overnight Pace went out of business and overnight we lost $6
million,'' Chung said.
</P>
<P>
   But within a few months, VIP Sales Co. of Tulsa, Okla.,
approached Chung's about becoming the exclusive entree manufacturer
for VIP's Taipan line of frozen Oriental dinners. Chung already had
supplied VIP with frozen egg rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were doing some entrees on their own and we thought they
had the capability of making ours,'' said Guy W. Lewis, owner of
VIP, which freezes vegetables and fruits for its own brand as well
as private-label brands sold by grocery chains.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Chung's and VIP signed an exclusive three-year contract
for Chung's to make entrees only for Taipan and for VIP to buy
entrees for Taipan only from Chung's.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis says soon after they signed the agreement, the quality of
Chung's entrees went down. He says the company did not automate its
plant as quickly as it had promised, and it failed to include the
amounts of chicken, beef and vegetables in the meals specified by
VIP.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ended up with a lot of rice,'' Lewis said. ``We had a lot
of customer complaints, and we lost customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Chung, however, said his company followed VIP's orders to the
letter, including reducing the meat portion of the meals from 2
ounces to 1.2 ounces, so more of VIP's vegetables could be used in
the meals, reducing VIP's cost.
</P>
<P>
   The companies' differences would have been worked out, Chung
said, if a rival entree manufacturer had not become involved.
</P>
<P>
   At some point in 1995, VIP began talking with McKinney-based
Delta DailyFood of Texas, a subsidiary of a privately held Dutch
company. Lewis eventually decided to end the contract with Chung's
and begin using Delta DailyFood as his supplier.
</P>
<P>
   Chung responded with a breach of contract arbitration lawsuit in
1996. But the damage had been done. VIP represented $3.5 million in
revenue to Chung's every year, said Chung's attorney Adam Schiffer,
a partner with Vinson &AMP; Elkins in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``VIP was larger than all of Chung's 19 other customers,'' he
said. ``As a result of the termination of the contract, Chung's was
forced to the brink of bankruptcy.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Chung asked Yellowstone Capital, an equity investment
firm that also operates food supply companies, for help. The firm
gave Chung's an undisclosed amount of money in exchange for 70
percent ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called it a merger,'' said Chung, ``but they are now the
majority owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the arbitration proceedings ended in October after
eight months. Chung did not have the money to continue. But in
December of that year, Schiffer agreed to work on contingency while
Chung sued Delta DailyFood for tortious interference with a
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Under contract law, a business can be found to have interfered
in a contract if it knows or should know that the contract exists
and disregards that to pursue a relationship with one of the
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Chung's lawsuit contended Delta DailyFood knew about his
company's exclusive three-year contract with VIP and bullied VIP
into firing Chung's. The jury agreed and granted the company a
multimillion-dollar award based on an evaluation of how much the
firm lost because its contract with VIP ended prematurely. Chung's
attorneys were awarded $430,000 in fees.
</P>
<P>
   But Katrina Packard, an attorney for Delta DailyFood, said her
client was approached by VIP because that company wanted to be rid
of Chung's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my understanding that this happens all the time in
business,'' she said. ``I think consideration of an appeal is
imminent.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said no one twisted his arm about leaving Chung's and that
he testified to that at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot see how that jury awarded him that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the case is finally settled, if he gets any money from it,
Chung says he plans to try to buy back a majority stake in his
company. But he will discuss that with his partner to find out what
will work best for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this country, you have to honor a contract,'' he said.
``You cannot break it; you have to honor it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
