<HEADER>
A8890 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPORT-SPENDING-0730     07-29 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-SPENDING-0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    AIRPORTS LOOKING FOR MAJOR BOOST FROM CONGRESS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN GEORGIA, TEXAS, FLORIDA: Story contains funding estimates
for airports in your states 
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A massive influx of federal funds to expand and
renovate the nation's crammed airports has flown into a holding
pattern in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   With parts of current aviation law due to expire August 6, the
Senate has yet to schedule action on a bill to overhaul the
aviation system, amid concerns that a House-passed version will be
a budget-buster.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, aviation backers continue to hold high hopes for
legislation to modernize air traffic control systems and improve
airports that are stretched to the breaking point by a huge
increase in passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do believe that this year we'll see some movement,''
said Darryl Jenkins, professor of aviation at George Washington
University. ``Congress is now tackling this issue _ they've put it
off for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Such optimism is based partly on legislation that glided easily
through the House last spring. That bill, sponsored by
Transportation Committee Chairman Bud Shuster, R-Pa., would triple
annual payments to major airports from funds raised through ticket
and fuel taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would also raise the cap on airport fees from $3
to $6 per passenger, an increase that would be a potential boon,
especially to high-volume airports in the Sun Belt.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House bill, Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport
would receive $27 million beginning in the year 2001, triple its
current $9 million entitlement for construction and improvements.
And an increase in passenger fees could be a major source of added
revenue for Hartsfield, which in 1997 served 33 million passengers,
the most in the nation. Georgia's total entitlement for its major
airports would rise to $44.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, with its overall high volume of tourism, would receive
$100 million for its major airports, triple the current statewide
payment. Miami International Airport would get $14.7 million
compared with $4.9 million now. Fort Lauderdale's entitlement would
go up from $2.3 million to $6.8 million. And Palm Beach
International's payment would go from $1.5 million to $4.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Texas airports would receive $136 million compared with the
current rate of $45 million. Under the proposal, Houston and Dallas
combined would receive $48 million. Austin would be entitled to
$4.5 million in the House bill, compared with $1.5 million now.
</P>
<P>
   Airport managers would do well not to count on all of these
hikes in the House bill, which would cost $57 billion over four
years. The Senate version of the legislation would hold spending
close to current rates. And a bipartisan group of senators,
including Budget Chairman Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M., are protesting
a House plan to exempt the airport spending from budget limits. In
a letter to Senate leaders last week, they opposed ``any
legislation establishing special budgetary treatment for aviation
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, an expected House-Senate compromise later this year would
almost certainly increase spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic the way things are going,'' said Dan Molloy,
aviation design and construction manager at Hartsfield
International Airport. Molloy said that more federal funds would
ease the way for building two new taxiways and adding a fifth
runway in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Such expansions are needed nationwide, said Jenkins, as
congestion clogs airports, delays flights, and causes frustration
for the flying public, who are crammed into waiting areas and often
bumped from over-booked flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an air traffic control system at airports that on a
good day is totally maxed out,'' Jenkins said. ``There is no
flexibility at all.''
</P>
<P>
   With air traffic controllers still using antiquated equipment
and procedures, flights are frequently delayed and hundreds are
cancelled solely because of inadequate facilities, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins assigned the blame broadly: ``The airlines should have
brought this up as a problem years ago. The White House has not
shown proper respect to aviation infrastructure. The FAA (Federal
Aviation Administration) is bogged down in bureaucratic processes,
and the Congress holds hearings but does not act.''
</P>
<P>
   He said of the current legislation, ``Anything we do will make a
difference. We haven't done squat, so the problem keeps getting
larger.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
