<HEADER>
A8892 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-29 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET THE SKIRT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It can now be firmly said that First Lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton also wears the pants in her family, both literally
and figuratively.
</P>
<P>
   Natty, tailored pants suits in a range of cheerful colors have
become her favorite uniform for official events, from a simple silk
number for the daytime semi-announcement of her Senate candidacy to
a white satin affair for an evening theater gala. They are her new
trademark.
</P>
<P>
   We have grown so accustomed to the fresh look that reporters
were startled when she appeared in a rare skirt at the recent New
York memorial service for John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife and
sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Is it news that a first lady has a penchant for pants as the
20th century nears an end? Well, yes. It represents another break
with the stuffy traditions that historically have entombed first
ladies.
</P>
<P>
   As the first president's wife to have a professional career
before entering the White House, Hillary Clinton has steadily
sought ways to affirm her own identity. Her aggressive move into
public policy with a sweeping health care overhaul was not a
success. Nor were her many hairdos, until this latest simple cut.
</P>
<P>
   With her new attire, she is inescapably making a political
statement of independence and modernity. And it works.
</P>
<P>
   She also reflects the national inclination of both genders
toward increasingly casual dress in the workplace as well as at
home. She's a trendsetter. She is nudging fashion along, but not
doing anything really scary or radical.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing color-coordinated pants suits is smart of her. She looks
good in them _ and feminine to boot. They are more attractive on a
middle-aged woman than the clumsy mid-thigh-length skirts, the
dowdy long skirts or the too-provocative short-short skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Any female who sees herself on television in a short skirt
showing more leg than is tasteful as she goes down the steep stairs
from Air Force One to the tarmac is bound to desire a more flexible
and less constricting costume.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, often photographed
showing a great expanse of stockinged thigh while sitting beside
important world leaders and negotiating tough global issues, would
do well to copy the first lady's example.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, this sartorial change is unusual for a president's
wife. Hillary Clinton's predecessors were never photographed in
anything but skirts at public events. In the bad old days not so
long ago, slacks were considered unacceptably mannish.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon forbade his wife Patricia to be seen in slacks
even on their vacations, but Nancy Reagan wore jeans when she and
Ronald Reagan relaxed at their California ranch. Normally the
height of elegance, Mrs. Reagan did make a fashion blooper once by
appearing at a formal reception abroad in velvet knickers. The
knickers created a sensation of the wrong kind and were never seen
again.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs of Barbara Bush anywhere, even on vacation at the
family summer home in Kennebunkport, Maine, invariably show her in
skirts.
</P>
<P>
   But Tipper Gore, the vice president's wife, often emulates the
first lady by appearing at public events or posing for photographs
in pants suits. Female members of Congress are also spotted from
time to time in pants, although none wears them as regularly as
Hillary Clinton now does.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush's wife Laura sometimes shows up at
campaign events in pants. However, GOP presidential hopeful
Elizabeth Dole, a genuinely old-fashioned Southern belle, wears
only skirts.
</P>
<P>
   Female pants suits are part of every working woman's wardrobe.
This columnist is wearing one as she writes.
</P>
<P>
   On their new covers both bibles of the fashion world, Vogue and
Harper's Bazaar, feature models wearing pants rather than skirts.
Vogue's model wears a tasteful tan and red sporty number suitable
for most activities short of a formal ball. Bazaar opted for a
sleazy, sexy look appropriate for bar-hopping but not for political
campaigns or the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   The fashion industry itself is partly to blame for this confused
and transitional state of affairs. For two decades, designers have
been trying to put women in frivolous clothes that bag and sag,
fluff and puff, and make us look stupid. Enough already.
</P>
<P>
   We've been expected to look like impoverished waifs in skimpy
rags that cling to imperfect figures like limpets, or like tarts in
daytime sequins and fishnet stockings, or juveniles in shapeless
baby-doll dresses, or hags in weird costumes of clashing prints and
colors. The latest idiocy is the notion that women should wrap
themselves in bulky bedding-type material, waddling out into the
world as tubs of lard in outfits that would overflow ordinary
closets.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reports that the big Paris fashion show last
week was a strange collection of black leather outfits with
chain-link tunics, English hunting garb with feathered hats
featuring embalmed birds and jackets with collars of knitted balls.
The Times found much of it ``ludicrous.'' So would any woman in her
right mind, which Hillary Clinton definitely is.
</P>
<P>
   For much of this decade, working women hid out by wearing
so-called power suits, plain jackets with straight skirts cut off
primly at the knee and accompanied by plain blouses, often with
bows. Barbara Bush popularized three-strand pearls to go with this
ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   This was a safe approach to the tricky business of being taken
seriously in the office while still being attractive enough to
avoid the dreaded wallflower limbo after hours. But it was boring.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton has now shaken free of that dullness in favor of
functional, flattering outfits in which she seems comfortable. It's
her brains, not her legs, that count anyway.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
