<HEADER>
A8907 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKNOTES29-COX     07-29 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKNOTES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Booknotes: Old JFK Jr. bios selling, new ones upcoming
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the publishing world discovered when Princess Diana died in a
car accident, nothing sells books like the tragic death of a
much-loved celebrity. Expect the same with John F. Kennedy Jr.
Three previously published biographies of Kennedy already have hit
Amazon.com's Hot 100 list and the publishing dates of new bios have
been moved up.
</P>
<P>
   Currently available are ``The JFK Jr. Scrapbook'' (Citadel,
$15.95) by Stephen J. Spignesi; ``John F. Kennedy Jr.: A Life in
the Spotlight'' (Andrews McMee , $14.95) by Michael and Montague
Druitt; and ``Prince Charming: The John F. Kennedy Jr. Story''
(Signet, $6.99) by Wendy Leigh.
</P>
<P>
   According to Publishers Weekly, the books are going back to
press for updated editions that are expected to hit stores by this
weekend. Also arriving this week is ``The Kennedys: The Third
Generation'' (Pinnacle, $5.99) by Barbara Gibson and Ted Schwartz.
The paperback originally was scheduled to hit stores in October.
</P>
<P>
   Other books in the works are ``The Kennedy Weddings'' by St.
Martin's Press and ``The Kennedy Men'' by Laurence Leamer. And C.
David Heymann, the author of ``A Woman Named Jackie,'' has pitched
a proposal for a new JFK Jr. bio.
</P>
<P>
   So far, sales of books about the Kennedys are not that great,
says Chapter 11 bookstore owner Barbara Babbitt Kaufman, but she
expects that to change once the books about JFK Jr. arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are waiting for these,'' she says. ``And on the `Prince
Charming' book, they're going back to press in hardback. That's how
strongly they believe the books will sell.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about making a profit from tragedy?
</P>
<P>
   Neither the authors nor the booksellers see it that way.
``People want to know more,'' author Spignesi said in one
interview. ``That's just the nature of American society.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman agrees. ``You're giving the consumer something to
perpetuate the memory. ''
</P>
<P>
   -- Teen tomes: Contrary to popular belief, teenagers do read
books. In a survey, Book magazine reports that 61 percent of kids
between 12 and 19 say they read books for pleasure. Of course,
that's not as many as watch television (98 percent), but it's
encouraging. And they aren't just reading trash. Matthew Smith, 16,
a student at Paideia School in Atlanta, told the magazine two of
his favorite authors are Victor Hugo and Ray Bradbury. Others list
John Grisham, Mary Higgins Clark and Stephen King as their
favorites, but they also read Jane Austen, William Faulkner and
Shakespeare. What should teens be reading? Anything is better than
nothing, but Book magazine's recommendations include ``The Perks of
Being a Wallflower'' by Stephen Chbosky, ``East of Eden'' by John
Steinbeck, ``The True Confessions of Charlotte Doyle'' by Avi,
``Slaughterhouse Five'' by Kurt Vonnegut and ``Rule of the Bone''
by Russell Banks.
</P>
<P>
   -- Politics and publishing: Hillary Rodham Clinton will be in
the publishing spotlight as well as the political when she
officially starts her Senate campaign in New York. ReganBooks has
signed Peggy Noonan, a former Reagan speechwriter, to write a book
about the first lady's campaign. ``The Case Against Hillary
Clinton'' will be published next spring. Meanwhile, Gail Sheehy's
biography, ``Hillary's Choice,'' is scheduled for release in
September from Random House, and Christopher Andersen's ``Bill and
Hillary: The Marriage'' is due from Morrow in late August. Still to
come next year from HarperCollins is ``The First Couple, State of a
Union'' by Jerry Oppenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   -- Making a point: The spring/summer issue of Five Points,
Georgia State University's literary magazine edited by Pam Durban
and David Bottoms, has an impressive lineup of talent. In addition
to a short story by Alice Hoffman and essays by Andre Dubus and
Rick Bass, the magazine features an in-depth interview with
Frederick Busch, author of the critically acclaimed novel ``The
Night Inspector.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
