<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8908 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-FIRE01-COX     07-29 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-FIRE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winslow's cool insurance-fraud thriller is one fiery-fun read
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, AUG. 1
 &HT;    By J. Edwin Smith
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Incendiary is the word that best describes Don Winslow's latest
novel. To use the vernacular of its lead character, Jack Wade:
``Surf's up, dude. So let the sparks fly. Let the eagles feast.
Let's go dance with the (expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   The expletive in question is fire _ what Prometheus gave to man
to warm his caves, cook his food, incinerate his fellow man in all
manner of nasty combustion. Which is where Jack Wade comes into
play. He adjusts fire claims for California Fire &AMP; Life Mutual. Too
often, it's grisly work: dudes crawling inside a booze bottle,
tanking out and lighting a cigarette, then dozing off with the
cigarette smoldering on the sheets, which eventually ignite. And
when that happens, says Wade, ``What's left is ... ah, well, you
end up scraping the dudes off the bed springs.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the coroner had to do with Pamela Vale. Police
contend she was a drunk and druggie, that when she zonked out with
a lit cigarette and subsequently became a crispy critter, it was
her own fault, which is why they rule the fire to be accidental.
</P>
<P>
   Whoaaaaaa, says Jack. Pamela had supposedly dried out. And she
didn't smoke. At least not until she was lying in bed with the
flames licking at her thighs. It just doesn't make sense. And what
about the fact that her financially strapped husband filed the
insurance claim on the very morning his wife and heavily mortgaged
house went up in flames?
</P>
<P>
   There you have it: the making of a good novel. Why, any rube
could take it from there and hold your attention. But only a Don
Winslow could make this bad boy snap, crackle and pop. Only a Don
Winslow could make you cringe and laugh within seconds of each
other. The man's gift for creating biting prose is that good.
</P>
<P>
   Incorporating Left Coast ``cool dude'' dialogue, a cast of truly
memorable characters and a masterful plot device that sizzles from
the book's opening page to its flashpoint finish, Winslow gives new
meaning to the term ``hot read.''
</P>
<P>
   There's something here for everybody. Winslow gives us a
penetrating insider's glimpse of the compost heap that is the
insurance industry. He puts us into the shoes of an arsonist, takes
us into a warehouse and allows us to strike the match; then he lays
out the telltale evidence that, long after the flames have been
quenched, would send us to jail.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, though, Winslow gives us a true
villain: Mother Russia, a character as despicable as anything in
recent memory, including Hannibal Lecter.
</P>
<P>
   -- FICTION
</P>
<P>
   California Fire and Life. By Don Winslow. Knopf. $24. 337 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Burn, baby, burn.
</P>
<P>
   J. Edwin Smith is a page designer for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitu-
</P>
<P>
   tion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
