</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MYSTERY ROUNDUP: Taking notice of series sleuths' latest
goings-on
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, AUG. 1
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sleuth, more than plot, is central to long-running mystery
series featuring characters fans have come to know. One reads the
newest novels about Kay Scarpetta, Kathleen Mallory and Lou Boldt
to keep tabs on the events of their lives as much as to find out
whodunit.
</P>
<P>
   -- Black Notice by Patricia Cornwell
</P>
<P>
   (Putnam, $25.95).
</P>
<P>
   Kay Scarpetta, chief medical examiner of Virginia, is not
holding up well after the gruesome death of her lover, Benton
Wesley. In addition to dealing with her grief, she faces a
multitude of problems: A disgruntled employee sets up a bogus and
embarrassing Internet chat room in her name, a new woman police
chief seems bent on destroying her and police officer Pete Marino's
credibility, niece Lucy gets involved in a dangerous drug sting
that goes wrong, an unidentified body shows up in a ship from
Europe and a serial killer with werewolf (yes, werewolf)
characteristics is savaging women. The search for the killer takes
Kay to Europe and Interpol, to events in her past and into the arms
of a new lover.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery is not without flaws: At times, Marino's bluster
grows tiresome, and Kay's lapse of judgment at the end of the book
seems a demand of plot rather than a function of character. But
this is one of Cornwell's better reads and holds up because of its
Gothic overtones. Evil increasingly becomes incarnate in
Scarpetta's universe, inveigling its way through the seem-
</P>
<P>
   ingly secure doors of one's house and heart.
</P>
<P>
   -- Shell Game by Carol O'Connell (Putnam, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell, whose last work was the outstanding ``Judas Child,''
excels in complex psychological explorations. ``Shell Game'' is
perhaps her riskiest and most ambitious book. The novel opens in
the mind of Malakhai, a magician in a private hospital in upstate
New York. As he awakes from a dream or from a minor stroke, he
watches a magician friend die performing a trick on television.
Kathleen Mallory of the New York Police Department, convinced that
the death is not an accident, investigates it, and ensuing deaths,
with risk to her reputation, life and career. The magical murder
tour takes her into the past, to Nazi Germany, to the death of
Malakhai's wife (from a magic trick during the war), into the
psychotic, to Malakhai, with whom she becomes enchanted.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell admirably treads the tightrope between appearance and
reality, memory and history, the magic and mundane. But events are
obscured by the book's permeating hallucinogenic haze that depletes
reader interest in the identity of the murderers (past and present)
or the mechanics of their dastardly tricks. Still O'Connell
achieves a nuanced portrait of the increasingly anti-social
Mallory, who perhaps because of her own brush with psychosis in
childhood, understands the darker chambers of the human mind.
</P>
<P>
   -- The First Victim by Ridley Pearson
</P>
<P>
   (Hyperion, $23.95).
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of his ``Pied Piper,'' a chilling page turner about
a ring of kidnappers, Pearson gives us another installment in the
life and career of Seattle police detective Lou Boldt. Someone is
illegally shipping Chinese women into the United States, where they
are enslaved in sweatshops. When some of the women die, Boldt and
Sgt. John LaMoia are assigned to the case. Their investigation is
made more difficult by an arrogant Immigration and Naturalization
Service official and a woman TV anchor whose Asian-born adopted
sister has disappeared while reporting on the case.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to care for anybody besides Boldt in this book, and
the plot is only intermittently engaging. LaMoia is remarkably
sexist, the TV anchor surpasses all ethical bounds, Boldt's wife,
though courageously fighting cancer, may grate on readers' nerves.
And the characterization of a Chinese woman connected to the
underworld borders on the stereotypical. All in all, a rare
disappointment from Pearson.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
