<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-NOTES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POP MUSIC NOTES
 &HT;    Fresh Fatboy Slim puts new spin on old beat
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, AUG. 1
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Records skipping. CDs jamming. Syllables frozen, isolated and
repeated, faster and faster or slower and slower until they lose
all conscious meaning and dissolve into hypnotic dada poetry, so
much verbal vertigo.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Cook, the British DJ sensation who is conquering the
United States as the clever oxymoron named Fatboy Slim, understands
the genius of repetition. His music thrives on stuttered catch
phrases, crazy walloping rhythms and twitchy eccentric grooves,
monstrous guitar and keyboard riffs that lurch and swoop out of the
flux, only to keep lurching and swooping. With two turntables, a
modest mixing board and a bunch of vinyl LPs, he creates
psychedelic fugues and roaring funk frenzies. In the United
Kingdom, it's called Big Beat. Here, it's the trendiest background
noise ever, the skittish pulse of hip TV commercials, movie
soundtracks, video games.
</P>
<P>
   It's what drew about 2,000 teen and college-age kids to the
Tabernacle recently, tweaked to the gills on ... mere nervous
energy?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its guise _ techno, house, big beat, electronica,
garage _ this is music that seems to achieve much of its punch from
extra-musical stimulants. As pop events go, Fatboy Slim's show was
at once anachronistic and slightly ahead of its time. The vibe,
enhanced by two large screens flashing with images of vaguely
ominous smiley faces and animated geometric patterns, was very
1960s, a psychedelic light show upgraded for the MTV-saturated.
Yet, there was no band, just the devilishly grinning Cook pirating
everything from Who licks (at least it sounded like the opening
chords of ``I Can't Explain'') to percolating bongo beats to the
surf guitars and infectious mantra _ ``Right about now, the funk
soul brother'' _ of his stateside breakthrough hit, ``Rockafeller
Skank.'' At most concerts, the moment when the headlining act
arrives on stage is dramatic. You kind of lose that when it's just
some guy who looks like he wandered in off the beach, toting a bin
of old records.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, well: that's the 1999 part. We live in the post-rock era, if
an era can be telescopically redefined as five or six years. Like a
scavenger in a dystopian Mad Max adventure, Fatboy Slim sorts
through the wreckage and builds a wacky go kart. What surprised was
how entertaining he was behind those wheels of steel. He had moves
to match the hyper-kinetic music: cocking his head back and forth
like a parrot; wagging his fingers at the crowd like a gunslinger;
half-circling his hand in the air, as if ``spinning'' the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Historically speaking, Norman Cook isn't up to anything new.
Steve Reich, one of the important composers to emerge from the
minimalist movement of the '60s, was messing around with tape
recorders and repeated phrases that looped in and out of sync on
his 1965 piece ``It's Gonna Rain,'' which features the voice of a
San Francisco Pentecostal street preacher named Brother Walter. At
17 minutes and 47 seconds, ``It's Gonna Rain'' is best appreciated
by the dedicated private listener late at night on headphones. I've
used it to drive people out of my house. What's new is that, 34
years after Reich toted his microphone out to a public square,
people will pay $25 to experience a funkier version of the same
thing. Contemporary DJs even pay homage on the recently issued CD,
``Reich Remixed'' (Nonesuch). Though conceptually nifty, the
project mostly suggests the DJs would be better off digging up
their own discrete sources.
</P>
<P>
   That's the beauty of Fatboy Slim. He sounds fresh, even though
he's not. When they start selling those '90s hit compilations on
cable TV in a couple of years, the DJ's latest CD ``You've Come a
Long Way, Baby'' (Skint/Astralwerks) will likely provide a few
tracks. It's the sound of these times and proof, too, that what
comes around goes around. Like an old record.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
