<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8913 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-RAP01-COX     07-29 2281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-RAP01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    White rappers: Hip-hop hybrids shaking up rock
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, AUG. 1
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greetings from Screamville. A few thousand preteen girls are
yelling, bouncing up and down, waving their hands in the air on a
recent late afternoon at Lakewood Amphitheatre. Atlanta-based
entertainer DJ Nabs mans a turntable at the side of the stage,
where the hot new boy band 98 Degrees will perform later.
</P>
<P>
   That's why all the girls are here. But that's not what prompts
their energetic outburst. It's the disc Nabs is spinning: hard-core
rapper DMX's ``Ruff Ryders Anthem,'' a tune whose undeniable
rhythmic insurgency has even the kindergarten crew getting down.
</P>
<P>
   Roll back a few months to Atlanta's Music Midtown festival. Kid
Rock, a 27-year-old Detroit performer who describes his fusion of
hip-hop rhymes and AC/DC riffs as ``hick-hop,'' is onstage. He
surveys a tightly packed crowd of maybe 10,000, mostly white fans
in their teens and early 20s, hoisting beers and pumping their
fists to his testosterone-fueled anthems of lowlife misadventures.
When Kid Rock glances up, he can't miss a downtown billboard
plastered with his likeness. Braided hair, cigar jutting from the
side of his mouth, flashy clothes, bowler. If his music is equal
parts Ted Nugent and Sugarhill Gang, he must have taken his fashion
tips from Iceberg Slim's ``Pimp: The Story of My Life.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to connect the dots between these two scenes. If
rap music once was the preserve of Bronx housing projects, it's now
something that any budding young music consumer grows up listening
to. Four decades after Norman Mailer's classic essay ``The White
Negro'' called attention to the birth of the hipster, urban black
culture _ blues and jazz in the 1950s, rap in the 1990s _ continues
to transform the popular culture around it. At this point, in fact,
hip-hop is the popular culture, and everything else adapts to it.
</P>
<P>
   Especially rock music, which in recent months has tapped into
rap's raw voltage to challenge the chart supremacy of manufactured
pop acts such as Britney Spears, the Backstreet Boys and their
sugar-coated like. Performers, such as Kid Rock, whose ``Devil
Without a Cause'' has spawned three hit singles, Florida's seething
Limp Bizkit and California's proud-to-be-dysfunctional Korn, have
discovered the merits of grafting hip-hop trappings onto rock's
power chords. Meanwhile, a former white rapper, Everlast of the
group House of Pain (``Jump Around''), has crossed over to the
modern rock charts with his socially conscious ``Whitey Ford Sings
the Blues,'' a cycle of cautionary tales that translate as hip-hop
for the coffeehouse crowd. More comically, there are the Detroit
acts Eminem (``My Name Is ...'') _ now on the road with the
mosh-happy Warped Tour _ and Insane Clown Posse, who play
disturbing scenarios for outlandish, often self-deprecating effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen anything like this since the early grunge days
when Nirvana came out of nowhere,'' says Leslie Fram, program
director of Atlanta's influential rock station 99X (WNNX-FM), which
has aggressively pushed Kid Rock and Limp Bizkit. ``It's the
biggest phenomenon. Limp Bizkit sold 22,000 records in Atlanta in
less than three weeks. Its album (`Significant Other') debuted at
No. 1 and stayed for three weeks against mass appeal acts like
Ricky Martin.''
</P>
<P>
   What's significant, Fram notes, is that bands such as Limp
Bizkit and Korn _ which had formerly cultivated an underground
audience _ ``are making videos for MTV and recording songs that can
be played on the radio.'' Fram laughs, acknowledging that the music
is still the edgiest in its format. ``A 30-year-old female who
listens to 99X may not want to hear (Limp Bizkit's) `The Nookie' at
lunchtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, that poses no obstacle to other listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing artificial about this. Anyone younger than 24
has pretty much lived their entire conscious life with hip-hop,''
says Jim Kerr, alternative radio editor for the industry
publication Radio &AMP; Records. ``Rock as a genre has transformed
itself and embraced a new point of view by including hip-hop
elements. Rock has gone through grunge and the corporate rock of
the '80s and punk, but it's all various shades of angry vocals over
guitar, bass and drums. You haven't seen a whole lot of stylistic
change since the Beatles. Nothing in terms of genre-bending has
happened to rock like we're seeing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck D, whose seminal rap group Public Enemy has exerted a
strong influence over rock acts since the late 1980s, isn't as
impressed. ``This topic is old, man,'' says the Atlanta-based
performer, who raps on the ``metal'' version of ``P.E. 2000,'' the
new single from Puff Daddy. The track features Concentration Camp,
Chuck D's latest project, which approaches the hybrid from the
hip-hop side. ``I don't know why people keep talking about it. When
MTV did `Yo! MTV Raps' back in the '80s, that right there told us
white kids love rap. They didn't put that show on for black kids.
So, the white kids tuned in, they've bought into the culture and
now people are trying to emulate, do it, incorporate it into their
music. What?''
</P>
<P>
   The difference is one of scale. Fifteen years ago, an all-white
rap act such as the Beastie Boys was a novelty, just as the notion
of a commercial radio station broadcasting songs as dissonant as
Limp Bizkit's or Korn's was merely punkish wishful thinking. But
when bands as self-consciously square as Canada's jokey Barenaked
Ladies can kick their record sales into overdrive by rapping, as
the group does on its 1998 hit ``One Week,'' it's clear pop culture
has turned another corner.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is the subject of satire. Performance artist Danny
Hoch, a Jewish New Yorker, deals with the subject in the upcoming
comedy movie ``Whiteboys.'' It's an extension of Hoch's bold stage
work. In one sketch, he portrays a white Midwestern rapper named
Flip who points to a dark mole on his arm, declaring that it's his
``real'' skin color. Flip's bedroom fantasy _ of ``representing''
to Jay Leno on late-night national TV _ is demolished only when his
mother calls from downstairs, demanding he take out the trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in the most multi-ethnic county in the world _
Queens, New York,'' Hoch says. ``So, there was and is a hip-hop
community that is composed of Jews, blacks, Arabs, Latinos _ you
name it. That was the case in 1979, and that's the case now. Now,
if I would have gone to Harlem, that would have been another story.
Assimilation takes time, doesn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Hoch's routine, part of the 1998 show ``Jails, Hospitals &AMP;
Hip-Hop,'' emphasizes the contradictions inherent in such a trend.
If hip-hop is an African-American concept, what is the cultural
identity of a white entertainer who appropriates it? And if someone
such as Kid Rock or Limp Bizkit vocalist Fred Durst is commanding
platinum record sales and sold-out concerts, is he adding something
to hip-hop's legacy or cashing in on it?
</P>
<P>
   Such rhetoric makes for a lively debate. There's plenty to be
found on the Internet newsgroup rec.music.hiphop, which recently
included 83 responses to the subject, ``Does Kid Rock have any
hip-hop credentials?'' Kid Rock and Eminem are dismissed as ``fake
wannabes from the suburbs'' and Limp Bizkit is written off as
MTV-driven ``rapcore.'' Yet, as a fan points out, hip-hop is the
most promiscuous of genres. To argue otherwise risks, well,
hypocrisy. ``I guess Cypress Hill is ruining hip-hop too because
they did a song with Pearl Jam,'' argues a newsgroup poster called
DarkNinja, cataloging a batch of rap-rock collaborations. ``I guess
(rapper) Kool Keith is wack because he did a song with Prodigy.
Public Enemy must be wack, because they worked with Anthrax.
Run-DMC must be wack, because they worked with Aerosmith.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy highlights the prime directive of hip-hop, which
is to ``keep it real.'' These rockers who rap attempt to establish
their credibility by disavowing ``skin privilege,'' and stressing
how socially and economically disenfranchised they were before they
became famous. Kid Rock, who grew up in rural Michigan as the son
of a wealthy car dealer, nonetheless touts the virtues of such
``white trash'' intoxicants as Pabst Blue Ribbon and Jim Beam
bourbon and is backed by a musician named DJ Kracker. He says his
music comes ``straight out of the trailer park.'' Eminem, whose
rueful adolescence and adult domestic squabbles provide much of the
backdrop for his debut, ``The Slim Shady LP,'' was actually living
in a trailer when his record hit the charts. He came home from a
tour to find an eviction notice. Durst, who grew up poor in
Gastonia, N.C., tells stories of how his white friends ostracized
him in high school because of his affection for rap music.
</P>
<P>
   As Chuck D contends, this isn't new. It's part of an endlessly
repeating cycle that generates from the core of American culture.
Go back to the early 1950s, and it was Elvis Presley or Jerry Lee
Lewis sneaking into black roadhouses or frequenting Sunday gospel
marathons in East Memphis or Ferriday, La., swept away by what they
would soon learn to synthesize into rock 'n' roll. It wasn't new
then.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as whites could observe blacks dancing and singing
along the coasts of the new world, they started grabbing those
moves, talking and dressing black, and promoting that culture as
the ne plus ultra of authenticity,'' says W.T. Lhamon Jr., a
professor at Florida State University in Tallahassee and the author
of ``Raising Cain: Blackface Performance From Jim Crow to Hip Hop''
(Harvard; 1997). ``The whole concept of white trash and disdained
black forms has been the generative swap meet for Atlantic popular
culture since the 1830s _ since the onset of the Industrial
Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   The new wave of dirty white boys may be reinvigorating rock
music or could be toppled from the charts by the next unpredictable
trend. But what's more notable is how these performers also are
playing out a story. Those little girls learning how to groove from
a DMX record, or the masses who hailed Kid Rock at Woodstock '99
last weekend, are a part of it, even if they don't know it yet.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution Staff writer Sonia Murray
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   SUBURBAN RAP WANNABES
</P>
<P>
   Kid Rock
</P>
<P>
   -- Album: ``Devil Without a Cause'' (Top Dog/Atlantic)
</P>
<P>
   -- Real name: Bob Ritchie, 27. Got his name as a teenager, while
DJ-ing in Detroit's black housing projects: ``Yo, watch that white
kid rock!''
</P>
<P>
   -- Home turf: Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   -- M.O.: Early career derailed in early '90s due to white rapper
credibility crisis caused by fluke success of Vanilla Ice. Got back
on track as a self-proclaimed ``white trash'' rapper who drinks
Pabst Blue Ribbon beer and listens to Lynyrd Skynyrd.
</P>
<P>
   -- What's unusual: Tours with a 3-foot, 9-inch midget.
</P>
<P>
   Eminem
</P>
<P>
   -- Album: ``The Slim Shady LP'' (Interscope)
</P>
<P>
   -- Real name: Marshall Mathers, 24. Thought up his alter ego
Slim Shady while sitting on the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   -- Home turf: Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   -- M.O.: Grew up poor and transient, was beat up a lot as a kid,
has issues with his mother. His album takes revenge fantasies to
violent extremes, but undercuts the sociopathology with comic
effects (nasal delivery, quirky samples). Hip-hop producer Dr.
Dre's big discovery.
</P>
<P>
   -- What's unusual: He's a pretty good rapper.
</P>
<P>
   Everlast
</P>
<P>
   -- Album: ``Whitey Ford Sings the Blues'' (Tommy Boy).
</P>
<P>
   -- Real name: Eric Schrody, 29. Everlast is the name of an
athletic gear manufacturer best known for its boxing trunks. He
plays Atlanta Aug. 18 at The Tabernacle.
</P>
<P>
   -- Home turf: Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   -- M.O.: Made a name with House of Pain, an Irish-American
hip-hop act influenced by Cypress Hill. The group's DJ Lethal is
now a member of Limp Bizkit. Reinvented himself as a kind of
latter-day Richie Havens, singing about the wages of inner-city sin
for alternative rock fans.
</P>
<P>
   -- What's unusual: Survived major heart attack while recording
his album.
</P>
<P>
   Limp Bizkit
</P>
<P>
   -- Album: ``Significant Other'' (Interscope).
</P>
<P>
   -- Lead vocalist: Fred Durst, 28. Supposedly, a ``limp bizkit''
is slang for the kind of thing that's probably the subject of a
Marilyn Manson rumor on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   -- Home turf: Jacksonville
</P>
<P>
   -- M.O.: One-time tattoo artist and hip-hop fan Durst was
befriended by California metal act Korn, which helped the group get
signed and put it on its ``Family Values'' tour. The new release,
the group's second, is sharply produced with radio-friendly fare to
help the band expand from its hard-core audience built up through
constant touring. Acts like Rage Against the Machine, Cypress Hill
and Wu-Tang Clan are key reference points.
</P>
<P>
   -- What's unusual: Durst is a devout Lutheran. He also has made
a cameo appearance in a porn film.
</P>
<P>
   Insane Clown Posse
</P>
<P>
   -- Album: ``The Amazing Jeckel Brothers'' (Island).
</P>
<P>
   -- Band members: Shaggy 2 Dope and Violent J, who are in their
20s. And if those aren't their real names, they should be.
</P>
<P>
   -- Home turf: Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   -- M.O.: They're clowns. And they're insane.
</P>
<P>
   -- What's unusual: The vividly theatrical duo actually sells a
lot of records. First gained national notoriety when Disney
subsidiary Hollywood Records dropped them from its roster
immediately upon the release of its major-label debut. Best known
for spraying untold gallons of Michigan-made Faygo soft drinks on
fanatically enthused audiences.
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
