<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8918 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-BUGATTI-ART-NYT &LR;      07-29 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-BUGATTI-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUGATTI: GENERATIONS OF ARTISTRY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By CHERYL JENSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say ``Bugatti,'' and most people think ``automobile.''
</P>
<P>
   That perception may soon change, thanks to the first American
exhibition devoted to the work of three generations of the Bugatti
family that took its artistry from Milan to Paris to Alsace.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, exclusive to the Cleveland Museum of Art,
showcases furniture and silver designed by Carlo Bugatti
(1856-1940) and the animal sculpture of his son Rembrandt
(1884-1916). But the drawing card probably will be the automobiles
designed by another son, Ettore Bugatti (1881-1947) and Ettore's
son, Jean (1909-39). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other families have produced multiple generations of artists,
like the Bachs and Strausses in music and the Barrymores in
theater. But the Bugattis stand out because each found a different
medium for expression, said Henry Hawley, the Cleveland museum's
curator who organized the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, secrets of production are passed through family
lines, so they tend to focus on the same sort of things instead of
each one doing something different,'' Hawley said. ``The Bugattis
were not that way. If they shared anything, it was the desire for
originality and working with their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   And they liked eggs _ or at least the ovoid shape.
</P>
<P>
   The Bugatti automobile gained its reputation through racing.
Ettore's Type 35 won more than 1,000 races from 1924 to 1940. The
Type 57 was the most commercially successful Bugatti car, with 680
built in 1930-40. The Atlantic Type 57SC, included in this
exhibition, was designed by Jean and is considered by many to be
the most beautiful automobile ever made. Jean's career was cut
short in 1939 when he was killed in a crash while testing one of
his Le Mans race cars.
</P>
<P>
   While racing established the reputation of Bugatti automobiles,
Hawley says their allure has lived on because of the beauty of the
design.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is said that probably a higher percentage of Bugattis
survive than any other automobile ever made,'' he said. ``They do
survive because they are admired.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the six automobiles in the exhibition, two of the best-known
are the Type 41 Royale, owned by the Henry Ford Museum and
Greenfield Village in Dearborn, Mich., and Ralph Lauren's Type 57SC
Atlantic. And all but two _ the Type 51 race car and the Baby
Bugatti, a small-scale version of a '30s racing car _ are Jean
Bugatti's design.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, which includes nearly 80 objects, runs through
Sept. 19. Tickets can be ordered by calling (888) 262-0033 (outside
Cleveland) or (216) 421-7350 (in Cleveland) or through the museum's
Web site: www.clemusart.com. Admission is $5 on weekdays and $7 on
Saturdays and Sundays; discounts are offered for students and
groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
