<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Friday, July 30. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Pat Ryan. The final FRONTPAGE will move later in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT _ After two years of galloping growth, the American
economy took a breather this spring. But that slowdown was
overshadowed by an unexpected spike in labor costs, an important
early inflation warning signal closely monitored by Alan Greenspan,
the chairman of the Federal Reserve. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   GA-SHOOT (Atlanta) _ More than 20 people reported shot by gunman
in an Atlanta office building. Developing. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Republican dissension over how to
regulate managed care spilled into the open in the House on
Thursday, forcing Speaker Dennis Hastert to acknowledge that he
would likely have to abandon plans to take up the politically
potent issue before the August recess. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-IMMIG (San Francisco) _ Gov. Gray Davis and opponents of
Proposition 187 reach an agreement. The state will now end its
challenge to a federal court's ruling that rejected Prop 187, which
would bar state services to illegal immigrants. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   NONSTOP-EATING (Chicago) _ On a Sunday morning at a Roman
Catholic church here, Mary Hallan Fiorito glanced at a nearby pew
to see a woman drinking a can of Coke during the Mass. At a musical
in a Broadway theater in New York, Alex Wang turned to the row
behind him to discover people eating corn on the cob. In schools
that once forbade chewing gum, students now bring doughnuts and
candy to class. Americans seem to be eating all the time, and
wherever they please. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JONES (Washington) _ A federal judge Thursday ordered
President Clinton to pay nearly $90,000 to lawyers for Paula Jones
in compensation for extra work they performed due to the
president's false testimony about his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LI-RAILROAD (New York) _ A status report on one of New York
City's major commuter systems. By David M. Halbfinger.
</P>
