<HEADER>
A8941 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-BRIDE30-COX     07-29 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BRIDE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unbridled `Runaway': Paired with Gere again, Roberts rides high
in a lightweight charmer
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``Runaway Bride''
 &HT;    Grade: B
 &HT;    Starring Julia Roberts and Richard Gere. Directed by Garry
Marshall. Rated PG for mild language and sexual innuendo. 1 hour,
 &HT;    56 minutes. At metro theaters.
 &HT;    The verdict: Not a runaway success, but a good bet for its
intended audience.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Garry Marshall didn't create Julia Roberts, but he did
a pretty good Pygmalion job on her when he cast her opposite
Richard Gere in 1990's ``Pretty Woman'' and made that Roberts smile
world famous.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later, Marshall, Roberts, Gere and second banana
Hector Elizondo have reunited for ``Runaway Bride,'' a not so
subtle attempt to cajole lightning into striking twice.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it doesn't. But that doesn't mean ``Runaway Bride'' is a
fiasco. It seems to me that there'll always be an audience for a
movie in which Roberts, wearing full wedding regalia, gallops on
horseback across gorgeous countryside. And that, in a nutshell, is
what ``Runaway Bride'' is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there is a plot. A pretty simple one. Ike Graham (Gere) is
a hotshot, streetwise columnist on speaking terms with everyone
from senators to construction workers. One day he's doing his usual
``research'' _ i.e., downing a cold one at a local bar _ when a
fellow barfly suggests that he do a story about one Maggie
Carpenter (Roberts) from Hale, Md. It seems that Maggie has gone
down the aisle three times and choked at the altar every time. Now
she's scheduled for a fourth trip, and Ike decides there's a story
in her almost certain flight. (There are intermediary
complications, but that would be telling.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Ike shows up in Hale, where, to Maggie's chagrin,
everybody in town _ including her groom (Christopher Meloni), her
best friend (Joan Cusack) and her father (Paul Dooley) _ is happy
to help him out. ``You're going to run again,'' Ike tells her.
``And I'm not leaving until you do.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie never completely capitalizes on its screwball premise;
imagine what Preston Sturges would've done with it. Marshall is too
much of a softie; he meanders around the story, milking it for both
sentiment and comedy and often tripping over himself in the
process. Still, his idea of small-town America is amusing _ a
crossroads of Mayberry and MTV. And he certainly knows how to
present his leading lady in every possible permutation of adorable,
whether she's radiant in bridal tulle or roguish in overalls. After
a while, you find yourself looking forward to the next scene mostly
to see how she'll wear her hair. But at least you're still looking.
</P>
<P>
   As for the ``Pretty Woman'' comparisons, they're almost beside
the point. This movie doesn't have the sheer sparkle of its
predecessor. How could it? ``Pretty Woman'' seemed as delighted to
discover Roberts as we were. Plus, there was the fairy tale quality
offered by Gere's super-rich character who could whisk poor little
hooker Julia off to polo games and the opera. Finally, almost a
decade has passed. Gere isn't a big '80s star looking for a
comeback, and Roberts isn't a semi-known waiting to unleash her
magic. As for Elizondo, his role is minuscule and he spends most of
his time with Rita Wilson, well-cast as Gere's boss and ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Runaway Bride'' is in no way a critics' movie. But you hope
that it's critic-proof, like such less deserving films as ``Wild
Wild West'' and ``The Haunting.'' Because, sometimes, you just need
to see Julia Roberts in full wedding regalia galloping on horseback
across the screen, and across our collective romantic fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   On-screen chemistry a mystery to Richard Gere P7
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
