<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, July 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By 1 p.m. local time Thursday, the mercury had already soared to
101 degrees at Pierre, S.D., a reading symptomatic of the extreme
heat gripping the upper Middle West. The overall pattern of the jet
stream will shift a bit, Friday and Saturday, signaling an easing
of hot weather across the northern Plains and western Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   For much of July, a phalanx of three very warm and expansive
high pressure systems over the eastern Pacific, the Middle West and
the western Atlantic created a very stable and generally hot
weather pattern across much of the contiguous states. A consequence
of this stable pattern was the restraining of the jet stream, which
was locked over southern Canada and parts of the northern-tier
states. But the eastern Pacific high will shift northward toward
the Gulf of Alaska on Friday and Saturday, a deviation that will
cause the jet stream to buckle southward over the upper Middle
West, allowing cooler air to ooze south from Canada. As a result,
high temperatures on Saturday across the region will range from the
upper 70s to the upper 80s.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south and east, however, heat and humidity will hold
steady through Saturday across the southern Plains, the Gulf Coast
states, the Southeast, the middle Mississippi and Ohio valleys, the
eastern Great Lakes and the Middle Atlantic states. Isolated to
widely separated thunderstorms will offer spotty, temporary relief.
Hot and humid air will surge back into New York state and parts of
New England by Saturday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Hot Topic &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Bismarck, N.D., the mercury soared above 100 degrees during
the last couple of days for the first time in nearly eight years.
The searing heat ended the longest period without 100-degree
temperatures in Bismarck since records began in 1884. The
protracted lack of very hot days in Bismarck is a reflection of the
natural regional variations that are a part of the Earth's climate.
Periods of unusual heat, chill, wetness and dryness that last for
many years or decades are probably related to the complex
interactions between the oceans and the atmosphere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
