<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8943 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHECKS-Y2K-0730-COX     07-29 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECKS-Y2K-0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOCIAL SECURITY ``Y2K OK'' TO DELIVER BENEFIT CHECKS
 &HT;    By JONATHAN HALL
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Social Security is ``Y2K OK,'' a congressional
panel was told Thursday. But just to make sure, benefit checks will
be delivered on Dec. 29 in case the U.S. Postal Service has
problems associated with the change to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been certified as 100 percent compliant through the
entire network,'' Social Security Commissioner Kenneth S. Apfel
told members of the House Subcommittee on Social Security. ``From
Social Security to the Treasury Department, the entire federal
system is Y2K compliant.''
</P>
<P>
   If localized problems do occur, there are local contingency
plans available to assure people appropriate service, Apfel said.
</P>
<P>
   If banks have electronic problems and transactions cannot be
processed on Jan. 3, the first Monday of 2000, the Social Security
Administration will immediately contact the Treasury Department and
issue replacement checks sent through the mail to be available
within five days. If someone faces an emergency and urgently needs
his or her check, Apfel said the local field office will
immediately issue it.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security Administration has been working on a
strategic plan since 1992 at a cost of $4.3 million. Apfel said the
agency's goal is to ensure that January 2000 payments will be made
correctly and on time to the nearly 50 million beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer systems are vital to ensuring that Americans receive
the Social Security benefits they have come to expect in a timely
and affordable manner,'' said Rep. Clay Shaw, R-Fla., who is
chairman of the subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Over the first weekend of 2000, Jan. 1 and 2, the agency will
set up a Y2K command center and test all of its technological
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Implementation of the strategy will ensure, to the extent
possible, that SSA's facilities will be fully operational on Jan. 3
_ the first business day of the new century,'' Apfel said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. General Accounting Office released a report Thursday
that praised Social Security's commitment to addressing the Y2K
challenges but criticized its discontinuation of a program designed
to speed Social Security payments to the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
