A8945 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINESE-SECT-HNS &LR;      07-29 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-SECT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WILL NOT EXTRADITE CHINESE SECT LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. State Department on Thursday flatly
rejected any chance that Li Hongzhi, the U.S.-based founder of the
outlawed Falun Gong sect in China, would be extradited to China
where officials have issued an arrest warrant for him.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Reeker, a State Department spokesman, said the United
States and China don't have an extradition treaty, thus making
extradition impossible. The United States has extradition treaties
with 115 nations, with Russia and China being the major exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials issued an arrest warrant Thursday for Li, who
is the leader of Falun Gong, and said they would seek international
help to place him in Chinese custody.
</P>
<P>
   Because the popular spiritual group has an estimated 10 million
followers, including many members of the Chinese Communist party,
Beijing leaders are concerned that the group poses a challenge to
their autocratic rule.
</P>
<P>
   Li, a Chinese citizen residing in New York City, was charged
with ``disturbing public order'' by organizing demonstrations
without permits, and with spreading ``superstition and malicious
fallacies to deceive people, resulting in the deaths of many
practitioners,'' according to China's official state-run Xinhua
news agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government claimed the group was to blame for 743
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move against a Chinese exile, Beijing said it
would ask for cooperation from member nations of Interpol, the
international police force, to arrest Li, according to Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
   Erping Zhang, a Falun Gong spokesman here, dismissed the charges
as ``groundless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not against the Chinese government, nor do we have any
political aspirations,'' he said, calling on the Beijing leadership
to ``respect the rights of freedom of belief, freedom of assembly,
freedom of expression as clearly stated in the constitution of the
People's Republic of China.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail Rachlin, a Falun Gong spokeswoman, added that the group was
not a cult, as the Chinese government asserts.
</P>
<P>
   Falun Gong participants practice a type of meditation regimen
similar to Tai Chi, a series of relaxation exercises popular in
China and growing in the West. It is based on the martial arts,
Buddhism and Taoism. The group claims 100 million practitioners in
over 30 countries. Li founded the group in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the group says it operates ``practice
centers'' in 39 states.
</P>
<P>
   China began a crackdown a week ago when it banned Falun Gong and
arrested members of the group. Government media said Thursday that
authorities were destroying more than 1.5 million books, posters
and other materials seized from the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deplore such heavy-handed attempts to censure free
expression and freedom of thought, conscience and religion,''
Reeker said. ``We call upon China to uphold its obligations under
international human rights instruments and to protect freedom of
expression.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's chief spokesman, James Rubin, said the
administration was ``disturbed'' by the government's actions
against the sect.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 members staged a protest Thursday on the grounds of
the U.S. Capitol seeking to draw attention to the plight of Li and
other members who have been arrested or harassed over the last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The group's members were arranged in a rectangle formation of 25
rows of 20 people and were seated on the grass, with each row about
15 feet apart. They sat silently, their eyes closed, and slowly
moved their arms as soft Asian music played over loud speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Several other members held up a yellow banner that read, ``We
request a peaceful dialogue with the Chinese government.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
