A8955 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-DRUGS-NYT &LR;      07-29 0315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH DRUG DEALER GETS LIFE SENTENCE IN JOURNALIST'S SLAYING 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ A major Dublin drug dealer was sentenced to life
imprisonment Thursday after being convicted for the 1996 murder of
Veronica Guerin, a prominent Dublin journalist who reported
aggressively on organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   The dealer, Brian Meehan, 34, who had pleaded not guilty, was
convicted in the Special Criminal Court in Dublin by a panel of
judges. The court was established to prosecute political terrorists
and other criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan was also sentenced to 47 years on 14 counts of drug
dealing and weapons possession. Police said he was the king of
Dublin cannabis dealers, earning about $1 million in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Normally there is no parole before 14 years have been served.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan was accused of being the driver of the motorcycle that
took the gunman to intercept Ms. Guerin's car on the outskirts of
Dublin on June 26, 1996. She was shot in the face and chest six
times by a man with a Magnum .357 pistol. The gunman, who has been
publicly identified only as Mr. A, has been arrested but not tried.
His trial is expected later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last November another Dubliner, Paul Ward, a suspected member of
Meehan's operation, was also sentenced to life for the murder of
Ms. Guerin. The court accepted testimony that he helped plan the
killing and disposed of the gun and motorcycle after the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan had sought to silence Ms. Guerin, 37, because of her
stories in The Sunday Independent newspaper, witnesses said. Before
the killing, she had been shot in the leg in her home, but she
refused an offer of police protection. There was criticism by other
journalists of the Independent's editors for having allowed her to
pursue criminals, including drug dealers, and confront them
directly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8956 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-HASEK-BOS &LR;      07-29 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HASEK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASEK SAYS UPCOMING SEASON WILL BE HIS LAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dominik Hasek will be the Dominator for one more year and then
no more.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Sabres goaltender, who was the NHL's most valuable
player in 1997 and '98 and won the Vezina Trophy as the league's
best netminder five of the last six years, made it official
Thursday that he will hang up his skates after the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, who helped carry the Sabres to the Stanley Cup finals
last season, said family considerations primarily were what
prompted his decision. Hasek and his wife, Alena, have a 9-year-old
son, Michael, and 4-year-old daughter, Dominika.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our kids to go back to the Czech Republic and share in
our families' backgrounds and cultures,'' said Hasek, a native of
that country and the main reason the Czech Republic captured the
hockey gold medal in the 1998 Olympic Games in Nagano. ``I can see
every year it's more and more difficult, especially for my son, to
adapt to the Czech life. Every year he has more problems to speak
Czech. This is one of the reasons. The longer we stay in the United
States, the harder it will be for our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been speculated that Hasek, who turns 35 in January, also
wants to retire at the peak of his career. It was also theorized
that Hasek was hobbled by injury and didn't want to continue to go
through the rigors of the game and its long schedule. However, in a
conference call Thursday, Hasek said the groin injury that bothered
him for much of the postseason had nothing to do with his decision.
He said his health is fine and that his passion for the game is as
strong as ever.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes at a tough time for the NHL, which is
already starved for marquee players. Wayne Gretzky, the sport's
greatest ambassador, retired at the end of last season, and with
two new teams coming into the NHL for the 2000-2001 season, Hasek's
departure will be felt even more acutely. He said Thursday that
there is no way he would change his mind halfway through the year,
even though he is signed through 2000-01.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the decision was met with great disappointment
from the league office.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a global stage, Dominik Hasek has been an outstanding
contributor to his team, his league, his sport, and the position he
has played with such distinction,'' said commissioner Gary Bettman.
``He has been exciting and unique, has challenged himself to set
standards of excellence with the same determination that he has
shown in challenging every shooter. We are looking forward to
watching Dom play this season. We wish him well and we wish he
would change his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   It had been speculated that Hasek was trying to use his leverage
to get the Sabres to improve the club, thinking that if the team
knew he would only play for this year, it would make a series of
moves to maximize its chances for capturing the Cup. However, Hasek
said there is no ulterior motive for his decision. He also cited
his desire to move out of the spotlight and to be more active in
his Dominator clothing business, which was started about 18 months
ago, as reasons for his decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres' front office said it can at least plan now for when
he leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it will be difficult to replace somebody the caliber
of Dominik Hasek,'' said assistant general manager Larry Carriere.
``But he gave us the opportunity to plan our future a year in
advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek said the timing of the announcement came as a result of
his wanting to concentrate on the game and not any outside issues
during his last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to have a lot of fun with my teammates,'' he said.
``I'm announcing it now so that when the season starts I can
minimize the distraction for my teammates, for me, and the Buffalo
Sabres organization, so we can concentrate only on hockey.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
