<HEADER>
A8961 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-CREDIT-SUISSE-N     07-29 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-CREDIT-SUISSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE IMPOSE SEVERE PENALTIES ON CREDIT SUISSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japanese financial authorities imposed severe sanctions
Thursday on Credit Suisse Group, closing a six-month investigation
into the firm's sale of derivative securities intended to help
Japanese banks and companies hide huge losses.
</P>
<P>
   The penalties were the most punitive ever brought against a
foreign company in Japan and were clearly meant to send a message
that the Financial Supervisory Agency, Japan's fledgling financial
watchdog, intends to end the cowboy-like activities that have long
characterized the brokerage business in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The agency and its parent, the Financial Reconstruction
Commission, revoked the license of Credit Suisse Financial
Products, thus banishing the firm's most lucrative business here,
and suspended some of the firm's other activities for periods
ranging from one month to more than one year.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign financial concerns have been watching the Credit Suisse
Group case closely as a barometer of the Japanese government's
attitude toward their business dealings in Japan. It had been
widely expected that Credit Suisse would be punished, but the
severity of the penalties was a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   There had been much internal debate among regulators about how
harsh the penalty should be, and clearly, the hard-liners won out.
It was the first time since World War II that regulators have
revoked a banking license. Prior to the war, under a different set
of laws, five banks lost their licenses, but only because they
failed capital requirements, not because of any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Hakuo Yanagisawa, the head of the commission, said investigators
had found that the financial-products division evaded and
obstructed inspections, participated in ``extremely inappropriate''
activities and violated the Banking Law and the Securities and
Exchange Law.
</P>
<P>
   An official of the Financial Supervisory Agency said regulators
had not yet decided whether to refer the case to the prosecutor's
office for criminal wrongdoing, but he noted that government
employees are required to report illegal activities for potential
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Thursday evening, Credit Suisse noted
that the revocation of the banking license held by its derivatives
unit was unprecedented in Japan and said it considered the
punishment ``disproportionate to the criticized conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm said it would still comply with the sanction and
reiterated its commitment to doing business in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the penalties were viewed as potentially damaging
to the image of Credit Suisse, Europe's sixth-largest bank. Its
shares fell 2.7 percent, to 272.5 Swiss francs ($183), on the Swiss
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   A Credit Suisse spokesman said that the penalties were
financially insignificant. He said the group's operations here
account for roughly 3 percent of its overall revenue and that loss
of the sophisticated derivatives business would probably have an
impact on overall revenue of less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The firm also said it understood that the practices of the past
were no longer appropriate under the stricter regulatory procedures
required as part of the ``Big Bang'' that began deregulating the
financial markets here last year. ``Serious lessons have been
learned, corrective actions initiated and disciplinary steps
completed,'' the firm said.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse _ and for that matter, many other foreign and
Japanese financial institutions _ sold sophisticated derivatives
that allowed Japanese companies to defer losses, a practice
commonly referred to as ``window dressing.'' The Financial
Supervisory Agency is conducting similar investigations into Lehman
Brothers and Cresvale International Ltd., a unit of Princeton
International Economics Ltd. here, and an agency official said it
would continue to look for such transactions in future inspections
of both Japanese and foreign firms.
</P>
<P>
   Window dressing is not illegal under Japanese law, however, and
regulators were careful to label such transactions as inappropriate
rather than illegal. They may have grounds to pursue charges
against banks that tried to dress up their balance sheets because
efforts to bolster capital adequacy using such means probably
violates banking guidelines. But no regulations or laws prohibit
the use of complex derivatives by the legions of corporate clients
that bought them in hopes of papering over losses.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investment bankers in Tokyo said they did not expect the
regulators to come down as harshly on other foreign firms.
``They're sending a message that this sort of behavior won't be
tolerated anymore, but I don't think they're going to make a
practice of punishing foreign firms,'' one banker said. Credit
Suisse was particularly aggressive about the business, and that is
what attracted the attention of authorities. The nationalization of
the Long-Term Credit Bank and Nippon Credit Bank also offered
regulators insights into the window-dressing practice. The two
banks were among Credit Suisse's best clients.
</P>
<P>
   But what seems to have especially angered the authorities was
the firm's attempt to cover up its activities and interfere with
the Financial Supervisory Agency's investigation, which started
with a surprise sweep on the morning of Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after investigators arrived, Michael Winning, who
oversaw Credit Suisse's legal affairs in Japan, sent e-mail and
verbal messages directing that documents be sent immediately to the
firm's offices in London, beyond the reach of the regulators, or
shredded.
</P>
<P>
   Winning and seven other employees were suspended after Credit
Suisse hired the law firm Wilmer, Cutler &AMP; Pickering to conduct an
independent investigation into the incident, and all have either
been dismissed or have resigned, the spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
