<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK-BLAME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SAY ENVIRONMENT WAS RIPE FOR WOODSTOCK RIOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As cleanup continues on
the decimated property that was once Woodstock '99, a national
expert in rock concert crowd safety says organizers are to blame
for creating an environment that was ripe for Sunday's riot. Paul
Wertheimer, owner of Crowd Management Strategies in Chicago, said
organizers should have taken stronger steps to enforce the rules
before things got out of hand _ and that the riots might not have
happened in the first place if enough people had been hired to keep
the sites and toilets clean. ``It was the design of their whole
crowd management plan that failed,'' said Wertheimer, a
crowd-control consultant who began his career investigating the
1979 deaths in Cincinnati of 11 people killed in a crush of fans
trying to get into a rock show by The Who. ``They didn't act quick
enough, and they weren't prepared enough,'' added Wertheimer, who
keeps statistics on concert injuries and is an advocate for safer
conditions. On Tuesday, it was announced that Woodstock had had a
second death. David DeRosia, 24, of Connecticut, was airlifted from
the concert Saturday afternoon after being taken to a medical tent
with a high heart rate, low blood pressure and confusion, according
to Woodstock spokeswoman Ilene Marder. He died at 2 a.m. Sunday in
Syracuse, but Woodstock officials say they did not learn of the
death until Tuesday. The cause of death was still unknown.
Woodstock '99, held at an airstrip in Rome, lured 250,000 people
for three days of mostly peaceful music. But the fun was shattered
Sunday night when hundreds of youths ran amok for hours, burning,
looting and destroying everything they could get their hands on
before State Police took control of the site at dawn.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Tuesday, workers continued to clean the site. Every square
foot is covered in refuse, from pizza boxes to water bottles.
Marder said the cleaning staff will use street-sweepers and large
vacuums to clean whenever possible. On Monday, however, a dozen men
with garbage bags were picking up refuse by hand. ``It's a lot more
than they expected, and half the workers quit,'' said a man who
identified himself as ``Bullfrog.'' ``They've only got one sweeper.
It's someplace else.'' Wertheimer said the Woodstock problems began
with garbage. Woodstock Ventures Inc. should have made sure they
hired enough staff to clean the site every night, he said. Instead,
the refuse built up until, by Sunday, you could not stand or sit
anywhere without being next to trash. He also said Woodstock's
biggest problem was not enforcing the rules. Once concertgoers
realized what they could get away with, such as breaking down the
12-foot fence and stealing from trucks, they became more brash. It
also didn't help that a number of bands, notably Limp Bizkit, were
successfully inciting the crowd to become more wild and
destructive, he said. Wertheimer added that allowing a number of
security guards to leave before the end of the show was a major
error. ``I cannot excuse the vandals who caused the trouble,'' he
said. ``But we know about that element. ... That's why everybody
plans for the hooligan element.'' Woodstock organizers could not be
reached for comment yesterday. Over the weekend, however,
organizers Michael Lang and John Scher have said they were trying
to clean the garbage as well as they could. They said security
guards were told not to try to put the fires out because of concern
for their safety, and firefighters were pulled back from trying to
put out the blazes because people were throwing bottles at them. At
least one state official is already proposing legislation to change
the way a show like Woodstock would be approved. On Monday, state
Senator Nancy Lorraine Hoffmann, a Republican from Syracuse, said
she would propose several bills that would affect large concerts
like Woodstock. She says State Police approval should be required
for security at such large shows, and the state Health Department
should be responsible for keeping the site clean and healthy. She
is also proposing a bill to require that concert venues recycle.
Much of the refuse at Woodstock was from plastic water bottles that
ordinarily would be recycled. The bottles were instead used by
concertgoers to throw at police and feed the bonfires that started
the riot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
