<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THIRD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTORED `THIRD MAN' HAS BEEN RESTORED TO ALL ITS GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If ever a film needed no introduction it's Carol Reed's 1949
masterpiece, ``The Third Man,'' which has been restored to all its
pristine glory for its 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   It's been considered a classic since the day it was released,
and last year the celebrated American Film Institute poll of the
100 greatest American films placed it at number 57 (even though
it's officially a British film). This year, American
Cinematographer Magazine named it one of the 10 ``best-shot''
films.
</P>
<P>
   Based on an original screenplay by Graham Greene, it's the story
of a naive American pulp writer, Holly Martins (Joseph Cotten), who
comes to postwar Vienna on the invitation of his old pal, Harry
Lime (Orson Welles) _ only to find Harry has just been killed, run
down in the street by his own driver.
</P>
<P>
   When he looks into the freak accident, he finds a certain
discrepancy in the facts. While the official witnesses all report
that two men carried the dying Harry to the side of the street, a
porter who came along minutes later says that a ``third man'' was
also present at the death scene.
</P>
<P>
   So Martins is in pursuit of the mysterious third man, propelled
by his own curiosity, by his horror of an accusation by the top
British military policeman (Trevor Howard) that Harry was an
immoral racketeer, and by his growing attraction to Harry's former
girlfriend, a Czech actress (Alida Valli).
</P>
<P>
   That's the basic premise, but it gives little clue to the
cinematic pleasures that ensue as Martins _ the most incompetent of
movie detectives _ bumbles his way through the rubble of a
war-torn, divided, morally ambiguous, curiously depopulated Vienna:
a ruin of Western Civilization.
</P>
<P>
   In his groundbreaking book ``The Great Films,'' critic William
Bayer argues that ``The Third Man'' is ``a flawless film of
intrigue and suspense, a summit of perfection within the genre ...
one of the most intelligent thrillers ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is also remembered for its purely visual aspects: its
Oscar-winning black-and-white cinematography; its innovative tilted
camera angles; its chases down rain-slicked, cobblestone streets;
its heart-pounding climax in the sewers of Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   And it's legendary for its haunting, minimalist and enduringly
popular zither score and ``Third Man Theme'' by Anton Karas _ who
Reed found playing for tips in a Vienna cafe after the shooting had
commenced and hired on an inspired hunch.
</P>
<P>
   Co-star Welles has only one major dialogue scene in the film,
but Harry Lime would be one of his signature roles, so popular and
so seminal to his persona that he considered it his most movie-star
charismatic piece of acting. He revived it for years in his ``The
Lives of Harry Lime'' radio series in the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   But the star of the film is Cotten, and he's a revelation.
Always an underrated actor who had an amazing knack for being in
classic films (``Citizen Kane,'' ``Shadow of a Doubt''), his Holly
Martins is one of the cinema's great characters _ as innocent,
tragic and prototypically American as Jay Gatsby or Huck Finn.
</P>
<P>
   Note: This restored version of ``The Third Man,'' which debuted
locally at the last Seattle International Film Festival, is the
original British version _ 11 minutes longer than the 93-minute
U.S. release, with opening narration spoken by director Reed
instead of Cotten. I personally think the U.S. version plays a tiny
bit better.
</P>
<P>
   The Third Man (1949). Directed by Carol Reed. Screenplay by
Graham Greene. Cast: Joseph Cotten, Alida Valli, Orson Welles,
Trevor Howard, Bernard Lee. Rialto Pictures. Varsity. 104 minutes.
Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
