<SLUG> BC-TREK-RICK-BERMAN-ON-STAR-TREK-ART-ADV09-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUARDIAN OF THE UNIVERSE: CATCHING UP WITH `STAR TREK'S' RICK
BERMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of ``Star
Trek'' executive producer Rick Berman.) 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Rick Berman is boldly going on. And on, and on. But it's well
worth hearing, because the executive producer of the entire ``Star
Trek'' franchise is talking about the future of ``Star Trek'' _
about ``Voyager's'' sixth year, the next ``Trek'' feature and even
the next ``Trek'' series.
 &HT;    ``We had a wonderful mix of episodes on `Voyager' last season,
in terms of action and aliens,'' Berman says. ``We had some very
poignant episodes, some time-travel shows and a decent balance of
Janeway (Kate Mulgrew) and Seven of Nine (Jeri Ryan) episodes. I'd
like to think the mix is going to be extremely similar this season.
 &HT;    ``In terms of what will be different, we have no major
changes,'' he says. ``We're not losing or gaining any major
characters, and as to the question of whether or not the ship will
return home, certainly it won't happen soon, if it were to happen
at all.''
 &HT;    The return of the Voyager has long been rumored, but Berman
confesses that, speaking strictly as a fan _ which he is _ he isn't
sure it would be such a good idea.
 &HT;    ``When you watched `The Fugitive,' you wanted Kimble to find the
one-armed man, but you also knew that would end the premise,'' he
says by telephone from his office on Paramount's Hollywood lot.
``That's not to say `Voyager' would cease to exist if the crew got
back to the Alpha Quadrant, but I think their journey back and,
hopefully, their final arrival in the Alpha Quadrant, is a
continual goal and one of the show's key elements.
 &HT;    ``There are issues that have us discussing the possibility of
getting the ship home and issues that have us realizing it would be
a good idea to hold it until much closer to the end of the show's
run,'' he concludes. ``It's an ongoing discussion.''
 &HT;    In the meantime, season six of ``Voyager'' kicks off on Sept. 22
with ``Equinox Part II,'' picking up where the fifth-season
cliffhanger left off. Subsequent episodes include ``Survival
Instinct,'' in which Borg drones inform Seven about dark secrets
from her past, and ``Barge of the Dead,'' with a sojourn to the
Klingon equivalent of Hell. Fans can also look for a Walter
Mitty-esque Doctor (Robert Picardo) episode and ``Dragon's Teeth,''
an hour that introduces a new ``Trek'' alien.
 &HT;    Behind the scenes, Brannon Braga remains co-executive producer.
Ronald Moore, Braga's old writing and producing partner, had also
joined the staff, but departed ``amicably'' after only a few weeks.
Ken Biller has since filled Moore's position.
 &HT;    With ``Deep Space Nine'' off the air and no ``Trek'' feature in
production, Berman has more time to devote to ``Voyager,'' but he
insists that _ while he ultimately has the final say _ the effort
is very much a collaborative one.
 &HT;    ``On `Voyager' I work with Brannon daily,'' he says. ``I don't
want to say I have the final word, but I guess I have the final
word.
 &HT;    ``It's a hammer I like to keep in my drawer and not take out
very much.''
 &HT;    Recently, Paramount Pictures studio boss Sherry Lansing wielded
her own hammer, commenting publicly that the 10th ``Trek'' film
might not spotlight Patrick Stewart and the rest of the ``Next
Gen'' cast.
 &HT;    After the box-office success of ``Star Trek: Insurrection,''
even in the face of lukewarm reviews, Berman thought ``Trek 10''
would focus on the same cast, he admits.
 &HT;    ``I still do,'' he insists. ``Have we seen the last of Picard
and Data and company? I can't imagine it.''
 &HT;    Even so, he admits that, one way or another, the show will go
on.
 &HT;    ``If Patrick Stewart were hit a truck tomorrow, would we stop
making movies?'' he asks. ``Probably not. But it's just too soon to
talk about a next movie.
 &HT;    ``Everything is just in such an early stage of conversation.''
 &HT;    Even more nebulous is the long-rumored next incarnation of
``Star Trek,'' the long-awaited fifth series.
 &HT;    ``Will another `Trek' series come to pass?'' Berman asks
rhetorically. ``I would say that's a pretty definite yes. I am
involved now in developing another series.
 &HT;    ``I'm doing it with Mr. Braga, and it's in a very, very early
stage,'' he adds. ``It's something that will be a pretty dramatic
departure from the last couple of series, and it will reach the
airwaves anywhere from fall 2000 to spring 2001.''
 &HT;    Given the phenomenal success of ``The Matrix'' and ``Star Wars:
The Phantom Menace,'' there appears to be a sci-fi boom in the
making. No less an authority than Leonard Nimoy has suggested that,
just as 1977's ``Star Wars'' paved the way for 1979's ``Star Trek:
The Motion Picture,'' so ``The Phantom Menace'' might spearhead
another resurgence in ``Trek's'' popularity.
 &HT;    ``I think Leonard is right,'' Berman says. ``Ironically, `Trek'
influenced George Lucas when it was a television series, and it
also inspired the space program and all that. It influenced the
first `Star Wars' movie, and `Star Wars' definitely gave birth to
the `Trek' movies. There has been a switch-off back and forth.
 &HT;    ``Now that we're dealing with the sixth season of the fourth
`Trek' series,'' he says, ``and now that we've done more than 500
hours of `Trek' television and nine movies, however, I think `Star
Trek' influences `Star Trek' more than anything else does.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
