</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8977 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-APPLES-PITTSNURGH-A     07-29 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-APPLES-PITTSNURGH-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PITTSBURGH: so splendid. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Determined Mayors
</P>
<P>
   It took a series of determined mayors to change the city's face,
starting in the 1950s with David Lawrence, who adopted the slogan
``Smoke Must Go.'' He and successors like Peter Flaherty and
Richard Caliguiri made common cause with business leaders, notably
Richard King Mellon.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Carson, who grew up not far from here, would have been
proud of what they accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday as the self-described Workshop of the World,
Pittsburgh was an industrial inferno. Only half a century ago, the
rivers teemed with tugs and barges, and the mills poured brown and
green ooze into the water and black and gray soot into the skies,
so much so that street lights often had to be kept on all day. One
week in 1948, 30 people were killed by smog in the grimy little
borough of Donora (where, incidentally, the baseball hall-of-famer
Stan Musial grew up).
</P>
<P>
   ``Blackest place I ever saw,'' said the 19th-century English
traveler Anthony Trollope, and he knew grim industrial landscapes
at home.
</P>
<P>
   But Pittsburgh produced steel in prodigious quantities. At the
end of World War II, United States Steel, the first billion-dollar
corporation in history when it was formed in 1901, made twice as
much steel as the entire Soviet Union. Set against that, what was a
little pollution?
</P>
<P>
   Enormous Fortunes
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh also produced enormous fortunes for men like Andrew
Carnegie, an immigrant from Scotland who built a steel empire;
Henry Clay Frick, the king of coke, the baked coal essential to the
steel-making process, who was first an aide and then a rival to
Carnegie, and Andrew Mellon, the banker who financed the new
magnates and grew rich in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Mellon money built the National Gallery in Washington, and when
Andrew Mellon's son, Paul, died this year at the age of 91, he had
given it more than 1,000 pictures, including two van Goghs and 12
Winslow Homers in a final bequest, as well as $75 million in cash.
Frick money built New York's finest small art museum. Carnegie
money built libraries around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Only small fractions of their wealth stayed in Pittsburgh,
though their names grace monuments, buildings, parks, streets and
museums.
</P>
<P>
   To work in the mills, peasants came from all over Europe. A sign
from one Carnegie plant, preserved in the excellent (if clumsily
named) John Heinz Pittsburgh Regional History Center, warned of
danger in English, Italian, Hungarian, Slovak and Serbo-Croatian.
My great-grandfather was one of those hardy spirits, and his son,
my grandfather, worked in nearby Jeanette, which was for some time
the center of the American glass industry. My father was born
there.
</P>
<P>
   Myths grew up about industrial Bunyans like Joe Magarac, a
Hungarian who could derail a locomotive with his little finger, and
Steve Mestrovic, a Serb who could supposedly twist a 500-pound
steel bar into a pretzel. In real life, the tough river towns where
the immigrants settled produced more than their share of sports
heroes, especially pro football quarterbacks, including Johnny
Unitas, Joe Montana, Jim Kelly, Joe Namath and George Blanda.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh quickly became a battleground between labor and
capital. In the notorious Homestead strike of 1892, Pinkerton
detectives employed by Frick clashed with workers; 20 people were
killed and 300 wounded. The Amalgamated Association of Iron and
Steel Workers was crushed. Industry won the battle, but labor won
the war, decades later, when Philip Murray organized the United
Steel Workers Union. Now plans are afoot to bring the site of the
strike and other steel-industry landmarks under the aegis of the
National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks streamed into Pittsburgh as well, and soon built a
thriving subculture. The Pittsburgh Courier was the nation's
leading African-American newspaper, and the city produced a
seemingly endless flow of jazz stars, from Billy Strayhorn to
Erroll Garner to Mary Lou Williams. Before the integration of major
league baseball, the Pittsburgh Crawfords and the Homestead Grays
flourished on the black circuit with players like Josh Gibson and
the inimitable Satchel Paige.
</P>
<P>
   Sports still loom large here, as befits the city's six-pack
image, though the relatively small population (350,000, with
1,335,000 in Allegheny County) makes supporting big-league teams
difficult. The Pittsburgh Penguins, twice National Hockey League
champions in recent years, were faced with bankruptcy until a judge
approved a plan under which Mario Lemieux, the team's greatest star
until he retired in 1997, took control of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Legends live on, like Pirates infielder Bill Mazeroski's
improbable last-of-the-ninth home run to beat the Yankees, 10-9, in
the seventh game of the 1960 World Series, and Steelers running
back Franco Harris' ``immaculate reception'' of Terry Bradshaw's
deflected last-gasp pass to win a crucial playoff game in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Architectural Highlights
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh is rediscovering its significant architectural
heritage and urging visitors to do the same. Southwestern
Pennsylvania has two of the very greatest American buildings, Henry
Hobson Richardson's Allegheny County Courthouse and Jail, in
Pittsburgh, and Frank Lloyd Wright's wonderful cantilevered country
villa, Fallingwater, an hour to the southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Fallingwater was built for Pittsburgh merchant Edgar Kaufmann,
who cooked up a number of other projects, most of them never built,
with the master of Taliesen. Plans and models can be seen in a show
at the Carnegie Museum through Aug. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The courthouse _ a great castlelike structure of rusticated
granite, with a 325-foot tower _ is connected to the jail by a
Bridge of Sighs like the one that links the Doge's Palace and the
jail in Venice. It is a massive, masculine ensemble; the voussoirs,
or blocks, that form the main entrance, one of Richardson's
trademark Romanesque arches, are eight feet long. Yet there is
nothing clumsy or heavy about the structure.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8978 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-APPLES-PITTSBURGH-A     07-29 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-APPLES-PITTSBURGH-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PITTSBURGH: the structure.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Richardson whets your appetite for more, walk down Grant
Street. On the way you will see Frick's Union Trust Building
(1915), with a breathtaking stack of nine balconies, crowned by a
round stained-glass skylight, and a froth of terra-cotta turrets,
balustrades, pinnacles and balustrades on the roof; the Koppers
Building (1929), in an urbane Art Deco style, and the USX Building
(1970), a bold tower in Cor-Ten steel, which oxidizes to a deep
red-brown, protecting against deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   The USX Building, by Harrison &AMP; Abramovitz, looks much less
dated than the slightly earlier buildings from the same hands, New
York's Metropolitan Opera House and Avery Fisher Hall at Lincoln
Center. Its exoskeleton of vertical beams is filled with water and
antifreeze as a fire retardant.
</P>
<P>
   In a real sense the USX Building is a continuing advertisement
for the company that built it, once named U.S. Steel. So is the
former Alcoa Building (1953), nearby on Sixth Avenue, whose skin is
formed of preformed aluminum panels, and the glass-faced PPG Place
(1984), on Third Avenue, which was built by a company formerly
called Pittsburgh Plate Glass.
</P>
<P>
   A Cultural Catalyst
</P>
<P>
   No family has done more for Pittsburgh, especially for the arts
in Pittsburgh, than the Heinzes, purveyors to the world of 57
Varieties _ actually, today, more like 5,700. It was H.J. Heinz II,
known as Jack, who had the idea that cultural resources could aid
in jump-starting an economic revival here. He bought four abandoned
movie theaters downtown and helped turn them into the Cultural
District, anchored by Heinz Hall, home to the Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz Reiner, William Steinberg, Andre Previn and Lorin Maazel
all helped to mold the orchestra's global reputation, but Heinz
dollars balanced the organization's budget. Without them, as Gideon
Toeplitz, the managing director, said several years ago, Pittsburgh
would have ``a small regional orchestra rather like the Wheeling
Symphony just down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, the new home of the Pittsburgh Public Theater will
open across the street from Heinz Hall with a world premiere of a
play by August Wilson, a Pittsburgh native. Designed by Michael
Graves, with a great copper cowl giving its facade a distinctive
appearance, it has a Heinz connection, too. It was partly financed
by the friends of, and named for, Anthony J.F. O'Reilly, H.J. Heinz
Co.'s 's Irish-born chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Next door will stand a fountain designed by Louise Bourgeois.
</P>
<P>
   Drama is a many-layered thing in Pittsburgh. Apart from the
Public Theater and the musicals that also play in the Cultural
District, there are the venturesome City Theater on the South Side
and Karla Boos' lively Quantum Theater, which performs in spaces
either discovered or improvised.
</P>
<P>
   Neither opera nor dance is big-league yet, but the city has an
amazing number of dance organizations, large and small. The most
prominent is the Pittsburgh Ballet Theater, whose artistic
director, Terrence Orr, has steered it away from the Balanchine
tradition toward that of his alma mater, American Ballet Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The Phipps Botanical Gardens, an 1893 gift from Henry Phipps,
one of Carnegie's sidekicks, has a 13-room Victorian conservatory,
one of the finest in the country. And the Frick Art Museum, a
country cousin of the New York showplace, exhibits the collection
of Henry Clay Frick's daughter, Helen; its highlights are a
magisterial Rubens portrait and works by the Sienese masters Duccio
and Sassetta.
</P>
<P>
   Bones and Art
</P>
<P>
   But the heaviest hitters here, in addition to the Symphony, are
the Carnegie and Warhol museums.
</P>
<P>
   The Carnegie complex, in Oakland, east of downtown, includes a
museum of natural history, renowned for its dinosaur collection, as
well as the art museum, headquarters for the International, whose
curator this year is Madeleine Grynsztejn. Since its beginning, the
art museum has concentrated on the art of the 19th and 20th
centuries _ ``the Old Masters of tomorrow,'' as Carnegie himself
put it.
</P>
<P>
   Paintings, sculpture and the decorative arts are intermingled to
good effect in galleries occupied by the permanent collection.
Take, for instance, the room devoted to the Arts and Crafts
Movement; there, furniture by C.F.A. Voysey and Harvey Ellis and
copperware by W.A.S. Benson keep company with two huge, newly
acquired Pre-Raphaelite canvases by Burne-Jones.
</P>
<P>
   First-rate pictures by the likes of Cezanne, Kirchner and Degas
(a smashing portrait of the engineer Henri Rouart) lie ahead. But
most intriguing to me was a selection of pioneer American
abstractionists like Burgoyne Diller, George L.K. Morris and
Stanton Macdonald-Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Over at the Warhol, installed in an old seven-story building
renovated by the New York architect Richard Gluckman, you are
greeted by a big cobalt-blue self-portrait of the artist,
wide-eyed, spiky-haired. The building is filled with Warhol's
collections (milk glass, shoes of famous people); Warhol's
wallpaper (I liked the pink-and-yellow cow pattern); Warhol's
films; Warhol's portraits of Mao, Liz and Mick; Warhol's books and
Warhol's archives _ 605 identical boxes filled with everything from
the master pack rat's mail to the original images on which he based
his famous silk screens.
</P>
<P>
   A Pittsburgh native whose parents came from the Carpathian
Mountains in central Europe, Warhol once wrote: ``You live in your
dream America that you've custom-made from art and schmaltz and
emotions just as much as you live in your real one.'' The museum is
Andy's world, custom-recreated.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh has taken to it slowly; Thomas Sokolowski, the
director, says, ``It's a sober city, very Presbyterian.'' Of the
65,000 visitors to the museum last year, half came from out of
state, many from Japan and Germany. But Sokolowski keeps plugging.
He has started a Friday happy hour and has big plans for musical
events, including a staging of the Satie-Poulenc-Ravel triple bill
``Parade,'' as big a scandal in its day as Warhol in his.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS IN 4TH TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
