<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-APPLES-PITTSBURGH-A     07-29 1619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-APPLES-PITTSBURGH-ART-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PITTSBURGH: in his. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enjoying Pittsburgh
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh is 365 miles southwest of New York City. Here is a
sampling of attractions and places to stay and eat in the area,
along with travel information:
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLETREE HOTEL, 1000 Penn Ave., (412) 281-3700. Renovated only
this year, the Doubletree is Pittsburgh's freshest hotel, with a
light-filled, four-story atrium lobby. Theaters are just a couple
of blocks away, and an enclosed walkway leads to the convention
center. Though pretty prosaic, the rooms are a good deal roomier
than the chain hotel standard. Double rooms: $189 weekdays; $119 to
$189 weekends.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH HILTON, Gateway Center, (412) 391-4600. In a city
that woefully lacks a top-drawer hotel, the Hilton is blessed with
those three cardinal virtues: location, location and location.
Overlooking the junction of the Allegheny and Monongahela, with 711
rooms and 38 suites, it is a convention hotel par excellence, with
all the pluses and minuses that go with that. The crisp, smallish,
up-to-date rooms on the top floors are the best. Double rooms: $199
to $250.
</P>
<P>
   SUNNYLEDGE, 5124 Fifth Ave., Shadyside, (412) 683-5014. Oakland
once had a pair of fine big hotels, the Schenley and Webster Hall.
Both are long gone, alas, but this eight-room red-brick inn
provides a classy refuge for visitors to the universities and the
museums. All mod cons: minibars, cable television, Jacuzzi tubs,
hair dryers and Frette linens. Double rooms: $199 to $189; suites,
$275.
</P>
<P>
   WESTIN WILLIAM PENN, 530 William Penn Place, (412) 281-7100.
Henry Clay Frick built this Beaux-Arts pile to house his business
friends when they came to town. After countless face lifts, the old
girl is handsome enough, with enormous crystal chandeliers in the
Palm Court. But the service is disheartening, with breakfast cards
sometimes left dangling on doorknobs, unfilled, and desultory
delivery of baggage and messages. Today's nabobs send their
visitors down the street to the veddy private Duquesne Club. Double
rooms: $169 to $229, weekdays; $99 to $169, weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   CAFE ALLEGRO, 51 S. 12th St., (412) 481-7788. The cooking is a
tad uneven at this relaxed spot next to the 1915 South Side Market
House, just off post-industrial Carson Street; one night recently,
the veal chop was tasty and sweet seared scallops were nicely mated
with a tangy tangerine-juice reduction, but smoked trout was too
dry and soft-shell were crabs overcooked. Still, the spirit is
willing; baffled at first by a request for cheese at meal's end,
the kitchen quickly improvised an appealing assortment.
</P>
<P>
   CASBAH, 229 S. Highland Ave., Shadyside, (412) 661-5656. This is
the lead restaurant of an entrepreneurial duo who call themselves
Big Burrito Inc. The menu is Mediterranean: tagines from Morocco,
fearlessly fiery merguez sausage from Tunisia, pasta, a dense
ragout of lamb with couscous. Flavors are as emphatic as a smack in
the chops. Terrific wines, especially the Rhones, and a sultry,
sand-colored decor with hanging lamps reminiscent of Venice and
Fortuny.
</P>
<P>
   STEELHEAD GRILL, 112 Washington Place, (412) 394-3474. An
outpost of Drew Nieporent's empire (and hence a sibling of New
York's Tribeca Grill and Nobu), this is the city's top table, for
my money. Greg Alauzen, a hometown boy, concocts a shellfish
chowder that would delight any Down Easter, and serves skillfully
grilled shrimp on a bed of linguine with a rich basil-lemon sauce.
The wines are chosen by the savvy Daniel Johnnes of Montrachet.
</P>
<P>
   TESSARO'S, 4601 Liberty Ave., Bloomfield, (412) 682-6809. You're
tired of beurre blanc and balsamic vinegar and waiters named Clyde.
You need a joint with no attitude. In Pittsburgh, Tessaro's fills
the bill perfectly: a bar in a working-class neighborhood with Sam
Adams on draft, decadently juicy half-pound burgers cooked on a
hardwood grill, and plenty of good cheer. No french fries, no
dessert, no reservations, just sensational meat.
</P>
<P>
   LA CUCINA FLEGREA, 2114 Murray Ave., Squirrel Hill, (412)
521-2082. The room is plain and tiny, but the minute you walk in,
you know you're in the right place. It smells Italian, not
Italian-American. Anna Fevola comes from a village north of Naples,
and her cooking has that superbly unadorned clarity of flavor we
all long for. Order the grilled sausage, with charred edges, served
underneath a blanket of bitter rapini. BYOB.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   CARNEGIE MUSEUM OF ART, 4400 Forbes Ave., Oakland, (412)
622-3131. ``Merchant Prince and Master Builder: Edgar Kaufmann and
Frank Lloyd Wright,'' through Oct. 3. ``Forum: Felix de la
Concha,'' through Sept. 19. ``The Other 19th Century: European
Prints and Drawings,'' through Aug. 15. Hours: Tuesdays through
Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, 1 to 5 p.m.; also open
Mondays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m., through Aug. 30. Admission: $6; $5 for
the elderly; $4 for students and children 3 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ANDY WARHOL MUSEUM, 117 Sandusky St., (412) 237-8300. The
permanent collection has more than 3,000 works of art, including
drawings, prints, paintings, sculptures, film and video tapes,
along with archival material. ``The Architecture of Reassurance:
Designing the Disney Theme Parks,'' through Oct. 10. Hours:
Thursdays through Saturdays, 11 a.m. to 8 p.m.; Sundays and
Wednesdays, 11 a.m. to 6 p.m. Admission: $7; students, $4; the
elderly, $6; children over 3, $4.
</P>
<P>
   FRICK ART MUSEUM, 7227 Reynolds St., (412) 371-0600. The
permanent collection consists of European paintings, sculptures and
decorative arts from the 12th to the 18th centuries; there is also
Clayton, the turn-of-the-century Victorian residence of the
industrialist Henry Clay Frick and his family. Opening today,
``Shamans, Gods and Mythic Beasts: Colombian Gold and Ceramics in
Antiquity.'' Through Oct. 3. Hours: Tuesdays through Saturdays, 10
a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, noon to 6 p.m. Admission to the Art
Museum, as well as the Car and Carriage Museum, is free.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH SYMPHONY ORCHESTRA, Heinz Hall, 600 Penn Ave., at
Sixth Avenue, (412) 392-4900. The season begins on Sept. 17 at 8
p.m. with Schoenberg's ``Gurrelieder'' conducted by Mariss Jansons;
repeated Sept. 19 at 2:30 p.m. Tickets: $14 to $69.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH PUBLIC THEATER, 6 Allegheny Square (two blocks from
the Andy Warhol Museum), (412) 321-9800. A college production of
Shakespeare's ``Twelfth Night'' runs through Sunday. Tickets: $12.
The regular, main-stage season runs from October through June. In
December, the Public will move into the O'Reilly Theater, a new
650-seat theater designed by Michael Graves across from Heinz Hall.
The first production there will be the world premiere of August
Wilson's new work, ``King Hedley II.''
</P>
<P>
   CITY THEATER, 57 S. 13th St., (412) 431-4900. The season opens
on Sept. 10 with ``A Raisin in the Sun,'' co-produced with the
Kuntu Repertory Theater and running through Oct. 10. Tickets: $19
to $28.
</P>
<P>
   QUANTUM THEATER, a company that presents new works and
adaptations of classics in site-specific spaces in Pittsburgh. The
next production is Shakespeare's ``Merchant of Venice,'' from Aug.
18 through Aug. 29 (daily except for Monday, Aug. 23), at the
former Kerotest Building, a 19th-century factory at 25th Street and
Liberty Avenue. Tickets: $12. Information: (412) 422-3823.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH BALLET THEATER, Benedum Center, Seventh Avenue
between Penn and Liberty Avenues, (412) 456-6666. The fall season
begins Oct. 7 with ``Dracula.''
</P>
<P>
   JOHN HEINZ PITTSBURGH REGIONAL HISTORY CENTER, 1212 Smallman
St., (412) 454-6000. The main permanent exhibition is ``Points in
Time: Building a Life in Western Pennsylvania, 1750-Today.'' Also:
``Eat'n Park's Anniversary: Celebrating 50 Years of Smiles,''
through Sept. 12; ``Pittsburgh Rhythms: Music of a Changing City,
1820-1950,'' through Jan. 2; ``Heinz: Preserved in Pittsburgh,''
through spring 2001. Hours: Daily except holidays, 10 a.m. to 5
p.m.; library closed Sundays and Mondays. Admission: $6; $4.50 for
the elderly and children 3 to 18; free for children under 3.
</P>
<P>
   PHIPPS CONSERVATORY AND BOTANICAL GARDENS, 1 Schenley Park,
(412) 622-6914. A 13-room Victorian glass house features desert
plants, palms, orchids, seasonal butterflies and traditional flower
shows. The Butterfly Forest, with 26 species of butterfly, is open
through Oct. 15. Visitors can see butterflies hatching and flying
freely around the glass pavilion. Hours: Tuesdays through Sundays,
9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission: $5; $3.50 for the elderly and students;
$2 for children 2 to 12; free for children under 2.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There From The New York Area
</P>
<P>
   BY AIR: U.S. Airways (800 428-4322) has nine nonstop flights
daily to Pittsburgh from New York's La Guardia and eight from
Newark, N.J. Last-minute fares are approximately $307 each way from
La Guardia and $322 each way from Newark. There is a special $306
round-trip last-minute fare from Newark with departure on a
Saturday or Sunday and a return on a Saturday or Sunday. The 14-day
advance fare from Newark is $316 round trip; not available from La
Guardia. The least expensive fare, $248 round trip from Newark,
requires a Saturday stayover, is based on availability and requires
21 days' notice. Continental (800 525-0280) has six nonstop flights
daily from Newark. Last-minute fares range from $324 to $425 each
way. The 14-day advance fare from Newark ranges from $293 to $476
round trip, with a Saturday stayover. The least expensive fare,
which requires 21 days' notice and a Saturday stayover, ranges from
$252 to $425.
</P>
<P>
   _ By R.W. APPLE Jr.
</P>
<P>
