<HEADER>
A8990 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-LOLA30-COX     07-29 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-LOLA30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Run Lola Run' a fine game of beat the clock
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``Run Lola Run''
 &HT;    Grade: B+
 &HT;    Starring Franka Potente and Moritz Bleibtreu. Rated R for
violence and language. 1 hour, 21 minutes. In
 &HT;    German with English subtitles.
 &HT;    At Garden Hills.
 &HT;    The verdict: A breathless kinetic delight from Germany.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A pyrotechnic celebration of style over substance, ``Run Lola
Run'' is the big-screen love child of every video game and MTV
quick-cut editing trick of the past 10 years. The Berlin-based
story is less important than how it's told. The movie is a nonstop
adrenalin kick, even though the script sometimes can't keep pace
with its leggy heroine.
</P>
<P>
   That's the flame-haired Lola (Franka Potente). The reason she
has to run is to save the life of her boyfriend, Manni (Moritz
Bleibtreu), a bagman for the mob who has misplaced 100,000 marks.
She has exactly 20 minutes to get the cash or lose Manni for good _
either to his trigger-happy bosses or to his dangerous plan of
robbing a grocery store for the loot.
</P>
<P>
   Spinning busy elaborations on this simple tale, writer-director
Tom Tykwer finds endless ways to stimulate the minuscule attention
spans of today's twentysomethings. He has so many visual surprises
and narrative digressions in his arsenal that you can never guess
where Lola, and the movie, are racing next. Especially since he
shoots the same 20-minute dash three separate times, with obstacles
in Lola's path _ a vicious dog, a baby carriage, nuns _ causing
completely different outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   In each, Lola confronts her aloof father (Herbert Knaup), a bank
executive whose daughter's financial needs are the least of his
concerns. It's in these scenes, revised three times, that ``Lola''
slows down for a taste of genuine emotion. Potente and Knaup make
the most of their moments as father and daughter, recognizing the
unbridgeable distance between them.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his swift, fat-free movie, Tykwer employs animation,
different film stock, split-screen images and sharp doses of irony,
such as Dinah Washington singing ``What a Difference a Day Makes''
on the soundtrack. His three what-if variations of Lola's run let
him shuffle the tone: romantic, tragic, funny, mystical. In case
her circumstances aren't suitably outrageous, Lola comes equipped
with a scream that shatters glass.
</P>
<P>
   Even while it's sprinting, the movie plays with big ideas,
especially the notion of fate: We watch as lives are repeatedly
altered by tiny delays or collisions, not only Lola's but those of
people she bumps into on the street. The movie spells out the
destinies of passers-by with lightning-quick flashes of Polaroid
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the film's speed and brevity don't quite obscure
the script's thinness. You may find yourself asking questions you
shouldn't. For example, why doesn't Lola just grab the phone and
call her dad? The answer is that, if she did, there wouldn't be a
movie. And because ``Lola'' is so much fun, you're willing to shrug
and accept the artifice. It's a celebration of the power of love
expressed in bursts of ingenuity and speed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
