<HEADER>
A8991 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SEX30-COX     07-29 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SEX30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tangled relationships, L.A. style
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``Relax ... It's Just Sex''
 &HT;    Grade: B-
 &HT;    Starring Mitchell Anderson, Jennifer Tilly and Lori Petty.
Unrated, but contains nudity, simulated sex, profanity and
violence. 1 hour, 53 minutes. At Lefont Plaza.
 &HT;    The verdict: A funny if meandering look at the lives and loves
of an extended group of gay and straight Angelenos.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The SoCal ensemble comedy ``Relax ... It's Just Sex'' gets off
to such a crackling, irreverent start, it's a shame when it hits a
melodramatic slick and spins out of control. The movie, which was
shown on opening night at Atlanta's Out on Film festival last
October, is writer-director P.J. Castellaneta's witty look at the
sexual mores of a group of gay and straight friends, centering on
Vincey (Mitchell Anderson).
</P>
<P>
   Eternally boyish, eternally boyless, gay Vincey is like the kid
brother of Tara Ricotto (Jennifer Tilly), the opinionated den
mother of a Los Angeles circle of friends. When she's not trying to
get pregnant by her reluctant boyfriend Gus (Timothy Paul Perez),
she's presiding over the romantic dramas of her friends.
</P>
<P>
   They include self-proclaimed ``lipstick lesbian'' Megan (Serena
Scott Thomas), whose affair with a man ends things with her
girlfriend Sarina (Cynda Williams), who winds up with sporty,
spunky Robin (the comically sharp Lori Petty). Among the
Y-chromosome cast, HIV-positive Javi (Eddie Garcia) hooks up with
activist painter Buzz (T.C. Carson), despite the latter's
conspiracy theories about the origin of AIDS. Then there are Dwight
and Diego (Gibbs Toldsdorf and Chris Cleveland), the gym-cut,
preppy couple whose lives are such a model of upper-middle-class
complacency that they get turned on talking about fresh herbs and
dinner parties.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through, ``Relax'' gets tense with an episode pitting
Vincey and pals against some gay-bashing thugs. This entails a very
awkward shift in tone, causing the movie to lose not only its
casual-sophisticated warmth but its central character, too. Vincey
disappears for much of the film. While it's not uninteresting to
find out whether Tara will get pregnant, or Megan and Sarina will
get back together, the movie's energy dissipates into a lot of
Californian relationship-speak, while all the characters (and we)
wonder where Vincey is.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, the film throws in sly bits of comedy, including the
angry reaction of Megan's mother when she learns that her daughter
has gone straight (``What are we going to say to our friends in
PFLAG?''). But by its end, ``Relax'' seems a bit too relaxed for
its own good, a sprawling group portrait that might have benefited
from a smaller, tighter canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
