<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SARATOGA RACE COURSE DRAWS RECORD CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LINDA TRISCHITTA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS _ The 131st opening of Saratoga Race Course
drew a dapper, chapeau-wearing crowd of 26,720 Wednesday, a record
for a July start and 1,150 more people than last year.
</P>
<P>
   Horseplayers packed the grounds and grandstand, full of
expectations and carrying fat wallets. A July opening day record of
$3,193,902 was wagered at the track, $95,700 more than 1998's
kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're delighted in every way,'' said William Nader, director
of broadcast communications and promotions for the New York Racing
Association. ``It's a great start and we hope to have continued
success for the balance of the meet.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening-day attendance record of 30,658 on Aug. 2, 1989,
remains to be broken.
</P>
<P>
   The booming beginning of the century's final Spa City season was
witnessed by arts patron Alfred Z. Solomon, 99, who began his 85th
summer at the track yesterday and in whose honor the eighth race
was named.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting 100 years for this,'' Solomon joked as he
posed for photos with jockey Jerry Bailey and trainer D. Wayne
Lukas after the race was won by Positive Gal.
</P>
<P>
   The soon-to-be centenarian epitomized the style and elegance of
Saratoga's mystique, with his soft white hair curling beneath the
brim of a Baku straw hat. Solomon, a resident of New York City,
also owns Madcaps Farms in Gansevoort, named for the hat company he
founded and ran until 1994.
</P>
<P>
   From his box seats, Solomon greeted well-wishers like state
senators Joseph Bruno, R-Brunswick, and Ronald Stafford,
R-Plattsburgh, as well as clubhouse neighbors like Sheila Rathbun.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very busy day,'' Solomon said. ``My birthday
is September 25th, but it won't be as exciting as this.'' In Jesus
``Chico'' Dumois' shoeshine chair, trainer Nick Zito was chatted up
before the first race by retired jockey Angel Cordero Jr., now a
jockey agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, so good,'' Dumois said, pocketing Zito's $20 for a $5
shine. ``This is the only place you can make some money. Here they
want to be dressed nice. In Belmont they wear sneakers.'' Dumois
said 20 customers came through between 7:30 a.m. and 1 p.m., and he
called that a good indication for opening day and the season
overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``More shoeshines means the economy goes up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baby-faced peace officers escorted jockeys through the crowds
after the races; families and friends staked out party spaces with
coolers and chairs in the picnic grounds and lines formed at all of
the betting windows.
</P>
<P>
   Mona Philips of Saratoga Springs, and her friends David Blackard
of Pompano Beach, Fla., and Marge DiNovo of Latham were as busy
watching people as they were the thundering thoroughbreds from
Philips' box in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call this `Kissing Day' because we're greeting old
friends,'' Philips said. DiNovo called the opener ``beautiful. I
had the early double and won $50 on a $2 bet, so the season is off
to an excellent start.'' ``Every year it gets more exciting,''
Blackard said.
</P>
<P>
   Smack in the middle of the outdoor crowd, sitting beneath a
shady tree in front of the paddock pari-mutuel betting windows,
were Karen and Leo Falconio from Latham. Leo Falconio, 59, began
his 43rd racing season yesterday. He looked forward to placing his
money on filly Circle of Life, which placed second in a photo
finish in the Schuylerville Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just great being here for opening day. I love the
atmosphere,'' he said. ``Plus, you meet everybody you haven't seen
all year. This is in my back yard. It's home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
