<HEADER>
A8993 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NONSTOP-EATING-ART-2T     07-29 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NONSTOP-EATING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNACKING ABOUNDS AS AMERICA BECOMES A NATION OF NIBBLERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos (NYT16, NYT17) are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ On a Sunday morning at a Roman Catholic church here,
Mary Hallan Fiorito glanced at a nearby pew to see a woman drinking
a can of Coke during Mass.
</P>
<P>
   At a musical in a Broadway theater, Alex Wang turned to the row
behind him to discover people eating corn on the cob.
</P>
<P>
   In schools that once forbade chewing gum, students now bring
doughnuts and candy to class _ along with chewing gum.
</P>
<P>
   Americans seem to be eating all the time, and wherever they
please.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers now see eating as something to be done while you do
something else,'' said Bobby Calder, a marketing professor at
Northwestern University. ``Everybody wants to save time by
multitasking. So you don't just sit down and eat. You eat while you
work, while you're watching TV, while you drive.''
</P>
<P>
   The automobile, among the favorite places for people to snack,
is well on its way to becoming a rolling dining room. A car is
scarcely considered worth driving now without cup holders in the
front and back. Some cars now have refrigerated glove boxes. And
within the next six months, the Samsung Corp. plans to market the
first microwave for cars and minivans. The microwave will plug into
the cigarette lighter.
</P>
<P>
   Less than one in four Americans now stick to the
three-square-meal routine. Only 24 percent of people eat breakfast,
lunch and dinner and nothing else, according to a 1996 survey by
Roper Starch Worldwide, a marketing research concern based in
Manhattan, down from 33 percent in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate that a majority of families still eat dinner
together, or at least say they do. But a walk through any
convenience store or grocery store shows that ``portable foods''
have been taking up a lot more room on the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get nervous if I don't have something to munch on,'' said
Paul Johnson, a 34-year-old computer programmer in Chicago, as he
left a convenience store with a bag of fat-free chips and a very
large cup of a frosty drink. ``I guess some people are like that
with smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   Health experts say the increased snacking is partly to blame for
the rising rates of obese and overweight people. Some 52 percent of
Americans are now overweight, the highest rate ever, according to
the National Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eating has become a recreational activity,'' said Linda Van
Horn, a nutritionist in Chicago. ``And it's one of the biggest
reasons for the epidemic of obesity in this country. It's the
biggest health problem we face.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Van Horn said that people were clearly snacking for reasons
that went beyond hunger. ``It's a comfort thing,'' she said, ``like
having your baby blanket with you.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Americans did not just recently pick up the habit of
eating outside the home. As far back as a generation ago, the New
Yorker cartoonist, Saul Steinberg, was skewering the growing
tendency of people to dine on the dash.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, people in the food business say, snacks
have become a main course. And stores like 7-Eleven are increasing
the number of products that can be eaten with one hand, like sealed
tacos, stuffed breadsticks and hamburgers in the shape of a hot
dog.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hultquist, a spokesman for the Food Marketing Institute, a
trade group in Washington, said the two-income family and busy
lives of children had changed eating habits for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're simply not going back to the days of spending two hours
in the kitchen every night preparing a meal,'' Hultquist said.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-food restaurants, which report that 50 percent of their
sales are now at the drive-by window, are selling things like
french-toast sticks, which can be eaten while driving.
</P>
<P>
   In some markets, McDonalds is testing the McSalad Shaker, which
comes in a plastic container that fits in a car cup-holder. It is
designed so that the customer can pour in the dressing, fasten the
top and shake it up, then eat it with a long fork.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of Michael Batterberry, the editor of Food Arts
magazine, the flowering of the eat-where-we-may style, was
nourished by mineral water.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing reached a kind of virus with the carrying of
water bottles by the yuppies in the '80s,'' Batterberry said. When
people started walking around offices with their water bottles, he
said, a line had been crossed. And there seems to be no turning
back.
</P>
<P>
   In some offices, desks and cubicles look almost like food
pantries _ chips, nuts, rice cakes, fruit _ all placed within easy
reach of the telephone and the computer keyboard. Food has become
requisite at almost any staff meeting. This practice of all-day
grazing, meanwhile, has largely replaced the old-fashioned business
lunch, for which workers actually leave the office.
</P>
<P>
   Libraries, which once stood at the vanguard of etiquette,
shooshing talkers and scowling at nibblers, have given up the fight
in many places. They have taken a page from the big booksellers and
started selling coffee near the stacks.
</P>
<P>
   Some movie theaters have apparently taken the tack that if
people want to eat, they will feed them. Some now sell turkey
breast sandwiches and even smoked salmon along with popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the big chain bookstores, Borders and Barnes &AMP;
Noble, where designer coffee and snacks was a big boost to
business, has not gone unnoticed by other businesses. The Ikea
furniture store has a cafeteria, and Crate and Barrel sells coffee.
</P>
<P>
   It has become rare for a group of people to gather, even for a
short time, without some snacking. At almost every youth soccer or
baseball game, one of the player's parents are assigned to bring
treats for the team, generally candy, chips and soda. Some of the
teams wait until after the game for the treats, but some have
half-time treats, too. As if that is not enough, some parents send
their children to the games equipped with soda and chips.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
