<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANK-BYPASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REP. FRANK TO UNDERGO BYPASS SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- US Rep. Barney Frank (D-Mass.) will have coronary
bypass surgery Friday, but he said Thurday expects to be back on
the floor of the House as soon as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, 59, who suffered a mild heart attack in 1990, is
scheduled to have the multiple bypass operation at the National
Naval Medical Center in Bethesda, Md. Four or more arteries from
his legs will be transplanted to his heart, allowing blood to
bypass clogged coronary arteries.
</P>
<P>
   Frank suffered chest pains after exercising or exerting himself
on several recent occasions, and consulted a doctor last week. A
stress test last Friday, and a heart catheterization procedure on
Wednesday convinced his physicians that he needed the surgery
before the August 7 congressional recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would obviously like to disrupt my work as little as
possible,'' said Frank. ``I hope to be able to do some voting next
week. They tell me if things go well I should be out by Tuesday.
Voting, as many of my colleagues know, is not heavy lifting. One
can vote without a great deal of stress and strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a job,'' Frank said. ``I'm not going to put my life at
risk. . . . But one vote can make a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank said that his overall cholesterol level was low, at 164,
but that he has a chronic shortage of the beneficial type of
artery-scouring cholesterol that helps prevent clogging. Both his
father and grandfather died at early ages of heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have enough good cholesterol, and that is causing
blockage,'' Frank said. ``The one defect in my inheritance.''
</P>
<P>
   After his 1990 heart attack, Frank had angioplasty treatment --
in which a thin tube with a balloon-type device at its tip is
threaded through clogged coronary arteries, and then inflated to
clear them. He has been taking drugs in the last decade to thin his
blood and boost his good cholesterol. He has also followed a
fitness regime, exercising on a stair machine and lifting weights.
</P>
<P>
   Frank helped lead the Democratic defense of President Clinton
during last year's impeachment debate, and said that the workload
might have been a factor in a recent loss of stamina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my first heart attack after I was involved in my own set
of accusations so maybe there is a correlation between sex-related
scandals and heart attacks -- in which case I hope everybody will
behave,'' Frank said. ``It gives the phrase `affairs of the heart'
a new meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank's health insurance will cover the cost of the operation,
after he pays a $250 deductible. His experience with heart disease
has given him a first-hand look at the problems Americans face with
health costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes the bypass operation leaves him in better condition
than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds, to some extent, more ominous than it is,'' said
Frank. ``The likelihood is I will resume my life after a
recuperation period in better physical health than before because
my arteries will be fully functioning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
