A8995 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NONSTOP-EATING-ART-2N     07-29 0226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NONSTOP-EATING-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CHICAGO: and chips.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To Mary Hallen Fiorito, who spotted the Coke-drinking woman at
church, the constant eating is a sign that people cannot deny
themselves, even for a short time. ``You'd think you could get
through 45 minutes, wouldn't you?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hallen Fiorito, the vice chancellor for the Archdiocese of
Chicago, said it had also become common for people to bring little
bags of cereal to church for their little ones. And then they leave
the bags in the pews.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're trying to reach a state of spiritual
contemplation,'' she said, ``there is nothing like sitting on a bag
of Cheerios to throw you off.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Van Horn, the mother of a soccer player as well as a
nutritionist, was alarmed by what she considered to be an excess of
treats. She said that children who are obese in the second and
third grade have a very difficult time ever slimming down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing playing children need is fluid replacement,''
Ms. Van Horn said. ``That's water.''
</P>
<P>
   At her suggestion, the treats for the soccer games were changed
from candy and chip to fruits.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the soccer players were happy about the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure at first they're thinking, `Oh, no here comes the
nutritionist,''' said Ms. Van Horn. ``They thought I was raining on
their parade.''
</P>
</TEXT>
