u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWISS-ACCIDENT-NYT &LR;      07-29 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-ACCIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS POLICE IDENTIFY 2 OF THE 19 VICTIMS ON `CANYONING' ACCIDENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Switzerland, New Zealand, Britain)   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERLAKEN, Switzerland _ As rescue workers in helmets and wet
suits continued searching churning rapids near here for two missing
tourists, the police said Thursday that they had identified two of
the 19 victims of Tuesday's flash flood, a Swiss woman and a man
from New Zealand who were guides on the disastrous canyoning
excursion.
</P>
<P>
   The flash flood turned the small Saxeten Brook near this resort
town into a torrent, crushing 15 men and four women against rocks
and drowning them. Six people were injured.
</P>
<P>
   A local fireman told investigators that he had gone to the top
of the gorge when 45 clients of the Swiss company Adventure World
and their eight guides were preparing to descend to the rapids and
warned them that an approaching storm could prove dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``A firemen in Saxeten warned the young people to be careful,''
said Markus Gerber, commander of the fire department in Wilderswil,
a mountain hamlet that overlooks the Saxeten. ``He told them it was
hazardous.''
</P>
<P>
   Police investigators confirmed Gerber's account.
</P>
<P>
   At least 20 survivors are being kept in the secluded Chalet
Jungfrau in Lauterbrunnen, 13 miles from Interlaken. Reporters are
being kept away by police officers and employees of Contiki
Holidays, a British tour company that had taken 99 clients on two
Swiss tours this week. Forty-four chose the canyoning option
offered in their package, and most of the victims are believed to
be Contiki clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be offering any canyoning trips anymore, anywhere,''
Bernice Windley, a spokeswoman for Contiki Holidays, told Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said it could take up to three weeks to identify
all the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Ulrich Zollinger, deputy chief of the Swiss Forensics Institute
in Bern, said at a news conference Thursday in Interlaken that 10
of the 19 bodies had been examined, and that the cause of death was
drowning. But he added, ``We found a lot of bruises on the faces of
the victims, and also found trauma to the brains and internal
organs,'' which he said could have been caused when the victims
crashed into rocks or logs. He said the bodies were found without
helmets or rubber shoes, which had probably been forced off by the
force of the torrent.
</P>
<P>
   In the third day of a tragedy that has turned Interlaken, a
carefree mecca for young thrill-seekers, into a somber retreat,
reporters have been kept away from witnesses, survivors and company
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Georg Hoedle, the founder of Adventure World, delivered a
statement to the press Thursday, saying he could not give out any
information about the incident, and pleading for understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still difficult to comprehend what was happening,''
Hoedle said, referring to the accident. ``While the investigation
is going on, I am unable to give you any further information than
this. I hope you understand our position in this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation could lead to criminal charges if the
magistrates determine that there was willful negligence. Civil
lawsuits by survivors and relatives of the victims could ensue
regardless of the police findings.
</P>
<P>
   Information about Adventure World's operations has mainly come
from its Web site, which boasts of its safety precautions and says
there are ``at all times emergency exists from the canyon every
400-500 meters.''
</P>
<P>
   Some former clients say their own experience led them to doubt
those claims.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Griesbach, 28, an investment research analyst in Chicago,
said that on a canyoning excursion organized by Adventure World in
June 1997, he shattered his wrist when he slipped while jumping
from a rock down into a churning river.
</P>
<P>
   Griesbach said that he knew instantly he was badly injured, but
that there was no way out of the gorge except by swimming and
climbing down rocks to the bottom of the river with the group,
which he said took several hours.
</P>
<P>
   He said his guides applied first aid but did not have
communications equipment and could not radio ahead for help. He
waited in a van while other clients ate snacks and discussed the
trip before being taken to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   After surgery, he said, two company representatives visited him
once and told him they had reassessed the safety of the area and
would remove it from their itineraries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was, like, you're telling me now it's not safe?'' he
recalled. ``I was 1 or 2 feet away from dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Griesbach had gone bungee-jumping with Adventure World the day
before and was asked to sign a waiver. No waiver was presented for
the canyoning trip, however. ``I don't know why,'' he said. ``Maybe
they forgot.''
</P>
<P>
   Adventure World representatives could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   There are few rules or regulations governing canyoning, which
has grown extremely popular in Switzerland over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of now, there are no rules on canyoning, or legal measures
to control it,'' Stefan Blaettler, deputy commander of the Bern
police, said Thursday. ``Everything is up to the enterprises that
offer the sport. They do it at their own risk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
