<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUBARAK OFFERS TO ACT AS MEDIATOR IN ISRAELI-PALESTINIAN TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Egypt _ Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, who has
considerable influence with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, on
Thursday offered to step in as an informal mediator to help settle
a dispute that threatens to sidetrack the Middle East peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to meet with Mr. Arafat in a couple of days to
see what can be accepted,'' Mubarak said after a meeting here with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak at Ras El Tin palace, the second
between the two men in the last three weeks as Barak has dashed
from nation to nation to enlist help in reviving the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has proposed rethinking the terms of the Wye River
memorandum, the latest agreement between Israel and the
Palestinians. But Arafat has demanded that Israel act immediately
to fulfill its obligations, objecting particularly to Barak's call
for a delay in carrying out parts of the accord, which calls for
further Israeli troop withdrawals from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak did not say whether Barak had persuaded him to accept
his plan to change the terms and timing of the agreement. But
neither did Mubarak echo Arafat's demand to carry it out as
written.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Egyptian leader indicated that he may try to
persuade the Palestinians to work out a compromise to find ``ways
and means'' to implement the accord.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after Barak made his proposal in a late-night meeting
with Arafat, the Palestinian leader dispatched emissaries to Egypt
and Jordan on Wednesday, seeking help in fending off the Israeli
idea. But Mubarak's language suggested that he might see merit in
Israel's request, and Barak, who smiled though most of a joint news
conference Thursday, seemed plainly pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we choose a bumpy road instead of a main road, we cannot
ask ourselves in retrospect why have bumps,'' Barak said, trying to
make the case that the path toward a comprehensive peace might be
swifter if the two sides agree for now to set aside part of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak has long been Arafat's most important Arab patron. In
September 1995, when Yitzhak Rabin was still Israel's prime
minister, it was weeks of prodding and reassurance from Mubarak
that led to Arafat's acceptance of the second and most
consequential stage of the so-called Oslo accords, the one that
spelled out the extent of the most significant Israeli troop
withdrawals.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, with Middle East diplomacy once again moving forward
at a rapid pace, Mubarak seemed intent on reassuring Arafat and
other Palestinians who have been complaining loudly, particularly
over Barak's request for a delay in carrying out parts of the
latest accord. The agreement, signed last fall in Wye River, Md.,
calls for further Israeli troop withdrawals from the West Bank. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Egypt and Israel made peace two decades ago, but the peace has
remained cold, with anti-Israeli sentiment running deep among the
Egyptian public. Israeli officials have hoped that Barak's election
might prompt an improvement in bilateral ties, with steps that
might include the opening of a long-planned gas pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   But Mubarak may be most important for his mediating role, and
there was no indication Thursday that bilateral issues had been
discussed. Both sides said the subject had been the Middle East
peace effort, and that the Palestinian question had been at the top
of the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office earlier this month, Barak has devoted nearly
all his time and effort to the quest for a broader Middle East
peace. Thursday's meeting was the latest in a dizzying race
prompted by his vow to seek agreements with Syria, Lebanon and the
Palestinians within the next 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   At the Tuesday meeting between Israel and the Palestinians, the
two sides agreed to discuss Barak's proposal in low-level talks
over the next two weeks, and Barak has pledged to carry out the
accord as written if the Palestinians turn down the request for a
delay.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the Palestinians have shown no enthusiasm whatsoever
for the idea, which they see as a ploy by Israel to maintain its
hold on Palestinian land. Barak is apparently prepared to go
forward with a second phase of troop withdrawals required under the
accord, following on a first phase carried out last fall.
</P>
<P>
   But he has warned that implementation now of the third and final
phase of the accord would leave 15 Israeli-settlements entirely
surrounded by Palestinian territory, creating a potentially
volatile situation.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than risk violence, Barak would apparently prefer to
defer those withdrawals until the thornier questions that surround
the Israeli-Palestinian relationship, including borders,
settlements and the future of Jerusalem, can be resolved as part of
final-status negotiations. Israeli officials have said those talks
could begin swiftly, perhaps by the end of August.
</P>
<P>
   In public, Barak would say Thursday only that he favors changes
in the ``ways, means, and timing'' of the Wye River accord. But he
maintained his warning tone, saying that ``both sides'' would bear
responsibility if a decision to carry out the accord now led to a
breakdown later.
</P>
<P>
   Both Barak and Arafat spoke by telephone to Clinton on
Wednesday, apparently in hopes of enlisting him on their side of
the argument. The three leaders met in the Moroccan capital, Rabat,
just five days ago, when the funeral of King Hassan provided a
brief opportunity for their first three-way meeting.
</P>
<P>
   After a prolonged stalemate under the last Israeli prime
minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, the Palestinians are plainly eager to
see tangible gains toward a broader peace. Among those who
complained publicly Wednesday about Barak's proposal was Ziad Abu
Zayyad, a Palestinian Cabinet member, who told Israeli Radio: ``We
wasted three years under Netanyahu when there was no advance in the
peace process, and it is too bad that we are wasting time again.''
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak said Thursday that the Palestinian skepticism was
understandable. ``Arafat has his doubts,'' he said. He said that
this was ``not exactly because of Wye, but because of the other
previous agreements that were not implemented'' under Netanyahu,
including the long delay in Israel's withdrawal from the West Bank
town of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Mubarak said, the Palestinians should recognize
that ``Barak is keen on implementing'' the Wye agreement and that
taking time to talk about possible arrangements would not be a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two or three weeks' delay is no problem,'' he said. Asked
whether he had been persuaded by Barak's reasoning, Mubarak would
say only that he had been persuaded that he and his guest had ``a
very good mutual understanding of the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other diplomatic steps in recent days has been a visit
by King Abdullah of Jordan to Syrian President Hafez Assad. That
meeting, the latest in a series between Assad and Jordanian
emissaries, came Monday, a day after the Jordanian monarch met with
Barak at the funeral in Morocco, which the Syrian leader did not
attend.
</P>
<P>
   The visit has added to speculation that King Abdullah may be
acting as an emissary between the two sides. And when Barak was
asked Thursday whether the king was serving as a go-between, he
chose not to answer that part of a reporter's question.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt was the first Arab state to make peace with Israel, in the
Camp David accords of 1979, and Barak said that his visit Thursday
reflected his determination to build on what he called that
``cornerstone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we are about to put the on capstones, _ peace with the
Palestinians and peace with Syria,'' the Israeli leader declared.
</P>
</TEXT>
