<HEADER>
A9005 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BRIDE30-COX     07-29 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BRIDE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gere, Roberts reunited in affable, unlikely `Bride'
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Jim Luksic
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nine years after Pretty Woman, its co-stars and director Garry
Marshall have joined forces again for Runaway Bride, a sugary
romantic-comedy whose components are crisply plugged into place.
</P>
<P>
   What you see is what you get, in slick moderation. And the
luster appears to be wearing off. Even seeing Julia Roberts riding
on horseback to the chords of the U2 anthem I Still Haven't Found
What I'm Looking For doesn't much restore the novelty of the
actress's pairing with Richard Gere.
</P>
<P>
   Plot mechanics pull us into downtown New York, where Gere
portrays columnist Ike Graham (``Journalism is literature in a
hurry.'') His job is to pen diatribes against women for USA Today,
whose editor happens to be his ex-wife Ellie (Rita Wilson).
</P>
<P>
   It isn't long before she fires Ike, not for his provocative
opinions, but because he used factual errors in a piece regarding
Maggie Carpenter (Roberts). The townsfolk of Hale, Md., have
witnessed her wedding debacles: she has left three prospective
grooms in the dust, while another sucker (Christopher Meloni) waits
_ to paraphrase the dialogue's sports parlance _ on deck.
</P>
<P>
   Now unemployed, Ike ventures to our heroine's hinterlands in the
hope of apologizing to Maggie and writing a feature about her next
ceremony's inevitable doom. Far from enthused is her affable but
alcoholic dad, Walter (Paul Dooley), while perpetual bridesmaid
Peggy (Joan Cusack, again contributing more to a role than it
deserves) lends support, however unnecessary; sparks between the
two leads fly inevitably and abundantly.
</P>
<P>
   What unspools is relatively harmless fluff in the fun-loving
hands of Marshall, a sitcom refugee who proved his filmmaking
mettle with Nothing in Common, teetered with Beaches and lost some
integrity with Exit to Eden and Dear God.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall did right himself, to an extent, earlier this year with
The Other Sister. This time he demonstrates a wise awareness of the
picture's limitations and an aptitude for making do. One shot
simultaneously captures Ike's flashy car and the old-fashioned
store from which he's driving away: It's a sharp, economical
glimpse of contrasting worlds. (Such editing, however, was needed
in a scene in which Maggie dangles from a church bell's rope for
what feels like an eternity.)
</P>
<P>
   And the director, who has a nonverbal cameo in a softball game,
assembles another engaging cast, including Hector Elizondo _ though
he and ever-dependable Cusack appear to be pining for stronger
material. Gere is asked to loosen up, and he does so naturally.
Roberts, conversely, seems inconsistent as her character, speaking
intellectually one minute and dimwittedly the next; she fared
better in the superior Notting Hill.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to appreciate a comedy that doesn't take itself
seriously. Amusing as this premise might be, especially videotaped
footage of the title figure's aborted trips to the altar, it
remains preposterous. Any viewer who believes someone would back
out of four weddings _ and that the guests would stand idly by _
should inherit the dunce cap from whoever ran for cover during
Orson Welles' The War of the Worlds broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Acclaimed cinematographer Stuart Dryburgh (The Piano)
perseveres, but he still can't augment the obtuse, golly-gee script
by Josann McGibbon and Sara Parriott (of Three Men and A Little
Lady infamy). One segment involving a guitar-playing former beau is
as stale as the garage in which it takes place.
</P>
<P>
   Runaway Bride traverses a breezy, winding road to mild thrills.
Country girl Maggie, like Sandra Bullocks' player in Hope Floats,
is truly the Queen of Corn _ and after sifting through this movie's
hokey platitudes, she appears in no danger of losing that label.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
