</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-WITCH30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Blair Witch' proves you don't have to have big bucks to be
scary
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Blair Witch Project
 &HT;    Directors: DANIEL MYRICK, EDUARDO SANCHEZ; Starring: HEATHER
DONAHUE, MICHAEL WILLIAMS, JOSHUA LEONARD; 87 minutes; CROSS
POINTE, HUBER HEIGHTS, LITTLE ART, NEW NEON MOVIES
 &HT;    R: Profanity
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A _ Excellent B _ Good
 &HT;    C _ FairD _ PoorF _ Abysmal
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pretty creepy stuff. That's how one woman describes the strange
lore surrounding the Blair Witch. Her words also apply to The Blair
Witch Project, a terrifying low-budget horror film that does for
the woods what Jaws did for water.
</P>
<P>
   Don't see it if you plan to go on an overnight camping trip any
time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ineffectual Hollywood fright flicks such as The Haunting,
the independent ``mockumentary'' scares the living daylights out of
you without a single special effect or an ounce of gore. Its
terrors lurk just beyond the camera's range, allowing your
imagination to conjure them through the power of suggestion. The
unseen proves to be much more horrifying than anything
visual-effects artists can create.
</P>
<P>
   I left an afternoon screening of the film with my heart racing,
grateful for daylight. That evening I found myself unable to sleep,
seeing the chilling final shot every time I closed my eyes. A local
theater manager said he slept with his television on as a night
light for several days after he saw the film.
</P>
<P>
   The Blair Witch Project has Hollywood studios running scared.
Warner Bros. Pictures moved up the opening of Deep Blue Sea and
Universal pushed back Mystery Men to avoid Blair Witch's expansion
today from limited release to 1,000 screens. Last weekend the
supernatural phenomenon averaged $63,812 per screen on 31 screens,
compared with The Haunting's $11,907 per-screen average on 2,808
screens. The film's Web site (www.blairwitch.com) has had more than
21 million hits to date.
</P>
<P>
   With that success comes the now widespread knowledge that the
film's ingenious premise is fiction. Yet the airtight execution of
directors Daniel Myrick and Eduardo Sanchez makes it easy to
suspend disbelief and share the vicarious nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1994, student filmmakers Heather Donahue, Joshua
Leonard and Michael Williams hiked into Maryland's Black Hills to
shoot a documentary on the Blair Witch, a local legend whose bloody
history dates to 1785. They were never heard from again. One year
later, their footage was found.
</P>
<P>
   The Blair Witch Project presents their ill-fated adventure,
using both their 16mm black-and-white film and Heather's High-8
color video recordings. Shaky hand-held shots and choppy jump cuts
heighten the film's frighteningly authentic realism.
</P>
<P>
   The Blair Witch legend develops through Heather's filmed
stand-up segments on sites of strange occurrences, such as Coffin
Rock, and through interviews with local residents. The seeds of
horror are planted in these seemingly innocuous scenes. Your mind
later draws on the accounts to psychologically complete the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   The story meanders somewhat as Heather, Mike and Josh trek
through the dense forest. Their camaraderie gives way to conflict
when they become lost and to terror when they are beset by an
escalating series of bizarre and disturbing events.
</P>
<P>
   When Heather cries into the video camera lens that she feels
``hungry, cold and hunted,'' she really means it. The actors shot
the film themselves in eight days, moving between predetermined
points and improvising their scenes. Direction was limited to
written notes left along with food and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Myrick and Sanchez shadowed the actors unseen and wore them down
physically and mentally by making them move farther each day on
decreasing amounts of food, and by terrorizing them in the night.
The performances, like the film itself, are extremely convincing
and unnerving.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty creepy stuff, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
