<HEADER>
A9007 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURD-NOMINATION-HNS &LR;      07-29 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURD-NOMINATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURD NOMINATION APPROVED BY SENATE JUDICIARY PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ David N. Hurd cleared the first hurdle in his quest
to become a U.S. District Court judge for the Northern District of
New York when his nomination was approved Thursday by the Senate
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination of Hurd, 62, of Rome, N.Y., is expected to move
shortly to the full Senate for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Utica jurist was nominated in February by President Clinton
to fill a federal district judge seat in Albany that has been
vacant since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd, a Democrat and a former trial lawyer who is currently a
magistrate judge for the Northern District of New York, easily
fielded questions from Senate Judiciary Chairman Orrin G. Hatch,
R-Utah, after raising his right hand and swearing to tell the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   Seated at a long table with four other nominees for federal
judgeships, Hurd thanked Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., who
recommended him for the post a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch started the questioning of Hurd by asking him whether he
believes cameras should be allowed in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd said cameras aren't allowed in the courtroom in the Second
Circuit except for at ceremonial events, but if that should change,
it would be up to the individual judges to decide.
</P>
<P>
   Under further questioning from Hatch, Hurd said that while he
would be bound by precedents of a higher court, he has no legal or
moral beliefs that would prohibit him from upholding a death
penalty sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch also asked the nominees to comment on the fact that people
sentenced to death often succeed in delaying executions for up to
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd responded, ``I agree that 10- to 15- to 20-year delays are
much too long and one of the duties of a district judge would be to
expedite cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch warned the nominees against judicial activism, saying he
is disturbed by judges who ``expand their role in unreasonable
ways'' by rendering opinions colored by personal bias or politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You understand your role is not to make the law,'' except in
cases in which there isn't any precedent, Hatch said. ``You really
need to follow precedent or we lose control of our system.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., in an interview predicted
``smooth sailing,'' for Hurd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Hurd has tremendous bipartisan respect,'' Schumer said.
``I think he's a classy addition to the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Judicial Conference of the United States,
the policy-making body of the federal courts, called on Congress to
quickly appoint a judge to New York's Northern District.
</P>
<P>
   The conference pointed out that the district had the eighth
highest backlog of pending cases _ an average of 664 per judge _ in
the country. The national average is 471 pending cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Northern District has waited far too long for this day,''
said Moynihan, who called Hurd ``superbly qualified'' to fill the
position.
</P>
<P>
   The seat that Hurd, 62, is being considered for has been vacant
since the late U.S. District Judge Con. G. Cholakis stepped down
because of illness.
</P>
<P>
   It's the only remaining vacancy in the 32-county Northern
District of New York, which stretches as far south as Ulster County
up through Albany to the Canadian border and west through much of
the Southern Tier.
</P>
<P>
   The post pays $ 136,700 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd, 62, who grew up in Camillus, N.Y., a suburb of Syracuse,
was accompanied to Capitol Hill by his son Steven, 30, a lawyer in
New York City, and his wife, Connie.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the American College of Trial Lawyers, Hurd was
first appointed as a magistrate judge in 1991 and was reappointed
in January to a second, eight-year term. Magistrate judges are
junior judges in the federal system who may officiate on
preliminary stages of criminal cases, but not at criminal trials.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd practiced law at O'Shea, Griffin, Jones &AMP; McLaughlin from
1967 to 1991. Hurd received his undergraduate degree in 1959 from
Cornell University and his graduated cum laude from Syracuse
University College of Law in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
