u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CBSMORNING30-COX     07-29 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBSMORNING30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CBS bets on Bryant Gumbel to end its morning slump.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Chemistry is the key, and that's why
Operation Glass Slipper is so important.
</P>
<P>
   The Cinderella reference is CBS News' code name for its search
for a co-anchor for Bryant Gumbel, the man the network hopes will
become its new Prince Charming in the morning. After years of
embarrassing failure, CBS hopes to succeed with ``The Early Show''
when it debuts Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   A glass-walled studio is under construction on New York's Fifth
Avenue, and on-air contributors are being lined up. But no partner
has been found for Gumbel, who left NBC's top-rated ``Today'' two
years ago. The chosen one almost certainly will be a woman,
although Gumbel and executive producer Steve Friedman would not
rule out hiring a man.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be a well-known CBS woman like Lesley Stahl of ``60
Minutes'' or an unknown from within or a star from another network?
Elizabeth Vargas of ABC News has been mentioned. But then so has
Oprah Winfrey, who almost certainly is not a serious contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have to be someone compatible, someone with live news
experience, someone with warmth,'' Gumbel told TV critics gathered
for the annual press preview of the fall season. ``It's a matter of
comfort. Finding the right person isn't as easy as it sounds. .
</P>
<P>
   Friedman, who worked with Gumbel on ``Today,'' pointed out that
Madame X will not have to be a star. Jane Pauley was an unknown
26-year-old anchor from Indianapolis when ``Today'' tapped her, and
Katie Couric was not exactly a household name when she landed the
job opposite Gumbel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television makes its own stars,'' Friedman said. ``The
important thing for us is to find someone who can do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS has been struggling in the morning news business for many
years and sees its best hope in Gumbel. Such luminaries as Paula
Zahn and Diane Sawyer, now at the helm of ABC's No. 2-rated ``Good
Morning America,'' have preceded him and failed. After retiring
from ``Today'' and presiding over CBS's short-lived newsmagazine
``Public Eye,'' Gumbel is ready to re-enter the morning news war.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Bryant Gumbel who put the 'Today' show on the map in
the '80s,'' Friedman crowed. ``They've really just been building on
that success. Maybe our friends at 'Today' are getting tired of
doing it, and maybe the people who watch are getting tired, too. I
think people miss Bryant. There's nobody better at live,
play-by-play television.''
</P>
<P>
   A quick reality check finds that ``Today'' ratings went up when
Matt Lauer was brought in as Gumbel's replacement. But reality
checks don't dampen CBS's optimism. The network is convinced that
Gumbel's ``Early Show'' will put an end to the network's legacy of
failure in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   You may ontact Diane Holloway at dholloway(at)statesman.com or
445-3608.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
