<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Friday, July 30 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   BIG-BREAK (Los Angeles) _ Studio City resident Joanne Small has
worked in movies and TV as a writer, an editor and now as a script
supervisor for ``The X-Files.'' But what she really wants to do is
direct. She's hoping her big break will come from a 20-minute film
she's making over five days starting Thursday. ``Joey Was Here'' is
her project for the Directing Workshop for Women, Hollywood's
best-kept secret. By Steve Carney. (Will move in the ``e''
entertainment and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   PROP-187 (Los Angeles) _ Supporters of Proposition 187 said they
would challenge the deal between Gov. Gray Davis and civil rights
organizations, nullifying the major provisions of the ballot
measure that sought to limit services to illegal immigrants. By
Rick Orlov and Terri Hardy. (Will move in the ``a'' national and
``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   MTA-PROJECTS (Los Angeles) _ The MTA board approved a staff
recommendation of nearly $570 million for many projects, including
providing funds to match the state's allocation for the 101-405
interchange. But the MTA board also warned that it might revoke
much of the money if it loses the legal battle over a consent
decree which will require the agency to buy more than 480 new buses
and hire the drivers and mechanics to keep them running. By Douglas
Haberman. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SPEARS-LOOKALIKE (Los Angeles) _ Guess who won the lookalike
contest for pop singer Britney Spears. Not only is the winner 24
years old (a decade beyond the age of the average contestant. He's
a man. The response of one of the hundreds of pig-tailed female
contestants _ ``That's show biz.'' By Donna Huffaker. (Will move in
the ``e'' entertainment and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   WELLPOINT-BID (Los Angeles) _ WellPoint has made a $260 million
bid on the Blue Plan in Colorado. Apparently the bidding was
reopened this month on advice form the Colo. attorney general and
others after WellPoint complained that the Blue Plan was sold to a
competitor for a lower bid than Wellpoint's. By Jason Takenouchi.
(Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IHOP-NYSE (Los Angeles) _ IHOP hopes it can stack up with the
big boys on Wall Street. The Glendale-based franchiser of
International House of Pancakes restaurants announced Thursday it
has filed an application to be listed on the New York Stock
Exchange, forsaking Nasdaq for the Big Board. IHOP officials hope a
NYSE listing will give the company greater exposure to investors _
both domestic and international _ that prefer NYSE listings. By
Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
