<SLUG> BC-MATCHMAKER-ROOMMATES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UT DEVELOPING ON-LINE SERVICE FOR STUDENTS SEEKING ROOMMATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ University of Texas students living on campus
may soon be able to steer clear of roommates from hell by applying
a new-fangled solution to an age-old problem.
</P>
<P>
   Student leaders and campus housing officials are developing an
on-line matchmaking service that's set to debut in December. Those
seeking compatible dormitory roommates for the fall of 2000, the
theory goes, can find who best matches their lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize this was such an innovative idea,'' said Eric
Opiela, student body vice president who hatched the plan with other
student leaders last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we do it is you have a series of questions the Web
page will ask you and you click yes or no,'' he said. ``It will
show you a list of other people that have the same criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions will attempt to identify and separate those who
have clashing personal traits or quirks that most often contribute
to roommate conflict: Smokers and nonsmokers, loud music lovers and
quiet types, night owls and early risers, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Ochner, director of UT's division of housing and food
services, said students returning to school this fall will be asked
for their ideas in drafting questions for the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Only students applying for housing will have access to the site
and all postings will be voluntary, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman LaDonna Davis of Dallas, who is studying business, said
she'd feel a bit uneasy posting personal information about herself,
even if the access to it is limited. She said you might meet people
you'd rather not, but the idea has potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know roommates that have conflicts over studying because
some are louder than others and play music, some can't stand the
music, so yeah,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a person that's been having a problem with her
roommate. She complains a lot because her roommate comes in, puts
all the lights on, slams doors, goes through drawers and all that
kind of stuff,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Kindsvatter, a graduating senior from The Woodlands near
Houston, said the online service could help alleviate anxieties for
those who want to see just what they might be getting into. Yet she
has doubts that matching roommates on the basis of such things as
sleeping patterns will somehow create eternally blissful dorm life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kind of things change throughout the year. I don't see
how basic personal information like that would eliminate
conflicts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the idea's biggest supporters acknowledge that there are
some human problems that even technology can't conquer, especially
intolerance of roommates with different sexual orientations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I think is the worst roommate problem I've seen can't be
solved with a program like this,'' said Opiela, who also has served
as a resident assistant at the Jester Center dorm for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their conflict was that one of the residents could not accept
that the other was homosexual. He kept coming to my room and saying
I can't deal with this. It's a very difficult roommate conflict to
resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   These days sharing a room is a new experience for a majority of
freshman college students, said Gary Schwarzmueller, executive
director of the Association of College and University Housing
Officers. As a result, the challenges facing housing officials
dealing with disgruntled roommates are greater than in the past
when most children grew up sharing a room with a sibling.
</P>
<P>
   He added the online matchmaking might be more effective for
returning students because kids in high school are often not as
self- aware and are prone to change when they reach college.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Sasse, director of residence life at Texas A&AMP;M University,
said the Aggie approach is simple, fair and objective. All room
assignments are based on the date of application.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried lots of different things. Though, to be honest, we
haven't found anything we think is successful. Maybe it's because
parents influence what the students fill out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At North Carolina State University in Raleigh, however, an
elaborate online match-making service gets credit for cutting
roommate assignment requests by a third, said Jim Pappenhagen,
assistant director for university housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think roommate conflicts will decrease because of this,''
said Opiela who studied the North Carolina system. ``But there's
something to be said for roommate conflict. It builds character.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
