r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     07-29 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING AS ART: COLLECTION OF TV COMMERCIALS IS ALSO A HANDS-ON
PRIMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If Michelangelo were alive today, he'd probably be working on
Madison Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   That shocking statement by industry journalist and author
Bernice Kanner reflects the power of what she terms a modern art
form _ advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than movies or TV programming, advertising holds a mirror
up to show us who and what we are _ or long to be,'' she writes in
her new book. ``The language of advertising becomes our vernacular;
their dress, our wardrobes, their mores, our customs. ... Like it
or not, it is a pure expression of the world we live in today.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Kanner needs to take a break from her world as a marketing
correspondent for CBS News, a marketing commentator for Bloomberg
News and a columnist for Working Woman. Maybe her 13 years of
writing the ``On Madison Avenue'' column for New York magazine has
completely warped her vision.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe she's just not afraid to tell us what we instinctively
already know. Regardless, her vision of the advertising age comes
shining through in her book ``The 100 Best TV Commercials ... And
Why They Worked'' (Random House, 252 pages, $29.95).
</P>
<P>
   After just a glance at this book, it's easy to understand why
Kanner is so impassioned about her subject. Who can forget the
powerful image of the Native American man silently letting a tear
roll down his cheek after observing pollution or the young adults
from every nationality singing about teaching the world to sing in
perfect harmony _ and buying them a Coke as well.
</P>
<P>
   This collection of TV commercials was organized by Leo Burnett's
Creative Exchange, an archive of more than 5,000 commercials put
together by the international advertising agency. The list was
organized by Burnett and then passed around to a number of other
creative and advertising industry luminaries.
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting to note that even though most consider the
United States to have elevated advertising to such Everest heights
in the power of persuasion, just 42 of the top 100 commercial
winners were made here. Twenty-eight were from the United Kingdom,
with the remainder from France, Japan, Spain, Brazil and even
Singapore and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   And it is because of this global look at the industry that the
book loses some of its impact. After all, this is video and audio
we're talking about. Though the commercials from the United States
lose some of their punch on the printed page, it's not hard to
recall experiencing viewing them as commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But when the reader hasn't seen the commercial but is merely
reading the dialogue and scene-setting, it's often hard to imagine
its effectiveness. I'm sure the collection on a master video is
much more compelling than the book in this respect.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for those involved with the industry, this book has many
practical means for hands-on learning.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Spanish Danone yogurt commercial in 1985. Children
urged their father to eat yogurt, offering such parental
suggestions as ``It'll make your hair curly, Dad.'' Yogurt sales
had dropped 8 percent before the spot, but sales soared 9.9 percent
the year the ad ran and an additional 5.9 percent the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The message: ``Children can be more than just adorable props
grabbing our attention; they can elicit profound emotion in us,''
Kanner writes.
</P>
<P>
   By using the commercials described, she engages the reader in
all the basics and secrets of advertising. ``Demo'' advertising, a
few well-crafted words, a catchy tune, a comedic situation, using
children, using animals, using sex, using violence _ all of this
and more are discussed.
</P>
<P>
   But the book goes further in showing us a history of this
amazing industry. Kanner shows how Apple's 1984 introduction of
Macintosh (in which the product wasn't even shown) was ``probably
the most publicized moment in advertising history.''
</P>
<P>
   Other such moments that have changed the face of a powerful
medium are discussed, further evidence, perhaps, that Michelangelo
would have ended up in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Promoted: Real Strategies for Advancing Your Career''
</P>
<P>
   By Harry E. Chambers
</P>
<P>
   Perseus Books, $13
</P>
<P>
   Most career books focus on changing jobs or making the most of
what you have. This one focuses on a third alternative: getting
promoted. Most of us are hard workers, consultant Harry E. Chambers
contends. But many are not being ``visibly efficient'' _ getting
the recognition needed as a crucial contributor to the organization
to be promoted. Think of this as an update to the Broadway show
``How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffettology''
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Buffett and David Clark
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster, $14
</P>
<P>
   Now out in paperback, this bestseller can't be overlooked as one
of the best books about mega-investor Warren Buffett. Written by
insiders, (Mary Buffett is Warren's former daughter-in-law, and
David Clark is an investment analyst and Buffett family friend), it
describes the master investor's strategy, as well as provides
profiles of the 54 companies in which Buffett has invested and
continues to follow. The book's approach is straight-forward and it
provides an interesting history of the most profitable investor out
there.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Along in Family Business: The Relationship
Intelligence Handbook''
</P>
<P>
   By Edwin A. Hoover and Colette Lombard Hoover
</P>
<P>
   Routledge, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   Why do some family businesses last more than a hundred years,
while others collapse before 12 months have gone by? Psychologists
and family business gurus Edwin and Colette Hoover contend that
``getting along'' is the secret. They call it `Relationship
Intelligence.' Using this model, the Hoovers discuss how to
integrate your RQ into your business successfully and then watch it
grow.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
