<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-WINE-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE MAKERS SAY PROPOSED LEGISLATION WOULD HURT LEGAL SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 1)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The wine industry sees legislation aimed at
stopping teen-agers from ordering its products over the Internet as
something worse than the grapes of wrath.
</P>
<P>
   Mounting a campaign against the measure, which has passed the
Senate and is expected to come before the House this week, the
industry says it would hurt small wineries' efforts to make sales
to adults over the Internet and through mail-order catalogues.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would give state attorneys general broad new
power to go to federal courts seeking enforcement of state liquor
laws. Now the prosecutors may go only to their own state courts.
</P>
<P>
   In 19 states it is illegal for alcohol to be distributed by
direct delivery _ whether bought over the Internet, mail-order
catalogue or phone.
</P>
<P>
   The measure began moving through Congress earlier this year
after Senate Judiciary Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, aired before
his committee a report from television station KUTV in Salt Lake
City. The report showed how a 13-year-old, using a home computer,
ordered a case of beer from a micro-brewery with her older
brother's credit card. The Senate adopted Hatch's legislation in
May.
</P>
<P>
   The identical House measure is authored by Rep. Joe Scarborough,
R-Fla. He says most wineries need not worry about his bill: ``Only
those shippers who violate state alcohol laws will be affected.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. George Radanovich, R-Calif., a lawmaker who also owns a
small winery in Mariposa, Calif., argues that the measure would
have the ``unintended consequence of crippling small wineries in
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Some state attorneys general have said they need the legislation
in order to target direct alcohol distributors located in other
states.
</P>
<P>
   But most California lawmakers insist there is no evidence that
people under age 21 are actually using the Internet to order wine
and beer despite the TV reports showing how easily it can be done.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., who opposes the measure, says the
rise of the Internet has scared beer and wine distributors, who
have pushed for the legislation because they view direct alcohol
sales as a threat to their profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's against under-age marketing of alcohol,'' Lofgren
said in an interview. ``But it's really a fight between different
parts of the alcohol industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, it takes two or three weeks for wine or beer to be
delivered once it has been ordered from the Internet or a
catalogue. Lofgren and Radanovich contend that most underage
drinkers will likely continue trying to buy alcohol from their
local liquor or convenience store rather than the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Wine makers say the legislation would hurt their efforts to get
all 50 states to allow them to ship their products directly to
out-of-state consumers.
</P>
<P>
   John De Luca, president of the San Francisco-based Wine
Institute, which represents 500 California wineries, said the
industry began its state-by-state effort 15 years ago _ before the
Internet became popular _ when rising numbers of tourists at
vineyards began asking if the wine they had tasted could be shipped
back home.
</P>
<P>
   De Luca noted that New Hampshire recently changed its law to
allow direct shipments and that Kentucky now allows its residents
visiting other states' vineyards to ship wine home to themselves.
But it does not allow direct shipment otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Other states with bans are Arizona, Arkansas, Delaware, Georgia,
Indiana, Kansas, Maine, Maryland, Mississippi, Montana, New York,
North Carolina, North Dakota, South Dakota, Tennessee, Texas, Utah
and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   With the Internet, wineries and breweries can reach beyond
tourists. Dozens of Internet sites like Beer Across America and
Virtual Vineyards beckon to new customers.
</P>
<P>
   De Luca says Internet sales of alcoholic beverages are minute.
Direct sales of wine from California are less than 1 percent of
total wine sales, he says.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases wineries _ as well as breweries and liquor
producers _ sell their products to distributors, who in turn sell
them to a liquor store or other authorized vendor.
</P>
<P>
   De Luca says the growing number of small wineries going on the
Internet will not hurt distributors because ``the average small
winery is only able to produce a few thousand cases each year and
simply does not have the quantities necessary to accommodate the
needs of wholesalers.''
</P>
<P>
   He says when there were fewer wine producers, distributors could
handle most of them. But the number of vintners has mushroomed. In
1963 there were 377 nationwide. Today there are 1,700 _ with 800 in
California.
</P>
<P>
   The wine and beer distributors say they have no problem with
people who directly sell alcohol legally, but they say legislation
is needed to crack down on people who sell it illegally.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation in Congress would ``maintain a level playing
field for all alcohol beverage sellers making everyone comply with
state laws,'' said Juanita D. Duggan, chief executive officer of
Wine and Spirits Wholesalers of America, Inc., a Washington-based
alcohol distributor trade group.
</P>
<P>
   David Rehr, vice president of the National Beer Wholesalers
Association, notes that the state of Utah, which does not allow
direct shipment of alcohol, recently intercepted 244 cases of beer
from Beer Across America. In Maryland, the Kendall-Jackson wine
company was fined $35,000 for illegal shipments in that state.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
