<HEADER>
A9030 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-650&AMP;ADD-N     07-29 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT TELLS KOSOVARS NOT TO ACT LIKE THEIR OPPRESSORS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ There were, no doubt, dark days during
the Kosovo conflict when Madeleine Albright wondered whether she
would manage to do what she did Thursday: address the Kosovar
Albanians in their own capital.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary of state arrived in Kosovo Thursday at a fragile
moment, when acts of revenge against Serbs by Kosovar Albanians
appear to be on the rise, tainting a victory that could be claimed
to be both theirs and hers. So the fiercest supporter within the
Clinton administration of the fight against President Slobodan
Milosevic _ some in Washington called it ``Madeleine's war'' _ had
a message that was celebratory but cautionary.
</P>
<P>
   Her theme appeared almost poignant as she delivered it on the
eve of a Balkan summit meeting with President Clinton in Sarajevo,
Bosnia, and just after the United States pledged $500 million for
the first phase of reconstruction of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is to be a true victory in Kosovo,'' she said, ``it
cannot be a victory of Albanians over Serbs, or NATO over Serbs. It
must be a victory of those who believe in the rights of the
individual over those who do not.''
</P>
<P>
   Revenge, she warned, was not the stuff of democracy. ``You will
not have the support of the world if you are intolerant and take
the law into your own hands,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Six days ago, 14 Serbs were killed at dusk as they were tilling
their fields in Gracko, a mostly Serbian village. Western officials
said Thursday that four suspects had been detained by NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   The killings caused concern among NATO and U.N. officials that
elements within the Kosovo Liberation Army are determined to force
the remaining Serbs in Kosovo to flee. Numbers are hard to pin
down, but of the 200,000 Serbs believed to be in Kosovo before the
war, fewer than 100,000 are still here, and families are leaving
daily.
</P>
<P>
   Albright talked of the Gracko killings in her speech, saying
critics would use the incident to show that the Kosovar Albanians
would act toward the Serbs ``as the Serb military and police acted
towards you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, `See, we are right, the Kosovar Albanians are no
better than the Serbs of Slobodan Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who swept into Pristina on a U.S. Air Force C-17, an
aircraft usually used for transporting troops and equipment,
started her day at NATO's headquarters. She met there with the
leader of NATO's troops in Kosovo, Gen. Michael Jackson of Britain,
and the head of the U. N. mission, Bernard Kouchner of France.
</P>
<P>
   Both NATO and the United Nations have blamed each other for a
slow beginning in Kosovo. Despite this, Albright declared herself
satisfied with the progress. For his part, Kouchner said, ``I am
still waiting for active police officers. Without means it is not
easy to move very fast.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons for the dearth of international policemen,
who are supposed to be the backbone of a new police force in
Kosovo, is an argument at the United Nations over whether retired
police officers from member countries can serve as active officers
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Extraordinary security enveloped Albright as she was driven
several hundred yards to the plaza in a bulletproof van, flanked by
heavily armed American security officials on foot.
</P>
<P>
   While Albright, on her first visit to Kosovo as secretary of
state, was holding meetings with political leaders, a shot was
fired in the street outside. Though the circumstances were unclear,
the special SWAT team flown in to protect Albright considered
canceling her public appearance. But Albright, in an ebullient
mood, was determined to press ahead.
</P>
<P>
   She addressed the crowd members as ``friend'' and asked them to
join in a pledge that ``never again will people with guns come in
the night, never again will houses and villages be burned.''
Basking in the applause and chants of approval, the secretary
finished her address with her arms aloft and the thumbs up sign.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Her speech was broadcast live over Radio 21, a private radio
station financed by the U.S. Agency for International Development
and the British government, and thus reached nearly half the
population in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Behind closed doors, her talk was more specific, her aides said.
Albright met with Hashim Thaci, the leader of the Kosovo Liberation
Army and the prime minister of a ``provisional government'' that
NATO and U. N. officials believe has become overbearing.
</P>
<P>
   Under the provisions of the peace settlement, the United Nations
is supposed to govern the civilian side of life in Kosovo. But
because of the slow start by the United Nations, Thaci's men, who
have appointed themselves to ministries, have filled the void.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was clear that the United Nations is in charge,'' one of
her aides said. ``She said there was a need to cooperate with the
United Nations, implicitly urging them not to establish a parallel
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright also met with leaders of other political parties, but
not with Ibrahim Rugova, the pacifist leader who visited Kosovo for
less than a day after the war and then returned to Rome.
</P>
<P>
   At Gracanica, a monastery six miles south of the capital,
Albright met with Bishop Artemije, a leading anti-Milosevic
official of the Serbian Orthodox Church, who expressed his concern
about the safety of the Serbs still in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
