<HEADER>
A9031 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ONCE-SFCHRON &LR;      07-29 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ONCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC'S `ONCE' DARES TO PUT FOCUS ON 40S 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Sincerity in the vicinity of Los Angeles is
even harder to find than career waitresses.
</P>
<P>
   So when you stumble across it, and it's combined with genuine
passion, it's like an ecstatic jolt. It warms the cockles and
gladdens the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Of all places, it came spilling out of an ABC press session the
other day for a new fall drama series called ``Once and Again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and Again'' is poised to be a rarity itself: an unfolding
story about two characters, 40 years old or so and single parents,
who meet and fall in love.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, stars Sela Ward and Billy Campbell aren't 40 in the
usual flab-and-bag sort of way. But they do stand out in a sea of
teens and 20ish folks on TV this coming season. To be 40 on TV is
to be a codger, a relic, an irrelevant piece of scrap meat. To be
40 and female _ well, ask Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a real problem with this issue because turning 40, I
feel like my life is just beginning,'' said Ward, who is 43. ``I
don't think I've ever been happier. I feel right. I feel yummy. I
feel incredibly intelligent. (I have) a lot of life experience to
offer.''
</P>
<P>
   And yummy she is. I think I can call that a consensus vote. But
after Ward finished a six-year run on NBC's ``Sisters,'' she said,
she tried out for a feature film role, only to hear that the
director said afterward, ``What we really want is Sela 10 years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward said, ``I went, `Ah! Does this mean I'm no longer sexually
viable? Does this mean life is over? My career is over?' ... It is
a wasteland for roles for particular women. You know if you look at
actresses playing opposite the Michael Douglases and even Harrison
Ford, you know, excuse me? They can't play opposite someone close
to their own age, or even 15 years younger?
</P>
<P>
   ``Which is one reason why I fell so in love with this script. I
think perhaps unwittingly they've written something that celebrates
age, that at 40 there is life. At 40, there are new experiences. At
40, you can have the same feelings and emotions and state of
expectancy that you had about life when you were 19 and 18.''
</P>
<P>
   By ``they,'' Ward means the show's creators and producers,
Marshall Herskovitz and Edward Zwick. And this veteran team
provided the session's next bolt of fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   Herskovitz and Zwick have good things going on for them on the
big screen. Separately, they've directed several feature films,
including Zwick's ``Glory,'' ``After the Fall'' and ``Courage Under
Fire.'' Zwick won an Oscar for producing ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   But television hasn't been altogether kind to Herskovitz and
Zwick. They had a moderate success with ``thirtysomething.'' After
that, they scored critically with ``My So-Called Life'' and
``Relativity.'' Both shows died young and bitterly.
</P>
<P>
   So why persist? Why come back to TV after those disappointments,
when people of their creative stature are in demand for feature
films?
</P>
<P>
   Herskovitz nodded softly and took a breath. ``We have had an
amazing ride in television,'' he said. ``We've had unbelievable
creative freedom. We've had the experience, which by the way we
were completely unprepared for, of what it means to have a show on
the air every week, being seen by millions of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, both of us got into filmmaking for very idealistic
reasons. Many of them were illusions, frankly. We had some belief,
which so many of us had in the early '70s, that film could change
the world, that film was a higher calling in some way.
</P>
<P>
   But the film business has been frustrating as well as
stimulating, Herskovitz said. The lesson, he said, is that you
spend two years fashioning an entertainment for moviegoers who
watch it for two hours, then go home and forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are wonderful films, memorable films, but most films are
not remembered,'' he said. You create a television show, and it
stays in the culture, week after week, year after year, if you're
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially if you're lucky enough to be doing a television
show that really gives you a pulpit to preach from, to talk about
the things you're interested in, and the things you want to say to
the world. To be able to do that, week after week, is just
remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Just for a minute, it didn't matter that ``Once and Again'' will
occupy the ``NYPD Blue'' time slot for several weeks, then be
pulled from the air for several more weeks, then return in a time
slot yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't even matter that the odds against ``Once and Again,''
as with any show written for adult sensibilities, are almost
criminally long.
</P>
<P>
   For a fleeting moment, it only mattered that one show actually
means something.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
