<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     07-29 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DECIDING ON A PASSER AND A LINE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the New York Giants and the New York Jets open
their training camps, the heat is on. Not just this summer's
scorching heat, but the quarterback heat that is always on. The
Giants must decide on their quarterback, the Jets must decide on
their quarterback's bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets know Vinny Testaverde is their quarterback, but they
also know that if they are to represent the AFC in Super Bowl
XXXIV, they must plug the leaks in the dike protecting him from the
ever rising tide of opposing pass rushers.
</P>
<P>
   Two leaks already exist, and a third could develop after their
Sept. 12 opener against the New England Patriots at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Quite simply, coach Bill Parcells does not possess one
established offensive guard, much less the required two. The depth
chart lists Alex Bernstein at right guard and Doug Karczewski at
left guard, but neither played a down for the Jets last season.
</P>
<P>
   Behind those two strangers are two rookies, the Jets' top draft
choices _ Randy Thomas from Mississippi State and David Loverne
from San Jose State.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an effort to get off to a better start, I'm going to
scrimmage my rookies a bit,'' Parcells has said, alluding to last
season's 0-2 sputter and to his search for two guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't done it in quite a few years, but I have to see
which guys I'm going to have to use. I'm going to have to make some
personnel moves in this camp and get some guys in there that are
going to keep the wheels of progress moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that progress in last season's 12-4 record developed
because the five linemen that kept Testaverde healthy _ left tackle
Jumbo Elliott, left guard Todd Burger, center Kevin Mawae, right
guard Matt O'Dwyer and right tackle Jason Fabini _ played every
offensive down except for two that Fabini missed. But in the
off-season, Parcells was willing to release Burger, and O'Dwyer
joined the Bengals as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of the offensive line, the 305-pound Elliott,
could spring a leak because of his July 9 brawl in a Long Beach,
N.Y., bar. If he is found guilty of a misdemeanor assault charge in
his Sept. 13 court date, orif he pleads no contest (on top of his
guilty plea last September to driving while impaired), there is at
least a chance he could be suspended by Commissioner Paul
Tagliabue. Whatever develops, he is likely to be distracted.
</P>
<P>
   And the efficiency, or inefficiency, of the Jets' offensive line
not only will determine the performance and health of Testaverde,
but also that of running back Curtis Martin. As this retooled line
goes, so will the Jets in their challenge to succeed the Denver
Broncos, now without John Elway, as AFC champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, meanwhile, are not concerned with their offensive
line but they wish they knew who their quarterback will be _ Kent
Graham, the returning incumbent, or the question mark Kerry
Collins, the Carolina and New Orleans discard. Giants historians
assume that Ernie Accorsi, the general manager, did not give
Collins a four-year, $16.9 million contract to be a backup, but
coach Jim Fassel disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kerry's money is a nonfactor,'' Fassel said the other day in
his Giants Stadium office. ``Going to camp, Kent is the starter.
I've told him, `If you perform, I'm happy.'''
</P>
<P>
   In explaining Collins' presence, Fassel mentioned how ``every
NFL team is trying to get more than one'' quarterback, if only as
insurance against the starter being injured. The coach also talked
about Collins' past; he quit Carolina early last season after his
racial slur, allegedly in jest, disillusioned black teammates.
Returning to Charlotte, N.C., with the Saints, he was arrested for
drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kerry needed to redirect his life,'' Fassel said. ``His work
ethic, his study habits, his football fundamentals. He's worked
very hard. He's lifted, he's run, he's thrown. But the main focus
is, will he dedicate himself to being a quarterback? So far, he
has.''
</P>
<P>
   Needing to improve on an 8-8 record, the Giants have other
questions. Will cornerback Jason Sehorn, returning from knee
surgery, be as skilled as before? Will Amani Toomer emerge as a
big-play receiver? Will Gary Brown's temporary absence create a
problem at running back? Will center Brian Williams anchor the
offensive line after missing two seasons with damaged vision? But
their big question involves the quarterback. It always does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
