<HEADLINE>
SHE MIGHT HAVE A PRAYER FOR MAYOR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keep your eye on the sky over Rome next week.
</P>
<P>
   I don't remember the exact code, but I think it's this: A puff
of white smoke will indicate that Angela Alioto has decided to run
for mayor. Of San Francisco, not Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto is vacationing in Roma, but on her way out of San
Francisco Wednesday she stopped at City Hall and took out papers to
run for mayor. Or so say sources who have never been wrong.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Alioto is officially running, but she's close.
And she was probably pushed a step closer when police Capt. Richard
Cairns took out papers to join the mayoral race.
</P>
<P>
   ``If two or three more men with a real constituency get in this
thing, Angela will  &UR; have  &LR; to run,'' said somebody who knows stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Another political insider theorizes knowingly that Cairns isn't
running in order to take votes away from Frank Jordan, as some
speculate. The insider says Cairns' job will be to pound away at
Tom Ammiano, which Willie Brown can't do for fear of alienating the
gay community. Da Supe will be busy putting out fires set by Cairns
and won't have time to go  &UR; mano a mayoro  &LR; with Brown.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, a gray puff of smoke over Rome will indicate Angela
has taken up cigars.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN F. KENNEDY JR. passed this way not long ago, gave a
memorable speech and never got his thank-you gift.
</P>
<P>
   On May 26, John Jr. spoke to 700 members of the local
advertising world at the Fairmont Hotel. Kennedy was promoting his
political/ &QL; 
celeb magazine George.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just blew everyone in the room away,'' says Mary Arnold,
executive director of the San Francisco Advertising Club. ``He was
extraordinarily bright and marvelously humorous.''
</P>
<P>
   It took four years of wrangling for Arnold to land JFK Jr. as a
speaker, and he requested a low-profile visit. No news media were
informed or invited.
</P>
<P>
   From the speech: ``The big question is whether Hillary will run
for the Senate and if it is unacceptable for someone born in
Illinois who grew up in Arkansas to run in New York. Sort of as
acceptable as someone who was born in Washington, D.C., coming to
San Francisco to get you to buy an ad in a New York magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   John Jr. gave a tiny hint that George wasn't the end point of
his political vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is wrong that needs to be right,'' he said, ``and a
magazine is a start.''
</P>
<P>
   In appreciation, the Ad Club commissioned a hand-struck pewter
likeness of Coit Tower. Arnold got the piece from the artist and
was ready to ship it to Kennedy when she heard the sad news.
</P>
<P>
   WHY CAN'T Democrats raise funds like Repubs do? Gar Smith might
have the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Gar got a ballot from the Democratic National Committee, to vote
for the top Dems of the century. On the ballot is a plea: ``YES, I
am also including a generous contribution to the DNC.``
</P>
<P>
   There are four boxes where you check off the amount of your
generous contribution. The boxes are for the following amounts: $0,
$0, $0 and Other.
</P>
<P>
   And yet those Democrats are so generous with everyone  &UR; else's &LR; 
money.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a generous liberal is like a compassionate conservative.
</P>
<P>
   THE PHOTO-OP KING strikes again. San Francisco Mayor Willie
Brown welcomed tennis sensation Venus Williams to town Tuesday, and
famed S.F. photog Scotty Morris suggested that Willie and Venus
stroll onto the lawn outside City Hall for a tennis lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Williams slammed a booming serve, then you know Willie, he
picked up a racquet and fired off a rocket, which smacked Morris in
the leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm suing,'' the photog yelped.
</P>
<P>
   Da Mayor glanced around at the 40 or so dignitaries on hand and
told Morris, ``You got no witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   NOBODY WALKS in Los Angeles, which might explain why 14 UCLA
football players were busted for using handicapped parking placards
they got with phony doctor's notes.
</P>
<P>
   It's the UCLA version of a full-ride scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   And, man, in L.A. you'd think the kids would be hip to the
concept of karma.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the players didn't discuss the scheme with Drew Bennett,
from Miramonte High in Orinda, who's fighting for the Bruins'
starting quarterback job.
</P>
<P>
   Just a guess, but Drew probably would have told them those
parking spots should go to athletes like his brother Richie, a
student at Cal who had cerebral palsy and is a hell of a wheelchair
basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   MARCEL MARCEAU doesn't normally work with sound effects, but he
doesn't have much choice in his current gig at Theatre on the
Square.
</P>
<P>
   A fan at Tuesday's show says the rapt silence was frequently
broken by the beeps and squeaks of wristwatches and cell phones.
Offenders received severe glarings from their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   FYI: The proper etiquette at a mime performance, if you're a big
shot who must be cell-available, is to shut off your phone and
pantomime taking calls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
