<HEADLINE>
UC MEDICAL TRAINING AND CARE ON CRITICAL LIST, OFFICIALS SAY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ The ability of the University of California's
medical centers to teach new generations of specialists and treat
the ``sickest of the sick'' is in critical condition, UC officials
warned Wednesday.
<P>
   The officials told reporters at a breakfast meeting that the
1997 cutbacks in Medicare, the huge health care program for the
elderly, are squeezing the centers to the point of damaging care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system is in desperate trouble,'' said William Gurtner,
vice president of clinical services development at the university.
Teaching hospitals rely on Medicare money to train doctors, and the
UC system has seen its reimbursement cut by $225 million, or about
10 percent of its budget, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   California Sen. Dianne Feinstein, a Democrat, also urged
Governor Gray Davis in a letter Wednesday to increase state funding
for Medi-Cal, the state-federal program that treats poor patients
and is also pressed for funds.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein warned that California's health care system ``is on
the verge of collapse,'' requiring ``major steps to prevent massive
deterioration.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein added a handwritten note at the end of the letter
emphasizing that Medi-Cal's reimbursement rates to providers are
the fourth-lowest in the nation, paying hospitals and physicians
between 4 percent and 39 percent of what private insurers pay for
identical procedures. Feinstein said UC San Francisco-Stanford
Health Care, the fifth-largest MediCal provider in the state, is
losing $80 million a year on MediCal patients.
</P>
<P>
   Health care providers contend that the current round of problems
in Medicare began in 1997 with the balanced-budget pact between
congress and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Locked in a major budget standoff and unable to agree on more
fundamental reforms of Medicare _ which was growing faster than
just about anything else in the federal budget and projected to go
bankrupt in five years _ the GOP-controlled Congress and the
Clinton administration simply agreed to cut reimbursement rates to
doctors and hospitals as a way to save money.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting Balanced Budget Act took most of its budget
savings out of Medicare, and UC officials said those cutbacks are
starting to squeeze hard now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the consequences of the Balanced Budget Act are
well understood,'' said Mark Laret, director of the UC Irvine
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   University officials said the UC medical system is hit
especially hard because the teaching hospitals tend to get the
sickest patients, requiring the most complex procedures, from organ
transplants to specialized chemotherapy. And by law, the centers
cannot turn away patients, even if they are uninsured or indigent.
</P>
<P>
   UC medical centers are hardly alone in their complaints. For the
past year, providers throughout the U.S. health care system have
been assailing the 1997 Medicare spending cuts, saying they are
turning out to be about twice as high as the government projected
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   UC officials said President Clinton's proposal to add a
prescription drug benefit to Medicare could further jeopardize an
already squeezed system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where does the money come from?'' asked Tom Cesario, dean of
the College of Medicine at UC Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're giving with the left hand, you're taking from the
right hand.''
</P>
<P>
   James Terwilliger, vice provost at UCLA's medical center said
the drug benefit makes providers ``very nervous'' because estimates
show that most of the added expense will be made up by further
cutbacks on payments to providers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
