<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LI-RAILROAD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIL RAGE GROWS AMONG RIDERS OF LONG ISLAND RAIL ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On July 6, as temperatures across New York topped 100
degrees, hundreds of commuters on their way home to Long Island's
North Shore boarded the 5:47 p.m. train at Hunters Point Avenue in
Queens, as usual. And, as usual, within minutes many of them were
cursing the Long Island Rail Road.
</P>
<P>
   Every trip has its aggravations, riders say _ an unexplained
delay, a filthy car, a bottomless seat, a surly ticket-taker. But
for even the toughest-skinned commuters, this was a new low. The
air conditioning in all 10 passenger coaches had broken down.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Kalbacher sat in a pool of her own sweat as far as the
St. James station, an hour-and-a-half trip. She fumed in silence as
other riders voiced bitter fantasies of boycotts, civil
disobedience, even violence against the train's conductors and the
railroad's managers. ``It just made people into monsters,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The 144,000 people who ride the Long Island Rail Road every day
are brimming over with rage. And they have good reason:
</P>
<P>
   _ The railroad's car fleet is literally falling apart. Four out
of five electric coaches are nearly 30 years old, and most coaches
on diesel trains date back to the 1950s. Worse, the 744 oldest
electric coaches never received their scheduled midlife overhauls
in the 1980s, so most are now considered beyond rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   _ A purchase of 134 new diesel coaches, begun several years
late, is another year and a half behind schedule, and the 48
coaches that have entered service so far are riddled with
mechanical, air-conditioning and computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ The railroad admits it cannot keep up with the breakdowns. By
this time last year, the mean distance between failures _ how far
the average car travels before breaking down _ was 32,601 miles.
This year, the distance between failures fell to 28,578 miles. By
contrast, at the Metro-North Commuter Railroad, a sister division
of the Metropolitan Transportation Authority that uses trains
nearly identical to the Long Island Rail Road's, the mean distance
between failures was 70,533 miles.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the LIRR's unforgiving network of branches and chokepoints
_ the best known is Penn Station in Manhattan, where morning-rush
trains arrive every three minutes _ minor failures are easily
amplified into near-catastrophes. A problem with a coupler on a
single train last month on Long Island, for example, caused 46
morning trains to arrive late.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no easy fix,'' said Thomas Prendergast, the
railroad's president, who concedes that he cannot expect riders to
be patient much longer. Yet he says he wishes riders would be more
``understanding of what we're dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, riders were more accepting of the railroad's
shortcomings. The LIRR, the nation's busiest commuter railroad, was
part of what could have been called the unholy trinity of life on
Long Island, along with traffic on the Long Island Expressway and
electric rates under the former Long Island Lighting Co. But the
Expressway now has express lanes. And LILCO's replacement has
actually cut electric rates.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad's commuters, meanwhile, appear to have lost any
interest in why things go wrong sometime around June 1998, when 13
percent of the trains arrived late, shortages of parts made it
impossible to repair many air-conditioning breakdowns, and the
scarcity of spare coaches meant many trains ran hot for days on
end. If anything, riders now seem more apt to believe that, no
matter the problem, the railroad's managers are to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Tempers flare most angrily on the Internet. A number of
commuters have launched Web sites since last fall to provide
outlets for fellow riders' frustrations. At www.ihatethelirr.com,
tales of woe and screeds against railroad managers pop up in
twice-a-day spurts after every rush hour; one rider recently mused
about gathering the garbage from a single train and dumping it on
Prendergast's lawn. Another site, billed as an ``unofficial guide''
to the railroad, has recorded 81,000 hits since September.
</P>
<P>
   The deep displeasure also surfaces in the railroad's customer
satisfaction surveys, distributed annually to the 600 managers who
make up 10 percent of the railroad's work force. Passenger
satisfaction ratings fell in 20 of 21 categories last year, with
the overall rating dropping from a 6.3 out of 10 in 1997 to a 5.4
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in decades, complacency seems to be giving
over to a kind of nascent rail rage. Confrontations between
passengers and crew members have become common, with passengers
refusing to show their monthly tickets as required, and crew
members threatening to eject disgruntled passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it gets hot, the tensions get hotter,'' said George Closs,
who rides from Merrick to Manhattan every morning. ``A lot of
times, the conductors don't even come through. They lock themselves
in their booths, out of fear they'll be lynched or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Prendergast says that comparisons with Metro-North, which is
roughly comparable in size and ridership but is widely considered
the best commuter railroad in New York, if not the nation, overlook
the LIRR's inherent handicaps. Those handicaps, he said, range from
a decades-old history of acrimonious labor relations to Long
Island's greater vulnerability to oceanborne thunderstorms and
other disruptive weather conditions. Above all, he said, is the
LIRR's extraordinary complexity.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all Metro-North trains on its three main lines run into
and out of Grand Central Terminal on four tracks, but the terminal
itself, which is also owned by the MTA, has 78 platforms and
sidings, enough for trains to sit empty for hours.
</P>
<P>
   The LIRR, by contrast, could have been designed by a sadistic
Rube Goldberg. Trains from nine eastern branches converge at
Jamaica, Queens, where they connect with other trains heading to
Brooklyn or Manhattan or elsewhere in Queens. Trains into and out
of Manhattan are limited to four tunnels, two of which are shared
with Amtrak. And in Penn Station, which is owned by Amtrak, the
LIRR is confined to only nine tracks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The LIRR's continual air-conditioning problems shed light on the
best and worst aspects of the railroad's culture and its
management. After years of passenger complaints and a 2 1/2-year
investigation, the MTA's inspector general issued a withering
report in December that revealed the railroad was letting an
average of four days go by before it even detected hot cars, and
another seven before they were fixed. One in four hot cars took as
long as 20 days to notice and repair.
</P>
<P>
   Train crews were reporting only one in five hot cars, the
inspector general said. The railroad routinely failed to track
repair progress; despite two reports of a breakdown, for example,
one car ran hot for 23 days in August. Air-conditioning repairmen,
stretched extremely thin, frequently performed the same repairs on
the same cars a few days apart because no record of the earlier
work had been made.
</P>
<P>
   Prendergast, 47, responded to the report by embracing some of
its recommendations. He said that a new computer system will
eventually enable the railroad to keep better track of its repair
work, but that system is at least a year away. So, he conceded, he
still has no way of knowing if hot cars are being detected and
repaired any quicker.
</P>
<P>
   The cars stink, passengers say. Closs, of Merrick, was nearly
overcome recently by the stench from a bathroom that had not been
cleaned in days. ``It smelled like a cesspool,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trains are filthy, passengers say. Edward Devane, of East
Islip, was dozing on the Montauk line the other day when he
awakened to find a roach running down his neck. ``I can't even sit
on this train anymore,'' he said. ``You get on in the morning,
there'll still be beer cans, papers, coffee cups from the night
before. Bugs don't need much to get started.''
</P>
<P>
   But nothing gets a carful of commuters muttering like
psychopaths faster than the fliers dropped on thousands of seats
every month in which the LIRR touts its latest on-time performance
statistics. For June, the railroad reported an overall on-time rate
of 91.6 percent, up from 87.5 percent in June 1998, the railroad's
worst single month in years.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Haynes, a 16-year commuter, snorted at the LIRR's claim
that 88.1 percent of the Montauk line's trains ran on time in June.
``The last three weeks, I haven't had one day without a delay,'' he
said early this month. ``Yesterday there was another major tie-up,
with 85-minute delays in the morning. And then on my way home, the
train was 16 minutes late.''
</P>
<P>
   Many riders simply do not believe the numbers. The leader of one
of the railroad's unions, speaking on condition of anonymity, said,
``I wouldn't, either.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 audit of on-time statistics by the inspector general
found no evidence of fraud, though it did find that the railroad
overstated its performance by about 7 percentage points.
Prendergast, clearly exasperated that riders still question the
veracity of the railroad's figures, said that any deliberate
misreporting is impossible because much of the data-gathering is
done automatically by computers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Prendergast's admirers suggest that he might be more
sensitive to such complaints if he were still a passenger himself.
After two and a half years riding the train to the railroad's
offices in Jamaica from Garden City, Long Island, an uncommonly
short commute, he moved to Staten Island for personal reasons in
1996. He now gets to work by car, and is seldom seen on the train
east of Jamaica, train workers say.
</P>
<P>
   But Prendergast seems deeply hurt by the emergence of the
anti-LIRR Web sites in recent months. ``No other railroad has
them,'' he said, a sheaf of printouts of the more rabid postings in
front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be extremely frustrating,'' he said. ``I don't turn a
deaf ear to those people at the extreme. But I don't know how much
to deal with it. I don't think this is a representative sample of
what our customers think.''
</P>
<P>
   Prendergast's idea of responsiveness does not seem to be
satisfying many riders.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most recent entries on the www.ihatethelirr.com site
came from Petra Devlin, who said she was amazed that Prendergast
spent a full 45 minutes on the phone with her, answering every one
of her questions. But she said in an interview later that she hung
up feeling miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really disgusted,'' Ms. Devlin said. ``He was very nice
on the phone. But he had an excuse for everything. He said the
money for the new trains is in the pipeline, but until they get
here he can't do a thing about lateness. There's nothing he can do
about anything. There's absolutely no hope whatsoever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
