r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN     07-29 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CRUEL INTENTIONS' TAKES PLOT FROM `LIAISONS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses'' was published in
1782, its author, Choderlos deLaclos, said that the novel was
intended to shock.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 years later, it continues to jolt the public on
stage and screen, including the 1959 film directed by Roger Vadim
(``God Created Woman,'' ``Barbarella'') and starring Jeanne Moreau.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, there was Stephen Frears' ``Dangerous Liaisons''
(1988), starring Michele Pfeiffer, Glenn Close and John Malkovich,
and then, a year later, Milos Forman's ``Valmont,'' with Colin
Firth and Annette Bening. This fall, Fox will even have an updated,
younger version of it on television, called ``Manchester Prep,'' in
which the action will take place in a ritzy East Coast high school.
Of course, you say, haven't we had that already? It was the film
``Cruel Intentions'' (Sony), which hits video stores Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   So what's with all these ``Dangerous'' visions? In the original
story, Valmont and Marquise de Merteuil, a couple of debauched
aristocratic Parisians and former lovers, spend their days in
pursuit of sexual prey or vengeance. Intent on revenge over a
slight, Merteuil proposes to Valmont that he deflower her enemy's
innocent bride-to-be, Cecile, before the wedding. In exchange,
Merteuil says she will return her sexual favors to Valmont. He
seduces Cecile with ease, unleashing the young woman's sexual
voraciousness. In the meantime, though, Valmont has taken upon
himself a more difficult challenge _ the seduction of Madame de
Tourvel, a woman known for her piety and faithfulness. Valmont's
subtle ploys eventually break her down emotionally, and she
submits, but in doing so he inadvertently discovers his own heart.
There is, however, no happy ending in ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Cruel Intentions,'' director Roger Kumble essentially keeps
the premise intact, adding some modern touches, such as a cross
that unscrews to reveal a tiny spoon and a vial of cocaine. Valmont
and Merteuil become Sebastian (Ryan Phillippe) and Kathryn (Sarah
Michelle Gellar), a rather venomous and amoral stepbrother and
-sister (another twist) who live on New York's Upper East Side and
attend private school.
</P>
<P>
   When Kathryn is entrusted to take care of her cousin, Cecile
(played for laughs by Selma Blair), she takes special delight in
turning the young girl into a sex maniac, even giving Cecile
kissing lessons before Sebastian seduces her. (And unlike the
mannered older version, Kathryn's offer of sexual favors to her
stepbrother is fairly graphic.) But the real object of Sebastian's
obsession is Annette (Reese Witherspoon as the Madame de Tourvel
character), a self-proclaimed virgin willing to wait for Mr. Right.
It is too great a challenge for the narcissistic Sebastian to pass
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruel Intentions''' crassness seems particularly calculated.
But it is mostly entertaining. Gellar, best-known as the title
character of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' is wonderfully venal.
And while ``Cruel Intentions'' reworks the source material in an
MTV ``Real World'' sort of way, it also retains its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   As reprehensible as Valmont (Sebastian) and Merteuil (Kathryn)
are, we enjoy a sort of complicity in their acts. They, in their
own way, represent a type of honesty. They understand their
degenerate natures amid a world of wealthy pretension. So when they
take someone down with them _ even an innocent like Cecile _ we
take secret delight in the scoundrels' success, because it is a
blow against the hypocrites. On the other hand, when they get their
comeuppance, we can also feel good, because their behavior
shouldn't be rewarded. In this way, ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses''
wields a double-edged sword.
</P>
<P>
   In its best version _ Frears' ``Dangerous Liaisons'' _ the story
goes beyond being a mere morality play and becomes a meditation on
sexual power. ``Cruel Intentions'' doesn't rise to that level _ the
characters too world weary and not human enough, the ending too
pat. Nevertheless, it still retains enough jolts to make it a nasty
little pleasure. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
