<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9048 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-BESTSOFAR01-CO     07-29 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BESTSOFAR01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At the year's halfway point, suggestions for Oscar voters
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, AUG. 1
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the occasional exception (``The Silence of the Lambs,''
``Fargo''), Oscar voters tend to focus on movies that arrive at the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But here are a few films and early performances from this year
that deserve to be noticed:
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Election'' (R): The leader of the pack is Alexander Payne's
painfully funny high school satire.
</P>
<P>
   It's the follow-up film to the director's biting, underseen
``Citizen Ruth,'' which found laughs in the struggle between
anti-abortion and abortion rights activists. Here the grudge match
is between a well-liked teacher (Matthew Broderick) and a
control-freak student (Reese Witherspoon, in a remarkable
performance), whose bid for student body president he sets out to
derail.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Winslow Boy'' (G): This film never steps foot inside a
school. The young student of the title is rarely onscreen. But he's
the catalyst for director David Mamet's crisp remake of the Terence
Rattigan play, an Edwardian British melodrama centering on a
family's determination, at all costs, to clear its good name.
</P>
<P>
   Nigel Hawthorne plays the Winslow patriarch and Jeremy Northam
the barrister who defends the 13-year-old boy on a petty theft
charge. With its British accents and elegant costumes, ``Winslow''
is actually the sort of movie Oscar voters like.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``October Sky'' (PG): Oscar might like this one, too. It's
the old-fashioned but beautifully realized fact-based tale of West
Virginia boys who struggle to build a model rocket. Why? If they
win the science fair, it could mean a ticket out of their dead-end
coal-mining town.
</P>
<P>
   It's a movie rich in texture and place (remember ``Coal Miner's
Daughter''?) with solid performances by Jake Gyllenhaal as the
young hero, Homer, and a smoldering Chris Cooper as his short-fused
dad.
</P>
<P>
   This is one for the whole family and has just been released on
video.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut'' (R): The epithet-laden
antithesis to ``Sky's'' 1950s aw-shucks tone, ``South Park'' is as
cleverly funny as it is gleefully obscene (very much so, in both
cases).
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the comedy about crude-talking schoolkids
distills the country's current moral climate, as parents and the
media debate the merits of V-chips, censorship and the Motion
Picture Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's many sardonic song-and-dance numbers represent the
final shovel of soil dumped on the corpse of Hollywood's
bright-eyed musical past.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Iron Giant'' (PG): The other animated feature (opening
in metro Atlanta on Friday) lies somewhere between the gee-whiz
innocence of ``October Sky'' and the sly humor of ``South Park.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iron Giant'' isn't trash-mouthed. But its story, about a
young boy who befriends an enormous robot from space, is full of
sharp jokes about its paranoid, Cold War '50s setting (you may
never hear the term ``duck and cover'' again without laughing).
</P>
<P>
   This Warner Bros. movie is beautifully stylized and proves an
animated feature can thrill you without a single Disney-style song.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Matrix'' (R): Another kind of sci-fi film, ``The
Matrix'' hit screens with little warning, and low expectations.
After ``Johnny Mnemonic,'' another trip into cyberpunk with Keanu
Reeves, it sounded like a very bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to the Wachowski brothers (``Bound''), ``Matrix''
turned out to be one of those rare high-concept action thrillers
that Hollywood gets right.
</P>
<P>
   It's like ``The Terminator,'' ``The Crow,'' ``Dune,'' ``Total
Recall'' and ``Dark City'' all rolled into one and fused into an
adventure that pleases comic-book fanatics and mainstream
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The special effects are fresh and bracing _ whether it's someone
running up a wall to avoid bullets, or stopping in midair to
deliver a karate kick.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Cookie's Fortune'' (PG-13): On the other end of the scale,
Robert Altman delivered ``Cookie's Fortune,'' a genial character
study of small-town Mississippi in the aftermath of a beloved
matriarch's death.
</P>
<P>
   It's typically Altman _ an unassuming showcase for an ensemble
cast including Charles S. Dutton, Julianne Moore, Glenn Close and
Patricia Neal.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Dreamlife of Angels'' (R): Since a movie critic's list
wouldn't be complete without at least one eggheady, subtitled film,
add ``The Dreamlife of Angels,'' Erick Zonca's extraordinary,
nuanced drama about two young women (Elodie Bouchez and Natacha
Regnier, sharing last year's actress prize at Cannes) drifting
through friendship in a small French town.
</P>
<P>
   There's not a false, actory moment in the whole movie.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Limbo'' (R): John Sayles' ``Limbo'' is also the sort of
movie most people would make a point to miss. Don't.
</P>
<P>
   It's a low-key character study about lost souls in Alaska,
giving David Strathairn and Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio meaty
roles, and featuring one of the most enigmatic endings of the year.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Blair Witch Project'' (R): This brilliantly conceived,
low-budget horror sensation is more than just a buzz-driven
audience sensation. It's also a reminder to the Hollywood suits
that $80 million might get you cool computer-generated ghosts, like
``The Haunting.'' But nothing beats imagination, ingenuity and a
great story.
</P>
<P>
   PERFORMANCES
</P>
<P>
   -- Juliette Lewis and Giovanni Ribisi. The actors' committed
work as mentally challenged lovers kept ``The Other Sister'' from
dissolving into glitzy mush.
</P>
<P>
   -- Cate Blanchett and Angelina Jolie. They play very different
kinds of wives in the air-traffic-control comedy-drama ``Pushing
Tin.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio. In ``Limbo,'' she plays a
down-on-her-luck saloon singer in Alaska, stuck with a surly
teenage daughter and bad luck in love.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sissy Spacek and Christopher Walken. They're a comic,
Eisenhower-era couple in the otherwise lame ``Blast From the
Past.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Diane Lane, Liev Schreiber and Tovah Feldshuh. All three give
lovely, nuanced work in ``A Walk on the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Reese Witherspoon and Matthew Broderick. The lethal rivals in
``Election.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Rupert Everett and Julianne Moore. For their sultry,
intelligent badinage in ``An Ideal Husband.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Patricia Neal and Charles S. Dutton. As unlikely best pals in
``Cookie's Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Joaquin Phoenix. He's the only spark of life in the trashy
``Eight Millimeter.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Jeremy Northam and Nigel Hawthorne. They personify the
British stiff upper lip in ``The Winslow Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Hugo Weaving. His ripely deadpan performance as the chief
villain gave ``The Matrix'' a welcome hint of self-mockery.
</P>
<P>
   If the academy ever gave out Oscars for ensemble work,
nominations should go to Omar Epps, Richard T. Jones and Taye Diggs
for ``The Wood,'' and the boys of ``October Sky.''
</P>
<P>
   And there ought to be a special award created for all the good
actors swallowed whole by special effects. Liam Neeson, survivor of
both ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' and ``The
Haunting,'' would be a shoo-in for the trophy. Runners-up: Ewan
McGregor (``Phantom Menace''), Lili Taylor (``The Haunting''), Will
Smith (``Wild Wild West'') and Kevin Kline (``Wild Wild West'').
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
