<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-LEADERS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Few Oscar contenders on radar in '99 thus far
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, AUG. 1
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This time last summer, you could predict at least one big Oscar
nominee: ``Saving Private Ryan.'' It hit theaters July 24, setting
a new standard for war films. But the year's other big movies
didn't arrive till fall, Hollywood's traditional season for
unveiling its prestige, trophy-chasing pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Though the mixed critical response to Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes
Wide Shut'' may translate into Oscar recognition for 1999, we
haven't seen a sure thing such as ``Ryan'' yet. The best of the
year's movies so far include a crowd-pleasing sci-fi mind-bender,
two animated features not by Disney and a talky French movie about
two young women who spend a lot of time doing ... not much.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of '99 has brought us a few terrific pics the
Oscar voters probably won't look at twice. Some of them are too
darkly funny, too wild or too on-the-fringe to fit in with the
types of movies the academy prefers _ epic historical dramas and
period comedies with lots of costumes.
</P>
<P>
   Today we offer a subjective view of some of the best of the
bunch (in no particular order), movies that help us forget the
summer's big-budget, super-hyped disappointments of ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' ``Wild Wild West'' and ``The
Haunting.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of the top films _ ``Election,'' ``The Winslow Boy,''
``October Sky,'' ``The Blair Witch Project'' and ``South Park:
Bigger, Longer and Uncut'' _ focus on schoolkids, but in different
ways, their tones veering from very proper to vilely profane. None
is the typical, having-sex-or-killing-aliens teen flicks Hollywood
is churning out overtime lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``ELECTION'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the pack is Alexander Payne's painfully funny high
school satire.
</P>
<P>
   It's the follow-up film to the director's biting, underseen
``Citizen Ruth,'' which found laughs in the struggle between
anti-abortion and abortion rights activists. Here the grudge match
is between a well-liked teacher (Matthew Broderick) and a
control-freak student (Reese Witherspoon, in a remarkable
performance), whose bid for student body president he sets out to
derail.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE WINSLOW BOY'' (G)
</P>
<P>
   This film never steps foot inside a school. The young student of
the title is rarely on screen. But he's the catalyst for director
David Mamet's crisp remake of the Terence Rattigan play, an
Edwardian British melodrama centering on a family's determination,
at all costs, to clear its good name.
</P>
<P>
   Nigel Hawthorne plays the Winslow patriarch, and Jeremy Northam
the aloof barrister who defends the 13-year-old boy on a petty
theft charge. With its British accents and elegant costumes,
``Winslow'' is actually the sort of movie Oscar voters like.
</P>
<P>
   ``OCTOBER SKY'' (PG)
</P>
<P>
   Oscar might like this one, too. It's the old-fashioned but
beautifully realized fact-based tale of West Virginia boys who
struggle to build a model rocket. Why? If they win the science
fair, it could mean a ticket out of their dead-end, coal-mining
town.
</P>
<P>
   It's a movie rich in texture and place (remember ``Coal Miner's
Daughter''?) with solid performances by Jake Gyllenhaal as the
young hero Homer and a smoldering Chris Cooper as his short-fused
dad.
</P>
<P>
   This is one for the whole family and has just been released on
video.
</P>
<P>
   ``SOUTH PARK: BIGGER, LONGER &AMP; UNCUT'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   The epithet-laden antithesis to ``Sky's'' 1950s ah-shucks tone,
``South Park'' is as cleverly funny as it is gleefully obscene
(very much so, in both cases).
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the comedy about crude-talking schoolkids
distills the country's current moral climate, as parents and the
media debate the merits of V-chips, censorship and the MPAA.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's many sardonic song-and-dance numbers represent the
final shovel of soil dumped on the corpse of Hollywood's
bright-eyed musical past.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE IRON GIANT'' (PG)
</P>
<P>
   The other animated feature (opening in metro Atlanta on Friday)
lies somewhere between the gee-wiz innocence of ``October Sky'' and
the sly humor of ``South Park.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iron Giant'' isn't trash-mouthed. But its story, about a
young boy who befriends an enormous robot from space, is full of
sharp jokes about its paranoid, Cold War '50s setting (you may
never hear the term ``duck and cover'' again without laughing).
</P>
<P>
   This Warner Bros. movie is beautifully stylized, and proves an
animated feature can thrill you without a single Disney-style song.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE MATRIX'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   Another kind of sci-fi film, ``The Matrix'' hit screens with
little warning, and low expectations. After ``Johnny Mnemonic,''
another trip into cyberpunk with Keanu Reeves, it sounded like a
very bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to the Wachowski Brothers (``Bound''), ``Matrix''
turned out to be one of those rare high-concept action thrillers
that Hollywood gets right.
</P>
<P>
   It's like ``The Terminator,'' ``The Crow,'' ``Dune,'' ``Total
Recall'' and ``Dark City'' all rolled into one and fused into an
adventure that pleases both comic-book fanatics and mainstream
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The special effects are fresh and bracing _ whether it's someone
running up a wall to avoid bullets, or stopping in midair to
deliver a karate kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``COOKIE'S FORTUNE'' (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the scale, Robert Altman delivered
``Cookie's Fortune,'' a genial character study of small-town
Mississippi in the aftermath of a beloved matriarch's death.
</P>
<P>
   It's typically Altman _ an unassuming showcase for an ensemble
cast including Charles S. Dutton, Julianne Moore, Glenn Close and
Patricia Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE DREAMLIFE OF ANGELS'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   Since a movie critic's list wouldn't be complete without at
least one eggheady, subtitled film, add ``The Dreamlife of
Angels,'' Erick Zonca's extraordinary, nuanced drama about two
young women (Elodie Bouchez and Natacha Regnier, sharing last
year's actress prize at Cannes) drifting through friendship in a
small French town.
</P>
<P>
   There's not a false, actory moment in the whole movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``LIMBO'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   John Sayles' ``Limbo'' is also the sort of movie most people
would make a point tomiss . Don't.
</P>
<P>
   It's a low-key character study about lost souls in Alaska,
giving David Strathairn and Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio meaty
roles, and featuring one of the most enigmatic endings of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE BLAIR WITCH PROJECT'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   This brilliantly conceived, low-budget horror sensation is more
than just a buzz-driven audience sensation. It's also a reminder to
the Hollywood suits that $80 million might get you cool
computer-generated ghosts, like ``The Haunting.'' But nothing beats
imagination, ingenuity and a great story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
