<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9055 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADIO-CONFLICT-HNS &LR;      07-29 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-CONFLICT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATIC BEGINS TO CLEAR IN BERKELEY RADIO CONFLICT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn. Calif.) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bitter, months-long dispute at the nation's oldest public
radio station, KPFA-FM in Berkeley, Calif., was set to end Friday
as management ordered padlocks removed from the station's doors and
its suspended staff placed in charge of broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict brought thousands of protesters to the streets of
Berkeley, home of a University of California campus and site of
much 1960s student revolutionary unrest.
</P>
<P>
   At the protest's height, gunshots were fired into studio of
KPFA, flagship of the listener-supported, left-leaning Pacifica
Foundation. Dozens of tents occupied by protesters clogged a nearby
street.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Pacifica chairwoman Mary Frances Berry said
removing guards and reopening the station, which celebrated its
50th anniversary earlier this year, marked the foundation's ``good
faith effort'' to end the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   She said Pacifica directors will monitor progress of the
self-directed staff _ represented by the Communications Workers of
America union _ in meeting foundation goals of increasing
listenership and diversity. Eventually, she said, directors will
appoint an interim station manager.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, who also is chairwoman of the U.S. Civil Rights
Commission, said Pacifica directors will consider offers to buy the
station. With the strongest FM signal in Northern California, the
station serves a market of about 6 million. Stressing the station
is not actively for sale, she said Pacifica specifically will
consider any offer from the city of Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   In an emergency session earlier this week, Berkeley City Council
passed a package of pro-KPFA resolutions and authorized the city
manager to investigate the possibility of buying the station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is earlier than premature,'' said Berkeley Mayor Shirley
Dean, who Thursday expressed doubt the city ever would acquire the
property. ``We have no information that it's for sale. And no
information on its value. Some tell us $60 million. Some tell us
$80 million ... So, the motion to investigate really doesn't mean a
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Possible sale of Pacifica stations, representation of local
stations on the network's board of directors and concern about
changes in program content were key issues in the protest.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the controversy was an e-mail from Pacifica board member
Michael Palmer, a Houston real estate broker, to Berry suggesting
that some Pacifica stations, notably WBAI in New York City, might
profitably be sold. Palmer declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Pacifica also owns stations in Houston, Los Angeles and
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Looming over the crisis was the perceived threat that the
Berkeley station, whose audience had dropped to 146,000 listeners a
week, most of them middle-aged white males, might follow the lead
of Pacifica's Houston station, KPFT.
</P>
<P>
   KPFT, under the leadership of general manager Garland Ganter,
dropped its local news programs and foreign-language programs in a
successful effort to boost listenership and revenue. As a result of
Ganter's actions, the station's weekly audience increased from
69,000 to 104,000.
</P>
<P>
   For about two weeks in July, Ganter, 35, oversaw day-to-day
operations of the California station.
</P>
<P>
   KPFA supporters dismissed the Houston station as a ``jukebox''
and as ``sanitized.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, the Houston station was picketed by local
listeners displeased with the station's programming. One protester
likened KPFT's largely musical offerings to ``being on marijuana 12
hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganter said he plans to reinstitute local news broadcasting, and
possibly a call-in talk program, this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the details of the KPFA dispute were lost in an opaque
swirl of claims and counterclaims, lawsuits and Web site postings.
What emerged, though, was a sense that the community radio station
commands a fiercely loyal listenership _ one that suspected the the
purity of even its closest friends, Pacifica's self-consciously
progressive administrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have a personal stake in all of this,'' said one
protester, David Jameson, 39. ``We're really floundering without
the news. Most people think National Public Radio is a big step
down. This station is my life blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Others handcuffed themselves to the chains that secured the
station's front doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy,'' said one who identified himself only as
``Shorty,'' ``is we've put our chains on the chains of Pacifica
that have closed our doors. We will unhandcuff ourselves only when
the doors are unlocked, the boards removed from the windows and the
staff returned to work.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his comments, Shorty, who occasionally emphasized
his point by gagging himself with a red, white and blue bandana,
had been handcuffed 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   During the protests, Berry and Pacifica executive director Lynn
Chadwick were vilified as vampires intent on gutting the radio
station, which was the first of the network founded by World War
II-era pacifist Lewis Hill and his associates.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, a New York advertising man, envisioned a noncommercial
radio empire dedicated to free speech and intelligent debate.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between KPFA and its parent foundation became public
in February when Pacifica directors voted to eliminate seats for
directors who also served on individual stations' advisory boards.
That action, they said, was necessary to comply with regulations of
the federal Corporation for Public Broadcasting, which provides
about 15 percent of Pacifica budget.
</P>
<P>
   Critics argued that Pacifica has received federal money since
the early 1970s, apparently without conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In March, popular KPFA general manager Nicole Sawaya was dropped
from management. Although management declined to discuss the
matter, sources suggested directors were displeased with
programming decisions.
</P>
<P>
   In April, a talk show host and volunteer disc jockey were
removed after they violated station policy by discussing the Sawaya
issue on the air.
</P>
<P>
   On July 13, ``Flashpoints'' talk show host Dennis Bernstein was
forcibly removed from the studio as he protested his suspension for
discussing the Sawaya removal on his show. Police in riot gear were
called to the studio to clear it of demonstrators. More than 50
people were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Pacifica officials, deeming the protester-surrounded studio too
dangerous to operate, then padlocked the doors and replaced live
programming with tapes. The first offering was a Marxist-Maoist
analysis of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks like ethnic cleansing to me,'' Bernstein said last
week as he ``broadcast'' his program through a public address
system set up at the closed station. ``Sawaya was Lebanese. Here we
had a Lebanese woman who brought in an African-American assistant.
Pacifica says it wants diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was a woman who was bringing in diversity. She was going
like a steam roller ... This looks like a hostile takeover to me.
Here at Pacifica, I thought we were speaking truth to power. In
reality, they were using power to fight truth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
