<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9061 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVTOUR-NBC30-COX     07-29 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVTOUR-NBC30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Morning TV heats up with `Later Today'
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ How many cooking demonstrations can Atlantans
watch in one morning?
</P>
<P>
   You'll find out at 9 a.m. Sept. 7, when NBC debuts ``Later
Today,'' a women-oriented news and issues program. It comes on
right after NBC's ``Today'' show and right before ``Peachtree
Morning'' on WXIA, Atlanta's NBC affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   ``At what point does it become saturated? That's an open
question,'' allowed Jeff Zucker, who'll oversee both ``Today'' and
``Later Today.'' ``We'll see. This kind of programming will be on
in Atlanta from 7 to 11 (a.m.). Hopefully it'll work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Later Today'' is NBC's attempt to build on the success of
``Today,'' right down to the borrowed title (``It's like `Today'
only later'' is the promotional line you'll soon be hearing). It
comes at a time when early morning TV is about to become more
competitive than perhaps it's ever been, with both ABC and CBS
ramping up their shows to cut into the big lead held by ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Later Today'' is essentially an extension of what ``Today''
does during its last half-hour, when news is ratcheted down and
replaced with a mix of entertainment and issue-related segments,
including health, parenting, fashion and ... those cooking
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no formal news summaries during ``Later Today''
(and there won't be a weather-
</P>
<P>
   person), but big news will be covered when it breaks out.
</P>
<P>
   Three women host it: Jodi Applegate, an NBC weekend anchor and
MSNBC daytime anchor; Asha Blake, who anchored at a Los Angeles
station; and Florence Henderson, ``The Brady Bunch's'' mom, who
also worked on ``Today'' from 1959-60 as the ``Today Girl,''
conducting interviews, hosting segments and singing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only the three of us _ I consider ourselves `The
Few,''' Applegate joked, a reference to the couchful of women on
ABC's ``The View.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're staking out a little new ground, but a lot of things are
what you see on the second hour of `Today,''' Applegate added.
``We're not reinventing the wheel. We're just shifting the focus.
We can be a little bit sassier, looser.''
</P>
<P>
   Applegate will open the show from outside the ``Today'' studio
window, but the rest of the program will take place in an enclosed
studio with a live audience. Zucker said the music acts that
sometimes end ``Today'' often play another 25 minutes off the air,
and ``Later Today'' will sometimes show that. Sometimes guests or
segments that were limited on ``Today'' will appear again on
``Later.''
</P>
<P>
   The show was not conceived as a third hour of ``Today,'' but
rather, Zucker said, as that show's ``cousin.'' Having three women
host was a conscious decision, Zucker added, since women viewers
outnumber men at that hour about 3-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean we won't have men running through,'' he said.
``A male point of view will be heard, but not necessarily on a
daily basis.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW FALL TV SEASON
</P>
<P>
   Exec discusses diversity
</P>
<P>
   It was NBC West Coast chief Scott Sassa's turn to address the
network diversity issue at the TV critics tour in Pasadena on
Thursday. ``This issue is a personal and business concern,'' said
Sassa, who's Asian-American. ``I don't know that I'm qualified to
tell you how African-Americans feel about how they're portrayed on
TV. And I don't think I'm capable of telling you how Latinos feel
about how they're portrayed. But I can tell you how I feel about
seeing Asian-Americans portrayed on TV. And I've got to tell you,
growing up, seeing David Carradine (on ``Kung Fu'') as a Chinese
guy pissed you off.'' As with the other networks, NBC has come
under fire from the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People for lack of diversity in its fall lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The news at NBC
</P>
<P>
   NBC plans to air a ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' movie later
this year. The only holdup is whether the series' co-executive
producer, Tom Fontana, can lock in enough of the most prominent
cast members, including Andre Braugher, for the movie. ``For loyal
`Homicide' fans, it will be some closure they didn't get,'' said
NBC entertainment head Garth Ancier. ... Also in development at
NBC, as a series: ``Not the Bradys,'' from Keenan Ivory Wayans. The
mixed-race takeoff on the old icon will feature a black husband,
white wife and four kids from previous marriages. No word on
whether there'll only be one bathroom. ...
</P>
<P>
   Michael Michele, who turned heads at the ``Homicide'' station
house last season, is yet another new face joining ``ER.'' She'll
play second-year resident Dr. Cleo Finch. Another ``Homicide'' ex,
</P>
<P>
   Richard Belzer, reprises his role as Detective John Munch on
``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Other ``ER'' newcomers just announced: Maura Tierney
(``NewsRadio''), Ming-Na (``The Joy Luck Club'') and Croatian actor
Goran Visnjic. With the addition of recurring regulars Alan Alda
and Rebecca De Mornay, it's one crowded ER this season. ... Lots
going on at ``Suddenly Susan,'' too: The magazine becomes a sports
mag, and joining the cast are Eric Idle (``Monty Python''), Sherri
Shepherd (``Everybody Loves Raymond''), Currie Graham (``Money for
Nothing'') and Rob Estes (``Melrose Place''). ...
</P>
<P>
   Jesse L. Martin (Ally McBeal's doomed love interest) joins ``Law
&AMP; Order'' as Lenny Briscoe's (Jerry Orbach) partner, replacing
Benjamin Bratt. ... Tim Matheson joins NBC's ``The West Wing,'' a
new drama set in the White House from ``ER'' producer John Wells
and Aaron Sorkin (``Sports Night,'' ``A Few Good Men''). Matheson
plays the vice president. Martin Sheen is prez. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Third Watch,'' a drama from Wells, premieres Sept. 23 in
``ER's'' time slot, then settles into its regular home at 8 p.m.
Sept. 26. ``ER'' starts Sept. 30, a week after the rest of the
lineup. ... Conan O'Brien will do his show for a week in Los
Angeles, beginning Nov. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
