<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXES-MARRIAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARRIAGE PENALTY': PROBLEM WITHOUT SOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Of all the tax cuts debated so hotly in Congress
this week, one has been raised above the rest as an outrageous
burden: the so-called ``marriage penalty,'' attacked by Republicans
as an unjust levy on those who tie the knot.
</P>
<P>
   It is a popular conservative foil, crystallizing the claim that
taxes are a drain on family values. Under current tax law, some 20
million married couples pay more than they would if they were
single.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike much of the controversy over taxes, the marriage
penalty debate is not just a partisan battle or a clash of economic
philosophy. It is a genuine mathematical puzzle _ one that has
confounded legislators since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The ``marriage penalty'' stems from the fact that within a group
of married couples with identical incomes, the shares earned by
different wives and husbands can vary dramatically. Among families
with a joint income of $50,000, for instance, one husband-wife team
may contribute $25,000 each, while in another household one spouse
makes $40,000 and the other $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   In our progressive tax system _ in which rich people pay more
proportionally than the poor _ there is no feasible way to have the
members of married couples pay the same amount as they would if
they were single while simultaneously ensuring that all the married
couples in that income class pay equal amounts of taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the intrinsically skewed nature of tax brackets,
someone always pays an unfair share.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never solve it,'' said Dan Feenberg, an analyst for
the National Bureau for Economic Research in Cambridge, Mass.
``There's no technical fix to this. It's always going to be a
matter of balancing values.''
</P>
<P>
   June E. O'Neill, director of the Congressional Budget Office,
told the House Ways and Means committee last year that because of
the competing interests of fairness and family, there is a
``continuing tension within the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, the tax code seeks to levy the same tax with
the same income. On the other hand, it tries to minimize the effect
of marriage on a couple's tax liability,'' she said. ``A tax
structure with progressive rates cannot attain both goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Individuals have paid income tax since 1913, but the debate over
how to handle married couples did not burst onto the national scene
until 1948, after the income tax had been expanded to cover a great
number of taxpayers. Married couples began to issue a complaint
similar to that today: that they were paying more than people who
filed taxes alone.
</P>
<P>
   Congress responded with a law that doubled the number of tax
brackets for married people _ a provision that meant married
couples would not shift into a higher tax bracket simply because
their combined income equalled a greater dollar amount. The new law
favored stay-at-home moms, whose husbands paid less in taxes than
their single counterparts. That fix worked until the 1960s, when
single people suddenly noticed they were paying as much as 40
percent more than their married counterparts _ an inequity that
particularly upset widows and unmarried couples.
</P>
<P>
   To swing the pendulum back the other way, Congress issued new
tax tables in 1969 to lower the so-called ``penalties'' for single
people. In the process, the lawmakers created a penalty for married
individuals. It did not affect many couples _ fewer than 15 percent
in 1971 _ and yet it underscored the tension between trying to tax
married couples and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Economists note that Congress' efforts have also created a
less-famous side-effect: a marriage ``bonus,'' in which some people
who marry suddenly drop into a lower bracket, depending on how much
they earn together and apart. According to a CBO report, some 25
million couples were getting the ``marriage bonus'' in 1996,
averaging $1,300. Only 20 million actually paid a ``marriage
penalty,'' averaging $1,380 per family.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in an election year in which each side is scrambling to
emphasize the importance of family values, the presence of any
marriage penalty at all is a natural target, especially for
tax-cutting Republicans. Senator William V. Roth, chair of the
Senate Finance Committee, gave no hint of the complexity of the
issue when he took to the Senate floor this week and said that
``American families have been suffering under the unfair burden of
the marriage tax penalty for too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the Senate voted down a Democratic measure
that would have increased the standard deduction for married
people, raising it to $11,550 from the $7,200 couples can deduct
now. Two GOP measures have also been proposed. Only one is expected
to come to a vote: Roth's, which would let married couples decide
whether they want to file separately or apart _ and then let them
file on the same tax return regardless of what they chose. That
proposal would save a couple earning $100,000 approximately $1,500,
a committee spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even if the problem is ``solved'' in this legislative
season, it is unlikely to go away. ``Those,'' Feenberg said, ``are
the mathematical rules.''
</P>
</TEXT>
