<SLUG> BC-TEACHING-DOCTORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCREPANCY IN REIMBURSEMENT RATES FUELS DEBATE AMONG TEACHING
HOSPITALS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When an aspiring doctor does his residency at Beth
Israel Medical Hospital in New York City, the institution receives
more than $57,000 annually from Medicare to defray the cost of
training.
</P>
<P>
   But if the same resident were to train at Houston's Memorial
Hermann Hospital, the Medicare program would pay the Texas hospital
$6,924.
</P>
<P>
   The vast discrepancy in reimbursement rates for
doctors-in-training by the federal health insurance program for the
elderly has long been a sore subject among teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   And the wounds were reopened recently when the New England
Journal of Medicine ran a story that highlighted the vast
differences in how teaching hospitals are treated by Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal study, based on 1996 Medicare cost reports, placed
several pre-eminent New York City teaching hospitals at the top of
the pack in terms of residency reimbursement. Texas hospitals,
meanwhile, ranked at the bottom of the list.
</P>
<P>
   In between fell hospitals from Boston, Philadelphia, Atlanta,
Seattle, New Haven, Conn., North Carolina and California.
</P>
<P>
   Since Medicare was created in 1964, it has helped subsidize
resident training under the assumption that the elderly patients
enrolled in the government program should have access to high
quality teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 direct Medicare payments to teaching hospitals for
residency training nationwide amounted to $2.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While hospital officials say that residency training costs can
vary somewhat between geographic regions, they are not as great as
those reflected in the Medicare payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not eight times more expensive in New York than Houston,
Texas,'' said Jeff Brownawell, vice president of managed care and
government reporting at Memorial Hermann Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, say Brownawell and others, is that Medicare is
still relying on an inflexible and outdated 1984 formula.
</P>
<P>
   The formula allowed hospitals to take several factors into
consideration in coming up with residency costs. Those factors
included the number of days Medicare patients spent at the hospital
as well as residents' salaries and the costs for faculty
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   However, when the funding formula was initially devised,
hospitals were given a certain amount of leeway in determining what
they could include in residents' costs.
</P>
<P>
   Many New York City hospitals included the cost of faculty
supervision in their assessments while Texas hospitals such as
Hermann did not, under the assumption that those costs should be
attributed to the medical schools.
</P>
<P>
   Once the formula was in place, hospitals could not change what
went into their residents' costs even after many discovered that
they may have been shortchanged by not including faculty
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you got locked into that rule you couldn't make any
changes,'' Brownawell said.
</P>
<P>
   Brownawell noted that the initial guidelines of what constituted
residency costs were arbitrary. So arbitrary, he noted, that today
there is even a variation among Houston hospitals as to how much
they receive from Medicare for resident training.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Harris County Hospital District receives $2,815
less per resident annually than Hermann, even though they are
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   With the Clinton administration and some in Congress lobbying
for Medicare reform this year, there is some hope that the issue of
how teaching hospitals are reimbursed for training future doctors
will be revisited.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is something needs to be done,'' said Houston
Democratic Rep. Ken Bentsen, whose district encompasses the Texas
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen is co-sponsoring a bill that would ensure more
uniformity in payments. The bill calls for Medicare to come up with
a payment system based on an average training cost for residents.
That Medicare reimbursements, however, would be modified for each
institution based on cost of living and wage factors in different
cities.
</P>
<P>
   A Medicare reform plan proposed earlier this year by Sen. John
Breaux, D-La., and Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., would have removed
Medicare from the business of subsidizing resident training.
Instead, teaching hospitals would be reimbursed as part of the
annual appropriations process.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years there have been various efforts to change the
distribution method.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its failed 1994 comprehensive health plan, the
Clinton administration proposed shifting to national average
payments for teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   But the New York congressional delegation, led by Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., has successfully fended off proposals
that would hurt the state's teaching hospitals. And with first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton expected to run for Moynihan's seat in New
York in 2000, there is little likelihood that the Clinton
administration will push any plan that would jeopardize payments to
teaching hospitals there.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the teaching hospitals have devoted most of
their lobbying efforts to fighting efforts to slash overall
Medicare funding for their institutions rather than pushing for a
reorganizing of payments.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the teaching hospitals are lobbying Congress to
restore some of the cuts resulting from the 1997 balanced budget
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dickler, senior vice president at the American Association
of Medical Colleges, the lobbying group for the teaching hospitals,
agreed that the disparity in Medicare costs did not reflect cost
differentials in training physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The costs of graduate education are not that disparate,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dickler also said he did not agree with suggestions that all
teaching hospitals should receive an average reimbursement rate.
Dickler said that some hospitals devote more faculty to resident
training than others.
</P>
<P>
   And he said that his association was not focused on closing the
gap on Medicare payments to teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not one that has been a top priority,'' he said. ``Our
top priority is to try and moderate the balanced budget
provisions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
