u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-DAEWOO-ART-NYT &LR;      07-29 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-DAEWOO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKEPTICS SEE KOREA'S SUPPORT OF DAEWOO AS BACKSLIDING ON ECONOMIC
REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphics showing the GDP, stock market, interest rates
and a timeline for South Korea are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ The government's decision to take charge of
the overhaul of Daewoo, South Korea's second-largest and
most-troubled business agglomeration, has pushed skepticism about
the country's commitment to economic restructuring to the
forefront.
</P>
<P>
   In ordering Daewoo's creditors to roll over $5.8 billion in
loans and provide a further $3.3 billion, the government prevented
a default on short-term loans, a lot of that owed to a
government-sponsored lending agency.
</P>
<P>
   That move may have avoided wider turmoil, as a default by Daewoo
would have sent painful ripples through the economy. It can be read
as a last-ditch effort to impose restructuring on a business group
that has thus far managed to avoid reform in a country where
free-market forces still struggle to assert their influence.
</P>
<P>
   But the government's actions can also be seen as the biggest
sign of the backsliding, damaging the veneer of economic
rejuvenation in Korea, one of Asia's most thriving economies before
the region's financial crisis began two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The support for Daewoo was an eerie reminder of the old order of
things, when government-directed lending and politics, not market
forces, determined the winners and losers in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   President Kim Dae Jung, the former political prisoner whose
ascent to power last year was spurred by the economic crisis, took
office with promises to overhaul the economy and the business
practices blamed for contributing to South Korea's near-disaster.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of his first year in office in February, South Korea
had become the model of efficacy for the harsh economic austerity
measures required by international lending agencies. The economy is
expected to grow 6.5 percent this year, unemployment has retreated,
the currency has stabilized and the stock market is up sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, however, Kim seems distracted from his reform
agenda by politics, and the forces that have opposed him from the
start _ the five large chaebol, as South Korea's powerful,
family-controlled business conglomerates are known, and the
nation's bureaucracy _ have moved quickly to exploit the situation.
</P>
<P>
   He is busy trying to buttress his party to win parliament
elections next April. A number of his top economic advisers have
fallen victim to charges of corruption. His policy of using private
business, primarily the biggest conglomerate, Hyundai, to promote
ties with North Korea is seen by some here as increasingly naive.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is that the reform led by Kim Dae Jung is at a
crossroads,'' said Hyun Hong Choo, a lawyer and former politician.
``He can go either way: He can continue to pursue the reform he
laid out when he was elected, or he can buckle to political
pressures and either retreat or simply stall, creating further
confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   These are among the increasing signs of backsliding:
</P>
<P>
   _ The sale of two large banks nationalized in the aftermath of
the economic crisis has stalled.
</P>
<P>
   _ The government's promise to sell state-controlled businesses
has been undermined because bidders balk at paying prices they
consider excessive.
</P>
<P>
   _ Efforts to streamline the conglomerates have been thwarted,
with the two strongest, Samsung and Hyundai, openly defying the
government.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many conglomerates have used accounting gimmicks as well as a
rush of investment from enthusiastic foreigners and mutual funds
they control to mask the size of their debts.
</P>
<P>
   While conceding that such signs are ominous, Kim's supporters
say he is keenly aware that doubts are surging. There are also
signs that reforms are taking hold. Both Commerzbank of Germany and
Goldman, Sachs have successfully invested in South Korean banks.
Royal Phillips Electronics of the Netherlands recently announced an
investment equivalent to $1.6 billion, the largest ever by a
foreign company in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is also worried about the slowing of the
momentum,'' said You Jong Keun, governor of North Cholla province
and until recently one of President Kim's top economic advisers.
``That's why the president has kept up the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say there were bound to be some relapses, given the scope
of the president's ambitions and how deeply they are intended to
attack the status quo. ``I can see some grounds for criticism, but
at the same time, the ground has been laid, and the momentum is
inevitable,'' said Oh Ho Gen, executive chairman of the Corporate
Restructuring Committee, the agency charged with overseeing
corporate reform.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the government no longer lets healthy businesses
guarantee debts of weak affiliates. It has also curbed corporate
debt issuance and toughened accounting requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest quandary lies in overall monetary policy.
Rejecting the advice of some of its own economists, the government
has lowered the high interest rates it imposed as part of a $58
billion bailout by the International Monetary Fund. That has helped
fuel the economic recovery, but it has also made it less expensive
for the conglomerates to raise money and thus diminished the
pressure for financial restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Change is obvious at smaller conglomerates. Hanwha group, a
major military contractor, for example, has sold major assets,
formed alliances with foreign investors and reduced its
debt-to-equity ratio to 2-to-1 from 12-to-1. Hanwha, once the
11th-largest conglomerate, is now ``somewhere in the middle,'' said
Lee Yong Ho, the managing director over the group's restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to look at ourselves and if there's something
we need to do, we'll do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
