<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-DAEWOO-ART-2NDT     07-29 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-DAEWOO-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
SEOUL, South Korea: he said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest conglomerates with the best political connections,
like Daewoo, have not found themselves bereft of credit, which was
the critical factor in pushing their smaller counterparts to
change.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials contend that Daewoo and Hanwha are
different because Daewoo's tentacles extend so deep into the South
Korean economy that to allow it to founder would derail the
country's recovery. They note that the intervention they mounted
was attached to several strings, including sweeping asset sales and
a pledge by Daewoo's chairman and founder, Kim Woo Choong, to use
part of his own fortune to reduce the group's $47.5 billion debt.
</P>
<P>
   But oddly, the government has said that Daewoo should keep its
most prized business, auto manufacturing, although that would be
the easiest to sell. The reasons behind this apparent inconsistency
help explain why South Korea's biggest chaebol remain a potent
political force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daewoo is the eye of the storm,'' said Jung Tae Soo, the
director of the Seoul office of Arthur D. Little Inc., the
management consultant.
</P>
<P>
   President Kim and the ruling parties want Daewoo to take over
the assembly line of Samsung Motors, currently under bankruptcy
protection. Samsung's production facility is in Pusan province in
the south, an opposition stronghold. With an election pending, the
president and his fragile coalition cannot afford the job losses
from a Samsung plant closing.
</P>
<P>
   That consideration is widely believed to be behind Daewoo's
reprieve. ``Samsung Motors is located in Pusan, and that means a
lot,'' Jung said. ``Business decisions are not made on business
rationales.''
</P>
<P>
   The Daewoo crisis may have been created partly by the skillful
maneuvering of the Samsung group, the third-largest chaebol, and
its chairman, Lee Kun Hee.
</P>
<P>
   The government had pushed Samsung into negotiations with Daewoo
earlier this year. Samsung was to acquire Daewoo's electronics
business, and Daewoo was to get Samsung's car company.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations did not progress smoothly, however. Samsung
Electronics, a semiconductor giant with a global investor base, had
no great desire to acquire a third-rate competitor. Daewoo was
hardly in a position to absorb Samsung Motors, which was losing
roughly $6,000 on every car it produced.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on June 30, Samsung halted the haggling and said it was
putting Samsung Motors into bankruptcy, threatening the future of
the politically sensitive Pusan plant. ``It was Samsung's decision,
not ours,'' a government official said.
</P>
<P>
   The government scrambled to put together some damage control,
stressing that Lee Kun Hee had pledged his own assets to erase
Samsung Motors' debts _ and that Daewoo was still a likely buyer
for the Pusan plant.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Samsung intended to create political turmoil may never
be disclosed. But Lee and his family will likely end up richer
because of the episode. In order to unlock the value of the
collateral he pledged, shares of Samsung Life Insurance, the
government is allowing him to take that business public. Analysts
say the publicly traded shares will be worth far more than their
face value.
</P>
<P>
   In one final act of arrogance toward the government, Samsung
recently confirmed that Samsung Life made $450 million in loans to
the Samsung car company earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The big chaebol like Samsung ``are more of a small empire than
the government itself,'' Oh of the Corporate Restructuring
Committee said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Daewoo, the weakest of the big five, has managed to stymie
reform.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months after a deal was struck to sell Korea First Bank,
one of two banks nationalized in the aftermath of the crisis, to an
American investor group, Newbridge Capital Ltd., the bank still
belongs to the South Koreans. Speculation is rampant that the deal
has stalled because the bank is one of Daewoo's three largest
creditors, and the government is worried that Newbridge will use
aggressive Western-style tactics to recover the bank's loans.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials seem to sense some need to restore
momentum. Word in the market is that South Korea will complete the
long-delayed sale of Seoul Bank, the other bank it nationalized, to
the HSBC Corp. by Aug. 2. The government announced it would float
shares in the state-controlled gas importer, having failed to find
a buyer at its price. Some are finding solace in its stance on
Daewoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess this is the time for the government to reaffirm its
support for reform and pursue it vigorously,'' Hyun, the former
politician, said. ``I remain rather optimistic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
