<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ An unexpected spike in an important
inflation warning signal that tracks labor costs spooked financial
markets, overshadowing a separate government report that showed the
robust U.S. economy took a breather in the spring. Investors
appeared worried that the Federal Reserve chairman, Alan Greenspan
may now be more likely to favor raising interest rates in the near
future. By Sylvia Nasar. (The story has moved in ``f'' news file.)
With graphic. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   GA-SHOOT-SCENE (Atlanta) _ The scene of the shootings at the
office buildings in the Buckhead section of northern Atlanta. By
David Barstow. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
800 words.
</P>
<P>
   The story runs under a 3-column photo, with headshot of suspect.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House Republican leadership,
facing another rebellion from some moderate and conservative
Republicans, backs away from plans to consider legislation on
managed health care next week, with Speaker Dennis Hastert
conceding that a vote before the August recess is now unlikely. By
Alison Mitchell. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``w'' news
file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LI-RAILROAD (New York) _ A status report on one of New York
City's major commuter systems. For years, riders on the Long Island
Railroad, the nation's busiest commuter line, were more accepting
of its shortcomings. Now complacency seems to be giving over to a
kind of nascent rail rage. Confrontations between passengers and
crew members have become common, and crew members are threatening
to eject disgruntled passengers. By David M. Halbfinger. (The
report has moved in ``a'' news file.) 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   NONSTOP-EATING (Chicago) _ On a Sunday morning at a Roman
Catholic church here, Mary Hallan Fiorito glanced at a nearby pew
to see a woman drinking a can of Coke during the Mass. At a musical
in a Broadway theater in New York, Alex Wang turned to the row
behind him to discover people eating corn on the cob. In schools
that once forbade chewing gum, students now bring doughnuts and
candy to class. Americans seem to be eating all the time, and
wherever they please. By Dirk Johnson. (The story has moved in
``a'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-IMMIG (San Francisco) _ The landmark 1994 ballot
referendum that barred illegal immigrants and their children from
receiving government services like a public education and became
one of the most divisive political issues in California history,
was declared all but dead. Gov. Gray Davis, striking a deal with
opponents of the referendum, Proposition 187, agrees to drop an
appeal of a federal court's ruling that found much of it
unconstitutional. By Evelyn Nieves. (Scheduled to move by 7:45 p.m.
ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   reefer: CLINTON-JONES (Washington) _ In what could be the final
chapter in Paula Jones' sexual misconduct lawsuit, a federal judge
orders President Clinton to pay Mrs. Jones' lawyers nearly $90,000
in compensation for extra work they performed because of the
president's false testimony about his relationship with Monica S.
Lewinsky. By Neil A. Lewis. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in
``w'' news file.)
</P>
