<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9078 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-DIGITAL30-C     07-29 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-DIGITAL30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth introducing high-speed phone lines
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth announced on Thursday its long-awaited entry
into the race to deliver high-speed lines to business customers.
</P>
<P>
   Using the technology known as digital subscriber lines _ DSL _
BellSouth is offering companies, government and universities five
different transmission speeds in 30 cities through BellSouth's
nine-state region.
</P>
<P>
   Key to BellSouth's strategy, the ploy is aimed at retaining
company customers by providing a broad range of cutting-edge
features.
</P>
<P>
   Faster connections make it more feasible for companies to use
videoconferencing, electronic commerce, telecommuting and links to
other branches of a company or agency.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's service is aimed partly at heading off a host of
rivals, including upstarts like Covad Communications and Level 3,
entering its largest markets _ especially Atlanta. Competitors
attack what is probably the most lucrative piece of BellSouth's
business, offering packages of telecommunications services,
including high-speed access, to companies.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, DSL competes with cable modems _ the high-speed
connection being gradually introduced by cable companies. The phone
companies lag in the race for consumers, but the more critical
market for BellSouth is among businesses, said analyst George
Peabody of the Aberdeen Group.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is wise to make the move, he said. ``The
communications industry is getting more and more competitive. And
the incumbent phone companies have the most to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of BellSouth's $23 billion-a-year revenues comes on its
nine-state home turf.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth rolled out DSL to consumers last summer, an offering
that had a somewhat rocky launch, with BellSouth unable to deliver
the service to many interested customers.
</P>
<P>
   DSL's greatest advantage for the phone companies is its ability
to use existing copper lines. However, those lines can generally
not carry the same transmission rate to customers more than 18,000
feet from a central office. BellSouth has promised to steadily add
the equipment needed to extend the reach of DSL. But for
businesses, which will pay from $85 to $850 a month for DSL, the
company would likely install whatever equipment is needed to
connect a specific customer.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's consumer DSL offers Internet access at speeds up to
1.5 megabits per second. The business offering includes a low-end
version with 768 kilobits per second starting at $85 a month, a 1.5
megabits-per-second version from $150, a 2 to 4 megabits service
for $335 and a 4 to 6 megabits version for $725. Upload speeds _
from the user to the Internet _ are typically slower. BellSouth
also offers a version in which download and upload speeds match, an
offering that would support videoconferencing, BellSouth said.
Installation for all the DSL variations is $300.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
