<HEADER>
A9079 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINDSPRING30-COX     07-29 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring signs with chat provider, e-commerce service
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MindSpring Enterprises announced two new partners this
week to provide additional content for the MindSpring home page.
It's all part of MindSpring's previously stated plans to make its
home page more useful to its 1.2 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based Internet access provider has lined up popular
chat and community site Talk City to provide online chats and
events to MindSpring users.
</P>
<P>
   The California-based Talk City is one of the most popular sites
for online chats and special events. The company also designs
customized electronic community events and does online market
research for a variety of clients including Cox Interactive Media
and BellSouth. Talk City is also able to build customized chat
rooms to suit the particular needs of any Web site. (Cox
Interactive, an investor in Talk City, is owned by Cox Enterprises,
parent company of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring also announced a deal with another Web site called On
Now (www.onnow.com), which allows users to browse Internet-based
events happening in real time or to search for events up to two
weeks in advance.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of these services is part of MindSpring's
long-stated plan to make its home page more attractive to users and
potential users. The company announced plans Tuesday to step up its
marketing and advertising efforts to attract nearly one million new
subscribers by this time next year.
</P>
<P>
   For its business customers, MindSpring announced a deal on
Tuesday with the privately-held Nexchange, an Atlanta-based company
that connects buyers and sellers over a network of thousands of Web
sites, to help MindSpring business customers make more effective
use of electronic commerce on their Web sites. MindSpring also has
a deal with Norcross-based Headhunter.net that allows MindSpring
Biz customers to place job postings on the service at discounted
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
