<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9080 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIATLANTA30-COX     07-29 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIATLANTA30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientific-Atlanta making purchases
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Scientific-Atlanta has announced two investments in
companies and technologies designed to speed up systems that
deliver cable TV programming to customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company, one of two leading providers of
equipment and software to the cable TV industry, is continually
looking for ways to enhance its product line for the operators who
are its customers.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Scientific-Atlanta has agreed to invest $13 million
in Bookham Technology, which makes a manufacturing process that
shrinks complex optical circuits that are ordinarily the size of a
deck of playing cards down to the size of a silicon chip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate that this technology will enable us to initiate
important performance improvements and cost reductions in our
Prisma optical products,'' said Paul Connolly, Scientific-Atlanta's
vice president of marketing and network architectures.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta's Prisma Optical network products are used to
send video, voice and data over fiber-optic networks, which a
growing number of cable operators are now installing.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate deal, Scientific-Atlanta said it planned to buy
the Megaflex and Photon business units of Memphis-based Thomas &AMP;
Betts.
</P>
<P>
   Terms were not disclosed, but the purchase is expected to close
within 90 days, said company officials.
</P>
<P>
   Megaflex and Photon make critical connectors and components for
analog and digital networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This acquisition will further strengthen our ability to lead
the industry with the most comprehensive fiber-optic system
architecture available for our customers,'' said Connolly.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta supports both current analog cable TV systems
and the new digital ones. It is pushing, however, a new digital
network called the Explorer 2000. It enables a host of new
services, including digital television, high-speed access to the
Internet and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The company's clients include some of the industry's biggest
operators, including Time Warner and Atlanta-based Cox
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
