<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9081 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-CAPITAL30-COX     07-29 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-CAPITAL30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOING FOR THE GOLD: Atlanta covets `sports capital' title
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Scarlett might be getting benched in favor of the
Falcons, the Hawks, the Braves and the Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if city promoters can convince a group of journalists
that Atlanta is the ``Sports Capital of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau, the Metro Atlanta
Chamber of Commerce and the Atlanta Sports Council will host a
four-day media update and showcase Aug. 11-14, touting the Atlanta
sports machine and its economic impact on the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not attacking places like New York and Boston as it
relates to the tradition of sports and who has the most titles,''
said Bill Howard, ACVB vice president of marketing, tourism and
communications. ``It's just one aspect of the city of Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be a tough sell, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way can it replace New York,'' said a skeptical Leon
Carter, deputy sports editor at the New York Daily News, who has
visited Atlanta several times. ``When you talk about a city being
the sports capital of the world, then it means the Knicks cannot
come into Atlanta and have half the crowd rooting for them. ... You
have to look and see exactly how many fans go to the Hawks
basketball games and how many go to the Falcons football games. Do
they sell out those games?''
</P>
<P>
   USA Today Sports Editor Monte Lorell thought the ``Sports
Capital of the World'' billing was ``a great goal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it's one of the sports capitals,'' said Lorell, who
was invited to the event but won't be able to attend because of
prior commitments. ``Atlanta will soon have a team in each of the
four major sports _ once the Thrashers come on _ and they have
college teams. It's at a crossroads of sorts for sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a doubt, the city has made some headway. The Sporting
News recently released its ranking of the 20 best cities for
sports. New York-Long Island-New Jersey captured the top spot,
followed by Dallas-Fort Worth and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta jumped to fourth from 16th, largely because of a good
performance by the Falcons. Detroit, which was No. 1 last year,
fell to seventh.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, season ticket sales for the National
Basketball Association Hawks at the new Philips Arena are moving
slower than those for the Thrashers, joining the National Hockey
League.
</P>
<P>
   Invitations for the event were sent to about 100 journalists
from around the country, many of whom work in sports. So far, about
17 journalists have confirmed, including writers with overseas
publications and from The Wall Street Journal, the Los Angeles
Times, Southern Living and Travel Weekly, said the ACVB's Howard.
All expenses are paid, although some journalists may opt to pay a
nominal fee of $100. Others may choose to foot the entire bill.
About one-third have chosen the nominal fee, said Howard, adding
that some are local and won't need hotel and air accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   The showcase includes dinner with heavyweight boxing champ
Evander Holyfield; a Braves game; a tour of Philips Arena and a
meeting with Stan Kasten, president of the Turner Sports-owned
Braves, Hawks and Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   Howard points to the city's hosting of several major sporting
events, including the 1996 Centennial Olympic Games, Super Bowl
XXXIV in 2000 and the Women's Final Four in 2003 as evidence of its
growing sports presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put the total inventory of everything we have
together, it's a pretty dynamic story in terms of
accomplishments,'' he said. ``I think it's a pretty big story to
tell.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that journalists will spread the word that Atlanta
has the ability to host major events and enhance the city's image.
That wasn't the case in 1996, when thousands of journalists from
around the world descended on Atlanta for the Olympics and in some
cases panned the city, particularly on transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Why invite more scrutiny?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any apologies to make,'' Howard said. ``Our
research has shown that the vast majority of consumers did not have
an unfavorable experience in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   City promoters aren't just bent on telling a sports story.
Sports mean big business, from packing restaurants to filling hotel
rooms and airline seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have definitely, up to this point, felt the impact of the
Braves when they're in town. And with the onset of Philips Arena,
we also hope to benefit from the Thrashers and the Hawks,'' said
Charles Powell, general manager of the recently opened Embassy
Suites at Centennial Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics brought in $5.1 billion. Next year's Super Bowl is
expected to have an economic impact of $250 million and the NCAA
Final Four in 2002 is expected to bring in $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Howard said the city plans to promote its other attractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope people look at you as a very diverse city,'' he said.
``People don't come here for just one reason; they come here for
many reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9082 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAWFIRM-ACQUISITION-B     07-29 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWFIRM-ACQUISITION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITTSBURGH, BOSTON LAW FIRMS TO MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Pittsburgh-based law firm Kirkpatrick &AMP; Lockhart will
acquire the 125-year-old Boston firm of Warner &AMP; Stackpole, the
latest in what legal industry observers say is likely to become a
frenzy of law firm mergers in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Some 35 Kirkpatrick &AMP; Lockhart lawyers who already work in
Boston will move into Warner &AMP; Stackpole's State Street offices
after the merger becomes official Aug. 1, forming a combined office
of about 80 lawyers, partners at both firms said.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkpatrick &AMP; Lockhart, with offices in Boston, Pittsburgh, New
York, Washington, D.C., Miami and Harrisburg, Pa., will have about
500 lawyers after the merger.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal, the smaller Warner &AMP; Stackpole will gain the
national presence and resources many small and midsized firms say
is now necessary to survive in the increasingly cutthroat business
of practicing law, the firm's partners said Thursday. But it will
lose its 125-year-old name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bittersweet situation,'' said Gordon Stevenson, a
Warner &AMP; Stackpole managing partner. ``There are pluses and
minuses. In the end, we felt there were more pluses.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Kirkpatrick &AMP; Lockhart, whose Boston practice
focused mainly on litigation, began courting Warner &AMP; Stackpole
almost seven months ago, largely because it wanted the firm's
lucrative corporate work, said Phil Fina, managing partner of the
Pittsburgh firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long mating dance,'' he said. ``They were going to be
surrendering a name and a 125-year identity, and they wanted to
make sure it was going to be a good fit. The history of law firm
mergers is littered with those that fell apart so that was
important to us too.''
</P>
<P>
   Such mergers are likely to become common in Boston over the next
year as national firms look for a foothold in Boston's raging
economy and native midsized firms struggle for a way to compete,
legal observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about every midsized firm in town is at least talking
about it right now,'' said Jane Sender of Jane Sender Legal Search,
a Boston consulting and head-hunting service for law firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every midsized firm feels pressure,'' she said. ``Their
overhead is high, and they feel pressure to compete with the big
firms. They're looking to the national firms for resources and
economies of scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Thursday's deal, the trend was becoming evident in a
half-dozen mergers since 1998, observers said. Among them were
deals like one late last year in which the Boston law firm
Sherburne, Powers &AMP; Needham merged with Holland &AMP; Knight, creating
the fifth-largest law firm in the country with 840 lawyers and
offices in 18 cities.
</P>
<P>
   And in May, Rochester, N.Y.-based Nixon, Hargrave, Devans &AMP;
Doyle announced plans to merge with Boston's 145-year-old Peabody &AMP;
Brown, creating a 450-lawyer practice. The combined firm, called
Nixon Peabody, ranks among the top 50 US law firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of activity is going to pick up,'' said one Boston
lawyer who asked not to be identified because of ongoing merger
talks. ``It's the buzz all over town. It's practically all lawyers
around here talk about anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
