<SLUG> BC-LOTUS-MACROMEDIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL LINKS LOTUS AND MULTIMEDIA SOFTWARE MAKER MACROMEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an effort to become a leader in delivering education through
computer networks, Lotus Development Corp. is linking up with
multimedia software maker Macromedia Inc. in a multimillion-dollar
deal that includes a product acquisition and licensing rights.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus, a wholly owned subsidiary of IBM Corp. based in
Cambridge, Mass., said it is especially interested in the corporate
training side of what is called ``distance learning'' and includes
delivery of traditional college courses by computer.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus chief executive Jeff Papows said in an interview that
companies nationwide spent about $62 billion last year on training
workers. ``Sixty percent of that is planes, trains and crappy
food.'' By delivering the courses on computer networks, much of
that money could be saved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can make a concentrated effort here to claim real
leadership in that space and really dominate this market,'' Papows
said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the deal were not disclosed, but Rob Burgess,
chairman and chief executive of San Francisco-based Macromedia,
said it would generate at least $30 million a year in licensing
revenue for his company over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge part of Lotus's future,'' said Papows. He
described the deal as vital in his effort to expand the company
beyond its present stronghold in corporate groupware _ including
Lotus Notes and Microsoft Corp.'s rival Exchange software. That
market will be saturated soon, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Lotus will purchase Pathware, a Macromedia
product used by businesses to design distance-learning courses.
These courses can be taken via the Internet or a company's internal
computer network. Pathware will be combined with Lotus
LearningSpace, software that allows users in different locations to
link their computers to form an electronic classroom.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Lotus will license Macromedia's Authorware, Flash
and Shockware software for use in its distance-learning software
products. Lotus will also act as a distributor of Macromedia
software, which will boost Macromedia's access to software buyers
at the Fortune 1000 companies that are Lotus's prime customers.
</P>
<P>
   Macromedia's Burgess said the addition of his firm's software
will allow Lotus LearningSpace users to develop multimedia courses,
mixing sound, animation and video images with plain text.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're multisensory creatures. Given a choice, people will
always prefer a multimedia experience,'' Burgess said. ``What this
allows you to do is create a much richer experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
