<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-CONGRESS-ART-860&AMP;     07-29 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-CONGRESS-ART-860&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP MOVES CLOSER TO SENATE PASSAGE OF $792 MILLION TAX CUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Del., Texas, Mich.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans moved closer Thursday to Senate passage
of a $792 billion tax cut over the opposition of President Clinton
and congressional Democrats, but still face the difficult task of
uniting the party on what form the tax cuts should take.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate took up dozens of amendments to the tax bill
Thursday, rejecting the broadest of them and heading toward a vote
on final passage late Thursday or Friday. The Senate bill was all
but certain to pass with its major provisions intact, including a
reduction in the lowest personal income tax rate.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to make political points, Democrats offered a series of
amendments, including one that would have postponed the tax cuts
and another that would have carved out money to provide a
prescription drug benefit within Medicare. All of them were
defeated, on largely party-line votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also voted down an attempt by conservative
Republicans to rework the $792 billion tax bill to include a
reduction in all income tax rates and in capital gains tax rates,
provisions that are included in the House version of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was also considering a host of special-interest
amendments. Sens. Mitch McConnell and Jim Bunning of Kentucky, both
Republicans, sought a change that would benefit horse owners by
reducing to one year from two years the length of time they would
need to own a horse before being able to sell it at a favorable
capital gains rate.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed its version of the $792 billion Republican
tax-cut plan last week. Once the Senate has finished work on its
legislation, appointees from both chambers will begin meeting to
hash out the many variations in their bills: Some reflect
fundamental differences in approach to tax cuts and others reflect
the priorities of interest groups with a political or economic
stake in the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Republicans have no higher priority this year than
passing a tax cut _ even though they know Clinton will veto it _
they will almost certainly reach a compromise among themselves in
the next week on what the tax package should look like.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debates will be of high energy and great commitment, but I
think it gets done,'' said Rep. Michael Castle, R-Del., one of a
handful of House Republicans who think the $792 billion tax cut is
too big. ``Those committed to getting this bill done are more
committed to getting it done at $792 billion than to any particular
provision.''
</P>
<P>
   But getting there may not be easy. And even after the House and
Senate negotiators reach agreement, they could face a tricky task
in selling the deal to their members, especially in the House,
where a renegade group of moderate Republicans is watching closely
to make sure their concerns are addressed in the final package.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are significant differences both in approach and in
structure in the House and Senate bills,'' said Trent Duffy, a
spokesman for Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the Ways and
Means Committee. ``Conferencing them will be challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   The House bill is generally more appealing to conservatives in
both chambers than the Senate bill, which was written to draw some
support from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, which was written by Archer, is built around a
gradual reduction in all income tax rates, a provision that
Republicans say would benefit those people who pay the most in
taxes but that Democrats say disproportionately rewards the
wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version, which was written by Sen. William Roth,
R-Del., chairman of the Finance Committee, provides a smaller
income tax cut and directs a greater proportion of it to
middle-income households than the House bill. It would reduce only
the lowest income tax rate, bringing the current 15 percent bracket
down to 14 percent and expanding the bracket to higher income
levels.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate version goes further than the House version in
addressing the so-called marriage penalty, a primary goal of social
conservatives, one of the most influential of Republican
constituencies. The Senate plan would almost eliminate the penalty
_ which leaves many two-income couples paying more in taxes than if
they were single _ by eventually allowing married couples to file
as if they were single.
</P>
<P>
   The House plan would limit its marriage penalty provisions to
people who use the standard deduction, meaning that it would do
little for higher-income couples, who almost invariably itemize
their deductions.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill contains a reduction in the top rate on capital
gains to 15 percent from 20 percent, while the Senate version has
no provision for capital gains.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate negotiators will have to maintain a
delicate political balance, retaining the appeal of the package
both to the conservative wing of the party and the moderate wing.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping that balance will be especially challenging in the
House, where Republicans have a razor-thin majority. A group of
Republican moderates in the House objected to the size and
composition of the original bill last week, forcing concessions
from the party's leaders intended to assure that the tax cuts would
not lead to renewed budget deficits.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thursday, a group of those same moderates circulated a letter
demanding that the party retain a feature of the House bill that is
certain to bring intense objections from the Senate. The House bill
contains a ``trigger'' that would allow the income tax reductions
to take place only if the interest cost on the national debt does
not rise.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen of the Republican moderates had signed the letter by
Thursday night, suggesting that the leadership could have trouble
passing the final version of the bill if it does not include the
trigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us have told the leadership that without a hard
trigger we will have difficulty supporting the bill,'' said Rep.
Fred Upton, R-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill has a procedural wrinkle that could also give
the negotiators heartburn. It would require that the tax cuts be
rescinded after 10 years, a provision that would be unappealing to
conservatives in the House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
