u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      07-29 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS READY TO ANNOUNCE SIGNING OF TWO NO. 1 DRAFT PICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ The Patriots did not announce the signings of
their two No. 1 draft picks _ Boston College center Damien Woody
and Ohio State linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer _ Thursday, but hope to
do so at Friday's opening of training camp at Bryant College.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots vice president of business operations Andy Wasynczuk
has a streak of no rookie ever holding out while he's been in
charge of the team's contracts, and he doesn't intend to blemish
his record this year _ though Woody's deal was still cloudy as of
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will enter camp another veteran short after the
team let Willie Clay go to save the $1.5 million they were
scheduled to pay him this season. While the Patriots brass had
wanted the team to get a little bit older, it's even younger now.
</P>
<P>
   With 34 new players on the preseason roster since the end of the
1998 season, the Patriots' coaching staff will be looking at 23
rookies, 11 first-year, 15 second-year, seven third-year and six
fourth-year players. Only 23 players on the roster have five or
more years experience.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots did not acquire that savvy veteran leader as they
had hoped, though Terry Allen is still a possibility if the Barry
Sanders-less Detroit Lions don't scoop him up.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will be returning from a disappointing 9-7 season
in which at one time or another there were 16 starters injured.
Training camp may be a tad tougher this year as coach Pete Carroll,
who appears to be on the hot seat, is expected to enforce the use
of pads more than he did a year ago in the hope that players will
be tougher and less injury-prone for the start of the season Sept.
12 at New York vs. the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll will basically have to get the Patriots back to or close
to the Super Bowl again, or risk being on the short end of this
winter's evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Many coaches who have gone 10-6 and 9-7 would have job security
for many years, but not Carroll, who succeeded a legendary coach
who has gone to the Big Game.
</P>
<P>
   While the offseason program was well-attended, it was nothing to
gloat about. The good news is the major players who stayed away _
Ty Law, Bruce Armstrong, Ben Coates, and Zefross Moss _ appear to
be in excellent shape. Law, who may be on the verge of a new deal,
continued his work with track coach Bob Kersee and intends to press
the Patriots to become a multi-dimensional player.
</P>
<P>
   The issues haven't changed much from the end of the season,
except the team has added the riddle of who replaces Clay.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll claims the replacement comes from a list of Chris
Carter, rookie Tony George, and Larry Whigham.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking issue will be finding a running back to
replace the injured Robert Edwards. LSU's Kevin Faulk will get the
chance unless the Patriots sign Allen or pick up a running back
from Miami's dirty dozen.
</P>
<P>
   The other player who will draw major attention is Terry Glenn.
Recovering from a fractured ankle, it remains to be seen whether
Carroll will approach Glenn differently in terms of trying to
preserve him for the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Another area of concern is the offensive line and replacing
veteran center Dave Wohlabaugh. The Patriots need their line to
run-block better. A smashmouth approach will be emphasized by new
coach Dante Scarnecchia, but the leadership in this area has to
come from Armstrong, whose run-blocking suffered last season
because he played with a fractured leg. Armstrong is under 300
pounds for the first time since his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   Woody should eventually be more than a capable replacement for
Wohlabaugh. Potentially more talented than Wohlabaugh, it becomes
vital that Woody is signed so he doesn't miss a good portion of
training camp, which certainly gives him the edge in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Woody has been working in Foxborough, Mass. since May 15 when he
quit Boston College after the draft. If he starts to understand the
offense, then Woody's athleticism should take over and make him a
dominating player.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Willie McGinest is to that unit what Glenn is to
the offense. When McGinest is sound and rushing the passer, it
opens up opportunities for Chris Slade and for the secondary to
make a play.
</P>
<P>
   To McGinest's credit, he has left no stone unturned in trying to
strengthen the area around his groin to prevent the strains and
pulls from the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   If all are healthy and participating and if Clay can be
replaced, the Patriots have one of the best defenses in the league.
They have All-Pro caliber players in Law, Lawyer Milloy, Ted
Johnson, Chris Slade, McGinest, an emerging Chad Eaton, and a
seasoned veteran in Henry Thomas. Tedy Bruschi and Brandon Mitchell
could blossom this year, and Tebucky Jones bears watching, as does
the aggressive Katzenmoyer.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the entire season rests on the arm and the
finger of Drew Bledsoe. As the Patriots found out at crunch time a
year ago, without Bledsoe, they are not capable of beating the
big-time teams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
