<HEADLINE>
FORMER STATE DEPARTMENT EMPLOYEE ACCUSED OF VISA IMPROPRIETIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Ind.)  (rk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A House panel Thursday accused a former State
Department employee at the American embassy in Beijing of
improperly granting visas to Chinese citizens seeking entry to the
United States, sometimes approving entry documents for friends of a
Democratic fund-raiser in return for gifts, money and favors.
</P>
<P>
   The employee, Charles M. Parish, was transferred out of his job
in 1996 and investigated by the State Department's Diplomatic
Security Service, the department's inspector general and finally
the FBI. He retired in 1998 without being charged with wrongdoing
and with a pension.
</P>
<P>
   Parish, who had been subpoenaed to testify Thursday before the
House government Reform and Oversight Committee, quickly departed
after he refused to answer questions. Parish cited his
constitutional right against self-incrimination, and when asked
whether he would decline to answer every question put to him, he
said he would.
</P>
<P>
   Although the investigation of Parish is closed, Republican
lawmakers on the committee have been examining his activities in
connection with the panel's long-running inquiry into campaign
finance improprieties in the 1996 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   In a report issued Thursday, the committee said it had found
evidence that Parish received gifts from Cofco, a Chinese
state-owned food products conglomerate, and BNU Corp., a real
estate company in Phoenix that is a wholly owned subsidiary of
Cofco. In return, the committee said, Parish supplied visas for
Cofco officials.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee report did not unearth any additional evidence
indicating that Parish had performed favors for anyone connected to
efforts to raise money from Asian-Americans or from Chinese
nationals, like the military and intelligence officials who
secretly funneled money to the Democrats in the 1996 presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony to the committee on May 11, one Democratic
fund-raiser, Johnny Chung, told the panel that he had met Parish
while trying to get a visa for the head of a large Chinese beer
company, the Haomen Group. Chung said that he had developed a close
relationship with Parish and estimated that he had approved 25 to
30 visas for Chung's business clients.
</P>
<P>
   Chung testified that in 1995 he had witnessed the chairman of
the beer company, He Yun Jei, hand Parish a bag containing bundles
of Chinese currency along with several Chinese passports that
needed to be stamped with visas permitting entry into the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1995, Chung took Parish, Parish's sister and a
girlfriend to a Democratic National Committee fund-raiser and a
private reception with President Clinton, he testified. Chung later
provided other favors for Parish, his secretary and his
girlfriends.
</P>
<P>
   In Parish's absence, Thursday's hearing focused on what Rep. Dan
Burton, R-Ind., and chairman of the committee, said was the State
Department's botched handling of the investigation of Parish.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, department officials acknowledged that they had
not examined Parish's bank accounts, had not tried to review all
his visa files and had narrowed their inquiry to his relationship
with just two Chinese citizens even though there were several
complaints against him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
