<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST STATISTICS SPUR INFLATION FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's nonstop economic expansion created the highest
increase of wages since 1991, the federal government reported
Thursday, fueling fears that the strong growth has finally unleased
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department said wages and benefits rose 1.1 percent in
the second quarter, a report that sent the financial markets into a
tailspin. Investors fear that the Federal Reserve would seize upon
the spike to justify another hike in interest rates in August in
order to keep inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average plunged as much as 258 points,
before recovering slightly to close down 180.78 points, 1.65
percent, at 10,791.29.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inflation risk shows up loud and clear in today's reports,''
said Allen Sinai of Primark Decision Economics in Boston. The
reports suggest ``the Federal Reserve might have to tighten sooner
than expected. One more dose of tightening, maybe two, maybe
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the Commerce Department reported that gross
domestic product, or GDP, grew at a 2.3 percent annual pace during
the second quarter. It was a dramatic slowing from the breakneck
4.3 percent expansion rate during the first quarter, a pace many
economists believed was unsustainable, even alarming.
</P>
<P>
   A slowdown had been expected and even welcomed, because it would
act as a natural deterrent to inflation. But attention Thursday was
riveted to the seasonally adjusted Employment Cost Index, which is
closely watched by the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The GDP news is all good news,'' said Barry Bosworth, an
economist at the Brookings Institution, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Bosworth cautioned that it is too early to firmly conclude, from
one wage report, that inflation will take off. For the average
worker, Bosworth said, the report ``should be seen as good news and
signals a return to a more sustainable path of growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The spike in the wage index, however, caused concerns because
labor costs account for a large portion of consumer prices. The
latest quarter's rise of 1.1 percent marked an acceleration from
the two previous quarters, when the index rose half a percentage
point on average. It was the biggest quarterly jump since a 1.2
percent increase in the second quarter of 1991, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   The employment cost index has risen 3.2 percent since June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the report put investors on edge.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market slumped, as yields on the benchmark 30-year US
Treasury bonds rose to 6.07 percent from a close the previous day
of just over 6 percent. During the day yields touched 6.12 percent,
the highest level since June 25.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks plunged in reaction to a hammering in the bond and stock
futures markets, which open before the stock exchanges, said Ned
Riley, BankBoston Corp.'s chief investment officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was across-the-board selling of cyclical (stocks), as
well as technology, health care, and financials,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still at a very high valuation level'' in the stock
market, Riley said, and ``any adverse news can puncture that
utopian environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists for months have predicted a labor market that is
tight as a drum would begin to drive up wages as businesses compete
for workers. As wages rise, they can, in turn, fuel inflation by
increasing prices for goods and services that workers produce or
provide. US unemployment in June, at 4.3 percent, remains at
30-year lows.
</P>
<P>
   Inflationary pressures eased last fall for two reasons,
economists said. Global financial turmoil prompted a plunge in
commodity prices, particularly oil. And worker productivity
continued to rise, easing any wage pressures. These forces combined
to dampen inflation, which in more normal times would be a
byproduct of strong growth.
</P>
<P>
   This unusual period of low inflation has helped to sustain the
longest peacetime expansion in US history.
</P>
<P>
   But prices for oil on world markets have risen as the global
economy has strengthened. Crude oil topped $21 a barrel Thursday
for the first time since November 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, a jump in the employment cost index
confirmed investors' worst fears about what Federal Reserve
chairman Alan Greenspan and the Federal Open Market Committee would
do when they meet to set monetary policy on Aug. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has been on the lookout for inflation, warning
repeatedly that it may lurk around the corner. Greenspan's warnings
continued this week in congressional testimony, even though the Fed
in June had already boosted interest rates by a quarter point, to 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The wage spike ``is the kind of thing the Fed chairman is
worried about, that the economy is too stretched and it may be
putting some upward pressure on inflation,'' said James O'Sullivan,
economist for J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., a New York securities firm.
</P>
<P>
   Economists will closely watch July's unemployment report for
more signs of expanding employment _ and, potentially, wage
increases.
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan and others said a closer inspection of the wage
report, in truth, revealed a mix of messages.
</P>
<P>
   For one, wage hikes were inflated by an increase in compensation
for workers on Wall Street, where broker commissions swelled during
a sizzling rally in stocks. Mortgage bankers and real estate
brokers also brought in higher commissions in a housing market in
which homes sell like hotcakes.
</P>
<P>
   The average of the first- and second-quarter employment cost
indexes is an increase of about three-quarters of a percentage
point, in line with last year's quarterly gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the employment cost index report tells you is wage
inflation is broadly stable,'' said William Dudley, chief economist
for Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
