<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9102 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOGAN-STOWAWAY-BOS &LR;      07-29 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOGAN-STOWAWAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICALS STUDY STOWAWAY'S BREACH OF LOGAN SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Abraham Derman, the 17-year-old who stowed away on a
British Airways London-bound flight, made his daring trek over a
fence and across restricted space at Logan International Airport in
the traditional garb of a Hasidic Jew, aviation sources said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That makes Derman's July 12 escapade, which he planned to
impress Israeli spies, even more remarkable because it makes it
unlikely that he could he blend in as someone who belonged in
restricted airport areas.
</P>
<P>
   Hasidic Jews typically wear long dark coats, wide-brimmed hats
and have side locks of hair and beards. Derman reportedly has the
wispy beginnings of a beard.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is an obvious failure of security,'' said an aviation
security specialist who spoke on condition that his name not be
used.
</P>
<P>
   Derman, of suburban Brookline, scaled a perimeter fence, walked
unchallenged for 2 miles across restricted areas, including at
least one active taxiway, and gained access to the 747 jet by
climbing the outside stairs of the jetway, an enlosed walkway
connecting the airport boarding area and the aircraft's doorway,
and passing through a door that should have been locked.
</P>
<P>
   Two sources said Derman reached the plane by using the exterior
stairs to the jetway from the tarmac after a ramp mechanic propped
the door open.
</P>
<P>
   He hid on the tarmac near the airplane and made a well-timed
dash up the stairs as the first group of passengers boarded Flight
214, British Airways's daily 8:10 p.m. flight to London.
</P>
<P>
   A source familiar with the investigation into Derman's trip said
the teenager reads spy novels and hoped to impress the Mossad, the
Israeli intelligence agency, with his stunt. Derman wanted to fly
on to Israel from London's Heathrow International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   His attempt ended after Heathrow airport security discovered
Derman in a restricted area.
</P>
<P>
   Sources also said Thursday that the teen was thwarted at least
once, and possibly as many as five times, by airport personnel
earlier July 12 when he first tried to gain access to the tarmac
from inside Terminal E.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd be in a restricted baggage handling area and someone
would confront him and he'd say, `I'm lost.' The kid looks like he
is 13,'' said one source familiar with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The airport is owned and operated by the Massachusetts Port
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   After being turned back by airport workers inside the Logan
terminal, Derman walked along a perimeter fence north of the
airport, then climbed the fence and either cut the razor wire on
top or found a section in which the wire was torn and jumped down
onto the airfield.
</P>
<P>
   Airport employees, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
they have been instructed to question anyone not familiar to them
who is in a restricted area and ask for their identification no
matter their age.
</P>
<P>
   One source said Thursday that when Derman entered the airplane,
he first sat in a seat reserved for flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   After an attendant told him to take his assigned seat, he moved
to a coach seat that belonged to someone else. Forced to yield the
coach seat, Derman moved to the more upscale business section and
stayed there for the flight to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration is investigating the
incident and could levy fines against Massport, British Airways,
and Derman himself.
</P>
<P>
   Security specialists said Derman's ability to breach the fence
at Logan is not remarkable because most US airports do not monitor
perimeter fences with cameras or electronic sensors.
</P>
<P>
   At least twice in the past year unauthorized individuals have
gained access to ramp areas at Logan. In both cases the individuals
were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have said they will not bring criminal charges
against Derman because of his age and because his parents
understand the severity of his actions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff member Thomas C. Palmer Jr. contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
