<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CONFIDENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CAMP SAYS PRESIDENTIAL FRONT-RUNNER NOT OVERCONFIDENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Dateline changed to Austin sted of Houston) 
 
By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ From the beginning of his presidential campaign,
Gov. George W. Bush has said he will take nothing for granted,
shunning the idea that the GOP nomination is essentially his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think `anointed' is something that I suspect others are
trying to attribute to this campaign. And `anointed' kind of means
that you're not working for anything. I'm working,'' Bush told the
Milwaukee Journal Sentinel last week. ``I take nothing for
granted.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has been criticized for taking Hispanic support for
granted by declining to attend three conventions of Hispanic
activists. Bush is on vacation, with a campaign stop here and
there, in the two weeks before the Iowa straw poll. And Bush is
vacillating on whether to participate in a Florida GOP convention
debate of presidential candidates in October.
</P>
<P>
   With a major lead in the polls and $30 million in the bank, Bush
and his campaign staff apparently have the self-confidence to take
a pass when other candidates are scrambling for attention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said Bush's absence from
conventions and his vacation have nothing to do with being
overconfident.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why he is interrupting his vacation to go to Iowa next
week and New Hampshire on Saturday, and he will be back in Iowa the
week after that,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made a number of visits to Iowa,'' Hughes said. ``He is
working very hard and our organization is working very hard to earn
votes in Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   But as of Thursday, the total number of Bush's days in Iowa were
four, according to the National Journal's The Hotline.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, here is the number of days some of his GOP
opponents have spent campaigning in Iowa: Lamar Alexander, 28; Gary
Bauer, 19; Pat Buchanan, 19; Elizabeth Dole, 17; Steve Forbes, 19;
and Dan Quayle, 14.
</P>
<P>
   Orrin Hatch, who launched his presidential campaign earlier this
month, has spent the same number of days in Iowa as Bush. Alan
Keyes has been there once. And John McCain, who is passing on the
Aug. 14 straw poll in Ames to concentrate his struggling campaign
elsewhere, has been to Iowa once.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the ease of Bush's positioning comes from his record
fund-raising and his standing in GOP primary and general election
polls.
</P>
<P>
   An NBC/Wall Street Journal poll released Thursday had Bush
leading for the GOP nomination by 59 percent, followed by Dole at
11 percent. And in a general election match-up with Democratic
front-runner Vice President Al Gore, Bush led 50 percent to 37
percent.
</P>
<P>
   And 48 percent of those surveyed said Gore would not be elected
president, while 44 percent said they thought Bush would be
elected. A whopping 84 percent said there is little or no chance
that they would support Gore for president.
</P>
<P>
   But the poll also contained evidence that Bush's days as the
golden candidate may be waning.
</P>
<P>
   While he wins in the horserace numbers, 64 percent of those
surveyed said there is little or no chance they would support Bush
for president. And 56 percent said his record $37 million in
fund-raising is excessive and a sign of what is wrong in politics,
against 29 percent who said they saw Bush's fund-raising as an
impressive sign of broad-based support.
</P>
<P>
   Bush already has had a rocky road on his quest for minority
votes in his presidential campaign, which has set its sight on
capturing a larger than normal share of the Hispanic vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bush first caught criticism for not attending the Unity
conference of minority journalists in Seattle where he was
campaigning. But then, when Bush dropped by the convention to
mingle, he caught additional fire for not speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Bush has skipped the conventions of the League of
the United Latin American Citizens and the National Association of
Latino Elected and Appointed Officials. Earlier this week, he was
criticized for not attending the National Council of La Raza
conference in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our people are a little angry he didn't show up,'' La
Raza President Raul Yzaguirre said. ``If he's taking us for
granted, he's misreading our community.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the criticism is unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has not attended any conventions this summer,''
Hughes said. ``We planned June and July as our introductory tour of
America to meet with supporters in different states and to
highlight some aspects of his message, such as faith-based
institutions and schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the Aug. 8 meeting of the National Urban League will
be the first time this summer that Bush has had any convention
speech on his schedule. Hughes said he missed the La Raza
convention because he goes to Maine on vacation with his family
this time every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it is a little out of line for these groups to suggest that
there is something else intended other than the fact he spends this
week every year with his family in Maine,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   But while the governor was in Maine, his wife, Laura, was
campaigning in Iowa Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Perverill Squire, a political science professor at the
University of Iowa, said he does not believe Bush's lack of a
full-bore campaign before the straw poll will hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of this is going to be dictated by the organization
you've already got on the ground,'' Squire said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So for him it can be portrayed as a normal person taking his
vacation. I don't think anyone is going to read into it that he is
arrogant or smug,'' Squire said. ``He can get away from it in a
fashion that the other candidates can't afford.''
</P>
<P>
   There already is a move to make the Iowa straw poll the last
before the Iowa caucuses early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has passed on an Alabama straw poll in late August, and the
Florida Republican Party has canceled its plans for its traditional
convention straw poll in October. Bush's brother, Jeb, is Florida's
Republican governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign also has declined to commit to a possible
candidate debate at the Florida convention, which has led some of
his opponents to cry foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has made clear that his strategy to win the
nomination is simply to buy it,'' said Brian Kennedy, political
director for the Alexander campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is going to debate anywhere, I would think he'd do it in
his brother's back yard before a friendly crowd,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't feel like he's capable of debating on those
terms, I don't know why we should expect he'll be able to debate Al
Gore in the fall of 2000 when the whole country is watching and the
presidency is at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
