<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OK, EVERYONE HOLD HANDS!  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Save me. My company recently brought in a ``team-building
expert'' to work with my department. The guy was straight out of a
``Dilbert'' cartoon, asking us to share all kinds of personal
stories and participate in goofy trust-building exercises. I
thought the nightmare would end when he left, but my boss seems to
have bought into this stuff. She started this morning's staff
meeting by having us go around the table and share something about
ourselves ``that no one else knows.'' How can I make it clear that
I'm uncomfortable with this touchy-feely stuff without alienating
my boss? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If it's any consolation, you're not alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard dozens of these stories,'' said Eileen C. Shapiro,
a management consultant and author of ``The Seven Deadly Sins of
Business'' (Capstone, 1998). ``This is common, and it's
appalling.''
</P>
<P>
   Although team-building is important, this type of exercise is
counterproductive, she said, explaining that ``it doesn't recognize
the boundaries between people's personal lives and what they have
to contribute to their businesses.'' For some people, sharing
personal tidbits is no problem. For others, it makes them feel even
more vulnerable and less comfortable with their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single most effective way to do team-building is to work
on an important and difficult, but not intractable, problem, and
solve it together,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing personal stories lacks such a clear goal, said Peter
deLisser, a leadership coach and author of ``Be Your Own Executive
Coach'' (Chandler House Press, 1999). And there is no way to tell
when the exercise may blow up in the boss's face. ``There's always
the risk that somebody's going to bleed their heart,'' he said.
``Somebody is going to wind up very embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, how can you avoid participating? You could be direct.
DeLisser suggested that next time it's your turn to share, just
say, ``One thing that no one else here knows about me is that I
hate these questions.'' But that could be what he calls a ``CLM'':
a career-limiting move.
</P>
<P>
   A less radical first step is to talk with colleagues. ``If
others are uncomfortable, perhaps a small group could go into the
boss and say, `We really respect the team-building you're doing,
but we're uncomfortable with the amount of personal disclosure
you're looking for,''' Ms. Shapiro advised.
</P>
<P>
   But be positive. ``Your manager may be staking part of her
identity on doing this team-building and may be feeling that this
is part of the way she's going to get ahead,'' Ms. Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   If you are the only person who loathes these exercises, or if
you and your colleagues fear that the boss won't listen, you may
need to adapt a bit. Look at it as a game, Ms. Shapiro and deLisser
said. Think in advance of simple, benign stories that can be
shared. ``That way, you've taken part,'' deLisser said. ``You've
done what your boss asked, but you didn't risk yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   And as you play along, keep your fingers crossed that the boss
eventually tires of hearing about everyone's personal life. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd St., New York, N.Y.
10036.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
