<HEADER>
A9111 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAIMLER-EARNINGS-ART-     07-29 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIMLER-EARNINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIMLERCHRYSLER STOCK FALLS AS 2ND QUARTER EARNINGS FAIL TO MEET
FORECASTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT, Mich. _ Shares of DaimlerChrysler AG took a pounding on
two continents Thursday after it turned in flat second-quarter
earnings, hurt mostly by weaker-than-expected profits from Chrysler
models.
</P>
<P>
   The company, formed in November when Daimler-Benz AG bought
Chrysler Corp., said its second-quarter adjusted net income fell
.03 percent, to 1.48 billion euros, or $1.53 billion, compared with
the 1.49 billion euros, or $1.534 billion, that the two companies
combined earned in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose roughly 10 percent, to 37.33 billion euros, or
$38.48 billion from 33.87 billion euros, or $34.92 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected more. Their consensus was that
DaimlerChrysler would earn $2 a share in the second quarter,
according to First Call Corp., which tracks earnings. But the
company earned 1.47 euros, or $1.52, a diluted share, down from the
1.52 euros, or $1.64 a share in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In Frankfurt, Germany, shares of DaimlerChrysler dropped 5.45
euros, or 6.8 percent, to 74.25 euros. They fared even worse in the
United States, falling $7.4375, or 8.75 percent, to $77.5625.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations were not met,'' said Scott F. Merlis, a managing
director and head of the automotive practice at Wasserstein Perella
Securities Inc. ``It is a paradox that the earnings were so
disappointing because the company continues to set sales records.''
</P>
<P>
   He said profits suffered because rebates were higher than
expected in North America and Europe and because of heavy losses
from the Smart car in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Executives defended the financial results. ``These are quite
good numbers,'' said Juergen E. Schrempp, the co-chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept our eyes on the ball and continued to grow the
business profitably,'' Schrempp said. ``We expect this trend of
profitable growth to continue in the second half of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   David B. Healy, an auto analyst with Burnham Securities, said
DaimlerChrysler's earnings in the second quarter suffered from
three problems: heavy losses in the Asian and Latin American
operations of the former Chrysler, continued losses on Daimler's
Smart car in Europe and the weakness of the euro, which made
European profits worth less when converted into dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Because the reporting of quarterly earnings remains fairly new
for DaimlerChrysler, the company might have made conservative
accounting choices that will result in better profits later this
year, particularly as economies from the merger begin to be
realized, Healy said. But he added that the steep fall in
DaimlerChrysler's shares Thursday suggested that many investors did
not believe this.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hottest American sales market ever, profits were
lower than expected from the mass-market brands sold under Chrysler
Corp. marques because higher rebates and other incentives were
required to keep people buying in the United States and because
unit sales outside North America fell 20.1 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Second-quarter operating profits for Chrysler, Plymouth, Dodge
and Jeep brands rose just 1.4 percent, to $1.36 billion compared
with $1.34 billion in the quarter a year earlier. Revenue for those
lines rose 9.6 percent, to $16.77 billion from $15.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Eaton, the other co-chairman, said sales continued
their sizzling pace this month and that sales of Chrysler's
minivans, which had seemed to be flagging, were picking up. ``We're
going to have a very strong July, headed by minivans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury Mercedes-Benz line fared better. Operating profits
for Mercedes and Smart jumped 17.8 percent, to $635 million, from
$539 million in the second quarter of last year. The tiny Smart car
remains unprofitable, but the gains came from rising Mercedes
sales, particularly high-profit sales of the Mercedes M-class sport
utility vehicle, built in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Operating profits from sales of DaimlerChrysler's commercial
vehicles dropped 1.2 percent, to $329 million from $333 million in
the second quarter of last year. Profits were hurt by the economic
crisis in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings from DaimlerChrysler's aerospace unit jumped 21.1
percent, to $195 million. The company plans to merge its aerospace
unit, known as Dasa, with the Spanish state aerospace company,
called Casa.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton said that the company had found many synergies since the
$36 billion deal combining the two automakers and that
DaimlerChrysler was on track to meet its goal of finding $1.4
billion in savings this year. Of the 1,200 separate projects
undertaken this year to combine the companies, 31 percent are
complete and 80 percent will be finished this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although executives expect further consolidation in the auto
industry, DaimlerChrysler is concentrating on making its own deal
work rather than shopping for other auto companies to buy. ``We are
not looking for any further acquisitions, except if something would
pop in front of us,'' Schrempp said.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the performance of DaimlerChrysler's stock since
the merger, there is still some work to be done. In Europe,
DaimlerChrysler's stock has risen 4.3 percent since the deal was
completed. In the United States, the company's stock price, which
is traded on the New York Stock Exchange, has fallen 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempp continued Thursday to campaign for DaimlerChrysler's
inclusion in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, a step that
would increase demand for its shares by index mutual funds. He
explained the stock's poor performance this way: ``Most analysts so
far have us on buy, but not sufficient people have bought us yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
