<SLUG> BC-TV-INTIMATE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INTIMATE UNIVERSE' BODY SERIES CONTINUES TO FASCINATE, TEACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Intimate Universe: The Human Body'' is aptly named. The
Peabody Award-winning documentary series about human life gets so
close to its subject that viewers may squirm right off the sofa,
though rarely will they see a TV series so informative and so
thoughtfully produced.
</P>
<P>
   The second half of the eight-hour ``Intimate Universe'' has its
North American premiere Sunday and Monday at 9 p.m. on The Learning
Channel. To catch people up, the first half of the BBC series,
which aired in April, will be rebroadcast Saturday from 8 p.m. to
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Part two encompasses three segments centering on the brain,
aging and death. A fourth segment looks at the amazing technology,
including endoscopic photography, ``time slice'' photography and
computer animation, that helped make the series what it is: a
fabulously engaging look at the processes that keep us alive and,
ultimately, facilitate our demise.
</P>
<P>
   The series smoothly toggles back and forth from extreme
close-ups of, say, a blood clot shutting down an artery to
stunningly illustrative camera work that makes complex scientific
material easy to grasp. A shot of synchronized swimmers, for
example, provides mesmerizing mimicry of the behavior of cells.
</P>
<P>
   The elements of part two are as full of fascinating information
as part one. For instance:
</P>
<P>
   _ When a neuron fires in the brain, the electrical impulse
travels at 250 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   _ Little of our bodies is actually more than 10 years old. Much
of it, including parts of the skeleton, is continually being
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   _ It takes about 200,000 frowns to etch a furrow in the
forehead.
</P>
<P>
   It's the soothingly avuncular approach of Dr. Robert Winston
that makes ``Intimate Universe'' so appealing. Winston, one of
Europe's leading infertility experts and a member of the British
House of Lords, treats his subject and his audience with enormous
respect, but without the cold aloofness of many documentary
narrators. Winston isn't a hired gun brought in to read a script.
He's a scientist with the engaging manner of a politician and the
on-camera ease of a seasoned news anchor. His curiosity is
infectious, his enthusiasm palpable.
</P>
<P>
   Even in episode seven, ``The End of Life,'' which airs Monday,
Winston's comfortable manner makes society's great taboo _ the
discussion of death _ eminently approachable. The episode follows
the last days of a man dying of cancer. Certainly it is unsettling,
but it is also sensitive and respectful _ no different from all the
other installments that make ``Intimate Universe'' one reason why
TV isn't such a vast wasteland after all.
</P>
<P>
   Intimate Universe: The Human Body. Second half of eight-hour
documentary miniseries about human life, hosted by Dr. Robert
Winston. Sunday and Monday at 9 p.m., The Learning Channel,
repeating Aug. 8 at 2 p.m. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
