<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Late race unfamiliar for Braves
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the pennants the Braves have won this decade, they
haven't done a whole lot of racing lately.
</P>
<P>
   The nip-and-tuck days of the early '90s are long gone. The
Braves haven't been in a pennant race since 1993, when they fought
the San Francisco Giants until the last day of the season to earn
their third playoff trip in a row. The next year, a strike
eliminated a potential stretch battle with the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   But they've got one now. A 7-8 record since the All-Star break,
an 11-3 record in that span by the New York Mets, a rash of
season-ending injuries for the Braves, and the National League East
is anything but secure.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves haven't been out of first place after July since
1994. At the end of July last year, they led by 14 games. The lead
was 6 1/2 in 1997, seven in 1996 and eight in 1995. Today, it's a
half-game over the Mets, with third-place Philadelphia coming to
town today for a three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being pushed,'' said pitcher Greg Maddux. ``It creates
excitement. Instead of waiting for the playoffs to get here, we're
actually trying to get in. Right now, I'm more excited coming to
the park. It's almost August and we're being chased.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been telling everybody for years now that nothing's
guaranteed and nothing's easy,'' he said. ``And I think for a few
years people may have believed that. This year, nothing's going to
be easy. So you take it a game at a time, a series at a time, try
and win your games. If you do that, the teams behind you can't
catch you. You can't worry about anything other than that day's
ball game. You can't afford to look too far ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The language might sound familiar to some of the Braves, but
only a few. Of the '99 Braves, only Glavine, John Smoltz, Otis
Nixon and Brian Hunter were here in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Just Glavine, Smoltz, Greg Maddux, Javy Lopez, Chipper Jones and
Ryan Klesko remain from the 1994 team. Jones was out that season
with his knee injury; Lopez is missing the rest of this season
because of his.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones said the circumstances aren't all bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen us pull together,'' Jones said. ``I think it's
helped our chemistry a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The year the Braves won it all, in 1995, they went 20-7 in July,
which matched an Atlanta franchise record for the most wins in a
month. Each of the last four seasons, they have clinched the
division with a couple of weeks to spare. This year, they'll have
to do some work to re-create that scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd always like to have a nice, comfortable cushion,''
Glavine said, ``but there again, there's always that argument,
assuming you get to the playoffs, 'Are you a better team because
you had a big lead all year long, or are you a better team because
you've been battle-tested all year long?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to think the more you're forced to play in tight ball
games and win your way into the playoffs, the more ready you are
for that atmosphere when you get there,'' he said. ``But it doesn't
hurt to have a lead and rest guys, either.''
</P>
<P>
   So, for now, the Braves are doing their best to think in terms
of today's game and this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try not to worry about it,'' Jones said. ``You go out and
play your game. You do the things that have made you successful and
gotten you to this point. ... So you go out there, you play
relaxed, one-ninth of the equation. You do your part, throw four
good at-bats up there, play good defense and let the chips fall
where they may. . . .
</P>
<P>
   `` If they match you win for win, you can't really help it,''
Jones said. ``But I feel like we have yet to play our best baseball
of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
