<SLUG> BC-ENTERPRISE-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ga., Mass) 
MARKET PLACE: SEC LOOKING AT FUNDS THAT BOOST INITIAL PERFORMANCE
WITH IPOs  
(rk) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ July was a tough month for shareholders of
Internet-stock funds, but not for the lucky few in the Enterprise
Internet fund.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny new fund has soared almost 65 percent since its
introduction on July 1, while other Internet funds have declined
about 10 percent. With just $18 million in assets, few investors
know about the fund, but that will most likely change once it
starts turning up on lists of top-performing funds.
</P>
<P>
   Smart stock picking? Perhaps. But even the fund's investment
adviser acknowledges that a good deal of the outsized gains have
come from what industry officials say is a common, though hard to
track, practice: Fund companies filling a small young fund with hot
initial public offerings that balloon its early performance record.
</P>
<P>
   Fund companies, which generate huge stock-trading commissions,
have enormous influence with the investment banks that underwrite
stock issues, and they wield it to grab allocations of offerings
that are sure to rise. There have been plenty of these issues this
year as Internet offerings have doubled or tripled on their first
trading days.
</P>
<P>
   But many industry officials say some fund companies misuse the
allocation of initial offerings to stuff a disproportionate share
of hot new issues into newer and smaller funds to sharply raise
returns and attract more money from investors.
</P>
<P>
   This practice is drawing increased scrutiny from the Securities
and Exchange Commission, which says improving the allocation of
initial offerings is one of the top compliance weaknesses the
mutual fund industry needs to address.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say initial offerings should be distributed
proportionally within fund families because the underwriters grant
them in return for trading and other business they get from the
funds _ costs ultimately borne by fund shareholders. Moreover,
lopsided allocations can lead to performance records for smaller
funds that, while technically true, are impossible to repeat and
give investors a misleading impression of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smaller the fund, the greater effect that hot IPO's could
have on its performance,'' said Douglas J. Scheidt, chief counsel
in the SEC's investment management division, which oversees the
mutual fund industry.
</P>
<P>
   Once the fund grows, it would need many more hot initial
offerings to have the same effect on performance, ``so investors
could be misled into believing that a small fund's great
performance could continue, when in fact that fund's ability to get
the same proportion of hot IPOs is far less realistic,'' Scheidt
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Enterprise Internet fund, which is managed by Fred
Alger Management, which oversees more than $12 billion in assets,
the company's chief executive, David D. Alger, said at least some
of the fund's hot performance could be attributed to initial
offerings. He said that was also probably true of another new fund
Alger manages, Enterprise Multi-Cap Growth, which has gained 70
percent since July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the slightest input of IPOs would make an impact on'' the
Internet fund, Alger said. ``Some funds you could never give enough
IPOs to get it up 60 percent a month.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the fund had received only its appropriate
allocation of new stock issues, which he said were doled out evenly
among various funds on a rotating basis. He added that he hoped no
one took the new fund's record as indicative of future performance.
``I don't want anyone to think that 60 percent a month is going to
continue,'' Alger said.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Ugolyn, chief executive of Enterprise Capital Management
in Atlanta, a unit of Mony Group Inc., the New York life insurer,
added that even though the Internet fund was small, having it run
by a much larger investment adviser has given it ``the opportunity
to participate in some well-known IPOs.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Lori Richards, director of the SEC's compliance
office, urged an audience of mutual-fund executives to look more
closely at how initial offerings are allocated within their fund
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen lots of problems in how fund groups allocate IPO
shares internally, and we've received complaints concerning the
allocation of hot IPOs,'' Ms. Richards said in a speech on June 10.
``Problems seem to range from the intentional to the sloppy. You
will want to review the allocations not only individually, but over
time, to  &UR; e &LR; nsure that they are consistent and fair.''
</P>
<P>
   SEC officials declined to say whether they were considering
taking action against any fund families for improper allocations of
initial offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's best-known enforcement action in this area came in
1995, when it settled a case against the Account Management Corp.,
a Boston investment adviser, after determining that the company,
among other things, had disproportionately allocated $218,460 in
profits from funneling initial offerings to a select group of
favored clients. The company, which paid a $100,000 fine, neither
admitted nor denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the agency settled a case with McKenzie Walker
Investment Management, of Greenbrae, Calif., after contending that
the firm misallocated shares of initial offerings to clients who
paid fees based on investment results over those who paid set fees.
McKenzie Walker agreed to pay a $100,000 fine and reimburse profits
of $261,000.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Barbash, the SEC's former director of investment
management and now a lawyer in private practice, said that legally,
allocations must be made within fund groups so they do not
advantage or disadvantage one fund over another. But getting more
specific than that raises some thorny issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, could a fund company legitimately withhold shares
of a hot initial offering from a deep-value fund _ one that invests
only in stocks with low price-to-earnings ratios _ if the initial
offering is of a high-flying Internet company? Or what if the fund
does not have the cash on hand to buy shares of an initial
offering?
</P>
<P>
   Most fund families already try to allocate initial offerings in
a fair manner, Barbash said. But, he said, ``history would suggest
that there are always some groups out there that have had an
inclination to allocate simply for performance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You are always going to have some industry members who play to
the edge,'' Barbash said.
</P>
</TEXT>
