<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves: No trading holdout Anderson
 &HT;    By Matt Winklejohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greenville, S.C. _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves acknowledged after
the first practice of training camp that the Washington Redskins
called to ask if holdout running back Jamal Anderson was available
to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins, who have three first-round draft choices next
yearl, are not alone in this regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called and other teams have called, and we've said we
don't want to trade Jamal,'' Reeves said. ``We wouldn't have been
where we were last year without Jamal. Jamal makes us as good as we
can be. We want Jamal here.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, three weeks ago David Ware, the Atlanta-based agent for
Barry Sanders, called Falcons officials offering to broker a
Sanders-for-Anderson trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons told Ware no thanks, partly because Sanders is 31.
Also, the Lions weren't likely to consider trading Sanders because
that would have cost them more than $7 million against the salary
cap.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Washington officials also inquired in Detroit about
whether the Lions would trade Sanders, who announced his retirement
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson probably isn't going to show up at training camp any
earlier than next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have said they will not negotiate with him or his
agent until he shows up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
