<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9119 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-COX     07-29 0303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons begin training camp
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greenville, S.C. _ With a change in perspective, it was possible
as the Falcons began training camp Thursday at Furman University to
consider their backfield half full rather than half empty.
</P>
<P>
   True, All-Pro Jamal Anderson wasn't there, as he remains holed
up and holding out in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   But Byron Hanspard was back in full gear for the first time
since tearing up his left knee last summer.
</P>
<P>
   That, and the sights and sounds unique to training camp were
enough to pick up the spirits of coach Dan Reeves, who began the
day handing out rings to returning members of last season's NFC
Championship team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to smell the grass and everything, you know the season is
coming,'' Reeves said. ``We miss Jamal, but I'll tell you what: if
Byron gets back to 100 percent of where he was . . . we'll have a
very good running game.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who is seeking a new contract, was indeed missed.
Several running backs had a hard time hanging onto the football.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was too hot.
</P>
<P>
   It was 98 degrees when the team took the field. After lightning
and rain forced the team under cover for 20 minutes, the
temperature dropped to the mid-80s.
</P>
<P>
   Hanspard, who averaged 6.3 yards as a rookie in `97 when he had
three of the 12 longest runs in franchise history, will be back out
there today, as two practices are scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knee feels strong,'' he said. ``I've never had any doubts,
but it was a matter of getting out here and getting that first
lick, taking that first hit.''
</P>
<P>
   That came Thursday when defensive end Chuck Smith cracked him,
and ripped the ball out of Hanspard's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
