<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING REBELLION, HOUSE LEADERS BACK AWAY FROM VOTE ON HEALTH
CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Republican leadership, facing another
rebellion from some moderate and conservative Republicans, backed
away from plans to consider legislation on managed health care next
week, with Speaker Dennis Hastert conceding Thursday that a vote
before the August recess is now unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to dispense with a politically potent issue that
divides his party, Hastert, R-Ill., earlier this week moved to
bypass the normal committee process and put a senior group of
Republicans in charge of writing a modified version of the Senate's
managed care bill to bring to the floor for a vote next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday some House Republicans rebelled and reached out to
House Democratic leaders on the health issue. Rep. Greg Ganske,
R-Iowa, who is a plastic surgeon, accused Republican leaders of
``going back to the old days of stacking the deck against anything
that doesn't happen to fit in to the special interests of insurers
and HMOs.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., a dentist who is usually a
staunch conservative, said he would demand a comprehensive health
care bill. ``Not frosting,'' he said, ``it's got to be the whole
cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood said the Senate Republicans' bill, which passed on a
near party line vote earlier this month, ``isn't worth the paper
it's written on.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from a closed-door party caucus Thursday morning,
Hastert did not completely rule out a House vote next week, but
sought to dampen expectations that it would happen. ``We're working
on it,'' he said. But then he described the chances of a vote next
week as about as likely as a ``70-yard field goal'' in a football
game.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the afternoon, Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, the House
majority leader, said the likelihood of the issue coming to the
floor before the fall was ``diminishing.'' But, he added, ``we
haven't given up on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's struggle on health care was just another sign of the
difficulty he has had running the House with a majority so small
that only a five-vote swing can doom legislation. And as Congress
moves toward the busiest time of the year, each day brings new
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, House Republican leaders succeeded in passing their
$792 billion tax cut, but only after making concessions to both
moderates and conservatives. And House leaders are also struggling
to pass spending bills that require deep cuts in domestic spending.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Republicans maintained party unity on managed
care despite a veto threat from President Clinton, passing a bill
that provided some protections for patients but complied with their
party's desire for only limited regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Senate bill's provisions on emotional issues like
access to emergency rooms outside a managed-care network, as well
as access to specialists and obstetrician-gynecologists, applied
only to the 48 million people in self-financed health plans usually
offered by large employers not regulated by states.
</P>
<P>
   But such people are rarely in health maintenance organizations
with the kinds of strict ``gatekeeper'' arrangements that have led
to many consumer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders favor a limited approach to health care
regulation. But Ganske, Norwood and another doctor _ Rep. Tom
Coburn of Oklahoma _ are leading a group of 20 to 60 Republicans
who are more sympathetic to the Democrats' approach, which seeks to
provide stronger protections for all 161 million Americans covered
by private health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   An intense competition was under way Thursday for their
allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   Several senior Republicans, under Hastert's instructions, were
trying to write a bill that could gain enough Republican votes to
pass. One congressman close to the negotiations said the
Republicans were seeking to broaden the protections for all those
with private insurance. They were also seeking to create a stronger
independent appeals process than the one contained in the Senate
bill for people who want to contest an HMO's decision to deny care.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior Republican aide said it was turning out to be
extremely difficult to calibrate the bill to win enough votes. ``In
many cases it's a zero sum game,'' he said. ``In many cases some
won't vote for the bill if X is in there and some will only vote
for the bill if X is in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey said that the issue of whether to expand the right to sue
a managed care provider was particularly thorny. In the Senate,
Republicans turned back an attempt by Democrats to expand the right
to sue health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have virtually no room to maneuver. They managed
to eke out passage of a managed care bill by a 216-210 vote last
year. But now there are five fewer Republicans, making the math
impossible unless the bill is changed to accommodate some
dissidents. And several Republicans who voted for the bill last
year insist they will not support a similar measure this year.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly unusual move, Ganske met Thursday with Rep. Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo., the House Minority leader, in search of a
bipartisan compromise. It was their second meeting in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Such a cross-party appeal to the Democratic leader was almost
without precedent in this partisan year. Democrats are hoping to
win back the House in the next election and both parties are
putting a premium on party unity.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Republican doctors Thursday, Gephardt said, ``I
respect deeply their sincerity. They have practiced medicine or
dentistry or nursing and they understand these issues from their
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can find a way to get a bipartisan bill that we can
pass, we are going to try to pass it.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood was negotiating with Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., who is
the lead sponsor of the Democrats' managed care bill, and aides to
both men indicated that they were extremely close to an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   John E. Stone, a spokesman for Norwood, said only small issues
remained, adding that Norwood was checking back with Republicans
who are supporting him on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Republicans control the floor, Democrats can force
a bill to a vote through a special petition. Such a petition effort
rarely succeeds because supporting one is viewed as an act of
disloyalty to the majority party. So far 181 Democrats have signed
a petition on health care: no Republicans have signed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
