<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-TRADE-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH RETALIATE AGAINST DUTIES ON FOIE GRAS AND SHALLOTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Belgium, Denmark, Germany, Italy, Ga.)   By CRAIG R. WHITNEY  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Hit the French in the breadbasket, and they strike back.
Gallic resentment and retaliation ran rampant this week after the
United States and Canada levied customs duties of 100 percent on
imports of foie gras, Roquefort cheese, mustard and even shallots
in protest against the European ban on hormone-treated North
American beef.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 farmers in southwestern France occupied a McDonald's
restaurant on Tuesday in Auch, slapping posters on the windows that
said, ``No hormones in foie gras country.'' The franchisee, and
most of the beef it serves, are French, an employee in Auch said.
In any case, the occupation was over Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But a pancake restaurant in Dijon, Burgundy, informed its
customers that it would slap a 400 percent duty on Coca-Cola.
Although Coca-Cola is not imported from the United States but
formulated and bottled in France by French subsidiaries of the
parent company, the restaurant, Creperie Domino, charges 50 francs,
more than $8, a bottle, instead of 10 francs.
</P>
<P>
   The owner, Luc Olivier, described the move as a gesture of
solidarity with French producers affected by the American tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   France would seek compensation for its farmers from the European
Union in Brussels, Belgium, the Agriculture Minister Jean Glavany
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Canada imposed the sanctions because the
European Union has refused to lift its ban on beef treated with
hormones, even though the World Trade Organization in Geneva agreed
with the North Americans that the ban was more protectionism than
consumer protection and approved $116.8 million in sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers in Brittany, which exported 4,500 tons of shallots to
the United States last year, may be among the first to claim
damages. An exporter, Pascal Jaouen, said the wholesale price would
rise, from $1 a pound to $1.70, with the tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This measure could lead to more production of shallots in the
United States, which raises very few of them now,'' Jaouen said.
</P>
<P>
   Danish hams, Italian tomatoes and German soups are also on the
American list, which includes handbags, linens and cashmere among
luxury items that are the focus in another trans-Atlantic trade
dispute over European protection for banana imports from former
colonies.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that would actually lead Europeans to buy
hormone-treated beef if the European Union agreed to let in any of
it is unknown. The French daily Le Monde quoted Peter Scher, the
U.S. deputy trade representative, as saying the United States was
willing to work out labeling agreements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
