<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9130 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SEC-HOLTZ-COX     07-29 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-HOLTZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holtz game to rebuild Gamecocks
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Birmingham _ It was fitting that the last coach to speak during
the 1999 SEC Football Kickoff was South Carolina's Lou Holtz.
Nobody in his right mind would want to follow his act.
</P>
<P>
   When Holtz entered the Sheraton Hotel at 11:20 a.m. Thursday, a
dozen television cameras were waiting for him at the top of the
escalator. ``I was wondering what all those people had found out
about me and figured that I was probably in trouble,'' said Holtz,
who was whisked away into an interview room before the mob could
descend upon him. ``Then I realized it. This is the SEC.''
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a reception for a man who is taking over a program
that went 1-10 last season and was picked to finish fifth this
season by the media in the rugged SEC East. But what Holtz has is
something that South Carolina has lacked in its long but uneventful
football history _ star power. ``Lou Holtz is going to be good for
South Carolina, and he's going to be very good for the SEC,'' said
Mississippi State coach Jackie Sherrill, who as coach at Texas A&AMP;M
once trounced Holtz and Notre Dame in the Cotton Bowl. ``We haven't
seen too many guys like him around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz won a national championship at Notre Dame in 1988,
performed magic tricks on ``The Tonight Show'' with Johnny Carson
and gets paid what is a year's salary for some just to give a
45-minute motivational speech.
</P>
<P>
   If there were any doubters before, Thursday's events proved that
Holtz is different.
</P>
<P>
   His address was one part prayer meeting, one part pep rally and
one part stand-up comedy routine. South Carolina has won just a
single bowl game in its history, but the 61-year-old Holtz is
convinced he can win in Columbia _ maybe not immediately, but soon.
``You might have noticed that I am not a young man,'' Holtz said.
``I don't have time for any eight-year rebuilding plan. But if I
didn't believe we could win at South Carolina, I wouldn't have
taken the job.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Holtz didn't want to take the job and turned it down on
three separate occasions. It took the insistence of his wife, Beth,
to return him to the sidelines Beth Holtz has been battling throat
cancer for more than a year, and Holtz did not want to jump back
into the profession while she was still in danger. Holtz reported
Thursday that his wife is doing fine and that the prognosis for her
is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is very special,'' he said. ``I don't pray for her; I pray
to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Holtz conceded that he does not have enough players to contend
with Tennessee, Florida and Georgia for the SEC East championship.
But with each concession he made to the shortcomings of the
program, Holtz would launch into an extended pep talk about how the
obstacles could be overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at all at the schedule we play'' _ Tennessee, Florida
and Clemson are the last three games _ ``and the lack of winning
tradition we have and you ask, 'How can we win?' `` Holtz said. ``I
have believed all my life that there is an answer for every problem
that you face. You just have to go out and find it. I never
promised South Carolina we were going to win. I just promised them
that we wouldn't forfeit.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everything has been positive since Holtz arrived at
South Carolina. Last week, he officially dismissed running back
Troy Hambrick, the team's leading rusher the past two seasons.
Hambrick had sat out spring practice in an attempt to improve his
academic situation. Hambrick regained his eligibility but later was
found guilty of violating an undisclosed team rule. Last Friday,
Holtz told Hambrick he was through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, it's a priviledge to play at a place like South
Carolina, not a right,'' Holtz said. ``If we're going to be
successful at South Carolina, we have to change. Everybody has to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
