A9134 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SEC-NOTES-COX     07-29 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vols picked to be champs;
 &HT;    Carter chosen best QB
 &HT;    By Stan Arey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Birmingham _ Tennessee was picked Thursday to repeat as
Southeastern Conference champion by the writers and sportscasters
at the SEC's annual football kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, a perennial threat, finished a distant second.
</P>
<P>
   The preseason picks in the Eastern division of the conference
are, Tennessee, Florida, Georgia, Kentucky, South Carolina and
Vanderbilt. In the West, they are Arkansas, Alabama, Ole Miss,
Mississippi State, LSU and Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   In the voting for the preseason All-SEC offensive and defensive
teams, Florida placed only receiver Travis Taylor and center Zac
Zedalis, while Tennessee had seven on the two squads.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia sophomore Quincy Carter, last season's SEC freshman of
the year, was chosen over Tennessee's Tee Martin as the first-team
quarterback and Bulldog senior Orantes Grant was chosen as a
first-team linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Quotable
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky coach Hal Mumme on why he chooses to go for it on
fourth-and-long so often: ``Dementia, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State coach Jackie Sherrill on the media: ``We've
been through the spring, the summer, and now it's talking time.
It's up to all you writers to interpret what all the coaches say.
But I don't know of any coach who'll tell you the truth about their
team, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Mumme on senior linebacker Jeff Snedegar: ``He's the epitome of
a linebacker. We had to institute a no-contact rule in practice
because he was hurting so many people. I hesitated bringing him
here today because he only knows three words and none of them are
printable.''
</P>
<P>
   Snedegar on why he chose Kentucky over Ohio State and Michigan:
``Kentucky people are nice. Everyone else was rude.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-2, 243-pounder said he thinks that Kentucky's defense will
be the stronger part of the team this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can hold people to somewhere between 14 and 21 points, I
think we'll win. If it gets much over 21, we'll have a hard time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats allowed 38 points per game two years ago and 30
points last season.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander for Heisman
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the University of Alabama has decided to
push one of its players for the Heisman. Tailback Shaun Alexander
is the chosen one.
</P>
<P>
   The talented senior said, ``If I win it, I'll win it for Bart
Starr and Joe Namath and Cornelius Bennett and some of the other
great Alabama players who never got a chance at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zow's the man at Bama
</P>
<P>
   Alabama coach Mike DuBose says that, contrary to popular belief,
there is no question about who the quarterback is in Tuscaloosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no quarterback controversy,'' DuBose said. ``Andrew
Zow is the starter, and Tyler Watts will get a chance to play. ``
</P>
<P>
   Life after Couch
</P>
<P>
   Mumme has installed Valdosta's Dusty Bonner as the quarterback
who will follow NFL No. 1 draftee Tim Couch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dusty has an unflappable personality and he'll have no trouble
following Couch,'' Mumme said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a freshman, we sent him in to throw a pass on a
fourth-and-long on a fake punt, and he completed it for a long
gain. Most freshmen's eyes would have gotten big as saucers, but
not his.''
</P>
<P>
   Game times
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia-South Carolina game Sept. 11 in Athens will be
televised by ESPN2 with kickoff set for 5 p.m. and Georgia's Nov.
27 game at Georgia Tech has also been scheduled for television with
a 1 p.m. kickoff on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
