<HEADER>
A9135 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SRILANKA-ASSASSINATE-     07-29 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SRILANKA-ASSASSINATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LEADING SRI LANKAN MODERATE IS KILLED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and locator map are being sent to NYT photo and
graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(yn) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ A leading Sri Lankan moderate who had sought
a peaceful solution to the violent ethnic conflict that has raged
for 16 years was killed Thursday in the Sri Lankan capital by a
suicide bomber.
</P>
<P>
   The politician, Neelan Tiruchelvam, 55, had risked death for
years pursuing a negotiated or legislated settlement of the strife
between the mainly Buddhist ethnic Sinhalese majority and the Hindu
Tamil minority in Sri Lanka, off the southern tip of India.
</P>
<P>
   ``He represented the essence of peace, sanity, good will _ all
the abiding human values,'' said Savitri Goonefekere, a law
professor who had taught Tiruchelvam. ``The horror of it is that
such horrible violence has killed such a gentle man.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no one claimed responsibility for the killing in
Colombo, the capital, the police blamed guerrillas of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, who have been fighting for an
independent homeland for the Tamils in a conflict that has left
more than 50,000 dead.
</P>
<P>
   Tiruchelvam, a Tamil, favored a peaceful resolution that would
provide Tamils a share of power and autonomy within a united Sri
Lanka, an idea that the guerrillas rejected. As a member of
Parliament and a Harvard-educated legal scholar, he had helped
draft a package of constitutional changes that President Chandrika
Kumaratunga, a Sinhalese, was expected to introduce in a month or
two.
</P>
<P>
   The disaffection of the Tamil minority is rooted in decades of
discrimination by the Sinhalese majority. Tiruchelvam had been a
critic of successive governments for their obstinacy in dealing
with Tamil grievances. But he always promoted a resolution through
peaceful negotiations and legal reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was probably the most articulate and renowned spokesperson
for moderate Tamil opinion,'' said P. Saravanamuttu, executive
director of the Center for Policy Alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, India and the United Nations condemned his
assassination. The U.N. secretary general, Kofi Annan, called it
``an act of terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiruchelvam, who led the International Center for Ethnic Studies
in Colombo, was often consulted by visiting journalists, diplomats
and scholars. And he well knew that his temperate views made him a
target for separatist rebels, who have used assassination in the
past to kill political leaders in their way. But he shrugged off
danger in a fatalistic good-humored way.
</P>
<P>
   The string of killings is impossible to ignore. The Liberation
Tigers were accused last year of killing two mayors of Jaffna who
belonged to Tiruchelvam's party, the Tamil United Liberation Front.
They were also accused of lobbing a grenade in 1997 that killed a
member of Parliament, also from the Tamil United Liberation Front.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel group is also widely believed to have dispatched the
suicide bombers who killed President Ranasinghe Premadasa in 1993
and Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi of India in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neelan knew that he was working against tremendous odds, and
he was quite aware of the risks, but he always believed one has to
take risks and work toward broader goals,'' said Jayadeva Uyangoda,
a professor of political science at the University of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Tiruchelvam left his home in an exclusive area
of the city, Cinnamon Gardens, Thursday morning, heading for his
office, when a suicide bomber leaped from the side seat of a
motorcycle and set off the deadly explosion a short walk from the
prime minister's house.
</P>
<P>
   The bomber's body blew apart, and Tiruchelvam's mutilated body
slumped over in the back seat of his Nissan. His driver and
bodyguard were seriously wounded. The motorcycle driver, who is
thought to have been wounded, escaped.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, human rights advocates and scholars gathered at
Tiruchelvam's home to comfort his wife, Sithie, and their son,
Mithran, 24. Their other son, Nirtuganan, 26, had not reached
Colombo.
</P>
<P>
   Jayampathy Wickramaratne, a lawyer on the committee for the
proposed constitutional changes, said Tiruchelvam had been eager to
see the president offer the plan in Parliament and was optimistic
that the opposition, the United National Party, would be forced to
support it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
