<SLUG> BC-BALKAN-SUMMIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT HEARS CHEERS,JEERS IN BALKANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia _ As President Clinton and other world leaders
headed here in search of a durable peace in the Balkans, Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright was confronted by the region's enduring
tensions during a visit to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who stopped Thursday in the Kosovar capital, Pristina,
on her way to the gathering in Sarajevo, was jeered by a crowd of
Serbs as her motorcade visited a monastery. But earlier, in a
speech to ethnic Albanians, she was cheered amid chants of
``U.S.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright, the highest ranking U.S. official to visit Kosovo,
brought a message of restraint and reconciliation, telling a crowd
of ethnic Albanians, ``democracy cannot be built on revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   While Albright held meetings with political leaders, a shot was
fired in the street outside.
</P>
<P>
   In Sarajevo, members of the European Union held preliminary
meetings with leaders of the region to press a message of inclusion
should the nations end differences that have fueled years of ethnic
war.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's summit, first envisioned by Clinton and German
Chancellor Gerhardt Schroeder, was designed to launch the Balkan
Stability Pact, an outline for rebuilding the southeastern corner
of Europe much like the Marshall Plan put western Europe back on
its feet following World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The Balkans are one of Europe's poorest, least-stable and most
war-torn regions.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton arrives in Sarajevo after an overnight stay at
Aviano air base in Italy, he is scheduled to meet with the Bosnian,
Croatian and Muslim members of Bosnia's joint presidency. Later,
before the summit formally opens, Clinton is scheduled to meet
privately with the prime ministers of Bosnia's two states, Slovakia
and Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   The summit is seen as a first step to putting the Balkans
states, Albania, Bosnia, Bulgaria, Croatia, Slovenia, Macedonia and
Romania on the road toward economic, political and security
integration with the rest of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   During the three-hour summit, most of which will be conducted
behind closed doors, regional leaders will present their plans for
political and economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The commitments will be used by the European Union and the
United States in determining whether and how quickly the Balkan
nations are admitted as members of the E.U., NATO and the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Sarajevo was picked by European Union planners as the summit
site for its symbolic value. Here, in 1914, the assassination of
the heir to the Austrian throne triggered World War I. In the early
1990s, the city was scene of some of the fiercest fighting of the
Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   Today, four years after the Croats, Muslims and Bosnian Serbs
traded fire in the streets, Sarajevo has yet to return to normal.
Many buildings bear scars of the conflict _ pock-marks from
bullets, walls sheared off by artillery shelling, and piles of
rubble from mortar fire.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment runs at about 50 percent, according to the United
Nations, largely because of delays in funding for privatization
programs. The largest and steadiest supplier of jobs are the UN
agencies overseeing Bosnian reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our meeting (in Sarajevo) I think symbolizes our shared hope
for the region,'' said Sandy Berger, the president's national
security adviser. ``We're ending the 20th century in Sarajevo with
the nations of Europe and North America coming together to talk
about how to build a peaceful region.''
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously absent from the session will be Yugoslavian
President Slobodan Milosevic, an indicted war criminal who was not
invited, largely to re-emphasize to his Serb followers that until
he is driven from office, Yugoslavia will remain cut off.
</P>
<P>
   During the summit and in meetings later with regional reporters,
Clinton will press his case against Milosevic. He plans to draw
distinctions between the Milosevic government and the Serbian
people and renew his insistence that Yugoslavia receive only
humanitarian aid _ mostly food and medicine _ until a new
government is installed in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message (to the Serbs) will be simple: with Milosevic, you
are excluded and isolated from the rest of Europe,'' Berger said.
``With a government committed to democratic reforms and
international cooperation, we are prepared to help bring Serbia
into the European mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Leery of funding any project that might aid the Milosevic
government, the U.S. has balked at a proposal by the European Union
to help rebuild Serbia's energy infrastructure, which was damaged
during the 79-day air war.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
