<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV OPPOSITION LEADER BALKS AT CHALLENGING MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Dragoslav Avramovic is sorely tempted to
heed the call, but he's nearly 80 and has serious kidney troubles,
and he's not really sure the moment is ripe.
</P>
<P>
   Avramovic, a frail, unlikely looking technocrat, is the most
popular opposition figure in Yugoslavia, revered for beating back
hyperinflation in 1994. The Clinton administration and the
foundering Alliance for Change here are pushing him to become the
prime minister of Serbia, the overwhelming power base in
Yugoslavia, and thereby take a leading role in the effort to oust
Slobodan Milosevic from the presidency of the Yugoslav federation.
</P>
<P>
   But Avramovic, who speaks modestly but enjoys the spotlight,
really is not convinced, he said in an interview on Wednesday, just
before leaving on Thursday for Sarajevo, to attend a Balkan summit
conference as the representative of the Serbian political
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm conscious of the pressure, and every morning I have a
serious self-examination about whether to get in deeper and
deeper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The country badly wants change, but not revolution, he said, and
the opposition ``has to have a theory about how it's going to work
out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't move from day to day without some idea of how
it's going to work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance for Change, to which Avramovic belongs, and its
rival, the Serbian Renewal Movement, which is led by Vuk Draskovic,
both suggest the naming of a transitional government that they hope
Milosevic will be forced to accept by popular pressure. That
government is supposed to bring Yugoslavia back to the world's good
graces and organize new elections, while Milosevic is supposed to
resign.
</P>
<P>
   A key member of the alliance, Vuk Obradovic, a former general,
has openly pushed Avramovic to accept the leadership, as has the
alliance coordinator, Vladan Batic. Avramovic, who will be 80 in
October, is the least controversial possibility, with the broadest
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would agree to serve, Avramovic sighed.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, will there be a transitional government?'' he said.
``How will it take place?'' He continued, ``There's a theory that
it will end up with a general strike, with all these people in the
streets, but that's not clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, he said, ``I'm not a young man, my health is not the
best, and while I'll do what I can, I naturally have some
reluctance to take on something with such demands.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is his wife, Marija, ``who thinks whatever I do
is wrong,'' he said. ``My wife says her whole life has been
centered around me and public affairs,'' he continued, ``and it's
high time to have some family life.''
</P>
<P>
   The country demands and needs a change of leadership, he says.
``The pressure comes from the feeling that there is no prospect for
improvement now, for citizens or for their children,'' he said.
``The prevailing uneasiness and demonstrations reflect this lack of
perspective, and people in the streets reflect this pessimism and
need for change.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, he said, Milosevic has been in power 10 years, ``and
there is an internal fatigue of a sort and a lack of imagination.''
While Milosevic ``must feel it's not all his fault and the world
illegitimately pushed him into a corner over Kosovo,'' Avramovic
said, ``the government should not have gotten into a situation
where the whole world is our enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Avramovic, a socialist and lawyer who spent more than 20 years
working with the World Bank, is disarming but shrewd. He says he
wants to do no harm to the opposition, which he thinks is improving
in its ability to work together. But he also has a healthy regard
for the tactical strength of Milosevic and his ability to keep a
tightly constrained economy afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Avramovic served Milosevic from 1993 to 1996, mostly as governor
of the central bank, probably saving the regime by ending
hyperinflation.
</P>
<P>
   His actions made him wildly popular. By ordering the exchange of
12 million old dinars for one new dinar equal to the German mark,
he stabilized prices, wages and pensions, expanded the economy and
gave the poor, old and working class not only hope, but sustenance.
</P>
<P>
   He was dismissed in May 1996 after calling for the government to
resign after a dispute over monetary and fiscal policy, when he
urged curbs on renewed inflation and refused to hand out loans
indiscriminately. His popularity increased, and he is known as Deda
Avram, or Grandpa Avram.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed to lead the list of opposition candidates in the 1996
federal and local elections, and the list of the coalition Zajedno
itself bore his name, as the list of the ruling coalition bore the
name of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But shortly before the elections, Avramovic pulled out and
insisted on taking his name off even the collective list. Many of
the opposition were hurt and furious; Avramovic said simply that
his health was too poor, but there were rumors, which he denies,
that he was somehow blackmailed.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he talked about the decision, as he has rarely done.
His health was indeed poor, he said; while he is off dialysis now,
he was then having it three times a week, and his blood pressure
was too high. But he also said he felt there were too many
divisions within Zajedno, and that he ``was pushed into deciding
who would get what post, which was not my job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a politician by training or by instinct,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And last, ``the coalition was moving too much to the right for
my taste,'' both economically and politically, with too much of a
nationalist tinge, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationalism continues to disturb him, especially as the world
wants ``a non-domineering nation in Yugoslavia.'' He thinks Kosovo
was a disaster and could have been kept within Yugoslavia had
Milosevic agreed to make it a federal republic, instead of removing
all its autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   The Milosevic government is not yet printing money, he said, and
while there is a deep recession, basic commodities and food are
probably adequate for the winter and at relatively stable prices.
</P>
<P>
   But electricity is another matter. Many Yugoslavs heat with
electricity, and the distribution system and the refineries were
badly damaged by NATO bombs. Some government ministers say they
think that supplies will be one-third less than last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can import electricity, will we have the hard currency
for it, and if we get it, can we transmit it?'' Avramovic said.
``Really, this is the main threat to the regime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
