<HEADER>
A9139 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-JETTA-ART-     07-29 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-JETTA-ART-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLKSWAGEN JETTA: A WORKHORSE ADDS PUNCH AND CURVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1)  
 (af)  
 By LEONARD M. APCAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sassy New Beetle has become a highly recognizable symbol of
Volkswagen's resurgence in the United States, but the real
workhorse in the showroom has been the company's best seller _ the
less retro, more roomy Jetta sedan.
</P>
<P>
   The American small-car market has been dominated by Japanese
auto makers who have churned out sturdy, sporty models year after
year. Volkswagen, after a decade of dwindling sales and quality
problems, has undergone something of a renaissance lately by
re-energizing its styling with fresh, curvaceous lines, refocusing
its advertisements to attract young buyers and recalculating how it
dresses up its cars.
</P>
<P>
   VW had pretty much been an also-ran to the coolly efficient
Honda Civic, one of the best-selling small cars, and other foreign
entries. VW was also hurt by a reputation for slipshod quality,
though it seems to have made some solid gains on that score lately.
</P>
<P>
   This year, on the heels of New Beetlemania and a midsized Passat
that got plenty of praise from most car critics, VW is offering a
restyled Jetta, the four-door-with-a-trunk based on its hatchback
sibling, the Golf. With the Jetta, VW is trying to take on the
pint-sized competition by offering a more spirited car under the
hood with a lot of standard features and people-pleasing details
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at $17,325, compared with $13,200 for the lowest-priced
Civic DX sedan or $15,245 for the best-selling Civic LX version, VW
is boldly suggesting that although these cars are about the same
size, more money buys a lot more car in the Jetta.
</P>
<P>
   This was no small gamble for VW, because so many buyers in this
market make up their minds based on reputation and value, two
categories in which the Japanese, especially Honda, have excelled.
But so far, the strategy is paying off: sales of the new Jetta are
up 26 percent over last year while sales of Civic sedans are off a
bit this year.
</P>
<P>
   In a test of both the Jetta GL, the least-costly version, and a
Honda Civic sedan, I found that while you quickly sense the Jetta's
power and acceleration, its handling was not as proficient as the
Honda's. The Jetta leaned slightly but noticeably in turns, and the
engine and suspension produced a tad more road noise and a harsher
ride than that of the smoothly competent Civic.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jetta stood out in two aspects. One is its delightful
styling. Big, bold wheel openings play off a smooth, arcing roof
that provides a styling touchstone for all VW models and echoes
through to the arched eyebrow over the instrument cluster.
</P>
<P>
   I loved the way the top half of the adjustable steering wheel,
like the bigger Passat's, lined up neatly with the curve of the
dash in front of me. And the gauges, backlit with neon blue and
highlighted with bright red needles, finished off an eye-catching,
sporty cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   The other plus is that the product planners have done their
homework. They have studied the Civic and other popular small cars
feature by feature and either matched the competition or gone them
one better.
</P>
<P>
   The stripped-down Jetta GL comes with many features that other
auto makers put only on higher-line models. It has
air-conditioning, power locks, a compact disk player and a keyless
locking system. Honda Civics offer these features, but only on the
more expensive LX and EX versions.
</P>
<P>
   In the safety area, VW has two front air bags and two side air
bags in both front seats. The Civic has two front bags, none on the
side. On the Jetta, anti-lock brakes are standard; the Civic
includes this safety feature only on its top-of-the-line EX, which
starts at $17,145 with a manual transmission.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Jetta has three adjustable head restraints in its rear
seat, with lap-and-shoulder belts for three passengers, too. The
Civic has two built-in headrests and lap-and-shoulder belts; there
is only a lap belt for the center passenger.
</P>
<P>
   The Civic is a larger car, with a wheelbase four inches longer
and an overall length three inches beyond the Jetta's. The
difference is seen in the Civic's leg room, which is slightly
better, both front and rear, though VW improved the Jetta's leg
space this year by an inch over the previous model.
</P>
<P>
   The Jetta has the larger trunk _ though neither could swallow my
bag of golf clubs. For that, I used the folding rear seat to stow
them lengthwise. Both the Civic and the Jetta have lockable,
folding, two-piece rear seat backs in 60/40 splits.
</P>
<P>
   Smartly, though, VW has placed the locks for the seat backs near
the passenger doors on both sides of the seat; Honda's one lock is
in the center, requiring you to get in the seat and turn around to
unlock it.
</P>
<P>
   Up front, the Jetta is powered by a 2-liter four-cylinder engine
with a cast-iron block and two valves in each cylinder. Its 115
horsepower is plentiful, but what is truly impressive is its
considerable torque at modest speeds. But it does not do much for
fuel economy. With a five-speed manual gearbox, the Jetta registers
a so-so mileage rating of 24 city and 31 highway; the rating is
22/28 with a four-speed automatic.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, VW added a turbo-charged, direct-injection
diesel to its Jetta line. The 2-liter engine gets a whopping 42/49
miles a gallon; prices start at $18,520.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Civic's leanly efficient base engine _ a
1.6-liter, aluminum-block four-cylinder _ produces 106 horses and
manages a thrifty 32/37 miles a gallon with a five-speed manual
(28/35 with a four-speed automatic). This is the first gasoline
power plant to meet California's tough low-emission standard.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Jetta and the Civic offer bigger engines on more
expensive versions. VW has a top-of-the-line GLX with a 2.8-liter,
174 horsepower V6. The Honda Civic EX uses Honda's
variable-valve-timing technology for a more efficient, cleaner
engine that produces 127 horsepower from a 1.6-liter, four-cylinder
power plant. The V6 Jettas begin at more than $20,000; fully
loaded, they exceed _ gulp _ $24,000.
</P>
<P>
   While the Jetta struck me as a very well conceived car, I did
catch a few goofs. One was that the neatly adjustable cup holders
that pop out of the dash obstruct access to a storage bin and the
driver's view of the top of the stereo. And while the sun visors
include lighted vanity mirrors for both front occupants, the
mirrors are covered by lids that, when you flip them up, block the
light embedded in the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   And one final annoyance. The windshield wipers kept noisily
slapping the body of the car. Was this bad adjustment or a Janis
Joplin retro touch?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK A small car with some big-car touches but a
not-so-trim price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
