<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-JOBS-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNAUTHORIZED DAYS TO REMEMBER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Maine, Md., N.Y., Ohio)   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)People may use terms like truancy and playing hooky.
But as the mail indicates, sometimes a little unauthorized time off
from work can lift the spirit and refresh the soul _ if you don't
get caught.(end italics)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One summer Friday, when he was Philadelphia bureau chief for The
Associated Press, George Zucker decided to spend a day at the race
track. ``If there's any emergency, call the clubhouse,'' he told
his deputy. ``The maitre d' has a telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, writes Zucker, who is now retired and lives in
Haverford, Pa., ``just as I was getting down to some serious
losing, the maitre d' came to the table and said my office was on
the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   The caller was the deputy. ``New York needs to talk to you right
away,'' he said. ``I told them you were on the road, and I would
try to track you down.''
</P>
<P>
   Zucker writes: ``Public phones weren't available during racing
hours, so the track's public relations guy said I could use the one
in his office. He showed me to his desk and closed the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as my boss came on the line, the stentorian voice of the
track announcer boomed from an office speaker: `The horses for the
fifth race are now entering the track!''' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Having found our dream house in another state, my wife and I
considered ourselves fortunate to find jobs in the same company,''
writes Will Hall, a scientist who is now retired and living in
Springvale, Maine. She was a secretary to a vice president; he was
a research supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   But they soon found their workplace unfriendly. ``Driving to
work one morning, we joked about playing truant until we thought of
a way we could work it,'' Hall writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found a phone, and I called my office to say that we were
terribly ill, perhaps from the slightly odd-tasting fried shrimp
we'd had for dinner. Then we drove to Atlantic City, where we saw a
couple of shows, enjoyed some good food and drinks and very
carefully avoided getting too much sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several days later, as we were driving to work, we were struck
by the idea of trying it again; but we thought better of it and
determined that we had better find new jobs. Still, it would have
been fun to call in sick again and tell them we had finished the
fried shrimp.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One day, Kathy Gambrell of Washington decided to award herself a
day off from her job as an office manager for a doctor and to pay a
visit to Baltimore's Inner Harbor. So she called her boss and said
she was caring for a sick relative.
</P>
<P>
   The boss said that since she had to go to an all-day meeting
anyhow, it was OK for Ms. Gambrell to miss work.
</P>
<P>
   So Ms. Gambrell wasted no time boarding an Amtrak train for
Baltimore. ``And who should get on the same train, sitting two
seats in front of me on the Metroliner?'' Ms. Gambrell writes. ``My
boss, headed to an all-day conference in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never said whether she saw me or not, though I assume she
did. I was wearing shorts, a T-shirt and sandals and did not
exactly have an elderly relative in tow.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson: ``Always find out where your boss is going to be and
be somewhere else.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1969, Martin Wakesberg, now of Burnt Hills,
N.Y., was 20 years old and working at his first full-time summer
job, as a file clerk for a scrap metal company in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scheduled to work July and August with no time off, as
my raison d'etre was to fill in for the regular employees who would
take vacation,'' he said. ``But of course, as everyone knows, this
was the summer of Woodstock, and all my friends were going. What to
do?''
</P>
<P>
   He called in sick and went.
</P>
<P>
   ``The following Monday I went to work as scheduled. Later that
morning, I was filing papers and daydreaming about the past weekend
when my supervisor came up behind me and said quite matter of
factly, `So, how was Woodstock?' Without missing a beat, I turned
and replied, `Great!'
</P>
<P>
   ``He just smiled and walked away.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakesberg offers an epilogue: ``To this day, I have used my sick
days honestly.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Use truancy as a tool,'' is the advice to managers from Audri
J. Carr, the manager of new product sourcing and a project team
leader at Lucas Aerospace, a division of TRW in Aurora, Ohio. ``Use
it as a reward. Be understanding. Promote it quietly and within
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carr, who believes that more time off than a standard two
weeks a year fosters creativity, loyalty and productivity, cites
the example of a manager in her group who runs three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has now been joined by several other engineers who run with
him,'' she writes from Shaker Heights, Ohio. ``Lunch is supposed to
be 30 minutes. What with the four-mile run itself, changing
clothes, then showering and changing back, that time pushes one and
one-quarter hours at least.
</P>
<P>
   At first it bothered me. Was he abusing the time out for lunch?
Then I decided the real question was: Did he perform on the job?
Were his assignments completed well and on time? The answer was
yes. So let them run. Running is a great stress reliever.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carr writes that she would rather manage ``a motivated,
productive employee than one with perfect attendance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
