<HEADLINE>
A BONDING FEST FOR SATURN OWNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1)  
 (af)  
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If America's streets and highways seemed devoid of Saturns on
Friday and Saturday, it was because tens of thousands of the cars
were converging on sleepy Spring Hill, Tenn., with headlights
shining and horns honking.
</P>
<P>
   The owners attended a two-day festival orchestrated by Saturn,
the General Motors unit, which called the event a ``homecoming''
because the cars are built at a sprawling factory there.
</P>
<P>
   Saturn fans drove from across the nation, with caravans from Los
Angeles, Seattle, Minneapolis, Boston and Miami stopping at Saturn
dealerships along the way to pick up more enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, one of the caravans passed through Secaucus, N.J.,
headed south on the New Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   The owners were given tours of the factory, heard Hootie and the
Blowfish, Tim McGraw and Faith Hill in concert, and test-drove
Saturn's new sedan, the 2000 LS. A Staten Island couple planned a
wedding in Spring Hill to coincide with the event.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case anyone attending missed the point that a Saturn is
more than just a car, performers in a rhythm and dance routine used
car parts as musical instruments to tell the history of the
company.
</P>
</TEXT>
