<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waltrip to confirm 2000 is final season
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indianapolis Motor Speedway is NASCAR's next stop, and it also
will be the site for the retirement announcement of one of the
sport's legendary drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Waltrip, a three-time Winston Cup champion, has
scheduled a news conference for Thursday morning in Indianapolis.
After more than a year of speculation, Waltrip, 52, is expected to
confirm that the 2000 season will be his last behind the steering
wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sad to see (Waltrip) retire, but I guess it is good when
someone can call it quits on their own terms,'' said Phillipe
Lopez, crew chief of the No. 66 Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was all Darrell's decision,'' Lopez said. ``He is just at
a point where he wants to see and do other things in life,
especially be at home more with his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis Carter, co-owner of Kmart Racing, said, ``Time waits for
no man; (it's) time to move on'' for Waltrip.''
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip has been racing in NASCAR since 1972 and leads all
active drivers in career victories with 84. He is one of the few
``old-time greats'' remaining on the stock-car circuit, along with
Dale Earnhardt and Bill Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip's retirement plans probably will boost the popularity of
the driver, who has not won a race since Darlington in 1992. Team
officials already are preparing for next season's farewell tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had meetings to discuss the pros and cons for next
year,'' Lopez said. ``Next to Jeff Gordon, (Waltrip) may have the
most highly publicized car next year. We are going to do everything
in our power to make sure Darrell goes out with a bang at each and
every race.''
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip needs to qualify
</P>
<P>
   The pressure is on Waltrip in more ways than one at Indy. He
used his last remaining car-owner provisional to earn a spot at
Pocono. He will have no such security at the Brickyard 400, needing
a qualifying time to participate in one of the season's biggest
races.
</P>
<P>
   Disabled list
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup points leader Dale Jarrett probably will be without
the services of a key crew member in Indianapolis. Brian Clark, the
left-rear tire-changer for the No. 88 Ford, suffered two broken
toes during a Jarrett pit stop at Pocono on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor said I should sit out four-to-six weeks, but I am
not one to let an injury slow me down,'' said Clark, who is on
crutches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am shooting to be back by Indy, but I know there is only a
slim chance of that happening. I'm probably looking at missing one
or two races _ well, definitely not more than one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Hall, a tire-carrier for Kenny Irwin, took the place of
Clark at Pocono because his driver already was out of the race.
Hall might continue to be a temporary substitute at the Brickyard
400, because both the Jarrett and Irwin teams are owned by Robert
Yates Racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for us to have a good tire-changer,'' crew
chief Todd Parrott said. ``You've got to have a guy that can use
all of his arms or legs. It can mean the difference between a
second or two on a pit stop, which can be the difference in winning
a race.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 28, broke his left big toe and second toe when the car's
tail pipe landed on his foot.
</P>
<P>
   Extra laps
</P>
<P>
   A blown tire at Pocono has blown away Jeff Gordon's chances of
winning a record-trying third Winston Cup trophy in a row. He is
sixth in the points, 492 behind Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   Carvell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
