A9151 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-MINIMUM-WAGE-BOS &LR;      07-29 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-MINIMUM-WAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE EXPECTED ENACT HIGHEST MINIMUM WAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL CROWLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Massachusetts Senate passed a $1.50 hike in the
minimum wage Thursday, all but guaranteeing that Bay State workers
will soon enjoy the highest such wage in the nation at $6.75 per
hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing's a done deal,'' said Massachusetts AFL-CIO
president Robert J. Haynes, ``and we're thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, minimum-wage workers would see their paychecks
swell by 75 cents per hour in January 2000, and by another 75 cents
a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci is expected to sign the bill, bringing a
long-running political drama to a swift and unexpected conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Ilene Hoffer, a Cellucci spokesman, said the governor would
``look forward to signing'' the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks to be a wage hike that's very similar to what the
governor proposed, without the indexing to inflation that we think
would have been detrimental to the economy,'' Hoffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, a significant hike in the state's $5.25 hourly
wage had seemed a long shot at best. House Speaker Thomas M.
Finneran had blocked prior efforts to raise the wage rate, and
Cellucci had called for a more modest, 90-cent increase.
</P>
<P>
   But Finneran dramatically changed his position on July 12,
proposing a $1.50 increase that was passed by the House the
following day. And Cellucci now agrees that the economy can sustain
the 29 percent wage increase.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham, who has long sought a
higher wage, had hardly expected to follow the more fiscally
conservative Finneran's lead on the issue. But he gladly ushered
the wage bill through an uncontested voice vote in his chamber
Thursday, bringing the Senate in agreement with the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a victory for the hard-working people of the
Commonwealth,'' Birmingham said after the vote. ``This sends the
message that work does pay, and if you work for a living in the
Commonwealth of Massachusetts you ought to earn a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, a full-time minimum-wage earner in Massachusetts
takes home $10,920 per year. The federal poverty line for a family
of three is $13,300. Under the new law, the minimum wage will pay
$14,040 per year in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent report by Northeastern University's Center
for Labor Market Studies, 262,000 Massachusetts workers currently
earn less than $6.75 per hour with 93,000 of those workers earning
between $5.25 and $5.75 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Although a political consensus has quickly formed around the
issue on Beacon Hill, business leaders and some conservatives
remain convinced that an increased minimum wage could endanger the
state's economy and scare off new business.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the economy here is very, very good, we are concerned
about the long-term impact the miniumum wage may have on the
creation or maintenance of minimum wage jobs,'' said Brian Gilmore,
a spokesman for the Associated Industries of Massachusetts (AIM).
</P>
<P>
   ``Minimum wages are at best public relations exercises, and
legislators enagage in them to satisfy their constituents, and
particularly their union consituents,'' said David Tuerck,
executive director of the Beacon Hill Institute, a conservative
think tank at Suffolk University. Tuerck warned that minimum wage
workers become ever more vulnerable to recession-triggered layoffs
as their pay rises.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those concerns, Massachusetts is about to leap ahead of
several other states to lead the nation with its wage rate. Oregon,
now the highest-paying state, requires an hourly pay of at least
$6.50 per hour. Washington state's wage will rise to $6.50 in
January 2000 and Connecticut's will reach $6.15 next year.
</P>
<P>
   The federally-mandated minimum wage is currently $5.15.
</P>
<P>
   Tuerck insisted that Massachusetts outpaces the rest of the
nation at its peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another signal to the rest of the country that this
state is unfriendly to business, and a signal to investors thinking
about opening up fast food franchises that they might want to put
their money someplace else where they won't face as hostile a labor
environment,'' Tuerck said.
</P>
<P>
   But Birmingham disputed that notion Thursday, saying it is ``a
badge of honor'' for Massachusetts to be number one in the nation
in wages for its lowest-paid workers. ``It's a cause for
celebration that Massachusetts leads the country,'' Birmingham
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Lazere, a senior analyst at the Washington, D.C.-based Center
on Budget and Policy Priorities, noted that many Capitol Hill
observers expect the federal minimum wage to be raised to $6.15 in
the next year. ``I think there is the political will for it,''
Lazere said.
</P>
<P>
   The final Bay State bill will not link, or ``index,'' the
minimum wage to the inflation rate, a move some had proposed to
ensure wages keep pace with the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed an indexing provision earlier this year, but
Finneran and Cellucci oppose indexing, and Birmingham was willing
to yield on the issue for now.
</P>
<P>
   The wage law would not require employers to raise the base
hourly pay given to waiters and waitresses whose income, including
tips, already equals or exceeds the new wage rate.
</P>
<P>
   The law must still be formally enacted by the House and Senate,
votes considered a formality now that the two chambers have already
overwhelmingly passed identical wage bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no surprise in today's vote, but one year ago the
prospects for low-wage workers in Massachusetts looked pretty
bleak,'' said state Rep. James J. Marzilli, the House's leading
advocate for a wage hike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
