<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9155 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-STORYTELLING-ART-     07-29 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-STORYTELLING-ART-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS A DARK AND STORMY SALES PITCH, AND MAYBE IT WORKED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J., Ariz., Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1)  
 (af)  
 By ERIC QUINONES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Preparing for a presentation to the news media, Hugh
Stuart-Buttle was wondering how best to promote the products that
his company, Ciba Specialty Chemicals, markets for protection
against ultraviolet rays. A scrap of childhood memory came to mind:
his mother, when he was a fair-haired young boy playing outdoors,
imploring him to cover up under the bright sun.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart-Buttle smiled at the recollection and used it to lead
into the presentation he was rehearsing. ``That's the issue we want
to talk about today,'' he continued, eyes scanning an imaginary
crowd of reporters as he led into a description of the products'
``unique technological strength'' against the power of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Seated across the conference table with a stopwatch in her hand,
Karen Berg, a communications consultant, nodded approvingly.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart-Buttle, the vice president for communications of Ciba's
North American division in Tarrytown, N.Y., was working to master a
technique that comes naturally to powerful speakers in politics or
the arts but until recently was seldom heard in business contexts:
personal storytelling as a way of enlivening speeches, sales
pitches, training sessions and other presentations on otherwise dry
or technical topics.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching the technique has become a thriving business for
consultants like Ms. Berg, who typically charges $3,000 to $4,000
for a session like the two and a half hours she spent with
Stuart-Buttle and a colleague a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that engages the mind's eye is more memorable than
just getting up and spouting off data,'' said Ms. Berg, chief
executive of Commcore Communication Strategies in White Plains,
N.Y. ``They will remember the visual images.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest annual report of the Walt Disney Co., for example,
Michael D. Eisner, the chief executive, departed from the
boilerplate of sales figures and product lines that leads off many
companies' reports. To illustrate the changes in his company's
business, he wrote instead of watching the seasons change from his
office window.
</P>
<P>
   Communications consultants say that grabbing and holding an
audience's attention is more difficult than ever in a world glutted
with information. Relating to the audience on a personal level is a
way through the clutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are time-starved, they're drained, their attention span
is shorter, they're full of stress,'' Ms. Berg said.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants say companies with complex products and services _
those in science and technology, accounting and engineering _ most
often want help with ``soft'' communications skills like
storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   The companies see such techniques as providing an edge over
rivals that hawk similar products or services in more prosaic ways,
said James F. Hennig, a motivational speaker based in Chandler,
Ariz., who leads seminars on negotiation skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are very relationship-oriented in their approach to
business communication and business deals do a lot better, because
they make people feel comfortable,'' Hennig said.
</P>
<P>
   But it can be difficult to persuade people who are accustomed to
dealing in facts and figures that telling a roomful of strangers
about personal experiences can help them achieve business goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm skeptical that it's going to be easily and quickly
accepted,'' said Susan Nurre, a Dallas-based management consultant
with the Computer Sciences Corp., a computer software and services
company with a large consulting division. ``It seems like quite a
few people would hesitate to tell a story, because they think
stories have to be about their grandmother.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Nurre herself is sold on the technique. In 1996,
Computer Sciences and Executive Communications Group of Englewood,
N.J., developed a program to teach storytelling skills to thousands
of employees in the consulting division of Computer Sciences, and
Ms. Nurre took to heart what she learned.
</P>
<P>
   One story she uses to good effect with her colleagues relates
how she improved her relationship with her mother-in-law, who
speaks Farsi but not English, by learning a few key Farsi phrases
as a sign of respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use that story and tie it to the fact that as consultants,
we have to speak our clients' language,'' Ms. Nurre said. ``We
can't go in there spouting our language, because that won't make
sense to them. We need to show that we're respecting them and we
believe that what they're doing is important.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is impossible to quantify the value of storytelling to
her company's business, she says she believes it has helped gain
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Communications Group has begun offering the
storytelling training to others in one-on-one sessions and in
one-day ``executive storytelling'' seminars. The first seminar,
held last year, attracted about 100 business people who paid $400
to $500 apiece, said Frank Carillo, the president of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Giuliano, the chairman, says he sometimes meets resistance
from executives who think storytelling has no place in serious
business. He responds with examples of analogies that clients have
drawn from the least likely sources, like fairy tales or fishing
trips, that when handled deftly conveyed useful business lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really requires a high level of strategy,'' Giuliano said.
``That's what differentiates executive storytelling from telling a
story across the kitchen table _ the strategic development and
intent of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Satow, the president and a founder of a start-up
investment firm, Eclipse Trading, in New York, worked with Ms. Berg
at Commcore when he was preparing himself to seek investors.
</P>
<P>
   After learning the storytelling technique, he blended personal
stories and business information in presentations that brought
Eclipse several partners, including the giant brokerage firms
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Salomon Smith Barney. One story he
often told was about the company's earliest days.
</P>
<P>
   He and Eugene Choe were working as lawyers for the Securities
and Exchange Commission when then they decided to leave their jobs
in April 1997 and found Eclipse, which is developing a system to
give individual investors access to after-hours trades.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, Satow's wife, Barbara, told him she was
pregnant. ``I was sitting there thinking to myself, `My God, I'm
not making any money and she's pregnant,''' he says. ``In fact,
during that entire period, she kept working.''
</P>
<P>
   Relating that anecdote, Satow said, helped him demonstrate to
potential investors that he was dedicated to Eclipse despite the
stresses of a new venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're interested in the journey and what it took to get
there,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
