<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-TAXCUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAY SEEN CLEAR FOR LARGEST TAX-CUT IN US HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republicans Thursday thwarted threats to
their proposed $792 billion tax cut from across the political
spectrum, as they rebuffed a conservative effort to sweeten the
plan for the wealthy and scuttled Senator Edward M. Kennedy's push
to trim the breaks in favor of prescription-drug coverage for
Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   A $500 billion compromise plan also buckled under the weight of
the Republican majority, as a bipartisan team of moderate sponsors
abruptly withdrew the measure rather than endure a crushing defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The developments cleared the way for the GOP majority to pass
the largest tax cut in history Friday despite warnings from Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan and members of both parties that
the package may be more extravagant than the government can afford.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown reflected the strength of a new generation of
conservative leaders in the Senate who have consolidated their
power since the departure of former majority leader Bob Dole, a
more moderate conciliator, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Lurching toward high-stakes negotiations with the White House
over the tax plan, leaders of the GOP juggernaut seized every
chance to portray President Clinton and his allies as the enemies
of fiscal restraint. ``Any dime that I can keep out of the hands of
the spenders and put in the hands of the taxpayers, I will,'' said
Senator Larry E. Craig of Idaho, chairman of the Senate Republican
Policy Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, bursting back into the political donnybrook after the
death of his nephew, John F. Kennedy Jr., wasted little time in
depicting the Republican majority as protectors of the privileged
at the expense of the poor. Deriding the GOP tax package as a boon
for ``the three-martini lunch'' crowd, Kennedy tried unsuccessfully
to counter a pledge from GOP leaders to address the lack of
prescription drug coverage for Medicare recipients in future
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why ask senior citizens to wait?'' he shouted on the Senate
floor. ``Why should they always have to be the ones to wait? Why
are they always left behind? It's a question of priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's initiative was defeated, 55-45, on a procedural vote,
with every Repbublican opposing the plan but one: Senator Arlen
Specter of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Only one Democratic senator, John B. Breaux of Louisiana, voted
against Kennedy's proposal to set aside an unspecified part of the
tax breaks to provide the first prescription benefit for Medicare
recipients since the program was established in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy also was expected to force the Senate to vote during the
tax debate on his plan to raise the minimum wage to $6.15 an hour
by September 2000, up from the current rate of $5.15 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Kennedy's Medicare measure was defeated, Clinton
renewed his vow to veto the $792 billion plan, though the president
continued to leave open the door to as much as $300 billion in tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we can get a bipartisan agreement that will save Social
Security, save and reform Medicare, continue to invest in education
and get this country out of debt,'' Clinton told reporters at the
White House. ``If we do those big things first, there's still money
left for a good size tax cut. But what is being done now is
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, who has led
the GOP assault on Clinton's tax-cut policy, endured a setback
Thursday when a group of moderate GOP senators joined the unified
Democratic minority to kill an alternative, $792 billion tax-cut
plan sponsored by Republican Senator Phil Gramm of Texas and
supported by Lott.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, much like the $792 billion measure the House passed
last week, would have cut taxes by 10 percent across the board and
further reduced capital gains taxes. Both moves would have
benefited high-income taxpayers and corporations far more than the
chief Senate Republican plan, whose key element calls for reducing
the 15-percent income-tax rate to 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With nine Republicans joining all 45 Democrats in opposing
Gramm's plan, the measure was defeated, 54-46, on a procedural
vote. Every New England senator voted against the Gramm plan except
Judd Gregg and Bob Smith of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the political fray, Senator John F. Kerry appealed to the
Senate to devote as much as $20 billion to restore health-care
services that have diminished because of reduced Medicare
reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, whose measure was expected to be voted on Friday, cited
recent layoffs at Massachusetts General Hospital and cutbacks at
South Shore Hospital as examples of the need to increase the
Medicare reimbursements and ease a ``fundamental crisis'' in the
delivery of health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to consider the impact on our hospitals, home health
care, and rural communities,'' he said. ``And I beg my colleagues
to try to find the money that is going to save us from the loss of
the crown jewels of the American health care system, our teaching
hospitals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
