<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-LOWGAS-NYT &LR;      07-29 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-LOWGAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAS PRICES TOP SUMMER'S LIST OF CONFLICTS IN RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The major contenders in Russia's 2000 presidential
election already are slinging mud by the bucketful, the Kremlin is
under criminal investigation and the Communist Party's
once-unassailable base in Parliament is developing serious stress
cracks. But as political issues go, it is safe to say all that
pales next to this summer's national fixation: the price of a liter
of gas.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the world's largest oil-producing nations, ordinary
Russians are combusting over the rising cost of ``benzin,'' and
everyone from President Boris Yeltsin to lowly regional legislators
is seeking cover from the political fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Since last winter, when the world was awash in oil and prices
were relatively low, gasoline prices have nearly doubled in Moscow,
and in parts of the nation they nearly tripled before retreating
this month to levels that are merely scandalous.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons behind the increase range from a sharp rise in the
price of crude oil recently, which made the already devalued
Russian oil a world-class bargain, to the fact that the shaky ruble
has given Russian oil companies a ravenous appetite for hard
currency. The result is that Russian crude is leaving the country
on trains, tankers and in pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   That has placed Yeltsin's government in a political bind, forced
either to endorse a free market that is draining consumers' wallets
or to impose the sort of heavy-handed state controls that it
professes to despise.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst-hit areas _ St. Petersburg and southwest Russia's
Black Sea region _ gas supplies have at times all but dried up,
allowing profiteers to prey on helpless motorists and, at times, on
one another.
</P>
<P>
   The Moscow newspaper Kommersant reported this week that some
vacationers returning from Black Sea resorts were reduced to buying
gas for as much as $2 per liter, the equivalent of $7.50 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   And in St. Petersburg, an executive at an oil company that was
accused of price-fixing and creating artificial gas shortages was
killed on Monday as he rode to work in his armor-plated Chevy
Blazer. His no-nonsense assailants attacked him during rush hour
with Kalishnikov automatic rifles and rocket-propelled grenades.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they presume the attack stemmed from a business
dispute as St. Petersburg's fuel companies are in a bitter war for
control of the city's retail gasoline market.
</P>
<P>
   Customers have, so far, been more forgiving. ``Some customers
just buy these cards _ it's a kind of a credit card _ and those who
have these cards had no problem with filling their tanks.'' Irina
Senko, an attendant at a busy station in central St. Petersburg,
said in an interview. As for the rest, ``They were angry,'' she
said. ``I explained to them that the refinery wasn't working, or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   At least some oil companies say they are innocent bystanders in
this economic carnage. One of the biggest, Lukoil, boasts that it
has continued to supply gasoline to its chain of more than 1,000
service stations even as competitors' pumps went dry.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently doubled gasoline production at a remodeled
refinery in in south-central Russia, and plans to boost production
at a second revamped refinery.
</P>
<P>
   In the company's view, the spokesman said, Russia's gas crunch
is due more to increased domestic demand than a desire for foreign
currency.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen O'Sullivan, a petroleum analyst and research director
for United Financial Group in Moscow, an investment firm, said that
explanation is unlikely. But don't blame the oil companies, he
added: they are simply behaving like businesses everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can get paid late, if at all, in a currency that's under
threat of devaluation, or they can get dollars,'' he said. ``The
oil companies are making a perfectly rational decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The government persuaded major oil companies and other
businesses to sign a so-called voluntary pledge to ``exclude
unwarranted price hikes'' this year. The International Monetary
Fund called the pact interference in the markets; private experts
predicted it would lead to shortages, which is apparently what
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the pledge halt the rise in gas prices, because it did
not apply to the vast majority of the nation's service stations _
mom-and-pop operations, beyond the oil companies' control _ which
continued to set prices according to supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   On July 23, the government proposed another tack: doubling the
petroleum-export tax. That would have benefited the government,
which already is enjoying a oil-tax windfall from the higher prices
and exports. But whether it would curb exports much is debatable
because exporting oil is highly lucrative for the oil companies.
With their considerable political clout, they fought the idea.
</P>
<P>
   So on Wednesday, officials abandoned that notion and pledged to
crack down on smuggling, promote increased oil production and use
unnamed ``economic measures'' to ensure that the gas drought in
parts of the nation ends.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by Russia's Interfax news service to explain what that
meant, Deputy Prime Minister Nikolai Aksyonenko said it ``will
depend on people, since prices are determined by demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words,'' he said, ``gasoline prices may increase.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
