<HEADLINE>
STOCKS TUMBLE SHARPLY AND BROADLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices tumbled sharply and broadly Thursday
after the government reported that employers paid unexpectedly
large wage and benefit increases during the spring quarter, making
it more likely _ but by no means certain _ that the Federal Reserve
will again increase interest rates to avert inflation.
</P>
<P>
   As traders reacted to a 1.1 percent jump in the Labor
Department's Employment Cost Index, the main gauges remained in
negative territory throughout the session. The Dow Jones industrial
average finished down 180.78 points, or 1.65 percent, at 10,791.29,
but that was somewhat above its low.
</P>
<P>
   For a while the Dow's slide was the biggest since May 27, but
the late firming made it less severe than a 191.55-point selloff
early last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index skidded 24.37 points, or
1.78 percent, closing at 1,341.03, while the recently-battered
Nasdaq market took the biggest hit, dropping 65.83 points, or 2.43
percent, to 2,640.01.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers, chiefly the labor costs, were worse than
expected,'' said Jeffrey Applegate, chief U.S. strategist at Lehman
Brothers. ``This makes another Federal Reserve tightening more
likely than not.''
</P>
<P>
   A separate Labor Department report showed a sharp cut in
first-time claims for unemployment insurance last week, suggesting
the extremely tight labor market continued into summer. Market
operators took little comfort from a Commerce Department estimate
that the economy's growth rate was slower than had been expected
during the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume quickened a bit, but analysts said much of the
weakness reflected program trades by professionals and there was
little evidence of indiscriminate selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a correction, not the beginning of anything we
should be concerned about,'' said Jeffrey Rubin, research director
at Birinyi Associates. ``It's not your grandmother going and
throwing the baby out with the bathwater.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were less sanguine. For example, Richard McCabe, chief
market analyst at Merrill Lynch, said, ``It looks like a resumption
of the downswing that started last week'' when investors who had
bet correctly on very strong second-quarter profits decided to cash
in. And the next upward push is unlikely to occur before the Fed's
Aug. 24 policy meeting, he said, with the interim clouded by fears
that the central bank will find much to fret about, especially next
Friday's report on the labor market in July.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Rich, a trader at BT Brokerage, largely agreed. ``We're
seeing some serious selling'' because of interest-rate jitters, he
said, expressing disappointment that good corporate earnings, the
best since the first quarter of 1997, have been rewarded with such
heavy profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices also slumped Thursday on rate fears, putting
pressure on financial stocks, with J.P. Morgan falling 3 3/8 to 130
5/8, leading the decline of the blue-chip Dow average.
</P>
<P>
   Only four of the 30 Dow stocks gained. The only sizable gains
were from Procter &AMP; Gamble, up 2 to 88 1/8, and Minnesota Mining,
up 1 11/16 to 90 13/16. Both reported profits that beat
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Gold stocks, one of the most depressed groups, finally managed
to gain, with Newmont Mining rising 1 1/8 to 19 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management was a major casualty, skidding 5 1/4 to 25
15/16 after warning again of lagging profits. The shares, which
traded at 60 in early May, hit a new low of 24.
</P>
<P>
   In a prominent initial public offering, Net2Phone's shares
surged as high as 29 1/2 from 15 before closing at 26 9/16. A total
of 18.7 million changed hands, meaning that each of the 5.4 million
shares issued averaged more than three different owners.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues swamped advancing ones on the New York Stock
Exchange by 2,242 to 809, and there were 166 new lows compared with
31 new highs.
</P>
<P>
   Major European stock markets, which were open long enough to
digest the American economic news, closed with even bigger losses,
ranging from 2.8 percent in Paris to 3.4 percent in Frankfurt.
Mexico's Bolsa dropped nearly 4 percent while stock prices climbed
1.6 percent in Tokyo.
</P>
</TEXT>
