<SLUG> BC-BROWN-UNITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON MAYOR SEEKS TO MEND RIFT OVER BILINGUAL EDUCATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Mayor Lee Brown is attempting to seal a rift among
Houston's minority politicians over bilingual education before it
spills into this year's municipal elections.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who campaigned on the promise that he would be the mayor
``for all of Houston,'' is convening a a closed-door ``unity''
session Saturday of black and Hispanic elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting follows a divisive vote last week by Houston
Independent School District trustees in favor of a policy that
emphasizes learning English ``as rapidly as individually
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-2 vote split along ethnic lines, with black and Anglo
board members voting in favor of the policy against the board's
Hispanic members save one _ Gabriel Vasquez, who also is a
candidate for City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a small coterie of Hispanic officials led by state Sen.
Mario Gallegos, D-Galena Park, are assailing Vasquez's vote on the
issue as a ``sell-out,'' and bringing the fight into the city
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez, one of four candidates for the open seat, is being
backed for the race by many of Brown's political supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The closed-door meeting, set for Saturday morning at a downtown
barbecue restaurant, is aimed in part at airing out the bad
feelings on all sides and staving off an all-out brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who has no authority over the school district,
nevertheless is being touted by both factions as a welcome
peacemaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``No politician likes to get involved in another politician's
business,'' said state Rep. Garnet Coleman, D-Houston. ``To stick
your nose in, it really has to be something extraordinary. And this
is one of those cases.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Vasquez said bilingual education is not an issue
for him in the city elections. Beyond that, he declined to mix it
up with Gallegos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's two different races, frankly,'' Vasquez said Thursday.
``Others may try to use this breakfast to their own ends, but I am
out there talking about neighborhoods and improving
neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallegos, whose mother, Olga Gallegos, is a Houston school
trustee opposed to the new bilingual education policy, said he
wasn't planning to get involved in the City Council race _ until
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm backing anyone but Gabriel Vasquez,'' Gallegos said.
``Anyone who would sell out to English-only, they have no business
on council. We are taking this to the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   The trustees' vote is the first time HISD has adopted a board
policy on bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
   Under the policy, non-English-speaking children in the
bilingual-education program would be moved into English as soon as
they can demonstrate proficiency in English reading.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters describe the policy as a middle ground between those
who believe in English immersion and those who think children
should spend years studying academic subjects in their native
language.
</P>
<P>
   Although short of the ``English-only'' directive described by
Gallegos and others, the policy is far from the final word on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, who along with other black legislators are supporting
Gallegos and Hispanic House members opposing the plan, said origins
of the problem lie in the manner in which the policy was shaped and
adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that the policy they passed is fine, but a certain
percentage of the people this has affected feel the policy has been
rammed down their throats,'' Coleman said. ``That is when people
start to distrust their government.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vasquez countered that opponents of the plan were repeatedly
invited to participate in the process and just as often rejected
efforts by trustees to work on a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
