u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-STEM-CELLS-NYT &LR;      07-29 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-STEM-CELLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLS FROM A MOUSE EMBRYO ARE CONVERTED INTO SPECIALIZED BRAIN
CELLS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Mass.)   By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Biologists have converted cells from the embryo of a mouse into
specialized brain cells capable of repairing a brain defect.
</P>
<P>
   The research, reported in an article in Science that is being
published Friday, lends substance to the hope of using human
embryonic stem cells to replace any of a patient's diseased tissues
and organs.
</P>
<P>
   The first of many steps in this grand design is to learn how to
drive these embryonic cells down particular lineages toward each of
the many different types of mature cell found in the adult body.
The Science article, by Dr. Oliver Bruestle of the University of
Bonn, in Germany, and by other authors, suggests that it may easier
than expected to mix suitable cocktails of growth factors to govern
these transformations.
</P>
<P>
   Using growth factors developed in earlier work, the researchers
converted mouse embryonic cells into all-purpose brain cells and
then into a specialized type of brain cell that wraps neurons in a
sheaf of the insulating material known as myelin.
</P>
<P>
   When the cells were injected in rats that are genetically
incapable of making myelin, they successfully clad the rat neurons
in insulation. If human embryonic cells can be converted into
myelin-making cells the same way, the method could eventually help
treat human neurological disorders, the authors say.
</P>
<P>
   Human embryonic stem cells, derived from surplus human embryos
created in fertility clinics, were first grown successfully by Dr.
James A. Thomson of the University of Wisconsin. Thomson said he
planned to work with one of the authors of the mouse experiment,
Dr. Ian D. Duncan of the University of Wisconsin, to see whether
human embryonic cells can be converted to myelin-making brain cells
with the same methods.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many technical problems in using human embryonic cells
as therapy is that of rejection by the patient's immune system. A
much-discussed approach would be to take one of Thomson's stem
cells, which can be grown in profusion, and to replace the cell's
nucleus, containing its DNA, with a nucleus from one of the
patient's skin cells.
</P>
<P>
   The main body of an embryonic cell is thought to be capable of
``reprogramming'' a nucleus inserted into it. The embryonic stem
cells would then be almost identical to those from which the
patient's body was originally generated. Converted into brain
cells, say, they should present no challenge to the patient's
immune system.
</P>
<P>
   Human embryonic cells cannot form an embryo because they lack
the embryo's other component, a sphere of organizing cells that are
not themselves part of the embryo but help shape the developing
embryonic cells into an organized structure. Left to themselves,
embryonic stem cells in the laboratory will often develop into a
chaotic mass of different tissues known as a teratoma.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have derived mouse heart cells from a teratoma and
have shown the cells will work efficiently in a mouse. But the
Science article seems to be one of the first to report that
embryonic cells were taken directly down a desired lineage by
manipulation with growth factors.
</P>
<P>
   An expected advantage of stem cell therapy is that it is not
necessary or even desirable to take cells to their fully
differentiated or adult form. They need to be immature cells,
appropriate for the tissue into which they are injected but young
enough to respond to the local cues under which they will continue
their development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message coming out from a lot of different studies is that
embryonic stem cells are very plastic,'' said an author of the
Science article, Dr. Ronald D.G. McKay of the National Institutes
of Health. ``You coax them a little bit, and they slip into these
states.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Thomson and other researchers with private funds are
free to work on human embryonic stem cells, government-financed
scientists cannot do so because Congress has prohibited federal
funds from being spent on research in which human embryos are
destroyed. The Clinton administration recently ruled that this
interpretation did not apply to the use of Thomson's cells, and the
National Institutes of Health is about to publish guidelines under
which research may proceed. But opponents of abortion hope Congress
will specifically ban federal financing of stem cell research.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists are eager to move ahead under appropriate guidelines.
``In terms of the political debate, this says we are getting better
at taking embryonic stem cells, which can give rise to all cell
types, and are directing them down a particular lineage,'' said Dr.
Evan Y. Snyder, a brain cell expert at Harvard Medical School.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
