<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-HOFFA-317&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMSTERS CHIEF INITIATES ANTI-CORRUPTION EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ James P. Hoffa, the president of the teamsters,
Thursday announced his union's most ambitious anti-corruption
effort in decades in a move that he said was designed to keep the
teamsters free of organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa named a highly regarded former prosecutor to head the
effort and said the teamsters would establish new ethical
guidelines for its leaders and members, and would establish new
internal procedures to guarantee that ethical violations are
investigated and punished.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a one-shot deal,'' Hoffa said at a news conference
here at the headquarters of the International Brotherhood of
Teamsters. ``It's being pursued on a number of levels to make sure
our union is corruption-free.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa, who became the teamsters' president in March, made clear
that one reason he was instituting the in-house effort was to
persuade the federal government to end its decadelong supervision
of the 1.4-million member union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been under government supervision for 10 years,''
Hoffa said. ``It's time for a fresh review of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa announced that Edwin H. Stier, 59, a former federal and
state prosecutor in New Jersey, would oversee the anti-corruption
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Stier vowed to determine whether any organized crime influence
remained within the union, and, if it did, he said he would push
the teamsters to move against any such links.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time now to help the union develop the capacity to police
itself, to make sure that any evidence of corruption or organized
crime influence is dealt with by the union itself,'' Stier said.
</P>
<P>
   Several labor experts praised Hoffa's initiative as an important
first step to show that he is serious about cleaning up a union
that had been long considered the nation's most corrupt, until
federal intervention in 1989 forced out more than 200 teamsters'
officials accused of corruption.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hoffa said he had come to respect Stier because of the job he
did as the trustee who supervised the cleanup of Local 560, the
4,400-member organization in Union City, N.J., that had been
regarded as the union's most mob-dominated local.
</P>
<P>
   That local was once headed by Anthony Provenzano, a captain in
the Genovese crime family who was convicted of murder and who
investigators say had played a role in the 1975 disappearance of
Hoffa's father, James R. Hoffa, who headed the union from 1957 to
1971.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa's father went to prison after being convicted of jury
tampering and pension fraud, and prosecutors said the father worked
closely with organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Stier said he took the job only after he had been convinced that
the younger Hoffa was intent on rooting out corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced,'' Stier said, ``that Jim Hoffa and the leaders
of this union are committed to running a clean union and are
determined to remove any remaining vestiges of organized crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa said he would seek to arrange a meeting with Mary Jo
White, the U.S. attorney in Manhattan, who is the government
official in charge of the federal supervision of the teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa said he would seek a dialogue in which he hoped to impress
the government about the seriousness of the union's anti-corruption
efforts _ all with any eye to persuading the government to end
federal supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. White has declined to say whether the federal supervision
should continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
