<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANCE: RELATIONS WITH ALGERIA IMPROVE
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine began a two-day visit to
Algiers, describing the former colony as ``an important strategic
partner for France.'' Improved relations would soon permit meetings
with Algeria's president, Abdelaziz Bouteflika, by President
Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, Vedrine said.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: BASQUE GROUP RETREATS
</P>
<P>
   The Basque leftist coalition seen as the political arm of the
Basque rebel group ETA made an abrupt about-face, saying it
mistakenly signed, earlier this week, its first multiparty document
condemning ``all'' politically motivated violence. Leaders of other
parties that had hailed the signature as a step toward peace in the
troubled Basque region quickly criticized the reversal.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA: RULING IN CASTRO PLOT CASE
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. district judge in Puerto Rico denied a request by six
Cuban Americans accused of plotting to kill Fidel Castro, the Cuban
leader, in Venezuela in 1997 to be tried separately from a seventh
man who allegedly confessed and made incriminating statements about
the others. The trial is scheduled for this November.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: PRESIDENTIAL RIVAL BOWS OUT
</P>
<P>
   Mathews Phosa, former premier of Mpumalanga province, said he
was quitting parliament to go into business. Phosa was abruptly
removed from his job by President Thabo Mbeki earlier this year in
what some analysts saw as a payback for daring to run for deputy
president of the African National Congress against Mbeki's wishes.
</P>
</TEXT>
