<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9173 &Cx1f; tic-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR &LR;      07-29 0254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, July 30. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
PHOENIX-GROWTH _ Phoenix has drawn its first line in the sand to
slow growth.
</P>
<P>
   In the Valley's far north desert, the city has set up a version
of an urban growth boundary in a &UR; housing hot spot north of Central
Arizona Project Canal that could be home to 150,000 people by 2020.
 &UR; The line limits how far the city will build streets and sewer
lines without special approval from the Phoenix Planning Commission
and City Council. &UR; By CATHERINE REAGOR. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHINA _ A former U.S. embassy official in Beijing asserted his
Fifth Amendment rights Thursday rather than respond to allegations
that he accepted favors from people seeking visas to travel to
Phoenix and other U.S. cities. The House Government Reform
Committee presented evidence at a hearing to show Charles Parish
received ``valuable gratuities,'' including gifts and free lodging
in Scottsdale, Las Vegas and other locations. By JEFF BARKER. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Undated) The most shocking thing about the murders
in Atlanta, the only thing shocking about the murders in Atlanta,
is that the murders in Atlanta aren't shocking. By E.J. MONTINI
Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL; 
