<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INS-POLICY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INS MAY FREE 289 IMMIGRANTS IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A shift in the Immigration and Naturalization
Service's detention policy could mean the release of 289 immigrants
held in Texas facilities _ some of whom have been held for years.
</P>
<P>
   INS spokeswoman Mariela Melero said bonds of $1,500 to $5,000
have been set for 308 detainees in the 18-state Central Region.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged that some detainees have been in custody for
years, but said the average time of those eligible for release is
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants released on bond or personal recognizance will be
free until issuance of a final removal order, and their release
will not affect deportation proceedings, Melero said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those released is Roberto Obregon, whose wife, Miriam,
said having him back at work means she can afford school supplies
and a few extras.
</P>
<P>
   The family of nine lost their income and insurance when Roberto
Obregon, a legal resident for 10 years, was picked up in March by
INS agents who found he had gotten a third drunken driving citation
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need him for moral and economic support,'' Miriam Obregon
said. ``When he was (in detention), I had a hard time buying food
for the house. My kids would ask me why I couldn't buy soda water
from the store, or something from a restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the new policy took effect July 12, said INS spokeswoman
Luisa Aquino, 30 others have been released from the Houston
detention facility.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials announced earlier this month that some immigrants
with criminal records could be freed on bond, pending the outcome
of deportation proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The change in policy was based on rulings from 13 federal courts
that the INS has some discretion in detention matters. The agency
had interpreted the Immigration Reform Act of 1996 as mandating
detention, pending deportation for immigrants who had felony
criminal convictions.
</P>
<P>
   But the court decisions restored the agency's discretion to free
immigrants deemed no danger to the community nor a flight risk,
said Melero.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants convicted of nonviolent offenses now are eligible for
release from detention if they completed their sentences prior to
Oct. 9 and have not received a final removal order.
</P>
<P>
   Melero said INS workers in the Central Region have reviewed
3,330 cases to determine eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the change in detention policy, the 1996 law
dramatically changed the status of all immigrants, including
resident aliens. The law broadened the list of crimes that trigger
deportation to include theft and even some infractions for which an
immigrant received deferred adjudication.
</P>
<P>
   Because the law is retroactive, an immigrant who has had a good
record for years after a minor scrape with the law could find
himself behind bars awaiting deportation.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials estimate the revised policy could reduce the
detention population of 17,400 by about 5 percent, Melero said.
</P>
<P>
   A local immigration attorney said the change is positive for
detainees and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have good cases, but they just give up because
they can't stand sitting in jail'' for months or years, said Robert
Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   The deportation process can take two years or longer, he said.
Frustration among detainees is especially high during Texas'
summers because many are housed in small county jails that don't
have air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn said seven of his clients have been released on bond under
the new policy, and many of his colleagues have been able to reopen
old cases for INS review.
</P>
<P>
   He said the most positive aspect of the change is that it will
allow former detainees to work during the lengthy detention
process. Resident aliens are not entitled to court-appointed
attorneys, and they can't hire counsel if they can't work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most detainees are left to present their own cases before an
immigration judge, facing opposition from experienced INS
attorneys, Kahn said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
