<HEADER>
A9176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-P&AMP;G-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      07-29 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-P&AMP;G-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 PROCTER &AMP; GAMBLE EARNINGS TOP WALL ST. EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. may finally be breaking out of a slump. The
consumer products giant, which has been struggling with a sluggish
international business and a need for bigger successes from new
products, reported robust quarterly earnings growth Thursday that
beat analyst expectations.
</P>
<P>
   For its fourth quarter ended June 30, P&AMP;G posted net income of
$414 million, or 29 cents a share, after a $385 million after-tax
charge for restructuring. There were no charges in the comparable
period a year earlier, when the company earned $684 million, or 47
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the charge, profits from operations rose 16 percent to
$799 million, or 55 cents a share, surpassing the 53 cents analysts
had forecast. Revenues rose 2 percent to $9.45 billion on flat unit
volume. Currency translations reduced sales by 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, who had not been pleased with the company's
inconsistent performance during the past year, were impressed
Thursday. P&AMP;G's shares rose $2, to $88.125, though the stock is
still trading far below its 52-week peak of $103.812 reached on
April 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed with the earnings, but I continue to await
volume accelerations,'' said Amy Low Chasen, an analyst with
Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G continues to suffer from weakness in some foreign markets,
particularly Russia, which has been gripped by an economic crisis.
It has also been hurt by stiffer competition in the laundry and
hair-care businesses in Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But the company is also beginning to benefit from the recovery
in some foreign markets, notably in Asia. Its growth for the
quarter and year was strongest in North America, where results were
helped by popular new products such as Febreze, a fabric freshener
that has become one of P&AMP;G's most successful introductions in
recent years, and Dryel, a home dry-cleaning kit, along with a
handful of other promising new products.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a lot of new-product activity coming, which should jump
start volume growth again,'' said Sally Desloch, an analyst with
J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, excluding reorganization costs, P&AMP;G earned $4.14
billion, or $2.58 a share, a 10 percent increase. Revenue rose 2.6
percent to $38.125 billion. What is more, the company's
cost-cutting efforts seem to be paying off. For the year, the
margin on core net earnings was 10.9 percent _ the highest in 58
years, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, ``we are pleased with our continued strong earnings
performance despite economic difficulties in key emerging markets
and the impact of currencies around the world,'' said Durk I.
Jager, the company's president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G predicts that greater revenue and profit gains are ahead,
thanks to a worldwide reorganization of its business that is
intended to speed product development and produce a more nimble
operation by streamlining the company's notoriously bureaucratic
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have our new organization structure in place, and we
anticipate significant benefits over the coming fiscal year and
beyond,'' Jager said.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G said it expected to increase long-term annual sales growth
to 6 percent to 8 percent and growth of per-share earnings to 13
percent to 15 percent during each of the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The company's ``Organization 2005'' plan will cost $2 billion
after taxes over the next six years but is expected to generate
annual after-tax cost savings of about $900 million by 2004. As
part of the reorganization, P&AMP;G will cut 15,000 jobs worldwide
beginning next April and will close up to 10 underperforming
plants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
