<SLUG> BC-CYCLING-ARMSTRONG-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG TAKES NEW YORK CITY BY TIME TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, France, The Netherlands, Belgium)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Lance Armstrong one-day victory tour hit town
Thursday for a whirlwind sweep of television shows, news media
interviews and promotional appearances. Then, before most New
Yorkers could get a glimpse of the 27-year-old Texan who battled
back from debilitating treatment for cancer to win the Tour de
France Sunday, the visit was over and Armstrong was headed back to
Europe for more bicycle races.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was choreographed by Nike, a longtime sponsor.
Everywhere Armstrong went, people cheered and yelled thank you.
Several times, cancer survivors told him what an inspiration he had
been.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has been the nicest part,'' he said during a news
conference. ``I have a responsibility to tell my story and
encourage people who have cancer to stay strong. At every stage of
the tour, people would come up to me and tell me they were
supporting me. It's a big community, unfortunately. The thing I'm
most proud of is being a cancer survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, Armstrong learned he had testicular cancer that
had spread to his abdomen, lungs and brain. Two operations and
intensive chemotherapy have left him cancer-free, and he has been
riding better than ever. There was no time to ride Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole day has been crazy _ good crazy,'' he said during a
midday interview. ``I didn't expect all this. I knew the race was
going to get significant play in the States, but I didn't think it
would be like this.''
</P>
<P>
   This was his ambitious 48-hour timetable that began Wednesday
afternoon in the Netherlands where he finished fifth in an
exhibition criterium race and didn't end until Friday afternoon,
back in the Netherlands, for another criterium _ a short race
around downtown streets:
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY, THE NETHERLANDS, 11 p.m. Boarding of a Nike 15-seat,
two-bed corporate jet with his wife, Kristin; his agent, Bill
Stapleton, and Nike officials.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY, NEW YORK AREA, 1 a.m. Landing at Teterboro (N.J.)
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   2 a.m. Arrival at the SoHo Grand Hotel for a quick nap.
</P>
<P>
   4:30 a.m. Wake-up call.
</P>
<P>
   6 a.m. Television interview on ``CBS This Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   7:30 a.m. Television interview on NBC's ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   8 a.m. Television interview on ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m. Visit to the New York Stock Exchange, where he walked
around the floor. (``It was unbelievable the way they cheered and
wanted to touch him,'' Stapleton said. ``I think that's when he
realized the impact he had made on America.'')
</P>
<P>
   10:15 a.m. Arrival at Nike Town store in midtown, for public
relations videos.
</P>
<P>
   11 a.m. Nike Town news conference before 100 reporters, 12
television camera crews and hundreds of enthusiastic customers and
fans who packed the two flights of balconies off the lobby. He gave
the Trek bike he rode in the Tour de France to NikeTown to display
around the country, and Nike gave him a $25,000 check for the Lance
Armstrong Foundation whose mission is to publicize cancer and help
find a cure. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani presented him with a crystal
Big Apple and a proclamation announcing that Thursday was Lance
Armstrong Day in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Noon. One-on-one interviews, mainly with television. (``I'm
tired,'' Armstrong said, ``but I'm having a good time.'')
</P>
<P>
   1:30 p.m. Meeting with Bud Greenspan, the Olympic filmmaker who
will produce a movie about his life.
</P>
<P>
   2 p.m. Satellite media interviews.
</P>
<P>
   4:30 p.m. Rest and dinner.
</P>
<P>
   7 p.m. Taped interview for ``Late Show With David Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Taped interview via satellite for ``Larry King Live.''
</P>
<P>
   11 p.m. Scheduled departure to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY, BELGIUM, NOON. Scheduled arrival in Brussels. (``I won't
even have time to get jet lag,'' Armstrong said.)
</P>
<P>
   Afternoon Another criterium in nearby Heerven, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   This breakneck pace will continue into the foreseeable future.
Armstrong is scheduled to ride in six criteriums in eight days, a
tradition for Tour de France winners. In each race, he is wearing
the yellow jersey of the Tour leader, ``so I can bring the Tour to
people from neighboring countries,'' he said, ``and let them feel
they are part of the race.''
</P>
<P>
   The schedule does not faze him.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are all the things I have to accept,'' he said. ``I have
to realize this stuff won't be here forever. I have a chance to
tell my story. I did prove there is life after serious cancer.
After I recovered, my doctor told me my cancer was probably among
the worst 2 or 3 percent he had ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   In a week, Armstrong and his wife will fly home to Austin,
Texas, where the city will honor him Aug. 9. He has no immediate
race plans. He will pass up the world championships in October
because his wife is expecting their first child then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to no interviews, no autographs, no
anything,'' he said. ``I just want to go back and resume our normal
lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
