<SLUG> BC-GA-SHOOT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN KILLS 9, INJURES 12 IN SHOOTING SPREE IN ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GA-SHOOT-SCENE) 
(EDS: An expanded version of this story will move by 10 p.m. ET.) 
(ART ADV: PHOTOS are being sent to NYT photo clients. A GRAPHIC and
LOCATOR MAP are being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By KEVIN SACK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the deadliest shooting spree in Atlanta history, a
securities day trader apparently killed nine people Thursday
afternoon in two office buildings in the city's glitzy Buckhead
business and entertainment district. Another 12 people were injured
during the chaotic rampage, seven of them from gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   The man eluded a massive police manhunt for five hours, and then
killed himself in his van after police pulled him over at a service
station in nearby Cobb County.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell said the suspect, Mark O. Barton,
44, also apparently is connected to the recent killings of three
other people in an apartment in suburban Stockbridge, about 15
miles southeast of Atlanta. Campbell said that those victims are
believed to be Barton's wife and two children. The Stockbridge
killings took place before the Buckhead shootings, but it was
unclear exactly when, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Barton, a chemist who traded in his lab coat for the high-risk
life of an independent stock trader, also reportedly was a suspect
in the 1993 bludgeoning deaths of his former wife and her mother in
Cedar Bluff, Ala. He was never charged in those killings.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta shootings took place on a sweltering Atlanta day
when the Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped 180.78 points, a loss
of 1.6 percent, raising suspicions by investigators that recent
trading losses may have contributed to Barton's rampage.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened today is a tragedy of massive proportions,''
Campbell said Thursday afternoon, his face locked in a
sweat-dampened grimace. ``We are praying for the families and
praying for our city.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's incident marked the third shooting spree in the
Atlanta area in less than three months. On May 20, a 15-year-old
student at Heritage High School in nearby Conyers took a gun to
school and shot six students, none of them fatally, before being
captured by school administrators. Then on July 12, an Atlanta man
killed six members of a family before killing himself in an
apparent domestic dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings in Buckhead began around 2:50 p.m., when Barton,
dressed in shorts and a shirt, walked into the All-Tech Investment
Group office at Two Securities Center. Without warning or
provocation, he began to fire with two weapons. Barton had traded
at the office in the past but not recently, the company said in a
statement released from its headquarters in Montvale, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Barton ``came into our office and after speaking to the branch
manager, suddenly stood up and for no apparent reason opened fire
on the branch manager and his secretary,'' said the statement from
All-Tech. ``This man then went into our main trading room and began
indiscriminately shooting at our customers. The man then ran out of
our office and continued shooting in another part of the office
building.'' Four people were killed in that building.
</P>
<P>
   Barton managed to cross bustling Piedmont Road and walked into
another brokerage firm in Building 8 of Piedmont Center, a
sprawling office campus. He opened fire there as well, killing five
people, police said.
</P>
<P>
   For confused hours after the shootings, police seemed to have
few clues to Barton's whereabouts or his method of escape. Aided by
specially trained police teams, dogs and helicopters, a
suite-by-suite search was conducted of the buildings where the
shootings occurred, as well as the leafy grounds surrounding the
office parks. THe search came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no idea where Mr. Barton is,'' Campbell told reporters
late Thursday afternoon. ``We do not know whether he has fled the
scene on foot or by car.''
</P>
<P>
   But at about 8:20 p.m., Campbell returned to a bank of
microphones near the scene of the crimes and announced that
Barton's green Aerostar van had been pulled over by police in Cobb
County, just northwest of Atlanta. Barton committed suicide in the
vehicle, Campbell reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``This brings a very tragic day to an end,'' he said. ``I don't
know if any of us can understand why something like this occurs.
All we can do is comfort the families and pray for our city.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
