<HEADER>
A9184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODSTOCK-RAPES-NYT &LR;      07-29 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK-RAPES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE INVESTIGATE WOODSTOCK RAPES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Ohio, Pa.) (rk) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Amid growing reports of sexual assaults at last
weekend's Woodstock concert, the New York state police began
interviewing people who were crisis counselors at the show and
reviewed videotapes Thursday for evidence of rapes that the police
said occurred in the campground and near the main music stage.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Thursday, the police said they knew of four rapes at
the three-day event, in Rome, N.Y. Three of them were believed to
have occurred in Woodstock's sprawling 260-acre campground and to
have involved women who were dragged into tents and raped by one or
more men, said Capt. John Wood of the state police.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth woman was said to have been raped in the ``mosh pit'' _
a circle of body-slamming dancers _ directly in front of the stage
where the rap-metal band Limp Bizkit was playing on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs or alcohol, or a mixture of both, played a role in each
case, Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to those four cases, others who attended the
concert, or who knew people who did, suggested that at least two
other rapes occurred and that sexual abuse of women, including some
who went topless, happened frequently during the performances.
</P>
<P>
   Though Woodstock '99 had billed itself as a reincarnation of the
peace and love spirit of the original concert in 1969, news of the
rape allegations and the violent melee that ended the concert on
Sunday night have reduced the sprawling concert site, inside a
former Air Force base, to a somber crime scene. No one knows
exactly why it turned out that way, though the police and other
people, including some who paid $150 a ticket to attend the
festival, blamed the concert promoters for booking hardcore
rap-metal bands that provoke their fans to violence.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lang, the creator of all three Woodstock concerts,
conceded Thursday that if he could have last weekend back, he would
have chosen more mellow bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew it was coming, I might have done a little different
booking,'' Lang said in a telephone interview. ``I would have tried
not to have had as edgy a bill as we had. I would have programmed
the days better, tried to spread them out a bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the bands were not to blame for the concert's list
of problems and that many of today's most popular performers, like
Korn, Limp Bizkit and Rage Against the Machine, all of which played
at Woodstock '99, make crowd control extremely difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``They generate a lot more excitement in the audience, a lot of
spontaneity and intense energy,'' Lang said. ``You can't just sort
of stop that. You have to let people to come back gradually. It's
just sort of hard to regulate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the three rapes in the Woodstock campground each
occurred in tents and involved men not known by the women they
attacked. The first assault happened around 11 p.m. Friday, Wood
said, when an unidentified white man dragged a 32-year-old Ohio
woman into a tent. About 24 hours later, a 20-year-old Buffalo,
N.Y., woman was assaulted on Saturday night in a tent by a man she
had met in the campground, the captain said.
</P>
<P>
   The third assault at the campground, he said, was between 2 and
4 p.m. on Sunday, when as many as three men attacked a 20-year-old
Virginia woman in a tent after they had taken the designer drug
Ecstasy. ``She just woke up in a tent unfamiliar to her and she
realized she had been sexually assaulted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth woman, 24 and from Pittsburgh, was sexually assaulted
by two men around 9 p.m. on Saturday as all three stood near the
mosh pit as hardcore rap-metal band Limp Bizkit played before
thousands of delirious fans.
</P>
<P>
   The woman told the police both men raped her in the mass of
people. ``After the incident,'' Wood said, reviewing the woman's
account, ``she figures that the best way to get out of there was to
body surf. She asked somebody in the crowd to help her on out. They
hoisted her up and she body surfs on out.''
</P>
<P>
   In three of the cases, the police were told of the rapes after
the women sought help in medical tents around the concert. The
woman from Buffalo returned home and went to see a doctor there,
who reported the case to the state police, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the men who committed the rapes will be difficult, the
police said. ``We're dealing with hundreds of thousands of people
from all over the United States,'' Wood said. ``The victims are
unacquainted with the perpetrators, they can't give us a name, and
these people have scattered.''
</P>
<P>
   With few other avenues, the police will review 65 hours of
Woodstock television coverage, as well as videotape from cameras
connected to cranes that roamed over the crowd near the stages
during performances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
