<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9187 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ICECREAM-AD-COLUMN-NY     07-29 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICECREAM-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: ICE-CREAM MAKERS SUFFER THROUGH HOT SUMMER OF FLAT
SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Pa.)   (af)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   July has been declared National Ice Cream Month by one of the
industry's chief trade groups, and, with local conditions
resembling one of the circles of hell, far be it from us to argue.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it is hard not to notice the relentless
marketing that ice-cream makers have put in place _ from movie
tie-ins to associations with Nascar drivers to spinoff products
like candy and children's clothing. Such tactics are a sign that
the titans of ice cream are experiencing a competitive inferno of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Americans consume an average of 23.3 quarts of ice
cream a person each year, sales in grocery stores are flat and have
been for some time. Profits are equally uninspired, especially when
dairy prices are relatively high. Companies that manage to grow do
so by snatching market share, sparking battles that have grown
particularly intense lately.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the efforts of Dreyer's Grand Ice Cream Inc., the
industry giant based in Oakland, Calif., which had $1 billion in
sales last year. Dreyer's markets its ice cream as Edy's on the
East Coast, and also produces Starbuck's and Godiva ice creams.
</P>
<P>
   The company has posted two consecutive money-losing quarters,
which it blames on a variety of developments, including butterfat
prices, discounting by competitors and the loss of a Ben &AMP; Jerry's
distribution contract. The company is tapping all kinds of sources
_ National Football League teams, movies, the Nascar driver Jeff
Gordon, even the Girl Scouts _ to try to bring in better results.
</P>
<P>
   The latest effort is built around Mia Hamm, the star forward for
the United States soccer team that won the Women's World Cup last
month. Ms. Hamm's photograph, in a charging-down-the-field pose,
appears on cartons of the company's frozen yogurt, and Dreyer's is
sponsoring a contest in which the top prize is a soccer clinic, led
by Ms. Hamm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our original intent was to find a figure who was very much
tied to the family element, and soccer is a huge piece of America's
fall time period with their children,'' said Mary Gold, managing
director for marketing at Dreyer's. The deal was locked up several
months ago, she added. ``We happened to like what Mia stood for as
a figure. We had no idea the team would win the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has not always been so lucky. Last year it decided
to bet on the movie ``Godzilla,'' marketing an ice-cream flavor
called Godzilla Vanilla, which was sold in grocery stores beneath a
giant cardboard cutout of enormous claws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been nervous, because the movie met with lukewarm
receptions in theaters,'' Miss Gold admitted. ``But there were a
lot of families that didn't even go to see the movie, but bought
the ice cream.''
</P>
<P>
   Practically the same thing happened this year, when the company
licensed the rights to ``Wild, Wild West,'' another movie that has
fallen short of the expectations fostered by its extensive advance
hype. Again, Miss Gold insisted, ice cream sales appeared to be
doing fine despite the movie's reviews.
</P>
<P>
   A big name in the superpremium category is also going into high
gear to win over consumers. At Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade Inc., the
last few weeks have seen the release of a limited-edition flavor
called Marbled Mint Chunk; a line of frozen smoothies, meant to
capitalize on the popularity of juice-bar smoothies; a new
ice-cream sandwich concept, named after s'mores, that old campfire
standby, and a fleet of ``Scoop Trucks,'' which dispense free ice
cream in six United States cities, all to try to improve sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like giving away ice cream,'' noted Mary Lou
Kelley, the company's director of product marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dreyer's plans to launch its own line of Ben &AMP;
Jerry's-style superpremium ice cream in September. The brand, to be
called Dreamery, will include flavors named Banana Boogie, Black
Raspberry Avalanche and Chocolate Truffle Explosion, a spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kelley said Ben &AMP; Jerry's was aware of the Dreyer's move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we make the best product and we deliver what our
consumers love and we're focusing on our own business,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy's Microbatch, a comparatively tiny, year-old company
based in Philadelphia, is also handing out free samples and coupons
for free pints. The company's top five markets, all in the
Northeast, have what are known as ``Secret Service teams'' whose
mission is to conduct what a spokeswoman called ``guerrilla
marketing,'' using a combination of samples, T-shirts, magnets and
stickers to pique people's interest in the product.
</P>
<P>
   The spokeswoman, Michele Parenteau, refused to disclose sales
figures, though she said the products were on sale in 6,000 places,
up from 1,000 in January.
</P>
<P>
   Some ice-cream makers are turning to the clothing business to
try to improve grocery-store numbers. Klondike bars, owned by
Unilever PLC, are about to be interpreted as children's jackets and
pajamas, thanks to a recently concluded licensing agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go after things that are more in tune with creamy
ice cream, rather than the vivid colors of a Popsicle,'' said
Carole Francesca, president of Broad Street Licensing, which
handles the rights to both Klondike and Popsicle, another Unilever
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Francesca's company refurbished Popsicle's image last year,
trying to make it more ``edgy,'' in her words, and more appealing
to children on the verge of adolescence. ``It's very kidlike, but
very today,'' she said of the new look, which is built around
bright colors and zippy lettering.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the company is trying to extend the brand into
areas including clothing (Popsicle tank tops and shoes) and candy
(products meant to taste like Creamsicles are to be on sale next
year). And the nostalgia audience hasn't been forgotten, Ms.
Francesca said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are regenerating artwork from the '50s and '60s on
products, everything from the Franklin Mint to collectible
Christmas ornaments,'' she said. Earlier this summer, she added, a
revival of the ``Polly Popsicle'' doll, along with her friends
Freddy Fudgsicle and Carrie Creamsicle, sold out on the Home
Shopping Network almost immediately. And there were no calories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
