<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRST-UNION-RETIRE-AR     07-29 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRST-UNION-RETIRE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 FIRST UNION, FACING DOUBTS, SAYS ITS PRESIDENT WILL RETIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing to wrestle with severe problems unleashed by a
botched merger and a troubled business strategy, First Union Corp.
announced Thursday that its president, John R. Georgius, would
retire by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Georgius, 54, will be succeeded by G. Kennedy Thompson, 48, who
currently oversees the capital markets business at First Union, the
nation's sixth largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   The move followed an unscheduled board meeting at the company's
Charlotte, N.C., headquarters that fueled speculation on Wall
Street that First Union might be taken over or that its chief
executive, Edward E. Crutchfield, might lose his job because of the
bank's travails.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of those scenarios came to pass Thursday, though, and
people close to the bank said that Crutchfield was determined to
see the bank through its current woes.
</P>
<P>
   In trading Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange, shares of
First Union rose $1.125, or 2.4 percent, to $48, on a day that saw
most bank stocks and the broader market beaten down.
</P>
<P>
   Georgius' future at the bank came into question in May after
First Union, a bank formed through costly, rapid-fire acquisitions,
warned that profits for the second quarter and the year would fall
far below previous estimates. It was the second time this year that
First Union had to revise earnings estimates sharply downward, and
it left the bank with a credibility problem and doubts among
analysts and investors about its future.
</P>
<P>
   Georgius, who said in an interview in May that he thought his
job was secure, has overseen First Union's ``future bank''
initiative. That strategy aimed to make the company a leader in the
electronic delivery of banking services through such channels as
the telephone and the Internet but has fallen well short of that
goal thus far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of First Union's growth and accomplishments, and I'm
confident in the direction the company is going,'' Georgius said in
a statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bank cast Georgius' retirement as a lifestyle
decision, executives close to the company said that his departure
was forced because of First Union's problems. To a large extent,
Georgius is taking the fall for Crutchfield's mistakes. Crutchfield
has been the leading architect of First Union's merger spree, which
ran into serious problems after last year's expensive and bungled
takeovers of Corestates Financial Corp. and Money Store Inc.
</P>
<P>
   First Union posted second-quarter operating earnings of $801
million, down 9.3 percent from about $883 million in the period a
year earlier. Revenue in the quarter was stagnant at $3.55 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed that it's taken the board this long to act,'' said
Nancy Bush, an analyst with Ryan Beck &AMP; Co.. ``There's always been
the potential at First Union that's never realized. As a customer
of the bank, it's my dream that they're bought by Wells Fargo.''
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts said they had faith that First Union would be
able to right itself and forestall an outright takeover. They also
made note of the strong underlying power of First Union's earnings,
which, even though they are depressed, are still among the best in
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always thought that this is a company that has
problems, but it's not broken,'' said Sandra Flannigan, an analyst
with Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.. ``In our opinion, the stock is
undervalued, and for people who can be patient, this should be a
great investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, many of whom blindly took First Union's earnings
projections to heart last year, have been largely skeptical about
the company's more recent promises to revive profitability. But the
bank, which will roll out new strategic initiatives in meetings
with analysts next week, said it was confident it would reach
earnings targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fully expect to meet our previously announced earnings
projections,'' said Virginia Mackin, a First Union spokeswoman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, First Union's new president, also was named to the
bank's board of directors Thursday and has emerged as the leading
candidate to succeed Crutchfield if First Union remains
independent. Thompson is a well regarded executive who has won
praise for his effective management of the bank's capital markets
business, which involves such activities as mergers and
acquisitions advice, syndicated lending, and debt and equity
underwriting.
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson, a 23-year veteran of First Union, does not have
extensive experience in consumer banking, and that is where First
Union is having its most significant problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply changing one member of senior management without
significantly changing strategy or tactics is not enough to change
the short-term outlook for the bank,'' said Diane Glossman, an
analyst at Lehman Brothers Inc. ``Until we see what they do with
`future bank,' nothing changes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
