<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9196 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTISPY-TRAINING-NYT &LR;      07-29 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTISPY-TRAINING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY SECRETARY ORDERS SECURITY TRAINING AT DEFENSE-RELATED
FACILITIES
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Colo., Ga., Idaho, Mo., Nev., Tenn., Texas, Wash.) 
 (sw) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Energy Secretary Bill Richardson has ordered a
one-day stand-down next week of many of the Energy Department's
research and defense-related operations for counter-espionage and
security training in the wake of charges that China had stolen
nuclear secrets from a government weapons laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson ordered the department's defense-related facilities,
except its three nuclear weapons laboratories, shut down on Aug. 3
for mandatory security training, including sessions on computer
security. The government's nuclear weapons labs _ Los Alamos,
Sandia and Lawrence Livermore _ had already completed
security-related stand-downs and are not covered by the new order.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson had ordered a work stoppage in April at the three
nuclear weapons laboratories, when classified computer networks
containing nuclear weapons secrets were shut down for two weeks.
Richardson had also ordered cyber-security training at the labs
after learning that Wen Ho Lee, a scientist at Los Alamos who has
been questioned during the FBI's investigation of China's possible
theft of nuclear secrets, had downloaded extensive data on nuclear
weapons from a classified computer system into an unclassified
network. There was also evidence that someone had accessed those
files once they were in the unsecure system.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was fired in March for alleged security violations. A
federal grand jury in Albuquerque, N.M., has been hearing evidence
in the Los Alamos espionage case, but Lee has not been charged. His
lawyer, Mark C.Holscher of Los Angeles, has stated that his client
is not guilty of the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has been scheduled to speak publicly about the case for the
first time on the CBS program ``60 Minutes'' on Sunday. On the
program, Lee stated that he did download secret information from a
classified computer to a nonclassified one at Los Alamos, but that
he did so only as a routine part of his job, according to a news
release by ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and Energy Department failed to monitor Lee's computer
use for nearly three years while he was under investigation, in
part because the Justice Department rejected an FBI request to seek
court authorization to wiretap and monitor him electronically.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the government's handling of the case had
prompted Richardson to take a series of high-profile steps to
tighten security at the labs. He had focused much of his attention
on the need for greater computer security, both at the laboratories
and throughout the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   Next week's stand-down at the defense-related sites had been
recommended by the Energy Department's new security chief, Eugene
Habiger, a retired Air Force general and former chief of the U.S.
Strategic Command.
</P>
<P>
   He had urged Richardson to extend the computer and security
training already mandated for the nuclear weapons labs to
defense-related facilities that handle classified information but
which had not yet been subject to intensive review.
</P>
<P>
   ``The security problems at DOE extend to sites beyond the
nuclear weapons labs,'' Richardson said in an interview. ``We've
had problems with safeguards and security at some of the
non-weapons sites, some of which have received low security
ratings. We are sending a signal to the employees that security is
a top priority.''
</P>
<P>
   The facilities affected by the stand-down will be Savannah
River, in Georgia; the Y-12 plant at Oak Ridge, Tenn.; the Pantex
plant in Amarillo, Texas; the Idaho National Engineering and
Environmental Lab in Idaho; the Hanford nuclear site in Richland,
Wash.; the Nevada test site near Las Vegas; the Rocky Flats
facility near Denver, and the Allied Signal plant in Kansas City,
Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at the facilities will be required to attend a series
of security-related seminars, including cyber-security, export
regulations, terrorism and how to handle disgruntled employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
