<HEADLINE>
RENO DENIES REPORT THAT SHE'LL RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno said Thursday that she
had no plans to step down and disputed reports that she was
considering resigning to become the dean at a Florida law school.
</P>
<P>
   There had been speculation in legal circles that Reno, who is 61
and the longest-serving attorney general this century, might leave
before the end of President Clinton's second term.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Reno denied a report in Washingtonian Magazine, a
monthly publication, that she was close to accepting the dean's
post at the Florida State University College of Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never wanted to be dean of a law school,'' Reno told
reporters at her weekly Justice Department news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about how long Reno will remain as the country's top
legal officer seem to be fueled in part by concerns about her
health.
</P>
<P>
   She has Parkinson's disease, a degenerative nerve condition, and
some aides have said the symptomatic tremors in her hands and arms
have noticeably increased. Reno has said she feels no ill effects
from her condition.
</P>
<P>
   When she was asked Thursday whether she would resign before
Clinton left office, she said, ``As I've told you before, I always
take it a day at a time, but I know of no reason why I would
change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
