u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DETROIT-CASINO-730&AMP;AD     07-29 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DETROIT-CASINO-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETROIT, STILL BLIGHTED, PUTS HOPES IN CASINOS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ With glittering lights and the roll of dice, a casino
opened here Thursday, the first of a number of promised attractions
that Detroit is counting on to bring long-lost prosperity back to
its blighted streets.
</P>
<P>
   The MGM Grand Detroit is the first of three casinos due to open
before the end of the year, making Detroit the largest city in the
United States with casinos. Two new sports stadiums will follow
close on their heels, and the momentum has helped persuade the
Compuware Corp., maker of software, to announce plans to move its
headquarters and 6,000 workers downtown from the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The three casinos are expected to add 7,000 to 8,000 jobs in
Detroit, where the unemployment rate, 7 percent, is more than
double the suburban rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The casino represents a piece of the puzzle that will be of
enormous help that will enhance the city's economy and image,''
Mayor Dennis Archer said. ``People will want to come to Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Henry Ford invented the assembly line, Detroit has
been a gritty city; only the fleeting glamour of the Motown era
interrupted its dirt-under-the-nails image. But just as Las Vegas
used a string of casinos to transform itself from a lonely stretch
of desert to a neon mecca, Detroit is hoping that opening casinos
and building ballparks will make it a tourist destination as well.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of adding tens of millions of dollars to annual tax
revenue persuaded a once-skeptical electorate to vote last spring
to allow three casinos here. The three will eventually be situated
on the city's waterfront, right across the Detroit River from a
pair of competitors: government-run casinos in Windsor, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Until those permanent Detroit casinos can be built, the city
will make do with three temporary, less expensive versions,
including the $220 million MGM Grand, which sits next to a highway
downtown. They will stay open 24 hours a day, every day of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   At the MGM Grand, owned by the Las Vegas casino giant of the
same name, bright lights beckon visitors to slot machines, some of
which cost just a nickel to play. There are 80 table games _
blackjack or baccarat, pai gow or poker _ along with three
restaurants, where gamblers can have something as simple as
macaroni and cheese or as steady as a steak.
</P>
<P>
   Except for all the card tables and slot machines, the place
looks like a strip club. Most of the decorations are of the
two-legged variety, well-built young women wearing white-and-gold
outfits cut low in front and high behind. These are the Grandettes,
the waitresses and hostesses who serve up drinks and smiles to the
customers.
</P>
<P>
   By winter, two more casinos are expected to open. And then
thoughts will turn to the two new stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Tigers will play their last home game at historic
Tiger Stadium on Sept. 27 and will start up next April at Comerica
Park, which construction crews have been working on all year. The
new stadium, made of light brown brick, will replace one of the two
oldest major league ball parks; Tiger Stadium opened on the same
day in 1912 as Fenway Park in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford family, which owns the Detroit Lions, has promised to
build a $225 million football stadium next to the baseball park
and, says Thomas J. Lewand, the Lions' vice president, could break
ground for it by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Having pro football games downtown again will itself benefit
Detroit, which long ago lost the Lions to suburban Pontiac. But
developers say the double-stadium complex is planned specifically
not only to draw suburbanites into the city but to keep them there
for a few extra hours.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ilitch, owner of the Tigers and the Detroit Red Wings
hockey team, said that he planned a number of retail stores and
restaurants and even a children's carousel in the stadium complex
and that an Embassy Suites hotel would sprout just beyond right
field. The last new hotel here was built two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ilitch believes that while the casinos will provide thousands of
jobs, their impact on the city as a whole could be overstated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the people, when they go into the casinos, are not
going to leave them,'' he said. ``There's some spinoff from the
casinos, but I don't think they're going to be the saviors by any
means.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, a momentum has been created in Detroit, and
``the city will turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, it has a long way to go. Race riots in 1967 caused
the flight of tens of thousands of white residents, which in turn
left this the nation's poorest big city. Detroit hit bottom in the
1980s, when a recession caused widespread layoffs in the auto
industry just as crack hit the streets of the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, boarded-up skyscrapers mar the downtown skyline, and
on hot days people with nowhere better to be can be found whiling
away the hours under trees in vacant lots, trying to stay cool.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor hopes to help some of those people, too, with taxes
collected from the casinos. The city and the state will divide 18
percent of the gross profits from the casinos _ 55 percent of the
tax share goes to Detroit and 45 percent to Michigan, which plans
to spend the money on educational grants statewide. The city
expects $250 million in casino taxes in the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   Laying down their share will be people like Leona Monit, 49, a
waitress from nearby Garden City, Mich. She said the casino would
bring both good and bad to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good is a lot of jobs,'' said Ms. Monit, who was so eager
to wager at the MGM Grand that she lined up two hours before it
opened at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad is a lot of people are going to gamble who can't
afford to,'' said Ms. Monit, who by 7:30 said she was even for the
night, playing slots.
</P>
<P>
   Among some of the gamblers, there was a buy-at-home sentiment.
Gloria Wheeler, 58, who works on a pickup truck assembly line in
Pontiac and was playing the slots Thursday, said that she had been
driving to the casinos in Windsor but that ``it is better to turn
over the money in the city.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
