<SLUG> BC-PHONE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-DISTANCE GIANTS REPORT SOLID RESULTS FOR QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's two largest long-distance telephone carriers, AT&AMP;T
Corp. and MCI Worldcom Inc., Thursday announced strong quarterly
financial results _ propelled, paradoxically, by just about
everything except long-distance telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's results underscored the fact that at the
long-distance industry's highest levels, the big growth
opportunities are not to be found in telephones anymore, at least
not in the kind of phones that plug into wall jacks.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the recipe for growth in the long-distance business
seems to be to expand into new markets while chopping costs in the
old ones.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, MCI Worldcom's pro forma revenue from standard
phone service rose only 5.6 percent over the comparable period last
year, while revenue from corporate data services increased 29.1
percent and Internet revenue grew 59.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from international services increased 55.6 percent. (The
pro forma figures are calculated as if Worldcom and MCI were
already a combined company in the comparable period of 1998, and
they exclude MCI Worldcom's interest in Embratel, a Brazilian
communications company.)
</P>
<P>
   The combined performance fueled overall pro forma revenue growth
of about 10.4 percent, to $8.3 billion from $7.5 billion in the
comparable period of 1998. At the same time, MCI Worldcom, the No.
2 long-distance carrier, cut operating expenses to $6.5 billion
from $6.7 billion in the second quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The revenue growth and cost cuts helped create a 175 percent
rise in pro forma earnings per diluted share, from 16 cents to 44
cents. Those earnings matched estimates by analysts surveyed by the
First Call Corp., a financial research firm.
</P>
<P>
   When Worldcom's acquisition of MCI and its investment in
Embratel are taken into effect, reported revenue for the company
increased to $8.9 billion from $2.6 billion. Earnings rose to 45
cents a share from 21 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Taken in a vacuum, the figures for AT&AMP;T, the No. 1 long-distance
carrier and the nation's biggest communications company, were not
as strong as MCI Worldcom's. But in the context of AT&AMP;T's
continuing awakening from slumber, the company's results were at
least as impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Showing AT&AMP;T's fastest growth in three years, the company's pro
forma revenue increased 6.7 percent, to $15.8 billion from $14.8
billion in the comparable period of 1998. The pro forma figures are
calculated as if AT&AMP;T had already completed its acquisitions of
Tele-Communications Inc. and of parts of IBM's Global Network unit
by the second quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Including the TCI and IBM deals, but discounting one-time
charges and gains and discounting some outside investments, AT&AMP;T
reported earnings of 49 cents, or $1.6 billion, down from 54 cents
a share, or $1.47 billion in the same period last year. The
per-share dilution was an effect of AT&AMP;T's issuing shares in the
TCI acquisition, but the 49 cent per-share figure beat the
consensus estimate of analysts polled by First Call by a penny.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest sign of strength for AT&AMP;T came in its wireless unit,
which posted a revenue gain of 42.4 percent, to $1.8 billion from
$1.3 billion, excluding AT&AMP;T's acquisition of Vanguard Cellular
Systems Inc. and the sale of AT&AMP;T's paging business.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most important figure in AT&AMP;T's results
reflected the company's sales, general and administrative spending,
which is often seen as a reflection of a company's ``leanness.''
AT&AMP;T spent 22.1 percent of its revenue on such expenses in the
latest quarter as it pared its work force, a big drop from the
comparable period of 1998, when that figure was 25.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called SG&AMP;A figure has long been a benchmark for Worldcom
managers, who had pushed that figure to less than 20 percent before
acquiring MCI. In the last quarter, the figure for MCI Worldcom was
24.4 percent, though SG&AMP;A figures cannot be compared directly
because different companies calculate them in slightly different
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Showing the effect of the TCI and IBM deals, AT&AMP;T reported
quarterly revenue of $15.7 billion, up from $13.2 billion in the
comparable period of 1998. Earnings increased to $1.6 billion, or
49 cents a share, from $1.1 billion, or 42 cents a share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
