</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARYLAND-DROUGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PARCHED MARYLAND, GOVERNOR DECLARES DROUGHT EMERGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the nation's capital and the surrounding region
continued to bake through a long, hot dry spell, Gov. Parris
Glendening of Maryland on Thursday declared the first statewide
drought emergency in his state's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This drought is a serious problem,'' the governor said, ``but
we do not intend to let it become unmanageable.''
</P>
<P>
   Glendening spoke from the edge of the Liberty Reservoir, which
serves the Baltimore area. The reservoir's water level is 24 feet
below normal, and two other reservoirs are also very low, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, if water consumption continues at the current
rate, there is only a 35-day supply in these reservoirs,''
Glendening said, noting that the three reservoirs served more than
1.8 million people in Greater Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's declaration, accompanied by pledges of financial
aid for farmers whose crops have been stunted, included a long list
of suggestions for conserving water: Take shorter showers, do not
wash cars, leave the lawn and flowers to the mercy of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   But Glendening said conservation measures might not be voluntary
for long. He has formed a drought task force that will submit
recommendations for water-use restrictions within a week.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a spokeswoman for Mayor Anthony Williams said
city officials were continuing to monitor the Potomac River, which
supplies the city's water. The river is running below normal for
this time of year, but there is no need yet for emergency
restrictions, the mayor's representative said.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, a drought task force has been meeting regularly, a
spokesman for Gov. James Gilmore said. Water supplies are still
adequate in most parts of the state, though there have been
scattered problems in central and western Virginia, the spokesman
said. If the dry spell goes on, it could cause forest fires, he
warned.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the summer, daytime high temperatures in Washington,
parts of Maryland and in the Virginia suburbs of the capital have
been well over 90, nothing unusual for the region in June, July and
August.
</P>
<P>
   But rainfall has been well below normal. From May 29 through
Thursday, Baltimore County had 3.8 inches of rain, just under half
of normal, the National Weather Service said. The District of
Columbia and the Virginia suburbs recorded 3.2 inches, just over 40
percent of normal.
</P>
<P>
   But the water scarcity was not created in two months. The region
usually has mild winters, and last winter was not only mild but
almost free of snow. There was only light rainfall in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland, especially, has been hard-hit. For the last three
years, rain and snow have been far below normal, Glendening noted.
Crops have dried up _ the governor's drought declaration provides
for $3 million in emergency assistance for farmers _ fish have died
in the Chesapeake Bay, and wild fires have been epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the weather around Washington has often been
humid, as though the sky is ready to unleash torrents of rainfall.
Sometimes, the sky has become tantalizingly purple; there have been
ominous breezes and rumbles of thunder.
</P>
<P>
   And then, too often, there have been only a few drops of rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we did get normal rainfall over the next few months,
the drought could continue to worsen,'' the Weather Service noted
in a statement released on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9205 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACCOMPANY-ACCOMPANY_S     07-29 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCOMPANY-ACCOMPANY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   E-Tailer Wins Backing of Marc Andreessen 
 &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Accompany Inc., the San Francisco startup that aims to change the
way goods are bought on the Internet, has won the support of one of
Silicon Valley's well-known wunderkind.
<P>
   Netscape co-founder Marc Andreessen, 28, has invested about
$500,000 in the year-old company, and Accompany announced yesterday
that he has become a director. He joins Forbes magazine Publisher
Rich Karlgaard, Mayfield Fund general partner Kevin Fong and
Accompany CEO Jim Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accompany lets individuals and small businesses get the same
discount prices previously reserved for large companies,'' said
Andreessen, now chief technology officer at America Online.
``Aggregated buying is the next wave in e-commerce, and Accompany
is leading the way.`'
</P>
<P>
   In traditional online auctions like those run by eBay, the
greater the number of bidders, the higher the prices. That's good
for sellers but not buyers. Accompany Inc. is out to change this
e-commerce equation by allowing multiple bidders to drive down
prices. In other words, the more buyers, the greater the discounts
on digital cameras, computers and scores of other goods.
</P>
<P>
   Another company that is letting individuals and small businesses
band together for volume discounts is Mercata Inc., the Bellevue,
Wash., company financed by Microsoft billionaire Paul Allen's
Vulcan Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Accompany has raised about $5 million of private
financing, including about $3.5 million from Mayfield Fund of Menlo
Park. Accompany was started last year by Rose, 25, who studied
comparative cultures at Duke University before becoming a
management consultant and shifting his focus to comparison shopping
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred thousand web browsers visit  &LR; www.accompany.com
 &LR; each month, according to Rose, and up to 5,000 make purchases. He
said they pay from 5 to 30 percent less than they would for a
single unit of the same product at another e-tailer. On Wednesday,
for example, 50 Accompany customers bought Palm V handheld
computers for $315 each. By contrast, the best price among 44
online merchants tracked by Cnet was $347.95.
</P>
<P>
   Accompany's prices to buyers include the 2.5 to 9 percent
commissions the company takes on each purchase. Accompany now lists
only about 200 products a day, much less than Mercata's.
</P>
<P>
   Accompany's offerings also are less diverse. Although it offers
the occasional Weber portable grill, Big Bertha golf club or Pierre
Cardin luggage, Mercata now has many more listings outside the
electronics niche.
</P>
<P>
   When consumers bid on Accompany, there is no certainty how low
the final price will be. Volume discounts ultimately depend on how
many others submit bids. The only guarantee is that prices won't go
up.
</P>
<P>
   Andreessen believes that Accompany, Mercata and perhaps a few
other companies are poised to build big businesses. ``One of the
underappreciated aspects of the Net is that it lends itself to ad
hoc group formation,'' he said. ``Chat rooms may not be big
moneymakers, but letting individuals band together to get discount
pricing is a killer idea. Everyone will want to be part of the
biggest buying club.''
</P>
<P>
   The July 26 issue of ComputerLetter published by Technologic
Partners suggests that the manufacturer's suggested retail price
could be an endangered species. It notes that nine
comparison-shopping engines have been acquired by bigger online
companies during the past two years for between $17 million and
$180 million.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Amazon.com bought Junglee, Yahoo acquired ViaWeb,
America Online purchased PersonaLogic, Microsoft bought CompareNet
and Cnet acquired KillerApp.
</P>
<P>
   These services let prospective buyers browse for bargains and
buy online. Returns, repairs and service can be a problem, but
ComputerLetter editorial director Jack Wilson believes that pricing
and procurement services have a bright future. ``One of the great
uses of the Web is to put individuals or small businesses together
into buying conglomerates that have more clout,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
