<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9207 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CABLE-CABLE_SFCHRON &LR;      07-29 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-CABLE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Two Companies Will Help Consumers Skirt AT&AMP;T's Lock on
Cable  System 
 &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
While San Francisco may not have forced AT&AMP;T to open its cable
system to competitors just yet, some Bay Area residents still will
get a choice for high-speed Internet access via cable TV lines.
<P>
   Two companies, RCN Corp. of New Jersey and Seren Innovations of
Minnesota, are building state-of-the-art digital cable systems in
parts of the Bay Area. They plan to offer high-speed Internet
connections, digital TV and local and long-distance phone service
over their networks.
</P>
<P>
   RCN, which plans to build a system that stretches across the Bay
Area, is laying fiber in San Francisco, San Mateo, Daly City, South
San Francisco and Redwood City. It plans to start offering service
to some customers by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Seren is building a fiber-optic network in Concord and plans to
expand to Walnut Creek, Danville, Pleasant Hill, Clayton and
unincorporated parts of Contra Costa county. The system should be
up and running in Concord by the end of this year as well.
</P>
<P>
   By constructing two-way digital networks, both companies will be
the Bay Area's first challengers to TCI Cable, which has been the
main provider of cable TV in the region. RCN and Seren also will be
the region's first viable competitors to Pacific Bell for local
phone service.
</P>
<P>
   Their entrance is important in the wake of an intense debate
between AT&AMP;T, which now owns TCI Cable, and Internet service
providers, such as America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, AT&AMP;T is the only choice in the Bay Area for cable
modem service. Although the technology is available only in about
41 Bay Area communities so far, AT&AMP;T is spending billions to
upgrade its cable plants in San Francisco and other cities to
handle high-speed Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T offers customers cable Internet connections 50 to 100 times
faster than traditional dial-up modems through its affiliate,
Redwood City's ExciteAtHome.
</P>
<P>
   AOL and other ISPs want to offer their customers superfast
Internet connections as well and have been fighting with AT&AMP;T over
access to TCI's cable lines. AOL and ISPs want ``open access'' so
that their customers can get cable modem access without having to
go through ExciteAtHome.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, where the issue recently was debated, AOL and
its supporters complained that AT&AMP;T and ExciteAtHome would have a
monopoly on high-speed Internet access if other ISPs could not
piggyback on AT&AMP;T's lines. City officials disagreed on Monday,
saying they would wait several months before deciding whether to
force AT&AMP;T to open its network.
</P>
<P>
   But industry watchers say competition from RCN and Seren most
likely will prompt AT&AMP;T to open its network. And consumer advocates
say it will lead to cheaper prices and better service.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T is going to have to make a decision _ do we encourage
other people to come in and build another system, or do we allow
people to come on and use our network?'' said Frank Murphy, a
telecommunications analyst with First Union Capital Markets in
Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said AT&AMP;T probably will choose the latter so it can make
money off the companies that use its lines, instead of losing
business to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   RCN officials say they welcome open access and will make their
lines available to other ISPs who want to pay for the access.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's little rationale for not having open access,'' said
Paul Sigmund, RCN's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Seren officials said they will decide on open access once their
network is built.
</P>
<P>
   Even without open access, RCN and Seren plan to offer
competitive prices to AT&AMP;T and TCI.
</P>
<P>
   Seren offers discounts on bundled packages of cable, phone and
Net services in the areas where it operates. The company has not
set prices for Contra Costa, but it charges about $40 per month for
Internet service and between $12 and $35 for cable TV in
Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston and Washington, D.C., RCN charges $31 per month for
cable TV but offers a discount to customers if they also purchase
another service. Its cable Internet service is about $40 per month,
the same price as ExciteAtHome's.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said RCN's attitude and pricing has made the company a
success in markets where it competes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Manhattan, when RCN builds out a network and starts
offering service, they have more than a 50 percent acceptance
rate,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that because RCN is building its network from scratch,
it's more up to date than TCI's cable, which is more than 20 years
old in some cities, including San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition is good, and customers will benefit from having a
choice,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
