<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9210 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AOL-AOL_SFCHRON &LR;      07-29 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-AOL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Net Instant Messaging Sides Forming  &HT;     By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The nation's most prominent technology companies may be forced to
choose sides in the skirmish over Internet instant messaging.
<P>
   America Online said yesterday that it would team up with Apple
Computer to develop new products that will allow Macintosh
customers to communicate in real time with users of AOL's Instant
Messenger (AIM) service.
</P>
<P>
   The move threatens to pit AOL and Apple against Microsoft, Yahoo
and a host of smaller instant messaging companies, who are
clamoring for open standards in the market.
</P>
<P>
   They accuse AOL of hijacking the instant messaging space and
denying consumers the right to conduct chat sessions with whomever
they wish. AOL, in turn, says Microsoft is bulldozing its way into
the market at AOL's expense.
</P>
<P>
   AOL said it formed an advisory group that includes its chief
technology officer, Marc Andreessen, and Apple interim chief
executive Steve Jobs to set standards for sending instant messages
online.
</P>
<P>
   The group includes Sun Microsystems Inc. Chief Scientist Bill
Joy, Novell Inc. Chairman Eric Schmidt and RealNetworks Inc.
Chairman Rob Glaser. Microsoft was also invited to join the group.
</P>
<P>
   As things stand now, the 40 million users of AIM officially can
only exchange online instant messages with one another and not with
friends and family members who use a competing product, such as
Microsoft's new MSN Messenger or Yahoo Messenger.
</P>
<P>
   But AOL is now saying it will create software that will allow
Mac users to chat online with friends and colleagues who are part
of AOL's Instant Messenger network. The companies were
intentionally vague about details. Officials declined to say
exactly what new products were in the works or when they would be
available.
</P>
<P>
   Apple of Cupertino has become a more significant force in the
computer world with the success of its candy-colored iMac
computers. In June, Apple was the No.3 PC-maker in retail and mail
order sales, with 11.2 percent of the market, according to PC Data.
</P>
<P>
   Instant messaging programs, which can be downloaded free off the
Internet, are wildly popular among Web surfers. The software is
used to locate ``buddies'' online and send and receive text
messages in real time.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry watchers believe the AOL-Apple deal has clear and
ominous implications. ``AOL is trying to create its own standards
body,'' said Rob Enderle, an analyst with Giga Information Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is that to get certified, you'll first need AOL's
approval.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Microsoft, Yahoo and others hope to adopt
standards created by an independent body that would allow their
messaging products to work with one another. Proponents of open
standards draw comparisons with e-mail, noting that it would be
ridiculous if a person running Lotus Notes could not exchange
messages with a business partner on, say, Microsoft Outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Though AOL and Apple are mum about future plans, there is some
speculation that next-generation versions of AIM &UR;  &LR; will come
preloaded on Apple's iMac computers.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dym, vice president of marketing at instant messaging
company Tribal Voice Inc. in Scotts Valley, said he was in
discussions earlier this year to co-brand his company's messaging
software on Apple products. ``It was a bit of an ego blow, but I
guess they decided to go with AOL,'' joked Dym.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL has built the biggest and best instant messaging service
in the world,'' Jobs said in a statement. ``We're partnering with
AOL to create instant messaging products that will further enhance
the Internet experience for Macintosh users.''
</P>
<P>
   An Apple spokesperson would not comment on whether the AOL deal
is exclusive or on Apple's position in the open standards debate.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say the AOL-Apple announcement is just a case of
bad timing and does not reflect Apple's intention to side with AOL
over Microsoft. ``This is not an agreement that was just thrown
together in the last week,'' said Mark Levitt, an analyst with IDC.
``This is more an indication that Apple is enjoying a successful
comeback and has partners like AOL who want to develop software for
its platform.''
</P>
<P>
   But some observers believe Apple, which eagerly accepted a $150
million investment from Microsoft two years ago, is straddling both
sides of the fence. ``This looks to be a classic case of
`coopetition,' said Richard Dym. ``Only in Silicon Valley can you
be friends and enemies at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hostilities between AOL and Microsoft first broke out last week
when Microsoft introduced its own instant messaging product called
MSN Messenger Service. It immediately raised eyebrows because,
unlike other messaging products, it boasted interoperability
features that tapped into AOL's offering.
</P>
<P>
   But AOL cried foul and said Microsoft was gaining unauthorized
access to its servers by asking people who downloaded the software
to first provide their AOL passwords. AOL attempted to block the
connection, but Microsoft continued to one-up AOL by releasing new
versions of its software that circumvent any attempts to stop it.
As of yesterday, Microsoft had released five versions of the
software in nearly as many days.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said it plans to release a version of MSN Instant
Messenger on the Mac platform by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
