<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON TALKS TAXES, BUT RESIDENCY ISSUE PERSISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(yn) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMIRA, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton came to this Republican
patch of upstate New York Thursday intent on embracing what
Democrats see as a major issue in next year's congressional
elections: The Republican drive to put through the largest federal
tax cut since 1982. But she also found herself again discussing the
question of whether someone who does not live in New York could
represent it in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, on her third week of touring the state since she
officially began exploring a Senate race, sought to frame her
latest ``listening forum'' around the Republican tax bill being
debated in Washington, which President Clinton has said he would
veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a debate going on in the Senate about a nearly $1
trillion Republican tax cut that I believe would damage most New
Yorkers,'' Mrs. Clinton said. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who is likely
to seek the Republican nomination for the Senate seat, declined
Thursday to say if he supports the proposal advanced by fellow
Republicans in Washington, though he has said he supports using
some of the federal surplus for a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Mrs. Clinton sought to turn the topic to Republican
fiscal policy with what were her most partisan remarks since she
began this tour, she twice found herself answering questions from
Elmira residents about her interest in representing a state where
she has never lived.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the residents were cordial, and afterward, both said
they were impressed by her answers. Nonetheless, their questions,
coming after the first lady has spent a fair amount of time in the
state _ and in a week in which Giuliani traveled to Little Rock,
Ark., where Mrs. Clinton used to live, to draw attention to the
issue _ suggest the task that Mrs. Clinton faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you become senator from New York state,'' asked David
Caton, a factory worker at the Hillard Corp. plant here, ``would
you work at getting a bill through that you have to be a resident
for `X' amount of time before you can run for office?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that would be a state decision,'' Mrs. Clinton responded
instantly. ``That's in the state constitution and it's state law.
So the people of New York would have to make whatever changes they
would make through their state Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Mrs. Clinton and Caton exchanged smiles and hand shakes,
she then called out with a grin: ``But I like it the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The question came up again at the end of the forum, when Jim
Davis, a registered Republican who is an executive with a natural
gas company here, told Mrs. Clinton that he admired her work in
Washington. ``But why did you choose New York, and how are you
going to overcome the carpetbagger question?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very fair question,'' Mrs. Clinton said. She said that
she and her husband had decided to live in New York before anyone
raised the idea of her running for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
