<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRTEEN MORE UMPS OUT; ONE-THIRD ARE NOW GONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From one of the two newest umpires to two of the
three most senior, the National League slashed 13 umpires from its
staff Thursday, accepting their resignations as the latest
development in the umpires' mass resignation strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Phillips, the umpires' labor leader, immediately
promised more action, vowing to ``fight to the death'' for the
umpires' jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The league did not announce the names of the umpires who will
lose their jobs Sept. 2, the effective date stated in the letters
of resignation they submitted July 15, then rescinded last Tuesday.
But various officials disclosed the names, and Phillips confirmed
10, declining to name the other three because he had not been able
to reach them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're angry,'' Phillips said after speaking with most of the
umpires. ``They feel that baseball's conduct is reprehensible and
oppressive. They feel this action of executing surrendered
prisoners is indicative of the mind-set of baseball today that has
led us to the position we're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with the American League's acceptance of nine
resignations on Monday, the Major League Umpires Association has
seen one-third of its 66 members lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, emerging from a two-day telephone silence, said he
vowed to each umpire who lost his job that ``I will fight
absolutely to the death,'' he said, adding: ``I will never rest
till I right this wrong. I have plenty of information. They know I
have the files. I have their internal memos, and I will expose the
fraud that exists in baseball today.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips provided a copy of one of those memos to The New York
Times. The memo figures to be a core piece of evidence in the case
the union plans to take to the National Labor Relations Board next
Monday. Phillips has contended that major-league baseball has
violated its labor agreement with the umpires by taking authority
away from the league offices and putting it in the commissioner's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Last January the commissioner's office denied that it had
intended to implement its centralization plan for the umpires for
this season, which is the last covered by the umpires' labor
contract. But in a Dec. 14 memo from the executive vice president
for administration, Robert DuPuy, to the league presidents, Leonard
Coleman and Gene Budig, DuPuy said otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Bud Selig, the commissioner, and Sandy Alderson,
the executive vice president for baseball operations, DuPuy wrote,
``Bud has determined that the umpires should be supervised
essentially by Sandy for the upcoming season, to be effective as
rapidly as can be accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips cited the memo as evidence that lopping 13 umpires from
the NL staff because the league had hired 13 minor-league umpires
was not a decision made by Coleman. ``These were decisions dictated
to him,'' the lawyer said by telephone from Philadelphia. Coleman
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In paring the staff, one baseball official said, the league
considered age, experience, ability and race.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Pulli, No. 2 in seniority, and Terry Tata, No. 3, both
crew chiefs, were the most experienced among the 13. Pulli is in
his 28th year, Tata his 27th. Paul Nauert was one of two umpires
added this season.
</P>
<P>
   Others among the 13, in order of years of service, were Eric
Gregg (23rd year), Joe West (22nd), Bob Davidson (18th), Tom
Hallion (14th), Gary Darling (13th), Bill Hohn (11th), Larry
Poncino (8th), Larry Vanover (seventh), Bruce Dreckman (third) and
Sam Holbrook (second).
</P>
<P>
   Hallion recently incurred a rare penalty for an umpire, a
three-game suspension for making contact with a player, Jeff Reed
of Colorado. Gregg, 48, was noted for his excessive weight and the
time he has missed, including this season, for health reasons. He
is listed as weighing 305 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Under their labor contract, some of the umpires receive
termination pay. For the 13 NL umpires, eight are scheduled to
receive a total of $2.6 million. The four umpires with more than 20
years receive $400,000 each; the five with fewer than 10 years get
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   While Phillips blamed baseball officials for the loss of the
umpires' jobs, officials said it was his bargaining strategy that
forced them into that position. After the umpires initially wanted
to engage in what would have been an illegal strike, they adopted
the resignation strategy at Phillips' suggestion at a meeting July
14.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 umpires signed letters of resignation, and they
were faxed to the league the next day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
