<SLUG> BC-DEEP-SPACE-CAMERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMERA FAILS IN SPACECRAFT'S BRUSH WITH ASTEROID 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It could have been a great picture, but the camera
was pointing at the wrong place, researchers said Thursday of a
disappointing encounter between an asteroid and a NASA spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   After spending much of the day examining data from an early
morning encounter between the Deep Space 1 craft and the asteroid
Braille, scientists said it appeared that the spacecraft aimed its
camera at the wrong spot and missed capturing close-up images of
the asteroid.
</P>
<P>
   The spacecraft, which was guiding itself with an automatic
navigation system, encountered targeting problems shortly before
passing within 10 miles of the asteroid, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph R. Basilio, the mission's operations manager at NASA's Jet
Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif., said engineers were
still assessing data from the spacecraft, but were not optimistic
about finding any of the black-and-white images anticipated from
the encounter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to give up,'' Basilio said in a telephone
interview. ``We are going to comb through every bit of data and may
just find some image information, but we are tempering our
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said there appeared to be good data on the small
asteroid from other instruments, including information on charged
particle activity around the object and infrared data on heat
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Space 1 is a barrel-shaped, 1,000-pound craft that was
launched on Oct. 24, 1998. The robot vessel, packed with miniature
instruments and other devices, was designed to troubleshoot 12
innovative technologies that could be used by future spacecraft.
Dr. Marc D. Rayman, chief mission engineer, said the spacecraft had
completed more than 95 percent of its mission and had validated
most of the technologies before the encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Technologies aboard include an autonomous navigation system, an
unusual solar-powered ion engine, an integrated camera and
spectrometer for determining the composition of distant objects, a
combination ion and electron spectrometer for studying charged
particles, and advanced artificial intelligence software that lets
the spacecraft manage its own mission as situations change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
