u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TOBACCO-FEES-BOS &LR;      07-29 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TOBACCO-FEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL AWARDS LAW FIRMS $775M FOR TOBACCO SUIT WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Five law firms, including three from Boston, have been
awarded $775 million in legal fees for representing Massachusetts
in its successful $8.3 billion lawsuit against the tobacco
industry, an arbitration panel announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While providing a huge financial windfall to the lawyers, the
decision by the Tobacco Fee Arbitration Panel gives the firms less
than half of the $2 billion they sought and were originally
promised under a contract with the state.
</P>
<P>
   The fee is believed to the largest ever awarded in Massachusetts
in a civil litigiation case.
</P>
<P>
   Brown Rudnick Freed and Gesmer of Boston, the lead local
attorneys, will get a 23 percent cut of the fee, or about $178
million, according to the agreement among the attorneys. It has not
been disclosed how the balance of the fees will be divided.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Brown Rudnick, which in the past has said it would
consider donating some of the funds to charity, defended its fee.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas M. Sobol, the lead attorney in the case, said the firm's
work was ``the most labor-intensive effort in the history of the
Commonwealth.''.
</P>
<P>
   David D. Sullivan, a partner, agreed: ``Our firm took an
enormous risk accepting this case to take on big tobacco in the
interest of public health and the people of Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Governor Paul Cellucci termed the payment
``excessive.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether the firms will try to enforce the $2
billion contract with the attorney general's office, and Brown
Rudnick did not address the issue. Any additional legal fees
awarded to the firms would be taken out of the state's $8.3 billion
share of the 1998 national tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But the panel's decision may have discouraged any further
attempts by the firms to collect fees from the state. It stipulates
that the $775 million be reduced dollar for dollar, by any fees the
attorneys gained from the state.
</P>
<P>
   The fee will be paid by the tobacco industry over as many as 25
years or more. As part of $206 billion national tobacco settlement
that was negotiated in late 1998 between 46 state attorneys general
and the cigarette makers, the industry will contribute $500 million
a year to pay all states' legal bills.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's chairman, John Calhoun Wells, said he and his two
colleagues, who held hearings on Brown Rudnick's legal fees last
month, said the decision ``represents a considered judgement of the
facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells said the arbitration board, which voted 2-1 in favor of
the fee, had fulfilled its charge to determine ``full, reasonable
compensation for these attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even the arbiter who concurred with Wells, industry
appointee Charles B. Renfrew, said the fee was more than he would
have awarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure to reach resolution would have created uncertainty and
may have had a serious and potentially adverse impact'' on the
arbitration process, said Renfrew, a former federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Huge, the dissenting member of the panel, supported a
higher award. The decision, said Huge, who was the Massachusetts
counsel's appointee, is ``arbitrary and capricious'' and not
supported by ``rational and reasonable reasons'' or ``compelling
evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells was chosen by consensus of both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's decision will receive close scrutiny around the
country because Massachusetts was the first state among those
included in the 1998 multi-state settlement to go to arbitration to
set legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   It will likely influence the size of fee awards in several
remaining states, though in many states, the lawsuits did not
involve as much legal work.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci and Attorney General Thomas Reilly both said they would
fight any attempts by the firms to collect additional fees from the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope they will be happy with the subtantial fee they are
receiving which I still think is excessive,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who has been highly critical of the firms' legal
bills, recently filed legislation that would bar the state from
paying the lawyers from the state's settlement money. Many
advocates want the settlement money to be spent mainly on health
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, who said the firms had provided an ``invaluable
service,'' said he does not expect any claims against the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be the end of it,'' he said. ``Enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Brown Rudnick, the state also retained the firms
Schneider Reilly Costello &AMP; Zabin and Thornton Early &AMP; Naumes, both
of Boston; Ness Motley Loadholt Richardson &AMP; Poole, of Charleston,
S.C.; and Leiff Cabraser Heimann &AMP; Bernstein of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   While Cellucci and Reilly have been critical of the lawyers' $2
billion legal bill, the firms received strong support Thursday from
one of the nation's leading anti-smoking lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seems to be a pretty reasonable compromise,'' said
Richard Daynard, chairman of the Tobacco Products Liability Project
at Northeastern University's School of Law. But he also said he
thought the $2 billion fee the firms had requested was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't find it absurd to say that if someone has a contract
and somebody performs under the contract and it was negotiated in
good faith they are entitled to the benefits of the contract,''
Daynard said.
</P>
<P>
   Daynard said the firms, particularly the lawyers at Brown
Rudnick, had agreed to take on the litigation when most in the
legal field were convinced the case had no chance of succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a downtown corporate law firm that took on the case
when most people thought it was all crazy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, however, noted that the legal team had drawn heavily on
documents and witness testimony from four other states who first
sued the industry.se case had already been litigated.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry argued the firms should receive $26.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   But the panel said its award reflects the ``substantial
contributions'' the Massachusetts legal team made to the national
tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitration panel noted that the team, led by Brown Rudnick,
invested thousands of hours of preparation for a trial scheduled to
begin early this year, and the prospect of a tough battle in the
Massachusetts courts helped prompt the tobacco industry to reach
its national agreement last year.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also cited the legal team's development of a
``sophisticated damage model'' used to determine the size of the
monetary claims against the industry. Arbiters also noted the
lawyers' work in the Liggett I settlement, which the arbiters
described as a ``landmark event in the litigation against the
tobacco industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
