<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9226 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-MAIN-COX     07-29 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gunman ends Atlanta killing spree by turning gun on himself
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Mark Orrin Barton, authorities say, found the answer to
his problems in killing .
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, when his wife apparently discovered he was having
an affair, they believe he hacked her and her mother to death at an
Alabama campground.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, firing pistols in both hands, he slaughtered
nine people and injured 12 more in two Buckhead office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police were still getting terrified office workers to
safety when a maintenance man entered an apartment in an
Stockbridge, Ga., and found the battered bodies of a woman and two
children _ apparently Barton's second wife and his children. Police
said they may have been beaten to death two to three days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Five hours later, pursued by police, Barton solved all his
problems by killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   He may not have been able to finish his final rampage; Henry
County police said they found a list in the carnage of his
apartment that indicated he intended to kill at least three more
people.
</P>
<P>
   The only motive authorities could offer for his final murderous
outburst was that he had lost heavily in day stock trading, and the
two offices he attacked on Piedmont Road were places where he
apparently had done some of his trading.
</P>
<P>
   The massive manhunt for the 44-year-old Barton's green Ford
Aerostar van ended shortly after 8 p.m. Thursday when police
spotted the van. They gave chase, and Barton pulled into a BP
station and killed himself with a single shot.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Mark Camp of the Acworth police department said that a
police officer pulled over the van at 7:53 p.m. ``I'm just glad one
of our officers didn't have to shoot him,'' Camp said.
</P>
<P>
   Henry County Police Lt. Roger Stubbs said Thursday night that
officers were trying to determine whether the three or more
additional victims whose names werte found in the apartment were
safe.
</P>
<P>
   Nell Jones, 53, a day trader at All-Tech Investment Group, said
she was working at her computer when five shots rang out in a
meeting room and Barton, described in a company statement as ``a
customer who had not traded in some time, `` emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked into his eyes,'' she said, and saw a man who was
``very calm, very determined. No feeling.'' He fired at her from no
further than 10 feet, Jones said. She felt the wind of the bullet
passing her forehead. It struck her terminal and he trurned to
shoot at someone else. She fled.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Bill Campbell, serving as a press spokesman at the scene,
said Barton was quickly identified by workers in the trading
offices who knew him. He was firing with a pistol in each hand, the
mayor said, and from cartridge cases found in the buildings police
said they were 9mm and .45 caliber semiautomatics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no provocation that prompted this shooting,''
Campbell said grimacing. ``Apparently this man had suffered some
financial losses.'' Day trading, a phenomenon of the personal
computer age, involves individuals linked to the stock market
through the Internet, buying and selling stocks many times in a
day, seeking instant profits with no regard to the long-term
prospects of companies. Experts say it is a quick way to make _ and
lose _ large sums of money.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Barton walked into the third-floor office of
Momentum Securities at 2:50 and began casually talking to employees
about the drop in the stock market Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   They said Barton seemed calm, but suddenly drew his guns and
started shooting. Four people were killed in that building,
Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police said Barton then calmly crossed the road and
entered the No. 7 and number 8 buildings of the office complex and
shot and killed 5 more poeple.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Bill Campbell said at least 12 other poeple were injured,
seven from gunfire and the rest with ``bumps and scrapes''
suffering while fleeing from their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had too many tragedies in this city over the last few
days,'' Campbell said, referring to an incident in southwest
Atlanta on July 12 where a man killed 6 people, then shot and
killed himself. Until Thursday's slaughter, that was the worst mass
murder in the city's history.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell asked citizens to pray for the families of the victims
and for the city. ``It is clear that we need something,'' Capbell
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Barton's wife of 15 years, Debra Spivey Barton, and her
mother were found hacked to death in a camper parked by Lake Weiss
in northeastern Alabama. Authorities said at the time that Barton
was their best suspect but were never able to place him at the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Spivey of Lithia Springs, Ga., husband and father of those
victims, said Thursday night that ``The man who it appears killed
my wife and daughter, also killed my two grandchildren. It's almost
too much for me to deal with, that my grandchildren too are dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry County police said the found the body of a woman,
presumably Barton's wife, wrapped in a blanket and stuffed in a
bedroom closet of the apartment at the Bristol Green Apartments.
They believe she was killed Tuesday. The two children, were found
under blankets in the bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   There were notes on all three bodies, authorities said, but they
would not divulge what was written. All apparently died of blunt
trauma, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
