<SLUG> BC-BBN-UMPIRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL LEAGUE ACCEPTS RESIGNATIONS OF 13 UMPIRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the latest development in the ongoing labor dispute with
Major League Baseball, the National League Thursday confirmed that
it had accepted the resignations of 13 umpires, bringing to 22 the
number of arbiters who will be replaced Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The NL umps join a list of nine umpires released by the American
League Monday. That means 32 percent (22 of 68) of the umpires
under contract have lost their jobs and will likely be replaced by
25 Triple A umpires.
</P>
<P>
   According to Associated Press, NL veterans Eric Gregg and Joe
West were among those let go.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg, criticized for a wide body and matching strike zone, had
been an NL umpire for 21 years. The same is true of West, famous
for slamming pitcher Dennis Cook to the ground in 1990. Also
departing, according to management sources are Tom Hallion, Terry
Tata, Bob Davidson, and Bill Hohn. Tata is a crew chief. It was not
immediately know how many of those rejected had asked for their
resignations to be rescinded. Forty-two umpires resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those umpires remaining have formed groups, urging
their colleagues to break with union head Richie Phillips and
renounced the strategy advocated by union president Jerry Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost 22 umpires because of a flawed strategy,'' said AL
umpire Dale Scott.
</P>
<P>
   He was not alone in his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, 14 umpires stated that ``Major league
umpires have been seriously harmed because of union leadership that
was doomed to fail from the beginning.'' The group of umpires
included Joe Brinkman, Scott, John Hirschbeck, Dave Phillips, and
Rocky Roe. The statement was also signed by NL umpires Wally Bell,
Mark Hirschbeck and Jeff Nelson, and AL umpires Gary Cederstrom,
Tim Craft, Jim Joyce, Tim McClelland, Durwood Merrill, and Tim
Welke.
</P>
<P>
   Other umpires, however, were angered by the statement.
</P>
<P>
   (That group) started this ball rolling against us _ to pursue
and save their own jobs instead of staying strong in our union,''
said NL umpire Dana DeMuth. ``They are the ones who did not stand
with the majority. We're standing here with our heads in a
guillotine, and the blade is right here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day the umpires announced their resignations, spirits
among the group were high. Many felt this was a good bargaining
tool to induce Major League Baseball into early labor discussions.
The current contract expires Dec. 31 but by resigning Sept. 2,
those who would be eligible for severance pay, reportedly as much
as $400,00 for some umpires. A no-strike clause made any other
option unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   But Major League Baseball saw an opening and took it. Those
umpires who finish the season can still negotiate, although there
might be someone other than Richie Phillips at the bargaining
table. But with the union broken by resignations and the threat of
replacements, it is likely Major League Baseball will seek a
complete overhaul of the system of hiring and firing umpires.
(Phillips recently signed a five year contract extension.)
</P>
<P>
   It was suggested that umpires would have to agreed to
accountability, like the players. New people mean lower salaries,
possibly two-tier. With baseball growing more international every
year, umpires might find themselves with new partners.
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret that Major League Baseball would like to remove
the hiring, firing, and discliplining of umpires away from the
league presidents and give that power to commissioner Bud Selig or
the vice president of baseball operations, Sandy Alderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final say is coming from Alderson,'' DeMuth said. ``And
who is Alderson _ who's never had any umpire capabilities and
doesn't know a thing about my job? How can he say that I must go?
It doesn't make sense. But everything that he's done to this point
doesn't make sense, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips and Crawford retained Cohen, Weiss, and Simon ``to take
appropriate aggressive legal action against major league
baseball.'' Cohen, Weiss and Simon has worked for the Airline
Pilots Association and the Teamsters Union.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires face an uphill battle, no matter what they do. They
sued in federal court in Philadelphia. But their attempt to gain a
restraining order was denied by US District Judge Edmund V. Ludwig.
A hearing on the case will be scheduled after Aug. 12. But the
damage is done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really very sad,'' said Brinkman, another Phillips foe.
``It's just a damn shame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
