<SLUG> BC-AMR-BRITISH-AIRWAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 AIRLINES' BID FOR ANTITRUST IMMUNITY REPORTEDLY REJECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain)  (mk) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The three-year effort by American Airlines and British Airways
to win approval to share revenue and coordinated schedules and
fares is expected to be rejected Friday by the U.S. Department of
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   But both airlines said Thursday that they intend to broaden
their ties and cooperation in ways that do not require government
approval. Nevertheless, their costly, prolonged effort to obtain
immunity from antitrust violations is likely to put them at a
disadvantage with rival aviation alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, American and British Airways will continue to dominate
traffic over the lucrative North Atlantic route, because of their
overwhelming combined presence at London's Heathrow Airport. At
Heathrow, an important connecting point for much of the rest of
Europe as well as the Middle East, Africa and elsewhere, British
Airways controls almost 38 percent of takeoff and landing slots,
while American and United Airlines each have only about 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trade-off for immunity for BA and American has always been
opening Heathrow to other airlines, and that's a big price to pay
for an incremental benefit,'' said Samuel Buttrick, an analyst at
Paine Webber. ``But now they don't have to worry about that
happening any time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AMR fell $1.25 Thursday to $66.1875, while American
depository receipts of British Airways fell $1, to $64.50.
</P>
<P>
   In saying that the airlines' petition for antitrust immunity
would be dismissed Friday, a Department of Transportation source,
who spoke on condition of anonymity, suggested that the reason for
the dismissal was the lack of progress in negotiations between
Washington and London, but that ``the airlines could come back and
refile the petition'' if progress were made in those talks.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's opposition to antitrust immunity for the American
Airlines-British Airways alliance has long been aimed at pressuring
the British government to renegotiate a so-called open skies
agreement. Such agreements, which Washington has negotiated with
many other countries, liberalizes restrictions on routes, fares and
frequencies between both nations, and allows airlines from both
nations to fly anywhere in either country.
</P>
<P>
   As part of open skies, Washington wants greater access at
Heathrow for U.S. carriers, including Continental, Delta and US
Airways, which also want to fly there. The European Commission and
Britain's Office of Fair Trading have both said they will not
approve the alliance until British Airways and American Airlines
surrender 267 slots. While not addressing that issue directly, John
Lampl, the British Airways spokesman in New York, said that the
airline's percentage of slots at Heathrow ``is less than that of
any major carrier at its biggest hub, including American at Dallas,
Delta at Atlanta and Northwest at Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Times of London reported Thursday that American
and British Airways abandoned their plan to set up the alliance
after they were informed that the Department of Transportation was
set to dismiss their application for immunity from antitrust
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, American and British Airways vowed Thursday to
continue their relationship. ``It would be better to develop
activities that don't require antitrust immunity rather than to
accept conditions which would be a dereliction of our duty to
shareholders' interests,'' said Bob Ayling, the chairman of British
Airlines. Those activities could include joint purchases,
reciprocity at airport lounges and enhancing their frequent flier
programs.
</P>
<P>
   While lack of approval would be regrettable, Ayling and Don
Carty, the chairman of American, said in a statement, ``It will not
stop continuing cooperation between the two airlines wherever that
is permitted by regulators, nor will it lessen either company's
commitment to Oneworld.''
</P>
<P>
   Oneworld is the global marketing alliance consisting of American
and British Airways, as well as Canadian Airlines, Cathay Pacific
(Hong Kong), Finnair, Iberia (Spain) and Qantas (Australia).
</P>
<P>
   But without antitrust immunity, American and British Airways
will not be able to share revenue on transatlantic flights, nor
coordinate fares and schedules. By contrast, Oneworld's main rival,
the Star Alliance, acquired antitrust immunity from the Justice
Department as part of the open skies agreement between the United
States and Germany. Star Alliance members are United Airlines,
Lufthansa (Germany), Air Canada, Air New Zealand, Ansett of
Australia, Scandinavian Airlines Systems, Thai Airways and Varig of
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Other airline alliances also have antitrust immunity. Northwest
Airlines and KLM of the Netherlands, members of the Wings alliance,
have had it since 1992, while the Atlantic Excellence alliance
among Delta, Austrian Airlines, Swissair and Sabena received it in
1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
