<HEADLINE>
MORGAN STANLEY AND U.S. PANEL GIVEN DEADLINE ON CASE DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission have been given two weeks to resolve a dispute about
whether the Wall Street firm must produce all the information the
federal government agency has subpoenaed in a gender-discrimination
case, people briefed on court proceedings said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The commission took Morgan Stanley to court Wednesday to force
the firm to turn over documents subpoenaed as part of an
investigation of Morgan Stanley's compensation and promotion of
female employees.
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from a complaint filed with the commission last
year by Allison K. Schieffelin, 38, a saleswoman in the firm's
convertible bond division. Ms. Schieffelin contends that she was
denied promotion to managing director because she is a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley declined to turn over some documents and other
information demanded by the commission on the grounds that its
subpoena was too broad. The commission said in court documents that
it seeks information about male and female employees whose tenure
and job duties resemble those of Ms. Schieffelin, and documents
involved in any other cases of sexual harassment or discrimination
at Morgan Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Denise Cote in Manhattan allowed lawyers
working for the agency and Morgan Stanley legal representatives
from the Manhattan law firm Epstein, Becker &AMP; Green to try to
resolve their differences within two weeks. If they fail to do so,
she said, she would decide whether to force Morgan Stanley to turn
over the subpoenaed material, people briefed on the proceedings
said.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Morgan Stanley issued a statement Thursday
reiterating its position that Ms. Schieffelin's charges of
discrimination were without merit. ``We do not tolerate
discrimination of any kind,'' a spokeswoman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
