<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-REWARD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SISTER OF SUSPECTED SERIAL KILLER RECEIVES $86,000 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ill., Ky., N.M.) 
 
By ERIC BERGER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The sister of suspected serial killer Angel Maturino
Resendiz has received $86,000 in reward money for her role in
getting him to surrender, the FBI announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Manuela Karkiewicz of Albuquerque, N.M., could receive $40,000
more if Maturino Resendiz is convicted of murder in Texas and
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in early June, when Texas Ranger Drew Carter began
cultivating a relationship with her, Karkiewicz played a central
role in brokering Maturino Resendiz's July 13 surrender at the
U.S.-Mexico border near El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Karkiewicz's pastor declined to say Thursday night how she would
use the money, but he suggested that she did not help the
authorities because of the reward.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't want the money, that's all I can tell you,'' said
Troy Robinson of Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Since the suspect's surrender, authorities have also insisted
that Maturino Resendiz had not conditioned his surrender on his
family members receiving the reward money.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, several agencies that worked on the task force
assigned to the case said they had no qualms about family members
receiving the reward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law enforcement authorities are very comfortable with the
decision here and where the money went to,'' said Don K. Clark,
special agent in charge of the Houston FBI office.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no disagreements or even arguments in terms of who
should get this money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kloesel, president of M-G Inc., a Weimar, Texas, feed store
and implement dealership that raised $5,000 of the reward money,
said, ``It's not an ideal situation, but I guess if she did help
get him to turn himself in, then she deserves the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz is being held in Harris County jail, charged
with the capital murder of Houston-area physician Claudia Benton
last December. The trial in that case, which could result in a
death penalty, is expected to begin early next year.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Maturino Resendiz is suspected of six slayings in Texas,
two in Illinois and one in Kentucky. He has been formally charged
in five of them.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $40,000 yet to be disbursed, $15,000 is from private
sources in Weimar, where Maturino Resendiz is suspected of killing
the Rev. Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic and his wife, Karen, last May, and
$25,000 is from Lexington, Ky., where Christopher Maier was beaten
to death in August, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in both areas said Thursday that the reward is
conditioned on a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel probably that our wording is specific to the
Christopher Maier homicide,'' said Assistant Lexington Police Chief
Fran D. Root.
</P>
<P>
   The reward money Karkiewicz received this week includes $50,000
from the FBI for helping to apprehend a Top 10 Fugitive, $20,000
from Weimar, $11,000 from the U.S. Marshals Service, and $5,000
from the West University Place Police Department. West University
is an affluent enclave of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
