<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE SOX SEND YANKEES TO BOSTON ON A LOSING NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The visiting dugout in Comiskey Park is floored with
wood, and underneath it water has collected and rot has set in,
creating a stench that prompted New York Yankees manager Joe Torre
to recall the day he uncovered a dead cat.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will not have to suffer any more games in the
powerful dugout this year, and that is about the only good thing
they could say as they left this town after losing the final two
games in a three-game series with the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Konerko slammed two home runs and the White Sox whipped the
Yankees Thursday, 5-1, to beat David Cone (10-5) in the Yankees'
100th game of the 162-game season.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, the Yankees' leadoff hitter and second baseman,
missed his second consecutive game with a viral infection, and
Torre said Knoblauch might miss another game or two in the coming
series against the Red Sox at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee, the Yankees' left fielder, is still bothered by a
strained groin muscle and may not be available this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez, who said the triceps in his throwing arm was
spent during his last start, threw in the bullpen without any
trouble Thursday, and the expectation is that he will be able to
make his next scheduled start Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Cone allowed four runs in seven innings Thursday, and in his own
estimation he failed to do what he usually does so effectively:
pitch out of jams. Opposing batters were only 18-for-111 (.162)
with runners in scoring position against Cone before the game. On
Thursday, the White Sox were 3-for-9.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and the White Sox, playing in temperatures nearing
100 degrees, were tied at 1-1 in the sixth inning when Cone fell
behind Konerko with two balls and no strikes. Cone challenged
Konerko with a fastball, but as catcher Joe Girardi remembered, the
pitch drifted over the middle of the plate, and Konerko crushed it
for a home run as Cone gestured in disgust with his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   There would be more in the inning. Cone walked left fielder
Brian Simmons, and Simmons stole second. Cone thought he threw Greg
Norton, the next batter, a good pitch _ a splitter low and away _
but Norton slapped the ball through the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox who led 3-1, added a run in the seventh and
another in the eighth, and the Yankees ate quickly, dressed and
boarded the bus to the airport. The Yankees, 61-39 and in first
place in the American League East, were thoroughly outplayed in the
final two games of the series, in the outfield in particular.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox, Torre noted, are ranked last in the league in
defense, but all week their outfielders were running down one ball
after another.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Chris Singleton once leaped high and extended his
glove over the wall to take a home run away from Paul O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played a very solid series,'' Torre said. ``They deserved
to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
