<SLUG> BC-GLAXO-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLAXO SAYS IT WILL NOT MEET ITS SALES AND PROFIT TARGETS FOR THE
YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wounded by dismal sales growth in the United States, Glaxo
Wellcome PLC, the world's third-largest pharmaceutical company,
announced Thursday that it would not meet its sales and earnings
projections for this year.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure pushed Glaxo's shares lower on two continents. On
the London Stock Exchange, its shares dropped 199 pence, or 11.4
percent, to 1,553 pence. The company's American depository receipts
tumbled $4.125, or 7.5 percent, to $51.1875.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Thursday that Glaxo's latest woes raised troubling
questions about its future. Many questioned whether the giant drug
maker would be forced to merge to improve its market position,
especially in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Glaxo Wellcome said Thursday that there was no
reason for the company to merge because of its current performance.
</P>
<P>
   Others wondered about the tenure of Glaxo's chairman, Richard
Sykes, who had reassured analysts earlier this year that Glaxo
would attain a 10 percent gain in sales and earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout this year, Glaxo has said they were committed to
double-digit growth,'' said Jonas Morner, a pharmaceuticals analyst
with Deutsche Bank Securities in London. ``Certainly, this is going
to cause some lost credibility with the company's management.
Investors will no longer feel the stock is a safe bet.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo, which does not release quarterly results, said its
earnings for the first half of the year rose 9.6 percent, to 932
million pounds, or 25.7 pence a share, compared with 850 million
pounds, or 23.7 pence a share, in the period a year earlier. The
company said it had sales of 4.1 billion pounds, an increase of 4
percent at a constant exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
   The results exceeded many analysts' expectations but still
lagged behind the industry average of a 15 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were concerned Thursday about the cause of Glaxo's
setback. Glaxo's drug sales in the United States only rose 2
percent at a constant exchange rate during the first half of this
year, a paltry tally given that Johnson &AMP; Johnson's sales increased
37.3 percent in the second quarter alone.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem, the U.S. market accounted for 41
percent of Glaxo's worldwide sales in the first half. Any decline
in the U.S. market is bound to take a huge toll.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo attributed its poor performance in the United States to
lagging sales of Imitrex, its migraine treatment, and Zyban, its
pill for smoking cessation. Imitrex sales in the United States
dropped 13 percent, to 217 million pounds, while Zyban's sales
plunged 44 percent, to 29 million pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The migraine and smoking-cessation drugs are two important
products,'' said Neil Sweig, an analyst with Southeast Research
Partners. ``When you start to go negative on your important
products, the new products that come on line can't make up that
difference so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo said Thursday that it was facing a challenge replacing
consumers who had recently completed treatment with Zyban. The
company attributed Imitrex's woes to heavy competition from other
migraine drugs, including Maxalt from Merck &AMP; Co. and
Astra-Zeneca's Zomig.
</P>
<P>
   Yet analysts pointed out other problems with Imitrex and Zyban.
Most of the smoking-cessation drugs are used by smokers to passify
their habits in places where they cannot smoke, notably airplanes
and meetings. Since Zyban did not contain nicotine, it did not get
any of these sales.
</P>
<P>
   Imitrex and the other migraine drugs have become textbook
lessons in marketing mistakes. Analysts insist that Glaxo and other
manufacturers released too many drug samples, especially for an
illness that is largely episodic. Patients who only suffer a few
migraines a year sometimes left their doctor's office with what
amounted to a year's supply of drugs, which resulted in a year's
worth of lost sales.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo remained confident that its five new drugs could lift
sales. The company has Seretide, an asthma drug marketed in nine
European countries; Zeffix, for hepatitis B; Ziagen and Agenerase
for AIDS, and Relenza, a nasal spray that was recently approved by
the Food and Drug Administration for flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glaxo's flu drug will have competition from Roche,'' Deutsche
Bank's Morner said. ``Glaxo doesn't have to merge, but it's likely
they will. If SmithKline Beecham is interested, the roles will be
reversed this time around. SmithKline is the stronger partner
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
