<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDISON-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDISON PROJECT ADDS SCHOOLS AND INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Edison Project, the ambitious nationwide network of
for-profit public schools, announced Thursday that it was raising
both enrollment and cash.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has expanded steadily since opening its first
schools in 1995 but has yet to make a profit, said it had received
a fresh infusion of $71 million from private investors. It is
expected to begin offering stock to the public next year.
</P>
<P>
   And it announced plans to open 26 new schools in the fall, for a
total of 77, and to increase its total enrollment to 37,000, up
from 24,000 in the 1998-99 school year.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest new investor, at $30 million, is Paul G. Allen, a
co-founder of Microsoft Corp. who has a reputation for backing
audacious ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Edison's deal with Allen includes an alliance with one of his
privately financed ventures, Apex Online Learning Inc., which last
spring began offering online advanced-placement courses to high
schools and online refresher instruction to individual students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
