<P>
   (NYT27) ATLANTA -- July 29, 1999 -- GA-SHOOT-3, 07-29 -- Atlanta
police check vehicles leaving the area where a gunman killed at
least nine people in the Buckhead section of Atlanta, Thursday.
Police where talking to drivers as the gunman's whereabouts were
unknown. (Alan S. Weiner /New York Times Photo) MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) RIVERHEAD, N.Y. -- July 29, 1999 -- DROUGHT-WINE, 07-29
-- Brian Caputo samples past vintages at the Palmer vineyard on
Thursday while looking out over what promises to be another great
year for the wine growers in the East End of Long Island. The dry,
sunny weather which has brought drought and hardship to other
farmers, has been ideal for grapes. Hopes are high for a vintage
year. ``If this drought continues through August, we would be in
heaven,'' said a local grower. (Maxine Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) CHARLOTTE, N.C. -- July 29, 1999 -- FIRST-UNION-RETIRE,
07-29 --Continuing to wrestle with severe problems unleashed by a
botched merger and a troubled business strategy, First Union Corp.
announces Thursday that its president, John R. Georgius, will
retire by the end of the year. Georgius, 54, will be succeeded by
G. Kennedy Thompson, 48, who currently oversees the capital markets
business at the nation's sixth largest bank. (Nancy Pierce/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) ATLANTA -- July 29, 1999 -- GA-SHOOT-2, 07-29 -- People
run from the scene of a shooting in northern Atlanta on Thursday. A
day trader opened fire in two brokerage offices killing at least
nine people. (Alan S. Weiner/New York Times Photo) MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) ATLANTA -- July 29, 1999 -- GA-SHOOT, 07-29 -- People
run from the scene of a shooting in northern Atlanta on Thursday. A
day trader opened fire in two brokerage offices killing at least
nine people. (Alan S. Weiner/New York Times Photo) MAGS OUT
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- July 29, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 1 --
ABOUT-CARS-JETTA-2, 07-29 -- The sassy New Beetle has become a
highly recognizable symbol of Volkswagen's resurgence in the United
States, but the real workhorse in the showroom has been the
company's best seller, the less retro, more roomy Jetta sedan. With
a price starting at $17,325, the restyled Jetta offers
people-pleasing details inside. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) SAN FRANCISCO -- July 29, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 1
-- ABOUT-CARS-JETTA-1, 07-29 -- With the newly restyled Jetta, VW
is trying to take on the pint-sized competition by offering more
spirit under the hood and a lot of standard features. With a price
starting at $17,325, compared with $13,200 for the lowest-priced
Civic DX sedan, or $15,245 for the best-selling Civic LX version,
VW is boldly suggesting that although these cars are about the same
size, more money buys a lot more car in the Jetta. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) MARSHALL, Calif. -- July 29, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG.
1 -- BIZ-ORGANIC-MILK, 07-29 -- Workers bottle organic milk at the
Straus Family Creamery in Marshall. Demand for organic milk is
booming across the country. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LOS ANGELES -- July 29, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 1 --
INVEST-RETIREES, 07-29 -- Jack A. Berman of Los Angeles with his
wife, Pearl J. Brown. ``Transition is a better word than
retirement,'' says Berman, 84, who has reduced his work hours but
enjoys an activity-filled life. ``You need to plan ahead so you can
make the transition to something that is new and creative.''
(Edward Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) TARRYTOWN, N.Y. -- July 29, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG.
1 -- BIZ-STORYTELLING, 07-29 -- Karen Berg, a communications
consultant, coaches Stuart-Buttle, the vice president for
communications of Ciba's North American division in Tarrytown, on
his speech and storytelling technique. ``Anything that engages the
mind's eye is more memorable than just getting up and spouting off
data,'' says Ms. Berg, chief executive of Commcore Communication
Strategies in White Plains. (Richard L. Harbus/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) ATLANTA, Calif. -- July 29, 1999 -- NONSTOP-EATING-2,
07-29 -- Wade Lander takes a bite of his soft taco dinner while
navigating Atlanta's streets. Americans seem to be eating all the
time, and wherever they please. ``Consumers now see eating as
something to be done while you do something else,'' said Bobby
Calder, a marketing professor at Northwestern University. (Alan S.
Weiner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) VENICE BEACH, Calif. -- July 29, 1999 -- NONSTOP-EATING,
07-29 -- Travis Downey, 13, right, is followed by his friend Cooper
Howard, 10, after picking up some pizza slices. Americans seem to
be eating all the time, and wherever they please. ``Consumers now
see eating as something to be done while you do something else,''
said Bobby Calder, a marketing professor at Northwestern
University. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- July 29, 1999 -- HEALTH-CONGRESS, 07-29 --
Rep. Greg Ganske, R-Ill., also a medical doctor, works the phones
trying to find a compromise to the Republican healthcare proposal
on Thursday in his Capitol Hill office. Republican dissension over
how to regulate managed care spilled into the open in the House on
Thursday, forcing House Speaker Dennis Hastert to acknowledge that
he would likely have to abandon plans to take up the politically
potent issue before the August recess. (Stephen Crowley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- July 29, 1999 -- TAX-CONGRESS-2, 07-29 --
Republican Senators, from left, John Warner, William Roth, and
Jesse Helms, seated, on Capitol Hill on Thursday. Republicans moved
closer on Thursday to Senate passage of a $792 billion tax cut over
the opposition of President Clinton and Congressional Democrats,
but still face the difficult task of working out the considerable
differences within the party about what form the tax cuts should
take. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- July 29, 1999 -- TAX-CONGRESS, 07-29 --
Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., points to a chart the Democrats claim
outlines the benefits of strengthening Medicare and a prescriptions
drug program during a news conference on Capitol Hill on Thursday.
Looking on are Sen. Jay Rockefeller, background left, Sen. Minority
Leader Tom Daschle, second from right, and Sen. John Kerry, right.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- July 29, 1999 -- CARS-BUGATTI, 07-29 -- An
exhibit at the Cleveland Museum of Art features six Bugatti cars,
including the 1938 Atlantic Type 57SC. The car was designed by Jean
Bugatti (1909-39) and is considered by many to be the most
beautiful automobile ever made. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- July 29, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 1 --
PEONY-PAVILION-MUSIC, 07-29 -- Qian Yi and Wen Yu Hang in Episode 3
of ``The Peony Pavilion'' at Lincoln Center Festival '99. The
resuscitation of this 19-hour Ming Dynasty classic has been
welcomed by nearly everyone, but it has also certainly altered any
festival theme Lincoln Center might originally have had in mind.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 29, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 1 --
CARNIVAL-CENTURY-FEST-B&AMP;W, 07-29 -- Leonard de Paur outside Lincoln
Center in 1972, two years after he introduced an outdoor
performing-arts festival there. The forthcoming series, the
``Carnival of the Century,'' starting Friday, continues that
tradition. It includes the jazz pianist Dave Brubeck, a Greek blues
singer, Les Ballets Trokadero de Monte Carlo, music of the Jewish
Diaspora, a Peruvian dance company and the Colorado String Quartet.
(Jack Manning/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PARIS -- July 29, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 1 --
CHEREAU-FILMS, 07-29 -- Patrice Chereau at La Gare de l'Est in
Paris. Part enfant terrible and part national treasure, Chereau has
built a formidable reputation in France, with three decades of
groundbreaking work in theater, opera and, increasingly, film. His
latest movie, ``Those Who Love Me Can Take the Train,'' had its
premiere at the Cannes International Film Festival last year. ``I
want my work to pose questions about how people live today,'' he
says. (John Giannini/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- July 29, 1999 -- CARS-DESIGN, 07-29 --
Visitors find a bit of the here and now in the Toyota Prius at the
Modern's exhibit, while the Honda VV, right, hints of the future.
Although all the vehicles displayed in the Abby Aldrich Rockefeller
Sculpture Garden include cutting-edge engineering and design
features, some are already available to consumers in various
countries, and most of the others will soon be as well. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SEAVEY ISLAND, N.H. -- July 29, 1999 -- TERNS-RETURN-BOS,
07-29 -- Common Terns fly overhead as field biologists Dan Hayward,
center, is followed by Drew Trested, of the Audubon Society of New
Hampshire, while searching for baby terns to band. The return of
the terns to Seavey Island is part of a broader recovery of the
sleek, fork-tailed birds, whose arrival has long been one of
coastal New England's sure signs of summer. Thanks largely to
intensive human efforts to save them, common tern populations from
Maine to New York have nearly tripled since 1977, reversing decades
of losing ground to gulls, rats, and other refuse-eating animals.
(Mark Wilson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- July 29, 1999 -- AUTO-REVIEW-BOS, 07-29 -- The
323i, BMW's entry-level sports sedan. For BMW, the strategy of
offering a designated entry-level car at $26,400, is clear. Sell a
buyer on the 3-series and hope to have him or her move up to a 5-
or 7-series down the road. (C.J. Gunther/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CHICAGO -- July 29, 1999 -- HEAT-WAVE, 07-29 -- Sharon
Przybocki, a traffic aide with the Chicago police, waves traffic
through an intersection as she cradles a bottle of cold water to
her cheek on Thursday as the temperature reached over 100 degrees
Fahrenheit. Przybocki said that people were bringing her bottled
water and was grateful for their help. Chicago opened over 100
cooling centers to help allieviete the heat for locals without air
conditioning. (Todd Buchanan Jul 29, 1999. (Todd Buchanan/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK-- July 29, 1999 -- CHINA-SECT, 07-29 --
Expanding its crackdown on a banned meditation group, China ordered
the arrest Thursday of Li Hongzhi, the U.S.-based leader of Falun
Gong and said it would seek international help to bring him into
custody. Li is seen in an interview last week. (Jeffery A.
Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ELMIRA, N.Y. -- July 29, 1999 -- MRSCLINTON, 07-29 --
First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton signs autographs as those against
her possible candidacy for U.S. Senator wave a banner in the
background on Thursday. Mrs. Clinton hit the Senate campaign trail
again on Thursday. Fifteen months before the election, Mrs. Clinton
was greeted by hundreds of fans and critics wherever she stopped.
(Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) COLOMBO, Sri Lanka -- July 29, 1999 --
SRILANKA-ASSASSINATE, 07-29 -- Neelan Thiruchelvam and his wife
Sitthie in his law library in 1994. Tiruchelvam, a member of the
moderate Tamil United Liberation Front party, TULF, and head of a
think tank studying ethnic strife between the dominant Sinhalese
and the Tamil minority, was killed on Thursday by a suicide
bombing. No one claimed immediate responsibility, but officials
blamed the Liberation Tigers for Tamil Eelam, which is fighting for
an independent Tamil homeland. (Nihal Mahawaduge/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- July 29, 1999 -- PICKETT-EARLY-MUSIC , 07-29
-- Philip Pickett, a recorder player and one of the most
imaginative early-music directors working in Britain, is just now
getting around to performing in New York with the New London
Consort, the ensemble he founded in 1976. The group is to make its
United States debut in a Mostly Mozart concert on Sunday. (Decca
Records/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
