<HEADER>
A9269 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-MERNOTE-LADN     07-29 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARSSON SIDELINED BY TENDINITIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Anthony Dupuis toiled for seven years without
reaching the quarterfinals of an ATP Tour tournament. His moment
finally arrived Thursday, but it didn't even require him to step
onto the court.
</P>
<P>
   Dupuis was awarded a walkover victory when Magnus Larsson
withdrew from the Mercedes-Benz Cup before their scheduled
second-round match. Larsson, a 29-year-old qualifier from Sweden
who played three matches in two days to reach the second round, was
diagnosed with tendinitis in both forearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate since I was hitting the ball well,'' said
Larsson, who lost only three games in a first-round victory Monday
over Paradorn Srichaphan of Thailand. ``I've had this problem since
Monday and it was getting more and more painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Thursday morning) when I practiced I had no energy in my arms
and no power in my muscles.''
</P>
<P>
   Tournament physicians examined Larsson and determined he could
not play. He will undergo an MRI today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad for him, but I'm lucky,'' Dupuis said. ``It's the
first time something like this has happened to me. I'll do my best
and try to reach the semifinals.''
</P>
<P>
   Dupuis has played sparingly on the ATP Tour, although he reached
the second round of the Mercedes-Benz Cup in 1996. The 26-year-old
Frenchman has reached the finals twice in Challenger events this
year.
</P>
<P>
   __ Aussiefest: Dupuis will face Andrew Ilie, whose victory over
Goran Ivanisevic made him the third Australian to reach the
Mercedes quarterfinals, joining Lleyton Hewitt and qualifier James
Sekulov.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a bit of team spirit at the moment, especially after
the Davis Cup,'' Ilie said. ``Lleyton is doing some great things
and James is on a real hot streak, so we are all playing some
high-quality tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Ranked No. 473 in the world at the start of 1998, Ilie overcame
a back injury and rose to No. 61, and has impressed opponents with
his sharp backhand and strong baseline play. Earlier in the week,
Ivanisevic said he would ``pay to see'' Ilie play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very flattering for Goran to say that,'' Ilie said. ``But
a lot of people are starting to ask, `Why don't you play better?'
I've been reaching the second round of tournaments, but then I
usually get excited and get a rush, and then I burn out too early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played well in the French Open, but by the fifth set of the
third round, I was already out of gas. Right now I'm just trying to
get out of the first couple rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Danger ahead? Second-seeded Pete Sampras looked strong in his
first two matches at the Mercedes, beating Phillip King and
Sebastien Lareau in two-setters, but in today's quarterfinals he
faces a familiar and tough opponent in Wayne Ferreira.
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira has beaten Sampras in their past four meetings, most
recently in a 1998 hardcourt tournament in Basel, Switzerland.
Ferreira has won five of their nine meetings, including three of
five on the hardcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know all that until somebody told me,'' Sampras said.
``Wayne is always a tough player, especially when he gets some
confidence going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9270 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-SHOOT-1STLD-WRITET     07-29 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SHOOT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-660(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN KILLS 9, INJURES 12 IN SHOOTING SPREE IN ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ADDS information, update throughout) (See also GA-SHOOT-SCENE) 
(ART ADV: PHOTOS are being sent to NYT photo clients. A GRAPHIC and
LOCATOR MAP are being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By KEVIN SACK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A securities day trader killed nine people Thursday
afternoon in two office buildings in the city's glitzy Buckhead
district, eluded an extensive police manhunt for five hours, then
killed himself in his van after the police pulled him over in
nearby Cobb County. Another 12 people were injured in the incident,
seven of them from gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Mark O. Barton, 44, also is suspected in the recent
killings of his wife and two children in an apartment in suburban
Stockbridge, about 15 miles southeast of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Two weapons were found near the suspect's body and a
computer-generated letter and three notes were found near the
bodies of his family, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stockbridge killings took place before the Buckhead
shootings, but it was unclear exactly when, said Atlanta Mayor Bill
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Barton, a chemist who traded in his lab coat for the high-risk
life of an independent stock trader, also was a suspect in the 1993
bludgeoning deaths of his former wife and her mother in Cedar
Bluff, Ala., the authorities said. He was never charged in those
killings.
</P>
<P>
   No motive was known for the killings, the deadliest shooting
rampage in the city's history, but investigators speculated that
recent trading losses contributed to Barton's ire.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened today is a tragedy of massive proportions,''
Campbell said Thursday afternoon, his face locked in a
sweat-dampened grimace. ``We are praying for the families and
praying for our city.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's incident was the third shooting rampage in the
Atlanta area in less than three months. On May 20, a 15-year-old
student at Heritage High School in nearby Conyers took a gun to
school and shot six other students, none of them fatally, before
being captured by school administrators. On July 12, an Atlanta man
killed six members of a family and himself in an apparent domestic
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings in the Buckhead business and entertainment
district Thursday began around 2:50 p.m., when Barton, dressed in
shorts and a shirt, walked into the All-Tech Investment Group
office at Two Securities Center and, without warning or
provocation, began to fire with two weapons, Campbell said. Barton
had traded at the office in the past but not recently, the company
said in a statement released from its headquarters in Montvale,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Barton ``came into our office and after speaking to the branch
manager, suddenly stood up and for no apparent reason opened fire
on the branch manager and his secretary,'' said the statement from
All-Tech. ``This man then went into our main trading room and began
indiscriminately shooting at our customers. The man then ran out of
our office and continued shooting in another part of the office
building.'' Four people were killed in that building.
</P>
<P>
   Barton then crossed bustling Piedmont Road and walked into
another brokerage firm, Momentum Securities, in Building 8 of
Piedmont Center, a sprawling office campus. He opened fire there as
well, killing five people.
</P>
<P>
   For confused hours after the shootings, the police seemed to
have few clues to Barton's whereabouts or his method of escape.
Aided by SWAT teams, dogs and helicopters, they conducted a
suite-by-suite search of the buildings where the shootings had
occurred and the leafy grounds surrounding the office parks, to no
avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no idea where Barton is,'' Campbell told reporters
late Thursday afternoon. ``We do not know whether he has fled the
scene on foot or by car.''
</P>
<P>
   About 8:20 p.m., Campbell returned to a bank of microphones near
the scene of the shootings and announced that Barton's green
Aerostar van had been pulled over by the police at a service
station in Cobb County, northwest of here, and had committed
suicide in the van.
</P>
<P>
   ``This brings a very tragic day to an end,'' Campbell said. ``I
don't know if any of us can understand why something like this
occurs. All we can do is comfort the families and pray for our
city.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Because the killings of Barton's family members, including a
12-year-old son and an 7-year-old daughter, took place before the
Buckhead shootings, Campbell warned that it was dangerous to assume
that Thursday's market fluctuations had triggered the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly this is a deranged individual and has nothing to do
with what occurred today,'' he said. But the mayor did say that the
police had learned that Barton's investments had ``substantial
swings, losses and gains'' and that Barton ``seemed to indicate
some concern about losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers in the office buildings described blood-splattered
walls, lifeless bodies and nervous police officers shortly after
the shootings. Many were locked in their offices for hours as
heavily armed officers swept through the buildings, their weapons
drawn as they looked for Barton.
</P>
<P>
   Dari A. Payrow, 23, a worker at Allegiance Telecom, which has
offices on the third floor of 2 Securities Center, said he was
returning to his office from a bathroom when he found a trickle of
blood in the hall. He glanced through the glass windows of the
building's leasing office, which is adjacent to his own, and saw
puddles of blood on the floor next to the receptionist's desk.
``There was a guy on the floor and nobody was helping him so I
assume he was dead,'' Payrow said. The man, he said, was face down
with a bullet wound in his side.
</P>
<P>
   Payrow and other terrified workers huddled in their offices
waiting to be evacuated by the police. ``They all had their guns
drawn, bullet-proof vests, guarding corners, near the elevators,
running around our office,'' he said. ``They told all the males in
our office to come out with our hands up and out of our pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   Periodically, the police escorted officer workers out of the
building and led them down Piedmont Road. Many jogged to safety,
then bided their time in a nearby Mexican restaurant, calming their
nerves with margaritas and bottled beer while using cellular
telephones to notify family members and friends of their safety.
</P>
<P>
   Melinda L. Truan, a 49-year-old psychotherapist, sat outside the
restaurant sipping a soft drink while speaking on her cell phone to
her boyfriend, Bill J. Post, an interior designer who was locked
inside one of the Piedmont Center buildings. ``We've seen a lot of
police activity,'' Post said as Ms. Truan handed the phone to a
reporter. ``We just saw 15 or 20 police and some SWAT members go
into Building 8.''
</P>
<P>
   In the apartment in Stockbridge, meanwhile, police said they
found the bodies of a 7-year-old girl and a 12-year-old boy in
their beds, covered except for a small part of their faces. Notes
had been placed atop each body. Henry County Police Chief Jimmy
Mercer said that Barton's wife was found in a bedroom closet, also
covered, with a note on top of the cover. Another letter,
apparently written by Barton on a computer, was found in the living
room.
</P>
<P>
   Mercer said that the police believed that Barton's wife was
killed on Tuesday and his children on Wednesday. He said the notes
suggested that the victims died as a result of ``blunt force
trauma.'' He also said the notes mentioned the 1993 killings in
Alabama, but not in the form of a confession.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost written in a denial phase,'' he said. He did not
say whether the notes specifically warned of Thursday's shootings,
but said, ``There may be reason to believe that this mayhem would
not stop at this particular point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
