<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASTE-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BAD NEWS FROM WASTE MANAGEMENT LEAVES INVESTORS PEEVED 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the second time this month, Waste Management Inc. has warned
investors that its second-quarter earnings will be tepid at best.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston-based trash hauler said on July 6 that its earnings,
which analysts had estimated at 78 cents a share, would not top 70
cents. Thursday it indicated that the earnings, which it is
scheduled to release on Tuesday, would be between 58 cents and 60
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Though the company announced several steps _ including the
resignation of Gregory T. Sangalis, its general counsel, and the
stepping-down of Earl E. DeFrates as its chief financial officer _
to improve its forecasting ability and shore up its bottom line,
Wall Street was not appeased. Investors sent the shares down $5.50
Thursday, to $25.9375, less than half of the $60 the stock peaked
at May 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``A month ago, everyone loved this stock, and now we have no
strong buys on it at all,'' said Charles L. Hill, director of
research at the First Call Corp., which tracks analysts' estimates
and stock recommendations. ``Analysts have clearly lost confidence
in this company.''
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management attributed at least 6 cents of the latest
reduction in its earnings forecast to higher-than-expected interest
expenses and a decision not to switch to more favorable accounting
methods. But analysts also blame management for not riding herd on
field operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management must find out why assumptions are too generous,''
said James N. Kelleher, an analyst with Argus Research, who
suggested that field executives ``are probably terrified that
they'll be sacked if they give out poor numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management is going through internal tumult. Its chairman,
John E. Drury, is being treated for brain cancer. Analysts say that
Rodney R. Proto, the president, has been trying to handle both top
jobs _ and doing neither very well.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, shareholders slapped Waste Management with a suit for
securities fraud, contending that the company had given out falsely
optimistic information even as several executives, including Proto
and Sangalis, were selling large blocks of their personal holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management's employees, meanwhile, have been up in arms
since July 14, when management said that, despite earlier promises,
it would not terminate its defined benefit pension plan and
distribute lump-sum payments. Thursday, acknowledging a need to
improve employee morale and to let management concentrate on other
problems, the company said it would terminate the plan after all,
at a cost of $215 million, substantially more than the $125 million
it first estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Waste Management is trying to persuade shareholders that
its executives are on top of the company's problems. Earlier this
month, the company tacitly acknowledged Drury's continued
disability and named Ralph V. Whitworth, an executive with
Relational Investors LLC, which controls 1.1 million Waste
Management shares, as acting chairman.
</P>
<P>
   It said Thursday that Proto would coordinate with field
executives to get more accurate sales and earnings forecasts. And
it has asked Roderick Hills, the head of Waste Management's audit
committee, to investigate the allegations of insider trading.
</P>
<P>
   The company has hired Chase Securities and Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette to assist Whitworth in evaluating share-buyback programs,
asset divestitures and other ways to increase shareholder value.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are unlikely to be an easy sell, though. Waste
Management was formed a year ago when USA Waste Services, a company
that held tight reins on its field operations, bought Waste
Management Inc., a much larger but floundering rival that let its
field managers run their own shows.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say investors harbor a good deal of ill will for the
old Waste Management, which had a history of mismanagement,
accounting discrepancies and earnings disappointments, and which
had to revise earnings from 1992 through 1997 downward by $3.5
billion. And they say the merged company still suffers from culture
clashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old Waste Management had a failure of discipline, but the
new one has a failure of communications,'' Kelleher said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2228EDT &QL; 
