<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GA-SHOOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SHOOTINGS IN ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, July 30: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the fatal shooting of nine people in Atlanta
Thursday can be seen in isolation, as the mad handiwork of a lone
individual venting uniquely twisted grievances through the barrel
of a gun. Yet the incident is also part of a larger and dismally
familiar story of shootings that seem increasingly to pop up out of
nowhere and in the most unlikely places _ in orderly small towns,
in offices, in suburban schools, in genteel neighborhoods and, in
this case, in the commercial district of the well-to-do Buckhead
section of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   There is one other thread that connects these shootings to the
others. It is of course hard if not impossible to protect society
from a determined killer camouflaged, as this one was, by his own
ordinariness. But it is also true that there are too many weapons
floating around this country _ 200 million at last count _ and,
because of the continuing failure of our national legislators, too
many ways for people to get their hands on those weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta killer has been identified by police as Mark Barton,
a 44-year-old suburbanite and day trader in stocks who walked into
a brokerage office in the Piedmont Center, made an apparently
casual comment about the drop in stock prices and suddenly opened
fire.
</P>
<P>
   He then walked across the street and started shooting in another
office in the same complex. Nine people died altogether, and a
dozen others were wounded. Later in the day, when the police
spotted his van and pulled him over, he shot himself. He apparently
was suspected but never charged in two murders in 1993. Police
suspect he may also have killed his wife and two daughters, who
were found dead Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the toll rises, in the workplace and in the schools. Just
last month a psychiatrist in Michigan was shot by a former patient,
who then gunned down a 45-year-old woman and wounded others. In
April, a 71-year-old man raked the first floor of a Mormon library
in Salt Lake City with gunfire from a .22 caliber handgun, killing
two people and wounding four others. In March, a Johnson City,
Tenn., man shot his lawyer and another client in an apparent
dispute over his former wife's will.
</P>
<P>
   Before that were the killings that gave grotesque definition to
the 1997-98 school year _ students dead and wounded in Pearl,
Miss.; West Paducah, Ky.; Edinboro, Pa.; Jonesboro, Ark., and
Springfield, Ore. All of that seemed but a preamble to this year's
carnage at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. This is an
appalling list, and while there are no easy answers, the failure of
Congress to limit access to weapons among dangerous or unbalanced
individuals in appalling, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9286 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-SHOOTER-COX     07-29 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-SHOOTER-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1STLEDE: Fixes name in 2nd graf.
 &HT;    Eds: WITH SHOOTINGS-MAIN, SHOOTINGS-TRADER and SHOOTINGS VICTIMS
 &HT;    Shooter didn't have the look of a killer
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Mark Orrin Barton walked into a stock brokerage
Thursday afternoon, he wore the same genial countenance that he
displayed even in his driver's license photos: a warm smile across
a round face, topped by a shock of dark curly hair _ hardly the
look of a killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He greeted people on the way in,'' Harvey Houtkin, head of All
-Tech Investment Services, said later. And as he began blasting
away with two handguns, Hautkin said, Barton told his victims, ``I
hope I'm not upsetting your trading day.''
</P>
<P>
   Such incongruity clouded the portrait that emerged late Thursday
of the 44-year-old Barton, one of Georgia's worst mass murderers, a
man who drove a green minivan.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Barton, whose last known address was an
apartment in Stockbridge, Ga., killed nine people and wounded 12
others during an afternoon rampage at three normally quiet office
buildings on Atlanta's north side. Police were also at the scene of
Barton's Henry County home, where the bodies of a woman and two
children were found after the Atlanta shootings _ apparently those
of his wife and his son and daughter from a previous marriage.
</P>
<P>
   It all ended about when Barton shot himself to death outside a
suburban gas station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no information at all'' on what set off the killing
spree, Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell said late Thursday, ``except
we're certain Mr. Barton came to (the office complex) and killed
nine people.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews, public records and police accounts indicated that
until Thursday's rampage, Barton lived a mostly unremarkable life
with one glaring exception - Labor Day Weekend 1993, when his first
wife and her mother were hacked to death at a campground on an
Alabama lake.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, Barton's former father-in-law accused him of the
crime. That same accuser said Thursday the killings in Henry County
and Atlanta completed what Barton had started almost six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If what I've heard is true, the man has destroyed nearly my
whole family,'' said Bill Spivey of Lithia Springs, Ga., whose
wife, Eloise, then 59, and his 36-year-old daughter Debra were
killed at northeast Alabama's Lake Weiss. ``The man who it appears
killed my wife and daughter also killed my two grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   No charges were ever filed in the 1993 killings, but Alabama
authorities said Thursday he had been under suspicion for almost
six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the No. 1 suspect all the way through and still was,''
said Richard Igou, district attorney in Cedar Bluff, Ala., at the
time of the killings.
</P>
<P>
   The current district attorney, Mike O'Dell, said investigators
had monitored Barton's whereabouts for almost six years. ``There
was no precursors to think this might happen,'' O'Dell said. ``It
was a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 1993 killings, a judge in Douglas County, Ga., where
Barton lived at the time, ordered him to undergo a psychological
evaluation in a custody case involving his two young children.
</P>
<P>
   The results ``to this day make me shudder,'' said David McDade,
the Douglas County district attorney, who has reviewed the case.
``They indicated to us that he was certainly capable'' of
committing the murders.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview with The Atlanta Journal-Constitution in
1994, Barton _ who won custody of the children, Matthew and Shelly
_ declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Michael Hauptman, told a local Atlanta TV news
reporter on Thursday that Barton recently won a $600,000 settlement
from an insurance company that had refused to pay his wife's
life-insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   Hauptman described Barton as ``very, very quiet'' and ``very
gentle,'' a man who ``cared about his children, cared, quite
frankly, about his wife's murder and his mother-in-law.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from his first wife's death, though, nothing in Barton's
background seems to point toward the extreme violence that
characterized his final hours.
</P>
<P>
   Barton was born in Sumter, S.C., in 1955. Answering the
telephone Thursday night in the house where Barton grew up, his
79-year-old mother, Gladys Barton, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking to reporters _ none,'' she said. ``I'm not
giving any information.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
