<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GAMBLING-ARRESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
38 ARRESTED IN ILLEGAL GAMBLING RING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla.) (yn) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal and municipal law enforcement officials
fanned out in the New York area Thursday to arrest 38 people in
connection with a gambling operation that the police said brought
in $50 million a year from more than 500 illegal-gambling spots. A
39th person, the suspected ringleader, was arrested in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents arrested seven people described as the principal
managers of the organization on federal gambling and conspiracy
charges, including the man the authorities said was the ringleader,
Raul Rodriguez, 63. Rodriguez, who was on parole on federal
drug-trafficking charges, ran the operation from his home in Miami,
the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City police arrested 32 people on state gambling
charges during the searches Thursday, which came after a 27-month
investigation by the Brooklyn North vice squad, police officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that these arrests have dismantled the hierarchy of
this gambling operation,'' Police Commissioner Howard Safir said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The six other people arrested on federal charges were Manuel
Alvarez Sr., 57, of North Bergen, N.J.; his son Manuel Alvarez Jr.,
33, of Franklin Lakes, N.J.; Elena Novo, 39, of White Plains, N.Y.;
Mazimo Tavares, 38, of Lynbrook, N.Y., and Luis Moreno-Garcia, 39,
and Orlando Ferrer, 61, both of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also seized nearly $500,000 they believe was
related to the gambling operation and to other criminal enterprises
during searches of homes and businesses in Brooklyn, Queens, the
Bronx, and Nassau and Rockland Counties in New York, and in Hudson
County in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS joined the investigation to help trace the
organization's money trail, said Rick Schmidt, chief of the IRS
criminal division in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Donovan, associate special agent in charge of the FBI's
criminal division in New York, said law enforcement officials
believed that some of the profits from the illegal gambling
operation had been reinvested in other criminal enterprises.
Officials would not comment on what type of criminal activities the
money was being funneled into; however, narcotics agents were
involved in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the gambling enterprise was built like a
pyramid system. In the New York area, managers were given
franchises that operated 40 to 50 gambling locations each. The
police said the more than 500 illegal gambling locations in the
region were often run out of newsstands, bodegas, beauty stores and
other small shops.
</P>
<P>
   Safir added that the police planned to close many of them using
the city's nuisance abatement laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
