<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9296 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-TRADER-COX     07-29 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-TRADER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Day trading a gambling proposition
 &HT;    By Tom Walker and
 &HT;    Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Think of day trading in the stock market as playing a
video game all day with your computer and risking tons of money at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   That's an exaggeration, to be sure, but not much.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called day trader wouldn't exist without the computer and
the software needed to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   And, very likely, the phenomenon of day trading probably
wouldn't have emerged as it has except for the lure of the greatest
bull market in Wall Street history _ a stunning and long-running
rise in stock prices that created the image of quick wealth at
minimal risk.
</P>
<P>
   A trade association estimates that up to 5,000 people are
full-time day traders.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the motive for day trading is a quick profit,
within minutes or hours. In a day.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Barton, a 44-year-old day trader apparently shot and killed
himself in his van at an Atlanta gas station after police say he
killed at least 12 people during a bloody rampage Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The day trader, working alone or with partners in a business
setting, scans the market looking for signs that a stock will move
higher _ and then takes advantage of market volatility to jump on a
price gain.
</P>
<P>
   This is not anything like the usual procedure, where investors
pore over volumes of research on individual companies or industry
groups before making a buy or sell decision.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, the day trader probably doesn't care what a company
does or even if it is profitable. The day trader wants to buy the
stock, wait for it to go up in price and sell it to someone else
before the price slips again.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Streeters see online and day trading as a form of gambling
and an easy way to lose money, said Fred Allvine, head of the Stock
Market Project at Georgia Tech in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just rolling the dice,'' Allvine said. ``With the market
going down the last two weeks, it's really bad on day traders. They
are gamblers. Now the gamble has gone against them, and it was
bound to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Alexander, 53, managing principal of IJL Wachovia, said,
``When you buy a mutual fund, you're told to hold for five to 10
years, but when you day trade, you're told to hold 'til lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics call day trading the ``greater fool theory of
investing.''
</P>
<P>
   Day traders are often willing to pay more for stocks than would
a conventional trader _ more than the stocks are worth based on
traditional measures. The idea is that they will find a ``greater
fool'' willing to pay an even higher price.
</P>
<P>
   This criticism is probably unfair to most day traders, who may
simply be savvy investors who found an opportunity in new
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantan John Berner put it this way in a published interview:
``What we do is analogous to playing a financial video game.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for sure, day trading _ also referred to as online,
electronic or Internet trading _ has had a big impact on the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   Day trading developed after January 1997, when the National
Association of Securities Dealers changed the rules relating to the
display of buy and sell prices for stocks.
</P>
<P>
   This led to the formation of electronic communications networks,
or ECNs, which match buyers and sellers of stocks without using
traditional market makers. They execute the trades of day traders.
</P>
<P>
   The Electronic Traders Association, which represents many of the
day-trading shops, estimates that 4,000 to 5,000 people trade full
time through day-trading brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   International Data Corp., a research firm, says day traders
using the Internet are doing about 440,000 trades per day, or one
in seven U.S. stock transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Those are trades, mind you, not shares traded. Bloomberg News
reports that a single ECN may execute trades of as many as 95
million shares, or almost 10 percent of the Nasdaq market's
billion-share daily average.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, electronic trading is one of the biggest revolutions
on Wall Street since May 1, 1975, when the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission abolished fixed brokerage commissions _ a
change that dramatically pushed up trading volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Even the conservative New York Stock Exchange is looking at
extending trading to 19 hours per day, partly because of small
investors who otherwise have little access to after-hours trading,
as do the major brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of day trading is that it can be ``extremely
risky,'' according to the Web site of StreetAdvisor.com, a trading
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers should be prepared to lose all of the funds that
they use for day trading,'' the trading organization says in its
primer for day traders.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should not fund their day trading activities with
retirement savings, student loans, second mortgages, emergency
funds, funds set aside for purposes such as education or home
ownership, or funds required for current income.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander of IJL Wachovia, a 32-year veteran of the brokerage
industry, said day trading ``is like going to Las Vegas and getting
on a slot machine. All you care about is taking a dollar and making
it $1.05 by the end of the day. It's advertized on TV as the
greatest thing since sliced bread. But day trading is gambling. If
you do it to have fun, fine, but it's not investing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Terry, head of the securities division in the Georgia
Secretary of State's Office, said some states are investigating
day-trading firms, and that Georgia officials have their eye on
such companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some problems we have become aware of with the
industry in general that has attracted our attention in recent
months,'' Terry said. ``Claims have been made by firms as to the
likelihood of profitability, about how quote-unquote it is easy to
be a successful day trader. There has been evidence elsewhere of
firms lending the money to traders to cover losses. We and other
state regulators are looking at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other tidbits from StreetAdvisor.com for
prospective day traders: Day trading requires knowledge of
securities markets and knowledge of a securities firm's operations,
and day trading may result in large commissions.
</P>
<P>
   Another hazard, according to market watchers, is what will
happen if the bull market comes to an end?
</P>
<P>
   With shrinking stock market volume and less volatility, traders
would not have the same opportunity to make a quick profit.
</P>
<P>
   Author Robert Sobel, who has written extensively about the
market, told Bloomberg News that online investors have no track
records with market cycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own suspicions is that a lot of these pole are just playing
with fires, '' said Sobel.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
