<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCK-FUNDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK FUNDS RETURN TO FAVOR WITH HEFTY JUNE INVESTMENTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investors poured $19.2 billion into stock mutual
funds last month, completing the strongest quarter for stock-fund
sales in a year and suggesting that many people have regained the
calm they lost last summer, when fund sales evaporated as the stock
market plunged almost 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, purchases of fund shares during April, May and June
exceeded redemptions by almost $60 billion. That is almost as much
money as what flowed into stock funds during the same period in
1998, and more than what the industry took in during the second
quarter in 1997, the strongest year in history for fund sales.
</P>
<P>
   Still, stock-fund flows for the first six months of this year
are down about 27 percent from the first six months in 1998, mostly
from poor sales earlier this year, according to the Investment
Company Institute, the mutual-fund industry's leading trade group.
Some industry observers predict July could be a slower month,
primarily because of the 5 percent slide in the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index during the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And while the industry surpassed another milestone last month _
total assets in all mutual funds topped $6 trillion _ the rapid
growth in new cash flows into stock funds that propelled the
industry for much of this decade shows no sign of returning.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts attribute the slowdown to the rise in popularity
of online stock trading and lingering effects of the market's
turmoil last fall, but they disagree somewhat about the outlook.
Some view Internet trading as a permanent hindrance to fund sales,
while others believe the industry suffered through a rough patch
typical after a period of heavy market volatility.
</P>
<P>
   For July, fund sales were strong at the nation's big fund
families.
</P>
<P>
   The FMR Corp.'s Fidelity Investments arm said net sales of stock
funds through Wednesday totaled $3.2 billion, led by funds
including Aggressive Growth, Magellan, Growth Company, Dividend
Growth and its Spartan U.S. Equity index fund. Total stock-fund
sales at Fidelity of $19 billion so far this year are more than
twice the company's sales for all of last year.
</P>
<P>
   At Vanguard Group, the second-largest fund family, executives
estimate investors bought about $3.2 billion in stock fund shares
this month. John J. Brennan, chief executive at Vanguard,
attributed the slowdown in sales earlier in the year to industry
rhythms. ``Cyclicality is a normal part of the business, as
emotions swing up and down with the markets,'' he said, and changes
occur ``in people's ability to save.''
</P>
<P>
   Total stock fund net sales were about $15 billion in the first
four weeks of July, said Robert Adler, president of AMG Data
Services, a fund industry researcher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
