A9299 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     07-29 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TVG NETWORK AN EARLY JOKE FOR RACING FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, fans looked forward to the marriage of racing and
technology that would give us round-the-clock TV coverage and
interactive wagering, serving the couch-bound horseplayer while
enticing the channel-surfing novice.
</P>
<P>
   The wedding took place this month when the Television Games
Network became available to 1.1 million households nationwide via
satellite and to the curious on racetrack sets.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of guests throwing rice, we were surprised to see
the hosts of TVG's studio shows tossing cream pies at each other.
</P>
<P>
   Where we envisioned endless racing video and analysis, we've
seen a weird combination of intertrack TV, bad morning-drive radio
and Three Stooges slapstick. Male and female anchors have traded
clothes on camera (not as provocative as it sounds), swapped
drinking stories and joked about their own incompetence as
handicappers. Yes, there was even a food fight, though I'm not sure
if pies were thrown.
</P>
<P>
   When racing has wormed its way into the conversation, the topic
has been treated with irreverence that goes far beyond
``SportsCenter's'' fashionable irony. You feel sorry for Caton
Bredar, the veteran racing commentator, and Gary Mandella, the
former assistant trainer to his father Richard. The two most
knowledgeable members of the cast come off as teetotalers at a frat
party.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is disappointing because of the high hopes that
greeted TVG _ blessed by the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association, backed by TV Guide and co-produced in Los Angeles by
Fox, and widely held to represent the future of a sport badly in
need of a fresh start.
</P>
<P>
   Well, TVG executives have been pleading for patience, and we'll
go along with that. The future is a long time. Even Secretariat
lost his first race.
</P>
<P>
   What we're seeing now is the window dressing, without the
interactive components that will allow betting by phone in
Kentucky, Maryland and Oregon as early as next month and in
California as early as next year, and allow internet betting via
TVG this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the tomfoolery has taken place during dead periods in
the nation's racing day. Eventually, TVG will round out its 24-hour
coverage of all things equine with foreign racing, more extensive
interviews and news features, and even horse-themed movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just barely stuck our toe in the water,'' said Rick
Baedeker, the former Hollywood Park executive who is TVG's vice
president for communications. ``Anybody who wants to look at the
first couple of weeks and form all sorts of conclusions is welcome
to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Baedeker said, TVG executives are determined to let the
shows and showmen develop their personalities at their own pace.
</P>
<P>
   The turf media's response has stung the TVG people _
particularly a blistering review by Daily Racing Form columnist
Stan Bergstein. Baedeker, though, said the criticism won't change
the network's direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a game plan and we're going to stick to it. And the
fact a couple of columnists have strong opinions is frankly better
news to us than not being talked about at all,'' Baedeker said.
</P>
<P>
   At least for now, traditional racing fans would get more use out
of Youbet.com, the L.A.-based Internet concern that provides odds
updates, past-performance information, choppy race video and online
wagering _ though for a shorter list of tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, feeding traditional fans is only half of TVG's
mission. To succeed, the network must pull in viewers who wouldn't
otherwise pay attention to racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a chance to make a big difference (for the racing
industry), we've got to get the channel-surfers to stop and
watch,'' Baedeker said. ``That hasn't happened with straight racing
programming in the past and it won't happen in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   TVG is expected to be available on basic cable by the end of
1999. By then it might be worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   __ Gold watch: Owners John Toffan and Trudy McCaffery announced
that Free House, winner of the 1998 Pacific Classic and the '99
Santa Anita Handicap, has been retired because of the hind-end
injuries he sustained in the Pimlico Special loss to Real Quiet
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Free House gained popularity when he won the Santa Anita Derby
and waged game battles with Silver Charm in the '97 Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   But Blood-Horse magazine's online service went too far when it
said Free House might be California's most popular horse of the
decade. Best Pal had a larger following. So did Silver Charm.
</P>
<P>
   __ The weekend: The Eddie Read Handicap, Del Mar's biggest turf
race, matches 1998 Horse of the Meeting Ladies Din, Hawksley Hill,
Brave Act, Joe Who, Lazy Lode and as many as five others on Sunday.
Out of town the same day, Saratoga's Whitney Handicap has NTRA
series leader Behrens, Victory Gallop and Sir Bear.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the United Nations Handicap on the Monmouth (N.J.)
Park turf should be dominated by leading turf runner Yagli.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
