<HEADLINE>
JONES AND RIZZO ARE TIED, BUT INKSTER HAS INCENTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIDDIS, Alberta _ Rosie Jones has won nine tournaments and
close to $4 million in her Ladies Professional Golf Association
career.
</P>
<P>
   Winning a major championship is one of the few goals that Jones
has not achieved. But based on Thursday's performance, she may not
have to wait much longer.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a five-under-par 67, including birdies on three of the
last four holes, Jones tied Patti Rizzo for the lead after the
opening round of the du Maurier Classic. Juli Inkster and Catriona
Matthew of Scotland were tied for second place, one stroke behind.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster is trying to become only the second woman to win three
of the four modern LPGA majors in one season, joining Pat Bradley,
who did it in 1986. Inkster also needs one victory to gain entrance
into the LPGA Hall of Fame, and with 54 holes to play, she was in
position for an historic weekend at Priddis Greens Golf and Country
Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's all over me about the majors and the Hall of
Fame,'' said Inkster, who has won this year's U.S. Women's Open and
the McDonald's LPGA Championship. ``But I'm just trying to do the
same things I've been doing. If I'm in contention on Sunday, I feel
I have just as good a chance as anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jones, who hopes to postpone Inkster's date with history,
closed with a flourish Thursday, making birdies on Nos. 15, 17 and
18. Jones, a native of California who makes her home in Atlanta,
will turn 40 years old in November, and she expects to remain on
tour perhaps only three or four more years. Time is running out in
her quest to win a major. But she remains a threat to win any week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a couple of more years out here, and I would love to
put a major on my bio,'' said Jones, who has earned more money
($3.97 million) in her career than any LPGA player who has not won
a major. ``I've had a great career. I've played a lot of great
golf. I don't think it's going to make or break my career. But when
I lay down my clubs, I could lay them down a lot easier if I had a
major.''
</P>
<P>
   Rizzo has not won on tour since 1989, but she played solidly
Thursday in a round that included seven birdies and two bogeys.
Meanwhile, Jones has been one of the game's most consistent
players, with one victory in each of the past four years. Although
Jones has yet to win in 1999, she has six top-10 finishes, and
entered this week in 12th place on the season's money list.
</P>
<P>
   Putting has always been one of Jones' strengths, and her stroke
was true Thursday. She made a 17-footer for birdie at No. 11, a
6-footer for birdie at No. 15, a 20-footer for birdie at No. 17,
and a 5-footer for birdie at No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   The greens at Priddis are large with numerous slopes, making
many putts difficult to read. But Jones only needed 29 putts in her
round, and she made life easier by hitting many approach shots
close to the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing the breaks well and using my imagination,'' Jones
said. ``Even when you don't see the break, you feel it with your
other senses, using your feet or the lay of the land. You have to
do that playing greens like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' only bogey came at the par-4 No. 13, when she hit a poor
6-iron approach shot that nearly sailed into the water near the
green. But Jones got a break when the ball hit a rock next to the
water and ricocheted onto dry land. Jones chipped onto the green
and scrambled for bogey.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jones was well aware that Inkster was lurking. ``It
doesn't surprise me at all that she is playing well,'' Jones said
of Inkster. ``She will be in the Hall of Fame before the end of the
year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
