<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KIMBALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS L. KIMBALL, 81; LED WILDLIFE GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas L. Kimball, former chief executive of the National
Wildlife Federation, died on July 20 at Manor Care Convalescent
Home in Citrus Heights, Calif. He was 81 and lived in Roseville,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a stroke, said his wife, Arvella Allen Kimball.
</P>
<P>
   As chief executive, Kimball was the highest-ranking paid officer
of the wildlife federation from 1973 until he retired in 1981. From
1960 until his promotion to chief executive, he was executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   Under Kimball, the foundation expanded its educational and
advocacy efforts and constructed two buildings, Mark Van Putten,
the group's president, said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimball served on various committees dealing with state and
national environmental policy and was a delegate to meetings of the
International Whaling Commission. The honors he received included
the Conservation Service Award from the Interior Department.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Los Angeles, grew up in Phoenix and received a
bachelor's degree from Brigham Young University. He was director of
the Colorado Game and Fish Department from 1952 to 1960.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife of 59 years, he is survived by two sons,
Thomas S., of Oakdale, Calif., and Allen K., of Seattle; four
daughters, Patricia Clark of Boise, Idaho, Pamela Hunt of
Escondido, Calif., Kay Lafleur of Herndon, Va., and Andrea
Zimmerman of Granite Bay, Calif.; two brothers, Horace, of Elkton,
Md., and Howard, of Phoenix; a sister, Nina Finley of Salt Lake
City; 25 grandchildren and 12 great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
