A9304 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-GERE-PROFILE-HNS     07-29 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GERE-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERE SHOWS LIGHTER SIDE IN SEEKING `RUNAWAY' HIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After making beautiful music together in 1990's
``Pretty Woman,'' Richard Gere and Julia Roberts were open to an
encore.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted to team for ``Pretty Woman II.'' They just couldn't
find a proper script.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty Woman'' may have grossed $463 million worldwide, but
where could Gere's lonely tycoon and Roberts' good-hearted
prostitute go after they fell in love?
</P>
<P>
   The artistic prospects looked as shaky as ``The Sting II,''
``The Odd Couple II'' or ``Beyond the Poseidon Adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A sequel would rely on picking up where `Pretty Woman'
ended,'' said Garry Marshall, the film's director. ``But too much
time had passed _ the actors were older _ and nobody had a script
that took them 10 years later, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, finding any well-written adult romantic comedy is
extremely difficult, Gere observed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lightning struck with `Pretty Woman,''' the actor said. ``You
can't expect it to strike there again.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can try to rekindle a special chemistry, which is why
Gere, 49, and Roberts, 31, reunited with Marshall for ``Runaway
Bride,'' opening this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Gere and Marshall met the press here to talk about the new film.
Roberts was off making ``Erin Brockovich,'' a drama for director
Steven Soderbergh. She and Gere are neighbors in Manhattan and have
kept in touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Runaway Bride'' is not a ``Pretty Woman'' sequel. But it is a
romantic comedy _ this time in a screwball vein _ and its zestful
fun should make it one of late-summer's biggest hits.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Runaway Bride,'' Gere plays an arrogant reporter for USA
Today who _ on hearsay _ writes a misogynist column about a woman
in rural Maryland (Roberts) known for leaving men at the altar.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts disputes the claim, leading Gere to investigate on her
home turf, just as she heads toward another wedding date.
</P>
<P>
   Feisty sparks fly between the reporter and his quarry _ and
perhaps sparks of another kind, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where does our chemistry come from?'' Gere echoes the
question. ``You tell me. Of course, it doesn't hurt that Julia's
beautiful, smart, talented and unexpected. And Garry brings out the
best in us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gere first read the ``Runaway Bride'' script by Josann McGibbon
and Sara Parriott. He then called Roberts, who was in London at the
time filming ``Notting Hill,'' her hit of this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been trying to develop other things over the years, and
they just weren't right,'' he said. ``But this one was full-blown _
right there. It was smartly combative, in the way that intelligent
men and women go at each other. It was as juicy and fun as such
films were in the '40s.''
</P>
<P>
   So Gere told Roberts, ``Whether or not I make this movie, you
should, because the part is perfect for you.''
</P>
<P>
   She resisted doing it without him, so they got together at
Gere's office to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very professional,'' Gere said. ``We got out our
directors lists, and about halfway through we started laughing and
saying, `This is ridiculous. This is for Garry. Of course it's
Garry.'''
</P>
<P>
   So they called Marshall, and within days the film was in
pre-production.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very quick _ very easy,'' Gere said.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said his stars ``grew'' as actors and as people over
the years, but their on-screen relationship hadn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the first day, that chemistry was there again,'' he said.
``With Richard and Julia, you don't need violins. With some couples
I've needed a full orchestra.''
</P>
<P>
   Gere especially relished playing a ``fun'' character this time.
``In `Pretty Woman,' I was very straight and depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Audiences may be surprised how much he opens up, playing
self-effacing and even silly bits.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't think of Richard as Cary Grant _ maybe Ulysses S.
Grant,'' Marshall said. ``But he can do light comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   It helped having Marshall at the helm. His fun-loving spirit
imbues the film.
</P>
<P>
   Each day on the set brought new celebrations, from birthdays,
anniversaries and engagements to surprise visits by friends and
family (such as the director's sister, Penny Marshall), who would
walk into scenes while the cameras rolled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Runaway Bride'' also has the same composer as ``Pretty
Woman,'' James Newton Howard, and about 10 of the same supporting
actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``For old times' sake I thought that would be interesting,''
Marshall said. ``The supporting cast for me was a gathering of
eagles. Everybody hit a home run for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief among them is Hector Elizondo, who's been in all 11 of
Marshall's movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garry likes the way I feed him the ball in the post,''
Elizondo said, using a basketball analogy.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pretty Woman,'' Elizondo was the kind hotel manager who
took Roberts under his wing. In ``Runaway Bride,'' he plays the
husband of Gere's editor and ex-wife, played by Rita Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   During his work, Elizondo said, many lines and bits were
ad-libbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garry just keeps the cameras rolling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he never heard of Roberts' own near-marriage to Kiefer
Sutherland coming up on the set, ``but I'm sure there were some
jokes flying around,'' considering the plot's parallel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always jokes on a Garry Marshall set, and a lot of
celebrations. There was a cake every day,'' Elizondo said.
</P>
<P>
   Gere said the director ``creates an atmosphere where it's
natural to be goofy and take a shot. It's very loose, full of life
and great fun.''
</P>
<P>
   That included a surprise that became a running joke.
</P>
<P>
   Since women were angry with Gere's character, Marshall quietly
asked an elderly woman passing him on a Manhattan street to hit him
with a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time, I didn't know it was going to happen, and she
clobbered me with an umbrella,'' Gere said. ``Garry hurried over
and said, `Not with an umbrella _ with a newspaper.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The bit worked so well, we kept finding other places to do it.
Garry would grab some old lady and say, `Hit him with a newspaper.'
But the umbrella take was the one we used for that first scene.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Pretty Woman,'' Gere plays piano in ``Runaway Bride.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Music is a gift my parents gave me,'' he said. ``I probably
spend more time with music than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   He also finds time to support Tibet and human-rights causes.
During the Kosovo crisis, Gere visited refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I have the resources and inclination to find out what's
going on in the world, so I feel a responsibility to do something
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   As he approaches his 50th birthday Aug. 31 _ ``It doesn't seem
like a big deal,'' he says _ Gere also nears fatherhood. His
girlfriend, actress Carey Lowell (``Law &AMP; Order''), is expecting
their child early next year. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Before then, Gere will make ``Autumn in New York,'' a romantic
comedy with Winona Ryder. Then he'll be in Dallas to make
``Mornings With Dr. T.,'' a comedy for Robert Altman.
</P>
<P>
   A Pennsylvania native, Gere got his start in theater, including
the musical comedy ``Grease.'' But most of his movies have been
dramas, such as the recent ``Primal Fear,'' and he relishes a shift
to comedy.
</P>
<P>
   That includes a ``snake dance'' scene in ``Runaway Bride'' in
which his character runs gingerly across a field at night, fearful
of biting reptiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to do farce and crazy stuff,'' Gere said. ``I grew
up doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing that snake dance for 50 years,'' he said with
a laugh. ``That was my snake dance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
