<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9426 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SANDERS-NYT &LR;      07-29 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SANDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: A SLICK MOVE, OR IS SANDERS REALLY DONE?
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier this month Detroit Lions wide receiver Herman Moore
bumped into Barry Sanders while they were running errands near
their homes in a Detroit suburb. It was one of the few times that
anyone had made contact with Sanders, the Detroit running back. A
few minutes into the conversation, Sanders dropped a bombshell.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders told Moore he was considering retiring. Moore was
shocked. Later that day Moore decided that Sanders must have been
joking, and he went about his business. He didn't give the
conversation another thought until he heard Sanders' retirement
announcement on Wednesday. That day Moore received 141 pages on his
beeper from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders ran into another teammate in the parking lot of a
shopping mall around the same time. Sanders again said he might
retire. Stunned, the player asked why, and Sanders responded that
he was tired of losing and had never known what it was like to play
for a winning franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you're gone?'' the player asked. ``That's it? No more
Barry?''
</P>
<P>
   He said Sanders responded, ``I don't know, unless you can trade
me to the 49ers.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore and the other player were left confused. Sanders was
saying he was leaving football. At the same time, he was expressing
hesitation, even joking about playing for another team.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lions players doubt _ very strongly _ that Sanders will
stay out of football, but then again, both never thought that he
would retire now. Sanders remains as unpredictable as one of his
spin moves.
</P>
<P>
   But many in the NFL agree with Moore and his teammate that
Sanders is not done. A consensus of general managers, coaches and
players interviewed since Sanders made his announcement is that the
running back will be seen running for yardage on the field again.
</P>
<P>
   The only disagreement is where. Some think he will play with
Detroit this season. Others, including one executive with the
Lions, think Sanders will sit out this season and then demand a
trade in hopes of playing with a contender next year. That scenario
is plausible.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders has $18 million left on his deal over the next four
years. He has been paid almost one-third of his $11 million signing
bonus. If Sanders was traded now, the unpaid portion of the bonus,
more than $7 million, would count immediately against the salary
cap, which is $57.3 million. As of late this week, the Lions had
only $625,000 worth of cap room left. Thus, this year it is
impossible for Detroit to trade Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lions would be able to make a deal next year when the
salary cap is expected to increase to about $62 million. A team
like the Seattle Seahawks, for example, only a few players and a
few years away from contending for a championship, could use the
greater cap room, trade for Sanders, giving Detroit at least two
No. 1 picks in return, and Sanders could get his ring.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the Lions' public stance, a team executive said the
club has considered such a scenario and is willing to trade Sanders
next season. It feels that it is too close to the beginning of the
1999 season to orchestrate a trade and that the salary cap
ramifications are too great.
</P>
<P>
   There are several precedents for a player missing a year and
then joining another team. Defensive lineman Sean Gilbert sat out
the 1997 season because of a contract dispute with the Washington
Redskins. At the start of that year the Carolina Panthers
considered trading for Gilbert but did not have the salary cap
space.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1998 season the NFL announced an increase in the cap
from $41.45 million to $52.38 million. The extra cash allowed the
Panthers to sign Gilbert to a seven-year, $46.5 million contract
that included a $10 million bonus. They also had to give Washington
two No. 1 draft choices because Gilbert had been designated a
franchise player.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders could be serious about retiring. Or he could come back
this season. But what happened with Gilbert demonstrated that all
general managers need is a reasonable amount of salary cap room,
along with a calculator, and almost any deal can get done.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders retired for a variety of reasons. He was distraught from
losing five straight games at the end of last season. The volatile
personality of coach Bobby Ross, who at times has a temper, wore on
the running back. And Sanders disliked how the Lions addressed free
agency. He watched key veterans, and friends, such as offensive
linemen Kevin Glover and Lomas Brown, leave.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when contract negotiations with the Lions moved
at a snail's pace, Sanders became infuriated. He almost retired out
of frustration, a teammate said.
</P>
<P>
   During Sanders' 10 seasons in Detroit, the Lions had a 78-82
regular-season record, and won only one playoff game. Sanders was
only 1,457 yards away from Walter Payton's career rushing record,
and teammates say Sanders wants to break it.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is vacationing in Europe. So maybe everyone is wrong.
Maybe Sanders will not return to American football.
</P>
<P>
   Do the Barcelona Dragons have a salary cap?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
