<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9430 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      07-29 0366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A DESERVED FINE FOR CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, July 30:
</P>
<P>
   Federal Judge Susan Webber Wright has set an appropriate
sanction in directing President Clinton to pay nearly $90,000 to
Paula Jones' lawyers for making false statements about his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky in the Jones lawsuit. The
constitutional and political issues raised by the events that
ultimately led to Clinton's impeachment will long be analyzed by
historians. But Judge Wright steered clear of pronouncing judgment
on the full harm done to the Clinton presidency or to the office
itself by Clinton's behavior. Instead she focused on his actions
not as a political leader but as a litigant governed by the rule of
law.
</P>
<P>
   In April she found him in contempt of court for ``giving false,
misleading and evasive answers that were designed to obstruct the
judicial process.'' That stark assessment, unvarnished by political
spin, now stands as the appropriate legal conclusion about his
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, as part of the contempt ruling, Judge Wright ordered
Clinton to pay the Jones lawyers for expenses and attorneys' fees
incurred as a result of his false answers to written
interrogatories and false testimony during a deposition on Jan. 17,
1998. He had denied ever being alone with Ms. Lewinsky and denied
having sexual relations with her. Judge Wright earlier ordered
Clinton to pay $1,202 for the costs the government incurred when
she traveled to Washington to preside over that tainted deposition.
</P>
<P>
   The Jones lawyers had sought nearly $500,000 in costs, but Judge
Wright ruled that the sanction must be based on actual losses in
light of the fact that the parties have already settled the case
for $850,000. Clinton's lawyers did not appeal the contempt ruling,
and many may have considered the ruling a symbolic gesture. But the
order to pay goes beyond symbolism. The $90,000 penalty sends a
clear message that even a president cannot get away with
intentional falsehoods under oath. It may also deter ordinary
citizens from emulating Clinton's abuse of the judicial system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
