<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-KLEIN-NYT &LR;      07-29 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KLEIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMUND KLEIN, 77, AN EXPERT ON SKIN CANCER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y.)  (rk) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Edmund Klein, whose pioneering work on skin cancer was
honored with a Clinical Research Award from the Albert and Mary
Lasker Foundation in 1972, died on Saturday at Millard Fillmore
Hospital in Buffalo. He was 77 and lived in Williamsville, N.Y., a
Buffalo suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The causes were complications of diabetes and congestive heart
failure, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Klein's early insights, that skin cancer could be treated
externally, led him to cancer research in dermatology. With the
advancing age of the population, he saw an increasing need for
nonsurgical therapies of skin cancer arising commonly from long
exposure to sunlight, and he became recognized for his work in
applying drugs directly to cancers and precancerous lesions.
</P>
<P>
   He also advanced the use of immunotherapy, in which the body's
own defenses are alerted to fend off tumors. This involved the
application of agents to stimulate the immune system and pointed
the way toward the use of interferon and interleukins in today's
cancer therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The Lasker Foundation honored him for developing the means of
treating superficial cancers with a topical ointment containing
potent anticancer chemicals. That type of treatment remains in use
today, especially for pre-malignant growths.
</P>
<P>
   Klein found himself amid controversy in 1977, when he was
interviewed by a Reader's Digest writer for an article about skin
cancer in general and stated ``authoritatively'' that President
Lyndon Johnson had been treated for it.
</P>
<P>
   Although Johnson had died four years earlier, the report was
considered significant, not so much because of the seriousness of
the illness as because of the implication of secrecy previously
surrounding the president's condition.
</P>
<P>
   But the Johnson family and White House doctors denied the report
of skin cancer, although the removal of less serious spots from the
president's skin was confirmed by his personal physician. Klein
said he had based his remark on a phone call he had received from
the Johnson White House, which, he said, had made a general inquiry
about a possible treatment for skin cancer. He also said he had
been authorized to disclose the condition by a Johnson family
representative, whom he declined to identify.
</P>
<P>
   Klein was long associated with the School of Medicine at the
State University of New York at Buffalo, where he was research
professor of medical dermatology and experimental pathology, and
with the Roswell Park Memorial Institute in Buffalo. He stepped
down as the institute's chief of dermatology in 1982 to enter
private practice but continued his association as a researcher.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Klein was born in Vienna and, as a refugee from the
Nazis, graduated in 1941 from the University of Toronto, where he
received his M.D. in 1951. He became a Canadian citizen and
finished his training at the Harvard University Laboratory for
Physical Chemistry and at the Children's Cancer Research Foundation
at Children's Hospital in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   After a time at Tufts University, he joined the staff at Roswell
Park Memorial as chief of dermatology in 1961. SUNY Buffalo
appointed him an associate professor of experimental pathology the
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Klein is survived by his wife of 48 years, Martha Doble Klein;
two sons, Lawrence, of Columbia, S.C., and Peter, of Philadelphia;
three daughters, Judith Augustino, Rene Rubino and Amy Szymoniak,
all of Williamsville; a sister, Ruth Klein of London, and nine
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9434 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI30-AZR &LR;      07-29 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI30-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER, (YAWN) MASS KILLING  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By EJ MONTINI   
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most shocking thing about the murders in Atlanta, the
``only'' thing shocking about the murders in Atlanta, is that the
murders in Atlanta aren't shocking.
</P>
<P>
   We pretend that they are.
</P>
<P>
   We say that they are, if only to make ourselves feel better, to
pretend we have a shred of old-fashioned innocence and sensitivity
left.
</P>
<P>
   But we don't.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to say exactly when it happened, when horror and
bloodshed became nothing more than a way for CNN and CBS and NBC
and ABC to bolster viewership on a slow summer's day. But it's
true. There's nothing a crazy man with a gun can do that stuns us.
</P>
<P>
   The news Tuesday kept getting worse and worse.
</P>
<P>
   First reports said a gunman was loose in an office building the
Buckhead section of Atlanta, a place filled with fancy stores and
fancy offices and fancy apartments. Elton John once had a place
there.
</P>
<P>
   Then we learned that a man had walked into a brokerage office at
a place called Securities Center and opened fire. About a dozen
wounded were being taken to local hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   How terrible, we said. How horrible. How disgusting.
</P>
<P>
   But no one said, ``How surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, we heard that the suspected gunman, Mark Barton, walked
across the street after his initial rampage and began shooting up
another brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters on the scene were told by emergency personnel and
witnesses that there are dead bodies in the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't throw us for a loop.
</P>
<P>
   Later, police said Barton's wife and two children are found dead
at an apartment 16 miles from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   We're a nation with many lunatics and many more guns. We weren't
bowled over.
</P>
<P>
   Bulletins flashed about a previous wife and mother-in-law of
Barton who were killed in 1993. No one was ever charged with the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Our minds weren't boggled.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of Atlanta went to the scene and reported that four
people were dead in one building and five in the other, shot with
.9 mm and .45-caliber handguns, and that there were a dozen
wounded, some of them critical.
</P>
<P>
   He asked us to pray for Atlanta and for the families of the
victims, and we did. We've done the same thing before.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, we can no longer remember all the times we've prayed
for the families of victims in mass killings.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, there was August 1986, when postal worker Pat
Sherrill, opened fire at a post office in Edmond, Okla., killing 14
people, then fatally shooting himself.
</P>
<P>
   A researcher found Sherrill's name for me. I couldn't remember
it.
</P>
<P>
   How about the 23 people fatally shot by George Hennard in 1991
after he drove his pickup truck through a plate-glass window of a
Luby's Cafeteria in Killeen, Texas?
</P>
<P>
   The Luby's part I remembered. But I couldn't recall the killer's
name or the town. Or the fact that he, too, killed himself.
</P>
<P>
   And there were the 21 people shot in a McDonald's restaurant in
San Ysidro, Calif., by James Oliver Huberty, an out-of-work
security guard. Huberty was killed by a police sharpshooter.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few months ago, we had Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, who
murdered 13 before killing themselves at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there was Aug. 1, 1966, when sniper Charles J.
Whitman took up a position on the University of Texas tower in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman was shot to death in the end, but not before killing 16,
injuring 31 and inflicting what turned out to be a fatal wound on
the American soul.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, before the last TV news of the day, Mark Barton
put a gun to his head and pulled the trigger. It gave Atlanta's
mayor one more chance to appear before the cameras and ask us to
pray. And we should.
</P>
<P>
   For the victims.
</P>
<P>
   For Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   For ourselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
