<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9437 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARISH30-AZR &LR;      07-29 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARISH30-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-ENVOY PLEAS FIFTH PRIVILEGE IN CHINA QUERY  
 HOUSE HEARS ABOUT U.S. VISAS IN EXCHANGE FOR `GRATUITIES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A former U.S. Embassy official in Beijing asserted
his Fifth Amendment rights Thursday rather than respond to
allegations that he accepted favors from people seeking visas to
travel to Phoenix and other U.S. cities.
</P>
<P>
   The House Government Reform Committee presented evidence at a
hearing to show that Charles M. Parish Jr. received ``valuable
gratuities,'' including gifts and free lodging in Scottsdale, Las
Vegas and other locations. The committee, in a report by its staff,
also said Parish had ``inappropriate contacts'' with Chinese
citizens that included sexual relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Visa officers must abide by strict rules, including reporting
personal relationships with people seeking visas, in order to
assure they are not compromised. In many countries, citizens wait
for hours in long lines to apply for a visa to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After entering the congressional hearing room with his attorney,
Parish, 52, an affable ex-Marine, said a cheerful ``Good morning''
to the committee and then declined, one by one, to answer any
substantive questions.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing produced new information about Parish and his
activities at the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   One of several previously undisclosed sections of Wednesday's
report said that Parish helped a Chinese student, Hong Zhao, get a
job with BNU Corp., a Phoenix real-estate company owned by a
Chinese government-owned conglomerate. BNU is operated by Elizabeth
Mann, Arizona's most important business connection to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The committee said it learned that Zhao wrote a $7,000 check to
Parish in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (the) committee staff interviewed Ms. Zhao, she denied
buying a visa from Mr. Parish, and claimed that she was simply
repaying Parish for money he had loaned her over the past several
years,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee report said there is evidence that Parish
processed visas at BNU's request so that Chinese executives could
travel to the Valley and elsewhere. BNU is a subsidiary of China
National Cereals, Oils and Foodstuffs Import and Export Corp.,
known as COFCO.
</P>
<P>
   COFCO ``denies any illegal action with respect to the processing
of visas,'' said Charles Conroy, attorney for COFCO and its U.S.
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Parish, who was responding to a subpoena, had never publicly
testified before, although he been interviewed by ``The Arizona
Republic'' and the ``Los Angeles Times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Chairman, on advice of my counsel, I must respectfully
invoke my constitutional right to decline to answer,'' Parish said,
eight times in all.
</P>
<P>
   The committee chairman, Dan Burton, R-Ind., wouldn't allow
Parish's attorney to read a statement explaining his client's
refusal to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not a witness and you are not allowed to make any kind
of statement. You are not to speak to the committee, OK?'' Burton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney, Ralph Martin, said in an interview later that the
committee was ``unfair'' in declining to put a statement in the
record on his client's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statement says Mr. Parish cooperated fully with the State
Department and the FBI. This committee has put unsubstantiated
allegations before it, and he had no choice but to seek the
protection of the Constitution,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, the committee released an internal U.S.
embassy memorandum from 1996 saying Chinese officials and
businessmen believed it was ``very easy'' to get a visa in Beijing
through favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese said that if you anticipated that you might have
difficulty obtaining a visa _ for instance, you were applying for a
visa allowing you to work in the United States, but you did not
speak English _ you simply t ook `the Black official' in the
embassy to dinner, gave him a `gift,' and you were guaranteed a
visa,'' said the memorandum from one embassy official to another.
</P>
<P>
   The committee staff member later said the memorandum referred to
Parish, who is African-American.
</P>
<P>
   Burton opened the hearing by declaring that three separate State
Department offices ``dropped the ball'' in their investigations of
the embassy, largely by not following promising leads or preserving
documents in Parish's office in Beijing. Parish, who was at the
embassy from 1994 until mid-1996, was transferred to Washington and
put to work reviewing visa applications from Iraq and Iran. He is
now retired.
</P>
<P>
   Jacquelyn Williams-Bridgers, the State Department inspector
general, said at the hearing that she could not discuss Parish's
case because of Justice Department concerns that her testimony
could violate grand jury secrecy laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely the most ridiculous thing I've ever
heard,'' Burton said in response. ``It's typical of the kind of
stonewalling Janet Reno's Justice Department has engaged in.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton said he had it ``on good authority'' that the Justice
Department was about to close the Parish investigation, but had
kept it open so there would be a reason not to cooperate with his
committee.
</P>
<P>
   John Russell, the Justice Department spokesman on criminal
matters, said he hadn't heard Burton's remarks and could not
respond.
</P>
<P>
   But Henry Waxman, D-Calif., the committee's top-ranking
Democrat, said Burton seemed out to attack the Justice Department,
no matter what the agency did.
</P>
<P>
   Burton's reasoning ``just seems to be contradictory,'' Waxman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they closed their investigation, they'd be criticized
because it should be taken more seriously. If they kept it open,
they're criticized because they haven't closed it so that witnesses
can come before this committee to give evidence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee hearing came 11 weeks after it heard testimony
from Johnny Chung, a Taiwanese-born Californian who was once a
Democratic Party fund-raiser. The committee has been trying to
determine, with Chung's help, whether China attempted to interfere
with the 1996 presidential election by funneling large
contributions to the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Chung and Parish saw each other occasionally in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Chung testified that Parish approved visas for 25 to 30 of his
business associates. Chung also testified that Parish requested
some favors, including asking him to hire a computer tutor for an
embassy secretary. Chung said he complied with the request. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2327EDT &QL; 
