<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9438 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROWTH-AZR &LR;      07-29 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWTH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA TAKES BIG STEP, SETS UP GROWTH BOUNDARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHERINE REAGOR  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoenix has drawn its first line in the sand to slow growth.
</P>
<P>
   In the Valley's far northern desert, the city has set up a
version of an urban growth boundary in a &UR; housing hot spot along
Interstate 17.
</P>
<P>
   Masked under the name ``infrastructure limit line,'' the
boundary surrounds a fast-growing, 14-square-mile urban core along
the Black Canyon Freeway north of Central Arizona Project Canal
that could be home to 150,000 people by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The line limits how far the city will build streets and sewer
lines without special approval from the Phoenix Planning Commission
and City Council. Any development outside the line will have to pay
for its own streets and sewers or seek aid from the city through
public hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, developers pay for some infrastructure costs.
</P>
<P>
   The goals are to steer growth to the central core along I-17
instead of letting it sprout in all directions and to ensure that
residential growth is accompanied by commercial construction and
new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club, which has been pushing for urban growth
boundaries, considers the line a step in the right direction to
curb the Valley's sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Developers in the area also consider it an effective way to
provide a focus for population growth.
</P>
<P>
   It definitely doesn't go as far as Portland, Ore.'s well-known
growth boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the same as an urban growth boundary without the hard
lines,'' Phoenix planner Dave Richert said, meaning that the lines
can be broadened later if the core is heavily developed.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix City Council approved the line around the North
Black Canyon Corridor on July 7.
</P>
<P>
   The infrastructure boundary stretches north along I-17, the
western edge, past the Carefree Highway and east as far as Seventh
Avenue. It drops as far south as the CAP Canal.
</P>
<P>
   If after 10 years the city wants to extend the line, the plan
can be amended. But until then, any development outside the
perimeter that wants assistance from the city must go to the people
and then the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a step in the right direction, and probably as
good as it can get for city planning,'' said Sierra Club activist
Chris Gehlker of northwest Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he questions why Phoenix didn't try to put up a growth
boundary in the Deer Valley &UR; area before growth spreads in all
directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city should clean up one mess before they move on to play
with a new toy,'' Gehlker said.
</P>
<P>
   Deer Valley is several miles south of the core of the North
Black Canyon Corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the North Black Canyon area's recent planning is due to
Anthem, a huge new Del Webb community near New River, which started
a stampede of home buyers in the Valley's far north.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem is in an unincorporated part of Maricopa County north of
Phoenix. As many as 50,000 people could live in the 5,800-acre
community when it's completed in the next five to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The growth-limiting line ends a few miles south of Anthem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nearby, developers are filling in the Phoenix corridor with
three big housing projects. Tramonto, Sonoran Foothills and
Dynamite Mountain Ranch, with a total of about 3,000 acres and at
least 6,000 houses, are all planned within the boundary.
</P>
<P>
   The developers of the three projects will pay almost $20 million
for their share of the area's infrastructure development and impact
fees, which covers part of the infrastructures cost. The city is
paying the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are winners and losers with the line,'' said John
Graham, president of Sunbelt Holdings, which is developing Sonoran
Foothills. ``Our community falls within its boundaries, but we are
still putting up a lot of money to build there.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; He said the infrastructure line has a lot of merit because it
will help build a core for the area, but he wouldn't want to repeat
the three-year process that it took for it to be put in place.
</P>
<P>
   Valley Partnership, a lobbying group for builders, backs
Phoenix's first version of the growth boundary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Urban growth boundaries such as this one are a planning tool
that can be used as necessary to help focus growth,'' said Maeve
Johnson, executive director of the trade group.
</P>
<P>
   The urban growth boundary is the centerpiece of Portland's
strong regional and preservation-minded plans.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 years ago, hundreds of Oregon cities drew imaginary
lines inside of which urban development would be permitted to take
place and outside of which it wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club is proposing something similar for Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   To counter that measure, which they say would put a halt to
Phoenix's growth and stymie its economy, developers and other
business interests backed the Growing Smarter Plan. It passed in
November.
</P>
<P>
   The act requires communities to adopt general plans every 10
years with plans for efficient transportation and well-timed
expansion of sewers, streets and other infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Developers must also pay their fair share of the cost of new
services for the their projects, but not the entire cost.
</P>
<P>
   The infrastructure limit line is part of a North Black Canyon
General Plan amendment quietly approved a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is for the 43,000-acre area, dubbed the North Black
Canyon Corridor that straddles I-17 and runs roughly from the CAP
Canal to the city's northern limits.
</P>
<P>
   The corridor is mostly raw desert that could be transformed into
several big communities with thousands of new houses. Another few
thousand acres to the east is also targeted by the city to become
preserve space.
</P>
<P>
   The North Black Canyon Corridor is one area in Phoenix that is
expected to experience huge growth, according to city planners.
</P>
<P>
   By 2020, at a 2 percent growth rate, almost 600,000 more people
will call Phoenix home. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
