<DOCNO> NYT19990729.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9440 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROP-187-LADN     07-29 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROP-187-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS QUITS STATE FIGHT FOR PROP. 187
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Gov. Gray Davis said Thursday the state will drop
its legal fight for Proposition 187, but supporters vowed to carry
on a court battle to enforce the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The ballot measure, which won 60 percent of the vote in 1994,
was intended to limit public education, welfare and health services
to illegal immigrants. It became ensnared in legal battles and most
provisions never took effect.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who opposes the measure, contended that federal law
already covers most of the proposition's main provisions, such as
the denial of welfare and other benefits to illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not gutted 187,'' Davis said during a news conference
in Los Angeles. ``I would say to supporters of 187 that they should
declare victory and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' decision resulted from a mediation process to find a
solution to the legal fight. Under the agreement, the state will
withdraw its appeal of a federal court ruling that found much of
the measure unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have dissolved a divisive wedge issue in a way that is fair
to the voters, the Constitution and the law,'' the Democratic
governor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have avoided years of divisiveness and costly litigation.
It's estimated we spent over $5 million defending this to date and
would have spent a good deal more to move this case to the U.S.
Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is 187 struck down by this agreement? Yes. But it is
supplanted by federal laws that implement the same provisions as
187.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Proposition 187 said they expected Davis'
decision, since proponents of the measure were not included in the
mediation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, only one side of the issue was represented --
the side of the opponents,'' said John Findley, principal attorney
for the Pacific Legal Foundation, a proponent of Proposition 187.
</P>
<P>
   The fight is not over, Findley said, adding: ``There are going
to be lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, U.S. District Judge Mariana R. Pfaelzer ruled that
most of the initiative was unconstitutional, in part because it
entered the jurisdiction of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Inheriting the push for Proposition 187 from his Republican
predecessor Pete Wilson, Davis asked the 9th District Court of
Appeals to appoint a mediator to help determine how to settle the
battle. Thursday's announcement came after Davis and
anti-Proposition 187 forces met for three months.
</P>
<P>
   Findley said the state's failure to press forward with the
appeal now clears the way for others to go to court to push for
enforcement of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will allow the issue to be re-litigated with genuine
parties willing to defend the initiative,'' Findley said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Browne, another Pacific Legal Foundation attorney, also
questioned the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this does is leave Proposition 187 basically undefended
because the governor has made it clear he opposes the philosophy
behind Proposition 187,'' Browne said. ``I don't see how this was a
fair mediation.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis aides contended that the group was invited to participate
in mediation but walked out after the first meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said Proposition 187 supporters won on the major points on
which they had campaigned -- prohibiting public welfare, health and
higher education to illegal immigrants as well as a crackdown on
manufacture and possession of phony documents.
</P>
<P>
   What was changed is that the state will continue to provide
education from kindergarten through high school and will not be
required to report suspected illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   However, the state and local jurisdictions will continue to
report the immigration status of those convicted of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   If the settlement is accepted by the courts, Davis said he will
ask state agencies to begin implementing the procedures that have
been developed over the past five years to enact those portions of
the measure taking effect.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, Davis angered Latino leaders by his decision
to enter the mediation process, instead of dropping the state's
appeal of the federal court decision blocking Proposition 187's
implementation.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Davis said that ``What we have gained from this is
an agreement by the other side to accept the federal laws and allow
us to move on,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante, who had angrily denounced Davis, said
he saluted those involved in the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, an ugly chapter in the history of California politics
has come to an end,'' Bustamante said. ``Most of Proposition 187
was never constitutional. Now, it will never become the law of our
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Federal Judge Shirley Hufstedler, who represented Davis
in the discussions, defended Davis' decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to go through this long and difficult process,''
Hufstedler said. ``The governor deserves credit for this in
avoiding a lengthy and costly procedure. And, there is no guarantee
the Supreme Court would have accepted this.''
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles, said the
main factor of the settlement is to end fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mothers and fathers will no longer have to worry about sending
their kids to school or getting emergency medical care,''
Villaraigosa said. ``This signals that the era of hate politics is
truly over and it's time to move into a new era of opportunity. We
must work together to improve our state and not allow ourselves to
be divided and distracted.''
</P>
<P>
   There also was an unintended benefit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure so angered minority communities, particularly
Latinos, that it resulted in energizing political organizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``For that, we can thank Wilson,'' Villaraigosa said. Latino
voters are the largest group among new voters and they are playing
an increasingly significant role in state and local politics.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
