<SLUG> BC-AIRTOUCH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRTOUCH INTRODUCES ACCESS TO INTERNET VIA CELL PHONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ AirTouch Cellular, a provider of digital phone
service, on Wednesday began offering direct Internet access from
computers through its cell phones at no extra charge in three
regions of the United States, including Western Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Claimed to be the first such service in this country, AirTouch's
Net Access also premiered in Detroit and in Salt Lake City, where
it underwent trials for two years before Wednesday's unveiling.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Seattle, one of the nation's most competitive cell phone
markets, none of the seven providers appears to offer a similar
service. Sprint PCS and US West said they plan to do so later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Seybold, a telecommunications analyst in Boulder Creek,
Calif., said the service is ``an invaluable tool for many
professionals and business people who can't afford to wait to
access vital information.''
</P>
<P>
   Using Net Access requires a Qualcomm 860 cell phone, which
retails for about $149, and a $25 cable to connect the phone to a
computer's serial port. Most AirTouch customers don't already own
those phones, which came on the market only a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Once physically connected, an AirTouch customer dials (pound
sign) 777 from the computer's dialer and is typically on the
Internet within five seconds, AirTouch said. That connection time
compares with the 35 or 40 seconds needed with dial-up modems.
There's no ring and no handshake, just a direct connection.
</P>
<P>
   The connection operates at a maximum rate of 14.4 kbps, about
one-third the speed of the 56-kbps modems found in most computers.
But one trial user found the speed difference wasn't pronounced or
annoying, especially with e-mail and other text.
</P>
<P>
   The direct Internet connection means customers can't check their
e-mail with a specific Internet service provider. To do that, they
can dial their ISP directly rather than using the (pound sign) 777
direct connection, though that entails a longer wait to connect.
</P>
<P>
   Net Access is an alternative to using older technology: A
specialized external modem connecting a computer to a cell phone.
Conventional PCMCIA cards and other internal modems can't be used
with cell phones, because they lack error-correction software, said
Bruce Cech, manager of AirTouch's wireless data applications.
</P>
<P>
   Special wireless modems usually sell for between $300 and $500,
and the top speed of the connections they make is generally 9.6
kbps, possibly hitting 11 kbps close to a cellular tower, Cech
said.
</P>
<P>
   Net Access took two years to engineer and test, the company
said. The most difficult task was integrating direct Internet
access into the cellular network. The technology underlying that
network _ called CDMA, for Code Division Multiple Access _ is
designed to work better with data than a competing technology
called TMDA (Time Division Multiple Access) used by AT&AMP;T Wireless
and other service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Though it won't cost customers extra, AirTouch anticipates Net
Access will increase its revenue stream, because customers
typically spend 12 minutes on a data call _ four times longer than
on a voice call, said spokeswoman Lisa Bowersock. AirTouch
typically charges customers between 10 cents and 25 cents per
minute, depending on volume.
</P>
<P>
   In a second phase of Net Access, scheduled to be in place by
year-end, the company plans to let customers use their handsets as
simplified Internet browsers, dispensing entirely with the
computer. A browser from Phone.com is already built into the
Qualcomm 860. A third phase will allow wireless transactions
online.
</P>
<P>
   Net Access will be rolled out to the entire AirTouch network,
which serves 9 million customers, by year-end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
