A9459 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-29 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNITY HAS LITTLE TO LOSE IN APPROVING RICHARDS-GEBAUR
PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- The main weapon in the arsenal of those
opposing the plan to transform Richards-Gebaur Memorial Airport
into a truck-rail freight-transfer hub proves that right doesn't
necessarily make might.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the proposal involves undeserved corporate welfare
for Kansas City Southern Railway, which they say will be getting
the benefit of a valuable economic resource on the cheap. Because I
have never been a big fan of public-private development
initiatives, they'll get no argument from me. The view here is that
these ventures are driven by natural inclination of business
managers to socialize losses and privatize profits.
</P>
<P>
   However, after nearly a quarter of a century of attempting to be
the taxpayer's advocate in these matters, the view here is also
that the corporate-welfare rap is no longer relevant to the debate.
It hasn't been for a long time, because society has accepted
public-private ventures as a beneficial way for communities to
further their economic interests.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the citizenry may have intuited what's in its
best interests better than the pundits and activists who have a
problem with conscripting taxpayers to bear burdens that rightfully
belong to those to whom the profits will flow. These deals have
become standard procedure, and very little gets done nowadays
without some form of public subsidy to enhance the potential
investment return of private interests.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, what has happened? The economy has been booming,
nationally and locally. That's what.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago the Kansas City area was known for its plodding
economy that never soared too high during booms, but never fell too
far during recessions. During what has been an almost nonstop
national economic expansion since the early '80s, however, Kansas
City has had a much more vibrant economy than it did a generation
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Is this happy development due to the proliferation of
public-private economic cooperation? Hard to say, but one thing is
certain. These partnerships certainly haven't hurt the area's
growth curve.
</P>
<P>
   While proponents hail the Richards-Gebaur project as a source of
future dynamism and opponents pooh-pooh such claims, nobody will
know for 10 to 20 years how this venture will turn out.
</P>
<P>
   What we do know in the here and now is that the airport appears
to be an underused resource. A local company says it can put this
resource to more productive use. Opponents decry the prospective
loss of its use as an airport, but if that were its optimum
economic role it would have been developed in that direction long
before now.
</P>
<P>
   What we have is a major company that sees long-term potential
and is willing to make a significant bet on its vision for the
property, if only it can get a little help from its friends in the
public sector.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of any other substantive offer to put this
resource to better use for such a long period, it makes sense for
Kansas Citians to take a flier on Kansas City Southern's
willingness to try to create a good deal more economic value than
currently exists at Richards-Gebaur.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, judging from what's now in place, the community has
little to lose and potentially much to gain from approving
Richards-Gebaur's transformation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-29-99 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
