<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9461 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEAT-STRESS-KAN &LR;      07-29 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-STRESS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE TEMPERATURE RISES SO DO TEMPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Feeling kind of grumpy? Slamming doors?
Using language that would make a sailor blush?
</P>
<P>
   Go on, blame it on the weather.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of heat that's been pounding the Kansas City area can
turn tempers nasty, psychologists say.
</P>
<P>
   Hot weather can boost the rate of violent crime, they say. But
the heat can also cause pitchers to throw more beanballs, spur
drivers to lean on their horns longer, and boost college students'
support for capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simplest explanation is people get more irritable and that
leads them to behave more aggressively in many ways,'' said Craig
Anderson, an Iowa State University psychologist and heat
researcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's reason to assume the stress accumulates over time.
Day after day of heat, you become more irritable.''
</P>
<P>
   The hot weather has been putting some Kansas City residents on
edge.
</P>
<P>
   Since last week, visits to Western Missouri Mental Health
Center's emergency room appear to be running at record levels, said
psychiatrist Cristina Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always there is someone waiting to be seen,'' she said.
``People are more irritable. They get frustrated and they
immediately go off. I'm thinking it's the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some patients are coming in just because the mental
health center is air conditioned, many others are being brought
involuntarily by police, Payton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have fights on the street, in the family,'' she said.
``They come with homicidal complaints, suicidal complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   The most serious social effect of the heat is an increase in
violent crime, Anderson said. Warmer regions of the United States
tend to have higher violent crime rates than cooler ones. And crime
rates in the United States tend to be higher in hotter years.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, Kansas City appears to have been spared.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City police said Thursday that domestic violence, robbery
and homicide actually were all down during the last couple of
weeks, compared with an average week.
</P>
<P>
   But there are plenty of ways heat can stir aggression that fall
far short of criminal violence:
</P>
<P>
   - University of Michigan researchers found that the higher the
temperature, the more likely major league baseball pitchers were to
throw balls that hit batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitcher-batter duel is one of guarding territory,''
Anderson said. ``If you as a pitcher are defending your territory
more aggressively, you're going to hit the batter more often.''
</P>
<P>
   - While researchers haven't linked high temperatures to road
rage yet, there is evidence that heat can ignite drivers' tempers.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers in Phoenix conducted a fiendish experiment in which
they had a driver stop at a traffic light and stay there after the
light turned green. From the side of the road, they observed how
often and how long the driver in the vehicle immediately behind the
experimenters' car honked his horn.
</P>
<P>
   They found that the higher the temperature, the more often
drivers honked and the longer they leaned on their horns. This
vehicular aggression was only present among drivers unfortunate
enough to be in cars that weren't air-conditioned.
</P>
<P>
   - Even people who don't act aggressively in the heat may turn
punitive as the temperature rises.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson put matched groups of college students into rooms with
the thermostat set in the comfortable mid-70-degree range and in
the verging-on-miserable mid-80s range. He had both groups fill out
questionnaires.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group left to boil were far more likely to answer
in favor of the use of violence, such as beating a disobedient
child, or executing a criminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we didn't expect to show up. Attitudes are
thought of as something stable,'' Anderson said. ``But heat has an
effect on what you consider an appropriate reaction to
provocation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
